<HEADLINE>
BIG BOARD VOTES TO END MANDATORY JOB-BIAS ARBITRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The board of the New York Stock Exchange voted
Thursday to no longer require industry arbitration of
job-discrimination claims, deciding that it will hear such claims
only when they are submitted and after a dispute has arisen,
according to executives at the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which affects the whole brokerage industry as it
covers stockbrokers and other members of the exchange, will be
filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission in the next few
days, and after a period for public comment, it is expected to lead
to a change in the exchange's rules, said James Buck, senior vice
president and corporate secretary of the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage industry's practice of mandatorily referring
employment disputes to industry arbitration _ as many brokerage
employees agree to do when they sign their work contracts _ has
gradually been eroded. Critics of mandatory arbitration have
maintained that it gives unfair advantage to brokerage firms, and
denies employees their civil rights by preventing them from getting
access to courts. The proponents of mandatory arbitration say it is
quicker, cheaper and more efficient than resorting to the courts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The change by the Big Board follows federal court decisions in
Massachusetts and California, which held that brokerage firm
employees could take discrimination claims to court and did not
have to submit to industry arbitration. It also follows a recent
decision by the National Association of Securities Dealers, which
oversees the Nasdaq market. That body recently ruled that the
matter of mandatory arbitration in these cases was one for
individual securities firms to decide for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   George Nicolau, a past president of the National Academy of
Arbitrators and now a spokesmen on such issues, called the decision
``a progressive step toward fairness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
