<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-INVESTMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT NAMED AT FIDELITY INVESTMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments named James C. Curvey as president
Thursday, shifting all operating responsibilities for the giant
mutual fund and investment firm to him.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1997, Curvey, 63, has served as chief operating
officer and a vice chairman of FMR Corp., Fidelity's parent. As
such, he has been second in command to chairman and chief executive
Edward C. Johnson III.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Curvey said Johnson, 68, would continue in
those posts and was not preparing to retire or otherwise remove
himself from Fidelity's management.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson will spend more time overseeing policy and strategy
for Fidelity and less time on the day-to-day operations of the
company's various business units, Curvey said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's post at Fidelity was last occupied from 1983 to
1986 by Samuel W. Bodman III, who left to join Cabot Corp., a
Boston industrial company, as its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey will have responsibility for overseeing Fidelity's mutual
fund business; its three distribution channels, which serve retail
customers, corporate retirement plans and brokers and other
financial intermediaries, and its venture capital unit.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey will also continue to supervise Fidelity's administrative
and legal departments. Robert C. Pozen, who heads Fidelity's mutual
fund unit, will continue to report to Johnson on matters of
investment policy.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey said his priorities as president would include
integrating the operations of Fidelity's domestic and international
units.
</P>
</TEXT>
