<HEADLINE>
VILLAGE KNOWN FOR QUAINTNESS IS CHANGED FOREVER BY CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ Troy Kruger, a young refueler at
Halifax International Airport, heard the voice on the radio in his
truck on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot in an unknown plane was carrying on an urgent, barely
controlled conversation with the man in the airport tower.
</P>
<P>
   What Kruger did not know was that the voice belonged to the
pilot of Swissair Flight 111 and that he had only moments earlier
told air-traffic control that he was ``one level below an
emergency,'' according to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot circled back, heading toward Boston, they said.
Air-traffic control advised him that Halifax was closer, 50 miles
away. The pilot turned around and flew on.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, his voice was being heard in Halifax by Kruger,
the tower operator, and a pilot on the ground named Andrew Arthur.
``He said there was smoke in the cabin, that it was an extreme
emergency,'' Arthur said. ``I wasn't sure it was a big plane, but
when he said he was going to dump 208 tons of fuel, I knew it was a
major problem.''
</P>
<P>
   With smoke filling the plane, the pilot guided the MD-11,
carrying 229 people, to within 30 miles of the Halifax airport.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur and Kruger stepped outside and stared up at the sky. ``We
were waiting for the lights to come down, something, anything. But
nothing came,'' Arthur said. ``You could hear the tower guy's sigh,
almost like he was crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the villages that dot the forested south shore
near Halifax, hundreds of people sat in square houses with the kind
of pitched roofs you find in a child's drawings. At the same time,
they all heard it. The boom, the thunder. And they felt it, the
noise that rattled their windows.
</P>
<P>
   In Hubley, Alice Wilson and her son heard what she said
``sounded like a plane, but all wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bayswater, Harris Backman and his son Steve heard a loud
clap, preceded by a sickly whirring, like ``a plane trying to take
off and failing,'' said Backman's wife, Audrey.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials, numerous emergency 911 calls came in,
reporting the sounds of a plane in distress.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the Backmans got a call from the local Coast
Guard Auxilliary office, where they are volunteers. Father and son
rode into the night on a boat to search for survivors of what was
now known to be a terrible plane crash. Instead, they found bits of
plane and bodies that none of them want to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Buckley, captain of a whale-watching ship from Peggy's
Cove, was shocked to see that the emerald sea was wearing a new set
of jewels: One white sneaker, a lady's glove, bits of paper, a
lonely floating teddy bear, an airpline wing, floating like a razor
blade in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley squinted his dark eyes against the horror.
</P>
<P>
   Merv Morash of Hackett's Cove said the sound reminded him of May
27, 1981, when an Canadian Air Force Thunderbird crashed near here
and he was sent to clean it up. That date remained with him, he
said, because it was such an awful sight. But this? ``My God,'' he
said, standing the day after on a rock, looking out to the sea for
something, some sign.
</P>
<P>
   All he saw was a large gray Navy tanker called the Preserver.
According to Constable Brad Reid, the spokesman for the Royal
Canadian Mounted Patrol in Halifax, the Preserver is equipped with
both a hospital and a morgue, but the hospital was not needed.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 a.m., 17 bodies had been found. Fishermen asked for body
bags, then more body bags. By 12:30 p.m., 36 bodies were taken to
the ship, one to shore.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they all were taken to the Shearwater military base,
where six teams of specialists under the watch of the coronor's
office did their scientific best to find names and pasts for what
remained.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, searchers were aided by good weather, a dramatic
change from the previous night's rain and high seas. But 120 feet
under the sea, a hunk of plane, still intact, sat mute in the
darkness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
