<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PIAZZA AND METS, COUNTDOWN NOW BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ If the Nerw York Mets end up winning the National
League wild card playoff spot this season, they will certainly have
earned it. And Mike Piazza, the All-Star catcher who has seemed
unhappy at times with the Mets, will have enjoyed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd say this, but this team definitely has
some good chemistry,'' Piazza said after homering in a 4-1 victory
over the San Diego Padres on Wednesday night. ``This is a real fun
team to play on. Obviously, you have more fun when you are winning.
But the guys are good guys here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Piazza has admitted enjoying himself with
the Mets, an experience that included repeated booing at Shea
Stadium before his hot streak began. His statements, however, were
not an indication that he will sign with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their future with Piazza, the Mets need to concentrate
on the rest of their season. Half of the Mets' remaining schedule _
11 of the final 22 games _ will be against a pair of division
leaders, the Braves and the Astros. A four-game series against
Atlanta begins Friday night at Shea, pitting two of the top
left-handers in the majors: the Mets' Al Leiter (13-5) against Tom
Glavine (18-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves are a real good team, we know that,'' manager Bobby
Valentine said after his team completed a 5-4 western swing
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had just been reminded that the Mets are 0-5 against
the Braves, the NL East leaders, this season. ``But we're a real
good team, too,'' he said. ``We believe that now. And we're a
better team now than when we last faced them,'' in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Mets are good enough to take a series from the
Braves remains to be seen. But the Mets have responded to their
toughest stretch of the season with some of their best baseball of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets weathered a homestand two weeks ago that featured three
doubleheaders in four days. Then they went west with a one-game
lead in the wild card race. After Armando Reynoso (6-1) shut down
the Padres, yet another first-place team, on four hits over eight
innings Wednesday, the Mets _ one game behind the Cubs in the wild
card race _ returned for a much-needed off day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing two games in the standing to Chicago, the Mets
(77-63) finished a West Coast swing with a winning record for only
the fourth time in their last 18 trips.
</P>
<P>
   And now things really get tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many games have we played them, five?'' Valentine said of
the Braves, whom the Mets trail by 14 games. ``I'm not worried that
we haven't beaten them. They haven't beaten this team yet.''
</P>
<P>
   What Valentine meant was that the Mets are much different than
when they were swept in Atlanta July 3-5, in the last series before
the All-Star break, and at Shea July 14-15. After the Mets lost
July 16 to Philadelphia, they were just two games over .500 and
their wild card chances seemed to be slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, they are 12 games over .500. Their starting
pitchers are rested, thanks to Valentine's six-man rotation
experiment. And the newcomers Tony Phillips and Lenny Harris have
energized a lineup that had often been punchless. Harris drilled
his fifth home run in 16 games Wednesday to erase an early 1-0 San
Diego lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference in the Mets is Piazza, who was
struggling in the Mets' first two series against the Braves. He has
all but carried the Mets offensively for the last month.
</P>
<P>
   For the 130 games he has played this season, Piazza is hitting
.319 with 28 homers and 93 runs batted in. In his 88 games with the
Mets, his relative numbers (.339, 19 homers, 58 RBI) are even
better.
</P>
<P>
   If Piazza can approach the September he had last season, when he
hit .406 with eight home runs and 27 runs batted in for the
Dodgers, the Mets will greatly improve their chances to reach the
post-season for the first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a more balanced club than the last time we played the
Braves,'' Piazza said. ``And we've been a lot more consistent since
before the break. But let's be frank. We've got a tough schedule.
And we've got some week ahead. If _ and it's a big if _ we do
happen to get there and win the wild card, we really will have
earned it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
