<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST DESERTS FOR KANELL: $9.5 MILLION FOR 3 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It made the Giants uncomfortable that
the starting quarterback Danny Kanell was making the league's
minimum salary of $216,000. It made Kanell uncomfortable that even
backup quarterbacks make five times as much.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, reached not coincidentally right before the
pivotal season-opening game with the Washington Redskins, was a
renegotiated three-year contract, worth $9.5 million, beginning
this season.
</P>
<P>
   And though the new deal makes Kanell one of the team's four
highest-paid players, it could be nothing more than a step toward
an even bigger payday. If Kanell blossoms this season into the star
the Giants hope he can become, this latest contract will be torn up
next winter and renegotiated as well.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Rob Johnson, with one National Football League start
in his career, extracted a five-year, $25 million contract from the
Buffalo Bills last winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' general manager, Ernie Accorsi, mindful of the
four-year, $12.8 million contract the Giants gave quarterback Dave
Brown in 1996, was unwilling to give Kanell that kind of
commitment. But he did not want Kanell, who was 7-2-1 as a starter
last season, to be distracted by his league-minimum salary this
year or to have the chance to field other teams' offers as a
restricted free agent next year. The new contract found a middle
ground, with the understanding that should Kanell flourish, an
annual salary of $3 million would no longer be adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Michael Strahan, with a salary-cap value this
season of $3.77 million, is currently the team's highest-paid
player. Incentive clauses make ranking Giants salaries difficult,
but the injured cornerback Jason Sehorn, with an average of more
than $3 million annually, would be next in the mix along with
Kanell and linebacker Jessie Armstead, whom the Giants upgraded
with a new deal last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very fair,'' Kanell said Thursday. ``I don't feel
like I'm one of the top quarterbacks in the league, but I shouldn't
be getting what backups and third-stringers are getting either.
It's a great step of faith. Now I want to make the Giants proud and
show them I'm worth every penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi said the Jets' signing of running back Curtis Martin,
who was a restricted free agent last winter, had some effect on the
Giants' strategy with Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell would have been a restricted free agent after this
season, and though the Giants could have matched any offer he
received from another team next winter, the Jets' successful
pursuit of Martin with a diabolically complex offer sheet revealed
the difficulty a team can have trying to keep a key player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny's the starting quarterback and something had to be
done,'' Accorsi said Thursday of his talks with Kanell, who signed
a three-year, $704,000 contract as the team's fourth-round draft
pick in 1996. ``We both got something out of it. And getting it
done now made sense because doing it during the season is not a
good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell said, ``I trusted the Giants' organization to pay me what
I deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do to celebrate his new salary, Kanell
smiled. ``Watch film of the Redskins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel had the Giants install a high-tech $36,000
videotape player and projector in the condo Kanell rents in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I guess I can get a big-screen TV, too,'' Kanell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
