<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-BASEBALL-BRONX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BERKSHIRES, A BASEBALL TIP FOR THE BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Summer vacation in the Berkshire Mountains included,
by custom, a family pilgrimage to Wahconah Park in Pittsfield,
Mass., where the minor-league Pittsfield Mets set up shop from June
to September. In case you wonder about the name, they are the New
York-Penn League offspring of the better-known Mets of Flushing
Meadows, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Wahconah Park (capacity 4,000) offers baseball the way it was
meant to be: in an intimate setting, with splendid seats for the
general admission price of $2.50 and with no silly distractions
like exploding scoreboards, guys in chicken suits telling you when
to clap or luxury skyboxes that make a mockery of the game's
egalitarian roots.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its pleasures, Wahconah is showing its age. It was
built in 1919, four years before Yankee Stadium opened, and the
summer has been filled with cries of how Pittsfield sorely needs a
new ball field. Sound vaguely familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Some New Yorkers may be interested in the relationship between
the ball club and its neighborhood. Pittsfield has fallen on hard
times, having endured its share of economic body blows, like
General Electric pulling up stakes a few years ago. But you do not
hear the local Mets talk trash about the community that has
sustained it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of being out in the community and being a part
of it,'' said Richard Murphy, the team's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at what our mission statement is,'' he added,
``and that's affordable family entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoughts turned to Murphy during a rain delay at Yankee Stadium
on Wednesday night (in a so-so seat near the right-field foul pole
that cost $20). It was hard not to contrast his remarks with the
behavior of the Yankees' owner, George Steinbrenner III of Tampa,
Fla., who has continued to bad-mouth the Bronx gratuitously despite
the millions he makes there and despite the season-attendance
record his team is close to setting.
</P>
<P>
   Mission? Steinbrenner makes clear that his is not to be part of
a community but rather to take New York City for what he can in his
quest for a new ball park. It certainly isn't to provide affordable
family entertainment, not with his lust for so many luxury boxes
that Yankees baseball risks becoming the preserve of the wealthy
and the corporately connected.
</P>
<P>
   Only George Steinbrenner can add a sour note to this enchanted
season when the Yankees may become the winningest team of the
century. Haven't they already provided enough magic to carry this
city through the bleakest winter? Not to their bilious owner. ``I
really don't care about how many victories we get this year, I
really don't,'' he said last month. ``What I care about is the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, City Hall politicians allowed this man's
ambitions to make a mess of their municipal budget negotiations.
Now, because of him, they are set to clutter the November ballot
with one dubious referendum or another.
</P>
<P>
   This may be as good a time as any to note how generous New York
has already been to the Yankees _ and, for that matter, to the
Mets. Compare that with the city's contract with the U.S. Tennis
Association, a favorable deal for New York even if its
Yankees-adoring mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, does not think so. (No
doubt, it is purely a coincidence that this agreement was reached
by David Dinkins, his tennis-loving predecessor.)
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, the tennis association has paid the city
$5.3 million in rent for its U.S. Open matches in Flushing Meadows,
compared with $2.1 million paid by the Yankees and $2 million by
the Mets for the use of their stadiums. Bear in mind that the Open,
now under way, lasts a mere two weeks while the regular baseball
season is six months long.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the tennis deal shine is that the Dinkins
administration required the association to pay all maintenance
costs. By contrast, the Yankees and Mets get to deduct those
expenses from their rent bill. And Steinbrenner has not been above
an occasional chisel. Some years, his accounting had the city owing
him money. Once, he tried dunning the city for an engineer who
supposedly worked 168 hours a week. Guess how many hours there are
in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, all this is something New Yorkers may wish to ponder in
the thickening battle over a new playground for the Yankees' owner.
How did the Pittsfield man put it? ``It's a question of being out
in the community and being a part of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
