<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE POUNDS FLORIDA WITH FLOODS AND TWISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lead graf) (sw) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A hurricane lashed Florida's Panhandle coast with winds
of 80 miles an hour, crossing the coast in the darkness of the
early morning hours and killing two people there and one in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But the hurricane, named Earl, spared the state major damage
before moving into Georgia and the Carolinas as a weaker storm.
</P>
<P>
   One person was killed near St. Helena Island in South Carolina
in a tornado spawned by the storm, emergency officials said. In
Florida, the bodies of two fishermen were found off Panama City,
one on a beach near the town and the other 10 miles at sea.
Injuries were few and mostly minor, Florida officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Downgraded to a tropical storm, the storm was traveling through
the southeastern states with sustained winds of 45 miles an hour
and was expected to stay inland through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the size of the storm and how erratic it was, for
the most part we got out pretty well,'' said Ann Rowe, a
spokeswoman with the Florida Division of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   Rated as a Category 1 hurricane, the mildest classification,
Earl approached with menacing winds of 100 miles an hour but lost
some of that punch as it went ashore near Panama City, a beach area
of about 35,000 residents that bulges with tourists in the summer.
But it was storm surges of 7 to 12 feet that caused the most
damage, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen counties along the coast south and southwest of
Tallahassee reported heavy beach erosion, damage to more than 1,100
homes, submerged coastal roads and more than 15,000 residents
without electric power. Six counties reported tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who wanted to return home on Thursday after being
evacuated were sometimes blocked by impassable roads. Gov. Lawton
Chiles, who asked the federal government for a disaster declaration
to insure financial aid, said most damage was caused by flooding
and a surge that some residents said was worse than previous
hurricanes that have pounded the area recently. Comprehensive
damage reports were note expected for a day or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we got quite a bit of water,'' the governor said
at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
   But state tourism officials said the hurricane caused ``little
to no damage'' to tourist destinations of the Panhandle. Panama
City, Destin, Pensacola and Fort Walton Beach all had reported
favorable conditions for travel during the upcoming Labor Day
weekend, they said, and beaches, golf courses and campgrounds were
open.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was less relaxing in areas like Shell Island, a small
community in Wakulla County, where 26 boats, ranging from small
fishing vessels to large cabin cruisers, washed away from a marina
and were bobbing atop the water in front lawns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
