<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BIRTHCONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CONTRACEPTION, THREE DAYS AFTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Sept. 4:
</P>
<P>
   In an important advance for women's health, the Food and Drug
Administration has approved the marketing and sale of emergency
contraceptive pills that women can take within three days after sex
to prevent pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, researchers have known that regular
contraceptive pills that are taken daily to prevent pregnancy are
also safe and effective if taken in larger doses as
``morning-after'' pills. Although this practice has been approved
in many European countries, most American doctors offer their
patients no guidance on it, so most women here know nothing about
emergency contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike drugs such as RU-486, emergency contraception pills
cannot end a pregnancy. Instead, they work by preventing ovulation
or by preventing a fertilized egg from implanting in the uterine
wall. They are thus acceptable to at least some anti-abortion
activists.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until 1996 that the FDA convened an expert committee
to examine this issue. The agency's action this week will now allow
a drug manufacturer, Gynetics, to package prescription
contraceptive pills into kits specifically for emergency use. Two
pills to be taken within 72 hours after unprotected sex and two
more taken 12 hours later will be about 75 percent effective in
preventing pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   By making this method more widely known, hundreds of thousands
of women may be able to avoid unplanned pregnancies and subsequent
abortions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-04 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
It was the question asked most often during the spring: How good is
the Astros' offense?
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We knew going in that we would score a lot of runs,'' manager
Larry Dierker recalls. It's time for an update:
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are zeroing in on the club record of 777 runs set a
year ago. Opening a three-game series at Arizona tonight, they need
five runs to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the past, the Astros' run production hasn't been limited
to a couple of players. Moises Alou already has 118 RBIs, and two
teammates are threatening to join him in surpassing 100. Never have
the Astros had more than two players top 100 RBIs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   And depending on their mood, the Astros have scored early, late
_ and often. Big innings. One run at a time. Somehow, the runs
continue to mount. And with them the wins, including 42
come-from-behind victories.
</P>
<P>
   But as Dierker points out, ``You can score a ton of runs and
still be a .500 club.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been the case with the Astros, who lead the National
League Central by 10 games. Through it all, the one constant has
been an offense that has shifted from being two-dimensional into an
eight-headed monster.
</P>
<P>
   Few teams in baseball have as solid a lineup from top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Astros would have found it difficult to survive
0-for-4 performances from Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell. But
because of what Dierker calls a ``magnetic`` effect, the Astros
aren't as dependent on their big two. Not that they have slacked
off.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio has the highest average (.329) among every-day starters.
Bagwell is on the way to a third straight season of at least 30
homers and 100 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell has kept his average above .300 all season and is
approaching 100 RBIs for the second time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Those who got a glimpse of Alou during the playoffs last year
had an idea what the Astros were getting when they traded for the
All-Star outfielder. He has punctuated his first go-around in
Houston with 38 home runs and could eclipse Bagwell's club record
of 135 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett began the season in a platoon with rookie Richard
Hidalgo before winning the job outright with a hot June.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of lineup, opposing pitchers have found it tough
to pitch around certain players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of all five of those guys having a bad day are not
good. The chances are a couple will have a good day,'' Dierker
said. ``If they happen to do it the same inning, you've got some
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have enough good hitters, what they'll end up doing is
acting like a magnet for the guys that aren't good hitters. They
draw them into the production line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pittsburgh Pirates and the Big Red Machine (Cincinnati)
used to be like that (in the 1970s),'' Dierker said. ``It seems
like they always had good-hitting teams. They would pick up some
guy from another team that had never been a good hitter, and all of
a sudden the guy is hitting .280 or .300.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the known big guns, there have been some pleasant
surprises. The third-base platoon of Sean Berry and Bill Spiers has
accounted for 16 homers, 86 RBIs and a .296 average. Everett and
Hidalgo _ who sometimes are on the field at the same time _ have
produced 18 homers and 95 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   That type of balance is what sets this team apart, a few Astros
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at a team like the Yankees that is really
successful, they don't have somebody hitting 60 home runs on their
team,'' Berry said. ``They have a lot of guys that can hit the ball
out of the ballpark, a lot of guys that get clutch hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we compare better to them _ not a bad team to compare
yourself to.''
</P>
<P>
   The best gauge of how well the offense has clicked is its
ability to produce clutch hits late. The offense has pulled out
victory 22 times in the Astros' last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   They showed Atlanta the late-game thunder Monday. Down two runs
in the ninth inning with John Smoltz dominating on the mound, the
Astros appeared beaten. Instead, six singles off Smoltz and Kerry
Ligtenberg produced a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an offense that can do so much. You just feed off one
another's success,'' Everett said. `` There's really no way to
pitch around our club. You have to go through five quality hitters
before you get to someone that you may say, `I can get this person
out.' By then, it's too late. The lineup is so talented, you can't
make mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
