<HEADLINE>
ANTI-AMERICAN ATTACKS CERTAIN, FBI CHIEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Terrorism is war, and Americans must expect more
and larger attacks and additional U.S. responses against groups
that hate the United States, FBI Director Louis Freeh told a Senate
panel Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It is well known that Osama bin Laden, the wealthy Saudi
expatriate believed responsible for bombing two U.S. Embassies in
Africa last month, has declared war on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   What is less well understood is that his declaration can be
taken literally even though bin Laden is not the leader of another
country, commands no formal army, and holds no particular
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh, who testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee at
the invitation of Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., said there is ``some
certainty'' that bin Laden will react with potentially spectacular
violence to the recent U.S. bombing raids on suspected Afghan
terrorist training camps and a Sudanese chemical weapons plant.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is highly likely to respond with force against
bin Laden's holdings and those of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there should be no illusions about the fact that (bin
Laden) as recently as May of this year declared war on America,''
Freeh said. ``That is about as serious a threat as I could
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   If new terrorist attacks follow the current trend, it could mean
greater losses of life and higher-profile targets, Freeh said.
Terrorism once meant the hijacking of an airliner; then the bombing
of an aircraft. Now, it often means attacks on large structures and
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The bombers of the World Trade Center, Freeh said, intended to
kill 100,000 people by toppling one tower onto the other. And the
group responsible for introducing sarin gas into the Japanese
subway system intended mass deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the signs and the trends, the public isn't prepared,
Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people need to get ready for (increasingly
horrific attacks) and need to do the things necessary to confront
that,'' he said. ``It's absurd we're in for something we're not
ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl said the United States needs to devise a stronger and more
consistent ``strategy, not just a policy'' for dealing with
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's administration must account for the
``disparity between public representations of his policy as one of
firmness and the . . . (revelations of a policy) of appeasement,''
Kyl said, citing complaints by Scott Ritter, a former U.N. weapons
inspector who quit over concerns that the United States allowed
Iraq to circumvent some inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh testified that although terrorist groups are not formally
organized under the flag of an army or country, they are
formidable.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 terrorist organizations have been identified by the
FBI in the United States, Freeh said, and there are dozens of other
loose affiliates. The bin Laden group has operatives in the United
States and ``several dozen'' countries.
</P>
<P>
   Because of bin Laden's vast financial resources, his allies have
access to some of the most sophisticated weaponry the world has to
offer, from night-vision technology to chemical weapons, Freeh
said.
</P>
<P>
   To combat these groups and respond to their attacks, the FBI
needs better communications equipment, dedicated aircraft to rush
its agents to crime sites, and the keys to computer encryption
technology developed by American companies.  &QL; 
 &UR; Adrianne Flynn can be reached at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
