<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TO LETT LOOSE ON DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Imagine All-Pro defensive tackle Leon Lett
playing the right side on one play and the left side the next. Or
maybe nose tackle Chad Hennings attacking the center one play, then
dropping into pass coverage on the next.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the preseason talk heading into Sunday's season
opener with the Arizona Cardinals has centered on first-year head
coach Chan Gailey's offense, the Cowboys were also making changes
in their defense. The Cowboys' new alignment will allow Lett to
play various positions, free up end Kavika Pittman to rush the
quarterback and, defensive coordinator Dave Campo hopes, make the
Cowboys stronger against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are better against the run,'' Campo said. ``I like our
speed and ability to get to the football. I think the biggest
question is, Can we get to the passer?''
</P>
<P>
   The alterations feature an alignment shift from the traditional
4-3 (with four down lineman and three linebackers) to an
overshifting 4-3 (that adds a nose tackle) and allows Lett to move
along the line of scrimmage and create mismatches. Lett will
primarily line up on the weak side, away from the tight end, but be
allowed to move to other positions.
</P>
<P>
   The premise in the scheme change, Campo said, is for the tackles
and ends to clog up the line of scrimmage and force the running
backs to the perimeter where Cowboys linebackers Dexter Coakley and
Randall Godfrey can make a majority of the tackles. The changes
also allow the Cowboys to take advantage of Pittman's speed, Campo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman will now play the weakside end position, which the
Cowboys liken to a glorified rush linebacker. First-round pick Greg
Ellis will play strongside end and will line up on the side of the
tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThe change\S was done to fit our players abilities,'' Campo
said. ``It gives us a chance to put our best 11 in the best
position possible to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defense's ranking of second in the league last year,
Campo said his unit was not without faults and that the changes
were necessary for the team to rebound from 1997's 6-10
performance. Specifically, the Cowboys needed improvement in run
defense, creating turnovers and third-down defense. They finished
24th, 30th, 18th in the league in those areas respectively last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is pleased with the early results, though he is still
concerned about the pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' pass-rushing concerns are serious enough for the
team to consider re-signing retired defensive end Charles Haley and
also negotiate with free-agent linebacker Quentin Coryatt over the
past few days.
</P>
<P>
   But even without any more player additions, the Cowboys coaches
and players said they will be better because Lett will be on the
field for a full season. He missed the first 13 games of last
season because of a suspension for violating the NFL's
substance-abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   Lett joins cornerback Deion Sanders and safety Darren Woodson in
giving the Cowboys three All-Pro caliber defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dominating players have to continue to make plays,'' said
defensive line coach Jim Bates. ``And the guys around them have to
be consistent, play their roles, and make plays when they have
their opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   While the changes could potentially turn Lett into a superstar_
as Campo said it puts Lett in position to be more of a playmaker _
the main goal was aimed at improving the Cowboys run defense first.
</P>
<P>
   Hennings, one of the league's tallest nose tackles at 6-foot-6,
295 pounds, will drop into pass coverage on some zone blitzes. He
said improving against the run was a must. The 1,994 rushing yards
allowed by the Cowboys last season were the most since 1986. The
last nine opponents in 1997 averaged 147.7 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, we must stop the run,'' Hennings said.
``That's what everything comes off of. If we stop the run, then you
set yourself up for a good pass rush, fumbles and everything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo agreed. He said creating turnovers and being better on
third-down were byproducts of good run defense. If the Cowboys can
improve against the run, that will keep them from playing more
eight-man fronts and free safeties up for coverage instead of run
support. That could help create more turnovers and improve on their
seven interceptions of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stop them and force them to throw the ball in the air,
good things can happen,'' Campo said. ``You've got to stop the run
first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
