r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-04 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE, SOSA BATTER HISTORY INTO CHEAP SEATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead, break it this weekend. Redo history here and now. Do
it in the name of progress. Do it for the good of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this greed-ridden era of baseball desperately needed
something grand, something that could even blow the opening of the
NFL season right off the sporting pages of America.
</P>
<P>
   But...
</P>
<P>
   Does the magical number of 61 have to be surpassed by ``so-sa''
much? By Mark McGwire hitting 70? By Sammy Sosa hitting 67 or 68?
Or who knows, Sosa maybe hitting more than McGwire?
</P>
<P>
   Let that nagging doubt serve as my only regret while the
greatest record in all of sports is about to be ... well, not just
broken, but chopped up like a machete going through sugar cane.
</P>
<P>
   Why 1998? The Roger Maris feat of 61 stood for 37 years, while
Babe Ruth's glorious achievement of 60 in a 154-game season was
untouchable for seven decades. Both will be left in the bat dust of
McGwire and Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Is the expansion-year pitching that bad? What about today's cozy
major league strike zone that ranges from the belly-bottom to the
top of the fly? Was there a sinister plot this season by major
league honchos to secretly juice the ball -- home runs sell
tickets, and this many home runs sell history?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, please be advised that neither McGwire or Sosa had
the pleasure of facing the Rangers' rotation. That might have meant
another 10 homers apiece.
</P>
<P>
   But due to the excitement and the fury at the top of the Maris
chase, few may have noticed that while the long ball derby of '98
will have two players over 60, there will also be two others over
50, and maybe nine to 10 over 40.
</P>
<P>
   One local baseball purist is Doug Melvin, who knows as much
about the inside history of the game as he does today's players.
And the Rangers' general manager takes pride in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the reasons there are this many homers this season, I
don't think that cheapens the accomplishment in any way,'' said
Melvin. ``This year is like the Maris thing in '61, with
expansion-era pitching, the rumors of the ball being wound tighter,
and that stuff. There were a lot of homers in '61 like there are
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I always go back to Ruth, who set the standard for
home runs in his decade \Rthe '20s\S long before he hit 60. No one
was hitting more than 10 and 12 a season, and then one year
\R1920\S he jumped up and hit 54, and then kept going. That, to me,
is the greatest achievement ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Melvin admits he cheers for McGwire and Sosa to
smash history. ``My only regret is the next generation might forget
a Maris or a Ruth,'' he said. ``To them, home-run history will be
all about McGwire and Sosa. Maris should never be just another
footnote in the history books. And, obviously, neither should
Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to current events _ is there any theory involved here
on both McGwire and Sosa being in the National League? The best
sluggers are supposed to be in the other league, where McGwire had
spent a career until late July of 1997. Since going to the National
League he has destroyed bleachers from coast-to-coast.
</P>
<P>
   The belief that NL pitchers challenge the power hitters more
than American Leaguers could be helping McGwire. But why then does
he have a chance to set the major-league record for most walks in a
season? That's not challenging him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the league makes no difference for McGwire. Maybe it's
simply a matter of this being the most healthy season he's ever
had, meaning more at bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in McGwire and in Sosa we are seeing hard work and
coaching pay off in the form of both being more selective at the
plate than anytime in their careers,'' said Toney Howell yesterday
from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Howell has had a front-row seat all season to the heroics of
McGwire and Sosa. He's a National League scout for the Rangers, and
two of the six teams he covers are the Cubs and St. Louis. Very few
have personally seen more at-bats this season from both McGwire and
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also happen to know them personally, and I love the attitude
both are showing over the last few weeks,'' said Howell. ``Even
with everything McGwire has been through with the media, he's now
more open and talkative than ever. That is so good for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitchers did spend about half the season working around
him. Mark took the walks, too. He's disciplined. But lately, the
pitchers have said what-the-heck. I think a lot of these guys want
to try and strike him out. It has made for some great
confrontations, and, yes, for more home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   So many more that the countdown-to-62 begins tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
