<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S.-OPEN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT QUITE SAMPRAS  
 LUCKY TO BE ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Also see TEN-U.S.-OPEN) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At age 18, Marat Safin does not often face someone
younger in a men's tennis tournament. Thursday was an exception,
and when the final 125-mile-an-hour serve had been pummeled, Safin
had given Taylor Dent, 17, a good sense of how much Dent needs to
improve to be competitive in the higher reaches of professional
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to play like Sampras, but he's not Sampras for the
moment,'' Safin said of Dent after beating him 6-3, 6-1, 7-6 (7-2),
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Safin was referring to Pete Sampras, of course, and to Dent's
voracious appetite for risk. But Safin, a Russian teen-ager who
upset Andre Agassi and Gustavo Kuerten en route to the fourth round
of this year's French Open, also had encouraging words for Dent,
son of the former Australian tennis star Phil Dent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to be top 10; maybe not now, but in four
years,'' Safin said. ``He's very young now, and he has not so much
experience. He made a lot of mistakes at the beginning of the
match, but he started to play better in the third set. The first
two, it was so easy. He missed all the balls. But the third was
different. He has unbelievable serve and nice shots, but he's going
for too much. He does not need to go for too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin has been known to get greedy from the baseline himself,
but though he, like Dent, is playing in his first U.S. Open, he is
considerably further along in the developmental, maturation and,
perhaps most important, conditioning process. While the
6-foot-4-inch Safin is built like a whippet and often moves like
one on the court, the 6-3 Dent appears a bit round around the
middle and often appeared a step too slow when Safin stretched him
wide on his forehand. To Dent's credit, he adjusted his tactics in
the third set, taking pace off his ground strokes and his serve in
an attempt to improve his consistency and break Safin's rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I'm just young I guess, and I happen to go off every
so often,'' said Dent, a Californian who turned professional this
week but might still play in next week's junior event. ``But I have
to hand it to the guy. I fought hard. I gave him a chance to mess
up, and he did good.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin was born in Moscow but has lived and trained in Valencia,
Spain, for the last four years. He hits a two-handed backhand as
consistently hard as anyone on tour and, according to Safin's
first-round victim, Magnus Gustafsson, he has a chance to be in the
top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to be there very soon,'' Gustafsson said.
``It depends on his head and who is around him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Safin wants the chance to play Sampras in the fourth round,
he must first get past a man 12 years his senior _ Thomas Muster _
in the next round.
</P>
<P>
   A Fateful Change of Plans
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decision one makes in a couple of seconds and because
of those couple seconds, you're alive,'' Marc Rosset said Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Rosset, the 1992 men's Olympic tennis champion from Switzerland,
and his coach, Pierre Simsolo, had booked seats on Swissair Flight
111, which crashed in the Atlantic Ocean on Wednesday night,
killing everyone on board.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday afternoon, Rosset, who had lost in the first
round on Monday at the U.S. Open, decided to stay in New York and
train for at least another day. He and Simsolo canceled their
reservations, and, on Wednesday evening, after a friend in New York
called and told him to turn on the television, Rosset said he
stayed awake most of the night watching television footage of the
crash scene with a mixture of relief and sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of emotions,'' Rosset said. ``Really, I should have been
on this plane, and then at the last minute I decided not to, so I
am so happy to have a chance to still be alive. But I am also very
sad for the victims and the families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed the footage of the families waiting at the airport
in Geneva. It just makes your heart hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rosset told a Swiss reporter that his parents called him
from Switzerland, he later said that he called his parents and
several of his friends shortly after he realized what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say they were pretty glad to hear my voice,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosset said Thursday that he was not sure when he would be ready
to fly again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I am going to leave tonight,'' he said. ``I am a
little afraid now. I have had car accidents, yet this is quite a
different thing. But I think there is less chance to die on a plane
than on the streets of New York, and I'm still walking around New
York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
