<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CORYATT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FOCUS ON SIGNING FORMER COLT CORYATT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Former Colts linebacker Quentin Coryatt was
expected to visit the Cowboys late yesterday to talk the club about
playing here this season.
</P>
<P>
   But a move to re-sign retired defensive end Charles Haley
appears to have been pushed to the bottom of the club's list of
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt, who has an injured pectoral muscle, took a physical in
Chicago on Wednesday. The Bears decided not to sign him. Before
Coryatt was released from the Colts last week, one of his teammates
questioned Coryatt's ability to play with pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably his worst critic because I tell him day in and
day out that we need him,'' Colts linebacker Jeff Herrod told the
``Indianapolis Star-News''. ``I say `Hey, I've got a fractured
wrist, I'm playing and I'm 32.' Quentin has great ability and he
means a lot to this defense; he's just got to play hurt. That's
something I've done my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys scouting director Larry Lacewell said he has reviewed
game tapes of the linebacker and believes the seventh-year player,
who was released by the Colts in a salary cap move last week, is an
impact player.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said he remembers Coryatt as an
intense competitor who gave the Steelers' offense fits. It was
Coryatt who knocked out Steelers quarterback Kordell Stewart during
a Sunday night game last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quentin is an excellent football player,'' Gailey said. ``I
know what kind of athlete he is. But right now, it's just pure
speculation,'' whether the Cowboys will sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey also said the Cowboys' coaching staff has not had
extensive talks about Haley, who had three back surgeries in four
years before retiring from the Cowboys before the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said team owner Jerry Jones ``made mention of it the
other day for about 10 seconds. I've got a whole bunch of other
things to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was in New York for much of yesterday for league matters
concerning the Cleveland Browns franchise and was unavailable for
comment. Haley, who would have to pass a physical to play again,
was not signed by the San Francisco 49ers after a brief workout in
Santa Clara, Calif., on Tuesday. Briefly Gailey said defensive
tackle Leon Lett (knee) and end Kavika Pittman (ankle) made it
through practice without re-aggravating injuries. He said he
expects both to start Sunday against the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Backup safety George Teague, who missed most of Wednesday's
practice with a strained left hamstring, surprised Gailey by
participating in team workouts yesterday. He could still play on
some passing downs Sunday. ``I don't know if he's 100 percent, but
he looks good enough to play,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The club completed its practice squad by signing wide receiver
Anthony Eubanks and offensive lineman Earl Scott. Defensive back
Zebbie Lethridge was signed to the practice squad Wednesday. Team
vice president Stephen Jones said the Cowboys will only have three
players on the practice squad for now.
Cowboys spotlight How much of a difference would re-signing Charles
Haley make?
</P>
<P>
   It would all depend on Haley's health, and how willing he is to
do things the way Chan Gailey wants them done. Haley has been
working out daily since the spring and despite his recent back
surgeries, he could probably pass a Cowboys physical. If the
Cowboys could get 15 plays a game from him, it would help a pass
rush that has been unimpressive this summer. But Haley's past
relationship with Cowboys defensive coaches was thorny sometimes,
and new coach Chan Gailey would not be expected to allow Haley to
upset team chemistry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
