r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TCU-VIOLATION-TEX     09-04 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-VIOLATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU REPORTS VIOLATION TO NCAA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU has turned itself in to the NCAA for a
violation in connection with the purchase of former basketball
recruit Brian Brookhart's books, athletic director Eric Hyman said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Brookhart's books were mistakenly deducted from the athletic
department budget instead of TCU's general scholarship budget,
Hyman said. According to a receipt obtained by the Star-Telegram,
Brookhart purchased three books for $139.45 on Aug. 21 and then two
more on Aug. 25 for $116.
</P>
<P>
   Brookhart renounced his basketball scholarship on Aug. 19 as a
result of a disagreement about TCU's desire for him to enroll in
junior college. As a concession to Brookhart and his family, TCU
administrators agreed to give Brookhart a scholarship for tuition
and books as a part-time student, once his release from the team
was completed.
</P>
<P>
   By going to school part-time, Brookhart can take classes and not
use up any of his collegiate eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, however, prohibits the athletic department from
contributing to any part of Brookhart's scholarship unless it
counts as a men's basketball scholarship. Hyman and provost William
Koehler said the money to pay for the scholarship should come from
institutional aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an honest mistake,'' said Hyman. ``But any time
something is charged to the incorrect account and you change it to
the correct account, you have to report that.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA director of enforcement Charles E. Smrt would not confirm
that TCU turned itself in, but said a ``secondary'' violation such
as this is considered minor and that his office normally accepts an
athletic department's recommendation for preventing further
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for a secondary violation can range from no action
to a 20 percent reduction in grants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
