r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-TICKET     09-04 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-TICKETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH WEATHERS ECONOMIC WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Tech chancellor John T. Montford lately has enhanced his
reputation as a hands-on administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out collaring people on the sidewalks,'' Montford
said, referring to recent university efforts to boost ticket sales
for tomorrow night's season-opening football game against UT-El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Montford well might find more truth than fiction
in his jest. He is not a reluctant solictor. But few can argue that
the university's strong region-wide marketing push of the past
month _ fueled by an anonymous $200,000 gift _ has turned midsummer
concern into optimism around an athletic department that is
financially challenged because of recent NCAA problems and a
region-wide economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's athletic ticket office had moved only about 20,000
tickets for UTEP just a few weeks ago. Ticket manager Russell
Warren now says with an expected active game-day purchase, he
anticipates a crowd of 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when it's all said and done that our
\Rfootball-generated\S revenue is going to be as good as or better
than it was last year,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is profoundly important to a department confronted by
millions of dollars in expenses and lost revenue because of an NCAA
investigation and subsequent sanctions. Included on the debit sheet
are a forfeited $1.75 million share of Big 12 bowl revenue,
approximately $1.5 million in internal audit and lawyer's fees and
the eventual loss of more than $1 million from the
conference-shared pot of NCAA Tournament-generated basketball
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic department last year operated under a 15 percent
expenditure cut from a $13 million budget. Athletic director Gerald
Myers says the department will again operate under a
yet-to-be-determined percentage slice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any chancellor who says he is not concerned about his athletic
department budget is suspect,'' Montford said. ``But from a
preliminary look at the numbers. ... we frankly made it fine last
year. And I guess I would say I'm cautiously optimistic we'll do
well this year.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude is markedly different from that of midsummer. The
1998 Texas drought will take a heavy fiscal toll when totals are in
from the October cotton harvest. That economic hit is compounded by
the eventual loss of some 600 jobs as a result of a Texas
Instruments plant closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier this summer, we were extremely concerned about the
economic factors,'' Warren said. ``The TI closing was a factor, but
the majority of it had to do with the cotton crop. Because out
here, everything goes the way cotton goes. And we had a sense of
urgency as to how we were going to combat this.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic department officials formulated a marketing plan.
Montford secured the donation that spawned a campaign that included
60-second television spots and billboards throughout the South
Plains region. Montford appeared in the spots along with Tech
president Donald Haragan, Myers and head coach Spike Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   Montford and Haragan also put their money where their mouths
were. They and health and sciences center president David R. Smith
donated $20,000 toward purchase of 4,000 UTEP tickets that have
been offered to faculty and staff for $5 apiece. Tech's strong
legion of supporters has also responded. Myers says Red Raider Club
donations of more than $1 million are up approximately $50,000 over
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans, our boosters and our alumni have all stuck with
us,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Warren estimates season-ticket purchases are down
approximately 5 percent, he says individual-game tickets are moving
_ in part because of response to selective promotional packages
offered individuals and local corporate partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``People out here tend to rise to the occasion,'' Montford said.
``I've been out here since 1971, and Lubbock as well as the South
Plains is pretty resilient. It seems like we rebound pretty well in
these downturn cycles. And in an agriculturally based economy, you
get used to those.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the economic situation nor NCAA problems has affected
response to the seat-option purchase plan for the United Spirit
Arena, which is scheduled to open for spring '99 graduation
ceremonies. That program has taken in more than $5.3 million,
according to program administrator and assistant AD Joe Hornaday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not seen any change in the buying habits of our fans,''
Hornaday said. ``The entertainment dollar out here is such that
people may be a little more particular where they spend it, but
athletics is such a high priority that most people feel comfortable
in continuing to support the various programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA investigation has had almost no impact that I can
tell. In part, that's because this is a 10-year commitment and
people knew the NCAA stuff would be over early in the program and
they wanted to go ahead and wrap up good seats for the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
