u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-JETER-NYT &LR;      09-04 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JETER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETER'S SEASON NOT WASTED ON YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whenever Derek Jeter's name is announced, whenever he
gets another pivotal hit or whenever he makes another slick
fielding play, the reaction is much different than it is for other
Yankees. For others at Yankee Stadium, there are roars. But for
Jeter, there are squeals. They escalate as if Jeter were a singer
with the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The young fans, especially young girls, marvel at Jeter. They
adore him because he is young and handsome, because he plays
shortstop for the Yankees and because he even chats with fans from
the on-deck area.
</P>
<P>
   Do not let the squealing obscure how important Jeter is to the
Yankees. Even the smartest baseball scout might squeal after
watching Jeter play. It sounds cliche, but the 24-year-old Jeter
keeps improving every day. It is not cliche to reason that Jeter is
as valuable a player as the record-setting Yankees have.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that raises another question. If Jeter is the most
valuable Yankee _ and it probably is either Jeter or Bernie
Williams during this special season _ could the shortstop also be
the most valuable player in the American League? It is an arduous
question because there are several worthwhile candidates, like
Williams, Boston's Nomar Garciaparra or Mo Vaughn and Texas' Juan
Gonzalez. Still, Jeter definitely belongs in this discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone would love to be the MVP,'' Jeter said. ``I think a
lot of guys on this team could be MVP. We have a lot of guys who
have done well this season. Regardless of what your numbers are, we
have a lot of guys having great seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Jeter handles questions about personal accomplishments
the way he might react to swallowing vinegar. He looks at his feet,
utters something about not being perfect until he bats 1.000 and
makes no errors and shifts the focus to the Yankees. Jeter has been
this modest since his 1996 rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter embraced a discussion about the MVP long enough to
thrust support behind his type of player. While not necessarily
pushing himself for MVP, Jeter argued that the award should not
simply be given to a player who has the gaudiest numbers and
stressed the value of intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flattering to have your name mentioned,'' said Jeter, who
is second in the league with a .335 average, and also has 17
homers, 73 runs batted in, a league-high 111 runs scored and 25
stolen bases. ``I'm not going to hit 50 homers or have 180 RBIs.
Not too many people can do that. But you can work on the little
things and the things that are valuable to your team. For me, it's
moving a guy over, bunting and playing defense. A lot of people
look at homers and RBIs as the only thing that's important, and
that's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Jeter mentioned how shortstop Barry Larkin won the award
with Cincinnati in 1995 while hitting .319 with 15 homers, 66 RBI
and 51 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``MVP is the most valuable player,'' Jeter said, ``not
necessarily the player who had the best numbers or had the best
year.''
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Torre was asked about the MVP, the first name that
spilled out of his mouth was Jeter, then Williams, who leads the
American League with a .341 average.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it tough with our ball club is we've had so many
players contribute, there will be a splitting of the votes,'' Torre
said. ``All of a sudden, the guy with the best numbers gets it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although that might be Gonzalez (.306, 39 homers, a major
league-best 144 RBI), Garciaparra has incredible statistics for a
shortstop (.324, 30 homers, 110 RBI) and is probably the
front-runner to win. Or will Vaughn, the soul of the Red Sox and a
.331 hitter with 34 homers, snag more votes? What about Williams, a
center fielder and integral switch-hitter with 21 homers and 83
RBI?
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeter what he needs to improve on and he responds like a
high school senior addressing a college coach. He wants to run the
bases better, reduce his strikeouts, boost his on-base percentage,
cut down on his errors and belt 30 homers. Most important, the MVP
candidate wants to continue hearing squeals until the Yankees win
another ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we can have a better season than when we won the
World Series in 1996 is to do it again,'' Jeter said. ``Regardless
of what we do in the regular season, unless we win the World Series
again, it's not going to be very rewarding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
