<SLUG> BC-NJ-STOCK-EXCHANGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY SEEKS TO LURE AMEX AND NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ State officials are involved in talks intended to
woo the nation's second- and third-largest stock exchanges out of
New York City and into a new home in New Jersey, an economic
development official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Lisa Kruse, who is the vice president for
marketing and development for the New Jersey Commerce and Economic
Growth Commission, confirmed unattributed reports in The Newark
Star-Ledger on Thursday that the state was talking to the
computerized Nasdaq Exchange and the American Stock Exchange about
a possible move to New Jersey. She would not disclose the locations
involved, but the published reports said that Jersey City and
Hoboken had been mentioned as possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both exchanges, which are working out the final
details of the merger that their members approved three months ago,
would not comment on whether they were involved in any talks.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Nasdaq has 3,100 employees in New York City,
Washington and its suburbs and Trumbull, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The 77-year-old American Stock Exchange, which has 600 employees
and 1,500 traders, is spread over three lower Manhattan locations.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Smith, executive vice president of Hartz Mountain
Industries, a developer of office space along the Hudson River and
elsewhere in the state, said he had no knowledge of such talks, but
he added that he was not surprised at the reports. All the
exchanges have expressed a need for new and larger sites, and now
New Jersey seems to have an edge over New York when it comes to the
cost and availability of office space, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, the savings of New Jersey over New York were
substantial, and it appears that we may be approaching that kind of
era again,'' Smith said. ``Every businessman, it seems to me, has
to periodically address the cost of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of the talks comes on the heels of reports in May that
New Jersey was trying to interest the New York Stock Exchange in
moving. Over the years, New Jersey has been a perennial option, but
it has lost out more than it has won; in many cases it appears that
companies used the threat of moving to New Jersey to wring more
incentives out of New York City and state officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
