<SLUG> BC-CRASH-VICTIMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH OF `U.N. AIRBUS' CLAIMED LIVES FROM MANY COUNTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to delete original lede graf; in 5th graf breakdown of the
victims' nationalities, changes ``United Kingdom'' to ``Britain,''
adds ``three from Germany'' and changes ``St. Kitts'' to ``St.
Kitts and Nevis''; in 10th graf of 2nd take, gives more accurate
information about John Mortimer; in hed, changes ``a dozen'' to
``many'') (ART ADV: Graphic on the crash's death toll is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-SCENE, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-FAMILIES,
CRASH-OBIT-MANN and CRASH-OBIT-CLEMENTS-MANN) (mk) 
 By N.R. KLEINFIELD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Swissair Flight 111 plunged into the inky waters
off Nova Scotia Wednesday night, it took an uncommon number of
lives of dogged humanitarianism. It claimed a tireless battler
against the scourge of AIDS and researchers perched on the
seemingly fathomless frontiers of science.
</P>
<P>
   It took a contingent of U.N. workers settled into a flight as
familiar and reassuring to them as the evening commuter train,
people who intrepidly hopscotched across the tender borders of
war-torn nations but met their end near a tranquil fishing village.
But most starkly it visited heartache on a dozen countries on two
continents.
</P>
<P>
   The cold statistics of the disaster were merciless. All 215
passengers and 14 crew members on the plane bound for Geneva from
Kennedy Airport in New York died.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger roster was something of a kaleidoscope of the
world's nations. Swissair said there were 136 passengers from the
United States, 30 from France and 28 from Switzerland. A half-dozen
came from Britain, three from Italy and three from Germany. There
were two passengers from Greece mixed in with solitary travelers
from Saudia Arabia, Yugoslavia, Afghanistan, Spain, Iran, St. Kitts
and Nevis, and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Air disasters rarely excuse anyone. Two of the victims were mere
infants. One man was bumped off two other flights that night before
getting a seat on the one that would never land.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday night, Swissair had not yet released the
passenger manifest of Flight 111, as officials continued the grim
task of notifying relatives. However, colleagues and relatives
confirmed the identities of some of those who boarded the doomed
airliner.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan Mann, who helped shape the international campaign
against AIDS, was traveling on the flight with his wife, Dr. Mary
Lou Clements, to attend AIDS-related meetings in Geneva. A public
health physician, he founded the Global Program on AIDS in 1986 for
the World Health Organization. In 1990, he resigned in bitter
protest against WHO's failure to move faster, and recently he
became the first dean of a new public health school at Allegheny
University of the Health Sciences in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clements was an epidemiologist and vaccine expert who headed
the center for immunization research at the Johns Hopkins
University School of Hygiene and Public Health. Both she and her
husband were 51 and lived in Columbia, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Gostin, a director of the Georgetown University-Johns
Hopkins University Program on law and public health who knew Mann
for some 20 years, remembered Thursday how he had accompanied Mann
on the first day he entered the WHO building in Geneva: ``It was
literally Jon and one Swiss secretary. He built that program within
a matter of years to be, by far, the largest disease- prevention
program in the history of the WHO. That alone, his mobilization of
the world against AIDS, is his greatest legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Mann, one of Mann's daughters, is a student of Gostin's at
Georgetown University Law Center. Gostin said he spoke to her only
hours before the crash and she mentioned that her father was
contemplating moving overseas to reapply his zeal to international
work.
</P>
<P>
   To workers at the United Nations, the nightly Flight 111 was
affectionately known as the U.N. airbus because it served as
something of a commuter flight for officials and diplomats
shuttling back and forth between the secretariat in New York and
the European headquarters in Geneva. ``This is a flight that so
many of us take routinely that I think it spooked a lot of us,''
said Fred Eckhard, the U.N.'s senior spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Few Swissair 111 flights lift off without at least a few U.N.
people buckled into their seats. And thus as soon as U.N. workers
learned the flight number, they knew that some of their people were
gone.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials identified seven staff members or associates,
including Mann, as having perished in Wednesday's crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heartfelt sympathy goes out to the families of all the
victims, and in particular to the relatives and friends of all
those who lost their lives in the service of the ideals of the
United Nations,'' said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan from
Durban, South Africa, where he was attending the summit meeting of
nonaligned nations.
</P>
<P>
   The victims included Pierce Gerety, 56, an American lawyer who
had devoted his life to the plight of refugees. Only an unlikely
convergence of events put him on the plane. According to his
brother, Tom Gerety, president of Amherst College, he had a ticket
for a KLM flight to Amsterdam. It was overbooked and he was bumped
along with some others. He was put on a Swissair flight. It was
canceled. His consolation was a ticket on Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   In charge of operations for the U.N. High Commission for
Refugees in the ravaged Great Lakes region of Central Africa,
including Rwanda, Gerety seemed to spend more nights in tents with
refugees than he did in his own home. Wherever war, famine and
social unrest uprooted people from their homes, he was there. Time
and again, he stared death in its face and scared it off.
Associates said he was shot at, narrowly evaded bombs and never
shied from jumping aboard a rickety plane for a perilous flight
into the bush. They could only wonder how he could die in the
comfort of a gleaming commercial jet.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Calvert-Mazy, 37, a French social worker and therapist
who worked as senior welfare officer in the Geneva headquarters of
the refugee unit, also died in the crash. She had counseled
refugees in Bosnia, Mali and Rwanda, and had transferred to Geneva
in June so she could spend more time with her husband and baby.
</P>
<P>
   Others victims among the U.N. family were Joachim Bilger and
Ludwig Beaumler, Germans who were respectively the controller in
the office of internal oversight and productivity and the senior
director for international and operational affairs with the World
Intellectual Property Organization in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8601 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     09-04 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS MUST TAKE GAMBLES LIKE CORYATT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were two things working against that foolhardy notion of
Charles Haley returning to the Cowboys' fold:
</P>
<P>
   A bulging disk and a big mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Both, as it turned out, have been detrimental to Haley's NFL
career, though the official stance at Valley Ranch has always been
that Planet Haley was an amiable, semi-cooperative sort.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   As Owner Jones indicated Wednesday, the Cowboys didn't think it
was anybody's best interests for the Planet Haley to resume his
local orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the guy apparently can still play _ he can still rush the
quarterback on scattered downs. But he can't practice. And maybe by
December, when a team would really need him, Haley wouldn't be able
to bend over to tie his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Is he worth the trouble, not to mention the expense?
</P>
<P>
   No, and Owner Jones agrees. Which means whatever money the
Cowboys can jiggle free from the NFL salary cap can go to
linebacker Quentin Coryatt.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys want to take a look at the former Texas Aggie
headhunter, who was officially declared a $19.5 million bust in
Indianapolis earlier this week. They want to take a closer look at
the once-torn pectoral muscle that he says still hurts him, but
that left the Colts doubting.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to his job interview here, Coryatt reportedly did not
pass medical muster with the Chicago Bears. It should give pause to
all loyal Cowboys fans. The Bears, after all, are in a position to
refuse no one, unless he has a note from the coroner.
</P>
<P>
   But this is what the Cowboys have had to resort to in the wake
of Broderick Thomas' season-ending knee injury in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt should not be considered a pass-rush specialist. The man
has 8 1/2 sacks in six NFL seasons _ more than $2 million per sack.
But the Cowboys apparently think Coryatt could help at the outside
linebacker spot and allow them to move Randall Godfrey inside.
</P>
<P>
   You do what you have to do. Not all that long ago, the Cowboys
dealt from a full deck. But free agency and their self-imposed
salary-cap stranglehold have made them 11th-hour scramblers, just
like the Bears, Giants, Redskins and, egads, even the proud 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Just wondering, but what do you suppose was really going on
inside 49ers quarterback Steve Young's oft-flogged head Wednesday
when he learned that Haley had been in for a visit? Wasn't it Haley
who dedicated an entire chapter in his autobiography (Haley, a
writer?) to saying Young couldn't hold Joe Montana's Jockey shorts?
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it Haley who bathed, so to speak, his exit from San
Francisco by relieving himself on a teammate's car tires?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the proud 49ers franchise must have had to swallow hard
just to let the Planet Haley back on the grounds, albeit for a
brief workout. But you do what you have to do.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco's case, there is a troubling lack of depth in
the defensive line. The 49ers have had draft problems. Younger,
stronger backs have come and some have gone _ Tim Harris? Todd
Kelly? _ but the 49ers have never really replaced Haley.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cowboys can attest, even the proudest of teams can make
drafting mistakes. With the release this week of Stepfret Williams
and Steve Scifres, the Cowboys symbolically admitted again that
their recent drafts have been cluttered with mistakes. There is no
one to show from the 1993 draft. The only one left from the 1994
draft is Larry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   So a team does what it has to do. It looks to a Coryatt, hoping
there is something left in the tank of a once-lofty draft choice
whose career may have turned perpetually south. Bad pectoral muscle
and all.
</P>
<P>
   In Coryatt's case, the gamble is one that a team coming off a
6-10 season must take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
