<HEADLINE>
NBA LOCKOUT ILLEGAL, UNION SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The basketball players' union contends that there is no
stipulation in the contracts of the 225 players who have guaranteed
salaries that enables National Basketball Association owners to
lock them out without pay.
</P>
<P>
   The owners' response is that a clause in the NBA's last
collective bargaining agreement, signed in 1995, allowed the owners
to shut down business and reopen the agreement if the players made
more than 51.8 percent of the league's basketball-related income in
a season.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, player salaries accounted for roughly 55 to 57
percent of such income.
</P>
</TEXT>
