<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD SAYS HE WAS ASKED TO HELP TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evander Holyfield said Thursday that he was
approached by a member of the New Jersey State Athletic Control
Board in July and urged to write a letter in support of Mike
Tyson's getting a license to fight in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield would not identify the board member and was sketchy in
describing the details of what had been asked of him. But it was a
curious admission by the World Boxing Association and International
Boxing Federation heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him what it should say, and I signed the letter,''
Holyfield said at a luncheon in Manhattan to promote his Sept. 19
fight against Vaughn Bean in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson withdrew his application to the New Jersey board one day
before it was to render a decision and immediately filed for
reinstatement in Nevada, which had revoked his license to fight
last year. A hearing is scheduled there on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Phone messages to the offices of the New Jersey board were not
immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Tyson, Anthony Fusco Jr., presented a letter signed
by Holyfield at the July 29 hearing before the board. The letter
said that Holyfield did not have any objections to Tyson's
receiving a license despite the incident in the championship bout
in Las Vegas, Nev., on June 28, 1997, in which Tyson bit
Holyfield's ears. The Nevada State Athletic Commission revoked his
license and fined him $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said Thursday that he was willing to fight Tyson
again, but did not think such a bout would happen.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-hour talk with reporters, Holyfield was sympathetic to
Tyson's problems, which worsened this week when two men filed
assault charges against Tyson following a traffic accident in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson will be back,'' Holyfield said. ``And he's going to whip
everybody out there, except me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
