</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FAMILIES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES RUSH TO ACCOMMODATE NEEDS OF SURVIVORS' NEXT OF KIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Adds details on services for families in Geneva; adds quote
from parent of TWA victim; polishing and rewriting throughout.)   (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-SCENE, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-VICTIMS,
CRASH-OBIT-MANN, CRASH-OBIT-CLEMENTS-MANN and CRASH-OBIT-GERETY)  
(js) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As relatives of passengers aboard Swissair Flight 111 filed into
the Ramada Plaza Hotel at Kennedy International Airport in New York
on Thursday and huddled in a private conference room to wrestle
with their grief, the scene carried poignant echoes of July 1996,
when families reeling from the crash of Trans World Airlines Flight
800 gathered under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
   There was a similar sense of astonishment over what had
happened. There was a similar hunger to know how and why.
</P>
<P>
   But to help relatives deal with the shock of Wednesday's crash,
Swissair and Delta, the U.S. carrier through which some passengers
had booked their tickets, flooded both the Ramada in Queens and the
airport in Geneva with airline officials, grief counselors and
clergy members.
</P>
<P>
   The two airlines seemed intent on avoiding the fury that TWA
drew from some relatives and politicians for taking too long to
confirm Flight 800's passenger list and not tending aggressively
enough to families' needs.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Hauer, director of New York City's Office of Emergency
Management, said there was ``no comparison'' between the actions of
Swissair and Delta and those of TWA two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an extraordinary amount of care and attention
paid to the details, which can make a horrendous situation that
much more horrendous,'' Hauer said Thursday. ``I've seen questions
get answered, and I've seen needs get met quickly, efficiently and
with great compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   But even such painstaking accommodations could do little to
assuage survivors' sorrow. At the Geneva airport, as the passenger
list was read out loud Thursday, relatives hearing the names of
loved ones broke into sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was there,'' one person blurted out. ``Oh, my God.''
</P>
<P>
   In the conference room in the Ramada, the somber atmosphere was
interrupted at one point by a woman's uncontrollable screaming.
Darren Mudge, a Salvation Army officer who was there, said she was
quickly taken out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of thing can become contagious, because everyone is
right there, on the edge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who stormed television news programs in
1996 to attack TWA, offered Swissair and Delta nothing but praise
at a press conference early Thursday evening at the Ramada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines have handled this exceptionally well from the
beginning,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 111 went down on Wednesday around 9:30 p.m. EST, and by
1:10 a.m. Thursday, according to a spokesman for Swissair, the
airline was providing information on the identity of passengers to
relatives over a special telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, it took nearly 20 hours for TWA to provide a
passenger manifest to New York City officials who repeatedly
requested one.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ed Merlis, a senior vice president with the Air Transport
Association, a trade group that represents U.S. airlines, said the
Family Assistance Act, a federal law passed in 1996 in response to
criticisms leveled against TWA, compels airlines to work as quickly
as possible to release passenger lists following crashes. Although
it applies only to crashes in the United States, he said, most
airlines have adopted that standard.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair and Delta also hurried to make flight arrangements for
relatives who wanted to fly to Halifax, Nova Scotia, near the site
of the crash. Charter flights from both Geneva and Newark were
scheduled to arrive there Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, relatives were assisted by clergy members from the
city's religious community, and by psychologists and physicians.
</P>
<P>
   A Muslim cleric, Ouardiri Hafid, described the gathering of
families as one of ``great dignity, great silence.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, counselors at the Ramada outnumbered relatives
3-to-1; many had rushed automatically to the hotel as soon as they
heard about the crash because they remembered the important role
they had played for relatives in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some relatives of the passengers aboard TWA Flight
800 began making plans to travel to Halifax to offer support to the
newly grieving mothers and fathers, daughters and sons, who would
be gathering there.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Becker of St. Petersburg, Fla., whose 19-year-old
daughter, Michele, was killed aboard Flight 800, said late Thursday
night that the Flight 800 families were merely awaiting assurance
from Delta that they would be able to see the relatives of
passengers who died on Swissair Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   Those relatives would be experiencing an agonizing ordeal, he
said, recalling the loneliness and confusion he felt in 1996.
``You're thinking that you're totally isolated and that something's
wrong with you,'' Becker said in a telephone interview. ``It still
comes and goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ROSS-LIBERALS-350&AMP;     09-04 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ROSS-LIBERALS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAUGHEY ROSS' MONEY PROBLEMS MAY HURT LIBERAL PARTY  
 (With NY-ROSS-CAMPAIGN)  
 (bl)  
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The financial problems hobbling the gubernatorial
campaign of Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross are also threatening the
viability of the New York state Liberal Party, which has staked its
future on her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The party chose Ms. McCaughey Ross as its candidate last spring
after concluding that she was its best bet to draw 50,000 votes in
the general election, a threshold that would allow the Liberals to
meet the legal requirement for retaining a place on the ballot for
the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a boon to the party that Ms. McCaughey Ross' husband
_ Wall Street financier Wilbur Ross _ pledged to spend millions of
dollars to underwrite her quest.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal nomination was an important victory for Ms.
McCaughey Ross, guaranteeing her a spot on the November ballot even
if she lost the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   But considerable doubt was cast Thursday on Ms. McCaughey Ross'
prospects of either winning the Democratic primary Sept. 15 against
three other major candidates or having a strong showing on the
Liberal Party line in November. After weeks of speculation, she
announced that her husband had taken back most of the roughly $4
million he had donated to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party's longtime leader, Raymond Harding, seemed
unfazed by the news. He predicted that even without the money, Ms.
McCaughey Ross would draw at least 50,000 votes on the Liberal
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am perfectly content with the situation the way it is,''
Harding said. ``We support her fully and expect her to wage a
vigorous campaign right through Nov. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   But people who follow state politics said the financial loss
could mean trouble for Harding, who has led the Liberal Party for
most of the last 20 years and whose political influence could be
sharply diminished if Ms. McCaughey Ross loses badly in November.
</P>
<P>
   Without a large campaign war chest, Ms. McCaughey Ross is
unlikely to do well in the Democratic primary, they said. And
without a strong showing in the primary, the lieutenant governor is
unlikely to win many votes on the Liberal line in November.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``She can't get it without the money,'' said former Gov. Mario
Cuomo, a Democrat who drew 92,000 votes on the Liberal line in 1994
despite losing the general election to Republican challenger George
Pataki. ``Money is just about the sine qua non.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party's choice of Ms. McCaughey Ross strained
relations between the party and Democrats, which have been tense
since 1989, when the Liberal Party began supporting New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats have complained that the party embraced Ms.
McCaughey Ross, who was a Republican until last year, only because
she was a woman and had promised to spend a considerable amount of
money on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Ms. McCaughey Ross announced her financial problems
Thursday, rumors were swirling that Harding was eagerly seeking a
new candidate. But Harding on Thursday described the rumors as
``disinformation.'' He pointed out that under state election law,
party nominees can be replaced only if they die, receive federal
judgeships or move out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is silly season,'' he said. ``People will say anything
during the early periods of campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding said it was unfortunate that so much attention had been
paid to Ms. McCaughey Ross' money problems. But, he added, the
focus on Ms. McCaughey Ross' finances was a sign that the campaigns
of the three Democratic candidates _ New York City Council Speaker
Peter Vallone, former state Transportation Commissioner James
Larocca and Brooklyn District Attorney Charles Hynes.
</P>
<P>
   Harding said his party would work hard to raise money for Ms.
McCaughey Ross this fall. He had planned to do that anyway, he
said, because the donation from Ms. McCaughey Ross' husband was to
be spent only on the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harding said, Ms. McCaughey Ross should stop talking
about money and focus on issues like education and health care.
``The reason the Liberal Party nominated her is her close
identification with certain issues,'' he said, ``and she has been
faithful to those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said he did not think the Liberal Party could raise much
money for Ms. McCaughey Ross. But he added that he would not be
surprised if Ross put a significant amount of money back into his
wife's campaign after the primary _ even if she is running only as
a Liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong to conclude that if he doesn't spend it now, he
won't spend it in November,'' Cuomo said. ``Nothing would surprise
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
