<HEADLINE>
AT SARATOGA, 2-YEAR-OLDS IN SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Some of the most accomplished and most
ambitious 2-year-old horses in the country will try to pass
milestones on the road to juvenile championships in the next two
days when Saratoga stages two Grade I stakes for beginners: the
Spinaway on Friday for fillies and the Hopeful on Saturday for
colts.
</P>
<P>
   The races mark the third and final stakes in Saratoga's cycle
for juveniles, and they are the richest in money and career values,
each with a purse of $200,000, each at seven furlongs, each filled
with history. In this decade alone, four Spinaway winners have gone
on to win the juvenile championship: Meadow Star in 1990, Flanders
in 1994, Golden Attraction in 1995 and Countess Diana in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This year's class strikes most observers as somewhat softer in
talent, but the Spinaway could give a substantial boost to the
credentials of the favorite, Things Change, who won the Adirondack
last month in only the third start of her career. Her trainer,
Linda Rice, has posted a high-yield record with five winners in 15
starts at Saratoga this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things Change is coming into this race in great shape,'' Rice
reported. ``Based on the numbers for her last race, she should move
forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
