A8616 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MISSOURI-PREVIEW-     09-04 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MISSOURI-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAN HELPS RESURRECT MISSOURI FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (One of a series) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missouri safety Caldrinoff Easter doesn't have to go far when he
yearns to talk to somebody from home _ he goes to football
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston native is one of 13 Texans on the Tigers' roster.
Twice that number are found at fellow Big 12 member Oklahoma, but
Missouri's Lone Star State contingent is second only to the 58
Missourians who wear the black and gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how nice it is to have these other guys up
here,'' said Easter, a strong safety with a reputation as a big
hitter who is scheduled to start his 23rd consecutive game tomorrow
night against Bowling Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came up here \R1995\S, I was one of the only
\RTexans\S up here. Really, being a Texas guy, at first I didn't
even know where Missouri was on the map. It was a hard adjustment,
but I played through it. And having other Texans up here supports
my bragging. Because I've been telling people up here all along
what Texans can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Easter needn't have wasted his time with fifth-year Missouri
coach Larry Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second-most number of players on our team is from Texas,
and that's by design,'' Smith said. ``Part of our recruiting
philosophy all along has been to get into the Texas high school
recruiting scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Texans reside on the two-deep roster of Missouri's featured
offense. Though quarterback Corby Jones finished high school at
Columbia (Mo.) Hickman, he went through the 10th grade in
Richardson, where he was good friends with Tigers redshirt junior
defensive tackle Steve Erickson. Easter and Erickson both play
prominent roles on a Missouri defense whose improvement is regarded
as key if the Tigers are to enhance last year's breakthrough 7-5
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both those guys have been in our system for four years, and
they bring a lot of experience,'' Smith said. ``They are both pure
football players who have been taught well in high school. Football
is important to them. They have been a big part of the rebuilding
of our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri won only 11 of 34 games through Smith's first three
seasons before recording the Tigers' first winning season since
1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a difference in attitude,'' Erickson said. ``Like night
and day from when I first came in. But we want more. We're going
after the big prize now. And I'm so pumped, I think it's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers ranked 84th nationally in scoring defense a year ago.
But Smith has pointed out some extenuating circumstances that led
to the conclusion Missouri was weaker defensively than it actually
was. Though they surrendered an average of 30.5 points a game, 76
points came after victory was assured. Twenty points came in
overtime and special-teams breakdowns figured in 23 opposition
drives of 56 yards or less. And over the latter half of the season,
MU had a 13-5 advantage in turnover ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to focus on playing better defense against the score
and cutting down on big plays,'' Smith said. ``We did improve on
forcing turnovers and we want to continue to improve on that. It
was a significant reason why we won four of our last five games.''
</P>
<P>
   Easter expects six returning starters and a wealth of backup
experience to translate into a defense that is not just an
afterthought to the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed up a few things to utilize our speed and
experience,'' Easter said. ``When you've been in a system as long
as most of us have, it's a wonder what you can do out there
adjusting things. But this year, we want to make people adjust to
us _ not us adjusting to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense was really getting after people by the end of the
season. We felt like we gave up way too many points last year and
we want to cut that in half. Our offense does an excellent job. But
we have to take up some slack. We have to be the ones controlling
things out there.''
Missouri at a glance
</P>
<P>
   1997 record: 7-5 (Plymouth Holiday Bowl), 5-3 in Big 12
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Larry Smith, 18-27-1 (128-107-7 overall)
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Memorial, Faurot Field (62,000)
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters: Offense _ 8, Defense _ 6
</P>
<P>
   All-star candidates: QB Corby Jones, OT Todd Neimeyer, FS Harold
Piersey
</P>
<P>
   Key newcomers: Jr-Tr RB Rob West, Fr-DE Justin Smith, Jr-Tr DL
Terrell Jurineack
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
