r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WAC-REPORT-TEX     09-04 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WAC-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAC'S FINAL RIDE WITH 16 PROMISES INTRIGUE, PASSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the poor, misbegotten Western Athletic Conference wobbled
into its final months as an overstuffed, underpaid curiosity,
suddenly there was a bolt of lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Up in East Lansing, Mich., a moment of redemption arrived for
the long-suffering, oft-abused and officially shattered league.
</P>
<P>
   Here were the Colorado State Rams _ ranked higher than they have
ever been since statehood _ taking on Michigan State in front of
almost 70,000 Big Ten types and a national viewing audience.
</P>
<P>
   In a daring ploy, they spotted the hosts 16 points, then raised
the flag and mounted a charge. The startled Spartans were rolled
under as if they were just another band of pilgrims from San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, what a moment, what a ... uh, hold it, something seems amiss
here. HEY! WHERE'S THE LOGO?!?!
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it develops that in this moment of glittering triumph, the
Rams showed up practically nude: no WAC logo on the jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the booth, the gents reporting it all to a grateful nation
were clearly confused. Or as one kept saying to the other,
``Y'know, Dan, this doesn't really look like a WAC team ... more
like a Big Ten team, wouldn't you say?''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, of course, it did not escape notice that CSU
is one of the eight defecting schools, and reasonable minds
instantly spotted a tawdry plot to discredit the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   But after a quick phone call to CSU athletic director Tim
Weiser, commissioner Karl Benson pronounced himself satisfied that
it was an ``oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wearing new jerseys,'' Benson said, ``and the
equipment manager simply did not get around to sewing the patches
on. Tim has assured me they will be on for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   This was met with the standard query: ``So, Karl, you're
satisfied there's no conspiracy here?''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the final days of the old WAC, which should prove
entertaining, if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Logos aside, the Rams' day on national TV was not a cheery
occasion for the schools that will constitute the WAC next year.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the gratuitous slam from ESPN analyst Lee Corso was
replaced by something far more graphic: a comparison of records
over the last two years, leading the boys in the booth to the
conclusion that the ``haves'' were defecting and the ``have nots''
would be left to carry the WAC banner next year.
</P>
<P>
   Juxtaposed against the image of CSU conquering the Spartans was
the announcement that TCU had opted to punt a three-game series
with Nebraska off the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``new'' WAC isn't exactly mummified.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50,000 are expected at Rice Stadium when the Owls and
SMU _ two of the more combative WAC teams in any scenario _ tee it
up tomorrow night in the traditional season-opening promotion.
</P>
<P>
   This one will benefit the Houston Food Bank, and could bring a
larger crowd than the 53,145 who showed up last year for Rice's
game against Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Average attendance is up to more than 35,000 a game _ more than
twice what it was 10 years ago _ and the Owls have won seven games
in back-to-back years for the first time since 1960-61.
</P>
<P>
   An ``academic'' school, Rice has revived under Ken Hatfield to
the point that it is now competitive with everyone in its own
league and has dotted upcoming schedules with Michigan, Nebraska,
Oklahoma and Texas and is feeling good about the future.
</P>
<P>
   SMU, which came up a winner last year for the first time since
'86, has a $50 million building program in progress and an
aggressive program under Mike Cavan. Both schools believe they can
survive the next couple of years and come out in good shape on the
other side of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win some championships and keep bringing people out
to see what our program is like and what our kids represent,''
Hatfield says. ``This is a great school, and there is a feeling on
the part of the remaining WAC schools that whatever happens, we
will stick it out together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the festivities in Houston will be the inauguration of a
new trophy _ the Mayor's Cup, which will be awarded annually to the
winner of the SMU-Rice game. Designed to strengthen the rivalry _
and the interest in it _ the concept is similar to that of The Iron
Skillet, which is awarded each year to the TCU-SMU winner.
</P>
<P>
   This one, however, has a new twist. All parties have agreed that
the mayor of the losing borough will show up at the next city
council meeting decked out in an elegant ensemble featuring the
winning school's game jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature of Saturday's game will be a halftime ceremony
in which former Rice All-American Dicky Maegle will present his
Cotton Bowl Hall of Fame trophy to the university.
</P>
<P>
   Maegle, a member of the inaugural class of inductees this
summer, gained fame in the 1954 game when Alabama's Tommy Lewis
lurched off the bench and tackled him as he ran down the sideline
en route to a 95-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   Officials awarded him the balance of the run, and Maegle went on
to score three times and establish a still-standing record of 265
yards rushing, as the Owls won, 28-6.
Still in awe
</P>
<P>
   Although Colorado State is loaded, is riding a 10-game winning
streak, and thoroughly dominated Michigan State in the second half
Saturday, coach Sonny Lubick was still a bit awed by the day's
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I've been around too long,'' he said. ``I go back far
enough to where teams like Michigan State still conjure up a lot of
fear in you. We got out there in front of all those people, and I
still had that thought, like, `I wonder if any of us really knows
what we're doing here?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ranked higher (15th) than we've ever been in ...
probably eternity. But it was still CSU against Michigan State, and
this school had never beaten a Big Ten team.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Rams got the expected strong performances from
stars Damon Washington, Kevin McDougal and Darran Hall, the big
news was senior quarterback Ryan Eslinger, making his first
collegiate start after backing up Moses Moreno for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Eslinger hit 13 of 26 passes for 205 yards and a touchdown,
effectively erasing what was considered CSU's biggest doubt about
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it was a great win,'' said Lubick, whose team faces
Colorado this weekend. ``but I kinda wish it had been the last game
of the year. Then I could spend a few days strutting around
celebrating, maybe getting a few free beers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, I have to spend the whole week trying to tell people
it was no big deal.''
Buzz
</P>
<P>
   A change of position is one thing, but San Jose State coach Dave
Baldwin] was taken aback when Carlos Meeks, his top rusher,
approached him last spring. ``He said he was quitting football
because he wanted to become a rapper,'' Baldwin recalled. But after
a brief fling in the music world, Meeks was back during two-a-day
practices, asking to be reinstated. ``I let the seniors vote on it,
and it was unanimous,'' Baldwin said. ``So we have our leading
rusher back.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   When Hawaii faced Arizona last night, two former Rainbows
coaches were on the Wildcats sideline _ head coach Dick Tomey and
assistant Bob Wagner. Asked if this brought extra significance to
the game, UH coach Fred vonAppen replied, ``We're not playing their
staff. As far as I know, no one has arranged a scrimmage between
the coaches.'' VonAppen was more concerned about his own team _
especially the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   While most coaches pronounced themselves ready to finally play a
game, Fresno State's Pat Hill said he is glad his team iss off this
week. ``We have 105 players, and 80 of them are in their first or
second year,'' he said. ``We need another week off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa's Dave Rader, on running back Reggie Williams, who led the
team in rushing in '95 and '96, but was benched last year in favor
of 1,000-yard man Charlie Higgins: ``I guess he's our forgotten
man, kind of like Wally Pipp,'' referring to the New York Yankees'
first baseman replaced by rookie Lou Gehrig in 1925.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
