<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8626 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     09-04 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TRY TO AVOID LATE SWOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The AL West race is the only race left for a division title in
the majors, as no other division leader besides the Angels entered
Thursday with less than a 10-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels open a five-game homestand tonight _ without Darin
Erstad, who re-injured his left hamstring Wednesday and figures to
miss the rest of the regular season _ having just played the
American League's top three teams _ record-wise _ on the road and
held their own. They won three of five in New York, two of three in
Boston and split two games in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue the Angels had more at stake. The Yankees have
an 18-game lead in the AL East, the Indians have a 12{-game lead in
the AL Central and the Red Sox lead the wild-card race by 7{ games.
</P>
<P>
   Those teams can afford to let up, or let down, for a game here
and there. They can rest their regulars to get ready for the
playoffs. Because for them, there is no doubting they will be
there.
</P>
<P>
   For the Angels, there is no such guarantee. Especially when they
are fighting history as much as the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels haven't had a winning month of September since 1991.
And they are a combined 49-83 in September since then.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins, meanwhile, was only a part of one
September with the Angels _ last season. But as a major-league
manager, he's finished in second place every year. Three times with
Houston and last year with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he sees the Yankees and Indians, and to a lesser degree the
Red Sox, use September as sort of a spring training for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, of course I'm envious of them,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the theory that a team that has a playoff spot
wrapped up so early it loses its edge and can't turn it on in time
for the playoffs? Collins doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of teams rise up,'' he said. ``The last couple of
games, I'll bet you see them turn it up, they won't rest anybody.
There will be a big buildup.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Collins might like his team to take a little
break now and then, he likes that his team has to fight for a
berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for us,'' he said. ``We'll go in doing the same
things we've been doing. Those guys (Yankees, Indians, Red Sox)
have been there. They know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins looks at the rest of the league's teams that have no
chance at the postseason and feels sorry for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``How nice is it to get up every day and know you have something
to play for?'' he said. ``Every day you come to the park there's
something on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   With a pennant race comes added attention, and Collins said it's
a matter of being able to prioritize your time when it comes to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a distraction, it's part of the job,'' he said. ``You
have to budget your time. That's why I get to the ballpark when I
do (typically noon for a 7 p.m. game). So I have a segment of time
that's mine. At 3 o'clock, I do interviews. I don't like it, but I
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He tells his players to remember what's important before each
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them first of all, make sure you get your work done,''
he said. ``Get your treatment if you have an injury. Do you weight
training, stretching, take batting practice. Handle it
professionally, but the only thing that matters is getting ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
