<HEADLINE>
MINOR-LEAGUE STARS GIVE RANGERS' FRONT OFFICE PREVIEW OF FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers acknowledged center fielder Ruben
Mateo as the organization's No. 1 prospect during July.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin refused to involve the 20-year-old
outfielder at Double-A Tulsa in trade discussions during his
attempts to strengthen the Rangers' pitching rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the closest to being untouchable,'' Melvin said in July.
``We think he's got a chance to be an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Few major-league officials disagree. Yet Mateo and the
organization's other top prospects will not receive a cameo
appearance this month, with the Rangers involved in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league officials identify second baseman Pedro Guerrero,
first baseman Carlos Pena, shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt, catcher
Cesar King and third baseman Rob Sasser as the Rangers' most
coveted prospects among position players. Right-handers Jonathan
Johnson, Ryan Glynn and Joaquin Benoit and left-handers Matt
Perisho and Corey Lee represent the best pitching prospects the
system offers, the officials say.
</P>
<P>
   All pale in comparison with Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is without a doubt the best Double-A player I saw this
year,'' said one major-league scout, who predicts Mateo will hit
.270-.275 with 20-25 home runs during his first major-league
season. ``He's a five-tool player. He's going to hit for average,
and he's going to hit for power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can run. He can throw. He's got great range. He can play
shallow and go get the ball. He can cut the ball off in the gap and
make the throw. He's just an exciting guy to watch.'' Ruben Mateo
