<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE'S PONCIANO PUTS PLAYERS FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Sometime in December, after Cal State
Northridge has completed its 11-game football season, rookie head
coach Ron Ponciano will be evaluated. Wins and losses will be
tallied, achievements and failures assessed.
</P>
<P>
   What the game notes, box scores and won-loss column won't count,
however, is what might matter most in the Ponciano era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Milhon taught me that people are more important than Xs
and Os,'' Ponciano says, recalling the words of the former Azusa
Pacific coach who gave him his start.
</P>
<P>
   As the Matadors kick off the 1998 season Saturday at Boise
State, the evaluation of Ron Ponciano, football coach, will begin
by those who employ him and those who support the team.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome, Ponciano already has won the respect
and loyalty of his team, and of other coaches, with a very
non-football trait. His humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cares for people. . . . Ron would do anything for a young
man,'' says San Jose State head coach Dave Baldwin, Ponciano's boss
for two years at CSUN and one year at SJSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make fun of him, that he's a softy,'' says CSUN assistant
head coach Jeff Kearin.
</P>
<P>
   And the listener thinks, (begin ital)you gotta be kidding(end
ital). Ponciano barks like Lombardi, cusses like Bobby Knight and
can, when he wants to, reduce a 300-pound lineman to a lump of
soft-serve frozen yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   But the burly 39-year-old's occasional bellowing belies his
downright '90s-man mentality. Ponciano cares. Almost to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, defensive back Howard Henry quit the team _ and
took his scholarship with him. Henry, who had sunk on the depth
chart, decided his studies had become more important than football.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano could have retracted Henry's scholarship and used it
elsewhere in the cash-strapped program. Instead, he told Henry to
keep it, with the agreement that Henry keep a 3.0 grade-point
average.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, receiver James Maldonado, a transfer from Kent
State, left the team suddenly to attend to a personal crisis. A
week later, Maldonado walked back into Ponciano's office and asked
to be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors are already seven deep at wide receiver, and again,
could have applied the scholarship elsewhere. But after listening
to Maldonado's story, Ponciano quickly invited the senior back to
the team and moved him to free safety, where he has a better chance
of playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's given me an opportunity again to play football, the thing
I love to do,'' Maldonado says. ``I didn't know what to expect, to
be honest with you. He was very compassionate about my situation
and very humanistic, understanding of what went on. He didn't give
me a life sentence for the mistakes I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's the lesson Ponciano learned from his old mentor at
Azusa. But perhaps, too, it is Ponciano's own mistakes that color
his responses.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman fullback at Cal, Ponciano left training camp one
night with four others, his morale crushed by a coach who placed
more value on football than individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember they weren't treating us right. We felt like
just meat,'' Ponciano says. ``And probably I was too immature to
deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also partying far too often, drinking and smoking and
generally acting like a typical 18-year-old away from home for the
first time. But Ponciano got a second chance at St. Mary's,
straightened out his life and eventually finished his career at
Azusa, where he later began a coaching career that wound through
USC, Valley College and Missouri Western State.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he picked up many of the traits of the head
coaches he worked for.
</P>
<P>
   The main lesson throughout: ``Your kids are all you've got.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Football, they'll take with them for the rest of their lives,
but it's a small portion of their lives,'' he says. ``Hopefully we
teach them some kind of skills, some kind of character things . . .
that can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words took on new meaning for Ponciano 18 months ago, when
his wife Lisa gave birth to their first child, Chad. Now it's rare
to pass through a practice at CSUN without seeing the tow-headed
tot scampering by, with Lisa not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best thing that ever happened to me,'' he says. ``The thing
since I've had Chad, I realize that whoever I'm talking to, (some
parent) feels as strongly about that player as I feel about my son.
Someone loves him that much. So there's no reason to degrade
anybody. There's times I can get in (a player's) face, which I do,
and there's times I need to chew on them, which I do. But there's
times to love 'em up, which I do.''
</P>
<P>
   So Ponciano has fired an assistant coach who used intimidation
tactics, has brought back players from the brink of dropping out
and is so protective of his players that he banned them from
fraternity parties after a freshman got into trouble at one.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps it's not surprising then that Ponciano sets a
general goal of finishing in the upper tier of the Big Sky
Conference but speaks at length about improving graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you can never do enough for them to make them
better people,'' Ponciano says. ``Because the only thing that's
really important is that they can get a job, hold down a job,
provide for their family and be good parents.''
</P>
<P>
   And the wins, well, they'll come in time too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8637 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS &LR;      09-04 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ASTROS manager Larry Dierker knows the feeling. He was pitching for
the Astros in September 1973 when he was called in from the bullpen
to face Hank Aaron in the next-to-last game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerin' Hank, in pursuit of Babe Ruth's career home-run mark
of 714, was sitting on 713.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd spent most of the year on the disabled list &UR;  &LR; with a broken
bone in my hand,'' Dierker said. ``I was only back with the team
for a few days, and I wasn't on top of my game, so I wasn't in the
best frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``But yeah, it pumped me up. Why not see if you can rise to the
challenge?''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the next few days, some other National League
pitcher is going to have the challenge staring him in the face. And
as Mark McGwire bears down on Roger Maris' single-season home-run
mark, few in the Astros' clubhouse would want the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pulling for Mark McGwire,'' Randy Johnson said. ``Just
like I'm pulling for Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr. I'd like to see
them all break the record. But now that McGwire's right there, I'm
hoping he gets it done before the Cardinals come to Houston next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't run and hide. You do your best and give him your
best pitches. But there's a lot of baggage that comes with the
situation. To be honest, I don't need that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of burden that has Tracy Stallard doggedly ducking
the media in this summer of the long ball. The man who served up
homer No. 61 to Maris on Oct. 1, 1961, has dodged every request for
an interview, still pained that his entire big-league career has
been capsulized in that one moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand his feelings about not wanting to talk about
it,'' Billy Wagner said. ``I mean, you have a career that lasts
years. You do your best, and the only thing that anybody wants to
talk to you about is one pitch. Was it a bad pitch or just a good
swing by Maris? I don't know. Nobody seems to care. But Tracy
Stallard can't get away from &UR;  &LR; it after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go in there and give it my best shot against
McGwire if it comes to that. But that's one hell of a way to make
it to the Hall of Fame. It's like you're infamous.''
</P>
<P>
   The list includes Tom Zachary, who delivered the pitch to Ruth
for his 60th homer, and Al Downing, who served up No. 715 to Aaron
in the spring after Dierker's confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The game is filled with victims. For years, Dodger Ralph Branca
was tortured by the memory of his 1951 playoff pitch that Bobby
Thomson launched to give the pennant to the Giants. But these days,
Branca has made peace with himself and makes appearances all over
the country with Thomson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't the kind of thing that I'd be proud of at all,'' Mike
Hampton said. ``History, maybe. But if you're a pitcher, giving up
a home run means you didn't do your job. It means you lost that
at-bat. There is never any honor in losing.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher who surrenders No. 62 to McGwire is likely to be
hounded by fans and the media almost as much as the slugger
himself. In this age of overanalysis paralysis, blanket coverage
and 24-hour sports channels, it might take a unique individual to
deal with the burden.
</P>
<P>
   Say, Jose Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, put me in there against any of them,'' Lima said. ``I'll
go right at them, give them my best shot. If they hit, they hit.
That's the name of the game. I'm not afraid of Mark McGwire or
Sammy Sosa or the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire's already got one off me this year. Pow! Gone in three
seconds. Hardest ball ever hit against me in my life. A line drive.
(Jeff) Bagwell told me if it had hit the scoreboard, we would have
had a delay in the game. It would have knocked the lights out. So
what, man? It's power on power.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it depends on the self-confidence of the pitcher. A
veteran, sure of himself, might not let one pitch define him. A
less secure individual could crumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing research for my baseball library as a
broadcaster,'' Dierker said. ``I looked into the only two home runs
that were ever hit all the way out of Dodger Stadium, both by
Willie Stargell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit the first one off a young guy named Alan Foster. Willie
told me that for the next several years, every time he came to the
plate against Foster, the guy tried to knock him down. He'd just
throw the ball and snarl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second homer came against Andy Messersmith, a great
pitcher, who just smiled at Willie and tipped his cap. I think
that's all you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   So what did Aaron do against Dierker &UR;  &LR; in that long-ago September
showdown?
</P>
<P>
   ``A broken-bat single over shortstop,'' Dierker said, smiling.
``I didn't get him out. But I kept him in the park.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
