<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8644 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPO     09-04 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GIRLS' ADD POLISH TO RUIDOSO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have bumper stickers, T-shirts, lapel pins and jealous
husbands. And if their 2-year-old quarter horse Old Habits wins
Monday's All American Futurity, the 10 women who own him will have
$1 million to share.
</P>
<P>
   They call themselves ``The Girls,'' and they are doing their
best to feminize the sport's good old boys.
</P>
<P>
   Their jockey, Dusty Stimpson, will wear racing silks that have
oversized red lips on the back. And in a ceremony tomorrow
afternoon that hopefully won't be televised, they are each painting
one of trainer Danny Cardoza toenails with red polish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm, the camaraderie ... we are having so much
fun,'' said Janice Knorpp, one of the partners. The only Texan in
the bunch, she resides in Clarendon, about 60 miles southeast of
Amarillo. ``We've all become very good friends. We just look at
each other and smile.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder. The women paid only $1,850 each to buy Old Habits,
and his quarter-mile qualifying time of 21.55 seconds was the
fastest of any All American finalist. The Ruidoso Downs, N.M., race
is the richest in quarter horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   Old Habits _ named for a country song _ already has made $85,203
from four wins in six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Knorpp said she and Sue Hukari of Bonsall, Calif., ``fell in
love'' with Old Habits at a yearling sale last year in California.
They bought him for $18,500, joined by their regular partners
Bonnie Vessels, also from Bonsall, and Mary Thead of Poway, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we went around to folks that we knew,'' Knorpp explained.
``We said, `Look, this one we really do like, would you like in?'
And they said OK. That's how it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first racehorse experience ever for Connie Cobb of
Tidewater, Ore., Glori Ekker of Hanksville, Utah, and Leslie
Schwabacher of Daniel, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the sorority are all from California:
Sharon Gordon of Orange, Melodie Knuchell of Los Alamitos, and
Cathy Monji of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Vessels, a racing veteran, acts as the unofficial social
chairman. She communicates with the other owners through e-mail,
and they all seem to get along wonderfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairy tale that's coming true,'' said Ekker. ``And what
a lucky fellow \ROld Habits\S is to have 10 women drooling over
him, granting his every wish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Girls are dressing in red for Monday's big race, which will
be televised live on ESPN2 with a post time of 5:45 p.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the husbands to be attired in whatever the wives want
them to wear. The Girls are laughingly referring to their spouses
as ``the five-percenters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas and California are community-property states,'' Knorpp
explained.
Hoofbeats and The Buzz
No Super showdown
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop meeting in
the Sept. 27 Super Derby lasted only a few days.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, trainer Shug McGaughey announced that instead of
shipping Coronado's Quest to Louisiana Downs, he would instead
point him toward the Sept. 19 Woodward Stakes in New York home
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea of staying home and running a mile and an
eighth,'' McGaughey told the New York Daily News. ``I'll get five
pounds from the older horses, and I won't have to ship all the way
to Louisiana Downs.''
</P>
<P>
   By running Coronado's Quest in Belmont Park's Woodward,
McGaughey is opting to send his 3-year-old against a battalion of
older horses expected to include Skip Away, Free House, Gentlemen
and perhaps Touch Gold.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, that was the most palatable choice.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative was loading the unpredictable colt on a plane
bound for Louisiana Downs in Bossier City, where the weather can be
hot, the paddock is more confining, and the distance is the same
mile-and-a-quarter that he just barely survived in the Travers
Stakes. That is one quest McGaughey chose not to undertake. Flat on
his back
</P>
<P>
   These horse races are fraught with peril, and lately it seems
Mike Smith has been on the receiving end of more than his fair
share.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Smith will miss an estimated four months with
fractured vertebrae he sustained in a Monday spill at Saratoga.
Smith cracked his T-12 and L-3 vertebrae and will be in a body cast
for two months, with no paralysis or other permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   The grass-race accident was determined to be the result of
careless riding by Edwin Cotto, who has a 1998 record of 0-for-41.
Most jockeys who are judged guilty of infractions are suspended for
a week, but Saratoga stewards handed Cotto a 30-day penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Smith broke his collarbone on the Florida Derby
undercard at Gulfstream Park and was sidelined for two months.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's latest injury will cost him big-race mounts this fall on
Coronado's Quest, and other top horses such as Ajina, Aldiza and
Maxzene.  &LR; railhed:Another jackpot The guaranteed pick-six craze
shows no signs of abating, and Del Mar cranks up another one on
Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The track is again guaranteeing $2.5 million in the total pool.
And again Monday, nationwide betting is likely to exceed $3 million
and perhaps $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The wager can be played at Lone Star Park's Post Time Pavilion
simulcast center.
</P>
<P>
   Three previous Southern California promotions have resulted in
modest payoffs, although $15,000 is certainly nothing to sneer at.
But one of these days, someone is going to hit a home run with a
single winning ticket in the $2 million vicinity.
 &LR; railhedDrug quandary
</P>
<P>
   Horsemen don't seem to care about the public perception that
racing has a drugging problem, and the new National Thoroughbred
Racing Association is being dragged into the middle of the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA has formed a task force to look into the controversial
issue, which has many avenues for exploration.
</P>
<P>
   First, not all performance-enhancing drugs can be detected by
urine or blood testing. Second, medication rules and penalties for
breaking them are different from state to state.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most ominous, some believe the foundation of the
thoroughbred breed itself is threatened by use of legal race-day
drugs such as Lasix and Butazolidin. For more than a decade, horses
needing these drugs to compete effectively have been retired to the
breeding shed, and critics say the result is becoming apparent:
succeeding generations of horses that are more fragile than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   There are no easy answers to this one, as the NTRA will soon
discover.
</P>
<P>
   As long as racetracks run long meetings and seek full fields,
and as horse-related expenses continue to rise, owners and trainers
will continue to face pressure to race their horses more often than
they know they should.
</P>
<P>
   And that, they say, can only be accomplished through the use of
therapeutic race-day medications.  &LR; railhedBonus rules According to
a rules stipulation by the insurance company, the $1 million
DeBartolo Racing Challenge bonus, payable if Classic Cat wins the
Super Derby, depends on whether a seven-horse starting lineup can
be put together for the race.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective field now includes just four other horses:
Victory Gallop, Raffie's Majesty, Leave A Legacy and Thomas Jo. But
chances are good that Louisiana Downs director of racing Pat Pope
will be able to round up a few more, especially now that Coronado's
Quest won't participate.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the seven-horse requirement isn't met (or if seven
horses start and he loses), Classic Cat won't go home with empty
saddlebags. According to the complicated rules of the DeBartolo
participation bonus, if Classic Cat doesn't win the $1 million, he
will be guaranteed a $100,000 bonus simply for leaving the starting
gate, and another $100,000 if he finishes fourth or better.
 &LR; railhedDel Marred To put it bluntly, a catastrophic injury in a
racehorse is defined as one that results in death. During the first
35 days of its 43-day season, Del Mar had 10 such injuries on its
dirt and grass tracks either in races or during morning training
hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of its meeting, six horses died as the result
of racing injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to Lone Star Park's recent thoroughbred meeting,
where, according to statistics compiled by track superintendent Ron
Moore, just three horses died from breakdowns in a 73-day meeting.
Two of those were in one race.  &LR; railhed:Et cetera Skip Away won his
eighth consecutive race Sunday, a dramatic photo-finish triumph in
Monmouth's Iselin Handicap despite carrying 131 pounds. That will
almost certainly be the heaviest weight he'll ever be asked to
carry. The Woodward and subsequent dates on Skip Away's tentative
schedule this fall are weight-for-age races and not handicaps,
after which the 5-year-old probably will be retired to stud,
perhaps as the horse that won the most money ever. ... Pat Day has
moved past David Gall into third place on the list of all-time
winningest jockeys. The 44-year-old Day rode his 7,264th winner on
Saturday, and trails only Bill Shoemaker (8,833) and Laffit Pincay
(8,632 through Monday). ... Pincay, 51, returned from a broken
collarbone and broken ribs Monday to ride a winner at Del Mar. ...
Texas-bred Thomas Jo runs Monday in the Pennsylvania Derby, his
scheduled tuneup for the Super Derby. ... Once-beaten filly
Relaxing Rhythm has been retired. ... Trainer Wayne Lukas tries for
the fourth Hopeful Stakes victory of his career Saturday with heavy
favorite Yes It's True, who looks like the country's fastest
2-year-old. ... Silver Charm worked a fast mile on Sunday, but
trainer Bob Baffert is still mum on a possible next start. ...
Saratoga's meeting ends Monday, and Del Mar concludes Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
