<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE QUICK TO DISMISS WILL CLARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will Clark should not be lightly discarded after this season is
over.
</P>
<P>
   That point needs to be made clear to all those people eager and
ready to spend Tom Hicks' money.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Rafael Palmeiro dearly wants to return to Texas and, yes,
his 41 home runs and 112 runs batted in would look terrific behind
Juan Gonzalez in the Rangers' lineup. There's no doubt at this
point of their careers that Palmeiro is the better offensive player
than Clark.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just not that simple. The Rangers unquestionably need
Clark back next year.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Clark remains the undisputed leader of this team, and
he changed the personality of this team after arriving in 1994. He
had help from Mickey Tettleton, Mark McLemore and many others.
Manager Johnny Oates also played a significant role. But Clark was
the one who began the badly needed change from me-first to
team-first.
</P>
<P>
   He plays hurt, he plays hard, he plays the game right and those
intangibles can't be overlooked. If they are, people are forgetting
the Ruben Sierra-Julio Franco era, when the Rangers had 25 players
doing their own thing, much to the detriment of team goals.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Clark is no longer the great offensive
player he was in San Francisco. There's also little doubt he has
played in his last All-Star Game and probably hasn't seen the last
of the disabled list. That body is being held together more by
willpower than any significant physical attributes.
</P>
<P>
   But as Oates said, ``Will Clark today is a pretty good player.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more, Clark reminds me of Carl Yastrzemski, the Red Sox
Hall of Fame outfielder. Yastrzemski, like Clark in San Francisco,
was one of the great players in the game in his peak years of
1967-70, when he was winning batting titles, Gold Gloves and a most
valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the injuries, and Yastrzemski's great talent slowly
eroded. For the last 13 years, he was never close to the player he
was in 1967, when he won baseball's last Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   But he remained a productive player and great team leader right
up through 1983, simply through determination. Yastrzemski's simple
philosophy was to tape it up, play every day and get the job done.
Clark does the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles have shown over the past three years that
buying the best players does not produce the desired results. They
have great talent on the field, but their clubhouse mix has been
bad. The melting pot has not worked there.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, on the other hand, have demonstrated the
value of having more than just great talent. The talent is there,
but they also have some gritty ballplayers like Joe Girardi, David
Cone, Paul O'Neill and, yes, even Darryl Strawberry, who has
matured greatly and is leading the team in home runs despite a bad
knee. Teams don't have the kind of season the Yankees are having on
great talent alone. Just ask the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, Palmeiro might want to come back to Texas, but he's
not going to come back cheaply. He's looking for $10 million a
year, which makes general manager Doug Melvin squirm.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have more important ways to spend Hicks' cash.
Pitching, as always, has to be their first priority. Shortstop
Royce Clayton also needs to be re-signed; otherwise, the Rangers
are going to be hurting at an important position.
</P>
<P>
   Clark won't come back cheaply. He makes $6.25 million this year
and his intense pride will make a pay cut difficult to accept. One
possibility is a two-year deal with performance-based options,
similar to what the Rangers did with John Burkett last year.
</P>
<P>
   It needs to be explored. He is not Rafael Palmeiro. He is not Mo
Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   But he is still Will Clark, and that has meant too much to the
Rangers to be discarded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
