<SLUG> BC-BBN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING LIKE 61-HOMER RECORD IN ALL OF SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Equipped with an agile thumb on the remote control,
the baseball fan Wednesday had an opportunity to experience the
local alpha and omega of televised experiences.
</P>
<P>
   On one channel was former Mariner Randy Johnson, blowing away
the Atlanta Braves and Greg Maddux and even laying down a sacrifice
bunt, a small-ball adventure his former teammates have yet to
consider attempting under manager Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   On another channel was Mariner relief pitcher Bobby Ayala giving
up a game-winning grand slam, an event as pathetically predictable
as a stadium cost overrun.
</P>
<P>
   On a third channel was blessed relief from Mariner grief.
Highlights from the Forearm Festival showed Mark McGwire on such a
vigorous stampede into baseball history that the porcelain Jeff
Manto doll atop the TV vibrated off the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to home run No. 59 this week might wind up nearly as big
a feat as besting the record of Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's home run analysts have always talked about how
difficult a big final month can be for sluggers. For 37 years, the
theory held, thwarting all the ``on a pace for 62'' projections.
</P>
<P>
   No one gave much consideration to the idea that the labors of
Hercules could be completed by Labor Day. Never has the most
majestic record in sports looked so vulnerable, and never have so
many people been so excited about a paper chase.
</P>
<P>
   A wonderfully curious thing, this record and its pursuit. Given
the otherwise dismal year of the St. Louis Cardinals, there is no
team reward at stake. And there are individual records of greater
improbability _ Ted Williams' .401 batting average, Joe DiMaggio's
56-game hitting streak, Johnny VanDerMeer's back-to-back
no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing like the single-season, major league home
run mark. And to have it pursued by not one but two engaging
fellows, each handling the pressure in his own way, yet with equal
aplomb, is almost better than discovering strawberry shortcake is a
cure for old age.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the record's conquest, its appeal is worthy of a
little scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is not only America's oldest organized professional
sport, it's the only sport where record-keeping is its own
institution. Great effort has been expended to seamlessly connect
generations by quantifying everything in universal numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Linear thinkers will rightly conclude it is mostly a bogus
exercise, since the many changes in ballparks, equipment and rules
have rendered moot most of the relevance of modern records to the
pre-World War II statkeeping.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball is linear only along foul lines and base lines. A
game of round ball against round bat takes many hops that can't be
defined by tabular mathematics. Those parts of baseball are
explained in words and legends that far exceed any other sport's
capacity to enchant.
</P>
<P>
   No figure in sports is as romanticized as Babe Ruth, for all the
reasons that are well-known, plus one that is often lost _ the home
run record before Ruth's career was 27, set in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   He doubled that mark in 1920, then hit 60 in 1927 _ gargantuan
leaps of achievement that have been exceeded only once in more than
70 years. That means three generations of fans have become attuned
to the 60 standard in an activity that, perhaps outside of fishing,
is the only one to remain mostly the same for a grandchild as a
great-grandparent.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the well-understood standard, there also is the nature
of a single-season record that makes it tidily comprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   A single-game superlative, such as a perfect game or batting for
the cycle, is a spontaneous development that can't be anticipated.
Anticipation is an integral part of a modern sports achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Career records, such as Cal Ripken's consecutive-game streak,
can be anticipated, but nearly all are intellectual appreciations
that are harder to connect with emotionally. (Besides, what did you
do in school with the kid who had perfect attendance? You gave him
a headlock and a noogie, or pulled up the back of his shorts.)
</P>
<P>
   All career sports records owe something to the luck of good
health, which is wonderful but not satisfying. Feats that span the
decades, such as Hank Aaron's record for homers, Cy Young's record
for pitching wins and Pete Rose's record for hits, are magnificent,
but not as compelling as a single season with a beginning, middle
and climax.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from matters of time and history, there is the nature of
the home run. As McGwire said recently, the home run is about power
and bigness, America's most identifiable characteristics. We savor
big cars, big conflicts, big landscapes, big pizzas and big debt.
McGwire the man is our perfect physical metaphor, built along the
lines of an RV, and his homers are big enough to be national parks.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs, thanks to the trot, also allow for instant, mandatory
celebration of an individual in the context of a team game, another
big deal to Americans (see Oscars, Emmys, etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Home runs also are instantly gratifying and have an indisputable
finality _ perfectly resolved chords for a culture that otherwise
seems like an AM radio on scan.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare your ears, and your sporting soul: The big ta-DAH is
coming.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
