<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      09-04 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Swissair Crash &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service moved the following package of
stories on the Swissair crash off Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-RDP (Undated) _ Ledeall on the crash Wednesday night off
Nova Scotia of a Swissair jet en route from New York to Geneva. All
229 people aboard were killed. By Robert D. McFadden. (2ndLd)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-OBIT-MANN (Undated) _ Dr. Jonathan Max Mann, a pioneer in
the international campaign against AIDS and a founder of a new
movement to link health issues with those of human rights, died
Wednesday night alongside his wife, Dr. Mary Lou Clements-Mann, a
vaccine scientist at Johns Hopkins School of Hygiene and Public
Health University, in the crash of Swissair Flight 111 off the
coast of Nova Scotia. He was 51. By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-SCENE (Peggy's Cove, N.S.) _ Overnight, when a jetliner
smashed into the ocean just five miles from this tiny town, known
mainly as the most visited, most admired old fishing village on
Nova Scotia's craggy East became synonymous with places like
Lockerbie and East Moriches. And the 60 or so people who live here
woke to a different hamlet, one whose carefree tourists have been
driven out by fire engines, television vans and somber emergency
crews. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-INQUIRY (Halifax, Nova Scotia) _ Developments in the
investigation into the cause of the crash, and a look at the plane,
an MD-11. By Matthew L. Wald. (1stLd)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-FAMILIES (Undated) _ Dealing with the shock and grief of
families of passengers in New York, Switzerland and elsewhere. By
Frank Bruni. (2ndLd)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-VICTIMS (Undated) _ A look at who was on board the fatal
flight. By N.R. Kleinfield. (2ndLd)
</P>
<P>
   With CRASH-VICTIMS-LIST (Undated) _ List of passengers and crew
members who died.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe, in addition to full coverage of the crash,
plans this obituary on Dr. Mann:
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-MANN (Boston) _ Boston native Jonathan Mann, 51, who was
widely credited with shaping the worldwide response to AIDS during
a stormy tenure at the World Health Organization, dies in the
Swissair crash along with his wife, a noted AIDS vaccine
researcher. By Richard A. Knox. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
