<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Couple's lawn ``unsightly'' in village eyes
 &HT;    By A. Scharnhorst
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Tequesta couple that has battled village officials for almost
a decade over their landscaping was cited again this week for
violating village codes.
</P>
<P>
   Hattie and Bill Siegel were cited for excessive accumulation of
plant material because their yard is overgrown and untended,
village officials said. They also were cited for creating an
unsightly condition because they used tar paper and cinder blocks
to try to smother unwanted grass growing in their front yard.
</P>
<P>
   The Siegels, who have lived in their house on Dover Road for
three decades, have chosen to landscape their back and front yards
with native plants and other shrubs, trees and flowers that require
little water to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and village officials believe the yard is a health
hazard and unsightly.
</P>
<P>
   The village has cited the couple several times in the past eight
years. Each time, the Siegels have appealed the citations. Several
cases were settled out of court. In the most recent case, a
three-judge panel overruled the village's hearing officer because
she hadn't followed the intent of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The village vowed to cite the Siegels again under the same
ordinance _ creating a public nuisance by allowing too much plant
material to accumulate on their property.
</P>
<P>
   Tequesta code enforcement officer Sgt. John Irovando issued the
warning letter this week, giving the Siegels 30 days to comply or
face another hearing before the village's code enforcement hearing
officer. Irovando said he also ordered the village to clean up the
portion of land in front of the Siegel's house that is in village
right-of-way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Code enforcement is having the village do the same thing we're
asking the Siegels to do,'' Irovando said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, when an article appeared in The Palm Beach Post
about the situation, dozens of people have called the couple
offering cash and help, Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple has declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not Hattie's way,'' said their attorney, Greg Tayon.
``She doesn't want to take anything for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
