<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Becky Howe speaks mind, saves senior community
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up in Piqua, Becky Howe learned little girls didn't
speak up, didn't rock the boat.
</P>
<P>
   As a licensed practical nurse for nearly 30 years, she learned
to bite her lip, to turn the other cheek, to never never talk back
to patients, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think, with all this practice, at age 50, she'd be adept
at holding her peace. Not so. Miami County's unlikely new heroine
has been speaking her mind since June 9, when she received notice
that Anthem was planning to cancel her coverage and that of some
20,000 Ohio residents using its Medicare HMO, known as Senior
Advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The change would mean a devastating lifestyle change for Howe
and her partner, Ronnie Hines, who has diabetes and multiple
sclerosis. Arthritis and a degenerative joint disease forced Howe
to retire two years ago. When the couple switched to Senior
Advantage around the same time, they saved an average of $150 to
$200 a month. They could play Bingo, go out to dinner from time to
time. That would all end. Worse yet, Howe says, ``The elderly and
the disabled would have no place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe started mouthing off, and she doesn't intend to stop until
Anthem promises continued coverage in 22 rural and suburban
counties threatened with losing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been spanked for holding my breath, let's put it
that way,'' Howe says.
</P>
<P>
   Good bet she has never been spanked for excessive politeness
either. ``I can go from zero to bitch in 1.2 seconds,'' she is fond
of saying. She told one Anthem executive, ``I hope you sleep well
at night.'' She reminded an Anthem doctor, ``You took a Hippocratic
oath to take care of any and all.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe's crusade began with a letter to the editor to The Piqua
Daily Call, urging others to join her cause: ``Maybe together we
can bring the company to their knees. Speak up, Miami County, your
lives are on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Her phone rang from 8:45 a.m. to 11 p.m. Still, friends
speculated, ``It's just Becky blowing smoke again.'' Naysayers
warned, ``You can't fight corporate America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm going to try,'' she declared.
</P>
<P>
   Before Howe knew it, politicians, TV cameras, lawyers and even
The New York Times camped out on her doorstep in Piqua. With
typical condescension to all things Midwestern, The Times referred
to her hometown as ``a weary looking city surrounded by
cornfields.'' But what the hey? It was legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   A class-action lawsuit was filed and some 1,000 protesters
appeared at four rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Howe has declared an ``85-percent victory'' with the news last
week that Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield officials have agreed
to reconsider their decision. Officials are meeting with federal
administrators about a plan to save Senior Advantage by
establishing premiums and higher co-payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of you,'' neighbor and bosom buddy Mary Atkins told
her friend. ``She showed us that one person can make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is congratulating me, but it took all of us
together,'' Howe corrects. ``There are a lot of people on this
bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right, of course. But the band needed a conductor. And
that's where Howe came in _ a single noisy woman who may very well
have shamed a huge corporation into doing the right thing. And if a
compromise plan isn't reached?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still going to be out here,'' Howe says, ``and I'm not
going to keep quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
