r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN05-COX     09-04 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biscuits rise to the task
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall a South Georgia friend, knowing of my taste for
old-fashioned eating, sent us a bottle of prime cane syrup. It
languished unopened on a back shelf in the pantry for almost a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they have been ruled medically incorrect, my wife is
never anxious for me to indulge in the wonderful but allegedly
artery-clogging delicacies that were staples of the Southern diet
before food police ruled everything good is bad. I was surprised
when she mentioned the syrup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why haven't you tried any of the syrup Ned sent you?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I haven't had anything to sop it with,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   Being a child bride with no memories of the Great Depression,
she didn't understand why you can't just up and have syrup for
breakfast the same way you do strawberry jam, or even fig
preserves.
</P>
<P>
   You can't sop syrup with toast, or bagels. You have to have
biscuits, and biscuits in our kitchen have gone the way of running
boards on automobiles. They don't exist anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I explained why it's necessary to have biscuits for breakfast if
you're going to have syrup for breakfast. I reminded her that when
I was growing up on the farm my mother always baked 10 biscuits for
my breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder your pants are always too tight,'' she said. ``In
addition to spoiling you rotten, your mother let you develop bad
eating habits.''
</P>
<P>
   I explained how my mother didn't make the big, sawmill-type
cathead biscuits they serve in places called Mama's Kountry
Kitchen. Her biscuits were classy and delicate, cut out of the
dough with a Vienna sausage can. A growing boy needed at least 10
to keep from having scrawny legs and skinny little arms, and being
too weak to learn multiplication tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ned was nice enough to send you the syrup all the way from
South Georgia you shouldn't let it go to waste,'' my wife said.
``I'll get you some biscuits.''
</P>
<P>
   I was shocked, but pleased. ``Great!'' I replied. ``You'll have
to buy a sack of self-rising flour and some lard. I don't guess you
have any buttermilk, either. Do you still have a rolling pin?''
</P>
<P>
   As my mouth began to water, I could visualize my mother at the
kitchen counter, preparing breakfast. She began by dipping several
cups of flour out of a tin canister, where the flour had been
transferred from the 25-pound sack bought at Mr. John M. Jackson's
store in Fayetteville. The sacks came decorated in flowered
patterns, so that wives and mothers could sew them into church
dresses and shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The flour went into a hand-hewn wooden bowl. She added a handful
of lard and fresh buttermilk from a pitcher. After kneading the
mixture with her hands, she sprinkled flour on a wooden board and
rolled the dough into a thin sheet before cutting it into circles
with the Vienna sausage can.
</P>
<P>
   Then she lightly greased an old black pan with lard, positioned
the uncooked biscuits so they could rise separately, and popped
them into an oven heated to precisely the right temperature by
practiced application of stovewood into the fire box.
</P>
<P>
   I was elated when my wife volunteered to fix biscuits. I offered
to make the trip to the grocery store to buy flour, lard and
buttermilk. She said no. She'd go herself.
</P>
<P>
   When she got back, she didn't have flour, lard, or buttermilk.
She had a can that said, ``Hungry Jack's Flaky Biscuits. Bake in
400-degree oven for eight minutes before serving.'' The can went
`poof!' when she twisted it open, according to directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only have one,'' she said. ``The label says each
biscuit has 100 calories, and you know how you've gained weight
this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief debate, she agreed to bake two for me and one for
herself. When she turned her back to get something out of the
refrigerator, I slipped another one into the oven.
</P>
<P>
   When the eight minutes were up, I took the four biscuits out of
the oven. They were nice and brown, and just about the size of the
ones my mother cut out with the Vienna sausage can. We buttered
them hot. We opened Ned's South Georgia ribbon cane syrup, poured
it on plates, and sopped it up with the Hungry Jack's biscuits. I
was surprised when they turned out to be the best I've tasted since
our semi-farmer son's wife cooked a batch several years ago and
Edith McCalla went on strike.
</P>
<P>
   I quickly consumed my two and was about to reach for the extra
I'd slipped into the oven when my wife beat me to it. ``Ned's syrup
is very good and 100 calories are only a little more than a slice
of toast,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Syrup is habit forming. That's the reason it's almost extinct in
the modern diet. Hot biscuits with syrup are like peanuts. It's
impossible to eat just one. Scientists found a way to split an
atom, but nobody yet has figured out how to make a helping of syrup
come out even with a biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   You just have to keep on pouring syrup and reaching for biscuits
until they're both gone, and that can take a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
