<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9019 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX     09-04 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Home runs make the game
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Home runs are the most exciting part of baseball.
That's my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather see a ball hit out of the stadium than watch a
pitcher throw a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   If that shows my ignorance of the game, then so be it. Mickey
Mantle made me this way.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey was my hero. He also was my big brother. Some quirk in
the universe caused Mickey to be raised by another family in
another state and prevented the two of us from ever meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The World Champion Yankees brought Mickey up to the bigs when he
was still a teen-ager. I was 12 at the time, only months away from
being a teen-ager. It was cosmic.
</P>
<P>
   Mantle could hit the ball a mile. That's how he made it to the
pros.
</P>
<P>
   A traveling New York Yankees scout who decided to catch a summer
league game in Baxter Springs, Kans. watched in amazement as a high
school kid from nearby Commerce, Okla. hit three home runs into a
river that ran behind the ball park.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later that kid from Commerce was wearing pinstripes
and playing right field next to the ``Yankee Clipper,'' Joltin' Joe
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Mantle was the only ball player I ever wanted to see break Babe
Ruth's home run record. The ``Sultan of Swat'' hit 60 home runs in
1927.
</P>
<P>
   It looked liked The Mick might break The Babe's record in 1956
when he hit 52 home runs. That year I played first base on my high
school team. I used a Mickey Mantle Louisville Slugger and swung
for the fence on every pitch within reach, plus an equal number no
one could reach.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1961 season, I did not want Mantle's teammate Roger
Maris to break the Bambino's home run record. That's because I
wanted my man Mantle to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, it was Maris not Mantle who hit 61 in '61 and
broke Ruth's 34-year-old record. Mantle hit ``only'' 54 home runs
that year.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I never became a well-rounded baseball player, I also
never became a well-rounded baseball fan. That's fine because the
1998 baseball season has been tailor-made for me and other fans
with stunted appreciation for the finer aspects of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Mickey is signing baseballs for angels, or whomever,
I'm enjoying heaven on earth watching Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and
Ken Griffey Jr. launch balls into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year of the sluggers. Surely McGwire and Sosa not
only will break Maris' home run record, they will smash it. Griffey
is only slightly off Maris' pace and also might break the record.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball purists, who always have something to complain about,
have three complaints designed to take the fun out of the current
home-run record chase.
</P>
<P>
   They complain that the balls appear juiced, that the players are
using drugs and that the pitching has been watered down.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the sluggers become too successful entertaining
low-brow fans such as myself, the purists complain that the
baseballs are being wound too tight or somehow doctored by the
powers that be just to jack up fan interest, as if that's something
terrible. That's a phony argument.
</P>
<P>
   The drug complaint involves the fact that McGwire and other
players take a legal, over-the-counter nutritional supplement that
they believe helps build muscle mass. Since the substance,
androstenedione, is untested, no one knows what it does, if
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa doesn't take it, so it's possible that the stuff doesn't do
anything. But anyway, it's legal and not banned by Major League
Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The third complaint made by baseball purists is on the money.
Due to the expansion of both leagues, there are pitchers in the
bigs whoought to be honing their skills back in double-A ball.
</P>
<P>
   Let the baseball purists stew in their own juices. Home runs are
great fun. That's my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
