<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WVU-KEATING05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tick-born disease halts WVU quarterback
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ After a freshman year spent learning the system
at West Virginia University, former Valley View football star Andy
Keating expected to make a run at the No. 2 quarterback spot this
season.
</P>
<P>
   If practice went well, maybe, just maybe, he'd get a chance to
play in front of family and friends in the Mountaineers' biggest
game of the year Saturday against No. 1 ranked Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately for Keating, who was at the very least
expected to be WVU's holder Saturday, things did not go well. After
the first day of practice in mid-August, he became violently ill,
with a fever of 103.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there it just went downhill,'' said Keating, who helped
lead Valley View to a state championship in 1996. ``I couldn't keep
anything down. I couldn't stop vomiting.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried to sleep it off. But when he awoke the next morning and
collapsed while trying to get out of bed, he knew his illness was
serious.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the next eight days in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Tests ruled out flu, mononucleosis, meningitis and E. coli,
Keating and WVU team trainer Dave Kerns said. Still puzzled,
doctors brought in an infectious disease specialist, Keating said,
who suspected a rare and potentially deadly tick-borne illness
called ehrlichiosis (pronounced air-LICK-i-o-sis). Ehrlichiosis is
usually transmitted by a certain type of tick or possibly by
mosquitos and is ``almost like Lyme disease or Rocky Mountain
(spotted) fever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What was odd, Keating said, is that he was told ``the tick
itself is not found in West Virginia or Ohio'' and that only about
500 cases of the disease have been documented in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said he was given antibiotics to treat
ehrlichiosis and released from the hospital soon after. WVU trainer
Kerns would not confirm the ehrlichiosis diagnosis, saying doctors
still aren't ``100 percent sure'' what Keating's illness was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible we may never know,'' Kerns said. ``Or it may
come back if it was this tick-related disease.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter, Keating, who lost 15 pounds during the ordeal,
appears well on his way to recovery. He's regained about five
pounds, he said, and just recently started attending classes and
team meetings. Football practice and weight lifting are off limits
for now, although he hopes to resume both in a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
