<HEADER>
A9022 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOW-GAS05-COX     09-04 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-GAS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida pays higher prices for gas, despite country low
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in those carefree days before oil embargoes and OPEC became
seared in the national consumer consciousness, gasoline wasn't this
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   As the last big driving weekend of the summer approaches, gas
prices across the U.S. are approaching their lowest level ever when
adjusted for inflation. Local prices are at or near record lows as
well _ but Palm Beach County drivers continue to pay more for gas
than other motorists around Florida and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The average price nationally for a gallon of self-serve regular
unleaded was $1.01 on Monday, according to a weekly report by the
U.S. Department of Energy. A survey by AAA last week put the
average at $1.03 in Florida and more than $1.11 in Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adjusted for inflation, this year's gasoline prices are the
lowest ever,'' said Michael Burdette, who tracks prices for the
DOE's Energy Information Administration in Washington, D.C. The
only time the weekly national average was lower was one week in
March when it was a penny cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Palm Beach County, the AAA's pre-Labor Day average
of just under $1.12 a gallon is the lowest inflation-adjusted price
since the organization started tracking local prices in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   For the West Palm Beach area, the only time real prices were
lower than AAA's latest $1.11 average was in March, when the
average was $1.10.
</P>
<P>
   A year before the 1973 Arab oil embargo, according to federal
government statistics, gasoline cost an average of 36.1 cents a
gallon _ the equivalent of $1.40 today. Prices peaked in 1980 and
1981 during Ayatollah Khomeini's heyday at $1.25 to $1.38 a gallon,
the equivalent of nearly $2.50 in today's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Experts list a variety of reasons for the plummeting pump
prices: a worldwide oil glut caused by the Asian economic crisis,
discord among members of OPEC (Oil Producing and Exporting
Countries), more cost-efficient offshore exploration and drilling
techniques _ even El Nino, which brought a milder winter and less
demand for heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, those factors have lowered average prices by
23 cents nationally. In Palm Beach County, pre-Labor Day prices
this year are 22 to 23 cents lower than a year ago, according to
AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County's consistently higher prices led Florida
Attorney General Bob Butterworth to launch a price-fixing
investigation in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   After several months, he found no conspiracy but concluded Palm
Beach County motorists pay more because there isn't as much
competition among major oil companies as in other parts of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth also found more ``consumer price insensitivity''
among local drivers than other Floridians. In other words, gas
stations can charge higher prices because locals seem willing to
pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this pricier market, several outlets were selling gas
for less than $1 a gallon this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine cents a gallon is pretty good,'' said Will
Seaberry at a suburban West Palm Beach Texaco station charging 99.9
cents per gallon for self-serve regular unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been delighted,'' said Barbara Keller while pumping the
sub-$1 fuel into her Dodge Caravan.
</P>
<P>
   Local prices vary widely. While many convenience stores and
independent stations are a few pennies below $1 a gallon, a Shell
station west of Boca Raton was charging $1.59 this week for a
gallon of self-serve regular unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there was a 14-cent price spread within shouting
distance of the Texaco where Seaberry and Keller tanked up at the
intersection of Forest Hill Boulevard and Military Trail.
</P>
<P>
   While the Texaco charged 99.9 cents, the independent Banks
Service Center on the other side of Forest Hill charged 97.9 cents,
a BP station diagonally across the intersection charged $1.07 and a
Shell station across Military Trail charged $1.12.
</P>
<P>
   At the BP station, manager Joe Garza looked at the sub-$1 prices
and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texaco shouldn't be doing what he's doing,'' Garza said.
``He's trying to make like a war, but we aren't going to play that.
These two guys (Texaco and Banks) have been at it for two or three
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the price wars, the Shell station was busiest during the
hour a reporter visited this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay attention to the prices,'' said Shell customer
Mike Jones of West Palm Beach, illustrating the ``consumer price
insensitivity'' Butterworth described.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's price insensitivity, or maybe it's heightened
sensitivity to other factors.
</P>
<P>
   For Hector Guajardo, who had been driving east on Forest Hill,
the ease of making a right turn into the Shell station made it
worth paying 14 cents a gallon more than crossing the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other one, you have to turn (left) or make a U-turn,''
Guajardo said, pointing to the less-expensive station. ``If they
were right next to each other, of course I would take the least
expensive one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
