<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAX-ADS05-COX     09-04 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAX-ADS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advertisers show interest in PAX TV debut
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAX TV won the lottery this week.
</P>
<P>
   Not the state's $6 million Lotto prize, but an advertising
contract for the Florida Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Because of better-than-expected Nielsen ratings that PAX TV has
generated since its launch Monday, local advertisers have taken
note.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the lottery, three more new advertisers signed on by
Wednesday in the West Palm Beach market, according to Roger Koch,
station manager at WPXP-Channel 67.
</P>
<P>
   The station has about 30 contracts with advertisers including,
Hulett Pest Control, Schumacher Automotive and Rapids Water Park,
Koch said. According to one advertiser, the spots range from $30 to
$150.
</P>
<P>
   But one advertiser got an even better deal. A Carl's Furniture
commercial aired Wednesday night at no cost _ a trial run while the
South Florida retailer and the station are in negotiations, Koch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carl's is ``the exception, because of the potential dollars they
can spend with us. They are a top 10 advertiser in the market,''
Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   The South Florida furniture company has 14 stores in areas from
Stuart to Kendall, according to Carl's Advertising Director Gary
Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at whether or not we're going to put them into
our annual mix,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   PAX, whose parent is Paxson Communications (AMEX: PAX, $10.31)
in West Palm Beach, has promised viewers and advertisers its
programming will be free of sex and violence and provide viewing
for the family. The foundation of its programming are reruns of
Touched by an Angel, Diagnosis Murder and Dr. Quinn, Medicine
Woman.
</P>
<P>
   The target viewers are women age 25 to 54, a demographic that's
a close match to what Carl's is looking for, Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a couple months before Carl's decides whether to buy
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We buy on an annual basis,'' Fitzpatrick said. ``We'll make
these decisions in October and November. If they do numbers, it'll
be a good buy,'' Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also noted that PAX doesn't have to do big numbers to be
successful. ``They do 2s (in ratings) and a lot of people are going
to buy that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research's overnight ratings of PAX's prime time
programming Wednesday was 2.1 in the West Palm Beach market. And
while the rating service has not provided a national rating for PAX
yet, a Paxson-devised measure put it at 1.4 on a national basis.
Both were nearly the same as the first night's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Barnette, of Barnette Advertising Group in West Palm Beach,
said he bought a three-month contract with WPXP on behalf of
Schumacher Automotive. Barnette wouldn't say what the ads cost, but
said the range for spots on stations in this market was wide: from
$20 to $4,000 for each spot.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Rice, marketing director and co-star of advertisements for
Hulett Environmental Services, bought a year's worth of
advertisements, with prices ranging from $30 for a daytime spot to
$150 for an ad in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits our demographic mix,'' Rice said, pointing out that
the pest control company likes to play to homeowners because its
business is residential.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Paxson reached an agreement Thursday to be carried by
Century Cable in markets where it has no broadcast stations. The
cable operator is the nation's eighth largest.
</P>
<P>
   A busy week
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday's launch of PAX TV, the network:
</P>
<P>
   Generated what analysts called `pretty impressive' ratings in
its debut
</P>
<P>
   Was knocked off the air briefly during a storm Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   Secured four local advertisers, including the Florida Lottery
</P>
<P>
   Reached an agreement to be carried by Century Cable in markets
where it has no stations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-03-98 2037E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
