<HEADER>
A9025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRATT-FLORIDA05-COX     09-04 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRATT-FLORIDA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pratt shutting down Riviera's Turbo Power
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Pratt &AMP; Whitney will close its Turbo Power
and Marine Systems subsidiary in Riviera Beach, Florida, leaving as
many as 52 employees without jobs, the company said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Turbo Power makes industrial gas turbine generators for
electrical power stationsplants. The small stepsister of Pratt's
huge Large Military Engines and Space Propulsion units in
northwestern Palm Beach County appears to be the first local
casualty of Pratt's plans to restructure its operations.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 of the workers are members of Local 971 of the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers. Its
secretary-treasurer, Paul Strand, said the company pledged to try
to absorb some of the positions at its sprawling plant on the
Beeline Highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best we can hope for is for them to absorb some of those
folks into (the Beeline) facility. According to their memo, they
said they would try,'' Strand said.
</P>
<P>
   The average pay of an hourly worker at Turbo Power is $20 an
hour, Strand said.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt spokesman Gary Minor said the volume of Turbo Power
production has been flat and the company can't justify keeping the
plant open. It has faced increasing competition from ABB Group of
Sweden, Rolls-Royce of England and General Electric, and couldn't
improve its already low market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been a particularly strong business for Pratt &AMP;
Whitney. The demand just hasn't been there for our product,'' Minor
said. ``We've always had single-digit market share. We're not a
significant player in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will try to relocate some of the workers, but others
will lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about severance and outplacement assistance
now,'' Minor said.
</P>
<P>
   Minor emphasized that Turbo Power's closing isn't an indication
of Pratt's intentions with its remote jet-engine and rocket plant,
where it employs 4,900 as Palm Beach County's largest employer.
Rumors have circulated for months that the company will lay off
workers, MOME design teams or the entire plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not associated with any rumors related to the closing
of the Large Military Engine and Space facility. It's actually a
wholly owned subsidiary of Pratt. No other decisions have been
made,'' Minor said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gov. Lawton Chiles and Pratt President Karl Krapek
have agreed to drop their meeting at the Farnborough Air Show in
England next week. Krapek had invited Chiles to meet after the
governor had called him with concerns about the company moving its
Florida operation to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor and Karl have agreed that no meeting is required
at this point,'' Minor said, because no other decisions on the
local plant have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
