<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WASTE05-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Nuclear plant sends improper letters to environmental panel
</P>
<P>
   By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ There's a fine line between the wonders of technology
and the blunders of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Utilities, a Dallas-based electric utility, and the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission learned that lesson this
week. As a result, officials are scrambling to salvage a
two-year-old legal case involving a proposed disposal site for
low-level radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   The blunder began when Jim Kelley, vice president of nuclear
engineering for Texas Utilities, urged employees of the company's
Comanche Peak nuclear power plant to write the state's three
environmental commissioners in support of the disposal site.
Conveniently, his memorandum included the electronic-mail addresses
of the commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mails, propelled by the click of a computer mouse button
and the wonders of the Internet, arrived Monday and Tuesday when
Chairman Barry McBee and commissioners John Baker and Ralph Marquez
logged onto their computers.
</P>
<P>
   There was just one problem: It's illegal for a party in a
pending legal matter to communicate directly with the
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mistake, frankly,'' said Eric Schmitt, a spokesman
for Texas Utilities. ``It was an innocent mistake. There was no
intent to try to short-circuit the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The violation is a serious one and in theory could require the
case to be thrown out and restarted from scratch, said Geoff
Connor, the conservation commission's general counsel. But the
infraction appears to be curable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Connor notified all parties in the case and gave
them until Sept. 18 to file legal briefs in response to the
e-mails, which argued that the site was geologically safe and that
it would have positive social and economic impacts.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners are expected to decide later this year whether
to grant a license to the Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Disposal Authority to build and operate a landfill near Sierra
Blanca, 90 miles southeast of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Two state hearing examiners recommended last month that the
commissioners reject the application because of questions about a
geologic fault and inadequate examination of socioeconomic issues.
The U.S. Senate on Wednesday enacted a measure allowing Maine and
Vermont to ship waste to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, the conservation commissioners function in a
quasi-judicial role. Much like judges, they are not supposed to
receive communications from parties in a pending case unless those
communications take place in a formal public session or are
submitted in writing simultaneously to all parties in the case.
</P>
<P>
   David Frederick, a lawyer representing the Sierra Club Legal
Defense Fund and other opponents of the waste site, said Texas
Utilities officials ``got caught with their hand in the cookie
jar.'' He said the incident did not seem to warrant starting the
case from scratch, however.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Caroom, a lawyer for the disposal authority, said he
doubted the e-mails raised any issues that had not come up in a
two-month hearing earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first instance of improper communication at the
environmental agency under the Bush administration, Connor said.
Staff members routinely screen letters, faxes and phone calls to
the commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail is not screened,'' Connor said. ``It just pops up on
their computers. E-mail is a very useful tool, and I wouldn't want
to unduly restrict its use. But that's obviously something we have
to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
