<HEADER>
A9028 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD05-COX     09-04 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodworkers' 'jewels' have grain, reveal painstaking delicacy
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now for something completely different:
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry. Wooden jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry by its very name connotes precious metals and stones,
but it has come to mean virtually any sort of personal adornment,
and you'd be surprised, perhaps, at how many woodworkers are making
jewelry, and how striking so much of it can be.
</P>
<P>
   All this is embodied in a new book from Sterling entitled ``The
Art of Making Fine Wood Jewelry,'' by Tony Lydgate, who made his
reputation on boxes designed to hold jewelry. The book, one of
Sterling's more lavish publications with lots of color
illustrations, is $19.95 in softcover. As far as I know it's the
only book extant on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The book covers the work of two dozen people. Some of it is not
difficult, in a technical sense, at all, providing your hands and
eyes are up to such fiddly work. Mine are not.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, a single simple project is outlined. However, the
book fortunately doesn't waste space trying to teach you things
like turning on the lathe.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the makers in this book use built-up laminate blocks as
the starting point for their jewelry. This is a simple matter of
selecting a bunch of thin strips of constrasting woods and veneers,
deciding upon a happy sequence for them, and glueing them up. Once
the block is ready, pieces are cut out of it at angles and put
together, sometimes with pieces from other blocks, to make the
finished pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The only technical problem here is, of course, absolutely
perfect and virtually invisible glue joints in the laminates. The
technique, of course, is perfect for rapid production.
</P>
<P>
   The many ways in which these laminates can be used is
fascinating. One maker, David Marson of Arkansas, makes very
intricate laminates and uses the end grain as a face, resulting in
work that is reminiscent of the rosettes in fine, if somewhat
gaudy, guitars.
</P>
<P>
   There are several turners represented, including that well-known
mistress of the miniature lathe, Bonnie Klein. Her work is quite
fine, but I like it no better than that of Mark Burhans, a young
midwesterner I met several years ago in St. Paul. Mark works in
spalled wooods, making every simple but very elegent pins and
buttons. Most charming are his tiny flower vase pins, into which
live wildflowers may be inserted.
</P>
<P>
   Shinichi Miyazaki makes a variety of work, ranging from
bracelets to small boxes, but most elegant of all are his small
combs.
</P>
<P>
   A young man with the unlikely name of T. Breeze VerDant uses
exquisite marquetry for his pins, which are among the most striking
work in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pieces appear to be shaped using a belt sander, but
a few are carefully carved. Chief among these are the fetish
jewelry _ exquisitely carved figurines of animals or objects _ of
Pat Metheny, the largely abstract work of William Chappelow, and
the tiny birds and musical instruments of Karen Scates.
</P>
<P>
   In the area of mixed media, most spectacular is the work of
Mindy and Larry King: insects with bodies of wood and appendages
made of wire.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful work in this scale is done in very
fine-grained wood; there are a few pieces here done in
coarse-grained wood which simply don't look right.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, much of what is in this book could be done in a
minimum of space and with very few tools; a bandsaw, a small belt
sander, perhaps a couple of good bench planes and some other
standard hand tools. It's just one more good way to get into
woodworking without hocking the family heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
