<SLUG> BC-VOC-FLORIDA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VOC Analytical buyout saves 45 jobs
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ A buyout of VOC Analytical's assets in a
bankruptcy liquidation will save 45 jobs in Palm Beach County, but
holders of the company's stock weren't as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer, Massachusetts-based U.S. Biosystems, is a private
pharmaceutical company in Wellesley, Mass. It produces drugs for
diagnostic imaging and plans to expand the Boca Raton operation to
add pharmaceuticals to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent is to build onto the facilities we already have,''
said John Connors, who is chairman of Biosystems.
</P>
<P>
   The Boca Raton operation, which was the first company to move
into the Florida Atlantic University research park, does
environmental testing for companies trying to comply with state and
federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Biosystems bought the assets of VOC for $1.5 million from
Comerica Bank and Brown &AMP; Caldwell, an environmental consulting
firm in California. The two were VOC's secured creditors who took
possession of the assets after foreclosing on collateral from loans
to VOC.
</P>
<P>
   Biosystems, which employs 70 people, bought VOC's operation on
July 25, three days after the VOC Chapter 11 bankruptcy case was
converted to a Chapter 7 proceeding to liquidate its assets. VOC
had filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Biosystems, Palm Beach County would have lost
45 jobs. Every person was rehired,'' said Alex Moreno, former chief
executive of VOC. Biosystems also hired Moreno as the manager of
its Boca Raton operation.
</P>
<P>
   The holders of the company's 5.9 million shares probably won't
be compensated. They are below unsecured creditors in the pecking
order of who receives money as a result of the sale of assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholders? They won't get anything unless someone buys the
corporate shell,'' said U. S. Bankruptcy Trustee Patricia
Dzikowski.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy case remains open to administer any assets other
than the physical assets already sold, to pursue claims and to
resolve legal challenges, Dzikowski said. VOC's registration as a
publicly traded company remains in effect and could be sold to pay
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a couple of inquiries. We've talked to them and they
haven't come back with anything concrete,'' Dzikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   One legal issue to be resolved is whether federal and state
regulators will receive money from any fines as a result of the
company's pleading guilty to unlawful disposal of hazardous waste
this week. The decision will be announced on Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
