<SLUG> BC-PARAMOUNT-RENOVATES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paramount improves Kings Island
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the eve of its third biggest weekend of the year, Paramount's
Kings Island announced plans to add a new roller coaster and a
free-fall drop ride.
</P>
<P>
   The projects are part of a $40 million capital-improvement
program slated to take place over the next two years. Park
officials said the proposed projects are Kings Island's largest
investment since it was constructed for $35 million 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The new rides are: _ Face/Off: Company officials said the
coaster will have paired sets of seats which face each other.
Riders of the hanging roller coaster will go over a 138-foot hill,
fly through a 72-foot loop, a boomerang with two inversions and up
another hill at 55 mph. They then repeat the ride backwards. _ Drop
Zone: A 315-foot free-fall ride, Drop Zone lifts and spins riders
on a 30-foot ring outfitted with 40 seats up more than 26 stories
and then drops them in a 67 mph free fall. Park officials bill the
ride as the world's largest ``gyro-drop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sort of set up a reputation or expectation for world
record thrill rides and we're just building on that reputation,''
park spokeswoman Barbara Colnar said.
</P>
<P>
   Colnar said the investment also includes construction of a third
ride, but she declined further details.
</P>
<P>
   Both rides will be placed at the park's northwest end. Plans
call for the park to recondition the area to resemble a movie
studio's backlot and rename it the Paramount Action Zone. The Top
Gun and King Cobra roller coasters, which sit near the proposed new
rides, will undergo cosmetic changes to fit in with the new theme,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials declined to say how much the projects will cost
individually. The park sits on 712 acres, only 237 of which are
developed.
</P>
<P>
   Crews expect work on Face/Off to start next week and conclude
before the park's April opening. Drop Zone will be ready by
Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day weekend stands as the park's third busiest time of
year. But holiday weekends typically do not attract the size crowds
one would expect since most people prefer to attend other events
such as family barbecues, Colnar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before (Memorial Day) and after Labor Day, it's really
Cincinnati and Dayton's park,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the smaller crowds, people traveling to Kings Island or
its neighbor, The Beach Waterpark, can expect slow going this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State Patrol Lt. R. Scott Borden said Labor Day usually
means heavy traffic around King's Island and The Beach. However an
effort to consolidate two exit ramps into one will slow traffic
even more this weekend, Borden said. Crews are combining two exit
ramps from Interstate 71 at Ohio 741 into a single, multi-lane
ramp, a project slated for completion in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, the weekends have been bad there all summer,''
Borden said.
</P>
<P>
   To offset this, the OSP's Lebanon post will station two troopers
between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m. _ the heaviest traffic time _at the exit
ramps to manually control traffic lights and prevent traffic from
backing up onto I-71.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the inconvenience, Borden suggests travelers factor
in construction delays and practice patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get angry,'' he said. ``Everybody is doing everything
they can. Getting angry just affects your driving rationale and
affects the nice day you had planned with the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
