<SLUG> BC-USOPEN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sampras, Agassi, Rusedski need extra sets
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pete Sampras needed four sets against a wild card
fresh out of Stanford who is friendly with first daughter Chelsea
Clinton. Andre Agassi took five to beat a 45th-ranked Frenchman
with a home in Boca Raton. And sixth seed Greg Rusedski held off a
match point to win in five sets for the second round in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from those few struggles, most of the top players
remain in both the men's and women's draws at the U.S. Open
entering the fifth day of play. On the men's side, just three of
the 16 seeds have lost with half of the second round left.
</P>
<P>
   The women didn't even have that much trouble: top seed Martina
Hingis, second seed Lindsay Davenport, fifth seed Venus Williams
and 15th seed Anna Kournikova all won in straight sets Thursday.
And the only women's seed not to reach the third round was Ai
Sugiyama, the 16th seed who retired from her second-round match
with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been weird because in other tournaments there have been
a lot of upsets and a lot of close matches,'' said Davenport, who
beat 35-year-old Lori McNeil 6-1, 6-1. ``You can't control things
like that and I don't know what the reason is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, the No. 1 seed and four-time champion, also didn't have
an explanation for the number of seeds remaining. He considered
fourth seed Petr Korda's first-round loss a big upset, but the only
other seeds missing are Alberto Berasategui (15) and Albert Costa
(16).
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who last won here in 1996, played a tight match against
Stanford graduate Paul Goldstein, member of a record four NCAA
championship teams. He won 7-6 (7-4), 2-6, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldstein, 22, didn't allow Sampras, 27, any service break
opportunities and lost just a handful of points on his own serve in
the first two sets. The crowd eagerly got behind the underdog,
making the match even more enjoyable for Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect going out there,'' he said.
``Part of me know I should feel I should win. Part of me wanted to
keep him out there at least an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goldstein never really felt he could win. That matched
Sampras' feelings, which appeared in the third set when he moved
better and played more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was really in risk of losing the match,'' he
said. ``It was one of those days where I wasn't playing that great
and I just needed to find a way (to win).''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi had to do the same thing, and it took him four minutes
less than three hours to fend off outstanding play by France's
Guillaume Raoux. Agassi eased by Raoux in the first two sets, then
had his serve broken early in the third set.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, the eighth seed and the 1994 Open winner, earned the
break back but lost the set in a tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real frustrated at myself for a period of the fourth set
for not executing my shots in the tiebreaker, and I lost my serve
early,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fifth set, Agassi fought off a break point in the
first game and then seemed to cruise, as Raoux increased his
errors. Agassi won 6-3, 6-2, 6-7 (6-8), 3-6, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski, a finalist here last year before losing to Patrick
Rafter, played Czech Bohdan Ulihrach, the second unseeded opponent
to take the Canadian to five sets. Ulihrach, 23, stretched Rusedski
to 4-6, 6-3, 4-6, 6-2, 7-5 and two hours, 50 minutes to earn the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski injured his ankle just before Wimbledon and had taken
two months off before the Open. He thinks the time off contributed
to his two long early matches. In the first round, he defeated
Wayne Ferreira 4-6, 7-6 (7-2), 5-7, 7-6 (9-7), 6-4. He plays Jan
Siemerink, ranked 21, next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never won two matches in five sets in a row before so
that just gives you more confidence,'' Rusedski said. ``Two days
ago, (I fought off) two match points. Today it was one so hopefully
there won't be any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
