<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-POLICE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minority recruiting gap delays police cadet class
 &HT;    By Bob Banta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin Police Department officials say they are
seriously lagging in their attempts to recruit more minority
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Their inability to attract African Americans, Hispanics and
women to the department, despite a big pay and benefits increase
approved earlier this year, is one of the reasons a November cadet
class has been postponed until January.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the lack of success range from competition by big
corporations to a distrust of the police in some parts of town,
according to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more black female applicants and just a lot more
females in general,'' said Lt. Joy Mooney, an African American
officer who heads recruiting for the department. ``A minority can
do more inside the police force to correct attitudes by the
community than they can from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eight cadet classes that have graduated since January
1995, 13 percent of the applicants were Hispanic _ 7 percentage
points lower than the department's goal. Nine percent of the
applicants were black, compared with the 11 percent recruiters were
hoping to get.
</P>
<P>
   While officials have struggled to make at least 20 percent of
the applicants women, only 12 percent of the applicants to the past
eight cadet classes were women, according to police figures.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Police Officer Catherine Haggerty, a 16-year veteran of
the force, said police work ``has been and still is a
male-dominated world, and that in itself may discourage some
women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From television, the public gets the perception that we are
tough and throw people around and wield guns and run down the
street,'' said Haggerty, president of the Austin Police Women's
Association. ``This makes some women less inclined to look at it as
a profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Although female recruits are especially sought by the department
these days, officers are combing minority neighborhoodsseeking
African Americans and Hispanics of either gender.
</P>
<P>
   Minority recruitment has been difficult because of sometimes
troubled relationships between police and minority communities.
Harsh feelings still linger from a 1995 Valentine's party on Cedar
Avenue in East Austin that ended with the mainly African American
party-goers scuffling with police.
</P>
<P>
   Party organizers called police to remove a suspected gang member
from the gathering, and 80 officers responded after an officer was
injured. Several of the teen-agers also were injured, and some
accused officers of using excessive force and racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit some party-goers filed against the police department
was settled out of court in July, with police admitting no
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who read about things like Cedar Avenue are focusing on
isolated instances,'' said Senior Sgt. Joe Munoz, head of Amigos en
Azul (Friends in Blue), which represents more than 150 Hispanic
officers in the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems have occurred, but these situations have involved all
colors, so everybody has to deal with (distrust),'' he said.
``Regardless of what's happened in the past, the police chief (Stan
Knee) has made it clear that fair treatment is a top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, veteran black and Hispanic officers are spending
time in neighborhoods scouting for promising young African American
and Hispanic adults they feel would make good cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this individualized approach will work,'' Munoz said.
``It's got to. The biggest problem we have with recruiting
minorities is not problems like Cedar Avenue. It's competition from
corporate America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These young people are asking themselves, `Why be a cop and
work night shifts and get shot at when you can go to work for Dell
or Motorola?''' he said. ``We've got to show them that we've got a
pretty good salary and benefits program and that police work is
extremely satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those face-to-face recruitment drives will occur Sept. 12
at the Austin Area Urban League Center. Officers will brief
interested people on requirements for being an officer, including
the types of tests given and the 28-week academy training course.
</P>
<P>
   Mooney said she hopes the the Urban League gathering and similar
programs will bolster the number of minorities in the postponed
class, which starts Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for delaying the class is to give training
officers a chance to add new curriculum and training methods to the
cadet courses.
</P>
<P>
   One of the possibilities being studied by academy commander Jim
Fealy is working the concept of community policing into every
aspect of police training.
</P>
<P>
   Community policing allows officers to get to know residents on
their beats and solve problems before they become crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we teach community policing as one block course,''
Fealy said.
</P>
<P>
   Postponement of the fall cadet class will not interfere with
producing enough cadets to reach the department's goal of having
more than 1,111 officers by next fall, according to police
spokeswoman Sally Muir. The department had 1,048 officers as of
late July. The total fluctuates day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
