<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agassi may cut Davis Cup ties
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Poor decision-making and players' lack of control has
ruined Andre Agassi's view of Davis Cup, and he's so frustrated he
may never play for the United States again.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi already had said he won't play the upcoming match against
Italy because the USTA-selected location conflicts with an event
for his charity foundation. He will not play the final round
either, if the team wins in Milwaukee on Sept. 25-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was in my backyard, I wouldn't walk out the back door to
play,'' Agassi said Thursday. ``I have heard a lot of apologies in
the last number of years ... (but) if you are really sorry about
something, be sorry enough to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis Cup has suffered from numerous problems in the past 10
years, including many players' refusal to play, a team captain
dispute, high ticket prices and refusing to let players make more
decisions _ from team captain to site selection. The USTA handles
U.S. Davis Cup issues.
</P>
<P>
   World No.1 Pete Sampras did not play the first two matches of
the year, won't play the third and probably will not play a final.
Michael Chang also hasn't played this year. He has no tournament
conflicts with the Italy match but wants to continue getting
healthy and has told captain Tom Gullikson he won't be available.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves 27th-ranked Todd Martin as the top player available.
Possibilities to join him are: Justin Gimelstob (ranked 89th and
injured), Jan-Michael Gambill (57), Boca Raton's Vince Spadea (42)
and Richey Reneberg as a doubles partner for Martin. Davis Cup
stalwart Jim Courier is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a good chance (to win),'' Agassi said. ``(But)
there is going to be a guy playing there that hasn't played before
and we have got to ask Todd to come through with three points, and
that is asking a lot under any conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Each win in a Davis Cup match equals one point.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi doesn't expect anything to change, because these are
issues he has complained about, publicly and privately, on many
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patching it up: Venus Williams wore the required Corel WTA
Tour patch on her neon-green cut-out dress, a decision she
discussed only briefly after her match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, I always wear the patch when I play,'' she said.
``I wasn't sending any messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok left the decision on how to handle the controversy to
Williams. She didn't wear the patch in her first match Tuesday and
was fined $100. Reebok said it would violate her contract to wear a
patch.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' first-round dress was strapless, but the second-round
dress had shoulder straps with room for the patch. Williams put it
sideways on the top of one shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   _ Safin advances: Unseeded Russian teenager Marat Safin easily
defeated unseeded American teenager Taylor Dent in a battle of
probable future stars.
</P>
<P>
   Safin, 18, won 6-3, 6-1, 7-6 (7-2) behind 35 winners. Dent, son
of former Australian player Phil Dent, made 29 unforced errors and
never got a chance to break Safin's serve.
</P>
<P>
   Dent, 17, was playing in his first tournament as a professional.
He entered his first grand slam with a wild card, meaning he can
keep the $18,000 prize money. The Newport Beach, Calif., player
reached the second round when his first-round opponent retired with
cramps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really played as well as I can at this level yet,''
Dent said. ``I'm a little inexperienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
