A9039 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIRT-RUCKUS05-COX     09-04 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIRT-RUCKUS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bastrop debates shirttail ruckus
 &HT;    By Rebeca Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nearly 300 Bastrop High School students, parents
and administrators gathered recently to speak, listen and learn
more about a controversial dress-code rule requiring students to
tuck in their shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The rule, which was written into the district's dress code this
summer in an effort to make it easier for school officials to spot
concealed weapons, had not been strictly enforced at the high
school during the first two weeks of classes. Earlier this week,
however, teachers began enforcing the rule, prompting some students
to speak out against it.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which was called after more than 100 students
walked out of their second-period classes and marched from the high
school to the district's administration building, was intended to
be a dialogue on the issue, not a meeting to change the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to consider what you've said,'' said Bastrop
Superintendent John Walch. ``I purposefully tried to be open.''
</P>
<P>
   Walch said the rule will be considered at a previously scheduled
school board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At least two-dozen speakers _ students and parents _ took the
podium in the school cafeteria to voice opinions and suggestions
about the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Richardson, a parent, said a rule requiring shirts to be
tucked in is too controlling and takes away students' freedom to be
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``School controls their life almost 100 percent these days,''
she said. ``Taking away their freedom of wearing their shirt
untucked is not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said she has a thin daughter and a larger daughter.
The rule, which school officials had said would be flexibly applied
to pregnant and obese students, discriminated against her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thin daughter is being punished, and my other one is not,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another parent, Hector Hernandez, beamed with pride over his
children's participation in the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, am I proud that my kids are in Bastrop High School and
they're doing things the American way,'' said Hernandez, a Bastrop
truck driver who had just returned from a trip. But not everyone
said they believed the rule is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Milliken, a father of two boys, was one of about three
speakers who had a different perspective on tucking in shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly agree with the rule, but I prefer a stricter
version of it,'' said Milliken, who has one son at Bastrop High and
another in a San Marcos boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule not only encourages respectable appearance, but it
encourages discipline,'' Milliken said.
</P>
<P>
   Uniforms would be an even better idea, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of uniforms appeared deplorable to many of the
students who took the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is your uniform, ma'am?'' student Michelina Fideli said
to one woman who had just advocated uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Although the meeting was peppered with sometimes disruptive
applause, school officials were generally pleased with the results
and looked forward to finding a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they will go away from here knowing we do listen,''
said Bastrop High Principal James Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
