<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9041 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWU-EXPANDS05-COX     09-04 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWU-EXPANDS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southwestern will unveil new building in October
 &HT;    By Pamela Coleman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Southwestern University unveils its new
campus center next month, the white limestone building will mark
one of the final steps in a decade-long push to upgrade facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz of construction has long filtered throughout the
liberal arts college's rolling grounds, as crews replaced a women's
dormitory, added a recreation center, built on-campus apartments,
erected an academic building and cleared playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   A 24,000-square-foot science building expansion will be finished
later this year, and an expanded fine arts center will open next
summer _ all this as the university prepares to celebrate the 100th
anniversary Tuesday of the oldest structure on campus, the Cullen
Building.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of Leadership 2000, the university's $75 million
campaign that includes scholarship funds and $42 million in new
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the buzz of saws and rumble of tractors on campus aren't
because of a booming student population. While full-time enrollment
and faculty at Southwestern have increased 30 percent over the last
two decades, school leaders decided in the 1980s to cap enrollment
at about 1,200 to maintain quality and a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   That's been difficult. Last year saw an enrollment of 1,215
students and the largest graduating class ever _ 284. This year,
the university, which has received national recognition as an
outstanding liberal arts college, accepted 378 incoming freshmen,
up from 334 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've added buildings not because we we're growing, but
because we wanted to enhance programs in academic and student
life,'' said Marilyn Rhoads Mock, vice president for university
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Red &AMP; Charline McCombs Campus Center was among half a dozen
construction projects outlined in the Leadership 2000 plan. From
the outside, the center resembles most other campus buildings _
white limestone, built in the Richardsonian-Roman- esque style,
found in many of the state's old county courthouses.
</P>
<P>
   But that old-fashioned style stops at the center's door. A
Starbucks coffee shop will peddle espresso and pastries inside, and
students will lounge on beanbag chairs in front of a 120-inch TV
screen. A food-court-style dining area, with lines where cooks
prepare food as diners watch, will cater to dorm residents, and a
marble fireplace and overstuffed furniture will beckon visitors who
just want to relax.
</P>
<P>
   A ballroom, meeting rooms, student activities area, bookstore
and post office also are part of the 62,000-square-foot facility,
which is more than twice the size of the school's old student
union. That building, built in the 1960s, was torn down to make way
for the new structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the wish list was fulfilled,'' said student Charles
Boehm, public relations chairman for the student government.
</P>
<P>
   Boehm will work in the new building as a staffer on the The
Megaphone, the campus newspaper that has been temporarily housed at
the college's old animal behavior lab.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Connally, student body president, said the new center is
long-awaited. ``Not having a central meeting place for students has
been hard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Red McCombs, chairman of the university's board of trustees,
donated $6 million toward construction of the $11.5 million
facility and headed the Leadership 2000 fund-raising project. The
San Antonio businessman said the new center will become the
heartbeat of the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this center means to the 1,200 students is, this is their
dining room, living room and den,'' McCombs said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect to serve the first meal at the center on Oct.
5. An open house is planned for Oct. 9-11, and a dedication
ceremony is set for Oct. 17, said Jaime Woody, director of student
activities and summer conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at first hoped to renovate the existing student union,
said Richard Anderson, vice president for fiscal affairs. But, he
said, ``Because of structural problems with that building, we
decided we couldn't save it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a common problem at older campuses. And Southwestern,
which formed when four small Methodist colleges built in the 1840s
merged, is one of the oldest in the state. First called Texas
University in 1873, it gave up that name in 1875 so the state could
name its own public institution the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni are proud to point out that Southwestern beat UT-Austin
in the first college baseball game ever played in the state, in
1884.
</P>
<P>
   But the school struggled during the Great Depression, and the
administration couldn't guarantee it would stay open from one year
to the next. The turnaround came during World War II, when the War
Department awarded the campus a naval training unit.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment grew slowly from 600 in 1958 to 1,000 in 1978 and
1,200 today. That could change as faculty develop a new plan to
lead the school into the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that rather than trying to become a grandiose school
and try to compete in size, we'll put our money into quality
educational components,'' said William B. Jones, acting provost and
dean of faculty.
</P>
<P>
   The new campus center is an example of just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to do something for cohesion of faculty and
students on campus,'' Jones said. ``It's almost what you would call
a little village. I think it's going to improve what is already a
good spirit on campus, make it more intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0077 </DOCNO>
