</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release the weekend of Saturday, September 5,
1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ If Russia had a government, it would
be flat broke. Before being shown the door, the prior government
defaulted on $40 billion in short-term debt _ money that was mostly
sucked out of the country with its connivance by the ruling
oligarchy. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ President Bill Clinton has returned from what we
may fairly, alas, call the Pathetic Summit to a worsening sink of
foreign problems that steamy, seamy Monicamess leaves him little
authority to deal with. The president either must find a way to put
this thing behind him or let Al Gore take command. (Teepen, Cox
News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ What Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have done
for baseball this year, in addition to filling stadiums that
otherwise would be near empty, is return the sport to its raw
basic: pitcher throws ball, batter slams the bejabbers out of it.
For too many recent years, the actual playing of the game has been
influenced by other elements, particularly pitching terminology I
cannot comprehend, or by calls by umpires that are beyond our
recognition. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   CSIBLEY-COLUMN _ It's not that I wanted a glass of sweet tea. I
really prefer it half-and-half, and most restaurants gladly mix it
for you. But I had to go to the Sweet Tea Sip-Off in Mobile, Ala.
because my friend Jay Greland, the Mobile Register columnist, and
the newspaper itself organized and sponsored it. (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 9/3.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _WACO, Texas _ Home runs are the most exciting
part of baseball. That's my opinion. I'd rather see a ball hit out
of the stadium than watch a pitcher throw a perfect game. If that
shows my ignorance of the game, then so be it. Mickey Mantle made
me this way. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ Last fall a South Georgia friend, knowing of my
taste for old-fashioned eating, sent us a bottle of prime cane
syrup. It languished unopened on a back shelf in the pantry for
almost a year. Now that they have been ruled medically incorrect,
my wife is never anxious for me to indulge in the wonderful but
allegedly artery-clogging delicacies that were staples of the
Southern diet before food police ruled everything good is bad. I
was surprised when she mentioned the syrup. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Growing up in Piqua, Becky Howe learned little
girls didn't speak up, didn't rock the boat. You'd think, with all
this practice, at age 50, she'd be adept at holding her peace. Not
so. Miami County's unlikely new heroine has been speaking her mind
since June 9, when she received notice that Anthem was planning to
cancel her coverage and that of some 20,000 Ohio residents using
its Medicare HMO, known as Senior Advantage. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
