 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release on the weekend of Saturday,
September 5, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New York
Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   DOWNSIZING-CONDO When Jill Vantosh, an Atlanta interior
designer, downsized froma house to a condo, she seized an
opportunity to create a streamlined interior that emphasizes a few
of her favorite things _ including an unconventional material.
Vantosh stripped the second-floor unit of a 1950s red-brick
building to its concrete bones, from floor to ceiling , then
extended the material to the kitchen countertops. The result is a
clean, industrial look made warm and inviting by juxtaposing the
unpainted beams and chrome furnishings with oak floors and rich
cabinetry. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DOWNSIZING-TIPS _ Tips on downsizing. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LAWN-FIGHT _ TEQUESTA, Fla. _ A Tequesta couple that has battled
village officials for almost a decade over their landscaping was
cited again this week for violating village codes. Hattie and Bill
Siegel were cited for excessive accumulation of plant material
because their yard is overgrown and untended, village officials
said. The Siegels, who have lived in their house on Dover Road for
three decades, have chosen to landscape their back and front yards
with native plants and other shrubs, trees and flowers that require
little water to survive. (Scharnhorst, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD_ Jewelry by its very name connotes precious
metals and stones, but it has come to mean virtually any sort of
personal adornment, and you'd be surprised, perhaps, at how many
woodworkers are making jewelry, and how striking so much of it can
be. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SWU-EXPANDS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ When Southwestern University
unveils its new campus center next month, the white limestone
building will mark one of the final steps in a decade-long push to
upgrade facilities. It's all part of Leadership 2000, the
university's $75 million campaign that includes scholarship funds
and $42 million in new facilities. (Coleman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-POLICE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin Police Department
officials say they are seriously lagging in their attempts to
recruit more minority officers. Their inability to attract African
Americans, Hispanics and women to the department, despite a big pay
and benefits increase approved earlier this year, is one of the
reasons a November cadet class has been postponed until January.
(Banta, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHIRT-RUCKUS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Nearly 300 Bastrop High School
students, parents and administrators gathered recently to speak,
listen and learn more about a controversial dress-code rule
requiring students to tuck in their shirts. Earlier this week
teachers began enforcing the rule, prompting some students to speak
out against it. (Rodriguez, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   PAX-ADS _ PAX TV won the lottery this week. Not the state's $6
million Lotto prize, but an advertising contract for the Florida
Lottery. Because of better-than-expected Nielsen ratings that PAX
TV has generated since its launch Monday, local advertisers have
taken note. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-WASTE _ AUSTIN _ There's a fine line between the wonders
of technology and the blunders of technology. Texas Utilities, a
Dallas-based electric utility, and the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission learned that lesson this week. As a result,
officials are scrambling to salvage a two-year-old legal case
involving a proposed disposal site for low-level radioactive waste.
(Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   VALUES-LABOR _ In these days of often surly service, a few
people seem to relish their jobs, taking pleasure in the most
menial work and always showing consideration for others. For Labor
Day weekend, we find some of those people and write about them in
the context of the theology of work. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   VALUES-LABOR-PEOPLE _ Six people who enjoy their work and bring
joy to others. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
