NYT-09-04-98 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX     09-04 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Dan Burton and the Jimmy Carter effect
 &HT;    (EDS: This column, which normally would move on Monday, is
moving today because of the Labor Day holiday.)
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I can think of few prospects less appealing than being treated
to a recitation of Dan Burton's sleepovers. Yet that intelligence
seems imminent. Word is widely about that this avidly unsought
information will soon surface in Vanity Fair magazine, and if not
there then in the Indianapolis Star or in other, as-yet unnamed
publications.
</P>
<P>
   There is suddenly a run on the sex life of the Republican
chairman of the House's Government Reform and Oversight Committee,
which has been investigating _ and investigating and investigating
_ Democratic political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Burton himself has acknowledged the bull market in his hanky
panky, tendering a pre-emptive confession in which he says he will
admit to whatever any publication gets right. The Indiana
congressman offers that he and his wife have been thrice separated,
one of those times to the brink of divorce. Burton seems to be
copping a plea that goes, ``Well, what's a fellow to do?'' It's a
chase-or-be-chaste world.
</P>
<P>
   Burton suspects the White House is behind his de-pantsing.
Clinton spokesfolk say no, but who can tell? Both sides have been
playing hardball with hand grenades. It would require no Clintonite
scheme to make Burton a target of skeptical curiosity. The
combination of Burton's low-road partisanship and moral high
dudgeon _ Burton dissed Clinton as a ``scumbag'' _ is Day-Glo spoor
to hypocrisy hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been atwitter for weeks _ memo to file: make
sure Republicans actually can twitter _ over reports that the
Clinton devils are preparing a purgatory of revelations about the
peccadilloes of the president's detractors. Storm shutters have
been going up at glass houses all over Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If we are on the verge of an unwelcome contest in sexual gotcha,
the larger push for it will come from within the press itself than
from any White House pressure. There's precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon skipped town claiming, as his diehard fans still
do, that journalist enemies had set the impeachment hounds on him.
In truth, newspapers had overwhelmingly supported his re-election,
most came uneasily to the conclusion he had to go and the reporting
that did him in was provoked not by animus but by his own abuses of
power.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the media set out to prove their even-handedness by
treating the new president, Democrat Jimmy Carter, as if he were a
parolee who hadn't checked in with his parole officer. He was
quickly the suspect at the center of fantastical misdeeds involving
a ``fugitive financier'' and other odd tales, none of which proved
true, and to boot, because he had campaigned saying he would never
lie to us, his every utterance was mined for traces of uncandor.
</P>
<P>
   Something of the sort may be brewing now, as media types blamed
for bringing Clinton low strive to establish their nonpartisanship
by shining their flashlights in the back seats of GOP cars in hopes
of catching the kids necking.
</P>
<P>
   Pray not, but especially with gossipy cable shows and Internet
sites aglow with attention to which they had been unaccustomed, we
may be in for more keyhole-peeping than the house dick in a
hot-pillow hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
