<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN05-COX     09-04 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW I SPENT MY BALTIC VACATION: Jamming with the Baltic Blues
Brothers
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIGA, Latvia _ If you're a tall, blond, beautiful woman who is
tired of standing out in the crowd, come to Riga.
</P>
<P>
   It's like a pretty woman parade all day and into the night,
long-legged women in short skirts and high-heel shoes.
</P>
<P>
   None of them, alas, was wearing her dancing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   I had found my way to a blues concert along the cobbled streets
of Old Town in this capital city of Latvia, pop. 800,000. Not far
away was Castle Riga, built by German knights in 1330.
</P>
<P>
   The language of Latvia is akin to German. ``Ja'' means yes, that
much I could understand.
</P>
<P>
   But the music this particular night was 100 percent American,
though more like '50s rock-'n'-roll to my ear than the blues. Good
drums, especially considering that the drummer, Artis, is only 14
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he was the kid of the group. It turned out that the
bass guitarist, Paulis, was all of 10.
</P>
<P>
   The band billed itself as The Omi, which evidently means
something to Latvians that's lost on me. I dubbed them the Baltic
Blues Brothers instead.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the group were Kalvis, 15, rhythm guitar; Oskars, 18,
vocal and harmonica; and Martins, 17, lead guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Their music made me feel right at home.
</P>
<P>
   During a break, I got to talking with them and we hit it off.
They knew English and I knew the blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bo Diddley, B.B. King, Fats Domino,'' I said, and they
accepted me as one of them _ one of the few there who could
appreciate their music.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I couldn't help noticing while they played. That
there was not so much as a toe being tapped by the crowd gathered
in the open-air cafe where they were playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up with blues,'' Kalvis said. ``Our parents played the
records. But most of the people of Latvia just can't understand
this music.''
</P>
<P>
   When the music resumed I put the crowd to the test. But I was
the one who almost flunked.
</P>
<P>
   I must have asked a dozen women to dance. Not one would say
``Ja.'' Finally I found a partner. Obviously, I wasn't the first
American she'd danced with. But I well might have been the first
since VE Day.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to say that we were like Fred and Ginger. More like
Fred and Ethel is closer to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. It was fun while it lasted. For a fact, Miss
Geriatrics outlasted me _ danced me right off my feet, she did.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I turned in early, while Riga continued to party.
</P>
<P>
   Late that night at my hotel, I was awakened by music floating up
from the streets and through the open windows of my room.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't blues in the night. This was like ghost music _ a
haunting melody.
</P>
<P>
   On the street corner below my window, I could see a young girl
playing a violin for coins from passers-by. She seemed hardly the
age of the bass guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   Her music made me feel a long way from home.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
