<HEADER>
A9177 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     09-04 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Sept. 4, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-CAR (San Francisco) _ Another San Francisco tradition may
go down if Mayor Willie Brown has his way. He wants to replace the
manually-operated cable car turnarounds with a motorized system. He
says he's pushing the plan to save the backs, shoulders and knees
of the cable car operators. By RACHEL GORDON and TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAPPING (Redwood City, Calif.) _ Life on the levee could soon
turn deadly for stray cats, raccoons, red foxes and skunks when a
trap-and-kill plan to protect two federally endangered species
starts here next month. By EVE MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-MOVEMENT (San Francisco) _ Eleven-year-old Deonte-Lamont
Kincaid is on his way to Atlanta to experience a couple of firsts.
He has never boarded a plane and flown through the skies. And he's
never stood amid a sea of black youth gathering for a purpose. But
on Saturday, that will all change at the Million Youth Movement. By
VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   ACID-RAIN (Lake Placid, N.Y.) _ Acid rain hasn't had any
apparent effect on tourism in the Adirondacks, but the airborne
pollution is still there. Scientists say acid rain has helped kill
fish in more than 450 ponds and lakes and a number of rivers. It
also is credited with killing a number of red spruce trees. Yet
people are divided about the threat. By ALAN WECHSLER. (For release
Sunday, Sept. 6)
</P>
<P>
   MANSON-FOLLOWER (San Francisco) _ An apparent disciple of cult
leader Charles Manson is in custody after allegedly stalking a
wealthy San Francisco man whose name appeared on the cult's hit
list 23 years ago, police said. By MALCOLM GLOVER.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Chilpancigno, Mexico) _ With gubernatorial
elections scheduled in the southeastern state of Guerrero next
February, things seem headed for a crucial confrontation _
electoral if possible, armed if need be. Guerrero is a perennially
poor and restive state that has nurtured rebellion since its
namesake for decades. By PHILIP TRUE. (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NET-JOBS (San Francisco) _ Backed by Richard Strauss' ``Thus
Spake Zarathustra'' on the sound system to underscore the import of
the event and in rare self-deprecating form, San Francisco Mayor
Willie Brown has launched an Internet-based program that has the
potential to help millions of job seekers throughout California _
perhaps himself included. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Scanning the newspaper computer ads
has turned into an exercise in reverse sticker shock. Even though
it's part of my job to keep tabs on what's happening with PC
prices, I'm always amazed at the amount of power $1,000 will buy
you today. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about a
desktop problem and doesn't know if it's the monitor, the graphics
hardware, or the driver. A Q&AMP;A. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: The WORKING-COLUMN will not appear this week. L.M. Sixel
is on vacation.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOOR-KNOCKERS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The doorbell is a 200-year-old
convenience. Fashionable door-knockers, however, have been around
since the Middle Ages. Door-knockers have a simple, yet functional
design that emit a loud noise audible throughout the house. By
FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOMERUN-CHASE (San Francisco) _ At sports stores here Mark
McGwire's St. Louis Cardinals jersey is moving faster than those
Ruthian tape-measure shots he hits out of baseball parks, and
Chicago Cubs caps like the one worn by Sammy Sosa are flying off
the hat racks quicker than you can say Wrigley Field. By GREG
LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-BALLPARKS (San Francisco) _ Led by San Francisco, where a
flinty electorate has virtually closed the public purse to the
Giants and 49ers, cities across the U.S. are requiring sports
franchise owners to share in the cost of the new ballparks and
stadiums they say they need to remain economically viable. By ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FAT (San Francisco) _ The health enforcers now are targeting
high-calorie food and caffeine. Those of us in the hospitality
industry have obvious reasons for concern. A society that treats
coffee and hamburgers with the disdain once reserved for heroin and
pornography is in serious disorder. By TIM GANNON.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-MILITARY (San Francisco) _ After coming under fire for
the first time during the Vietnam war, I lit up a cigarette.
Inhaling on that death-bearing cig seemed to offer the promise I'd
walk out of the infernal mudhole alive. By BOB ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HISTORY (San Francisco) _ This Labor Day weekend,
California begins to celebrate the Gold Rush and the drive to
statehood. It will be a two-year observance, leading up to the
Sesquicentennial in the year 2000. The weekend events will also
usher in a statewide debate on the history of the Golden State.
Some Chicano activists will allege that the U.S. ``stole'' the
Southwest, including California, from Mexico. History gives lie to
these assertions. By MICHAEL WARDER.
</P>
