w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERYL-STREEP-IN-ONE-T     09-04 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERYL-STREEP-IN-ONE-TRUE-THING-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERYL STREEP'S NEW MOVIE HAS HER RECALLING EX-FIANCE'S FIGHT WITH
CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;     Includes a color slide of Meryl Streep in a scene from `One
True Thing.' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    For Meryl Streep, her new movie, ``One True Thing,'' hit close
to home, perhaps too close.
 &HT;    Playing a woman with cancer in the film based on Anna Quindlen's
best selling novel, Streep was flooded with memories of ex-fiance
John Cazale, who died of cancer in the early 1980s.
 &HT;    Streep and Cazale met on the set of ``The Deerhunter'' (1978).
When he was diagnosed with terminal cancer, Streep became his
caretaker.
 &HT;    Streep has never talked in-depth with the press about it and
it's obvious she still finds it difficult. ``It all lines up really
clearly,'' she says. ``I learned what really is important. I found
what is true and what's just stupid and meaningless and not worth
pursuing. It lined up for me at an early age. I'm sure that's why I
am strong today.''
 &HT;    On the set of ``One True Thing,'' Streep says she thought about
Cazale's fight ``on a day-to-day basis. And that was helpful to
me.''
 &HT;    With a life-or-death plot in the new movie, it's easy to see why
Streep thought of him.
 &HT;    In the movie, opening Sept. 18, it's a freezing night in
Princeton, N.J., and Streep's character is preparing to die. The
wind chill is 10 below. Snow is falling. And she is slumped over in
a wheelchair struggling to breathe.
 &HT;    They say that those who are about to die think about the
strangest things. For 12 hours, Streep thought about her shoes. She
figured death could be not proud. But why did it have to be so
unfashionable?
 &HT;    As a woman whose body is in the final stage of cancer, she had
to stand in dark brown slippery flats and inch her way toward her
character's version of heaven on earth: a Christmas tree in the
center of town filled with family and friends.
 &HT;    Getting there wasn't easy. Streep stood and wobbled. Extras
gasped because her pain looked real. When her knees buckled,
William Hurt, who plays her husband, involuntarily grabbed one arm
and lifted her into his arms.
 &HT;    Suddenly, Streep's entire body pitched forward like her bones
were turning to dust.
 &HT;    Renee Zellweger, who plays her daughter, couldn't take it
anymore, weeping uncontrollably. Those were unscripted tears. ``It
ruined me. Twenty times in a row, I just lost it,'' Zellweger says.
 &HT;    How good is Streep? The memories of watching her work makes
Zellweger tear up 12 months later in a Chicago hotel room.
 &HT;    For her part, the vibrant Streep vaults her body into a couch
and looks feisty during an interview when she starts whooping,
``suckers!''
 &HT;    This is what really motivated her: ``In my mind I was inching
toward that Christmas tree thinking, `Don't fall down.' I had these
extraordinary slippery shoes on. These horrible flats that didn't
have any grooves on the bottom. It was treacherous! The snow would
melt and re-freeze turning it into a solid block of ice.''
 &HT;    Of course, there were deeper, sad emotions in a cancer movie.
Streep's face turns angelic. The setting sun frames the beautiful,
regal 49-year-old when she says, ``This movie was not hard to act.
There are a lot of things that are hard to act.''
 &HT;    In ``One True Thing,'' Streep plays Kate, the perfect wife and
mother who spends her days cooking, sewing and throwing her husband
surprise parties much to the eye rolling, take-it-for-granted
attitude of her children.
 &HT;    Suddenly, she gets cancer. The bake sale is postponed. And
Zellweger, a self-absorbed New York City magazine writer, must move
home to pick up the pieces.
 &HT;    ``I fell in love with the book. I think this book got it right
about the confrontation between two generations of women,'' Streep
says. ``It's about stay-at-home mothers who didn't exploit any of
their larger ambitions. Of course, their daughters think they
wasted their lives. Their daughters don't see the invisible
contributions.''
 &HT;    Some might not see the invisible thread that connects Streep's
real life to her reel life.
 &HT;    But it's there. And the connection made her extremely sad. ``You
know what makes me sad?'' she says. ``Why is it that only in the
most extreme circumstances do you get down to saying what you need
to say to someone you love?
 &HT;    ``Why does someone have to be sick before they think about the
worth of their life and what they want to leave behind? I think
these are gorgeous thoughts to have on a daily basis,'' Streep
says.
 &HT;    A moment passes and when you think Streep will change the
subject she continues. ``For me, his (Cazale's) death has always
been something so private. I think making this movie is my way to
talk about it.
 &HT;    ``It's hard for me to talk about this in any context except with
people who were there and knew about it,'' Streep says. ``Talking
about it makes it smaller, and it had so much significance in my
life. It helped me focus on what to do with the rest of my life and
how to be in my life.''
 &HT;    Which brings her back to ``One True Thing.''
 &HT;    ``I just hope that people won't be afraid of seeing this movie.
I hope they don't think it's too sad. To those people, I want to
say, `Life is sad. Sometimes the sadness is what counts. It's what
makes you understand the whole thing,'' she says.
 &HT;    Streep also understands how to have a life.
 &HT;    Is she a different mother than her mother?
 &HT;    ``I finally gave up trying to be everything to all people after
about the third child,'' the mom of four says. ``I realized I just
couldn't make every deadline the way my mother had.''
 &HT;    The Oscar-winning actress notes that she could work more.
 &HT;    ``I just don't do as many movies as other people. It's my
choice,'' she says. ``I make all the decisions based on my
family.''
 &HT;    As a mom, she can be, well, motherly. ``I nag the kids to read.
I'm the one who says, `You don't know how lucky you are to have all
these opportunities afforded you.' But kids don't hear it. They
just live their life and basically they just want to watch TV.''
She pauses. ``Of course, I don't let them watch that much TV.''
 &HT;    When she's working, Streep's husband Donald Gummer, a sculptor,
takes over. Ask her the secret of her long-lasting marriage.
``Love. We know life is about change,'' she offers.
 &HT;    With ``One True Thing'' done, she is about to get back to work.
First, Streep stars in another fall film, ``Dancing at Lughnasa,''
already getting critical raves. She is also training to play a
violin teacher in Harlem in ``Fifty Violins,'' a role she got when
Madonna dropped out.
 &HT;    Clearly, she doesn't lack for work, unlike struggling peers.
And, Streep can't help but notice the trend of much younger
actresses co-starring with actors Streep's age and older.
 &HT;    ``I read Sharon Stone say that she is too old to play opposite
Mel Gibson, and she's 10 years younger than him. That makes me mad.
I don't know why people are perceived as done at a certain age,''
she says.
 &HT;    She tells a story about her hit film ``The Bridges of Madison
County'' which garnered Streep a Best Actress nomination. ``You've
got Clint Eastwood. He's 65. He's playing a 50-year-old man. I'm
playing a 45-year-old woman. I was 45 at the time. But the studio
said I was too old for the part.''
 &HT;    ``Clint finally had to say, `OK, I'll direct this movie, so I
can have the person who I want in the part.''' She groans. ``The
perception is that we're contemporaries, and Clint is 20 years
older than I am. It's very bizarre.''
 &HT;    And too complicated to talk about, since her children are about
to arrive from the mall.
 &HT;    Will she let her kids watch this movie? ``I think it would
really upset them to see their mom looking so ill.''
 &HT;    However, she took her mother to a screening. ``She found it very
difficult to watch, but at the end, my mom said, `That was a
helluva good movie.'''
 &HT;     c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
