<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIZABETH-PENA-IN-RUS     09-04 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIZABETH-PENA-IN-RUSH-HOUR-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTING WAS IN THE GENES FOR ELIZABETH PENA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Elizabeth Pena in ``Rush Hour.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Acting was in the cards for Elizabeth Pena.
 &HT;    ``My father's an actor-director-playwright and, besides, I went
to see a play when I was 8 years old and I was blown away by the
woman starring in the play,'' the effusive Pena says. ``I got
goosebumps when the play ended, and I was sobbing.
 &HT;    ``My mother came over, going `Baby, what's the matter?' I said,
`I want to be an actor.' And that's how it all began.
 &HT;    ``My father secretly rejoiced in it, but my mother _ who
actually now works at the Latin American Theater Ensemble _ thought
that if you're an actor you're a loser who will be insecure, judged
and broke. She felt acting was not a career, but I told her that
I'd incorporate business on to the show, that I'd make money from
it.
 &HT;    ``I have and I do, and I've done nothing but act since I was
19.''
 &HT;    Pena's credits include such features as ``Lone Star'' (1996),
``Down and Out in Beverly Hills'' (1986), ``La Bamba'' (1987),
``Jacob's Ladder'' (1990) and ``Blue Steel'' (1990), the TV series
``Shannon's Deal'' and the cable TV movie ``The Second Civil War''
(1997). The Cuban-American actress returns to the big screen on
Sept. 18 in ``Rush Hour,'' an action-comedy with chopsocky
superstar Jackie Chan and funnyman Chris Tucker.
 &HT;    Chan stars as Inspector Lee, a Hong Kong cop who arrives in Los
Angeles to retrieve the Chinese Consul's kidnapped 11-year-old
daughter. Tucker plays James Carter, a reckless, self-centered
detective chosen for the make-work FBI assignment of distracting
Lee.
 &HT;    Pena is Tania Johnson, an LAPD explosives expert who finds
herself reluctantly helping Lee and Carter once they decide to
solve the case on their own. Of course, plenty of jokes, explosions
and Chan-style fights ensue.
 &HT;    ``I was interested in doing a Jackie Chan movie, and that was a
big attraction for me,'' says Pena, a petite woman who sports a
silky brown dress and short brown hair as she sits for an interview
in a suite at the Rihga Royal Hotel in Manhattan. ``With most of
your action heroes, you applaud, realize they've shot 250 people,
and then you're ready for them to shoot another one. That's a
little weird to me.
 &HT;    ``Jackie doesn't shoot a gun, and he actually doesn't want to
fight. To do an action movie that's Zen, that's a bonus.
 &HT;    ``I obviously didn't do the movie because Tania was the most
fascinating character I'd ever read in my life. I auditioned, got
the part, and after I got it, (director) Brett Ratner was open
enough to make some changes I needed.''
 &HT;    Pena, who turns 37 on Sept. 23, specifically requested that
Johnson not come across too girlish or too bitchy, as she'd been
depicted in the first script drafts. She wanted Johnson to hold her
own with Lee and Carter, and to carry and fire a gun.
 &HT;    ``I also wanted Chris to have to come to me to help him out,
which wasn't in the script,'' Pena says. ``When they did write it,
it was a phone conversation and I was off-camera.
 &HT;    ``I said, `This is the only opportunity to see Tania not at her
job, but in her house, hanging out, and to see that she's a female
who has a life.' I didn't want more dialogue: I just wanted Brett
to shoot my side of the conversation.
 &HT;    ``Brett was very cool, and he did it for me. So, add that to
getting a kick out of working with Jackie and Chris, and I was a
very happy camper on this film.''
 &HT;    Following ``Rush Hour,'' Pena rushed into two independent
features, ``Strangeland'' and ``The Pass.'' The actress describes
``The Pass'' as a black comedy road movie that allowed her for the
first time to portray a truly dark and mean-spirited woman.
 &HT;    ``Strangeland'' sounds, well, strange. It's a horror movie
that's the brainchild of Dee Snider, former lead singer of the rock
group Twisted Sister.
 &HT;    ``It's about Dee's character, who's into body piercing and
tattooing,'' Pena says. ``I'm not talking about a little nose ring,
but bones in your head.
 &HT;    ``Dee lures teen-agers into his house by using the Internet.
Basically, he keeps them captive and does all sorts of stuff to
them, but doesn't kill them.
 &HT;    ``What I liked in shooting it was that it wasn't gross. The
camera was not focused on the guy doing some horrible thing. The
horror comes from you watching the nail that's going to go into the
head or the reaction of the person observing something.''
 &HT;    Pena and Kevin Gage play a couple on the verge of divorce whose
daughter falls prey to Snider. And, to put it mildly, Pena's
character doesn't take it very well.
 &HT;    ``You don't know how a picture will be put together, but the way
we were making it was that somewhere in the middle you're suddenly
not sure who's the good guy and who's the bad guy,'' Pena says. ``I
know it sounds like a sick movie, but if they put out the film we
tried to make, it could be very exciting, very scary.''
 &HT;    To date, Pena counts ``Lone Star,'' ``Jacob's Ladder,'' ``Down
and Out in Beverly Hills'' and ``La Bamba'' as her best films.
``Lone Star,'' John Sayles' acclaimed multicharacter drama about
the denizens of a small Texas town haunted by past sins, remains
the actress's personal favorite credit.
 &HT;    ``It was a joy to actually have words you could speak, and the
words were beautiful,'' says Pena, who played a proud teacher.
``John's a wonderful director and it was a wonderful experience.
 &HT;    ``When it came out, I'd started shooting `The Second Civil War'
for Showtime and I found out I was pregnant. So, I decided to go
away for a year.
 &HT;    ``I ended up not riding the wave (of box-office and critical
popularity) for `Lone Star.' But the way I figure it, I'm going to
be in this business until they bring me in, I'm drooling, they give
me a cracker, show me a cue card and I go, `Uuuhhh, I can do this.'
 &HT;    ``So, I may have another break.''
 &HT;    Pena, who lives in Washington State with her husband, a
carpenter named Hans, and their 16-month-old daughter, doesn't know
what she'll do next. One offer on the table, though, intrigues her
tremendously.
 &HT;    ``I got the strangest proposition, which was to do a talk
show,'' she says, shaking her head in disbelief. ``I sat there and
went `What?' It's bizarre.
 &HT;    ``I said, `You're talking to me? You've seen my resume. Why in
the world would you want me to do a talk show?' They said, `Think
about it,' and I said, `There's nothing to think about. I don't
want to be Arsenio Hall. I like to act.'
 &HT;    ``Then I started to think about it. Maybe instead of being an
entertainment show, I could have people come in (as guests) and
read excerpts from books. I could introduce new artists.''
 &HT;    Pena laughs.
 &HT;    ``I proposed this to them, and everybody's yessing me,'' she
continues, obviously bemused. ``I don't know what it means, though,
because this is Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``If they let me do something different and interesting and they
pay me lots and lots of money, I might do it. I've been in this
business a long time, and I ain't rich yet.''
 &HT;    Pena may not yet be rich, but she's certainly respected by
filmmakers and audiences alike. Even her mother now approves of her
career choice.
 &HT;    ``About a year ago I went to a Cuban-Chinese restaurant in
Manhattan,'' she says. ``I'm sitting there about to open my
newspaper, I look up and I see a picture of me, autographed. But I
didn't sign it.
 &HT;    ``I go look at the picture, and the signature's in my mother's
handwriting. So, I think she's a little proud of me.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
