<HEADER>
A9213 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAQUILLE-O'NEAL-HAS-     09-04 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAQUILLE-O'NEAL-HAS-NEW-RAP-ALBUM-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQUILLE O'NEAL DRIBBLES TWO BALLS: BASKETBALL AND ENTERTAINING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Shaquille O'Neal 
 By BONNIE SIEGLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Shaquille O'Neal, the 7-foot-1-inch Los Angeles Lakers center,
was born to be a basketball player. The question now is can he play
basketball and be an entertainer?
 &HT;    It's an issue that comes up often in the seemingly overlapping
world of sports and music and acting. ``Ya know, I think all
basketball players want to be rappers and all rappers basketball
players,'' he says in a telephone interview, his 2-year-old
daughter in the background.
 &HT;    ``But few sports stars have been able to make the jump to
Hollywood while they were still playing good basketball,'' O'Neal
says. ``I know that's a risk for me because if I make that
crossover, I have to do it very well. If not, I get blown out of
the box.''
 &HT;    While he's been touring this summer to promote his new album,
``Respect,'' this particular day finds him playing with his
daughter. ``Oh baby, now baby,'' O'Neal says in a soft-spoken
admonishment to Taahirah, looking up at her gentle giant dad.
 &HT;    ``You have to be softer with little girls,'' O'Neal says.
``Little boys can handle a little roughness. Taahirah has no
time-outs _ ever! She's still young, so I think you teach by
example.''
 &HT;    Sure doesn't sound like a tough athlete who piles up points by
pounding the boards and proving he's an immovable object. And his
soft voice shows no signs of a hardboiled rapper setting out to
grab a piece of the rap action.
 &HT;    But the big man _ 310 pounds and 20 inch neck _ hit the road for
a 12-city tour for his fifth rap album. Released on his TWIsM (The
World Is Mine) Records through a joint venture with A&AMP;M Records,
the album debuts Sept. 15.
 &HT;    Whose respect is O'Neal after anyway?
 &HT;    ``Everyone and anyone,'' O'Neal says, looking forward to trading
dunks for smash cuts. ``I want people to see me not as some
Superbowl rapper/basketball player, but as a legitimate rapper.''
 &HT;    It seems gaining respect is important to this multi talented
performer, attempting to meld his sports and entertainment careers
that so many sports figures shoot for, but few attain.
 &HT;    O'Neal has already appeared in three movies: ``Blue Chips''
(1994), a basketball-set story starring Nick Nolte; ``Kazaam''
(1996), in which he played the rappin' genie springing from a
boombox; and ``Steel (1997), the second movie with O'Neal as lead,
playing an armor-clad crime fighter battling bad guys.
 &HT;    ``Kazaam'' pulled in a modest $18.9 million domestically, while
``Steel'' did even less. ``I don't try to come out and make
millions the opening day. Only a few people can do that,'' O'Neal
says.
 &HT;    ``I just want people to go and enjoy themselves. I just want to
have a good time making them and give people a good product _ that
doesn't always happen,'' he says, ``but it's not for lack of
trying.''
 &HT;    He's also put considerable efforts into rap. His first album was
1993's ``Shaq Diesel,'' which went Platinum with 861,000 copies
sold, and produced a hit single, ``I'm Outstanding.''
 &HT;    In 1994, he wrote his memoirs, ``Shaq Attack.'' Add to that his
Shaq Attaq clothing line, multi million dollar endorsements and
directing debut in Nickelodeon's ``Cousin Skeeter,'' and you wonder
why is respect so important to this 26-year-old?
 &HT;    ``Cause it is. I don't want to disrespect people so my rappin'
words are always friendly and clean. I don't want mothers saying to
their kids `What did he say?''' Admittedly, O'Neal says he is not
the world's best rapper, ``but I've got some of the best on my
album.''
 &HT;    ``Respect'' showcases DJ Quik, Lord Tariq and Peter Gunz as well
as Fat Joe and Big Pun. ``If I couldn't flow with them even a
little bit, they wouldn't rhyme with me and would let me know.''
 &HT;    ``The Way It's Going Down'' with Brandy and Monica, Backstreet
Boys and Usher is a really good track, ``for both dance floors and
jeeps,'' O'Neal says. ``Show Me,'' about a search for true love
combines two lost loves of O'Neal. ``An old love and new one with a
rather famous person _ they both went bust.''
 &HT;    Anyone we know? ``Yeh, but I'll never say who. I'm not looking
anymore _ I'm off the shelf,'' referring to his domesticity with
lady love and mother to his daughter. O'Neal declined to say
whether he is married or identify the woman.
 &HT;    For all his time spent on a basketball court _ ever since his
dad put a basketball into his hands _ O'Neal also spent hours as a
teen-ager working on musicians' moves.
 &HT;    ``I used to get in front of the mirror and mock my favorite
artists: UTFO, Heavy D, Run-DMC and LL Cool J. I'm sure people
think of me first as a basketball player and that's OK, but I don't
want people to remember me just for that,'' he says.
 &HT;    Now, O'Neal's show biz profile is going up. While the No. 34
Lakers star had 208 offensive rebounds last season with a field
goal percentage of .584, O'Neal's music, movies and TV shows have
been put full-court as well.
 &HT;    As the Laker's $120 million man, he was No. 5 on Forbes' 1995
list of top earning athletes. The four above him then were Michael
Jordan, Mike Tyson, Deion Sanders and Riddick Bowe.
 &HT;    His appeal as America's approachable, winning gentle giant has
bought him two homes, one in upscale Manhattan Beach, Calif., and a
condo on tony Wilshire Boulevard plus four cars.
 &HT;    ``I love cars,'' is all he can say. He also has a personal chef
and trainer. Isn't it tough cooking for someone O'Neal's size?
 &HT;    ``Naw, I eat the same thing almost everyday,'' he says. ``I have
an omelette in the morning, tuna or fish for lunch and chicken for
dinner.''
 &HT;    What about slushing down some of his endorsements such as Pepsi
and Taco Bell? ``Yeh, I drink Pepsi, and I occasionally stop for a
Taco Bell grandito.'' He doesn't believe in dieting.
 &HT;    Growing up in Newark, N.J., to Army dad, Philip Harrison, and
secretary mom Lucille, ``who always cooked for the whole team,''
O'Neal says he always wanted to play pro basketball.
 &HT;    ``But my next dream was a professional rapper. Some days I
wanted to be Dr. J, other days I wanted to be LL Cool J.''
 &HT;    He attended Louisiana State for one year before being drafted in
1992 by the Orlando Magic in the NBA draft. In 1996, he signed with
the Lakers as a free agent.
 &HT;    So it's O'Neal's world. Why doesn't he take time off?
 &HT;    ``I have all the leisure time I want,'' O'Neal says. ``I'm in
control of my schedule unless I'm playing ball or doing a film.''
 &HT;    In fact, he admits he's watched his favorite movie, ``The Fish
That Saved Pittsburgh'' (1979), too many times to count.
 &HT;    ``See, I'll sit down and watch a movie or listen to some of my
favorite music.'' On the other hand, he says he doesn't really sit
still for all that long.
 &HT;    ``My parents were real hard workers. I love both of them very
much.'' Hard work and determination formed O'Neal's values of
today. At 14, he was working at McDonald's on an Army base until he
got the job of baby sitter for his four siblings.
 &HT;    ``My parents taught me to work hard and make something of
myself. I've always worked hard. And they told me to follow my
dreams _ don't let anyone tell you that you can't accomplish
something _ because you can.''
 &HT;    And he wants to bring his philosophy to the public. ``I'm
working on a book now and would like to call it `Dreamful
Attraction.' I always had dreams when I was a boy _ mystical type
dreams where you tell yourself you can do anything if you apply
yourself.''
 &HT;    Not surprisingly, O'Neal dreams of NBA playoffs ``but also that
I will have a good life with my family. Almost all of my dreams
have come true, but I've worked really hard for that.''
 c.1998 Bonnie Siegler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Bonnie Siegler is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
