<SLUG> BC-SUE-COSTELLO-IN-COSTELLO-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUE COSTELLO, STAR OF NEW FOX SHOW, IS STILL A BOSTON GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Sue Costello and her dog in a scene from
`Costello' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    No matter how big a hit _ or nonhit _ the rookie FOX sitcom
``Costello'' becomes, it's a given that the show's bombastic star,
Sue Costello, isn't going to let the whole Hollywood thing go to
her head.
 &HT;    In fact, the way she tells it, she doesn't have to change a darn
thing. ``Remember Popeye?'' Costello says in that broad South
Boston accent. ``Me and him have the same philosophy: I am what I
am. That's why this show is perfect for me. I can just be myself
and be honest, and hopefully that's what viewers will want.
 &HT;    ``Sure, if the show is a bomb, then I guess it means people hate
me,'' she says. ``But there's no damn way I'm going to become a
different person, or some big Hollywood phony. Uh-uh, no sir.''
 &HT;    Working in Costello's favor is the fact her series, premiering
Sept. 8, is based largely on her own real life. On the show, she
plays Sue Murphy, a motor-mouthed 27-year-old bartender working in
the tough, working-class area of South Boston.
 &HT;    In real life, Costello grew up on the mean streets of South
Boston as part of a hard-working Irish-Catholic family, which is
also replicated on the show. One exception: On the TV version, Sue
Murphy's family _ belligerent parents Spud and Lottie (Dan Lauria,
Jenny O'Hara) and sluggish brother Jimmy (Chuck Walczak) _ spend
most of their time yelling at each other, albeit in a loving
fashion.
 &HT;    ``Even though the neighborhood and the family is very
dysfunctional,'' Costello says, ``you can see that I still respect
it and that's how I'm portraying it ... The family is a lot like my
own. The characters all have a little bit of every Southie I've
ever met.''
 &HT;    The blue-collar aspect of Costello's character is authentic.
Back in the old neighborhood, her mother was a laborer in the
maintenance department at the University of Boston, and her father
worked for the local carpenter's union.
 &HT;    As a kid, Costello says she felt ``different'' growing up,
primarily because she wanted to express her creative urges. Last
year, when she saw the Oscar-winning film ``Good Will Hunting,''
also set in South Boston, a lot of the old memories came back.
 &HT;    ``They did capture it,'' she says. ``He (Matt Damon) said in the
movie: `I didn't ask for this.' That made me cry, because it showed
the excruciating pain of being somebody who is creative in that
neighborhood.''
 &HT;    As a teen-ager, Costello was hell-bent on self-improvement and
enrolled in Salem State College. ``I went to night school, because
I didn't feel I was smart enough to go to day school,'' she shrugs.
``I was an English major, and I had to write a paper. So I gave the
paper to the English guy, and he asked me if I ever thought about
being a chef.''
 &HT;    Instead, Costello started taking acting classes: Her first role
was as a hooker in a college stage production. Soon after, she got
into stand-up comedy and found herself onstage at Caroline's, the
famous comedy club in New York.
 &HT;    It was around that same time that she began going to therapy in
order to discover more about herself (on ``Costello,'' her
character does the same thing, starting in the very first episode).
Therapy, she says, helped put her tough streetwise past into proper
perspective.
 &HT;    ``When I meet people,'' Costello says, ``still to this day _ and
this is after 10 years of serious, intensive help _ if I walk up to
somebody, a grown man, I say, `Hey, can I take him?' If I can take
him, I can hang around with him because then I won't be afraid. My
business manager? I figured, I can take him in a fight, I can hire
him.''
 &HT;    Costello moved to Los Angeles in 1994 and was subsequently cast
in roles on a movie remake of ``Spenser: For Hire'' and ABC's
police drama ``NYPD Blue.'' She also had parts on two pilots,
``Queens'' and ``Paulie Dodge,'' neither of which were picked up by
a network.
 &HT;    ``Those were pretty good shows and it was a great learning thing
for me, but they really didn't have anything to do with the way I
really am,'' she says.
 &HT;    The real payoff for Costello came with her very own show, which
meant she could finally just be herself. ``It's the best,'' she
beams. ``The absolute best.''
 &HT;    And like a good Southie native, one of the first things Costello
did after getting her own series was to go back home for a visit.
``One of the guys came out of the bar,'' she says laughing, ``and
he's like, `Sue, you told us you were going to be famous, but we
didn't think you really meant it!'''
 &HT;     c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada.) &LR;  - &QC;
