<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-SORRY-$ADV06-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEN BILL SAID TO HILLARY, WHO SAID TO BILL, WHO. . . 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vacation talk that Bill and Hillary Clinton must have shared
recently came into my empty head unbidden like a random, uninvited
vision of hanky-panky in the Oval Office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I cannot, of course, vouch for the authenticity of any voices
that creep into my cranium that way, but, on reflection, the
special drawl and angularity of the words seemed to have an eerily
convincing ring to them. Listen: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill: Now, dear. . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hillary: Stop right there, Mr. Perjurybreath. I'll tell you
when, if ever, you can call me dear again. How dear was I to you
when you were being serviced by Moonica? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: Monica. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: You call her what you want and I'll call her what I want. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: Yes, dea. . .uh. . .Hillary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: Now let's review the mess you've made. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: Could I please say somethin' first? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: No, Mr. Pinocchionose. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: (He looks at his watch and wonders why the phone doesn't
ring, but he simply sighs.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: (She sighs, too. Deeply. Then she stares at him. The look on
her face is one of disgust, tinged with puzzlement. For as long as
she's known this wonderful, fallible, smart, stupid man, she's
never been able to figure him out altogether. Now that she's got
him cornered and defensive and quiet, she thinks that maybe, just
maybe, if she stares at him long enough she'll be given some kind
of helpful revelation.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: (After 50 or 60 seconds, he coughs a little and clears his
throat. And he turns to stare out the window.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: Damn you, Bill Clinton! You look at me when I'm not talking
to you! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: (His eyes meet hers. He blinks a wounded blink.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: Now the fact of the matter is, Mr. Hotspringspants, you've
really gone and done it this time. You may have cooked your goose
as well as mine, to say nothing of the Democratic party's and the
whole institution of the presidency. You've lied to me. You've lied
to Chelsea. You've lied to Buddy. You've lied to Socks. You've lied
to the world. And _ AND, Mr. Cock and Bull _ you've lied to that
24-carat jerk Ken Starr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: I agree with you. He is a jerk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: Don't you try to change the subject, Mr. Didn't Inhale. You
and I aren't going to agree on a thing here today. Not one hoodooed
thing. I don't want anything in common with you here today. In
fact, for the rest of the day I'm dropping Clinton from my name.
You will call me Hillary Rodham today. I knew I kept that name for
some good reason. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: Now, let's don't be silly about this. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: Look who's talking about overreacting, Mr. Shuck and Jive.
One night I tell you I've got a headache and your reaction is to go
have a months-long affair with someone young enough to be your
waitress at McDonald's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: Are you hungry? I'm starved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: Is that all you think about? Food? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: You got that right, Mr. Subpoenahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B: Hillary Rodham, I did some wrong things. I hurt you. I been
bad. Bad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H: When you should have been building a bridge to the 21st
century, you were building one to a 21-year-old. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On it went until it faded out of my noggin. Except for one last
snippet in Hillary's voice: ``If they impeach you, can I still be
first lady?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
