<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACID-RAIN-$ADV06-HNS &LR;      09-04 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACID-RAIN-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKE PLACID STRUGGLES WITH DISQUIETING REPORTS ABOUT ACID RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Fran Betters still remembers the phone call
he got a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran fly-tier was sitting at his usual post, tying flies
in his store not far from Whiteface Ski Area, when the phone rang.
It was a worried customer from down south. He had just read a story
about acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   Fran, he asked, are there any fish left in the Adirondacks?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, fishing in certain parts of the Adirondacks has never
been better. On a recent drizzly day, Betters was busily tying
flies by the dozen as a steady stream of anglers wandered through
his shop. Outside under the overcast sky, several casters stood in
the Ausable River.
</P>
<P>
   Decades after the effects of acid rain were first spotted in the
Adirondacks, life is just about the same here. Sure, there are
occasional stupid questions, like the elderly woman who once asked
an atmospheric scientist: ``I remember seeing a lot of old barns
here. Did the acid rain destroy them all?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is no. Acid rain's effects are far more
subtle. While it hasn't had any apparent effect on tourism or old
barns, it's still there. Scientists say acid rain has helped kill
fish in more than 450 ponds and lakes and a number of rivers. It
also is credited with killing a number of red spruce trees at high
altitudes, where the acid burns away root hairs. It also ruins the
finish on automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just rain,'' shrugs 15-year-old Brian Corrow, manning the
counter at the A&AMP;W snack bar stand outside Lake Placid, which
hosted the Winter Olympics in 1932 and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But most residents are not so dismissive. Especially in the face
of a federal report released earlier this month, saying fish and
trees are still dying. Although pollution from the Midwest _ the
main factor behind acid rain _ has been reduced, the report says,
it's not enough to prevent the damage from getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   To people here, that makes acid rain one of the biggest problems
in the Adirondacks since the black fly.
</P>
<P>
   Acid rain is not only found in the Adirondacks. Scientists say
it has killed stunted trees in New Hampshire, damaged evergreens in
Colorado and helped deteriorate Civil War monuments at Gettysburg,
Pa. It begins in the Midwest, as coal-burning plants send sulfur,
nitrogen and particulates into the easterly winds. When the air
masses hit the mountains of the East, the air condenses and rain
forms. During that process the sulfur turns into acid, although
scientists don't fully understand how it happens.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Clean Air Act of 1990 helped lower the amount of
acid rain that is created. For instance, in 1980, electric plants
nationwide put out 18 million tons of emissions. In 1995, that
number was down to 11.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's a drizzly, foggy day in the Adirondacks. Acidic drizzle,
presumably, which is entering lakes, ponds and streams around the
mountains, is lowering the pH to a level in which many fish cannot
live. Some high-altitude ponds are so acid-heavy the water cannot
even support algae.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the acidic fog is wrapping its tendrils around the
tops of peaks, damaging the roots of red spruce trees, and, slowly,
killing them.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything about acid rain is clear, like the rich blue of
certain mountain lakes that signifies the complete loss of aquatic
life. It depends on which expert you talk to. And it depends where
you stop.
</P>
<P>
   Betters, the fly-tier, said he worries about acid rain but
hasn't seen its effect on the Ausable River, which is stocked by
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Betters has been fishing here for more than 35 years. He's done
a lot of research on acid rain, and notes how Adirondack lakes were
acidic to begin with, how a single volcanic eruption fills the air
with more sulfur than any single coal-burning plant. Even feeder
streams are still filled with young brook trout, a sign that life
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't affected the streams at all,'' Betters said. ``We've
got better streams up here than we did 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not every angler agrees with him. Wayne Failing, a rafting and
fishing guide from Lake Placid, said he is worried about acid rain
and other water quality problems, like heavy metals in lakes that
make eating certain fish dangerous. He also is familiar with the
lakes that don't have fish in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a guide, it's my job to find out which lakes are the least
impacted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming up here for 50 years,'' said Gary Caudle of
Rochester, N.Y., packing his family into his truck after a morning
on the Ausable. ``I've seen most wildlife coming back, but I'm not
seeing nearly the amount of fish I used to. They're stocking it a
lot more, but it's not like I was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, acid rain has been a political issue in Washington
and Albany. In the Adirondacks, most residents aren't privy to
legislative committee discussions and thick reports. They just know
what they see.
</P>
<P>
   C.V. ``Major'' Bowes, the owner of a lodge at Big Moose Lake, is
pretty sure acid rain made his daughter sick. But he can't prove
it.
</P>
<P>
   After one of his children complained of stomach cramps and
funny-tasting water, Bowes had his water tested. He found it
contained lead and copper. Apparently, the high acid content of
their water was dissolving the metal in their pipes. Now they treat
their drinking water with limestone to cut down the acid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been studied to death,'' he said of acid rain. ``The big
problem is getting someone to do something about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
