<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LAUNCHES INTERNET JOB-LISTING SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Backed by Richard Strauss' ``Thus Spake
Zarathustra'' on the sound system to underscore the importance of
the event, Mayor Willie Brown launched an Internet-based program
that has the potential to help millions of job-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``CalJobs,'' a job-opening and resume-listing system at
www.caljobs.ca.gov that was launched Thursday for the California
Employment Development Department and can match workers with job
openings in the San Francisco area and statewide by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   Users can log on and view job listings from private and public
organizations. Just the same, people seeking employees can post
their listings free of charge. The site does ask users to register,
giving their Social Security numbers and other personal data.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, the mayor said, is at the center of an expanding
job market in which CalJobs can be an extraordinarily useful tool.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several years in Northern California, expectations
are that there will be 25,000 more jobs than there are people to
fill them, Brown said. ``We believe that everyone who is
employment-ready is going to have an option of one or two jobs that
they can contest for,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is anywhere on the globe that prospect has
the potential of being a reality as is the case with those of us in
the San Francisco Bay area and particularly in San Francisco,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The Employment Development Department and its director, Ray
Remy, hosted the gathering at One Embarcadero Center's SkyDeck
Thursday to demonstrate the automated, easy-to-use labor exchange
system that lists jobs and resumes, using Internet technology to
share employment information.
</P>
<P>
   The site allows the public and agencies, including county
welfare departments, to access job information.
</P>
<P>
   Remy, who formerly headed the Los Angeles Area Chamber of
Commerce and was chief of staff for Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley,
said he had heard complaints about government and CalJobs answers
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business colleagues said, `Why the heck can't government
deliver a product to more people with greater efficiency and why
can't they use technology and why can't government be more
customer-service friendly?' My response is we can, we have and it's
called CalJobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Remy said that savings is built into the system, as it reduces
office visits, and that those savings can now be spent helping
people without computer hardware or skills or on additional
counseling. CalJobs also has the potential to assist people with
the transition from welfare to work, Remy said.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans for CalJobs to be presented in Spanish and the
state is working with the National Federation of the Blind to
assist visually-impaired people, Remy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It serves more people, it serves them better and it does not
cost anything, and we will be able to do it cheaper than we have
been doing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Achtenberg, senior vice president of the San Francisco
Chamber of Commerce, said employers support the new state system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
