<HEADER>
A9308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEALTH-PAST06-COX     09-04 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTH-PAST06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Which comes first, consumer blues or sluggish market
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Economists have a classic chicken-or-egg debate on which comes
first: consumer blues or a sluggish market.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, number-crunchers have indexed, charted and plotted
consumer confidence as an indicator of whether we're headed for
good times or hell in a hand basket. But the underlying
rule-of-thumb could have as easily come from Dear Abby as an
economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get too optimistic, you're vulnerable to
disappointment,'' said senior equity strategist Tim Hayes, who
studies the relationship of consumer confidence and stock market
trends at Ned Davis Research in Venice, Fla. ``We tend to go with
the flow until the market reaches an extreme, then it reverses.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer sentiment is important because consumer spending
accounts for two-thirds of the nation's economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   While it's tough to draw conclusions from history because of
wildly different economic and political factors, one thing's for
sure: ``There is a very high correlation between confidence and the
stock market,'' said Donald Ratajczak, director of the Economic
Forecasting Center of Georgia State University. ``When confidence
is high, as it is now, the decline can be absorbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence has soared in recent times, hitting a
29-year high in June. But financial and political unrest in the
United States and abroad has disenchanted consumers lately, putting
a dent in the confidence for two straight months.
</P>
<P>
   With the speculation that current market turmoil could be the
start of a bear market, monthly consumer confidence results will be
monitored like the daily drama of the Dow Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The main measures of consumer confidence are put out monthly by
the New York-based Conference Board and the University of Michigan.
Launched in 1967, the Conference Board has the longest-running
tally of consumer confidence, measured in an index based on a poll
of 5,000 U.S. households. The survey asks questions about consumer
attitudes and buying plans.
</P>
<P>
   Past bear markets that have stuck around for a while were
ushered in by a lapse in consumer confidence. Confidence hit rock
bottom at the end of 1974. Granted, there wasn't too much to be
upbeat about in the middle of that nasty decline, which kicked off
at the start of 1973 and coincided with other confidence bruisers
such as Watergate, an energy crisis and rampant inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current environment bears no resemblance to the 1970s,''
observes John Williams, managing director of Equity-South Advisors,
an Atlanta-based venture capital firm. ``One of the most important
factors then was that the Soviet Union was in full force, and there
was always potential for nuclear confrontation. That had a huge
impact on psychology of the United States, and the whole investment
front was colored by that.''
</P>
<P>
   If consumer confidence rides the ups and downs of market
conditions, it certainly is strapped to job security, a far greater
driver of sentiment than what's happening on Wall Street, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've weathered social shocks, political shocks and economic
shocks, and consumer confidence generally bounces back within a few
months,'' said Lynn Franco, associate director at the Conference
Board. ``Unless it really hits consumers in term of jobs, stock
market declines won't have a major impact on confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Equity-South's Williams isn't so sure: Dips in the stock
market are more likely to steer consumer confidence today because
of the larger pool of investors, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, markets reacted to changes in consumer confidence
because savings and consumption patterns would drive investors to
the industries where consumers were spending, Williams said. ``With
45 percent of the public allocating money to mutual funds, that
pattern is reversed. What was the cart is now the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
