</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTH-PSYCHO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The psychology of Baby Boomers
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Economists are wondering whether the stock market's recent
gyrations will lead to a significant decline in consumer spending.
As a baby boomer, allow me to make this prediction: No.
</P>
<P>
   If our parents were still the dominant force in the economy, I
would be worried about a collapse in consumer spending. Americans
born in the 1920s and 1930s tend to be conservative with their
money because they lived through the depression that followed the
1929 market crash. No matter how wealthy they grew in later years,
they never forgot the taste of those stale bread and ketchup
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   These early experiences shaped their attitudes about using
credit, hopping jobs and spending money. For the most part, they
became the coupon-clipping smart shoppers who paid off their
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   But their children were influenced by very different economic
forces. The 76 million baby boomers born between 1946 and 1964 grew
up in a much more affluent time. Born into families that were
growing richer and better educated, they developed an upbeat
outlook about money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the affluence of the 1960s wasn't the primary influence
on boomers' financial habits. In fact, it was the wild inflation of
the next decade that made them eager to borrow and spend freely.
</P>
<P>
   If you bought your first house in 1978, your parents might have
been worried about the inflated price and outrageous mortgage rate.
Yet, it turned out you were wise to buy because housing prices just
kept going higher. In Atlanta, the people who bought homes in
intown neighborhoods in the 1970s and 1980s made killings on them
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And if you bought Coca-Cola stock in 1981, your parents might
have scolded you for risking money in a dicey market. But if you
ignored their advice and hung on to your stock, you were right
again. Your shares soared in value.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson: spending is good. In the long run, asset
appreciation will make your purchases pay off.
</P>
<P>
   To increase their spending ability, boomers learned to embrace
debt and make it work for them. Every time they took out a
home-equity loan to expand their house, they ended up profiting
because of rising real estate values. Whenever they bought stock on
margin, they positioned themselves to reap gains in the great bull
market. When they hopped from one job to the next, they typically
ended up getting raises.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bulk of boomers are in the heavy-spending decade of the
life cycle. Economists say our spending peak is reached at 46, an
age when money is flying out the door for mortgage payments, cars,
teenagers' clothes, tuition, furnishings and vacations.
</P>
<P>
   This is very good news for the world. Why? Because the primary
economic problem today is overcapacity. Too many factories are
making too many cars, clothes, toys and other products. To keep the
global economy from falling into a depression, somebody has to keep
buying.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, now that's a job for my generation. Unlike our parents who
might take the recent turbulence in financial markets as a signal
to reduce spending, we are searching for bargains in the stock
market and good deals on bigger cars.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Federal Reserve Board pushes down interest rates,
we'll get home-equity loans to spruce up our houses. When 30-year
mortgage rates slip to 6 percent, we'll call the Realtor and start
shopping for a bigger place. And we'll continue working long hours
so we can keep spending.
</P>
<P>
   Our motto has always been, ``When the going gets tough, the
tough go shopping.'' Now the world can count on us to do what we do
best: spend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
