<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NIRELAND-HNS &LR;      09-04 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NIRELAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER PEACE MAY BE CLINTON'S GREATEST ACCOMPLISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ History may decide that peace in Northern Ireland was
primarily due to President Clinton and was his finest achievement.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it means that a lot of us called it wrong. When Clinton
first made friendly gestures to Sinn Fein, the political branch of
the terrorist Irish Republican Army, critics assumed the president
had embarked on another of his cynical maneuvers designed to
placate Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and the Irish-American
community _ and not much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as political analyst Brian O'Duffy of Belfast
University has said, it proved to be the start of a highly skillful
and subtle policy of bringing Sinn Fein into negotiations without
alienating Northern Ireland's Protestant majority.
</P>
<P>
   There were many dicey moments when the whole intricate structure
threatened to be blown away _ literally, by the bombs of the IRA
and Protestant paramilitary gangs. But last month when a small
breakaway IRA band, calling itself the ``real'' IRA, planted a bomb
that killed 28 people in the town of Omagh, the whole Ulster
population turned on the perpetrators in fury, and they were forced
to claim the attack had been an ``error.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a crucial moment of change. It meant that the Catholics
and Protestants alike had come to believe in a realistic prospect
for peace and dearly wanted it. Twenty-four hours before Clinton
arrived in Northern Ireland this week, Sinn Fein appointed one of
its top leaders to sit on the so-called decommissioning committee,
which was set up under the peace settlement to supervise the
disarming of paramilitaries including the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Sinn Fein had steadfastly rejected disarming until
British troops were withdrawn from Ulster. After Omagh, it could no
longer resist public pressure in favor of it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clinton wasn't alone in bringing about the historic
movement toward peace in a land where violence has been endemic for
centuries and even in its latest phase has gone on for nearly 30
years, causing more than 3,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the rapturous welcome that the crowds gave him demonstrated
their belief that his role in cajoling and twisting arms was vital
and decisive, as was that of his representative on the spot, former
Democratic Sen. George Mitchell of Maine. U.S. influence is
probably greater in Ireland, north and south, than anywhere on
earth and the two Americans used it for all it was worth. Clinton's
exceptional rapport with British Prime Minister Tony Blair also
played a big part.
</P>
<P>
   Without Clinton, the efforts to get a peace settlement would, at
best, have been one of those near-misses Ireland has experienced in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was all a happy accident. Maybe the president was a
cynic at the start who didn't really think his initiative would get
off the ground. But what counts are the results. So let the rest of
us admit once and for all that we were wrong and that Clinton got
it right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9321 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAIL-MEXICO-ART-R &LR;      09-04 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-MEXICO-ART-R </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY STAYS ON COURSE DESPITE CANCER, STORMS ON BAJA VOYAGE  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS WERE SENT THURSDAY TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Not a day went by that Monte Berget, beaten down by
radiation treatment and lying exhausted in the gray recliner,
didn't think of the catamaran docked in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Odysseus.
</P>
<P>
   His family had bought the white sailboat the summer of 1996 and
set a date of Aug. 5, 1997, to move from their Chandler, Ariz.,
home to San Diego. There, they would live on the boat and prepare
for the 2,500-mile journey _ south from San Diego around Baja
California to La Paz, Mexico, across the Sea of Cortes to Mazatlan
and back, ending in San Carlos, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just before Christmas, less than a year before they were
supposed to leave, came the news.
</P>
<P>
   Berget was diagnosed with a particularly aggressive form of
throat cancer, and the weeks in the gray recliner began.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mouth was all scarred and burned up,'' Berget said. ``I had
a hole burned through my shoulder. They come as close to killing
you as they can without killing you because that's what kills the
cancer. It's dark and you hurt and you're discouraged and
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Maureen, wavered briefly, she said. She feared her
husband would not survive. She didn't know if he would be strong
enough for the trip. At the very least, she decided, the family
could live on the boat and take short trips out of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   For Monte, he never thought about if he would go. He only
thought of when.
</P>
<P>
   Two things kept him going: his faith and looking ahead to the
boat trip. ``I said God didn't do this without a reason, and if you
don't believe that you'd be very bitter because I never smoked,''
he said. The boat trip was something he'd been aiming at for years,
a voyage that promised to be equal parts adventure and family
bonding.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-foot boat had replaced a small sailboat, sold a few years
earlier for the start-up capital for their business. Monte had
dreamed of another boat and sailing around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Other family members weren't so enthusiastic. So they
compromised. They'd take a shorter trip _ the 1997-98 school year _
and stay closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Monte came through the difficult surgery and radiation
treatment, and on the date they had planned to leave all along,
they headed to San Diego. They had three months to get the boat
ready.
</P>
<P>
   There was interior remodeling _ one cabin was being converted
into a bathroom for the girls and new windows and hatches were
needed, among other things. And they needed supplies _ 72 rolls of
paper towels, 700 cans of food, spare parts, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Dana, who turned 16 on the trip, and Lexi, who was 11, were
being home-schooled for the first time and missed their friends.
And they went from living in a large home to living in about 500
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The first three months weren't easy, Maureen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a standing joke that their mom was the toughest teacher
that they would ever imagine having,'' Monte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no joke,'' Dana added.
</P>
<P>
   The day the catamaran left San Diego was one of the best days of
Monte's life.
</P>
<P>
   And once the adventure moved into Mexico and the girls met other
``boat kids'' their own age, attitudes improved. Mazatlan was the
best, the girls said.
</P>
<P>
   Dana met up with her church youth group there, where they helped
with a vacation Bible school, painted churches and built benches,
and she showed them around Mazatlan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had everything in Mazatlan. They had a Dairy Queen,
Domino's, Baskin-Robbins, a mall,'' Dana said.
</P>
<P>
   The family made lots of friends, from the families who lived on
boats to the villagers who traded their fresh tortillas for school
supplies from the Bergets.
</P>
<P>
   Days were filled with studying, exploring islands, swimming,
fishing, stargazing and hanging out with friends. Life on the boat
was a slow-paced change from life in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Notable exceptions to the slow pace were two crossings made
during severe storms.
</P>
<P>
   The trip from La Paz to Mazatlan would mark the family's first
crossing. At about 250 miles, the trip would take about 48 hours.
They waited for a good weather window of 72 to 96 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people said (their crossing) was boring,'' said Lexi,
sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergets' trip was another story. The ``light and variable''
forecast, for both crossings, turned into heavy winds and heavier
seas. The family experienced winds of 35-45 mph with gusts up to 57
mph. Waves crested at 12 to 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The crossing turned them into a team, and though they were
scared, they all took care of the boat and each other. The girls
had to help stand watch through the night. They worried as they
shone flashlights on their dad who was hanging off the back of the
lurching boat to secure broken equipment. On the return trip,
Maureen made the girls wear their life jackets to bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us had been in seas like that. They never balked at
it,'' Maureen said. ``It's the middle of the night. It's not
convenient and we say, `Would you please come out and get wet and
cold for three hours?' We just all said a prayer when we anchored
and we were all together. We were all completely soaked and yucky
looking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were alive and the boat was floating,'' Monte added.
</P>
<P>
   Lexi and Dana downplayed their contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like something that comes along with it, the
responsibility of knowing you are going to have to do something
like that,'' Lexi said.
</P>
<P>
   The family took a few trips back to Arizona for follow-up
doctor's appointments and to check in on the business. They ate
turkey for Thanksgiving on the boat and decorated it for Christmas,
although they spent the actual Christmas holidays in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   They returned permanently in June. The Bergets plan to make
another trip, probably sometime after Dana finishes high school,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   The girls are back in public schools. They enjoy showing the
trip pictures to their old friends and keep in touch through e-mail
with their new friends around the world.
</P>
<P>
   For Maureen, slowing down drew her closer to her daughters, she
said. It's a good reason to say no more often now, spend time with
her family and admire the sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played games. We don't do that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Monte was grateful for the time. His cancer is in remission, but
he knows that his cancer has a higher-than-average rate of
recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're glad to be there and you're really glad to share that
with your family and you appreciate it more,'' he said. ``Some day,
we will be sitting down for Thanksgiving or Christmas dinner, and
it might be five years or 15 years from now, and they'll say, `That
was a really cool trip.' It was a great year.'' &QL; 
Kelly Ettenborough can be reached at kelly.ettenborough(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
