<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMWEST-EARNINGS-AZR &LR;      09-04 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-EARNINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAYS TAKING TOLL ON AMERICA WEST  
 (EDITORS: STORY CAN BE UPDATED WITH FRIDAY STOCK ACTIVITY) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Flight delays and cancellations, which America West
Airlines blames on labor struggles with mechanics, is taking its
toll on the company's profits.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Wall Street walloped the airline's stock Thursday
after the company announced it expected a shortfall in
third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   America West shares fell 5|, or 28 percent, to 14[ in extremely
heavy trading. Nearly 2.6 million shares changed hands, about seven
times its daily average. The stock, which was as high as 30 in July
but has gradually fallen during the market swoon, is now near its
52-week low of 123/16.
</P>
<P>
   William Franke, America West Holdings Corp. chairman, said in a
statement that he did not expect the company to reach the 61 cents
per share earnings that analysts had predicted for the third
quarter because of poor July and August performances by the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   American West's results could equal 40 cents per share, Franke
added, which would match earnings a year ago. Third-quarter results
will be announced next month.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Goodmanson, America West president and chief executive
officer, cited the labor troubles in explaining unsatisfactory
on-time performance for the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   America West's on-time arrival rate was 64.9 percent in July,
which was last among the top 10 airlines. The leader, Southwest
Airlines, had an 83.9 percent on-time arrival rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The protracted and difficult negotiations the airline has had
with the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, which represents
some 450 line mechanics, are negatively impacting the airline's
operating and financial results,'' Goodmanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters spokesman Patrick Lacefield said there is no organized
slowdown by America West mechanics, but mechanics are just doing
their jobs to ensure that aircraft are safe before being put back
into service.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with the airline's operations, Lacefield said, are
tied to its decision to outsource some maintenance to contractors
whose work often has to be corrected by America West mechanics,
leading to delays.
</P>
<P>
   Outsourcing was done to cut costs and it's not clear that it has
done that, Lacefield said. What it has done is raise questions
about whether the carrier is placing the movement of airplanes
above safety, he said, a charge the airline has denied in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The airline paid the largest fine in U.S. airline history, $2.5
million, in July after the Federal Aviation Administration
discovered safety violations. The FAA is continuing to monitor
America West.
</P>
<P>
   Lacefield said Thursday's announcement is a vindication for the
America West mechanics, but they don't want it stop there. They
want the company to bring the maintenance work back in-house, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   America West spokeswoman Patty Nowack said flight delays and
cancellations are hurting earnings because America West must shift
passengers onto other airlines and often has to provide meal
expenses and hotel stays.
</P>
<P>
   To address the operational problems, America West has added 100
mechanics and plans to hire 20 more. It also has increased its
overnight repair stations to 13 from four, boosted its spare parts
inventory and added two spare aircraft, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She would not comment on whether the mechanics were engaging in
a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between America West and the Teamsters are to begin
again next week, Lacefield said, and outsourcing is the key issue
for the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Buttrick, a Paine Webber analyst, said there is no question
in his mind that flight cancellations are maintenance related, but
it's unclear the exact source of the maintenance delays. Some may
be the result of mechanics working strictly by the book and some
may be due to a lack of parts or increased FAA scrutiny, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just disappointed that senior management didn't recognize
the extent of the problems earlier,'' Buttrick said.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the earning shortfall, analyst James Higgins of
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette pointed to the labor troubles and the
FAA oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is operational, related to slowdowns by
maintenance workers who are in contentious contract negotiations
with the company, plus a far more smothering presence of the
Federal Aviation Administration on the `property' than we had
understood,'' Higgins' report said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts are maintaining their buy rating for America
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lowered estimates to reflect what we know at this
point about the outlook, but confess little confidence over the
next couple of quarters,'' Higgins said in his report. ``Beyond
that, we feel more comfortable that, if the domestic economy
continues to grow modestly, this company will reassert what we
believe had been an improving earnings trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins noted that the current scenario is reminiscent of an
operations-related shortfall in 1996. &QL; 
Republic writer Dawn Gilbertson contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
