<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9331 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMF-Q&AMP;A-1STLD-WRITETH     09-04 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-Q&AMP;A-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IMF IS THE `9-1-1' CALL FOR NATIONS IN ECONOMIC TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)   (EDs: SUBS 12th graf to UPDATE with ruble exchange rate)  
 (EDs: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Russian economy melting down and global
markets and economies in crisis, political leaders trying to calm
the tumult are looking to the International Monetary Fund for help.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF _ the ``911'' call for nations in financial disarray _
has been a controversial player in the international efforts to
transform Russia from a lumbering centrally planned economy to an
agile western-style market economy. But despite $25.5 billion in
IMF loan commitments and billions more made by the World Bank and
the government of Japan, Russia's economy remains deeply troubled.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow isn't the only borrower at the IMF loan window these
days. Since the Asian economic crisis began last summer, the
organization has made $36.1 billion in loan commitments to South
Korea, Indonesia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Though it plays a crucial role in nursing global economic
health, D.C., the IMF is shrouded in secrecy that the organization
assiduously maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some questions and answers about the IMF:
</P>
<P>
   Q) What is the International Monetary Fund?
</P>
<P>
   A) The IMF opened for business in 1945 after 29 countries signed
a treaty to promote monetary cooperation among nations as a way of
encouraging world trade. The idea was that trade would increase if
it were easier to convert one nation's currency into another.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF was a direct response to the Great Depression of the
1930s when the world economy plummeted in part because nations
placed severe restrictions on the exchange of domestic and foreign
currencies. This made trade practically impossible. In fact,
trading became so cumbersome that some governments resorted to the
barter system, exchanging one cargo for another.
</P>
<P>
   Q) What does the IMF do?
</P>
<P>
   A) One of the IMF's main missions is helping member nations
suffering from payment imbalances, as Russia is now. This problem
crops up when a nation doesn't take in sufficient foreign currency
from exports, tourism and financial services to pay for what it
imports.
</P>
<P>
   When this happens, the country has to borrow money from banks to
make up the difference. If a country borrows too much and fails to
correct the causes of the imbalance, currency speculators such as
banks and international corporations may lose confidence in the
government's ability to correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Speculators may sell the nation's currency in an
effort to exchange it for more stable currencies, causing its value
to plunge. In Russia, the ruble declined in value from 16 cents in
June to around 5 cents last week.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the IMF loaned Russia $4.8 billion to restore investor
confidence by bolstering foreign currency reserves and closing a
budget deficit. However, President Boris Yeltsin's administration
apparently used most of the sum to prop up the ruble. This effort
failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have gone and wasted that money to buy up rubles of banks
that wanted to get rid of them, and the money has ended up out of
the country,'' said Charles Gaddy, a Russian economics expert at
the independent Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   IMF spokesman Vasuki Shastry says: ``Dollar for dollar, there's
no way we can account for what happens to the money when we give it
out to a member country. The money is fungible.''
</P>
<P>
   Q) Where does the IMF get its money?
</P>
<P>
   A) The IMF has 182 member nations, each of which contributes
funds that are loaned to nations in need. The amount of a nation's
contribution depends on the strength of its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the United States, with the world's richest economy, has
contributed the most to the IMF, about $36 billion, or 18.14
percent of the total in the IMF bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Marshall Islands in the Pacific make the smallest
contribution, $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF also asks member nations to make new contributions when
its reserves are low. For example, last December the IMF requested
new contributions because of its loans to slumping Asian nations
and Russia. The U.S. share came to $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the United States, other top donors to the IMF are
Germany, Japan, France and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Q) Do IMF members have equal status?
</P>
<P>
   A) No. Member nations have voting power in direct relationship
to the size of their financial contributions. Because it is the
biggest donor, the United States has the most votes and the biggest
clout within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Q) Who runs the IMF?
</P>
<P>
   A) The head of the IMF is Michel Camdessus, a French economist
and banker, who has held the post of managing director since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-member executive board appoints the managing director and
advises on which loans to make. The IMF, based four blocks from the
White House in Washington, has a staff of 2,600 from 110 countries
with offices in Paris, Geneva, Tokyo and the United Nations in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Q) What are typical terms of an IMF loan?
</P>
<P>
   A) The IMF imposes strict rules on borrowers: They must agree to
repay the money within a specified time and they must agree to
reform those economic policies that created the problem in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   The loans typically are disbursed in installments tied to
progress in making the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms can cause political instability. In Indonesia,
rioting broke out shortly after that nation adopted strict IMF
austerity measures last year. The unrest eventually toppled the
government.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Russia, the Yeltsin administration agreed to cut
government spending, an action that exacerbated the financial woes
of the average Russian because many government workers and
pensioners are not being paid.
</P>
<P>
   To ease financial hardships on the average Russian, the
legislature has suggested softening the austerity measures. Western
governments, meanwhile, are pushing for greater belt-tightening
with a formula of high interest rates, reduced government spending
and more taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Q) What sparked Russia's recent economic crisis?
</P>
<P>
   A) A political dispute over economic reforms between
reform-minded Yeltsin and reform-cautious legislators, coupled with
Russia's partial default on domestic debt, exploded last month in a
sweeping loss of investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the collapse of Russian financial markets, a
steep devaluation of the ruble and a spike in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Q) How is the IMF responding to Russia's problems?
</P>
<P>
   A) In 1995 and 1996, the IMF approved about $14.3 billion in
loans to Russia. The money was supposed to bolster Russia's foreign
reserves, help it ride out a balance of payments problems and
attract foreign investment by building investor confidence,
according to Shastry.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian economy is faltering and the IMF has become
Russia's lifeline. It is ``virtually the only source of major
external funding in sight,'' said Keith Bush, a Russian economics
expert at the non-partisan Center for Strategic and International
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The organization approved $11.2 billion in new loans in July,
$4.8 billion of which the Russian government already exhausted in a
failed effort to support the plummeting ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Russians want to use the next installment of IMF funds, $4.3
billion, to pay workers and pensioners and to pay down the
country's debt. The IMF hasn't yet agreed to release the sum,
pending a review of the country's economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF also has provided Russia with expertise for establishing
institutions and services essential for market-based economies such
as central banks, currency convertibility and tax collection
systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
