<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9336 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAIRIE-DOGS-AZR &LR;      09-04 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAIRIE-DOGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK OF THE TOWN: PRAIRIE DOGS HAVE SOMETHING TO SAY  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN VAN DER WERF  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. - It is a sight that has delighted millions:
prairie dogs perched on their hind legs, their forepaws hanging
limp against their coarse fur, peering off into the distance, then
letting out a sharp bark and disappearing into their burrows.
</P>
<P>
   Another adorable sight to most humans, another bark in the
inscrutable background noise of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Con Slobodchikoff, a biology professor at Northern Arizona
University, hears much more.
</P>
<P>
   After listening for 12 years, and recording these sounds for
constant replaying, Slobodchikoff thinks he has deciphered a
language in this chaotic chatter.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks these prairie dogs are ``talking'' with a lexicon that
has the equivalent of nouns, verbs and adjectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have different wordlike sounds for every species of
predator,'' Slobodchikoff said. ``In the lab, we have identified
the `word' for ferret, and also for great horned owl. We had
figured out the call for red-tailed hawk, human, coyote and
domestic dog. This summer, it looks like we will identify `words'
for a cat, a deer and an elk.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitch, volume, and frequency are plotted on sonograms. For
example, a hawk is a single note, a yip, at a high frequency.
Different predators also result in different behavior by the
prairie dogs. Coyotes and domestic dogs result in multiple calls
from several prairie dogs. With humans, usually only one prairie
dog at a time will call.
</P>
<P>
   To test his theories, Slobodchikoff has humans walk through the
prairie dog town wearing different colors of clothing, acting
threatening or peaceably, running or walking. Stationed in an
above-ground blind in the middle of the community, the researchers
have been lucky enough to record the sounds when a predator passed
by. Otherwise, they have fashioned cardboard cutouts of predators
and rolled them around.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow researcher, Kathy Frederickson, a doctoral candidate at
the University of Nebraska at Omaha, had a friend go out one day
and fire a shotgun blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he ever came out again and he was wearing the same
clothing, they would give out two or three calls, and they were
gone, and they would stay underground for hours,'' she said. ``They
remembered this guy months later.''
</P>
<P>
   Vervet monkeys of East Africa were the first species documented
to have distinct aural descriptions of predators. They are known to
make different sounds depending on whether the predator is an eagle
or other bird, a leopard or a snake.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have been left to scratch their heads over other
animal sounds. The well-known mournful baritone of whales, for
example, could mean anything from ``I miss my Mommy'' to ``Good
krill ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   What has made the prairie dog experiment unique is that
Slobodchikoff has been able to identify that the animals are
``speaking'' about predators and nothing else. Prairie dogs also
partake in ``social chatter,'' but that is not part of the
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out in the field, we can associate the calls with whatever
predators are out there, so that is like a Rosetta stone for us,''
Slobodchikoff said.
</P>
<P>
   That it is the prairie dog that is the center of this research
seems like some kind of cosmic justice.
</P>
<P>
   The prairie dog is arguably the most hated animal in North
America. It has been shot, drowned, and poisoned nearly into
oblivion, losing 98 percent of its former range.
</P>
<P>
   To many ranchers, prairie dogs are varmints with no reason to
live. They tear up the grasslands and cattle are known to break
their legs when they step into prairie dog burrows.
</P>
<P>
   After numbering 5 billion in North America, two of the five
species, the Mexican and Utah, are listed as either endangered or
threatened. Another species, the black-tailed, has been proposed
for listing.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodchikoff, who works with another species, Gunnison's
prairie dog, hopes that his research will help the prairie dog, and
other animals, get more respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really pushing the envelope of what we thought animals
could do,'' he said. ``If these animals have this ability to
communicate, other animals probably have it, too. If that is true,
it raises an ethical issue about how animals are treated. It might
force us to reassess the way we treat animals, like they are little
robots that you can get rid of like a pile of leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Caplan, director of the University of Pennsylvania Center
for Bioethics, said, ``The Catch-22 of animal research is the more
research we do about animals, the more we find that they are
similar rather than unlike us. The more the gap closes, as science
shows that there isn't much of a gap, the harder it gets for us to
feel as though we can treat nature as our dominion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know now that pigs are smarter than we thought. It's made
some people vegetarians, but not a lot. I still eat meat. I don't
consider them (cows and pigs) my moral equivalent. I don't think if
it was between a prairie dog and a human being that I would flip a
coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Slobodchikoff has heard a lot of criticism, but says, ``I just
say to people I am not denying that we are special. Look at what
we've done with our world.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he is not arguing that a school of fish could
build the Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   There are other larger issues to tackle, such as the possibility
of becoming the real Dr. Dolittle.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodchikoff has begun working with John Placer, an NAU
computer-science professor in an attempt to assign probabilities
for what sounds might mean and then establish patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible domestic animals have some kind of
communication with one another,'' Slobodchikoff said. ``Down the
line, we might be able to decode that language, and maybe through
computers, actually allow people to have a conversation with their
pets.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a long way from the fidgety rodent squeezed into the
corner of a burlap bag being held tightly by Sarah Long, who
recently received a master's degree in biology from NAU.
</P>
<P>
   The prairie dog was about to get a number and letter painted
onto its sides with indelible dye, and was barking a flurry of
high-pitched yelps.
</P>
<P>
   What's he saying? she's asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Long answered. ``Probably something
unprintable.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martin Van Der Werf can be reached at martin.vanderwerf(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
