<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT ALL-AMERICAN SHADOW HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the bulging Mark McGwire is Casey at the Bat, Sammy Sosa
is Chico Escuela. Escuela, the fictitious baseball player created
on Saturday Night Live by Garrett Morris, was famous in mock
interviews for saying, ``Beisbol been berry, berry good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   All season Sosa has played a powerful yet deftly deferential
tenor to Mark McGwire's bass. McGwire is on the verge of breaking
Roger Maris's record of 61 home runs. Sosa, just behind McGwire, is
also on pace to surpass the hallowed, 37-year-old record.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Sosa who was once a shoeshine boy in the Dominican
Republic, has expanded his thanks from his sport to America itself.
When asked in general about Maris's record, Sosa has said: ``I
didn't have it in my mind to break the record. But if it happens,
God bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the possibility of getting the record first, he
said, ``If I get it first, God bless America. It's a beautiful
country.'' When asked if McGwire reached the record first, Sosa
said, ``I still love America.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about being swamped with media requests, Sosa said:
``I'm just having fun. I'm ready to take care of people. That's why
I love America. It's a beautiful country.''
</P>
<P>
   All along, the 29-year-old Sosa has said he wants the
34-year-old McGwire break the record first. ``Mark McGwire is the
man,'' he has said what seems to be a thousand times. ``I'm just
another kid.''
</P>
<P>
   This humility may mask a mind worthy of a doctorate in American
sociology. The last time a dark-skinned man threatened to replace a
white icon in the home run books was when Hank Aaron supplanted
Babe Ruth as the all-time home run king.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, as Aaron closed in on Ruth's 714 home runs, he received
enough hate mail and death threats to require federal protection
for his daughter and make him a prisoner in his hotel room on road
trips. Aaron should have been the stuff of American rags-to-glory;
he came from a family where his mother could not afford a baseball
bat.
</P>
<P>
   But Aaron's intelligence and serious critiques of racism in
baseball made him a target rather than an icon. Aaron broke Ruth's
record in 1974 and finished his career with 755 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very sad time,'' Aaron has said. ``I don't think
about it much because of all the things I had to go through. My
kids had to suffer.... That period left some very bad and deep
scars on me.... It was pure racism.''
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century later, another black man is challenging the
white icons. The way Sosa is dealing with it, it is as if he knows,
instinctively or otherwise, that America remains a delicate place
for a dark athlete, a place where the grinning of Willie Mays and
Magic Johnson, the neutered politics of a Michael Jordan, even the
tattoos of Dennis Rodman are preferred to the insights and candor
of an Aaron or a Jim Brown.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if he knows it is critical to issue consistent
concession speeches to an America that needs to view white athletes
as men and black athletes as kids. A good example: The majority of
professional basketball and football players are African-American,
yet the players who are seen as mature enough to be groomed for
coaching and management are overwhelmingly white.
</P>
<P>
   Surely America has matured enough not to visit a black athlete
with the hell it rained down on Aaron. Aaron, now in his mid 60s
and an executive in Atlanta, said three years ago, ``This is a new
generation of people, and I think I've been appreciated more by
this generation than I was by the generation before.''
</P>
<P>
   The next few weeks will reveal how much a new generation
appreciates dark athletes as well as how it receives the increasing
numbers of foreign-born athletes who excel on US soil. At this
moment, old distinctions punctuate the air.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was flatly proclaimed an ``American hero,'' by columnist
Randy Harvey of the Los Angeles Times. He was called an
``all-American hero'' by anchor Jane Robelot of ``CBS This
Morning.'' The Denver Post called McGwire ``the great American
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, despite his bowed posture at the Statue of Liberty, has
not been so received. A computer search of major national
newspapers found no stories in which he was been called an
``American'' hero even though he is ahead of Maris's pace. The
closest he has come to icon status in newspapers is an open
question from Jon Heyman of Newsday. In a column that quoted
several people who wondered why Sosa's story is not yet seen in
colors of red, white, and blue, Heyman asked:
</P>
<P>
   ``If this guy isn't a true American hero, then who is?''
</P>
<P>
   Until America answers the question, Sosa must play the game by
the current rules. Mark is the man. Sosa is the kid. Sosa has
recognized that America has not yet grown up. For all the times
Sosa has said ``God bless America,'' he understands that the best
chance for a black athlete to be blessed by America is to find a
way to accept being called ``boy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
