<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ROSS-BOS &LR;      09-04 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ROSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI MAY HAVE NO RIVAL LIKE A DEPUTY SPURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Betsy McCaughey Ross _ who holds an unusual dual role
as both the Republican lieutenant governor and the front-running
Democratic candidate for governor _ has been having a bad summer.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 18, her boss, the current governor, George W. Pataki,
cut off her Associated Press news-wire service. This, after taking
away most of her other state perks.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, her deputy campaign manager quit _ the fourth
senior campaign staffer to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, while unveiling her six-point health-reform
proposal at a Manhattan senior citizens' center _ billed in advance
as a major policy address _ the center's director walked in,
exclaimed, ``Nobody told me there would be all these cameras,'' and
kicked them out.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Thursday, she announced she would have little money for
TV ads in these last two weeks before the primary, because her
husband _ multimillionaire Wilbur Ross, who has almost
singlehandedly financed her campaign _ is tightening his purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey (pronounced McCoy) Ross _ 49, a Ph.D., and a former
fellow at the conservative Manhattan Institute think-tank _ has
been derided by pols and the local press for running a sloppy
organization, for switching parties, even for being an attractive
blonde. (A Village Voice headline last month called her the ``wonk
with a wiggle.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she is widely seen as having the best chance of
winning the four-way Democratic primary Sept. 15, and thus going
toe-to-toe with Pataki, the man who fathered her political career.
All told, it is shaping up to be the strangest New York governor's
race in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki tapped her as his running mate in 1994, mainly because he
needed a woman to lure female voters _ and because she had recently
written a much-lauded critique of President Clinton's health-reform
plan in The New Republic magazine.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted, in an interview late last month, that she probably
would not have entered politics had Pataki not approached her. ``I
was writing a book about constitutional law _ that's my field _ and
I was very happy doing it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Once tapped, she made the mistake of taking her post seriously.
She recalls the night Pataki's aides asked her to be his running
mate. At the end of the chat, she said, ``I'm going to take my
laptop home and write my acceptance speech.'' One of the aides
said, ``We'll write the speech.'' She said, ``No, I'll write it.''
She finally prevailed, but, looking back, she said, ``That was the
time for them to decide they didn't want an independent-minded
person.''
</P>
<P>
   In office, she kept writing policy memos to Pataki, and grew
more frustrated when he kept ignoring them. The bigger the fuss she
kicked up, the more Pataki's aides leaked word to the press that
she was ``unstable,'' a ``ditz.'' It did not help when her own
staffers deserted her in droves, saying she was ``impossible to
work for,'' calling them at all hours, ``screaming and screeching''
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, she quit the Republican Party, joined the
Democrats, and announced her candidacy as governor.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross said the idea came to her six months earlier,
when she brought a bill to the state senate, requiring HMOs to pay
for any care a doctor says is needed. ``Every single Republican
voted against it, every Democrat voted for it,'' she recalled.
``When I walked out of the chamber, I knew I was going to change
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   She has since lambasted Pataki in ever-more-caustic terms and
labeled herself a ``progressive liberal,'' which some of her former
think-tank colleagues find at odds with her previous stances,
though she insists she hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York needs a serious problem-solver, an expert,'' she says
in her stump speeches. ``I'm not a career politician. I'm a mother,
a health-care expert, an educator.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic consultant (who is working for no
candidates in this race), thinks she has the correct line. ``She
has the advantage in a Democratic primary being the only woman in
the race, but she also needs to focus on gender issues that make
women come out and vote for her,'' he said. HMOs and education are
such issues.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``she has to get this word out in the media''
_ which she has not yet done and, it seems from Thursday's
announcement, may not do.
</P>
<P>
   The point may be moot. Pollster John Zobgy has Pataki winning
about two-thirds of the vote in November's general election, no
matter which Democrat runs against him.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby's poll shows McCaughey Ross leading her opponents in the
primary with 24 percent of the vote, against 14 percent for the
runner-up, Peter Vallone, speaker of the New York City Council, and
single digits for the other two candidates, Brooklyn district
attorney Charles Hynes and former state transportation commissioner
James Larocca.
</P>
<P>
   But half the Democrats polled are undecided. ``There's
terrifically low interest in this election,'' Zogby said. Without a
decisive media campaign, any fires lit between now and Sept. 15
won't be ignited by McCaughey Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $2.6 million she has raised in this campaign, over $2
million comes from her husband, the senior managing director of the
Rothschild finance firm. Village Voice columnist Wayne Barrett
reports nearly all the rest has come from Ross's business
associates. None of this money can be spent without the personal
approval of Ross _ ``suggesting,'' Barrett chides, ``just how
foolish Wilbur thinks voters would be to trust Betsy with the $71.5
billion-a-year checkbook controlled by a governor.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross chafes at this suggestion. ``I studied accounting
at Columbia, I was a bank officer at Chase Manhattan at age 24, I
know finance in and out,'' she said tersely in an interview after a
recent candidates' debate. ``Put me in a room with these three guys
to talk about finance,'' referring to her primary opponents, ``and
I'll rub them in the dirt... I am not a hack. I'm a serious
scholar. I won the National Magazine Award, I got a post-doc from
the (National Endowment for the Humanities). I take ideas
seriously. I do my homework.''
</P>
<P>
   That, to some of her newly fellow Democrats, may be part of the
problem _ she's too much the academic, not enough the politician.
She practically says so herself. Asked why she hasn't raised much
money outside her husband's pockets, she shrugged and laughed,
``I'm a policy wonk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
