<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBIDDING-JOB-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN MANAGER THRIVES ON DOUBLE DUTY IN MAINE COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; VINALHAVEN, Maine _ On her first visit to her new lighthouse
home after being named Vinalhaven's town manager, Susan Lessard
brought her mother and grandmother to see the place.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chilly November day in 1993, and nothing seemed to work
properly _ not the heat, not the odd cistern-well water system, not
even the telephone. On remote Brown's Head _ a rocky promontory on
a largely uninhabited stretch of Vinalhaven island _ the three
women seemed a long way from help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were you, I'd call your former boss in Fayette and ask
for your old job back,'' her mother advised.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard said she intended to stay in Vinalhaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that case,'' her mother said, ``the first thing you need to
do is find a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Lessard _ divorced since 1987 and still
single, by choice _ is thriving here.
</P>
<P>
   She claims to be the only town manager in the country whose job
requires that she live in a lighthouse. She's an islandkeeper _
tending not only the light but to the needs of Vinalhaven's 1,300
year-round residents.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, male or female, would find the job forbidding.
</P>
<P>
   The wind howls over Penobscot Bay so ferociously that her home _
a three-bedroom Cape attached to the lighthouse _ has to be bolted
to the rocks beneath to keep it from blowing away. Getting to the
town office in winter often means spending an hour chiseling ice
off the 32 treacherous steps on the steep incline from her driveway
to the house.
</P>
<P>
   And managing the needs of this fishbowl of a community _ a small
island town 15 miles from the mainland _ is all-the-more daunting
because, as Lessard observes, when the last ferry for the mainland
leaves at 4:30 p.m. in summer (3:15 in winter), ``no one can go
anywhere else to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   With her 6-foot frame and huge shock of long, curly red hair,
Lessard isn't intimidated by much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in not having `can't' in your vocabulary,'' said
Lessard, who came to Vinalhaven from a town manager job in Fayette,
Maine, near Augusta. ``I never found anything I couldn't do or
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an approach that serves her well in this hard-working
community, where lobster boats, bait shacks, and fuel docks line
the harbor. More than 75 percent of the population is
self-employed, mainly in the lobster industry, and locals pride
themselves on finding unpretentious ways to get by.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lessard, many folks work two or more jobs. The gourmet chef
and owner of the only year-round restaurant serves as safety
officer in the fire department. A local producer of Broadway plays
works at a fish-processing plant. Many lobstermen also care for
somebody's landholdings. And employees of the local grocery store
double as quasi-bank tellers, cashing islanders' checks after
banking hours.
</P>
<P>
   In Lessard's case, her two-fer job _ tending the lighthouse and
managing the town _ was Vinalhaven's innovative answer to the
problem of how to keep down the manager's salary and also make sure
that the Brown's Head Lighthouse, automated by the Coast Guard in
1987, would be well-maintained and accessible to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard still is responsible for operation of the light
and the tower. But Lessard lives in the lighthouse year-round,
maintaining the building and grounds, which includes 6 acres of
mossy forest, a rocky beach, and a picnic area. Her job includes
mowing the grass, whacking weeds, landscaping, and picking up
debris that washes onto the beach.
</P>
<P>
   In other communities, town managers might shun this sort of
manual labor. But it is vintage Lessard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's hands-on,'' says Bodine Ames, town janitor, who also is
a case worker for the local social service agency. ``When the
surplus food truck arrives, she's the first one there to help
unload it. And the road crew loves her; when she wants to talk
about their problems, she takes them homemade muffins.''
</P>
<P>
   The let's-all-pitch-in approach seems tailormade for Vinalhaven.
Locals joke that the island is ``15 miles and 40 years'' from the
mainland. Not that they're uninterested in the Internet, which is a
popular diversion, but islanders say they identify more with the
values and simplicity of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining Vinalhaven's appeal, Edward ``Pumpkin'' York, who
manages bait for the Vinalhaven Lobster Co., puts it this way: ``On
the mainland, there's just too much going on. Here, it's peaceful.
Quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   The town has no mall, no theater, no laundromat, no gas station.
What it has are a handful of stores, a lot of friendly people who
always wave at each other, and 65 square miles of scenic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   As several locals observe, life in Vinalhaven revolves around
``the boat,'' as the ferry service is known _ actually two, 17-car
ferries that make six round-trip excursions daily from Rockland,
Maine. Much of Lessard's time is spent helping people figure out
how to get what they need to the island.
</P>
<P>
   One recent controversy involved the town dump, a landfill that
was overrun with rats and needed capping. But traditional capping
would have meant barging clay and loam through waters filled with
lobster pots and unloading them on cramped downtown docks, which
would have wrought havoc on the lobster industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard's answer was to cap the dump with local granite, at the
same time that she began a vigorous recycling program, including a
lively swap shop at the dumpsite. Locals were asked to pay $1 for
every bag of refuse that had to be trucked off the island by ferry.
</P>
<P>
   This meant some ferry passengers had to travel with the refuse
trucks. But now the town has gone from 9.5 percent refuse recycled
to 60 percent, and the dump, covered with local blue-gray granite,
is a showplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my `Mission Impossible,''' Lessard says proudly. ``Now
people say it looks like an Earthworks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
