A9348 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEALTH-SNAPSHOT06-COX     09-04 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTH-SNAPSHOT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smaller investors in the market for the long haul
 &HT;    By Shelia Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Irving Fordham is still planning a big Christmas for his family
.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the 40-year-old father of two has nearly $60,000
invested in the stock market, which last week had the
second-biggest plunge in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put: Fordham is letting it ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know investing in financial securities is the best thing for
my family in the long term and my retirement, so these small
fluctuations don't impact my spending habits,'' said Fordham, a
systems engineer at Siemens Energy &AMP; Automation in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham is a typical individual investor. Like many Americans
who own stock, he is in the market for the long haul, and he wasn't
panicked by the recent end to what had been a joyride for
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increased interest in stocks by individuals who have
wanted to get in on the unprecedented market appreciation of recent
years, less than half of Americans own any stock. According to an
April 1998 survey by Hart-Teeter Research, 48 percent of adults in
the United States said they have $5,000 or more invested in mutual
funds or stocks. That's up from 40 percent in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 Federal Reserve study on consumer finances found that 41
percent of Americans have direct or indirect stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Individual ownership of stock is usually passive, often through
employer 401(k) or profit-sharing plans. Few individual owners of
stock are active traders or even aware how their holdings fare
day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham, for example, watches financial news regularly and reads
his quarterly statements, but you won't find him scouring the
Internet for the latest stock quotes or burning up the phone lines
to a broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, individual investors constitute a relatively
minor portion of the overall trading activity,'' said Richard
Wines, senior managing director of Georgeson &AMP; Co., a shareholder
analysis firm. He estimated that on a typical day, individuals
account for less than 10 percent of trading activity. Institutions
account for about 45 percent and the rest is done by arbitragers
and specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals are ``less likely to be following stocks closely.
They can't monitor the stock as thoroughly as a professional,''
Wines said. ``Most are pretty long-term holders. The vast majority
sit on their portfolios forever and probably have a turnover rate
of 20 years _ a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   As much attention as the market gets in the news, the actual
workings of stock trading remains a mystery to most individuals.
Most Americans simply don't understand how trading works, said Lee
Jenkins, a broker with Raymond James Financial in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Given the market woes of last week, Jenkins said individuals
will probably be even less likely to trade actively. ``The stock
market is not a one-way street going up, and people have learned
that over the last few weeks,'' he said. ``It probably will scare
people off. ''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said most of his clients are what he calls investors for
life. ``They will always invest because they have goals they are
trying to achieve either for themselves or the next generation. To
them its a stewardship issue. You should always make your money
work for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
