<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIEFDOMS FOIL ON-LINE UNITY AT HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ``disaster.'' A ``shambles.'' The George Bachrach
congressional campaign? No, a $60 million Harvard computer plan
that has stumbled badly.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, like many other large organizations, has been trying to
standardize its computer functions. The university is
decentralized; the policy of ``each tub (school) on its own
bottom'' not only means that business school grandees luxuriate in
a members-only gym while education school staffers grovel for
quarters behind the seat cushions of their 1978 Toyotas _ it also
means that each school has a separate computer system.
</P>
<P>
   Something called Project Adapt (not an acronym, but a ``slogan
for change,'' according to one principal) was supposed to change
all that. President Neil Rudenstine commissioned the project when
he asked a simple question _ how many people work for the
university? _ and couldn't get an answer. In some organizations,
that answer could be called up with a few keystrokes. But not at
the World's Greatest University, where some of the back-office
computing systems are more than 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The project has been reorganized at least once and is well
behind schedule, partly because of institutional resistance; top
bureaucrats bridle at the notion of channeling tens of millions of
dollars away from teaching and research. Staffing Adapt has been a
huge headache. In the middle of a nationwide high-tech boom,
Harvard has had trouble hiring and keeping techies. (Computer
czarina Anne Margulies left her job in May, and her slot in the
provost's office has not been filled.) There's more money to be had
in the private sector, and the cachet of working at WGU goes only
so far. Remember the rallying cry of Harvard's clerical union?
``You can't eat prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Many a crossed finger attends the project's putative July 1999
completion date. Margulies, now an executive vice president at the
lobbying firm of McDermott/O'Neill, allows that Adapt ``is a very
difficult project to implement,'' but remains bullish on its
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bookwatch 1
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who is Nick Negroponte and why are people saying those awful
things about him?
</P>
<P>
   Nick, longtime boss of MIT's smoke and mirrors factory, the
Media Lab, needs no introduction here. But my playful joshing over
the years pales in the face of invective soon to be published by
L.J. Davis, author of ``The Billionaire Shell Game.'' The book is
an account of the short, happy, and painfully expensive life of
``interactive television,'' a faddish technology promoted at
various times by media giants like Time Warner, and the lab. Davis,
a contributing editor at Harper's magazine, heaps abuse on such key
players as cable baron John Malone and Time Warner's Gerald Levin,
but he reserves special scorn for Negroponte.
</P>
<P>
   A sampler: ``Arrogant crackpot ... a highly flexible notion of
the truth. ... When it came to curbing his tongue and moderating
his ego, Nicholas Negroponte had a problem'' Davis openly questions
Negroponte's qualifications to work in mass media: ``It did not
seem to occur to him, as a man accustomed to wealth and comfort, he
might know remarkably little about the daily experiences of 90 per
cent of the human race.'' The last chapter of ``Shell Game'' is a
hilariously irreverent look at the Media Lab's 10th-anniversary
celebration in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bookwatch 2
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best book I read this summer? ``Revere Beach Boulevard,'' by
my friend Roland Merullo. It's well written, it's a terrific
thriller, and it's set in Roland's hometown of Revere. (Roland's
first novel, ``Leaving Losapas,'' which I loved, is set in both
Polynesia and ... Revere.) Merullo's now a card-carrying member of
the Berkshire literary mafia (charter members: Elinor Lipman,
Jonathan Harr, Madeleine Blais et al.). But he writes beautifully
about both Revere and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cliffhanger. When the cavalry arrives on Page 312 _ well,
I won't give the ending away. ``Boulevard'' is Volume 1 of a
planned Revere Beach trilogy. It's every bit as good as Ernest
Hebert's superb ``Dogs of March,'' and I hope Roland does for
Revere what Hebert did for the fictional town of Darby, N.H. _ put
it on the literary map.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
