A9364 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WALKING-BOS &LR;      09-04 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WALKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL RIGHTS MEMOIR DETAILS THE SIMPLE ACTS OF COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY DOWDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WALKING WITH THE WIND 
A Memoir of the Movement 
By John Lewis, with Michael D'Orso 
Simon and Schuster, 496 pp., illustrated, $26 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If 19th-century abolitionist Frederick Douglass was right when
he wrote that without struggle there is no progress, John Lewis's
life symbolizes at once a man's route to self-actualization and a
nation's steps, however awkward, toward social justice.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 58, a poor black boy from Troy, Ala., who is now a
Democratic congressman from Atlanta, &UR;  &LR; endured punctured ribs, a
cracked skull, tides of scorn, and streams of indignities during
the marches, sit-ins, and protests that defined what we call the
civil rights movement of the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   His autobiography, ``Walking With the Wind: A Memoir of the
Movement,'' with writer Michael D'Orso, brings that hazy period
into focus for a digital age, with nauseatingly vivid accounts of
the beatings captured on grainy black and white footage and
telecast routinely in Black History Month. It is superbly written,
with Lewis's searing honesty showing through.
</P>
<P>
   Besides those accounts, Lewis's book illuminates further by
magnifying a movement through the eyes of one of its
observer-participants, a student leader who believed the
Gandhi-inspired philosophy of nonviolence, ahimsa, and applied it
like balm to soothe the sting of Birmingham Sheriff Bull Connor's
lead-packed batons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence does beget violence, but the opposite is just as
true,'' he writes, describing a 1960 protest in a Woolworth's in
downtown Nashville. ``Hitting someone who doesn't hit back can last
only so long. Fury spends itself pretty quickly when there's no
fury facing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's own reflections on his life and the movement cast him in
the role of the purist for whom human rights was sacrosanct. He
never deviated from prescribed rules of conduct that governed
everything from what the student protesters could say and do right
down to the clothes they could wear.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis details clashes between the feisty youth of his generation
and the seasoned warriors who had pushed the civil rights agenda to
the fore &UR;  &LR; of the nation's consciousness. The students acknowledged
that those older folks had sacrificed, yet they believed that
drastic conditions called for drastic measures. Even the advice of
Thurgood Marshall, the NAACP attorney who &UR;  &LR; had helped craft
arguments that had defeated segregation in Brown v. Board of
Education, was rejected by the Lewis-led Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Lewis writes, recalling a statement in response to Marshall's
advice that the students use the courts to achieve social justice,
``There are times in history _ and this was such a time, I said _
when more immediate, more dramatic means are called for, when the
people themselves must be asked to put their own bodies and hearts
and spirits on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   His earliest experience advocating for others in the face of
authority came when he protested the consumption of the chickens
his father and mother had raised on their farm in Troy. He recalls
mornings at age 5 when he would open the doors of the henhouse to
feed them and set off a chorus of cackling. Eventually, he said,
the birds would quiet and stand before him, watching and seemingly
listening to him talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something magical, almost mystical, about that
moment when those dozens and dozens of chickens, all wide awake,
were looking straight at me, and I was looking back at them, all of
us in total, utter silence,'' Lewis wrote. ``It felt very
spiritual, almost religious. I could swear those chickens felt it,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The fights he had with his parents over killing and eating the
chickens would mirror their conflicts over whether the boy they
sent off to Nashville's American Baptist Theological Seminary to be
a preacher had been spoiled, seduced by this movement. ``You went
to school to get an education,'' Lewis's mother, Willie Mae, wrote
after he had been arrested during a Nashville protest. ``You should
get out of this movement, just get out of that mess.''
</P>
<P>
   But he hung on in ``that mess,'' and his travels from his birth
in a modest shotgun house to Capitol Hill tell the tale of a nation
witnessing assassinations _ John F. Kennedy, Martin Luther King
Jr., Robert F. Kennedy _ and legislation, including the Civil
Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Those deaths signaled to Lewis the demise of the civil rights
movement. But he remained focused on justice and the effort it
requires, and his book makes clear that his optimism is still
burning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
