<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTFOLIOS MORE SMOKE-FREE SINCE START OF YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are Fidelity's Marlboro Managers finally kicking the habit?
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, even as the anti-smoking fervor has
grown, no one in the world made a bigger bet on Big Tobacco than
Fidelity's fund managers. But since the start of the year the giant
Boston money manager has been significantly cutting back its
tobacco holding.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend continues at the world's biggest mutual fund
company, this could be good news for the antismoking crowd and bad
news for the tobacco companies and their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   According to an analysis done for us by the Carson Group, a New
York consulting firm, tobacco as a percent of Fidelity's entire
portfolio fell to 1.6 percent by the end of June, the latest
numbers publicly available, from 2.7 percent at the start of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts have come across-the-board.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Cos., the world's largest cigarette maker, was
Fidelity's No. 1 holding at $9 billion at the first of the year,
but has fallen to No. 5 in its portfolio. Fidelity cut its Big Mo
holdings by 20 percent, unloading $2.3 billion in stock in the
first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff has been even more dramatic in RJR Nabisco Holdings
Corp., maker Joe Camels. Fidelity has cut its RJR holdings by 57
percent this year, or about $900 million. Fidelity has also reduced
its stake in UST Inc., maker of Skoal and Copenhagen chewing
tobacco, by 13 percent this year, and cut its stake in General
Cigar and Consolidated Cigar Holding by half or more, according to
the Carson Group.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the sales, however, Fidelity remains the largest
holder of Philip Morris (6.6 percent) and second largest
shareholder of RJR (5.1 percent). But a little historic perspective
shows just how broad the realignment has been.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago we looked at Fidelity's tobacco holdings and found
that fully three dozen of its funds counted tobacco in their top 10
holdings at the time. Eleven funds had Philip Morris or RJR as
their No. 1 holding; another 13 funds had one of them as their
second-largest holding.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's own mutual fund guide tells a different story today.
By the end of June, only 12 funds included either Philip Morris or
RJR among their top 10 holdings. Only one Fidelity fund, the tiny
Food &AMP; Agriculture select fund, has tobacco as its top holding;
only two funds have tobacco as a No. 2 holding. The $4.7 billion
Retirement Growth, which lists both Philip Morris and RJR among its
top holdings, probably is the Fidelity fund with the heaviest
weighing in tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Fidelity's stake in General Electric was just half
that of Philip Morris; at the end of June, G.E. was Fidelity's
largest holding at $10.4 billion while the Philip Morris stock was
worth $6.3 billion. While it has been selling tobacco, Fidelity has
been loading up on stocks like Microsoft Corp., Associates First
Capital Corp., McDonald's Corp., Time Warner Inc., Lucent
Technologies Inc. and America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco stocks, dogged by all the usual worries, have been weak
all year, particularly RJR, which has lost 38 percent this year.
Philip Morris is down 5 percent, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is
up 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But tobacco retains much of what originally made it so
attractive to Fidelity and other value investors. Philip Morris,
for instance, sells for about 13 1/2 times next year's earnings
compared to 23 1/2 for the S&AMP;P index. In addition, the company
raised its quarterly dividend last month by 10 percent, boosting
its yield to 4 percent, the highest of the 30 stocks in the Dow
Jones Industrial Average.
</P>
<P>
   James H. Lowell, editor of the Fidelity Investor, a newsletter,
believes Fidelity's decision on tobacco stocks is driven less by
political correctness than the analysts inside the big fund company
changing their outlook for the sector. But Lowell says he would be
surprised to see Fidelity continuing to sell off tobacco because
the sector is a good defensive holding in a slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't stop drinking, smoking or eating when things get
bad,'' Lowell says. ``It's the common man's antidepressant.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, as usual, declined to talk to us about its position in
tobacco, saying it does not discuss individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
