<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-     09-04 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYNCH, TOMLIN MIX FUN AND FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as investors could use a few laughs coming off a volatile
week on Wall Street, Fidelity Investments has unveiled a new ad
campaign that includes humorous skits with Peter Lynch, once
Fidelity's star fund manager, and comic Lily Tomlin.
</P>
<P>
   While other mutual fund companies, most notably Charles Schwab &AMP;
Co., have used spokesmen to put a human face on financial services,
the use of Lynch as a corporate pitchman marks the first time
Boston-based Fidelity has done so.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fidelity, it also marks the first time Tomlin has
ever pitched a product or service for anyone.``This campaign is a
real departure,'' said Stephen Cone, Fidelity's new president of
customer marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Among the themes Lynch highlights in ads created by Boston
agency Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos is, ``Know what you own and
know why you own it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike recent Fidelity ad campaigns, this one is less about
selling products and more about educating customers in Lynch's
``fundamental principles of responsible investment,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   One aim of the new ads is to convince people that Fidelity is
more than just the world's largest family of mutual funds with
nearly $700 billion in managed assets, it's also ``an overall
solution to their investing needs,'' Cone suggested.
</P>
<P>
   By teaming Lynch and Tomlin, Fidelity can create ads that are
``memorable and engaging _ ads that break through the clutter,''
Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping Lynch as Fidelity's spokesman makes sense. &UR;  &LR; Given his
fame as a former money manager of Fidelity's Magellan fund, he
evokes Fidelity's glory days.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tomlin, presumably some of her biggest fans are the same
baby boomers who are investing heavily for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been a fan of Peter's for 15 years,'' said Cone of his
decision to use Tomlin. ``She'd been dying to meet him for a long
time. There's a natural chemistry between them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lowell, editor of Fidelity Investor, an independent
newsletter that tracks Fidelity, said he thought Tomlin's humor
might play better in TV ads than her faith in Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her belief in the company may be less valuable than her comic
relief, given the market's current climate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several ads in the new Fidelity campaign were specifically
designed to run during times of temporary market downturns.
</P>
<P>
   One such TV ad finds Lynch wired up on a jogger's treadmill with
Tomlin cast as a nurse giving him a stress test.As the treadmill
begins to buck up and down, causing Lynch's test readings to
fluctuate wildly, Lynch says, ``This reminds me of the stock
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Tomlin: ``It can just shoot up without warning .... And
then fall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five percent or more,'' Lynch says. ``Four times since
1970. Fidelity can help you better prepare for the market's ups and
downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers are asked to contact their financial advisers or visit
Fidelity's Web site. Those who do may be sent such Lynch inspired
tracts as ``Investing in Volatile Markets.''
</P>
<P>
   A second series of ads shows Lynch, but not Tomlin, talking
about ``the Fidelity difference.'' In these ads, he discusses how
diligently Fidelity checks the companies it invests in and how it
picks its analysts as carefully as it picks its stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The themes that Lynch espouses in TV and print ads will be fully
``integrated'' at every point of contact that Fidelity has with its
customers and potential customers, Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   People who call Fidelity's 1-800 number will hear phone
operators reading from a Lynch script. Those who visit Fidelity's
Web site will also be treated to much Lynch imagery and wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Fidelity spent $85.7 million on TV, radio, print, and
billboard ads, according to Competitive Media Reporting, a New York
firm that tracks spending. While Cone would not confirm those
numbers, he said Fidelity will spend about the same on ads this
year as it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   After using so many different ad themes in recent years, how
long will Fidelity stick with the Lynch-and-Tomlin comedy duo?
</P>
<P>
   All Cone would say is that plans call for Fidelity to use these
ads for the rest of the year and the early part of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9382 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-LATIN-ROCK-2ND &LR;      09-04 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LATIN-ROCK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... be the one.  
 
Cafe Tacuba
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mexico's Cafe Tacuba made headlines from the New York
Times to Newsweek when it performed in Central Park. Observed
Newsweek: ``a whole world of music crammed onto one stage ... what
held this glorious mishmash together was a single, driving
principle: Cafe Tacuba rocked.'' The Miami Herald has called Tacuba
``one of the best bands in rock, period.'' It's true. This group
has mastered the American alternative and hip hop idioms, and
remains fearless about folding in lounge, polka, funk, and Latin
American classics such as ``Ojala Que Llueva Cafe,'' a merengue
made famous by Dominican composer and singer Juan Luis Guerra. It
reached a wider audience in 1992 by playing at the Los Angeles
``Lollapalooza'' and this year opened for Santana. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shakira
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Soraya, Shakira is a one-name singer, composer, and
guitarist from Colombia. But that's where the similarities end.
</P>
<P>
   Shakira (Isabel Mebarak Ripoll), 21, has been recording
professionally since she was 13. At 19, Shakira released ``Piez
Descalzos,'' an album of sophisticated and mature pop rock songs
reminiscent of Natalie Merchant; it went platinum in Mexico,
Colombia, the States, and Venezuela, selling 900,000 copies in
Brazil alone. Her anguished alto moves across octaves in the style
of Sinead O'Connor and Alanis Morissette, without being as
annoying. Her guitar-playing is deft and determined, and her
compositions experiment with rhythms from Latin America and the
Middle East (her father is Lebanese). Because of her celebrity,
Colombia declared her a goodwill ambassador to the Vatican, where
she met Pope John Paul this year. He received her warmly, in spite
of the lyrics of her song ``Se Quiere, Se Mata,'' about a woman who
dies after an illegal abortion. Shakira's much-awaited new album,
``Donde Estan los Ladrones?'', was released this month. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   La Ley
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Led by a 30-year-old singer, Alberto Cuevas, who spent 10 years
in Montreal, La Ley is the first rock band from Chile to make it
big on the rock en espanol scene, and the first to experiment with
hypnotic techno sounds. La Ley comes at rock from the INXS/Duran
Duran school, with a bit of a Depeche Mode sensibility. Cuevas, a
graphic artist who wears black nail polish and designs the band's
album covers, resents his original band being labeled a ``Latin
American act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be seen as citizens of the universe, and not be
prejudged because we are Latin Americans,'' he said from Santiago,
where he lives. ``I think all Latin rock bands are hoping to do in
America what American music did in Latin America in the '50s. We
didn't know what you were saying, but it didn't matter. The music
spoke for itself.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Los Aterciopelados
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the few woman-fronted rock en espanol bands,
Aterciopelados is quickly gaining on groups like Mana and the
Cadillacs. Lead singer Andrea Echiverri is considered by many
critics to be the best singer in the genre, period. With much of
her body pierced and with in-your-face feminist lyrics, Echiverri
has disproved the former industry assumption that there was no room
for women in the machismo world of Latin rock. Watching her
sold-out shows, it's hard to believe that women were literally
booed from Latin rock stages as recently as the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   From a wealthy Colombian family, Echiverri comes at her
rebellious stance from a debutante's background. Under her lead,
the band was nominated for the Latin rock Grammy last year, along
with four all-male bands. More than any other female artist to
date, Echiverri has revolutionized the rock en espanol revolution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Molotov
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wildly popular throughout Latin America, the rock-rap band
sounds a lot like the Beastie Boys _ and about a million other
American copycats. What sets them apart is language _ Spanish _ and
culture _ Mexican. With two bassists who rap, the group is loud,
crude, curses a lot, and, when it attempts to rap in English, shows
its heavy imitation of misogynist American faux-gangstas like Snoop
Dog. In the land musically defined by corny balladeers like Luis
Miguel and Alejandro Fernandez _ who still appear onstage in velvet
mariachi outfits _ these nasty boys with the baggy pants have
caused quite a stir, something like the early days of Madonna, when
the Christian Coalition was out in full protest. Interesting from a
historical but not necessarily musical point of view.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other bands
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are literally hundreds of rock en espanol bands. Here are
some of them:
</P>
<P>
   Madita Vecindad y Los Hijos del Quinto Patio, famous for its
song ``Pachuco,'' is one of the first Mexican bands to document the
downside of urban life in Mexico City; lead singer Roco howls
through lyrics about police brutality; the group has used its
popularity to raise money for Indians in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Julieta Venegas is a classical pianist from Tijuana who took up
the accordion and then made it rock; as the former keyboardist for
the punk band Tijuana No, Venegas has gone solo in a big, feminist
way. She, along with fellow Mexicana rocker Ely Guerra, have begun
a Mexican version of the Lilith Fair, called De Diva Voz (In the
Diva's Voice).
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's Fito Paez is the only singer on the scene doing
moody rock operas, and has been compared to David Bowie. Andres
Calamaro is another Argentine solo artist; he looks like Bob Dylan
with a stylist, and turned a childhood filled with military horrors
into a successful rock career; his new debut album, called ``Alta
Suciedad,'' is a word play on ``high society'' that comes out
meaning ``high trash.'' Argentina's Soda Stereo was a
U2-sound-alike that broke up recently but still has some nice discs
out there; and Todos Tus Muertos is one of Argentina's top
speed-metal slam bands.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be excluded from the rock en espanol roster are acts from
Spain. Heroes del Silencio is a pure thrash-metal band whose lead
singer sounds like a thundering Satan on speed.
</P>
<P>
   Several American rockers have come out with their own rock en
espanol projects. Lysa Flores is a guitarist and singer from Los
Angeles who dresses like a mariachi girl and proceeds to crank the
distortion and wail like Janis Joplin; her music and acting were
featured in the film ``Star Maps.'' King Chango is one of the
hottest new Latin rock bands, made up of New Yorkers with
Venezuelan roots. Puerto Rico's best-known rocker is former Menudo
member Robi Draco Rosa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
