<HEADLINE>
`FIRELIGHT` IGNITES SMOLDERING PASSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
FIRELIGHT 
Directed and written by: William Nicholson 
Starring: Sophie Marceau, Stephen Dillane, Kevin Anderson, Joss
Ackland, Lia Williams, Dominique Belcourt 
Running time: 103 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality and brief strong language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few period dramas reach into the present as compellingly as
``Firelight,'' William Nicholson's impressive follow-up to
``Shadowlands.'' Its themes, especially that of surrogate
motherhood, could have been lifted from Thursday's headlines. Yet
the thing that ultimately makes ``Firelight'' persuasive is
Nicholson's ability to transport us to its Victorian world and the
conventions of the 19th-century novel _ from its insistence that we
go along with some blatantly convenient plot twists to its ability
to make the physical environment seem a metaphor for the moral
universe.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's an impressively wrought piece, handsomely mounted
and vibrantly acted, starting with its central character, Sophie
Marceau's impoverished Swiss governess, Elisabeth. She agrees to
bear an anonymous English landowner's child and then hand the baby
over, abandoning any future claim to it. In exchange, the
Englishman agrees to pay her father's debts. The deal is
consummated in convincingly stilted fashion, yet we're asked to
believe they could have enjoyed it under less strained
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The governess doesn't forget the child. She keeps a journal,
complete with delicate watercolors, in which she maintains a
one-sided dialogue with the daughter who doesn't know her. Seven
years and one whopping coincidence later, she applies for a
governess's job at a remote manor in Sussex, only to find that the
spoiled brat she's supposed to govern is her daughter. It seems
that Stephen Dillane's agonized lord of the manor, Charles, needed
an heir he couldn't expect from his wife, who has lain paralyzed
and comatose since a riding accident.
</P>
<P>
   Into this ``Jane Eyre''-like world is thus introduced maternal
pining, but Elisabeth has been sworn to silence as a condition of
keeping her job, whose loss, given her feelings, would be
unthinkable. Clapping a lid on her yearnings, she sets about
relating to the ill-mannered little girl, named Louisa, whose
existence has a visual analogue, a gazebo in the center of an
artificial lake, to which Louisa rows when she wants to brood
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth finally breaks through Louisa's antisocial sullenness,
as the conflicted Charles stands by nervously. His anxiety is
deepened by the conduct of his spendthrift father, a neat reversal
of the usual alignment of responsibilities. Dillane's earnest,
sober, responsible son wrings his hands over the heedless
extravagance of his hedonistic father, played by Joss Ackland with
mischievous yet shrewd high style and a world of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Except when the lordly wastrel is onscreen, airily indulging
this folly or that, the mood is dark and heavy and cold with
foreboding. How things can be put right is anything but apparent,
quite apart from parenting issues and the concealed blood
relationship between mother and daughter. Newcomer Dominique
Belcourt touchingly reveals the pain behind Louisa's unruly
behavior and the vulnerability. But ``Firelight'' is French actress
Marceau's showcase and will usher her decisively into the world of
English-speaking prestige films, thanks to Nicholson's superior
craftsmanship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1343EDT &QL; 
