<HEADER>
A9387 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ROSIE-BOS &LR;      09-04 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROSIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`QUEEN OF NICE' HOPES TO STEAL CROWN FROM TV MATRIARCH OPRAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She once rivaled Oprah Winfrey for the throne of
daytime talk shows, but the royal title that has stuck with Rosie
O'Donnell after two years is ``the queen of nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is nice indeed, but it doesn't always mean ratings. ``The
Rosie O'Donnell Show'' has slipped from its powerful debut two
summers ago, with ratings down more than 20 percent from last year
(due largely to an increase in Jerry Springer's audience). Tuesday,
a tweaked ``Rosie'' will switch from WCVB-Ch.5 at 10 a.m. to
WBZ-Ch.4 at 4 p.m., which is Winfrey's time slot on Channel 5,
pitting the two daytime divas against each other for the crown in
this market. (WBZ's rights to the show actually begin Monday, but
it is showing US Open tennis that day, so it intends to show
Monday's show Tuesday at 3.)
</P>
<P>
   The show is a key part of WBZ's strategy to improve its local
news ratings, hoping that O'Donnell will pull more viewers to its 5
and 6 p.m. newscasts, which now trail channels 5 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Take away the numbers and the cutthroat nature of the TV
syndicate market, however, and you'll find a relative newcomer who
says she admires the matriarch Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, it appears, wears her title well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer not to be against her,'' O'Donnell said, ``not
because she is the reigning queen but because I really like her
show. I can't compete with somebody who inspired and continues to
inspire me.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was ``Oprah,'' in particular O'Donnell's first
visit, for a segment on female comedians, that drew attention to
the up-and-coming stand-up comic. O'Donnell appeared three times on
``Oprah'' before she had a show of her own. For many years,
O'Donnell hung in her office a photograph taken in 1987 of the two,
on which Winfrey had scribbled the message, ``I can't wait to see
how bright your star will shine.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for her streetwise New York wit melded with an open-armed
cheeriness on her show, O'Donnell hasn't faded in the public eye.
Among her roles are stand-up comic, Rizzo (in a six-month Broadway
run of ``Grease''), movie actress, MC for the Tony Awards, and
single mother _ and she still is considered a woman of the people.
Her well-known crush on Tom Cruise, for instance, as well as her
affinity for kids have infused the talk-show host with ahuman
quality. ``When they see me at McDonald's, people don't seem to be
shocked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention her show's craft segment, which will become a
mainstay this year because of its popularity. The Long Island
native revealed she has her own ``craft room'' in her house and
likes to paint by number and build birdhouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come and they go, `Whose room is this?' And I go, `It's
mine,''' O'Donnell said in her usual tough and brassy voice. ``I
don't know what they think _ that I live in a garage and only work
on cars on my day off?''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell will loosen her show's format a bit this fall,
broadening the segments that seemed to have clinched her appeal
among her audience, many of them at-home parents. She'll be
interviewing youngsters for the Kids Chat segment, inspired by Art
Linkletter's ``Kids Say the Darndest Things.'' She'll also have
room for longer celebrity interviews and more human interest
stories.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that won't change on her show is her nicety. Even
with the crisis in the White House, offensive Clinton jokes will
remain off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it a show that your kid can watch and you don't
have to explain to them about stains on a dress,'' she said. ``I
try to make it an hour of escapism, an hour of TV that moms who are
at home can kick back and relax and not have to worry about the
ills of society.''
</P>
<P>
   As she points out, she's not really that nice off the show. Her
stand-up routines poke adult-humor fun at the president and O.J.
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek's labeling her the queen of nice was ``only in direct
response to the show in relation to Jerry Springer,'' she
explained. ``When they were comparing me, the only other shows on
the air, except for Oprah, were downtrodden humiliation festivals,
not exactly a celebratory, nice atmosphere. I think, in comparison
to those shows, I am the queen of nice.''
</P>
<P>
   When O'Donnell went on the air in 1996, she naively suggested to
Warner Bros. that her show air in the hour before ``Oprah,''
O'Donnell recalled. ``That would be a great two-hour chunk for
people who are home to get some positive moments and some
spirituality and some humor all in one.'' She pauses. ``But that's
not how the syndication business works.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more competition is in the works, with other syndicated
talk shows hosted by Donny and Marie Osmond and by Roseanne coming
to TV this year.
</P>
<P>
   And now, at 36, O'Donnell has bigger challenges ahead. In three
years she turns 39, the age at which her mother died of breast
cancer. Losing her mother as a child, she said, has made her own
children _ Parker, 3, and Chelsea, nearly 1 _ the focus of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell (Parker) she died when I was 10, and he looks up in the
sky and says, `She's with God in heaven,''' O'Donnell said.
``Sometimes he waves. I go, `What are you doing?' He says, `I'm
waving to your mommy.' I say, `Aw, honey ...' He's a heartbreaker,
that kid.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows that being overweight will put her more at risk as a
candidate for breast cancer, so she has been consulting a physical
trainer to help her exercise regularly. The trainer has convinced
her to air her progress on the show as a way to inspire others and
motivate herself. ``39 is approaching,'' O'Donnell said. ``I want
to get myself into a more healthy approach to defy those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual to see O'Donnell at the grocery store, wheeling
one of her kids in the shopping cart's kiddie seat. She has often
mentioned the food-shopping bit in other interviews, but she
insists that it's not to boast. ``Food shopping to me is not
writing it down on paper,'' she said. ``You have to go in the
aisles and see, is there a new cereal or _ look, there's new Oreo
Cereal!
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be credited with this, but people are always
shocked about it and I don't know why. I don't think there's
another choice for me to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
