<HEADLINE>
ALTERNATIVES TO DIVIDENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, September 7, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a divorced 67-year-old woman who's concerned about
making a wrong move investing. I need to supplement my Social
Security income of $550 a month. I have $60,000 I would like to
invest, and a further $10,000 that I will keep liquid. I have been
doing some research on no-load direct investing in individual
stocks. I've checked on Exxon Corp., Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., Texaco,
Home Depot, and Boston Edison. My major concern is that I need the
dividends to live on, or I'll use up my bank account. My money is
now making only 4.33 percent in a special savings account. I know I
can do better. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   R.G., Rochester Hills, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can certainly do better than 4.33 percent, but not
necessarily with a portfolio of the stocks you mention.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five issues you cite, the only one with a dividend stream
in excess of what you're now getting is Boston Edison, which is now
called BEC Energy. This stock has a current yield of 4.7 percent.
The others don't come close, with Texaco at 3.2 percent, Exxon at
2.4 percent, Procter &AMP; Gamble at 1.4 percent, and Home Depot at a
near-negligible 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All are well-established companies, with good prospects for
raising dividend levels in the future. But they are also companies
in the large-cap sector of the stock market _ the big national
companies whose shares have been among the driving forces in the
big gains in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   So while there's the positive prospect of dividends rising,
there's also the unpleasant prospect of your principal value
falling should the market take a further tumble.
</P>
<P>
   If you go in this direction, take only a modest step, perhaps
putting $10,000 in BEC Energy. By no-load investing I assume you
propose to buy a few shares through a broker and then enroll in the
company's dividend reinvestment plan, which in the case of BEC will
allow you to add up to $5,000 per quarter to your position.
</P>
<P>
   As for the additional $50,000, I would look for an investment
with a higher yield and lower risk. At the very conservative end of
the spectrum, you could pore over the nation's highest CD rates
(discussed in the next question) or look for one of the
better-yielding mutual fund money market accounts, where you will
find yields of 5.25 percent to 5.30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Or if you wanted to take on a little risk in exchange for a
still higher yield, you could look to a no-load mutual fund such as
Vanguard GNMA, which is yielding 6.44 percent as this is written.
</P>
<P>
   But you should understand a lot about such funds and their
risks. GNMA, or ``Ginnie Mae,'' funds invest in portfolios of
government- guaranteed mortgages. While there's no credit risk in
these investments, they are quite volatile when interest rates
change _ and even when people think interest rates may change.
</P>
<P>
   When interest rates rise, the share value of these funds falls,
sometimes substantially. The reverse happens in a falling
interest-rate climate.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's going to be a bumpy ride. But the good news is
that the interest checks keep rolling in steadily. If you have the
patience to stay with such a fund for many years _ I'm talking
about a decade or more here _ you'll see it pay off in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
   You should not put money in such an investment if you think you
might have to cash out at an inopportune time; invest only as much
as you're willing to leave there through thick or thin.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I would move that last $10,000 into a mutual fund money
market, since this would give you the same liquidity as the bank
savings and a higher yield.
</P>
<P>
   If you took my most aggressive suggestion _ $10,000 in BEC
Energy, $50,000 in Vanguard GNMA, and $10,000 in a money market
fund _ you could expect a total annual yield of $4,215. That's
$1,184 more than you're now getting. This would bump your returns
up from the current 4.33 percent to an average portfolio yield of
6.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where do you find a CD at 6 percent plus, such as you have
mentioned in recent columns?
</P>
<P>
   M.A., Chelsea, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Entering this week, one-year CDs with interest rates from 6
percent to 6.05 percent were available at Atlanta Internet Bank in
Georgia; Cross County Bank in Delaware; and Providian Bank in Utah.
Five-year CDs at the same institutions ranged from 6.35 percent to
6.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These figures, along with a number of other categories, are
available in the Sunday business section of The New York Times, and
are drawn from information supplied by Bank Rate Monitor and
Veribanc Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If you're investing a substantial amount of money, tracking
these can be rewarding, since the national average for one-year CDs
was 4.95 percent; for five-year CDs it was 5.23 percent. The
figures are published in the Consumer Rates feature, and include
toll-free telephone numbers of the institutions with the top rates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. No doubt some editorial shrinkage occurs in your columns that
affects my understanding. For example, take an attached column.
Since IRAs, 401(k)s, and 403(b)s, etc., started just before my
retiring, I have difficulty understanding how the conservative
gentleman in the article could amass nearly $1 million with the
limited contributions allowed. Could the GNMAs have possibly been
that good? Perhaps I missed something?
</P>
<P>
   A.G., Beaumont, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're certainly right that it would be tough to amass a $1
million IRA over a couple of decades simply by making the $2,000
maximum annual contributions. But you are also allowed to roll
qualified retirement plans over into an IRA.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at retirement many people are given an option of
taking annuity payments or a lump sum. If they chose the latter,
they roll the proceeds over into an IRA to avoid immediate
taxation. Such sums, of course, can be very substantial, and thus
account for the seven-figure IRAs that sometimes crop up in the
column.
</P>
<P>
   As a curiosity, I calculated what return would be necessary to
generate a $1 million IRA beginning in 1981 when the deductible IRA
was approved by Congress. Counting on nothing but regular $166.66
monthly contributions, the answer came out to 32.31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where can I get information about the Stein Roe Young
Investor's fund? I am planning for a grandchild's college.
</P>
<P>
   A.M., Spurger, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You can reach Stein Roe by calling 800-338-2550. It's an
excellent fund, and especially good as a gift to young investors
because of its excellent reports designed to be read and understood
by very young owners.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes most of its investments in companies that are
likely to interest younger investors _ Coca-Cola, Walt Disney, and
William Wrigley Jr. are among its top holdings, but so are FNMA and
Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   Because this is an all-stock fund, it is most appropriate if
your grandchild is about 5 or younger. This is because you'll want
to give a stock fund at least 10 years to perform. If your
grandchild is 7 or older, you might want to consider a balanced
fund, which divides its investments between stocks and fixed-income
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
