u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-$ADV0     09-04 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SETS TONE FOR PRESIDENT'S PUNISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 6, 1998)  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Of course Joe Lieberman was right the other day,
so long as you understand that what the Connecticut
senator-moralist had to say was far more diagnostic than
prescriptive.
</P>
<P>
   Judging others is risky business, including in scripture, but
the proper course is therefore to judge conduct rather than people.
It should not be to excuse it in order to avoid playing God with
the person.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's contributions on the Senate floor extend well beyond
the application of a word, immoral, to President Clinton's sexual
encounters in the workplace with an intern less than half his age.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first serious words from a serious Democrat since
the president admitted that he had indeed had what the rest of us
would call sex with Monica Lewinsky and had lied in denying it
until cornered by facts and legal process.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's words stand in important contrast to those of
another New Democrat, Dianne Feinstein of California, who
pronounced her faith in Clinton shattered. Last week, I'm told, she
began the weekly private luncheon of Senate Democrats with a
lengthy tirade against the president for the damage he has done to
his party's prospects this year and perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   As such, what Feinstein said involved what Clinton's conduct
meant to her and by extension to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   What Lieberman discussed, beyond his own personal anger and
disappointment, was what Clinton's conduct as currently established
means to the country _ not to him, but to us, reaching the higher
plain on which responsible decisions about what to do can be made.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's contribution was also personal in the best sense of
the word. Other than the president himself, there has been no more
articulate New Democrat in recent years, able to explain the
emerging ideology's critical marriage between opportunity and
personal responsibility. As fellow ex-presidents of the Democratic
Leadership Council, Clinton and Lieberman are not close friends,
but they go way back, to when Lieberman's first insurgency campaign
against a big shot state senator succeeded in 1970 with the
volunteer assistance of a certain student at the Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spoke for a lot of people last January, myself
included, when he said that he believed the president's clear and
explicit denials _ not merely of crimes but of the underlying
affair itself. He and others believed them both in the absence of
any direct evidence to the contrary and as the embodiment of the
presumption of innocence that should guide responsible people in a
tabloid culture whose abysmal standards blur the distinction
between fact and allegation.
</P>
<P>
   But that belief demands an outcry when one of the denials turns
out to have been not only false but intentionally so. And the
underlying conduct cannot be shielded by privacy. In addition to
close study of Lieberman's speech, Clinton would also learn much
from a stunning speech by Senator Edward Kennedy at Harvard seven
years ago as his own life was changing. In it, Kennedy, without
even acknowledging the tabloid culture, recognized how what may
seem private can become legitimately public.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to underscore how Lieberman built his comments
on the assumption that the Lewinsky matter is what we're talking
about here. Anything more, obviously, and the damage is mortal _
politically, legally, and morally.
</P>
<P>
   On that assumption, however, Lieberman constructed a wall
between his moral condemnation and such extreme steps as
impeachment hearings and resignation from office; he doesn't use
words like ``unjust and unwise'' lightly. He was also careful to
build another wall between ScandalRama as played around here and
the ``time and space'' the president must have to do his job and
for his sin to be both acknowledged as very serious yet seen and
judged in broader context.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in a critically important phrase that I didn't see
quoted anywhere in the press, he said that on the basis of the
basic facts as they are now known, what is called for is ``some
measure of public rebuke.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the impact of Lieberman's comments has been
considerable, both publicly and privately. In public, it has
overnight become the Democratic standard, a stance worthy of the
problem presented that is not self-centered or election-centered,
but country-centered.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, they have also served as a warning to partisan
Republicans that ``unjust and unwise'' responses that offend the
Constitution's high standards can also be opposed effectively from
principled ground.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, they have reached his pal, the president, as the
words of no other pol have. They can both help Clinton to overcome
his remaining, human problems with pique and denial, to then say
more to the country, and then to be in position to deal maturely
with a public rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   The report from Kenneth Starr must still be received; it must
contain no new bombs beyond whatever salacious sex details Starr
feels compelled to disclose; and Lieberman has no problem at all
with an accompanying White House refutation that is based on
evidence and law.
</P>
<P>
   But then, assuming that's it, it is time for trustworthy people
in both parties (aided by some new Clintonian ambassador) to settle
this case in a way that joins legitimate condemnation with
proportionate response.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
