<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEBOK-VENUS-BOS &LR;      09-04 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEBOK-VENUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEBOK LOSES ANOTHER ENDORSEMENT BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the high-stakes marketing bonanza of professional sports,
Reebok International Ltd. is again fighting to get what it paid
for.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it &UR;  &LR; spent $1.5 million for a product placement in the
popular movie Jerry McGuire, only to see the spot fall to the
cutting room floor. Reebok's suit was settled out of court. In
1992, the Reebok Vector appeared on the US basketball team's
warm-ups, but the US Olympic Committee permitted players who had
contracts with Reebok's competitiors to cover up the logo. &UR;  &LR; Reebok
officials are still fuming.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Reebok's marketing coup of securing the endorsement of
tennis star Venus Williams was diminished on the world stage of the
US Open in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Williams took the court Thursday wearing the logo of another
company _ in clear violation of Reebok's exclusive contract with
her, one that industry observers value at $2 million. She had
little choice. Williams faced major fines if she did not wear the
logo of the tournament's sponsors, the Canadian software
manufacturer Corel Corp. and the Women's Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
   While Reebok's Vector still appears on her outfits, the
company's investment in exclusivity has been diluted. To the casual
observer, that may seem trivial. But in the highly competitive
world of sports endorsements, exclusivity is paramount. This is
especially so at the US Open, where players under contract with
Reebok's archrivals, Nike and Adidas, do not have to wear the
additional logo because their endorsement deals were signed before
Corel became a tournament sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It some respects, this harkens back to the '92 Olympics when
we outfitted the basketball players _ the Dream Team _ and the US
Olympic Committee decided they could cover up the logo at the
awards ceremony,'' said David Fogelson, Reebok's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is described by sports marketing experts as among the
most desireable athletes currently available to companies seeking
to burnish their brand names by attaching them to rising stars. The
great demand for her is magnified by the fact that her father,
Richard, her coach and manager, has forestalled major business
deals in the hope of keeping Venus and her sister Serena focused on
their tennis skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a hot property,'' said Bob Williams president of Burns
Sports, in Chicago. ``They've been very slow to accept any deals at
all and Reebok did tremendously well to sign her.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams' contract with Reebok requires her, in effect, to
wear only its logo. Her contract, according to Fogelson, states
that she may wear other logos only when she wears outfits with
sleeves &UR; .  &LR; But Williams has no other endorsement agreements, and
her seven US Open outfits, supplied by Reebok, are all sleeveless.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, at the US Open, Williams was required by the
Women's Tennis Association to wear the Corel/WTA logo. Industry
sources say Corel paid $4 million for the deal, which expires at
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in the face of fines threatened by the WTA _ and at
risk of creating a controversy that might overshadow her play _ she
wore the Corel/WTA logo on the left shoulder strap of a stunning
lime-green tennis outfit. As Williams moved about the court, in
taped clips of her performance and in photographs moved by the
print media covering the event, the Corel/WTA logo appears in sharp
contrast with the distinctive Reebok Vector.
</P>
<P>
   According to WTA officials, because agreements between Nike and
Adidas predate the WTA's agreement with Corel, the Women's Tennis
Association has allowed other stars _ like Steffi Graf, Monica
Seles and Martina Hingis, to name a few _ to play without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the concern, and this is a major issue for us,
going forward,'' said Joseph Favorito, director of communications
for the WTA, who said the tour has recently talked to Adidas and
FILA about the situation, and will sit down at the US Open next
week with officials from Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Because the tour will name a new title sponsor next year,
Favorito said, ``it is a good time to deal with this situation once
and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Reebok, Fogelson said what Williams wears along with the
rest of the five outfits Reebok has designed for the rest of the
tournament is entirely up to her. The company appears to have made
its point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't seek to make an issue out of it, the WTA did when
they went to Venus and Richard (Williams) and said they were going
to be fined,'' Fogelson said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Venus, she said in her post-match interview Thursday that
the brouhaha had not been a distraction. Would she continue wearing
the Corel/WTA patch, she was asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``You all have to talk to Reebok,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
