<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTER INFLATION BY ADDING MORE TO RETIREMENT POOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 47 years old and we wish to retire at
age 65 with a monthly income stream of $4,600. Our projected
monthly income from Social Security will be $2,000. Our investments
consist of these IRAs: $24,516 in Vanguard Index 500, $8,259 in
Vanguard Balanced Index, $8,940 in Vanguard Equity Income fund,
$22,957 in MFS Emerging Growth, and $37,324 in MFS Investors Trust
funds. We also have a $10,000 taxable CD. Is our portfolio properly
diversified, and how much should we save monthly to achieve our
future goal?
</P>
<P>
   J.T., Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. At first blush, it appears that you wouldn't need to add
anything. If we project 10 percent average annual portfolio growth
-- and despite the horrors of the markers in the last week, that
still seems to me to be a reasonable long-term assumption -- your
pool would reach $622,727 over the course of the next 18 years.
That would be more than enough to be reinvested in fixed-income
holdings and produce the desired income.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, all of that is before considering inflation. Let's assume
that over the years the Social Security payments will be adjusted
to reflect the effects of inflation, so that means what you'll be
looking for is the equivalent of $2,600 monthly in today's buying
power, or the equivalent of $31,200 a year. If we project future
inflation at 3 percent, that would require a $53,115 annual income
stream; at 4 percent, the number jumps to $63,205.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, in addition to an income stream in retirement, you'll
want to have some additional funds invested to counter the effects
of inflation in the later years of retirement. So from my point of
view, to be comfortably on track toward a secure retirement, the
goal should be somewhere north of $1 million. To achieve a $1
million pool over the next 18 years would require monthly additions
of $659 to the pool.
</P>
<P>
   As for the portfolio, it seems solid enough. I can't find a fund
called MFS Investor's Trust; perhaps that's only a part of the
name? But if this is a fund which is largely dominated by large-cap
stocks, I think you would want just a bit more diversification,
since MFS Emerging Growth would then be the only holding outside
the large-cap arena. If it was my portfolio, I'd establish 10
percent positions in a health care sector fund, and in a small cap
fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am an older woman, aged 80, and I have been getting by with
CDs. But with interest rates going down and my rent going up, I
could use a little extra income. I have a fairly large CD coming
due and I would like to put a little of it -- maybe $10,000 -- to
generate a little more money for rent increases and living
expenses. I have a friend who has money in Salomon Brothers Fund. I
don't know exactly what it is, but she has got more than 16 percent
interest. It must be a managed fund, and it has to be bought
through a brokerage firm. I also enclose a flier I got in the mail
from Atlas Balanced fund. What do you think of that?
</P>
<P>
   J.W., La Mesa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think I would give both of these suggestions a pass.
Salomon Brothers Fund is a closed-end fund, which means it's a fund
with shares traded on the New York Stock exchange rather than
through direct purchases and/or sales by the fund company. That
means that when people are leery of stocks -- which constitute
almost all of the assets of this fund -- the shares will tend to
bring less than their inherent value. Entering this week, they sold
at an 11.49 percent discount from net asset value. Moreover, that
16 percent wasn't exactly interest -- it represents the amount paid
out in a combination of dividend and capital gains distributions in
the past year. With stock funds, the lion's share of such
distributions represent capital gains, and these are factors you
can't count on -- some years, when the markets are sour, there may
be none at all.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas Balanced, a small and relatively new fund, divides its
assets among stocks and bonds, but again, it's the stocks that give
it the kick in strong markets, or which can give you a kick you in
the pants when the markets go bad. The statistics in the brochure
look nice, but they don't reflect a lot of current history:
According to Lipper Analytical Services, the two Atlas Balanced
funds produced year-to-date returns of 1.91 percent and 1.52
percent through Aug. 28. (There are two classes of funds, with
different sales charges, and accordingly with different results.)
Anyway, the bottom line is that these investments might do great
things for you, but they might also produce little income and even
losses. You can't pay the rent on that. The only kind of funds that
might be attractive to a person in your situation would be
something like a Ginnie Mae fund, which is one that invests in
government-backed mortgages. But the best you could except from
such a fund is an income stream of about 6.5 percent, which would
mean $650 a year income on a $10,000 investment. Entering this
week, the nation's best rates on one-year CDs are slightly higher
than 6 percent. The question I'd ask you is whether an extra $4.16
a month is sufficient to warrant the additional trouble, and
sufficient to offset the additional risk? For most people, I think,
the answer would be no.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a single 35-year-old female. I purchased a home in 1990,
and suddenly became disabled in 1995. I now have an income of only
$1,300 per month. I have these IRAs: $18,000 in Vanguard Index
Value, $14,000 in Vanguard Health Care, $11,000 in Vanguard Index
500, $12,000 in Vanguard Wellington, and $6,300 in Vanguard
Wellesley. I also have taxable accounts of $3,000 each in Vanguard
Windsor II and Health Care, and a $7,000 money market account. What
do you suggest I now do, since I have such a low income. Are my
present investments wise. If not, where might I do better?
</P>
<P>
   J.B., La Mesa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the IRA portfolio has been well established, by and
large -- provided that you expect to allow the accounts to grow for
many years. As a disabled person, you can qualify for early
withdrawals without penalty (although you would still have to pay
the taxes on the withdrawals). If you think it's likely that you
will have to call on some of this money in the relatively near term
-- by which I mean a significant level of withdrawals in the course
of the next decade -- I think I would look to move to a more
conservative balance. This would begin with a reduction of the
Health Care position, which now constitutes 22.1 percent of the IRA
portfolio and a whisker more of your total savings. That's a high
level for a sector fund, and while these positions are likely to be
the strongest for you over the course of many years, they also
represent the riskiest part of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore unless you're confident that you're likely to leave
the IRA accounts alone for 10 to 15 years or even longer, I would
reduce the Health Care position in the IRA to about $6,300, or 10
percent of the total portfolio. If you think you're likely to be
making withdrawals in the near future, you might do well to move
the money that came out of Health Care into Vanguard GNMA; if you
think there's a possibility of some intermediate-term withdrawals
but you don't know when they're likely to come, I suggest you put
the money into Vanguard Wellington until the time comes when you
anticipate withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other accounts, my guess based upon your limited
income is that your crying need is a steady stream of cash. Both
for that reason, and because of the risk element in the two stock
funds, I suggest that both the Health Care and Windsor II positions
be sold, with the proceeds going into Vanguard GNMA. If you
achieved a 6.5 precedent yield there and 5 percent returns from
your money fund, the yields on these two investments would add a
little more than $60 a month to your income stream.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
