<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION FORCES GIRD FOR CRITICAL STRUGGLE IN MEXICAN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHILPANCINGO, Mexico _ With gubernatorial elections scheduled in
the southeastern state of Guerrero next February, things seem
headed for a crucial confrontation _ electoral if possible, armed
if need be.
</P>
<P>
   The election likely will be decided between Guerrero's two
dominant political parties: the long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, and the center-left Democratic
Revolution Party, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   While the PRI has ruled Mexico's third-poorest state like a
corrupt political fiefdom for the past 70 years, the PRD has
chipped away at the PRI's hegemony since the opposition party was
founded 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, says Saul Lopez, who heads the PRD contingent in the
Guerrero state legislature, it's time for a real change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee you that whatever happens, we will win. People
are fed up with the PRI. If they (PRI) try to steal the election,
it will blow up in their face,'' he said. ``The options are clear:
either the PRD wins, or there will be war. That's not blackmail,
that is a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   With a growing leftist guerrilla movement now operating in the
Guerreran countryside, Lopez's boast is not idle.
</P>
<P>
   While he does not predict a PRD victory, Florencio Salazar Adame
agrees that the PRI can no longer wield the ruthlessness it used
to.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar _ who heads the PRI faction in the legislature _ wants
to build a kinder, gentler PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of crushing the opposition, using brute force at times,
Salazar says it is time to learn to live with the PRD and even to
begin negotiations with the guerrillas now attacking police
stations and army troops throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar hopes to win his party's gubernatorial candidacy for
February's elections over hard-line, traditional PRI elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I belong to a renovative current within the Guerrero PRI,'' he
said. ``We are not tied to caciques, political cliques or economic
interests. We want transparency within the government,'' he said.
Caciques are rural PRI political bosses, often with the power of
life and death over peasants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are significant changes being made within the PRI, and
that is good. I think we are living in a delicate situation,
because if the elections are not completely transparent, things are
ripe for an explosion of frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific coastal states of Guerrero, Oaxaca and Chiapas are
Mexico's poorest and home to the country's two active insurgencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatista National Liberation Army has been locked in a
seemingly endless peace process with the Mexican government since
the insurgents attacked four Chiapan cities in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Oaxaca and Guerrero are the back yard of the Popular
Revolutionary Army (EPR) and its recently announced offshoot, the
Revolutionary Army of the Insurgent People (ERPI).
</P>
<P>
   The EPR went public in June 1996 on the first anniversary of the
massacre of 18 unarmed peasants who were killed by the Guerrero
state police. In August 1996, the EPR launched a coordinated attack
on army barracks and police stations in Oaxaca and Guerrero, in
which dozens of police officers, troops and guerrillas died.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Mexican army surrounded a platoon of guerrillas in
a village schoolhouse in El Charco, southeast of Chilpancingo,
killing 12 and arrested several more.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, the ERPI announced it had split from the EPR,
which was considered bureaucratic, centralized and docile. The ERPI
claimed to have taken with it virtually the entire EPR organization
in Guerrero and planned to boost the pace of action.
</P>
<P>
   A fresh round of attacks on the police and soldiers throughout
Guerrero in recent months suggests the ERPI is serious.
</P>
<P>
   David Spencer, writing in the August issue of Jane's
Intelligence Review, said the guerrilla violence in Guerrero's
countryside has reached levels ``that have not been seen since the
beginning of the conflict'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero is a perennially poor and restive state that has
nurtured rebellion since its namesake, Vicente Guerrero, helped
launch Mexico's war of independence from Spain in the early 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Acapulco is Guerrero's economic motor and home to nearly
one-third of its population. In contrast to the glitter of the
tourist hotels lining the beach, most of the rest of the state
lives in abject poverty or relies on subsistence farming or growing
copra, dried coconut meat.
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 percent of the state's people are illiterate;
nearly 50 percent of the children show some signs of malnutrition.
Crime is rampant and more than 620 activists from peasant
organizations, student groups and opposition political parties like
the PRD have been killed in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Years of heavy-handed, corrupt rule in Guerrero have bred a deep
cynicism among many here toward the PRI. Many more have lost faith
in electoral politics altogether.
</P>
<P>
   PRI politicians will never change, asserted Maximo Gomez Munoz,
a parish priest from Atoyac who can quote Karl Marx as well
scripture and is known informally as the guerrilla priest.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Salazar wanted to reform the Guerrero PRI, Gomez said
flatly: ``It's a lie. Until they resolve the peasant situation
here, it must be a lie. What they want is to keep peasants
dependent on the state to maintain their power.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if the PRD wins in Guerrero in February, Gomez said,
unless the PRD also wins the Mexican presidency in 2000, real
change will be frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be violence if the February elections return PRI
hard-liners to the Guerrero governor's mansion?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Gomez said. ``The people have never been violent,
it's always been the government. It's time they decided to defend
themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
