<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUGUST GAMES ARE A CLASSIC WASTE OF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you missed it, the college football season opened last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there was only a handful of games, most of them assorted
``classics,'' such as the Pigskin and Kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   They were also games in August, which count on regular-season
records, albeit with an asterisk attached, since they are
``exemption'' games.
</P>
<P>
   Again in case you missed it, here's what happened. Nebraska beat
Louisiana Tech, Colorado State beat Michigan State, Southern
California beat Purdue, and Florida State beat Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   And now for the real news. The official opening of the 1998
college football season will occur Saturday _ in September, not in
August.
</P>
<P>
   A season that some administrators argue is already too long has
been stretched even longer by the glut of preseason games. First
there was one, then there were two. This year the number rose to
four, which is four too many.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone is going to have them, we ought to have a 12-game
schedule,'' said Florida State coach Bobby Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they are played to aid good causes, such as the coaches' and
athletic directors' pension funds and the Black Coaches
Association. But the risk-reward issue is way out of whack here.
Ask Nebraska first-year coach Frank Solich how he felt when he saw
his new quarterback, Bobby Newcombe, go down with what could have
been a serious knee injury against Louisiana Tech. Or ask Bowden
how he felt when he saw All-America wide receiver Peter Warrick go
down with a leg injury in Monday's Kickoff Classic. Ask Michigan
State coach Nick Saban and Purdue coach Joe Tiller how they feel
about being 0-1 before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries and losses are part of football. But college football
in August should not be a part of the landscape, just as college
football on Monday and Thursday nights should not be part of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   But with a new multimillion-dollar extravaganza known as the
Bowl Championship Series in place this season; with ABC controlling
all four of those bowls and dictating that bowl games will now be
played after the traditional Jan. 1 end of the season, why not play
in August?
</P>
<P>
   Why not play in June or July then? Why not play on Sunday,
Monday, and Thursday nights?
</P>
<P>
   Greed is the motivating factor. There are bigger ratings in
prime time than on a Saturday afternoon. ABC has a Monday night
football package it wants to sell, so why not tack on a college
game in August and one in January as part of the deal?
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the same college presidents and officials who
argue that a Division 1-A football playoff would make the season
too long were strangely silent about the issue of adding games and
playing them on different nights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   But now legislation is on the books which will eliminate these
preseason games in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Thank heavens. If the season is going to get longer, extend it
with meaningful postseason games that will determine a national
champion rather than with meaningless and dangerous exhibition
games in August that are forgotten almost as quickly as they are
played.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Irish Rose?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Notre Dame has yet to play a game, here's one thing you
can guarantee. If the Irish win enough games to get into the BCS
(nine will probably do it), they will almost certainly be heading
to Pasadena and the Rose Bowl Jan. 1 as long as there is a slot
open.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Rose Bowl resisted joining the Bowl Alliance for
years, fearful of losing its guaranteed draw of a Big
Ten/Pacific-10 matchup, it has also lusted after Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   So write it down as a mortal lock right now. If Notre Dame has
enough wins to become eligible for the BCS and either the Pac-10 or
Big Ten champion makes it to the national championship game in the
Fiesta Bowl, Notre Dame will play in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A prevent defense
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a sellout crowd of more than 65,000 expected for Saturday
night's game at West Virginia against Ohio State, Mountaineer
officials have beefed up security to an all-time high, with dozens
of law enforcement officers from local, county, and state agencies
making sure everything goes smoothly. The game against the No. 1
Buckeyes is being called the biggest in West Virginia history ...
It's still too early, but Colorado State's win over Michigan State
last week has some people projecting CSU to go 14-0. Fiesta Bowl
officials would squirm if a marquee team like Florida State or Ohio
State is left out of the game because of the new selection process,
which puts a heavy emphasis on number of victories ... Kentucky
quarterback Tim Couch has taken out a $3 million injury insurance
policy. Couch, who some feel is the best quarterback in college
football, had a $1 million policy last season ... If you are
wondering why some people are skeptical of Kansas State, check out
its nonconference schedule, which includes Indiana State, Northern
Illinois, and Northeast Louisiana ... Penn State coach Joe Paterno
starts his quest for win No. 300 Saturday when the Nittany Lions
play Southern Mississippi in their opener. A win _ and that's
hardly a sure thing _ would mean Paterno would get the milestone
next week against Bowling Green ... Notre Dame has an interesting
first month of the season. The Irish open Saturday at home against
Michigan and then play Michigan State, Purdue, and Stanford, all of
which beat them last season, as did Michigan ... West Virginia
could become the first Big East team to finish in the Top 5 since
Miami in 1992. Beating Ohio State Saturday would go a long way
toward achieving that goal ... Oklahoma, once a football
powerhouse, could be in for an unprecedented fifth consecutive
losing season ... Houston, which once made a habit of playing its
home games in the dreary Astrodome, will play all of its home
gamees on campus for the first time since 1949. Wonder if new
athletic director Chet Gladchuk had anything to do with that ...
How would you like to be a Rice fan? The Owls have gone 7-4 the
past two seasons _ which is great for them _ and didn't even go to
a bowl game ... Rutgers is 0-0 and has already lost. Both starting
wide receivers are out for the season with injuries. With a 2-20
record the last two years, coach Terry Shea may not be around much
longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Encouraging? Naturally
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a good trend in college football. According to an NCAA
survey, of the 112 Division 1-A schools, 73 are now playing on
natural grass surfaces ... Texas Christian has backed out of a
three-game series with Nebraska. Why? The Frogs don't think they
can compete with the Huskers. Normally, such a breach of contract
would warrant a $100,000 penalty, but Nebraska athletic director
Bill Byrne waived the fee. TCU officials say they hope to get
Nebraska back on their schedule when they are more competitive ...
There are fans and then there are fans. But who's going to top
Southern California follower Giles Pellerin, who is 91 years old
and has seen 787 consecutive Trojan games, home and away, since
1926? Pellerin has seen everey UCLA-USC and every Notre Dame-USC
game ever played, as well as all 26 of the Trojans' Rose Bowl
appearances ... New USC coach Paul Hackett broke a precedent with
the win over Purdue. The last six USC coaches had lost their
debuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from college football sources, wire service reports,
sports information directors, athletic directors, conference
commissioners, and coaches was used in this report.)
</P>
