<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON-COLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYE SET TO GO AFTER A LONG WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ When he set out from his home in Valley Cottage,
N.Y., to Columbia Presbyterian Hospital in Manhattan, Brian Maye
could not stop worrying about the delicate neck surgery he faced on
that cold morning of Jan. 26. As he and his father, William, made
the 6 a.m. drive down the Palisades Parkway, Maye's fear and
anxiety mounted with each mile that brought them closer to the
city.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how tightly he shut his eyes and his heart to it all,
Maye could not escape the lingering image of what his doctors were
prepared to do to him.
</P>
<P>
   In his mind's eye, Maye could see the scalpel slicing into his
flesh, drawing a bead 2 inches long across the base of his neck ...
doctors poring over the opening in his neck to remove a damaged
cervical disk ... the insertion of an anonymous donor's disk,
withdrawn from a bone bank ... and the cervical fusion of bone and
metal plate, surrounded by a protective metal cage.
</P>
<P>
   Maye shuddered at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   How could he go through with it?
</P>
<P>
   He had already been through so much as a linebacker at Boston
College. A knee injury in the third game of the 1995 season against
Michigan truncated his junior year, though he received an extra
year of eligibility as consolation. A dislocated elbow in the
eighth game of the 1996 season prematurely ended what was supposed
to be his redshirt junior campaign. And just when it appeared
things couldn't get any worse for him, Maye was one of 13 players
implicated in a gambling scandal and suspended for the final three
games of '96.
</P>
<P>
   Declared ineligbile by the NCAA for four additional games at the
start of the 1997 season _ the stiffest suspension served by any of
the five BC players allowed to return to the team _ Maye was set to
make his comeback for his fifth year of eligibility last Oct. 4
against Georgia Tech. Because of the lingering disk problem, Maye
sat out the season but was granted a rare sixth year of eligibility
by the NCAA as a medical redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered if neck surgery was too steep a price to pay in
order to play for the Eagles again. After he tossed and turned the
night before, Maye realized on the ride to the hospital that he
wasn't prepared to go through with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad,'' Maye told his father, ``turn the car around.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Maye did. For the next two weeks, Brian sought his
family's counsel on what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all just said to make sure it's something you want to do
and you're not doing it for anyone else but yourself,'' Maye said.
``But I just couldn't live with the decision. I just said, `I'm not
going to beat myself up for the rest of my life by not coming
back.' So, yeah, I'm glad I made my decision, you know _ or
reversed my decision, I should say _ to have surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 10, Maye began his long journey back by riding to the
hospital and undergoing neck surgery. Successful neck surgery. It
has enabled Maye to don his No. 46 jersey for full-contact
preseason workouts. He will make his first start in two years as
the middle linebacker in Saturday's season opener at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it ironic? Not necessarily. I just look at it as the first
game I've played in a while,'' said Maye, who will finally start
against the Yellow Jackets after all. ``I don't see any irony in
the year before. I'm just going to treat it as any first game of
the season, but this one will just be bittersweet to get back on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll be emotional,'' he added. ``It's not like
I'm going to get choked up or something before the game. It's just
nice to be back playing, you know? It's been kind of of a long
journey to get where I am right now. So everything culminates on
Saturday when I go out there for the first play.''
</P>
<P>
   The way BC coach Tom O'Brien figures it, Maye has ``had so much
bad luck there's going to be nothing but good luck for him this
fall.'' Maye certainly hopes that will be the case, but he doesn't
necessarily believe his luck has been all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been lucky in some regards,'' said Maye, who was
voted a cocaptain by his teammates. ``When you put things in
perspective, then you don't feel sorry for yourself at all. I've
had some bad luck, but I could be a lot worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   What could possibly be worse? ``A hell of a lot, man; just look
around,'' he said. ``I'm happy, you know? I'm here and I'm playing
and I've got a second chance. I had successful surgery and I'm back
here with a lot of guys I enjoy being with and playing the game
that I love to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to come back was really tough,'' he added. ``Did
I want this enough to go through neck surgery, (wearing) a neck
brace for a couple of months, then rehab and'' _ he broke into a
chuckle _ ``all the `sixth-year' jokes?''
</P>
<P>
   Maye has heard them all. Yadda, yadda, yadda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (BC trainer) Steve Bushee gets in one a week on him,''
said senior running back Mike Cloud. ``After practice, Bush-man
comes in and says, `Freshmen report for treatment at 7:30.
Upperclassmen report at 8. And our sixth-year player reports at
8:30.' It's just jokes like that. Some people call him the
`player-slash-coach' because he's so old. There's another joke,
people say, `By the time he graduates, he'll be coaching his
kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Don McPherson spoke to the team recently during preseason
camp, O'Brien introduced him as a former Syracuse quarterback who
started for the Orangemen in 1987 and joked, ``Brian, you probably
played against him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say it in a witty way, there's some that are funny,''
said Maye, one of four 23-year-old players on the team. ``But if
it's just like `Blah, blah, blah _ what are you, like, 35 years
old?' That's not funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Maye just shrugs it off now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' he said, ``but like (Scott) Mutryn said the
other day in the paper. He was saying when you give up football,
you give up your youth almost. I just thought how it was so true. I
mean, I figure if I'm not sitting here talking to you right now,
I'm probably in a suit and tie commuting into the city. Now I'll be
playing football and having fun. This was where I was hoping to be
after making the decision. It took me two weeks (after the initial
reversal), but it was a solid decision. And so when we went back to
the hospital, there was no turning back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Or now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
