<HEADLINE>
HE'S TOAST OF ST. LOUIS, BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Anthony's Bar sits diagonally across the street from
Busch Stadium, and there is a big red ``59'' sitting in the front
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been putting those numbers up there since 45,'' reports Mike
the Bartender.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to St. Louis, ground zero for the assault on Roger
Maris's record.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Farnen, Steve Melnick, and Bernie Plassmeyer are sitting at
the bar, nursing their Buds. And well they should, because each of
them draws a paycheck from the King of Beers. They all work in that
nebulous world where sales, advertising, and marketing mix, and
they are celebrating the end of another working day doing what they
always seem to be doing these days. They are talking about Topic A,
and in these parts, that does not mean the over/under on how many
days Yeltsin can hold on to his job or the dollar damage attributed
to Hurricane Earl. You know darn well what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember Opening Day?'' Farnen is saying. ``Remember in the
ninth inning when (Delino) DeShields was up and the crowd was
begging him not to swing, praying he'd walk so Mark would get up
with the bases loaded? Remember how they cheered when he drew that
walk? And then Mark did it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a box with 30 or 40 people,'' adds Plassmeyer, ``and
when he hit that ball, everyone rushed forward.''
</P>
<P>
   For those of you a bit on the obtuse side, Mark McGwire got off
to an appropriate start in 1998 by hitting a ninth-inning
game-winning grand slam on Opening Day to beat the Dodgers. And
now, 58 home runs later, he is on the verge of zooming past Maris,
perhaps putting the home run record well into the 60s. And these
good baseball fans are having a hard time digesting it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to do it,'' says Melnick. ``We all know that. The
question is, will people care what happens after he hits 62?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, they will,'' declares Farnen. ``That last ball will be
the record. It will be very valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Osantowski needs to be heard. He's a lawyer from Detroit
whose business is concluded but who can't get out of town until
Saturday because of the Northwest Airlines strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a baseball fan, but not so much since the
strike,'' he says. ``But I'm following this. And I can tell you
that there is a resurgence of baseball interest in Detroit because
of this, and only this. You listen to talk radio and that's all
they're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, the interest is off the scale. The story is Mark
McGwire. The Cardinals won, 14-4, Wednesday night. Pitcher Kent
Mercker hit a grand slam. Nobody cared. The only two at-bats that
mattered were McGwire's last two, when he hit a pair of
out-of-the-strike-zone baseballs a total of more than 900 feet for
home runs No. 58 and 59, leaving him two shy of Maris's record set
in 1961. He is now a good two weeks ahead of schedule. A five-game
homestand _ three with Cincinnati and two with Chicago and You Know
Who _ began Friday night (Sept. 4), and it is not inconceivable
that McGwire, who has hit six home runs in his last eight games and
four in his last two, could have the record by Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The game is incidental to the McGwire at-bats. The Cardinals are
20 1/2 games behind the Astros in the National League Central. The
games are nothing more than an excuse for McGwire to get his rips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the last time we cared about who won or lost was a
while back when we had a doubleheader with the Mets,'' Farnen says.
``If the Cards had won, they'd be 5 1/2 back in the wild-card race.
But they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Now who cares? What's going on here is food for the soul of any
legitimate baseball fan, and every member of this Budweiser Trio
says he qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are good baseball fans,'' maintains Farnen. ``Believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time,'' assures Melnick. ``We've suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid,'' says Plassmeyer by way of validation, ``I
caught a foul ball hit by Darrell Porter.''
</P>
<P>
   They can hardly believe you can have this much fun when your
team is 20 1/2 games out of first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fantastic,'' says Farnen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three reasons why this is so great,'' offers
Melnick. ``One, it's history. Two, the fact that he hits them so
far. And three, (Sammy) Sosa is still so close to him (with 56
homers). It's a real race. That really adds to the drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Cubs slugger, Farnen conjures up a sick scenario
that suggests he might have been a Red Sox fan in another life.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about this?'' he begins. ``You know that McGwire hasn't
hit one this year against Cincinnati. So Sosa keeps up. Then he
comes in here on Monday and Tuesday, tied at 60, and there's the
Cardinal pitching _ Jeff Brantley! _ and those guys let Big Mac
down.''
</P>
<P>
   That notion gets hooted down and the boys return to the general
business of praising McGwire and toasting baseball, St. Louis, and,
of course, the mother ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more thing,'' says Farnen as he heads out the door. ``This
sure is helping Budweiser.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
