<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN '61, MARIS GOT THE RECORD _ AND LOTS OF ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Roger Maris were alive today, he might be smiling. Happy that
a record that has hung around his neck like an albatross since 1961
might soon belong to someone else. Grateful that by relinquishing
it, he could be judged strictly by what he accomplished in a
12-year career. And the heck with the rest of it.
</P>
<P>
   When Maris died in December 1985, it was generally assumed that
his record of 61 home runs in a season was unsurpassable _ just as
Babe Ruth's record of 60 had been considered unassailable when he
set it 34 years before.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, thanks to a rush by Mark McGwire, the home run feats of
both Ruth and Maris are on the verge of being obliterated. The
Cardinal slugger has 59 going into a Labor Day weekend series in
St. Louis against Cincinnati. And right behind him is Sammy Sosa of
the Cubs with 56.
</P>
<P>
   It's exciting. And it's also a lot different from the home run
chase by Maris and Yankee teammate Mickey Mantle (who wound up with
54) in 1961. One obvious difference is that the fans have embraced
both McGwire and Sosa, who are drawing adoring crowds and
transfixed TV audiences wherever they perform.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like this in 1961 when 27-year-old Roger Maris came
out of the pack and wound up hitting his 61st homer in the season's
162d and final game, one more than Ruth had hit in a 154-game
season.
</P>
<P>
   Little did the 6-foot, 203-pound Maris suspect that he would be
tormented by a hostile media, unforgiving fans who conisdered him
an unworthy successor to the Babe, and a commissioner more
concerned about protecting his good friend than acknowledging
baseball history. Maris was caught in the crossfire, and his epic
quest became an ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a people's choice to break Ruth's mark, it was
Mantle, the sublime center fielder who was in the midst of a Hall
of Fame career. Maris was dismissed as the interloper, despite the
fact that he was on the way to his second straight American League
MVP Award and would go on to make seven World Series and All-Star
Game appearances.
</P>
<P>
   If Mantle and his fans weren't enough of an obstacle, there was
commissioner Ford Frick, an old crony of Ruth's. On July 19, 1961,
Frick declared that unless Ruth's record were equaled or surpassed
in 154 games, any mark achieved in the remaining eight games added
because of expansion would be accompanied by an asterisk. Maris had
58 homers after 154 games and did not get No. 60 until Game 158.
</P>
<P>
   His 61st, off Red Sox rookie righthander Tracy Stallard,
provided the only offense in a 1-0 Yankee victory. Maris celebrated
at the time, but that didn't obscure the anxiety and vilification
he had endured, graphically manifested in a dramatic loss of hair.
In fact, he never received his due. He went to his grave with that
cursed asterisk compromising his place in the record book _ it
finally was removed in 1991 by commissioner Fay Vincent, long after
it could do Roger Maris any good.
</P>
<P>
   Maris's life might have turned out differently if he'd followed
another path out of Fargo, N.D., where he grew up. An all-state
halfback in football, he was courted by the University of Oklahoma.
But once there, he changed his mind and returned home. Baseball was
his true love, and he excelled at the American Legion level. That
earned him a tryout with the Cleveland Indians. Maris eventually
signed for a $5,000 bonus and a promise that he would get $10,000
more.
</P>
<P>
   Very quickly, according to one source, he became a player who
would not blend into the crowd. In his first minor league camp, he
refused assignment to Class D but said he would accept a spot in
Class C _ with Fargo. Maris eventually got his way and responded by
hitting .325 with nine homers. Then came another stormy battle as
he argued for _ and received _ promotion to Class B. At the age of
22, he was in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   With Cleveland and Kansas City, his first two major league
clubs, Maris was at best considered a prospect. He lasted only a
year and a half in Cleveland; ditto with the Athletics, who many
suspected of being tantamount to a Yankee farm club. Whatever the
reason, the Yankees took note of Maris's power _ 28 homers with
Cleveland and KC in '58 _ and acquired him after the 1959 season
for first baseman Kent Hadley and shortstop Joe DeMaestri.
</P>
<P>
   Maris arrived in New York with a flourish, hitting 39 homers
with 112 RBIs as he led the Yankees to their 10th pennant in 12
years under Casey Stengel, a performance that earned the right
fielder MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing compared to 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Maris's improbable quest for immortality was the centerpiece on
a team that won 109 games, cruised to another pennant, and bashed a
record 240 homers in the process. The lineup included bona fide
sluggers like Moose Skowron, Yogi Berra, Elston Howard, and John
Blanchard. But all paled next to the M&AMP;M Boys, Maris and Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   They waged a personal _ and historic _ battle, exploiting the
diluted pitching that was the byproduct of the addition of two
expansion teams, as is the case with McGwire and Sosa in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The season began inauspiciously for Maris. After 10 games,
according to Mantle's account to writer Mickey Herskowitz, Maris
was hitting .161. He was struggling, and by April 26, Mantle was
ahead in home runs, 7-1. But a trip to an eye doctor seemed to work
wonders. By mid-July, Mantle's lead had been cut to two, 35-33, and
the M&AMP;M Boys then took turns at the top.
</P>
<P>
   As the season wore on, so did the pressure. The media horde
grew, though not nearly to the dimensions of the McGwire-Sosa
legions. By Sept. 13, Maris was ahead, 56-53, and everybody figured
it would be a dogfight to the finish. But Mantle was forced out by
a hip injury and dropped out of the derby. The spotlight was solely
on Maris. There was now no peace for him. In contrast to the
outgoing, fun-loving Mantle, he was shy, virtually colorless _ in
fact, there were rumors of a rift between the two even though they
were roommates. There was no question as to which side the publc
took. Maris was booed by Yankee fans, which deeply hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure was there every day,'' recalls Jack Lang, former
baseball writer for the Long Island Daily Press, who covered the
Yankees. ``From the fans who would cheer for Mantle to the writers
who might be in the clubhouse asking questions for an hour after
the game ... Maris wasn't too fond of this, but I can think of only
one time when he wasn't available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Fishel, who was the Yankee public relations man at time,
said to me that in retrospect, he should have protected Roger more.
But it was 1961. It was different. There weren't the national media
or the cameras around. Columnists came early. Players stayed and
answered questions until the writers left.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the resentment toward Maris was intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were letters that said Maris shouldn't even be mentioned
in the same breath with Ruth,'' says Lang. ``It's funny. Almost
nobody was pulling for Maris. But everybody is pulling for McGwire
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantle said in his book, ``All My Octobers,'' that Maris was not
prepared for the fame that came with the record chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came almost overnight to Roger, who never wanted to be a
special person,'' wrote Mantle. ``No player ever accomplished so
much and enjoyed it so little. As he closed in on the record, the
buildup engulfed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was uncomfortable in the spotlight. While Ruth had reveled
in it, he was too nervous to enjoy the cheers and unable to ignore
the boos that came when the cheering stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris had his own definition of trouble, Mantle wrote. ``He said
trouble meant the reporters who were coming in waves, the strangers
who wouldn't leave him alone, and the great players of another era
who wanted to protect Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having 58 homers through 154 games, Maris was openly
defiant of Frick's declaration that the Ruth chase was over. ``As
far as commissioner Frick is concerned, I have only one game left
to break the record,'' he said. ``But as far as I'm concerned, I
have eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll consider it a record if I hit No. 60 and No. 61 in the
162d game. Any homers I hit now will be just fine and dandy.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit No. 59 in Game 155, then tied Ruth with No. 60 off Jack
Fisher of Baltimore in No. 158. The Associated Press reported,
``Roger Maris blasted his 60th home run of the season Tuesday night
but it came four official games too late to officially tie Babe
Ruth's 34-year-old record in 154 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher stills remembers it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wound up, and in the middle of my delivery, I decided to
take a little bit off,'' he said in an ESPN interview earlier this
week. ``And when I did, all the ball did was just run up there. As
soon as I let it go, I knew I was in trouble. It was one of those
you'd like to run down there and catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the last game of the season, the finale of a
three-game series against the Red Sox, the quset was complete.
Maris reached Stallard for a 360-foot solo shot into the
right-field stands in the fourth inning. The ball was caught by Sal
Durante of Coney Island, who turned it in and received $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a premonition that he might do it,'' said Ralph Houk,
the Yankee manager at the time, who in later years as Red Sox
manager called it one of the classic moments in his career.
``Stallard threw fastballs, changeups, and sliders. Stallard was
the type a batter like Maris could get under and hit. I was happy
because it was a real good homer _ no fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   But no joy, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
