<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RUNNING-2TAKES-BO     09-04 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RUNNING-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO WIN TEAMS MUST RUN FOR THEIR LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bud Goode may understand more about the importance of the
running game in the National Football League than any man alive.
Certainly he understands more about it than any 75-year-old,
136-pound man alive, and what he understands is statistically
proven and simple to follow.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, in the NFL you run or you die.
</P>
<P>
   There may be other ways to put it, but that's as valid as any
law of the NFL jungle. A year ago, for example, seven of the 12
playoff teams had a 1,000-yard rusher, three of the four teams in
the conference championships ran more than they passed, and of the
seven teams that ran more than they threw, six reached the playoffs
(only the Tennessee Oilers coming up empty) and four (Kansas City,
San Francisco, Pittsburgh, and the Giants) won their division.
</P>
<P>
   Statistical aberration?
</P>
<P>
   Well, consider that the same was true for the losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year when we ran more than we passed we won every game,''
said New Orleans Saints president and general manager Bill
Kuharich. ``That's why (head coach Mike) Ditka wants to run the
ball. Last year, we're 0-3 and 9-point underdogs at home against
Detroit and they've got Barry Sanders. We beat them, 33-17. How?
They threw four interceptions. We ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get the ball on the 20, run some, and then have to
punt, it's all right if you stop them on defense. Now you get the
ball back near the 50. Then you run some and kick a field goal.
That's how Tampa played. They'd start a drive at the 20. Next time
it would be the 35 or 40. Then it's a touchdown drive. That's the
way Mike played in Chicago. We want to play that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's the way everyone wants to play, and for good
reason. Two of the league's worst teams last year, Indianapolis and
Arizona, threw far more than they ran, with the Colts passing 523
times to 450 rushes, while the Cardinals were ridiculously out of
balance with 602 passes and 395 runs. If they'd listen, Goode would
be happy to tell them that's no way to play winning football.
</P>
<P>
   Goode knows better because he's been crunching the NFL's numbers
longer than anybody and understands what they mean. He has been
advising the likes of Bill Parcells, Ditka, Chuck Knox, Chuck
Fairbanks, and Raymond Berry right up to Norv Turner and Steve
Mariucci since 1960. At one time he was a consultant to 16 teams.
In fact, when the Patriots lost to Ditka's Bears in the 1986 Super
Bowl, Goode was a statistical adviser to both teams, leaving him
and his television in a precarious position that Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw the cat at the set every time either team did wrong,''
he joked.
</P>
<P>
   A Hollywood writer and public relations man by trade, Goode was
once the head writer for Groucho Marx's ``You Bet Your Life,'' but
over the past 30 years has led a double life. Around the same time
he was analyzing the Nielsen ratings in Hollywood, NFL coaches
began betting their futures on the accuracy of his statistics.
Through the years one of the things he's learned should comfort the
Patriots as they enter a new season faced with an old problem _ the
absence of a proven running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on 30 years of selling advice to teams, one thing is
clear,'' Goode said this week from his home in Studio City, Calif.
``Number of rushes is more important than average per rush. The
quantity is more important than the quality. In contrast, the
passing game's importance is more one of quality than quantity. You
must have enough of a running game to control the clock and make
first downs. You need to be able to protect a lead to win in the
NFL. You do that by running.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A satisfied customer
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O ne of Goode's newest clients is Mariucci, who first began
paying attention to his numbers when he was the quarterbacks coach
of the Green Bay Packers. Almost without fail, those numbers have
indicated the same thing year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Throw if you want, but in the end winners run the football.
</P>
<P>
   So when Mariucci took over the 49ers last season, he did a
remarkable thing for a disciple of Mike Holmgren's West Coast
passing game. Holmgren had already adapted the offense to both the
present day and the Wisconsin winters and Mariucci took it another
step. He ran more and he ran more physically, trading in Bill
Walsh's traps and finesse runs for Holmgren's power oriented
running game that features aggressive zone blocking with linemen
coming off the ball and backs picking a hole.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci put in a similar running game but more important he
insisted on using it more than they ever had in San Francisco. He
had the Niners run the ball nearly 100 times more than they threw
it (523 to 432), the first time that had happened in San Francisco
since 1984. Although some observers thought the 49ers ``slipped''
to 12th in total offense (a run-plus-pass stat Goode said means
nothing because ``it compares apples with bananas''), the fact was
they finished 13-3, reached the NFC Championship Game, averaged
more yards per catch than anyone in the NFL, and had their first
1,000-yard rusher (Garrison Hearst) in five years.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this was the result of losing Jerry Rice in the opening
game and having quarterback Steve Young sustain a concussion the
same afternoon. But Rice, Young, and a savage Tampa Bay defense
weren't the only factors in the decision. There was Bud Goode and
his computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always trends in football,'' Mariucci said this
week. ``The West Coast offense has lasted longer than most, but now
rush zones (zone blitzes) are prevalent, so some of the West Coast
thinking has been altered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The protections we've used in the past don't hold up against
zone blitzes, so the trend in the NFL is back toward the run. If
you can run it more than 30 times, you win 90 percent of your
games. That's a statistical fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud showed me that the next most important stat after points
scored is number of rushes plus completions. Rush 31 times and
throw 20 completions, you're number is 51. If your number is higher
than theirs, you win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incomplete passes are not good. It's much better to run three
times and punt than throw three incompletions and punt. You use up
a couple of minutes running as opposed to 15 or 18 seconds. That's
that much less time for a (Drew) Bledsoe or a (Brett) Favre to beat
you. It's like riding time in wrestling. It's so important to be on
top, to have possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s it was pass to set up the run for the 49ers and
other teams adopted it. It was not 3 yards and a cloud of dust. It
was finesse. But with the advent of the zone blitzes, expanded
coverages, and situational substitutions, today you're forced to
throw `hot' (to a receiver reading a blitz and breaking off a route
hopefully at the same time the quarterback expects him to) a lot
more than in the '80s. You don't want to do that. So we've had to
adjust and run more to control those blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a side of all of us on offense that would rather throw
the ball better than anyone else because there's a certain amount
of excitement and sophistication and glamour that comes with that,
but what's best for the team is controlling the clock, not setting
passing records. I'd like to rush 30, 31 times a game. If you get 3
1/2 to 4 yards a run you got your 115-120 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the last 10 or 20 Super Bowl teams, they all
had great defenses and darn good running games. Very few teams who
throw it almost every down get there. That (1984) Miami team with
Dan Marino may be the one exception. Generally, if you're throwing
that much you're behind, so while my personality is `let's wing it
around,' I feel have to be like water and take the shape of the
container I'm in. To be a good team in the NFL today, you've got to
be able to run.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What they were thinking
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T hat being the case, why did the Patriots let one of the best
backs in the NFL go to the division rival New York Jets? Why did
owner Bob Kraft, who has paid the (over) price time and again both
for his team and for his players, refuse to match Martin's $36
million free agent offer?
</P>
<P>
   ``This was in our best interest,'' Kraft said at the time he
announced the offer would not be matched. ``There's always another
running back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, as several analyses of recent running back
production showed Kraft before he made the decision. One pointed
out that of the eight most productive backs in NFL history after
three seasons, six averaged fewer yards per carry in their fourth
year. In other words, they had begun to slip, often because the
physical demands of the job had taken a toll, as Kraft feared might
have started to happen with Martin.
</P>
<P>
   That there is always an abundance of new running backs is also
clear. Four were drafted in the first round this year and that is
pretty much the norm. So you can always get a running back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RUNNING-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     09-04 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RUNNING-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... running back.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Miami has been trying to establish a running game since
Jimmy Johnson arrived in 1996 and has failed despite drafting four
running backs, including this year's first-rounder John Avery.
Considering Johnson is one of the best judges of talent in the
game, at a time when more and more teams are trying to run the ball
and searching for someone to do it, is there always another Martin
out there may be the more relevant question.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition season there didn't seem to be in Foxborough,
where No. 1 pick Robert Edwards was limping much of the summer and
The Runners Shaw (Sedrick and Harold) seldom got farther than their
height (2 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Juxtaposed with that slowdown is Martin's past production. He is
one of only four backs to gain 1,000 yards and catch 30 passes in
each of the last three seasons. Since 1995, roughly 80 percent of
Bledsoe's handoffs had gone to him. And since his arrival in the
NFL, Martin had been responsible for a greater percentage of his
team's rushing yards (79.2 percent) than anyone other than
Detroit's Barry Sanders (84.7).
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, coach Pete Carroll insists the Patriots will run
more than ever this year, Martin or no Martin, because Bud Goode's
stats prove it's the rushes that are important, not the average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, we're going to run the football,'' Carroll said.
``The running game is not a second thought this year. Zone pressure
has allowed defensive coaches to attack your pass offense more.
When you throw, you're exposing yourself to an array of pressures
today, so the run is called for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to create enough balance to keep defenses
base-oriented at least, so they aren't attacking you all the time.
As long as you're running the football, you're making them play it.
Curtis was a great player for us but even 2-yard runs can be
efficient plays if you're stubborn about running it. The way
defenses are presented today, you've got to play your running
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Martin, can a team newly committed to the run move the
ball with the efficiency he showed the past three seasons? The
Patriots have contended all along they can because young backs tend
to gain yardage and if Edwards and the Shaws can combine for
something near what Martin produced, they say everything will be
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but the fact is teams with a 100-yard rusher win 70
percent of the time and teams with a 300-yard passer win 35 percent
of the time. That's teams with a 100-yard rusher, not teams that
rush for 100 yards. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In search of go-to guy
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   S o while Goode says it is number of carries rather than average
per carry that is the true barometer of success, a team generally
needs one back it can count on to win consistently. All four teams
that played in the conference championships, for example, had
1,000-yard rushers and seven of the 12 playoff teams did as well.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Kansas City used the approach New England is
considering, having four backs rush for 350 yards or more but no
one for 600. That made the Chiefs only the sixth team in NFL
history to win a division title without a single back rushing for
more than 600 yards. On the upside, the last team to do it in a
five-team division was the 1986 Patriots, but that team was knocked
out in its first playoff game and didn't return to the postseason
for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   That trend seemed to apply across the board. According to STATS
Inc., only two teams using the Chiefs' rushing approach repeated as
a division champion and one, Dallas, added Tony Dorsett, who rushed
for 1,007 yards in his rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   While someone will replace Martinthis season, neither Edwards
nor Sedrick Shaw has shown he can do the things Martin did while he
was rushing for 3,799 yards and averaging 4 yards a carry. What is
worse is that history does not support the idea that they will.
</P>
<P>
   After Jim Nance rushed for more than 1,000 yards in 1966 and
'67, the Patriots did not have another 1,000-yard rusher for 10
years. After Sam Cunningham did it in 1977, the wait was six years.
And After John Stephens rumbled for 1,168 yards in 1988, it was
five years before the next 1,000-yard rusher appeared in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   So if one studies history, the picture of the year following the
loss of a 1,000-yard rusher is often bleak. In the past 25 years,
121 runners have rushed for 1,000 yards (including the same runners
only if they moved to a different team, thus Sanders would count
once not eight times, while John Riggins would count twice, with
the Jets and Redskins).
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 times did a replacement rush for 1,000 yards the year
after, with the Los Angeles Rams making a habit of it. In 1986,
Eric Dickerson broke the 1,000-yard mark. The next season, Charles
White did the same and a year later Greg Bell gained 1,000 in place
of White.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, a team that has done little right, actually has
immediately replaced a 1,000-yard rusher with another twice, in
1983-84 and 1995-96. Perhaps the greatest was replacing William
Andrews, who gained 1,000 three times in four years, with Gerald
Riggs, who did it three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But these are clearly the exceptions. If it as easy to replace a
back like Martin as the Patriots suggest, why did it take 28 years
to find a replacement for Nance, the only two-time 1,000-yard
rusher in Patriots history before Martin?
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight backs, who, like Martin, have rushed for 1,000
yards in each of their first three seasons (Dorsett, Sanders,
Dickerson, Andrews, Terrell Davis, Earl Campbell, John Brockington,
and Ottis Anderson), most took years, not months, to replace. While
the Rams didn't miss a beat after Dickerson's departure, and the
same was true in Atlanta when Andrews's knee injury finished him,
the other four left a hole their teams did not quickly fill.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, it was five years after Campbell before a back
rushed for 1,000 yards. The same was true in Dallas after Dorsett.
</P>
<P>
   The news was worse for the Cardinals, who had only one
1,000-yard rusher in the next 10 years after letting Anderson go
(to Parcells's Giants). And don't even ask what happened in Green
Bay after Brockington left because the Packers had just one
1,000-yard rusher in the next 20 years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best of intentions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F inding a running back is one thing. Finding a running back
like Curtis Martin is quite another. So what can the Patriots do
this season with Martin gone? According to Goode and the people who
listen to him, they have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the offseason, everyone says they want to run the ball
more,'' said Johnson. ``Once the season is over they study all the
statistics and invariably the teams who won the highest percentage
were the ones who ran the football. Then the next season starts and
some of those teams see they can't run and the easy thing is to
fall back and start throwing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the zone blitz has really put more of an emphasis on
running because you can't make a living now with three wide
receivers. The best way to hold them out of that is running the
football and there are hidden stats that come from doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can run, you play better defense. You have better
field position. You have less turnovers. I'm not a high-risk
offense man. That doesn't fit my style. Our defense and special
teams will give us field position and turnovers and the way to
exploit that is to run the ball. In the past we've said we'd run
and ended up with four wideouts. Not anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Dolphins plan to do then is run. Just like the Patriots
and everyone else, including the guru of the passing game, new New
England offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting an attitude about it,'' said Zampese, who when
he first took the job mentioned Martin as one reason he left
Dallas. ``There's no question defenses have caught up with passing
offenses in general. Primarily they've done it with blitzes and
linemen dropping off with zone dogs (blitzes).
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, you don't want to get into a pass rushing contest.
Nowadays you'll get your quarterback killed if all you do is throw,
so we do want to run it more. But most of your runs come in the
fourth quarter, when you have a lead. That's when your true ability
to run comes out. Otherwise, all you need is the perception that
you can run it and you will.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're not yet convinced, ask Giants quarterback Danny
Kanell. Earlier this week when he and his teammates arrived at
their practice facility, coach Jim Fassel had put a chart on the
locker room bulletin board. On it was a simple message:
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were 9-2-1 last year when they rushed for more than
100 yards. When they rushed for less than 100, they were 1-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see that and you realize how important it is in this
league,'' Kanell said. ``You have to be able to run the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The same will be true for the Curtis-less Patriots. Despite the
odds against them in the first year without their favorite Martin,
the Patriots know what Bud Goode knows.
</P>
<P>
   They run or they die.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
