<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HAPPY AS THEY FOLLOW ZENGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Zenga was the most demonstrative of players on the field
and polemical off the field during his professional goalkeeping
career. As a coach, Zenga is exacting and intense, but so far, he
is transmitting confidence and serenity to his team _ as he did
when he was a player.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has been coaching the Revolution for less than a week, and
the team appears to be responding to his direction. The Revolution
have outscored opponents, 4-1, in the last 135 minutes, including a
2-0 victory over the New York/New Jersey MetroStars Wednesday,
which kept them in Major League Soccer playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution defense remained poised, and the team retained
its overall organization against the MetroStars. They trail Miami
by 6 points with four games remaining _ against Columbus (Sept.
12), Tampa Bay (Sept. 19), at Chicago (Sept. 23), and the
MetroStars (Sept. 26) _ in the race for the fourth and final
Eastern Conference playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always changes things when you have a new coach,'' said
Edwin Gorter, who has returned to his starting midfield position.
``He arrived and he tried to find something positive. We knew we
weren't mathematically out of it, but we only had about a 10
percent chance. We were just playing for pride. We were fed up with
losing. And we scored first, which we hadn't been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution withstood early MetroStars assaults and took the
lead on Joe-Max Moore's 20-yard bending free kick off the underside
of the crossbar in the 31st minute. Gorter's goal in the 36th
minute gave the Revolution their first two-goal lead in the first
half since June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, 38, has not attended coaching courses. He played for
disciplinarians in Italy, but his uninhibited nature made him seem
anything but coaching material. His style is much different than
that of former Italy national team coach Arrigo Sacchi, who valued
his system of play above the players and had little patience for
personalities such as Roberto Baggio, GianLuca Vialli, and Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   The image Zenga is projecting as a coach is far from
stereotypical. He has donned a golf shirt in the Tampa heat, a
long-sleeved dress shirt in East Rutherford, N.J., both times with
a baseball cap worn backward.
</P>
<P>
   But his knowledge of the game is advanced far beyond anything
that can be generated in formal coaching courses. Certainly, Zenga
has defensive expertise, judging by his remarkable record with
Italy _ 39 shutouts and only four games in which he allowed more
than one goal in 58 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   And the Revolution players have responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter knows what he is talking about,'' defender Richard
Goulooze said. ``He has been a goalkeeper on the top defensive
teams in the world. Almost everything he says about defense is
right. Defending looks easy, but you are always reacting to the
other team's movements and you have to do it as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had looked hopeless, and as Walter said, we had no
personality on the field. All of a sudden, everyone can play. Our
outside players were staying with their runners, and that makes it
easier for everyone. We proved we are a good team. We weren't
panicking out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
