<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHERNOMYRDIN NOT ALONE, OPPOSITION PUSHES ALTERNATIVE PM
CANDIDATES
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-POLITICS-0905.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Communist party and other opposition Duma factions
have agreed to negotiations with the Kremlin, seeking to avoid
another confrontation with President Boris Yeltsin over the
creation of a new government. While the Communists agreed to seek a
compromise, they say they will continue to oppose Yeltsin's choice
for prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at Chernomyrdin and three figures who have emerged
as possible compromise candidates to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   VIKTOR CHERNOMYRDIN, 60, acting prime minister
</P>
<P>
   A Soviet-era bureaucrat who headed the natural gas monopoly
Gazprom, Chernomyrdin went on to serve as Yeltsin's prime minister
from December 1992 until March this year, when he was fired for
failing to fix the economy. Now he's back and struggling to form a
government amid economic turmoil. So far, he has failed to satisfy
the interests of the Communists, Russia's powerful tycoons and
Western leaders like President Clinton, who visited Moscow this
week urging Russia not to abandon democratic and free-market
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   YURI LUZHKOV, 62, mayor of Moscow and business tycoon
</P>
<P>
   The powerful boss of Moscow, who like Chernomyrdin has
aspirations to succeed Yeltsin as president. Luzhkov has emerged as
the leading alternative to Chernomyrdin. A nationalist who enjoys
strong popularity in Moscow, Luzhkov has distanced himself from the
Kremlin during the current crisis. Promotion to prime minister
would give him the nationwide visibility he needs to win the
presidency, but it also would expose him to intense criticism as he
inherits Russia's financial chaos.
</P>
<P>
   YEGOR STROYEV, 61, chairman of the Federation Council
</P>
<P>
   The lackluster head of Russia's upper house of parliament,
Stroyev largely has served as a go-between for the Kremlin and the
Duma. Opposition parties have promoted him as an alternative
candidate for prime minister because of his dispassionate
reputation, but others question whether he has the guile and
resourcefulness to succeed in the job. A Soviet-era economist, he
represents the interests of Russia's provinces, whose governors sit
on the federation council.
</P>
<P>
   YURI MASLYUKOV, 60, former trade and industry minister
</P>
<P>
   A Communist, Maslyukov was brought last month into the reformist
government of ex-prime minister Sergei Kiriyenko as a token in an
attempt to broaden political support for that short-lived
government. In Soviet times he was a director of Gosplan, the
mammoth state economic planning committee. He went on to become a
Duma member and has strong ties to some of Russia's largest
industrial firms. If Yeltsin were to choose a Communist as prime
minister, Maslyukov is considered the most likely candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
