<HEADER>
A9436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-04 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S GOVERNOR RIDES THE `WEDGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- At the Democratic National Convention of
1884, Edward Bragg of Wisconsin nominated Grover Cleveland for
president, saying of the delegates: ``They love him most for the
enemies he has made.'' As governor of New York, Cleveland made
enemies in Tammany Hall, a den of pariahs for ``reform'' Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Enemies are useful in politics. As governor of California, Pete
Wilson has made plenty, a roster of which would agitate any GOP
gathering: civil rights leaders, the California Teachers
Association, nearly the entire professoriat of the University of
California, and every liberal editorialist and columnist in the
Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   In the final hours of his last legislative session, the man they
call Pete ``Wedge Issue'' Wilson paused between signing and vetoing
bills to discuss his eight years here. He talks in an earnest,
lightly profane patois based on two formative experiences, Yale
University and the US Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dedicated liberals don't like me, largely because I have
been successful. Nothing excites enmity quite like succeeding,''
says the governor who sponsored ballot questions ending affirmative
action and cutting off aid to illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wedge issues are issues that liberals want to duck. It's `Oh,
you dirty guy, you're talking about this issue that I don't want to
talk about,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want some wedge issues? Slavery was a wedge issue. And
women's suffrage was a wedge issue. All these things that some
people don't want to talk about are wedge issues. And of course,
the worst thing in the world to do is to say that the emperor is,
in fact, buck-ass naked and say that preferences and quotas are
what they are, which is a form of racial discrimination practiced
against new victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson celebrates a wedge that separates opinion-molders from
other Californians. ``If I'm supposed to be this mean-spirited,
crabbed guy who is so hard-hearted, believe me, on an anecdotal
basis, travel with me,'' he suggests. ``The day doesn't go by that
people don't come up and say `Thank you for insisting that this
money be spent so that my kids can be in a class of 20 students.'
And the union fought me on that.''
</P>
<P>
   When California revived after the recession of the early 1990s,
Wilson's plan to improve schools clashed with the CTA, ``which has
become a very militant union, a trade union. God, I'd rather deal
with machinists. They admit they're a union.'' To reduce class
size, ``I was very heavy-handed, using the budget to get the
votes.'' This year, he used similar tactics, holding out for $3.6
billion ``of honest tax relief.'' Democrats in the Legislature
called it extortion. Wilson's reply: ``Too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa of Los Angeles and
Senate President John Burton of San Francisco did win a tax break
for low-income renters and even an increase for welfare recipients.
``There are some people who can't work. They can't,'' Wilson says.
</P>
<P>
   The man whose poll numbers have gyrated since 1990 enraged
Californians when he broke a promise not to run for president,
which he did poorly, quitting in 1995. Today, ``liberals are not
happy, but overall the results are pretty good. I mean, my
favorable to unfavorable now is very good.''
</P>
<P>
   In four months he'll be back in private life. ``I honestly don't
know what I'm going to do. I'm not being coy. I just can't answer
it,'' says the self-described ``policy wonk'' who'll probably run
for president again.
</P>
<P>
   Even in apolitical California, governors define their decades.
In the 1950s, Pat Brown was, as Wilson once called him, ``the
master builder.'' In the 1960s and 1970s, Ronald Reagan and Jerry
Brown left distinctive marks. Wilson reigned in the 1990s and is
unsure of his epitaph, but offers, ``If you're looking for a
consistent theme in a stylistic way, even my enemies have said:
`He's a tenacious son of a bitch, and he generally wins.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
