u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-     09-04 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS FACES ISSUES IN RETURN TO THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The operative word for CBS's $4 billion return to the NFL is
patience.
</P>
<P>
   The Tiffany network goes up against well-established
heavyweights in Fox and ESPN/ABC, and CBS Sports President Sean
McManus concedes as much. He is just asking for patience. And with
good reason.
</P>
<P>
   His ``NFL Today'' studio team consists of Jim Nantz, former 49er
Brent Jones, future Hall of Famer Marcus Allen, and former San
Francisco coach George Seifert. Surrounded by three rookie network
talents, the burden falls on Nantz. After a disappointing Winter
Olympics performance, it's unclear if Nantz can sway viewers from
Chris Berman or James Brown, the hosts of ESPN's and Fox's pregame
shows, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I will be scrutinized and picked apart,'' Nantz said
recently. ``I'm not afraid of that. I expect it. This is network
television. I just hope people give us a chance to grow together as
a team before judging us against the other shows.''
</P>
<P>
   As the symbol of CBS Sports, Nantz has other larger issues to
worry about. Some good, some bad.
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a moment the business side of CBS's return to the
NFL, and go with one basic assumption that not too many hardcore
football fans turn off a game based solely on the announcers. They
will turn down the volume, maybe, but turn the picture off? Never.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point? ``Monday Night Football.'' No one is complaining
that Frank Gifford will not work the Patriots game in Denver. The
game will still lure about a 750,000 viewers in Boston alone. That
doesn't mean Gifford is a bad guy. It's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS has assembled some of the best NFL play-by-play/analysts
in the country. Greg Gumbel and Phil Simms are solid; as are Verne
Lundquist and Randy Cross. Kevin Harlan and San Wyche will probably
have the most fun, while Gus Johnson, one of the best young
play-by-play men in the business, will shine with Steve Tasker, the
former Buffalo Bills All-Pro special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   A problem, however, is that the group of hardcore fans has
remained constant over the last three years. The numbers tell the
story.
</P>
<P>
   National ratings for the regular season have dropped from 12.9
in 1995 to 11.6 last season. During that same period, playoff games
have also dropped from 22.1 percent to 19.2. The Super Bowl, the
granddaddy of all programming, has even taken a hit, from 46
percent in 1995 to last year's 44.5. Each rating point is
equivalent to 980,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with fewer viewers, television executives, saddled with an
almost $18 billion NFL debt, are forced to ask advertisers to pay
more for the networks' astronomical television rights packages.
Many are balking.
</P>
<P>
   The networks were asking advertisers for as much as a 20 percent
increase; that didn't sit well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buyers are going to dig in,'' Tom DeCabia, senior vice
president at the Paul Shulman Co., told Broadcasting &AMP; Cable.
``Every client is telling every buyer out there that they overpaid
and that we are not going to fix their mistake. If that was what
they wanted to do, that was their business. But it is only worth X
amount to me. I love a Lexus, but I'm not going to pay $100,000 for
a $40,000 car.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts contend that while there are plenty of
companies that want to reach the young male demographic offered by
the NFL, few are going to pay more than an 8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Remember what P.T. Barnum said, ``There's a sucker is born every
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS sales president Joe Abruzzese told Broadcasting &AMP; Cable in
June that the network had sold nearly half its ad inventory at
between 15 and 20 percent increases.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that a third of those sales were by companies new
to either CBS's AFC games or the NFL. In addition to deals with
General Motors, Volkswagen, Anheuser-Busch, Honda, Staples, and
American Express, CBS said the new money comes from Southwest
Airlines and a $14 million-deal with NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   Even still, the chase for viewers, a perennial issue, is even
more pressing, largely because the networks, and particularly CBS,
is counting on its affiliates to pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame shows matter not only for programming but for
advertising revenue, nationally as well as locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be very satisfied if our show is as well-produced and
polished as Fox's was and ESPN's was in their first year,'' McManus
told reporters. ``We are starting at a disadvantage as the new guys
on the block.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
