<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OFFENSE, SAME DEFENSE FUEL PATRIOTS' HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The spin on Route 1 is that the Patriots
have a suitable replacement for Curtis Martin, and they've solved
the right cornerback spot.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably they were the team's two major problems when training
camp began at Bryant College back in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The spin is that the newly installed Ernie Zampese offense is
taking hold. A little more of this and a little bit of that, and
presto! _ the second-coming of the Super Bowl champion Dallas
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The spin may be accurate. Five exhibition games certainly helped
the perception that they might be on their way. But the Patriots'
play also indicated that they need to show more.
</P>
<P>
   A good team? Yes. A Super Bowl team? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team has more depth than last year's team,'' said
vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier. ``I think the
players we drafted have all stepped in and have been able to take
the duties we needed them to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The key for Grier, however, is that the players understand Pete
Carroll's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it for me,'' said Grier. ``The players understand Pete.
They know his system now. There's no more questioning of the
system. You have to understand that a lot of these players only
knew one way because they'd had only one coach in their
professional careers. Now they understand they can have success
with a new style and philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Five exhibition games didn't really answer the question of who
will replace Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Sedrick Shaw, the second-year back out of Iowa, is getting the
starting nod for the opener in Denver Monday night, but No. 1 pick
Robert Edwards (18th overall), who returned from the MASH unit in a
24-7 win over Philadelphia to run for 38 yards on 15 carries,
showed signs he may eventually work his way into the job.
</P>
<P>
   Despite averaging 3 yards per carry against Philadelphia, the
Patriots decided to commit to the running game. In the final two
exhibition games, the Patriots ran 84 times.
</P>
<P>
   The running game will have to be effective because if it isn't,
it'll all come down upon the shoulders of quarterback Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Having played under offensive coordinators Ray Perkins, Larry
Kennan, and Zampese (and three different quarterback coaches),
Bledsoe is now trying to adjust to his third offensive system.
</P>
<P>
   It took Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman two years to perfect the
system, but the scheme is similar to the one Bledsoe used at Walla
Walla (Wash.) High School with his father, Mac, who got the system
from Washington State head coach Mike Price _ who later coached
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Bledsoe was in a different style for the
first five years of his professional career. Now, he must go back
to his roots.
</P>
<P>
   While Bledsoe seemed to master the short stuff after five games,
he'll be looking for his first long ball Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll come,'' said Bledsoe, who threw his only touchdown pass
of the exhibition season Saturday against Philadelphia, a 3-yard
toss to Troy Brown. ``I'm not worried about it. I'd rather get
these bad throws out of my system now rather than when it's for
real.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reason the Patriots will be a playoff team and possibly
get back to the Super Bowl is their defense.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last year, it had become one of the best in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell created an exciting unit
that used its speed and gimmickry with blitzes to befuddle
opponents. The emphasis in the exhibition season was to shut down
the opposition using their base defense. And they did.
</P>
<P>
   Little by little, the Patriots will throw in some of their zone
blitzes in which they'll let their safeties or their linebackers
loose.
</P>
<P>
   And eventually they're hoping to see the real Tebucky Jones
surface.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were criticized for not taking North Carolina
defensive lineman Vonnie Holliday with the 22d pick in the first
round, but Carroll and Grier wanted a big corner who could cover
the Keyshawn Johnsons of the league. With their third-round pick,
the Patriots might have gotten a player who's every bit as good as
Holliday in Greg Spires from Florida State, who will start out
rushing the passer on third down.
</P>
<P>
   So it won't be Jones at right corner, yet. It will be Chris
Canty.
</P>
<P>
   Canty has decided to take things more seriously in terms of
conditioning and learning the position. He now has the complete
respect of his teammates and coaching staff, and he will get the
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I need to worry about the position anymore,''
said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Canty will be tested constantly because few will dare throw to
Ty Law's side. And with the blitz packages that the Patriots show,
their safeties and linebackers will often get to the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is basically together for the third straight year.
It should be one of the toughest defenses to run against with
middle linebacker Ted Johnson and excellent run-stoppers such as
emerging defensive tackle Chad Eaton, veteran defensive tackle
Henry Thomas, and defensive end Ferric Collons. It should also be
tough to pass with Chris Slade, Willie McGinest, Tedy Bruschi, and
now Spires all considered top-of-the-line pass rushers.
</P>
<P>
   If the running game remains effective and Bledsoe continues to
be a 3,500-4,000-yard passer, and if Canty, and eventually Jones,
plug that right corner spot, the Patriots appear to have an
excellent shot to win their division for a third straight season
and raise havoc in the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
