<SLUG> BC-HOMERUN-CHASE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE, SOSA MAKE BASEBALL A HOT COMMODITY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At the Going to the Game store, Mark McGwire's
St. Louis Cardinals jersey is moving faster than a baseball smacked
out of the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   At Copeland's Sports, Chicago Cubs hats like the kind worn by
the Cubs' Sammy Sosa are flying off the hat racks quicker than you
can say Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa have rekindled a national interest in
major-league baseball not seen since before the 1994 baseball
strike drove so many fans away. Their pursuit of Roger Maris'
single-season record of 61 home runs has rejuvenated baseball card
sales, game attendance, television ratings and baseball
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Associated Press poll showed that 46 percent of people
queried have had some level of increased interest in baseball
because of the attempts by McGwire and Sosa to surpass Maris' mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a baseball fan,'' said Gareth Steen, a student from
Dublin, Ireland, who works at Copeland's Sports. ``But it's very
interesting to watch the reaction to those two guys. The whole
country's watching.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire jerseys are the hottest-selling item at Going to the
Game, which specializes in sports merchandise. And while a few
Cardinals hats were still in supply, there were no Cubs headgear.
</P>
<P>
   ``His jersey was $65 _ and have been selling since the start of
the season. Then, suddenly, mysteriously, there was a price
change,'' sales clerk Brian Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The jersey now goes for $75.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire wears number 25 on his jersey, but he's No. 1 in the
hearts of collectors. As of Thursday, he led Sosa in the home-run
derby 59 to 56 and has been the season-long favorite to top Maris'
record.
</P>
<P>
   As he has inched toward the mark, McGwire's jersey is not the
only item that has gone up in price.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's 1985 Topps rookie card, which pictures him as a member
of the U.S. Olympic team, is a major focus of the home-run mania
that has taken the country by storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been flying, actually,'' said Darren Yamashita of
Dave's Dugout, a sports card and merchandise shop in Albany, Calif.
``We recently bumped them to $150 from $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire is the man around here. But a lot of people are
looking for Sosa cards, too. We never sold Sosa before the home-run
chase. The craze is not just Mark McGwire. People are buying cheap
Sosa cards.''
</P>
<P>
   And they're buying other players' baseball cards, too, Yamashita
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, baseball cards in general are doing very well
this year,'' he said. ``It's the best year since before the
strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Peters of MVP Baseball Cards in St. Ann, Mo. _ about 15
miles from McGwire's home park in St. Louis _ can attest to that.
</P>
<P>
   He said he fields 100 calls a day from people all over the
country asking about that McGwire rookie card, which he sells for
$175 to $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out of them,'' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since McGwire's been here over a year, I've sold 15. They've
been tough to get a hold of. No one wants to sell them. But there's
a lot of interest in Sammy Sosa, too, particularly the 1990 Leaf
card. It books at $25 but sells for $50 to $75. It's really
underpriced.''
</P>
<P>
   Even tougher to find are McGwire-autographed items. McGwire is a
reluctant signer and doesn't sell autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold an American League ball about four to five weeks ago
for $100,'' Peters said. ``I imagine now it would go for between
$150 to $200.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also is feeding America's baseball fever. The
Internet carries Cardinals radio broadcasts through the Cardinals'
Web site, www.stlcardinals.com, or at
broadcast.com/sports/baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' World Wide Web site links to a site that allows
viewers to watch a video of each of McGwire's homers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you clearly have one of the all-time greats in your
industry, the accomplishment does have a halo effect on all the
teams, even if he doesn't play for your team,'' said San Francisco
Giants Vice President Larry Baer. ``Michael Jordan's career was
good for basketball; good for everybody. What's happening with
McGwire and Sosa has captured the imagination of casual fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
