<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMARTEN UP, BUCKLE UP, ENJOY THE RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seems as if the Fourth of July fireworks have only sputtered out
and here it is Labor Day, the last hurrah of summer vacation. This
weekend, summer goes out with a bang.
</P>
<P>
   For some among us, that bang may be the sound of collision.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you've heard it all before, read it all to the point,
perhaps, of boredom _ wear your seat belts, don't drink and drive
etc., etc. Nag, nag, nag. Still, there are some out there who just
don't get it. I became painfully aware of that fact a couple of
days ago while watching a young woman race by in a car with two
kids standing up in the back peering out the rear window. Nice
view, maybe their last, if Mom has to smack the brakes and they go
flying toward her and the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for seat belts and child restraints is not a
government urge to curtail your freedom or impose restrictions on
your children; the reason is public safety. If you do not wear a
safety restraint in a moving automobile, you are not only at risk
yourself but a threat to someone else _ maybe me.
</P>
<P>
   In a sudden stop _ such as occurs when you plow into another car
_ the belt restrains you during deceleration, otherwise the car
would stop and you'd still be hurtling along at whatever speed.
Hurtling, that is, until you hit something _ the windshield, the
pavement, or perhaps a properly restrained person up front.
</P>
<P>
   Air bags are great, most of the time, but without belts they
don't help much, can be dangerous, directing your unrestrained body
into something unyielding. The belts position you for the bag to
save your face.
</P>
<P>
   The belt also restrains a driver when the car is going out of
control _ skidding, perhaps. Instead of merely hanging onto the
steering wheel to keep from being tossed about, you can actually
attempt corrective action and perhaps succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other things to remember this weekend:
</P>
<P>
   _ That so-called ``package shelf'' under the back window of your
car isn't; the moron who thought that up ought to be sent to
Singapore for proper caning. Things piled on the ``shelf'' cut down
on rear visibilty and, in a collision or sudden stop, are missiles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting in a dither because the car in front of you is driven
by a mope isn't likely to speed up the mope _ but it may raise your
blood pressure. Tailgating, honking, and repeated flashing of
lights will only serve to increase your risk, not his speed. If you
control your rage, you are less likely to fall victim to someone
else's rage.
</P>
<P>
   _ As a driver, exercise some discipline within the car. Bring
stuff to amuse the kiddies, and be firm about disturbing behavior _
sibling quarrels, yelling, etc. That goes for adults, too; yells of
any sort can sound like a dire warning and trigger the wrong
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember the Golden Rule _ that ``do unto others'' stuff is
the real McCoy. Empower yourself by giving the other driver a
break, surrendering the right of way when appropriate or letting
somebody into the line of traffic. Friendly behavior is contagious.
</P>
<P>
   _ On long trips, stop at least once an hour and get out of the
car. Sitting for hours on end behind the wheel increases fatigue,
dulls your senses and, we now know, increases the risk of stroke.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep your eyes moving. Check way ahead, check the rear and
side mirrors frequently. Get your passengers involved; note out
loud what you see ahead and what you're doing about it _ they may
join in and point out hazards or traffic changes that you somehow
are missing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alcohol will not sharpen your wits, keen your senses, or
improve your reaction time. It makes you talk funny and act stupid.
</P>
<P>
   _ Relying solely on your brakes to slow the car will result in
excessive brake wear and in some cars on a warm day may induce
brake fade _ as in the brakes fade away _ with unpleasant results.
Your car's transmission isn't there just for acceleration. Use it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reserve your time in the car for driving _ reading, eating,
drinking, or primping while underway will not help your driving,
but it will make those with whom you share the road nervous.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are stopped by a law enforcement officer, roll down the
window, keep your hands in plain view on the steering wheel, and
tell your passengers to keep their hands visible and their mouths
closed. Be polite; it's your holiday, but he or she is working and
may not be having a great day. Your good nature now could cut down
on your grief later.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep your brain engaged at all times. In short, smarten up,
lighten up, buckle up, and enjoy the ride.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
