<HEADLINE>
HOW THE AFC STACKS UP 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 EAST  
 
 1. New England Patriots
<TEXT>
<P>
   Head coach:  &LR; Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1997 record:  &LR; 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New faces:  &LR; RB Robert Edwards, RB Harold Shaw, FB Tony Carter,
FB Chris Floyd, DE Greg Spires, CB Tebucky Jones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook: &LR;  Class of the division. Deepest roster. Franchise's
best defensive unit in years, perhaps ever. Might lead league in
creating turnovers with solid defensive blitz package that will be
very effective against most opponents. QB Drew Bledsoe will have to
carry the offense. Will look to establish the pass to set up the
run, which will be limited. Special teams improved. Kicking game
excellent with punter Tom Tupa and kicker Adam Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Starting offense:  &LR; QB Bledsoe; RB Sedrick Shaw; FB Carter; WRs
Terry Glenn and Shawn Jefferson; TE Ben Coates; LT Bruce Armstrong;
LG Max Lane; C Dave Wohlabaugh; RG Todd Rucci; RT Zefross Moss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Starting defense:  &LR; LE Ferric Collons; LT Chad Eaton; RT Henry
Thomas; RE Willie McGinest; LLB Todd Collins; MLB Ted Johnson; RLB
Chris Slade; LCB Ty Law; RCB Chris Canty; FS Willie Clay; SS Lawyer
Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Special teams:  &LR; K Vinatieri; P Tupa; KR Derrick Cullors; PR
Troy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. Miami Dolphins
</P>
<P>
   Head coach:  &LR; Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1997 record:  &LR; 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New faces:  &LR; G Kevin Donnalley, RB John Avery, CB Patrick
Surtain, DL Kenny Mixon, FS Brock Marion, LB Robert Jones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook:  &LR; J.J. says this is the best team of his three years in
Miami. Defense much improved, with additions from the draft. Like
the Patriots, Miami has a suspect running game. Johnson brought in
a new offensive coordinator and changed the entire approach to the
run. Key is still QB Dan Marino and keeping him healthy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Starting offense:  &LR; QB Marino; RB Karim Abdul-Jabbar; FB Stanley
Pritchett; WRs Charles Jordan and O.J. McDuffie; TE Troy Drayton;
LT Richmond Webb; LG Mark Dixon; C Tim Ruddy; RG Donnalley; RT
James Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Starting defense:  &LR; LE Mixon; LT Tim Bowens; RT Daryl Gardener;
RE Jason Taylor; LLB Jones; MLB Zach Thomas; RLB Derrick Rodgers;
LCB Terrell Buckley; RCB Sam Madison; FS Marion; SS Shawn Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Special teams:  &LR; K Olindo Mare; P Klaus Wilmsmeyer; KR Avery; PR
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. New York Jets
</P>
<P>
   Head coach:  &LR; Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1997 record:  &LR; 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New faces:  &LR; RB Curtis Martin, FB Keith Byars, G Todd Burger, C
Kevin Maewae, LB Bryan Cox, T Jason Fabini, DE Anthony Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook:  &LR; Jets are still thin talentwise. Parcells thinks his
team will run the ball better than a year ago with the addition of
Martin and some new offensive linemen. Special teams will be
outstanding, as they were a year ago. Defense is the problem.
Linebackers are good, but the rest of the unit isn't. Glenn Foley
will start at QB.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Starting offense:  &LR; QB Foley; RB Martin; FB Jerald Sowell; WRs
Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet; TE Kyle Brady; LT Jumbo
Elliott; LG Burger; C Maewae; RG Matt O'Dwyer; RT Fabini.
