<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SWISSAIR CRASH &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-RDP (Undated) _ Developments in the aftermath of the
Swissair crash: More bodies recovered; the search for clues;
families of victims arrive on a flight from JFK to help identify
the dead.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-INQUIRY (Undated) _ Developments in the investigation of
the crash. By Matthew L. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-VICTIMS (Undated) _ More on the victims of the crash. By
Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-DITCH (Undated) _ Despite the demonstrations by flight
attendants on how to inflate a life vest, and instructional videos
on how passengers should operate the life vests, the chances of a
pilot successfully ditching a stricken aircraft in the water are
pretty slim, experts say. By Andrew C. Revkin. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-SWISSAIR (Undated) _ A look at Swissair, its history,
managers and safety record.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-PLANE (Washington) _ What is known about the type of plane
that crashed, the MD11. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ The second vote in parliament on the
nomination of Chernomyrdin as prime minister is put off until
Monday, giving both sides time for maneuver; Chernomyrdin unveils
an economic plan. Other developments. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ Looking at acting Prime Minister
Chernomyrdin's economic plan. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CLINTON (Dublin) _ Developments on Clinton's meetings in
Ireland. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MOOD (Dublin) _ A Reporter's Notebook on the moods of
the president during his trip to Russia and Ireland. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, see other Clinton stories under Washington.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-MISSILE (Washington) _ North Korea says its launching on
Monday of a two-stage rocket had been to carry a satellite into
orbit, not to test a missile. It denounces Japan and other
countries for jumping to the conclusion that it was launching a new
class of missile. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-TRIBUNAL (Arusha, Tanzania) _ A U.N. tribunal Friday
sentenced a former prime minister of Rwanda to life in prison for
his part in the 1994 genocide there, despite his agreement to plead
guilty and to testify against other high-ranking officials. By
James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
