<P>
   CORPUS-CHRISTI-TOURISM (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ After a
decades-long dependence on natural gas and oil, Corpus Christi,
Texas, was sent reeling when energy prices tumbled during the
1980s. So it decided to spend millions of dollars to build a
tourism industry. A handful of other cities have fashioned
successful tourism industries in recent years through a combination
of vision and good luck, including Branson, Mo., now a country
music capital; Tunica, Miss., which opened casinos; and Sedona,
Ariz., whose rocks and crystals lure hordes of tourists seeking
spiritual growth or physical healing. But in a manner befitting its
status as a socially conservative city, Corpus Christi has gone
about its pursuit of tourists in a methodical manner, spurning
casino gambling and hiring consultants to help point the way. By
Edwin McDowell.
</P>
