<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-EDWARDS-SHAW-BOS &LR;      09-04 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EDWARDS-SHAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MARTIN GONE, PRESSURE ON EDWARDS, SHAW, TO MAKE GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ On Robert Edwards's first carry last
Saturday night against the Eagles, the back took a handoff from
Drew Bledsoe and _ a nanosecond later _ was hammered for a 3-yard
loss. A lineman had missed his block and it was Edwards who paid
for the sin.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, it was Edwards who circled out of the
backfield and caught a pass _ on his fingertips _ from Bledsoe,
even though two Eagles were lined up and ready to hammer him.
Edwards got hammered, indeed, but he held onto the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He held onto that pass,'' said New England fullback Tony
Carter. ``That's what you look for in a rookie _ that he's going to
be hard-nosed.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went, as so it will go this season with the Patriots and
their running backs. Hit or miss, hit a hole when a hole is there,
or get hammered when a block is missed.
</P>
<P>
   On one play in that first quarter, Edwards slithered off left
tackle but Carter missed his lead block and Edwards was stopped for
no gain. On another play, Edwards went right, made a nifty cut, and
ran inside a seam for a 9-yard gain. Hit or miss. Miss (a block)
and be hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just won't know that until we're done with the season,''
said Bledsoe, when asked how much the Patriots will miss Curtis
Martin in 1998. ``It just depends on how well we do up front and
how well Sedrick (Shaw) and Robert (Edwards) do carrying the
load.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so intertwined, just as Bledsoe's reply was intertwined.
Whether the line blocks well will determine if Shaw and Edwards run
well.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it was last season with Curtis Martin, and the year
before, and the year before that. Even when Martin was gaining his
thousands of yards, the Patriots' ground game still was not
consistent. Few outside the locker room at Foxboro Stadium would
argue that the New England running game was dependable, that it
absolutely could be counted on to get those 2 yards on third and 2
and that 1 yard on fourth and 1. Remember first and goal against
the Packers last season?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to finish last season without Curtis so we knew (what
it took from the team),'' said Bledsoe. ``The good thing was, we
went into this year knowing we didn't have him. So we were able to
make a contingency plan and get other guys involved right from the
start. Whereas last year you're counting on one guy and then he
goes down and then all of a sudden you're scrambling. This year we
know what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, Edwards has potential. The rookie has a similar body
and style to another running back from Georgia _ yes, the Broncos'
Terrell Davis _ and some even see a hint of another powerful
Georgia running back, Herschel Walker. Edwards is tough, has hands,
and may be a good running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played well (last Saturday),'' said Carter, who
conceded he kept a close eye on the rookie because he may be
blocking for him all season. ``He hit the ball into the holes and
that's what you're looking for. He looked like he's going to stick
it up into the hole and get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   What Carter likes about Edwards ``is that he's strong and he
makes guys miss. He runs with power and he used good leverage, and
those are all things that show he's going to be a good running
back. He's got speed, too, so he's got the big-play potential, but
he's also a guy who can hit it up between the tackles when he has
to go inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as impressive as his style, Carter said, was Edwards's
mental state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty cool out there. That's what I'm saying. I'm sure
his heart was beating pretty good the first couple of plays, but
then he settled down and realized it's the same game no matter
where you play it, high school or college or here.''
</P>
<P>
   For center Dave Wohlabaugh and the rest of the line, it will be
a learning experience as the backs learn about the line and the
line learns about the backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a real extreme contrast in backs, like if you go
from Sedrick Shaw, who's running downhill and he's hitting the line
hard or Curtis Martin, who was making cuts in the backfield, then
it's different. But now we have two backs who are really similar;
they're a little different here and there, but I don't think it's a
big difference in their styles.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Shaw and Edwards, he went on, ``seem to hit the holes
really hard, and then try to make something happen after that. They
seem similar. That's what you hope for, anyway; hit the hole and
hope to get 4 (yards), and then if you get more than that, it's a
bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth _ at least for the early part of the season _ the
expectations for the New England running game are minimal. Just let
the running game be good enough so that there is merely a semblance
of balance between running and passing, so defenses can't load up
against the Patriots' passing game, their strength, and ignore a
weak running game. Just be good enough to keep defenses slightly
honest. Anything more, at least early on, would be a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always get better,'' said Wohlabaugh, when asked to
reply to the many critics of the New England running game. ``You're
always trying to get better but, at the same time, we've gotten
progressively better every game. That's what preseason really is
for. But we've made strides while knowing that we can get better.
We at least have established a benchmark to go from.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the questions about the Patriots' running game is the
fact that the defense is so good that, except when New England is
playing the very best teams, it will have the luxury of bringing
along its running game. The Patriots will not be behind, 21-0, in
the first half, so they seldom will have to abandon the running
game completely just to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the exhibition season, as coach Pete Carroll conceded,
there was concern because the Patriots could neither pass nor run.
Drew Bledsoe and his receivers were learning yet another new
offensive system and against the 49ers and Vikings, the learning
process was ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first couple of (exhibition) games, it didn't look
like we would be able to hit anybody in the throwing game,'' said
Carroll. ``But Drew's into it now. It took a few weeks to get
going, and I feel much better about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Patriot fans should take the long view about this
offense and this running game. The offense is in much the same
position as the defense was at the start of last season _ learning
a new system _ and the Patriot defense didn't finally jell until
December.
</P>
<P>
   New England has a workmanlike back in Shaw and a rookie with
potential in Edwards, and expectations among Patriot fans and
around the NFL are so low that the most likely scenario is this:
the Patriot running game will be a surprise, possibly even
surprisingly good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
