<SLUG> BC-ENJOYING-DISNEY-THE-ORGANIZED-WAY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING TIME AND MONEY AT WALT DISNEY WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Walt Disney World in Orlando is the grand prize of American
tourism. But a vacation there does not come cheaply.
 &HT;    Adding up the cost of admission tickets, parking, eating and a
couple of T-shirts, the average family of four can spend $360 per
day in the land of Mickey and Minnie. And that's before factoring
in the cost of hotel accommodation, car rental and air fares.
 &HT;    ``It can be a very expensive vacation,'' says Bob Sehlinger, the
author of ``The Unofficial Guide to Walt Disney World 1998,''
(Macmillan, 1998; $15.95), a jampacked 742-page bible for
Disney-goers.
 &HT;    ``We're geared for travelers who really want to get their
money's worth,'' he says. ``My average readers are very organized
and button-down. But they're intimidated by the destination. It's
twice as big as Manhattan, with four major theme parks and three
minor ones. They want to be in control before they set foot in the
place.''
 &HT;    Sehlinger, who's been authoring this guide since 1985, has
become an expert on planning a vacation in Walt Disney World. He
extols the merits of traveling during low season, which runs from
September to mid-December, except Thanksgiving.
 &HT;    He ranks all the hotels _ both inside and outside ``the World,''
as it's known. Accommodations outside the park may lack Disney's
magic, he contends, but they almost always give better value.
 &HT;    Sehlinger rates Disney's full-service restaurants. He gives
strategies for those with small children, honeymooners, couples and
single travelers. And he gives specific itineraries for touring
each park within Walt Disney World.
 &HT;    ``Our research methodology is very unique,'' Sehlinger says of
himself and his staff. ``Most of us come from business backgrounds
and about half are MBAs. We use a scientific approach and do
sophisticated survey work. And we've worked on queuing theory.
That's another way of saying that there's got to be a better way to
go through this place than standing in the sun all day.''
 &HT;    Sehlinger's guide is a statistical marvel. He's figured out down
to the minute how to beat the crowds with early admission, how to
cope if a line proves to be too long and when and where to eat.
 &HT;    He's also figured out, based on the number of people standing in
line at a given attraction, how long a wait will be. At ```Honey, I
Shrunk the Kids' Movie Set Adventure Playground,'' a line of 100
people means a 20-minute wait.
 &HT;    At ``New York Street Backlot,'' 100 people in line signifies
almost no wait, because this attraction can process people faster.
 &HT;    ``We had a platoon of researchers with stopwatches who hung out
inconspicuously and monitored line lengths,'' Sehlinger explains.
``We produced flow charts of how the traffic was moving, how it
dispersed and what it did during the course of the day.''
 &HT;    ``We had a test group and a control group who started at the
same time,'' he adds. ``The control group had never been to the
park before and toured according to their own plan. Their only
instruction was to see as much as was humanly possible in a single
day.''
 &HT;    When Sehlinger compared groups, he discovered that on a day when
the park has an average to high attendance of, say, 40,000 people,
the group using his plan at the Magic Kingdom spent three hours and
10 minutes less time standing in line than the other group.
 &HT;    ``People feel a lot of pressure to maximize their time,''
Sehlinger says. ``In some cases, they're almost obsessive about
squeezing value out of their vacation.''
 &HT;    While conceding that having and using such a rigorous plan is
not as necessary in low season, Sehlinger says, ``The bottom line
is that the place is large and overwhelming and Disney is
hyperorganized. If you go, you have to have a plan. If you don't,
whatever spontaneity you have is going to be lost standing in a
line.''
 &HT;    A visit to Disney World with the family is often not a relaxing
vacation. Sehlinger notes that many people tell him they need a
vacation after their vacation to recover.
 &HT;    ``It's important to get your butt out of there during the hot,
crowded part of the day,'' he advises. ``Take a nap, swim, eat.
People think that they have to see a theme park from opening to
closing, and they hit the wall after two or three days. They're
just flat wiped out and not having much fun.''
 &HT;    But for all of Sehlinger's organizing, there are the naysayers _
those who contend that such planning and strategizing are the very
antithesis of a vacation.
 &HT;    Sehlinger admits there are the ``type Bs.''
 &HT;    ``They stop and enjoy the architecture and people-watch,'' he
says. ``They draw the line, no pun intended, at standing in a queue
for hours and hours. That's how my sister goes. She never uses a
plan and she loves the atmosphere. Being there is good enough for
her.''
 &HT;    But for the readers who write to him ``with a certain amount of
rebellion and glee when they circumvent regimentation,''
Sehlinger's book is probably the Disney-goer's best friend.
 ---- 
