<HEADER>
A9490 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MARTIN-2TAKES-BOS     09-04 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARTIN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET MARTIN COPES WITH NOISE OF THE CITY _ AND HIS COACH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ He always thought there were too many sirens
screeching through the air and echoing off miles and miles of
pavement. Too many busy people, transmitting nothing but attitude
as they walked too fast on the sidewalks. Too many angry faces
behind him in traffic, peering over steering wheels and leaning on
horns because he ... because he ... well, he wasn't sure what he
had done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But he remembers the time he was in his car in Manhattan waiting
for a red light to turn green, which is what any decent driver
would do. Except the guy behind him didn't understand why he wasn't
moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stopped at a red light,'' Curtis Martin says, ``and
there's this beeping at me to go through it. I'm like, `It's too
busy, too ``rushy'' over here; they don't even stop for red
lights.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was a couple years ago, long before the running back's
paychecks began to say something that he never expected: New York
Jets. Martin used to hate New York. He is a peaceful man, so much
so that he doesn't even watch football when he isn't playing it.
Ask him about his most memorable plays and he'll tell you about a
great one that they draw up each night 'round about Broadway. It's
called ``Beauty and the Beast.'' He tells you that ``the animation
is incredible; it's my favorite. It's between that and `The Lion
King.'''
</P>
<P>
   A cynic could say that Martin, the former Patriot, had a $36
million reason to come here and be screamed at in traffic. But that
would be ignoring Martin's demeanor as well as the fact that the
Patriots offered him a $20 million contract in March. No, Martin
did not come here to be yelled at by an accountant from Queens or a
small-business owner from the Bronx. He came here anticipating
that, when he runs through the traffic of linemen and linebackers
on NFL fields, he would once again hear the familiar shouts of a
New Jersey loudmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me to be a north-south runner, taught me to hit the
hole, to take what you can get and don't always try to make
everybody miss,'' Martin says of the man who, you get the feeling,
could hold his own in a Road Rage Debate. ``He told me to run
through people, break arm tackles, and don't get tackled by one
man. Just a lot of different things that he instilled in me. When
I'm going on the field sometimes I can hear his voice saying,
`Curtis', cursing at me or whatever and saying, `Do this! Do that!'
A lot of times it just rings; his voice rings in the back of my
mind when I'm out there running sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   And when contract time came in New England last winter and
spring, Bill Parcells rang up Martin's agent, Eugene Parker, and
said he wanted the quiet man from western Pennsylvania to play in
noisy New York City. Or so Martin thought. New York was such a blur
to him that he hadn't even considered that 40 minutes away from the
city lies a mellow community near the Jets' training and practice
facilities. Martin lives five minutes away from Hofstra University.
Most of the time, it's quiet. The noise? He can deal with that. He
recently went back to Manhattan to see the energetic ``Bring In Da
Noise, Bring In Da Funk'' and to have dinner at a restaurant owned
by pop singer Puff Daddy. So there's always enough noise. And when
he's at work, he can always count on the noise brought by that loud
Jersey guy, Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he thinks of it, ``I'm really enjoying New York now.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odd couple reunion
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's funny, isn't it, that these men would like each other so?
Parcells knows the history of running backs, the mannerisms of
running backs, and the psyche of running backs. The only running
backs Martin knew were Walter Payton and Tony Dorsett. The only
thing he knew about Parcells before he met him in 1995 was that,
``I used to play with his New York Giants on those old Nintendo
games when I was a kid. The defense was always dominating on that
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin wasn't even a football fan growing up in Pittsburgh. The
only reason he liked running outside as a youngster was the
enjoyment he got from ``juking'' his friends and taunting, ``You
can't catch me'' in games of ``Tag.'' One time he couldn't juke
like he wanted and a persistent little girl chasing him caused him
to lose his balance in the rain and bang his noggin on the
concrete. He earned a cut over an eye for that move. That's far
from a classic running back story. You think the gruff Parcells was
hard on Terry Glenn, whom he tried to insult by calling him
``she''? What would he have said if he heard that Martin story?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not a real big football fan,'' Martin says. ``I
watch a lot of tapes and films for my job. But I'm not big on
sitting down and watching other teams play. I'm not into stats and
all that. I wasn't a fan of too many other sports, either. When I
was younger, I was just into ... I think I was a fan of women.
Girls. You know?''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as a teenager. When you want to dress nicely and all
that, going through those stages. I was just a little knucklehead.
Thankfully, I have changed my ways from back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one of his closest friends now is a woman. Her name is
Toni Braxton. She's a famous singer. But, Martin reminds, ``She's
not going to be blocking for me on Sunday (against the 49ers).''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Parcells gushed about the great Earl Campbell
saying, ``Now, there was a man among boys.'' And: ``You give me one
guy and let me coach him; that's the guy; I loved him.'' And:
``Some of these guys now, you tackle them three times they're out
for a month. That's the truth.'' The coach breathes football, often
researching the game's factoids in his spare time. Parcells has
researched so much that he knows there is no formula to being a
great running back. So if he has a guy who cringes at noise, loves
``Beauty and the Beast'' and reads Bibles more than playbooks, it's
no problem. As long as that man is capable of rushing for 3,799
yards and 32 touchdowns in only three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at that position,'' Parcells said of running back,
``it is by far the least predictable because there is no prototype.
It's just results. Some guys can do it and some guys can't do it.
Who is the prototype running back? I don't think you can say
physiologically this guy is the guy. There are some: the Gayle
Sayerses, the O.J. Simpsons. But then there are Tony Dorsetts and
Barry Sanderses and Jim Browns. All shapes and sizes of guys who
have been successful at that position. There is just some innate
ability to run the ball in traffic; some innate instinct that a lot
of them have and most of them don't have. When you see a player
that has it, it's really fairly obvious to you.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MARTIN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     09-04 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARTIN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 HEMPSTEAD, N.Y.: ... obvious to you.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martin is just under 6 feet and has been the same weight, 205
pounds, since his junior year in college. Earlier this week he
planned to go home and eat a huge meal featuring green beans,
collard greens, potato salad, yams, fish, and either banana pudding
or peach cobbler. After all that, he knows he won't be able to gain
a pound. In many ways, he doesn't fit the part of the punishing
runner. But his coach is smart enough to know it doesn't make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically like a guy who, what I would call, has a Delco
look; built to last. Know what I mean?'' Parcells said. ``I like
those kind of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin doesn't look that way. Neither does another slightly
built runner Parcells mentioned while speaking of his favorite
runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at him and say, `This guy's going to play?','' the
coach said of former Raider and Chief Marcus Allen. ``I remember,
it was in 1982 in Tampa. We're down there at the Combine looking at
players: Terry Kinard, Darrell Green, Richard Dent. I remember the
whole group of guys ... You tell me 15 years later (Allen's) still
going to be playing? Any scout who tells you they knew that is
hallucinating. No one knew. You just look at him you say, ``This
guy is high cut, he's going to take a lot of hits, he's slender ...
He could just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin can just do it, too. The Patriots can tell you about
that, but maybe not as candidly as they should. The statistics that
Martin was never into tell you that he averaged 4 yards a carry
during his Patriots career. What the stats don't tell you is that
he was a constant threat to run the field. The Patriots don't have
anyone like that now. Parcells does. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strictly business
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My contract had been an issue for two or three years prior to
me coming here, so uh, when that time came around, I just said,
`I'm going to pray about it. If I'm to be here, I'll be here. If
I'm not, I'll be elsewhere,''' Martin is saying.
</P>
<P>
   He knows New Englanders are interested in his story. He knows
many of them are asking themselves, ``Why New York?'' Many of them
don't even have an inexplicable horn-blowing-at-red-light story to
explain their dislike of New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I just didn't imagine playing anywhere else but
New England. I thought it was the team I would play for the rest of
my life,'' he says. ``Parcells, he was the only other coach I would
consider playing for.''
</P>
<P>
   But why leave New England? And what of the stories coming out of
Foxborough, Mass.? Stories of the Patriots not being able to talk
to you personally when they needed to?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had left things to my agent by that point,'' Martin says.
``It was already very late in the game. I was praying about it and
always believed someway, somehow things would work out because, you
know, my faith is in God. It wasn't the factor of money or anything
like that. I mean, I played there for three years making basically
the minimum and performed at a fair level. I never conditioned my
play to my salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the situation here came up, my agent said, `Curt, I want
you to chill out and relax. You don't need to talk to anyone right
now. Just play the background and I'm going to work on a few
things.' I have nothing against anyone. We were just in the middle
of handling business.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Pete Carroll or Bobby Grier or Robert Kraft?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' he says. ``I hope they don't feel that way, either.
Sometimes change is a good thing. Change is a part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   And his former teammates?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm close to a lot of people. Jimmy Hitchcock was my roommate,
but he's gone now. Sam Gash was my boy, also. Ty Law, Lawyer
(Milloy), Willie McGinest, Chris Slade, all of them; they're all my
boys. Shawn Jefferson, Terry Glenn, Drew (Bledsoe). They're all
cool. I miss those guys. We operated as a team, a family. We were
building a family.''
</P>
<P>
   So, maybe it will be weird playing against them next month at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' he says, ``it won't be weird; it will be fun. Like when
Parcells came down last year and we faced him, it was like playing
against your brother. You want to go out and take it to a whole,
other level.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Source of inspiration
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, Martin will get a chance to do just that. After a
one-year break, he will be back with Parcells. The coach promises
that Martin will not run the ball 30 times per game, although
Martin says he wants to touch the ball as often as possible. Guess
who put that hunger in him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it started when I had something like six carries for 4
yards against Denver (in '95),'' Martin says, smiling now. ``I
didn't get the first down on a fourth-and-1, and I think he was mad
at me. He sat me on the bench the next game and I was there
thinking, `I can't sit on the bench. That's just not me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself that if I got a chance again, I wasn't going to
lose yards. I knew I would have to get those fourth-and-1s, even
though (Steve) Atwater popped me pretty good to keep from getting
it. But it was miserable sitting on the bench. I think Parcells
knew it would tick me off and inspire me. He knew what I was
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended that season with five consecutive 100-yard games. He
learned how to run like Parcells wanted. He also maintained that
ability he had when he juked eager children in Pittsburgh. Now he
just wants to be hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mentality is, `I can deal with a hit, can you?' That's how
I approach defenders. They're bigger than me. It's their job to hit
me. But I feel like I'm going to make them miss. And if they don't,
I want to hurt them as much as they hurt me. It's war.''
</P>
<P>
   You look at the man as he says this, strong words coming from
his mouth like soft music. The two don't fit. But neither do New
York and Martin. Or Parcells and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   Parcells says great running backs have all told him one thing to
tell blockers. ``They tell me, `If you can just keep (the defender)
there and let me get running, then I'll deal with what's the
traffic pattern,''' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   And we already know Martin can handle himself in traffic, on the
field or in the City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
