<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DAVIS-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      09-04 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DAVIS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER WILL AGAIN HITCH UP ITS WAGON AND RIDE DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER -- The exhibition against Green Bay was done, a lively
game for an exhibition, and now Terrell Davis was at his locker,
saying strange words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still go some kinks in our offense,'' said the Broncos'
running back as the media gathered. ``We've got things we need to
iron out. Our offense did some good things but we're still not the
team we need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it been only seven months? Only seven months ago, Terrell
Davis had punished the Green Bay Packers. Only seven months ago,
the Broncos' offensive line had left Gilbert Brown a mere panting
blob of a defensive lineman and had sent Reggie White to the
sidelines and to safety from the relentless surges of Denver right
tackle Tony Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But that was seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't run the ball that much in this game,'' said Davis
after the exhibition, saying more strange words, because if the
Denver Broncos don't run the ball much, they will not be back in
the Super Bowl. John Elway or no John Elway. ``I thought we'd run
the ball more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but worry not until there is reason because Davis _ after
his strange words _ spoke the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're saving me for the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be the strangest sensation of all for Davis, watching
and waiting and sitting and waiting and waiting some more for his
number to be called. Davis, after all, is a running back, a very
good running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting itchy,'' he said. ``I'm a running back and ...
just by nature I like to go out there and run the ball. When you
don't run the ball, sometimes you sit back and you just can't wait
for the regular season to start because then I know I'm going to be
running the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   A few lockers away, tight end Shannon Sharpe was taking this all
in. Sharpe thought back three years ``when this low-round running
back came to camp that nobody had ever heard of,'' but ``I knew
real soon that Terrell was a runner. I can know why he's itchy.
Terrell just loves to run ball and he gets frustrated when he's not
running.''
</P>
<P>
   And so does the Broncos' offense. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Details, details
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A book signing was held last week in Denver, and it was an
event. Terrell Davis's autobiography ``TD: Dreams in Motion,'' was
being released in conjunction with the opening of the season and
Broncos fans, as usual, could not get enough of their team or
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis not only is the reason Denver escaped its big-game loser's
image but also was responsible for one of pro football's greatest
ironies _ for 13 years John Elway had strived mightily to win a
Super Bowl and, in San Diego last January, Elway finally reached
the pinnacle. But it was primarily Davis, and not Elway, who won a
Super Bowl for John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   So every detail of that Super Bowl win remains huge in Denver.
Every detail.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis forgot to take medication for his migraine
headaches before the Super Bowl? Huge. Terrell Davis's migraine was
so severe at the end of the first quarter of the Super Bowl that he
couldn't see? Huge.
</P>
<P>
   Literally. He couldn't see the Packers, he couldn't see the
holes he was supposed to run through, he couldn't see the crowd, he
couldn't see the scoreboard? Huge. Terrell Davis there on the
sidelines at Qualcomm Stadium, sucking oxygen, all the while
praying to God, ``Let there be light?'' Huge. Terrell Davis's sight
gradually returning in the locker room at halftime? Huge.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Packers nor the millions watching the game knew the
details. But what became even better known in the second half was
how huge a running back Terrell Davis is, but even moreso how huge
his presence is to his team. He was physical, he was bruising, he
was slithering, he was banging, he was sliding, he was punching, he
was immense.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was his nightmare _ a migraine at the Super Bowl.
The second half was his and the Rocky Mountains' dream _ a Super
Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to Terrell,'' said Sharpe. ``No two ways about
it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the zone
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has a running back and his offensive line been so in
synch as were Davis and the Denver line in the fourth quarter of
the Super Bowl. Jones, the right tackle that day but now Denver's
left tackle, said he had never experienced such a feeling in
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in synch is when you're in a stadium as loud as that and
the guy next to you can't hear you and you can't hear the guy next
to you,'' he said, ``but you can feel the way he's thinking and he
can feel what you're thinking. It's like going into a place
blindfolded, but you can see what the person next to you is seeing,
and feel what he feels ... without talking.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so intangible, so ephemeral, so mystical, almost, ``because
a lot of lines have been together as long as we've been, and a lot
of backs have been running behind those lines, and still you won't
see what we were like in that fourth quarter of the Super Bowl,''
said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   So much of it can be credited ``to our work habits, because when
we go on the field _ every day, mind you _ everything is done at
full speed. Everything we do in practice, technique-wise, is done
at full speed. All the time ... and the coaches are on our butts
when it's not. And when the game comes, the game is the most easy
thing for us. We see that we're so much quicker than our opponents.
We beat our opponents to the punch all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   All well and good, but such offensive line cohesion is wasted if
the running back is a plodder, a dancer, a horizontal guy who goes
more for the sidelines than upfield.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, said Jones, ``what we have going for us is Terrell
Davis. When an offensive lineman is coming to Denver, the first
thing he's told is that No. 7 (Elway) don't get hit _ if No. 7 get
hit, you don't have a job _ so that's always first on our mind,
protecting No. 7. Then we go on to the next thing, which is to let
Terrell have fun, to let Terrell do his thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the thing about Terrell,'' he continued, ``is that Terrell
is the kind of back that runs downhill. Terrell always come at you.
Terrell always put pressure on the defense, and, eventually,
Terrell knows that the defense is going to crack. And then Terrell
is going to break a long one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones smiled again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9500 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DAVIS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     09-04 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DAVIS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 DENVER: ... a long one.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Terrell isn't one of them running backs that's going to shake
and bake and jiggle. Terrell's going to come right at you.
Terrell's going to put pressure on you to make a tackle to stop him
from making a big run.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Nalen, the Broncos' center from Foxborough, Mass., and
Boston College, said Denver's offensive line ``doesn't have the
most talented bunch of guys, that's for sure. But we're an
aggressive offensive line and we stick up for each other. That and
we know we've got to pass the ball if we're going to run the ball
and we've got to run the ball if we're going to pass the ball and
so we know we've got to pass block and we've got to run block.''
</P>
<P>
   Nalen paused.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... and, of course, we've got Terrell back there behind us
running the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has it come together for an offensive line better than it
did in last January's Super Bowl for the Broncos, especially in the
final quarter. Quarterbacks win Super Bowls, defenses save Super
Bowls, running backs run to glory in Super Bowls, but seldom, if
ever, can it be said that an offensive line is the reason a team
wins the Super Bowl. But Denver's offensive line _ with Davis
exploding through the holes _ won the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play-calling was such that we were really able to wear out
Green Bay,'' said Nalen. ``And that was all through the first three
quarters, setting us up for that last quarter. The thing is we had
a lot of good plays that really tired them out; you know, a lot of
running plays. We wore them down and then we were able to feed off
how they looked.''
</P>
<P>
   Even seven months later, Nalen recalls ``I had the most fun
playing in that game ... especially in that fourth quarter, when we
had destiny in our own hands. We came through.''
</P>
<P>
   And Terrell Davis came through the holes.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked, said Nalen, ``is how well our wide receivers block,
guys like Ed (McCaffrey) and Rod (Smith). All our receivers are
coached to block on running plays and that helps a lot because once
Terrell breaks through the first few yards, there's virtually no
one behind there because the receivers are blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   But the thing ``that you can't forget,'' said Nalen, ``is that
Terrell makes all of us look pretty good.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Period of adjustment
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Denver offensive line of 1998 is in flux _ three players
in new positions _ and Davis, for his part, said ``it's going to
take a while'' before the unit gels.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I go back and watch the films, I'm sure that I'm
going to learn that (new right tackle) Harry Swayne does this a
little different or that (new right guard) Dan Neil does a little
something else when he's in there,'' said Davis. ``It's probably
going to take a game or two to figure that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played with the same five guys the last three years,''
Davis continued. ``So this will be a different line for me to get
used to.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line _ of all football positions _ is more than a
sum of its parts. The very good lines, as Denver's was last season,
have a true chemistry that allows each member to know instinctively
what the player to his right or left will be doing once the chaos
begins after the ball is snapped. The best offensive lines exude
teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm thinking is that after a few games that we'll both be
learning who's doing what and what's working,'' said Davis. ``I'm
thinking that after we come back and watch (films of) a few games,
and I see the techniques they're using, and they see what I'm
doing, that we can adjust to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry _ the real Chemistry _ can be learned from study.
Chemistry _ the football chemistry _ seldom can be learned merely
from study. It's obvious when it's there, but football coaches are
like alchemists when it comes to developing chemistry on their
teams, or at certain positions. It's more a mystery than a science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starting offense (in the exhibition against Green Bay)
wasn't very good,'' said coach Mike Shanahan. ``The starting unit
only had four first downs (in a half). But take my word, we'll be
more consistent when we'll be going against live bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan now is faced with tweaking his beakers so that
chemistry can return to the offensive line, now that Gary Zimmerman
has retired from left tackle for good and two newcomers are on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big question for me,'' said the coach. ``I can brag and
say we've done some good things in pass protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches can mix equal parts talent, practice, study, and film
work, add a touch of success and chemistry can happen _ as was
evident last season with the Broncos' offensive line. But many
times the chemistry doesn't take, so observers will likely be able
to decide if the 1998 Broncos will be like the 1997 Broncos simply
by focusing on the chemistry _ or lack thereof _ of the offensive
line. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New season, same expectations
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe said Davis is no different from last season, even if
Davis now has $57 million coming to him as the result of a new
contract. ``I had him down to my house in Atlanta for a week over
the summer and I gave him my car for the week,'' said Sharpe, ``and
everything was cool ... same old Terrell. He hasn't changed at all.
And I got my car back at the end of the week, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Any dents?
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe laughed. ``No dents ... and even if there was, I wasn't
worried because I know Terrell's got all that money now and he
could buy me another car.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if Davis is the same running back he was last season,
there is apprehension in Denver because new pieces have been added
to the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put '97 out of my mind already,'' said Davis. ``I'm the
person who looks forward to challenges. I don't ever try to look
back and say, `Let me try and do the same thing I did last year.'
If I do the little things like block, take care of my assignment,
and run as hard as I can and protect the ball, then everything else
will come around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
