<P>
   IMPEACH-HYDE _ WASHINGTON _ Henry Hyde still vividly remembers
the most frightening day in his life. In 1945, he was a 20-year-old
Navy ensign skippering an amphibious boat in the South China Sea.
The boat was tied up to a grounded freighter when a typhoon struck
and ``the sky and the ocean turned solid green. The waves, man,
they were 25 feet high. I was slapping against the freighter like
this _ slap, slap, slap,'' he says, his hand hitting the desk. You
thought you were going to die any minute. My knees turned to
water.'' ``Are we going to make it?'' his worried crew asked.
``Sure, sure, we'll be fine,'' Hyde reassuringly replied. Now, half
a century later, he appears equally calm in turbulent political
waters. As chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, the
Chicago-area Republican is poised to take center stage in the most
politically charged event since Watergate _ weighing evidence in a
possible impeachment proceeding against President Clinton.
(Morehouse, Cox News Service 1800).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEGAL _ WASHINGTON _ The authors of the U.S.
Constitution wrote that impeachment _ a formal accusation that a
public official is unfit to serve in office _ should result from
``treason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.'' No one
quibbles over treason and bribery. But what did the framers mean by
high crimes and misdemeanors? (Morehouse, Cox News Service 650).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ History shows that impeachment
is more of a political than a legal process. (Shepard, Cox News
Service 650).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-PROCESS _ If historical precedents are followed,
potential impeachment proceedings would go like this. (Cox News
Service 430).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: All have moved for release Saturday, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-BATES _ WASHINGTON _ A profile of scholar Stephen Bates,
tapped to write Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report to
Congress. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move Friday for release Saturday, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEMOCRATS _ WASHINGTON _ Democrats hope that President
Clinton's reputation won't hurt his efforts to raise $18 million in
big contributions at ``unity events'' in August through October.
They're depending on him to help offset similar efforts by the
Republican party. The chief House GOP fund-raiser, Rep. John Linder
of Georgia, says the GOP has already raised more than $17 millio
toward its goal of $37 million in big gifts during the same period.
Both parties are getting a lot of those funds from favor-seekers
giving the kind of ``soft-money'' contributions that would be
outlawed under a campaign finance bill that Sens. McCain and
Feingold promise to bring to the Senate floor for a vote between
Monday Sept. 7 and Friday Sept. 11. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Thursday for release Saturday, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   FAIRCLOTH-SIERRA _ The Sierra Club wraps up its two-week issue
ad campaign against Sen. Lauch Faircloth (R-N.C.) asserting that it
moved the environment to the forefront of the Senate race there.
But the ad also had some unintended consequences. The Raleigh News
&AMP; Observer, which has long criticized Faircloth on the environment,
rose to his defense. We talk to voters across eastern Carolina,
including Faircloth's hometown of Clinton,
</P>
<P>
   to find out what they are saying about Faircloth, the Sierra
Club and the environment. (Foskett, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-BITTENBINDER _ More on Suzanne Bittenbinder of Boynton
Beach, Fla., who died on Swissair 111. She was with USAir and then
switched to United as a flight attendant eight years ago. She flew
international flights to South America and was fluent in
Portuguese, having spent some time in Brazil, a former co-worker
said. (Mnookin, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-SPRINGER _ More on Judith and Lloyd Springer, realtors
from Boca Raton, Fla., who also died on the flight. They were avid
members of the Boca Garden club. Family is releasing a statement
after lunch. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-MALLIN _ More on Gilda and Ralph Mallin of Boca Raton,
another couple who died on Swissair 111. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post).
PHOTOS POSSIBLE.
</P>
<P>
   BEEKILLER _ FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ Florida beekeepers believe
they've found a chemical to control the South African beetle, which
threatened to wipe out hives. Have to get EPA approval to use it,
could be available early 1999. An agricultural specialist says this
quick discovery is ``beating the odds like winning the lottery with
only one ticket. And if EPA doesn't deliver the prize, they'll have
to bury me.'' (Reeder, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MEDALS-LOST _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Retired Vietnam veteran
Willard Roy didn't think shiny new replacement medals would feel
the same as the original war medals he lost in a burlgary two
months ago, but they did. On Friday, Port St. Lucie police and a
medal collector from Lake Worth, Fla., presented Roy with the
Purple Heart, Bronze Star, presidential unit citation and four
other medals he earned during the war. The collector, also a
veteran, had all seven original-issue medals in his cabinets and
handed them over at no cost. (Lane, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-SIGNS _ ATLANTA _ Political candidates spend thousands
of dollars on signs, and without fail, they complain that many of
them are stolen or torn down before the election. Now a Georgia
state legislator has been caught on camera taking down an
opponent's sign. The representative was photographed with a sign of
his opponent's in hand before the last runoff. A supporter of the
opponent followed him around, snapping photos. (Torpy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ If Russia had a government, it would
be flat broke. Before being shown the door, the prior government
defaulted on $40 billion in short-term debt _ money that was mostly
sucked out of the country with its connivance by the ruling
oligarchy. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ President Bill Clinton has returned from what we
may fairly, alas, call the Pathetic Summit to a worsening sink of
foreign problems that steamy, seamy Monicamess leaves him little
authority to deal with. The president either must find a way to put
this thing behind him or let Al Gore take command. (Teepen, Cox
News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ What Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have done
for baseball this year, in addition to filling stadiums that
otherwise would be near empty, is return the sport to its raw
basic: pitcher throws ball, batter slams the bejabbers out of it.
For too many recent years, the actual playing of the game has been
influenced by other elements, particularly pitching terminology I
cannot comprehend, or by calls by umpires that are beyond our
recognition. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   CSIBLEY-COLUMN _ It's not that I wanted a glass of sweet tea. I
really prefer it half-and-half, and most restaurants gladly mix it
for you. But I had to go to the Sweet Tea Sip-Off in Mobile, Ala.
because my friend Jay Greland, the Mobile Register columnist, and
the newspaper itself organized and sponsored it. (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 9/3.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _WACO, Texas _ Home runs are the most exciting
part of baseball. That's my opinion. If that shows my ignorance of
the game, then so be it. Mickey Mantle made me this way. (Nethaway,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ Last fall a South Georgia friend, knowing of my
taste for old-fashioned eating, sent us a bottle of prime cane
syrup. It languished unopened on a back shelf in the pantry for
almost a year. (Minter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Growing up in Piqua, Becky Howe learned little
girls didn't speak up, didn't rock the boat. You'd think, with all
this practice, at age 50, she'd be adept at holding her peace. Not
so. Miami County's unlikely new heroine has been speaking her mind
since June 9, when she received notice that Anthem was planning to
cancel her coverage and that of some 20,000 Ohio residents using
its Medicare HMO, known as Senior Advantage. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   LOW-GAS _ As the last big driving weekend of the summer
approaches, gas prices across the U.S. are approaching their lowest
level ever when adjusted for inflation. Local prices are at or near
record lows as well. (Bennett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PRATT-FLORIDA _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Pratt &AMP; Whitney will close
its Turbo Power and Marine Systems subsidiary in Riviera Beach,
Florida, leaving as many as 52 employees without jobs, the company
said recently. (Pounds, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DELL-STOCK _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As Dell Computer Corp. approached
its latest stock split, the stock's price belies the wild ride it
has taken in recent weeks. When Dell's board authorized the 2-for-1
split on Aug. 18, the share price was $109.56 1/4. In the interim,
the stock soared to $128.62 1/2 on Aug. 26 and fell to $100 on
August 31. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   DOWNSIZING-CONDO When Jill Vantosh, an Atlanta interior
designer, downsized froma house to a condo, she seized an
opportunity to create a streamlined interior that emphasizes a few
of her favorite things _ including an unconventional material.
Vantosh stripped the second-floor unit of a 1950s red-brick
building to its concrete bones, from floor to ceiling , then
extended the material to the kitchen countertops. The result is a
clean, industrial look made warm and inviting by juxtaposing the
unpainted beams and chrome furnishings with oak floors and rich
cabinetry. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DOWNSIZING-TIPS _ Tips on downsizing. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   LAWN-FIGHT _ TEQUESTA, Fla. _ A Tequesta couple that has battled
village officials for almost a decade over their landscaping was
cited again this week for violating village codes. Hattie and Bill
Siegel were cited for excessive accumulation of plant material
because their yard is overgrown and untended, village officials
said. The Siegels, who have lived in their house on Dover Road for
three decades, have chosen to landscape their back and front yards
with native plants and other shrubs, trees and flowers that require
little water to survive. (Scharnhorst, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD_ Jewelry by its very name connotes precious
metals and stones, but it has come to mean virtually any sort of
personal adornment, and you'd be surprised, perhaps, at how many
woodworkers are making jewelry, and how striking so much of it can
be. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SWU-EXPANDS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ When Southwestern University
unveils its new campus center next month, the white limestone
building will mark one of the final steps in a decade-long push to
upgrade facilities. It's all part of Leadership 2000, the
university's $75 million campaign that includes scholarship funds
and $42 million in new facilities. (Coleman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   PAX-ADS _ PAX TV won the lottery this week. Not the state's $6
million Lotto prize, but an advertising contract for the Florida
Lottery. Because of better-than-expected Nielsen ratings that PAX
TV has generated since its launch Monday, local advertisers have
taken note. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
