<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-BATES05-COX     09-04 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-BATES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    LAWYERLY AUTHOR TO WRITE STARR REPORT
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To write the investigative report to Congress that
the world is waiting to read, Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr has
turned to a soft-spoken literary lawyer who shares his smalltown
Texas roots.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the hard-bitten, career prosecutors who make up most of
the team that has investigated President Clinton for four years,
Stephen Bates was recruited as much for his talents as a scholarly
wordsmith as for his legal skills as a Harvard-educated attorney.
The author of several non-fiction books and an editor of the
``Wilson Quarterly,'' a serious cultural journal, Bates is hard at
work on a massive document that is expected to include explicit
details about Clinton's sexual affair with Monica Lewinsky in
making a case for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very well qualified to write the report,'' said Lynn Chu,
a New York literary agent who represents Bates, as well as Starr
and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga. ``He's a terrific lawyer and
a really good writer.''
</P>
<P>
   At 40, Bates is about a decade younger than his boss, but they
have similar backgrounds. While Starr grew up in the tiny Texas
town of Vernon, Bates was reared in Pecos, a dusty agricultural
community of 12,000 souls about 200 miles east of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what propelled his son from the West Texas prairie to the
nation's capital, Bob Bates declared ``sheer talent.'' But that's
about all the friendly fertilizer dealer would allow. His son has
asked his family not to talk to reporters, the elder Bates
explained, lest they unwittingly provide ammunition to the ``White
House attack dogs'' eager to discredit Starr's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a low-profile type anyway,'' Bob Bates said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Stephen Bates did not return phone calls or reply to
e-mail seeking information for this story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very soft-spoken. Middle of the road politically. Really
smart,'' said Chu. ``He's not going to make any mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The prose about Clinton will likely stretch 300 pages or more
and will probably be presented to the House of Representatives
within weeks. Along with charges of perjury and obstruction of
justice, it is expected to include embarrassing details of
Clinton's sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised address to the nation, Clinton maintained he has
been ``legally accurate'' in denying a sexual relationship with the
25-year-old former White House intern. So prosecutors aim to show
that activities in a hideaway off the Oval Office meet the
definition of sex outlined in Clinton's deposition in the separate
Paula Jones sexual harassment suit. Using Lewinsky's testimony
about specific sex acts, Starr's team will try to prove Clinton
committed perjury in the deposition and perhaps later when
testifying before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Bates and other members of Starr's team are expected to use
lawyerly language to tone down this tawdry tale.
</P>
<P>
   The writing has been underway for months. Bates began working in
the Office of the Independent Counsel in 1995. He is a graduate of
Harvard College and Harvard Law School, but has made his mark more
as an author than as an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   His 1993 book, ``Battleground,'' told the story of a
fundamentalist Christian mother's crusade to shield her children
from schoolbooks that she said promoted satanism and evolution. The
case grew into the so-called Scopes II trial in East Tennessee and
attracted publicity minded lawyers from national advocacy groups
like the conservative Concerned Women for America and the liberal
People for the American Way.
</P>
<P>
   Legal Times credited Bates with a ``beautifully researched and
meticulously balanced account of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   His other books include ``If No News, Send Rumors: Anecdotes of
American Journalism,'' ``The Media and Congress'' and ``The Spot:
The Rise of Political Advertising on Television.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, he has also been a prolific provider of
magazine articles on an assortment of subjects. He has
</P>
<P>
   written for publications ranging from The National Journal to TV
Guide and Playboy on topics varying from the Constitution to
cyberspace. Last year, however, Bates and Starr struck out when
they tried to interest publishers in a jointly written, scholarly
book on the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Although Time magazine reported that Bates considers himself a
``lapsed Episcopalian,'' he grew up in a Bible Belt town where
Baptists fill the most pews on Sundays. Pecos is known for its
irrigated fields of cantaloupes and claims to be the ``Home of the
World's First Rodeo.'' The region's best known citizen, the
mythical cowboy Pecos Bill, rode a cyclone to his final glory and
is commemorated in a downtown museum that also features a replica
of Judge Roy Bean's saloon. Pecos is a town where a bookish boy
might take a backseat to the high school football players in their
letter jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was different...almost like a nerd. Some people gave him
a hard time,'' recalled Cookie Cannon, who along with Bates, was
among the 200 members of the Pecos High School Class of 1976. ``He
was a memorable character ...extremely intelligent. But he didn't
seem to care about grades all that much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve had a sister named Suzanne, but called Suky, who is the
same age as my younger sister,'' she said. And the Bates family was
well off, living ``on what we called Silk Stocking Road at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Cannon said she and Bates worked on
the annual staff and played in the high school band. ``He did
literary stuff. He was very smart,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not arrive at Harvard as an urban sophisticate,'' said
Abigail Thernstrom, who taught Bates in a freshman political
science seminar on constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Stephen for over 20 years,'' she said. ``He was a
wonderful student. He's a gentleman out of the Old School. He's a
very strong writer with a very nuanced voice. There's not a
strident bone in him. He's not an ideologue.''
</P>
<P>
   Thernstrom and her husband, Stephan,(CQ) are the authors of the
book, ``America in Black and White: One Nation Indivisible,'' which
criticizes granting preferences based on race or sex. She had a
televised run-in with Clinton during a town hall meeting on race in
Akron, Ohio, in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a very good conversation with the president at that
time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thernstrom has remained friends with Bates over the decades and
praises his talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a gorgeous writer,'' she said. ``Politically, he's very
careful. He sees all sides of everything. ...Judge Starr has a
prize.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from law school, Bates was a clerk for U.S.
Appeals Court Judge James Buckley in Washington and has been a
fellow at several think tanks, including the American Enterprise
Institute, the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars and
the Annenberg Washington Center.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in suburban Silver Spring, Md., with his wife, Polly,
and their daughter, Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
