<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CLINTON _ DUBLIN, Ireland _ President Clinton turned
today from the turmoil in Northern Ireland to the Irish Republic's
thriving economy, holding it up as the prize of peace. ``I hope
that success will whet your appetite for working together,'' the
president said. Ireland, with the highest economic growth rate of
any country in Europe, is a ``truly astonishing'' model for other
nations, Clinton said at a reception for Ireland's business and
political leaders at the Royal College of Surgeons. Irish Prime
Minister Bertie Ahern, in turn, credited Clinton and his role in
brokering the Good Friday peace accord with holding out to Northern
Ireland the same promise of prosperity. (Roughton, Cox News
Service). EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS _ MOSCOW _ Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin offered up his economic crisis plan Friday, saying he
would establish an ``economic dictatorship,'' in a bid to gain
opposition support for his confirmation. The State Duma postponed a
planned vote Friday to allow negotiations over the weekend.
Although Chernomyrdin's crisi plan would supposedly strengthen the
battered ruble, it was slow to address the market reforms that
President Clinton made tanatmount to Russia receiving Western aid.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOX-0905 _ MOSCOW _ Information on the three candidates
being offered up by the Communists as alternatives to Viktor
Chernomyrdin and the three other candidates for prime minister.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   With RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-$ADV06 _ MOSCOW _ As politicians dither
and the Russian economy crumbles, one man seems clearly aware of
his role as a Moscow power broker. Boris Berezovsky is one of the
wealthiest men in Russia, and among the closest to the Kremlin
inner circle that surrounds President Boris Yeltsin. He is believed
to have engineered the re-appearance of Viktor Chernomyrdin, and
publicly stated this week that Yeltsin should resign if a strong
government cannot be formed soon. A look at Berezovsky and the
other so-called oligarchs, who many believe are Russia's real
rulers. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-IRAQ-$ADV05 _ KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait Billboards in this
modern, rebuilt capital warn the people of this oil-rich nation not
to forget their POWs -- the more than 600 thought to be held in
Iraq. A few bombed-out buildings downtown still stand like
incongruous war memorials amid the gleaming towers of the sterile
city. And every Kuwaiti has a tale of their life under or flight
from Iraqi occupation. Kuwait's citizens are keenly aware that
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein still rules and blusters just beyond
the border of their two countries, posing a constant threat. And,
they closely followed recent reports that the United States is
allegedly changing its strategy for keeping Hussein in check. But
they take comfort in the 3,500 U.S. troops out in the deserts
protecting their cities. Also, many in Kuwait -- both the 740,000
Kuwaiti citizens and their 1.1 million foreign workers -- are just
tired of the annual Saddam-inspired crises. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton for the first time
says ``I'm very sorry'' about his affair with Monica Lewinsky, we
watch for signs of whether the apology will temper the rising
criticism of Clinton by his Democratic allies. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MORAL _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman's statements
that the president has no private life and has a duty to stand as a
moral exemplar for the nation carry profound implications for
public service. If it is accepted by voters, the standard could
reshape the next crop of candidates for president _ and perhaps for
other high positions such as a member of Congress. (Malone, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   STARR-BATES _ WASHINGTON _ A profile of scholar Stephen Bates,
tapped to write Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report to
Congress. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move Friday for release Saturday, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEMOCRATS _ WASHINGTON _ Democrats hope that President
Clinton's reputation won't hurt his efforts to raise $18 million in
big contributions at ``unity events'' in August through October.
They're depending on him to help offset similar efforts by the
Republican party. The chief House GOP fund-raiser, Rep. John Linder
of Georgia, says the GOP has already raised more than $17 millio
toward its goal of $37 million in big gifts during the same period.
Both parties are getting a lot of those funds from favor-seekers
giving the kind of ``soft-money'' contributions that would be
outlawed under a campaign finance bill that Sens. McCain and
Feingold promise to bring to the Senate floor for a vote between
Monday Sept. 7 and Friday Sept. 11. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Thursday for release Saturday, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   FAIRCLOTH-SIERRA _ The Sierra Club wraps up its two-week issue
ad campaign against Sen. Lauch Faircloth (R-N.C.) asserting that it
moved the environment to the forefront of the Senate race there.
But the ad also had some unintended consequences. The Raleigh News
&AMP; Observer, which has long criticized Faircloth on the environment,
rose to his defense. We talk to voters across eastern Carolina,
including Faircloth's hometown of Clinton,
</P>
<P>
   to find out what they are saying about Faircloth, the Sierra
Club and the environment. (Foskett, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-BITTENBINDER _ More on Suzanne Bittenbinder of Boynton
Beach, Fla., who died on Swissair 111. She was with USAir and then
switched to United as a flight attendant eight years ago. She flew
international flights to South America and was fluent in
Portuguese, having spent some time in Brazil, a former co-worker
said. (Mnookin, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-SPRINGER _ More on Judith and Lloyd Springer, realtors
from Boca Raton, Fla., who also died on the flight. They were avid
members of the Boca Garden club. Family is releasing a statement
after lunch. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-MALLIN _ More on Gilda and Ralph Mallin of Boca Raton,
another couple who died on Swissair 111. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post).
PHOTOS POSSIBLE.
</P>
<P>
   BEEKILLER _ FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ Florida beekeepers believe
they've found a chemical to control the South African beetle, which
threatened to wipe out hives. Have to get EPA approval to use it,
could be available early 1999. An agricultural specialist says this
quick discovery is ``beating the odds like winning the lottery with
only one ticket. And if EPA doesn't deliver the prize, they'll have
to bury me.'' (Reeder, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MEDALS-LOST _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Retired Vietnam veteran
Willard Roy didn't think shiny new replacement medals would feel
the same as the original war medals he lost in a burlgary two
months ago, but they did. On Friday, Port St. Lucie police and a
medal collector from Lake Worth, Fla., presented Roy with the
Purple Heart, Bronze Star, presidential unit citation and four
other medals he earned during the war. The collector, also a
veteran, had all seven original-issue medals in his cabinets and
handed them over at no cost. (Lane, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-SIGNS _ ATLANTA _ Political candidates spend thousands
of dollars on signs, and without fail, they complain that many of
them are stolen or torn down before the election. Now a Georgia
state legislator has been caught on camera taking down an
opponent's sign. The representative was photographed with a sign of
his opponent's in hand before the last runoff. A supporter of the
opponent followed him around, snapping photos. (Torpy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
