<SLUG> BC-MANSON-FOLLOWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED MANSON DISCIPLE ARRESTED ON WEAPON CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MALCOLM GLOVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An apparent disciple of cult leader Charles
Manson was arrested for possession of a dagger as he waited near
the home of a wealthy San Francisco man whose name appeared on the
cult's hit list 23 years ago, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Shackelford, 42, was arrested Thursday as he sat in
his car parked in the Pacific Heights driveway of George Jewett's
multimillion-dollar house. Officer Stephen Paulsen of the San
Francisco police was on routine patrol when he spotted a blue 1989
Ford Mustang parked in Jewett's driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a recent rash of burglaries in the area, Paulsen
parked nearby and kept the car under observation. While waiting, he
ran a check on the car and learned that it belonged to Shackelford,
who had a record of prior arrests for weapons possession.
</P>
<P>
   When Paulsen and other officers walked up to the car, they
spotted a gold-trim handled dagger with a 17-inch blade sharpened
on both sides lying on the passenger seat, a police report said.
</P>
<P>
   The officers also found a picture of Manson inside the car. When
asked why he had the knife, Shackelford told the officers it was
for protection.
</P>
<P>
   He also reportedly said that he was waiting for his girlfriend
who lived there.
</P>
<P>
   When the officers contacted Jewett, the owner of the house, he
denied that anyone by the name that Shackelford had given lived
there.
</P>
<P>
   When Jewett overheard the officers question Shackelford about
Manson's picture, he told them he was on a list of businessmen who
were targeted to be killed in 1975 by Manson's followers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Jewett, great-grandson of pulp, paper and lumber
tycoon Frederick Weyerhaeuser, was an executive with Potlach
Forests Inc. and very active in San Francisco's art and culture
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Manson, one of the nation's most notorious criminals, was
convicted in 1971 of the first-degree murders of seven people in
1969, including actress Sharon Tate. He is serving a life sentence
and last year was denied parole for the ninth time.
</P>
<P>
   Shackelford was booked on suspicion of possession of a dangerous
weapon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
