<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-MOVEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BLACKS PREPARE FOR RALLIES IN NEW YORK, ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Deonte-Lamont Kincaid, 11, is on his way to
Atlanta for a couple of new experiences: his first airplane ride
and the first time he has stood amid a large gathering of other
young people for a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid plans to attend Saturday's scheduled Million Youth
Movement, where he will assemble with young blacks trying to tackle
the problems that affect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a million youth together doing positive stuff,
talking to each other without fighting,'' Kincaid said.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid's father, Ivory Morton, said his son was more apt to see
young people in his San Francisco neighborhood caught up in
trouble. Morton, who attended the Million Man March in October
1995, wanted his son to experience something similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living here in the community ... he doesn't have much
opportunity to see positive things going on,'' Morton said. ``He'll
see young men hanging out, womanizing, getting into drugs. (The
march) is a chance to see something positive on a large scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the Million Man March and the Million Woman March in
October 1997, young blacks have helped organized two marches for
the Labor Day weekend _ the Million Youth Movement in Atlanta and
the Million Youth March in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The New York march, organized by attorney Malik Zulu Shabazz and
former Nation of Islam official Khallid Abdul Muhammad, has
received the most attention, focusing on the organizers' legal
fight with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the right to hold the march
in Harlem. Giuliani pegged the event as a ``hate'' rally, pointing
to Muhammad's penchant for incendiary rhetoric and vitriolic
attacks on Jews.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Shabazz and Muhammad won a U.S. Court of Appeals
decision allowing them to go ahead with a scaled-down version of
the march in Harlem. Reports say 50,000 are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   While the New York march carries a black nationalist agenda that
aims to address demands for reparations for slavery and black
economic self-sufficiency, the Atlanta march focuses more on
personal and spiritual development, as well as increasing political
and community involvement among young people.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Dennis Rogers, an activist leading a national
voter-registration campaign targeting young blacks, the Atlanta
march will include four days of meetings and conferences, running
through Monday, the day of the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's New York march is scheduled to consist of one full
day of speeches, talks and musical performances.
</P>
<P>
   Both events have been endorsed by the Nation of Islam, although
the Atlanta march also has won the support of the NAACP, the
AFL-CIO and the Rev. Jesse Jackson. Organizers say they are not
competing and hope young people will rally in their own cities if
they can't go to the two larger marches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1500EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     09-04 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET THE BIRTHING PROJECT'S FIRST ARRIVALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were never more perfect moments in my life than when I
held my daughters for the first time. Tears splattered my face, but
somehow I felt as though I were in the middle of a marvelous laugh
with one _ or all five _ of my sisters.
</P>
<P>
   My daughters' safe arrivals did not so much make me happy as
make me realize how splendid happiness can be.
</P>
<P>
   I had another such a moment Saturday, when my den echoed with
the gurgles and cries of the first babies born into the Fort Worth
chapter of the Birthing Project, a national organization that works
to lower the infant mortality rate among African-Americans by
pairing teen-age mothers with volunteers who provide care and
support during and after their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   As one who tries to embrace Scripture, to live by it, I believe
that when we do good deeds, they should be done in secret. But I
share this with you now for several reasons, not the least of which
is the joy of having witnessed something that deserves remembering.
</P>
<P>
   I do it because I need my daughters to know that I cared not
just for them, but for all children. And not just in private, but
in public as well.
</P>
<P>
   I do it so that these babies' lives will always mean something.
Not just to me and the nine volunteers who helped usher them safe
and healthy into the world, but to you.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that, after all, what we all want for our children? For
their lives to have meaning and purpose?
</P>
<P>
   And so Saturday, we gathered for our first baby shower. This was
not the traditional shower where the expectant mother receives
gifts and plays cute games.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the babies were born in July. Several of them came
early. Now their mothers had come to dream for them.
</P>
<P>
   We started with 10 pregnant teens, ages 14 to 19. All come from
single-parent households. Most of their mothers, many of whom were
teen-age moms themselves, are younger than my 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   One new mom doesn't know her mother's whereabouts. Another one
lives with a family friend because her mother is in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the 10 were transient, moving from home to home. In the
end, we lost touch with two after they gave birth. One moved. The
other's phone was disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the moment they knew they were pregnant, each
teen-ager was asked to describe what she wanted for her baby. What
she envisioned the child wearing on the first day of school, how
she might feel on that day, the day her child graduates from high
school, college, gets his first job. We wanted each mom to start
thinking about what she might do to make those things happen. Will
she need to stay in school and do the same things for herself?
</P>
<P>
   Their wishes were both simple and ambitious. One mother hopes
that her daughter will wear Tommy Hilfiger on her first day of
school, and that she will grow up to be a beautician in a shop on
Lancaster Avenue. One hopes that her son will become a doctor or
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Another hopes that her daughter will marry a man who won't beat
her.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, when we became the 50th Birthing Project chapter in
the country, each of us was asked to make a wish for the baby we
would help bring into the world. On Saturday, the stones we had
chosen to represent those dreams, and the dreams themselves, were
passed on to our ``little sisters.'' They, in turn, were charged
with keeping the dreams and, when the time was right, passing them
on to their children.
</P>
<P>
   To some, I suppose, this little exercise might seem futile. It
did to me in the beginning, but I had only to remember the dreams I
have for my own daughters, and it all made sense.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to predict what will become of our babies. None of us
can say with certainty, for instance, that little Michael will
become a lawyer or businessman, as his mother hopes.
</P>
<P>
   But the likelihood of him becoming either is surely diminished
if we don't dream.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can e-mail her at: gbs(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
