<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9561 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SUMMITRY-HNS &LR;      09-04 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SUMMITRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TEAM WEIGHS NEXT FOREIGN TRIP AS LEWINSKY CRISIS DEEPENS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ As President Clinton enjoyed the admiration of jubilant
Irish crowds disinterested in the White House sex scandal, White
House officials said Friday he may make a peace-seeking visit to
Pakistan and India in November.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has traveled abroad 39 days so far this year to
visit 14 countries, would stop in Pakistan and India on his way to
the annual summit of Pacific rim nations known as the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum (APEC). The APEC nations convene in
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, on the weekend before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy National Security James Steinberg said Clinton is ``very
actively and intensively involved'' in efforts to reverse the
Pakistani-Indian nuclear arms race that flared in May with a series
of tit-for-tat underground nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may launch a new round of diplomacy with Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif and Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee next week. The president returns to the White House late
Saturday night after four days of summitry in Moscow and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg indicated the president might make telephone calls or
send personal letters to both leaders in an effort to foster the
cooperation that would be needed before Clinton would visit them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials are pressing Pakistan and India
to forego future tests and sign the Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Treaty that governs nuclear weapons development.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and India have waged three wars and edged to the brink
of a fourth over disputed territory since they won independence
from Britain in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   An indication of the importance that the administration places
on a potential visit to India and Pakistan came when Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott flew from the Moscow summit to
New York to meet Thursday with Jaswant Singh, the Indian government
official dealing with Clinton administration concerns over India's
nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott met with Pakistani officials in London last week en
route to Moscow for Clinton's Kremlin summit with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have worked to orchestrate five rounds of
negotiating sessions between Indian and Pakistani officials since
the nuclear arms race erupted in May.
</P>
<P>
   Previous U.S. presidents in political trouble at home have found
foreign travel especially valuable as a way of showcasing their
presidential allure to audiences either less interested or less
informed about U.S. political issues.
</P>
<P>
   Since allegations of a sex-and-cover-up scandal emerged in
January, Clinton's extensive foreign travel has taken him to a
34-nation pan-American summit in Chile; a six-nation foray across
sub-Saharan Africa; an eight-nation summit in Birmingham, England
and visit to East Germany; a nine day trip to China; and the latest
five-day trip to Moscow, Northern Ireland and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   He has been toasted by enthusiastic crowds during a two-day
visit to Northern Ireland and Ireland as well as public praise by
both Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern and British Prime Minister
Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry said Clinton was
heartened by the personal support offered by world leaders. ``I
think the president takes some satisfaction from that,'' McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the president rolled out a fourth version of his
apology for carrying on an affair with Lewinsky, Ahern praised him
for his efforts to forge peace in Northern Ireland
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before have we had such intense and sustained contact
from the United States president in a period when we desperately
need it to be able to move forward,'' Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered his latest remarks one day after suffering
unusually harsh criticism from three influential Democrats in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already said that I made a bad mistake; it was
indefensible; and I'm sorry about it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton apparently hoped his remarks, offered calmly and with a
tone of contrition, would help bolster his support from skeptical
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., a long-time Clinton ally,
criticized Clinton in a Senate floor speech Thursday as Clinton
barnstormed Northern Ireland in triumph, receiving accolades for
his efforts for peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman called Clinton's behavior ``immoral'' and
``disgraceful,'' adding that it warranted ``public rebuke and
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's criticism was echoed by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., and Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some past American presidents in trouble at home have found
overseas summitry a tonic for their spirits and an opportunity to
spiff-up their image back home.
</P>
<P>
   President Richard Nixon, facing congressional and criminal
investigations into the Watergate scandal, traveled to Egypt in
early 1974 where he was greeted by hundreds of thousands of
clamorous Egyptians as he traveled by train along the banks of the
Nile River.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon hit the overseas campaign trail again in late June 1974,
traveling to Moscow for a summit with Soviet President Leonid
Brezhnev. The two leaders signed a number of limited agreements on
nuclear weapons _ including a pact not to conduct underground
nuclear weapons tests of more than 150 kilotons.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was forced to resign from office on Aug. 9, 1974, shortly
after his return to the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9563 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YELTSIN-LEGACY-ECONOM     09-04 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-LEGACY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN: THE MAN WHO CAUSED DEMOCRACY TO FAIL IN RUSSIA?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week beginning
5 September 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
