<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING CHANGE TO JAIL OVERCROWDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim DiPaolo came to his view about the finite limits of prison
sentences the old-fashioned way: as a rookie street cop in Malden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized it when I went to my first disturbance. There were
three people to be arrested, and I only had one set of handcuffs.''
Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   What do you do with six wrists and one set of cuffs? ``I
handcuffed the first guy to the second guy, right hand to right
hand, so they couldn't run as easily, and I just held the other guy
till more help arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Now DiPaolo is the sheriff of Middlesex (Mass.) County, the
state's largest, home to one-quarter of Massachusetts' six million
citizens. But that episode from his rookie cop days 25 years ago
sticks in his mind as he juggles prisoners and cells. ``That's when
I first realized that there were too many potential prisoners out
there, and not enough jail cells.''
</P>
<P>
   The skyrocketing growth of America's prison population is fueled
by the public's fear of street crime, and TV shows and newspaper
scare stories. Even though crime is down virtually everywhere,
jails and prisons are overflowing. The US has 1.6 million prisoners
under lock and key, by far the highest proportion of the citizenry
in the calaboose of any developed nation.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory sentences and lengthy terms for drug and
alcohol-related offenses have stuffed our jails. Sheriff DiPaolo
has 1,600 prisoners to house on any given day; last Wednesday it
was 1,125 at the Billerica (Mass.) House of Correction, 495 in
pre-trial detention at the Middlesex Courthouse-jail skyscraper in
Cambridge, and another 195 inmates parcelled out to other county
jails because he'd run out of space in Middlesex.
</P>
<P>
   When DiPaolo, after 18 years as a policeman, won a four-way race
for the Democratic nomination for sheriff, ``I found that out of
1,200 prisoners at the time, 18 percent of them were serving time
for domestic violence. But I also found that there was no
rehabilitation program at the time for domestic batterers.''
</P>
<P>
   So he designated a 60-man unit at Billerica as base for a new
VIP program. That is not an acronym for coddling prisoners; it
stands for Violence Intervention and Prevention. Nearly one-fifth
of his clientele is jailed for spouse or child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   DiPaola knew he couldn't keep up with the demand for jail cells,
at an average of $30,000 per inmate per year. The endless assembly
line supplying drug-or-alocohol-soaked prisoners threatens to break
the bank, unless more innovative methods are found to curb
antisocial behavior. DiPaolo: ``We've established a preliminary
agreement with the state Probation Dept. to run and operate
together community correction centers for non-violent offenders.''
</P>
<P>
   This would involve setting up arrangements where inmates could
be restrained variously by house arrest, reporting to probation
officers by phone or in person, use of electronic bracelets to see
that a prisoner is inside his home at the required times.
</P>
<P>
   The savings would be dramatic, and the rehab potential is far
greater than stuffing sullen, angry men in dangerously overcrowded
facilities. DiPaolo and other Middlesex County officials live in
fear of a high-rise fire or some other disaster in the cumbersome
and poorly conceived Middlesex court-jail complex.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer a leaking railway tank car in nearby freight
yards caused authorities to virtually cordon off a large section of
East Cambridge, Mass. Hundreds of public safety people were
mobilized to be ready to move 300 prisoners out of harm's way. ``I
had the buses lined up out back, ready to move them all,'' said
DiPaolo. But the logistics of feeding, housing, treating,
transporting and safeguarding hundreds of prisoners around the
clock, year in and year out, is tremendously costly.
</P>
<P>
   DiPaolo has 650 employees. He initially enlisted a lot of
support for the plan, with the Probation Dept., to experiment with
alternatives to traditional jail terms. ``I went to one of the
local newspapers in Middlesex County, and explained to the editor
what we were trying to do. He said, `I'm for it,' till we explained
we wanted to put a community corrections center in his city, then
it was, `No, no, I don't think so.'''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming resistance to reform is part of the process of
bringing change to county-level government. ``It can be a lonely
place out there,'' said DiPaolo, when you are advocating what
people instinctively oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took over as sheriff, I found there were 90 employees
(including prison guards) who'd never been through any kind of
training for corrections officers. We got all of them trained
promptly in an innovative arrangement that did not cost the
taxpayers very much money.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPaolo has only one primary opponent this time around, whom he
beat handily last time. That would be one Edward Kennedy _ not that
Kennedy, the one in the US Senate. But DiPaolo is taking no
chances, and wears out his shoe leather running from one end of the
county to the other.
</P>
<P>
   He may be on the cutting edge of meaningful prison reform that
saves the Commonwealth hundreds of millions of dollars. House
Speaker Tom Finneran has signalled he is ready to enact sweeping
changes in the present unwieldy system of mandatory sentences that
leave judges, prosectuors, police and perpetrators unhappy. In
their zeal to address voters' fears and media hype, lawmakers have
gone overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran has studied the problems in depth and immersed himself
and his staff in negotiations with judges, prosecutors and prison
experts. Given the current lead of Atty. Gen. Scott Harshbarger in
the Democratic gubernatorial primary, it is likely that
law-and-order issues, which inevitably touch on prison reform, may
become part of this year's election debate.
</P>
<P>
   As a former Middlesex County District Attorney, Harshbarger was
a career prosecutor, and has signalled he is receptive to changes
in the present system which is deeply flawed in the minds of just
about everyone who has to work within it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
