<HEADLINE>
IT'S ONLY A GAME. OR SO YOU THOUGHT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Fla., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)The Duke of Wellington supposedly said that the battle
of Waterloo was won ``on the playing fields of Eton.'' Indeed, many
a valuable lesson is learned in games _ and that goes for business
just as much as war. Some lessons may sting, but as these anecdotes
demonstrate, they linger in the memory.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1966, Barry Augenbraun, now of St. Petersburg,
Fla., was a newly minted associate attending his first summer
outing at a major Wall Street law firm. Asked to choose an
afternoon sport, he picked tennis; around 6:30 that evening, before
the dinner festivities began, he phoned his wife, Janet, and told
her he had some good news and some bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' she said, her concern evident in her voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he replied. ``I came in second in the firm doubles
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great!'' his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Augenbraun said. ``That was the bad news.'' He told her
that he had been teamed with one of the firm's partners, who was
also a nationally ranked tennis player, and that ``this is the
first firm championship he has lost in six years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the good news?'' Augenbraun's wife asked.
</P>
<P>
   The partner, he replied, ``offered to buy me golf lessons before
next year's outing.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meet Bill Byrne of San Francisco, a member of the winning team
in an unusual race.
</P>
<P>
   At a company picnic where food and beer were in ample supply, a
new executive, having decided that team-building games would
provide a good way to observe organizational culture, set into
motion an odd variation on the three-legged race:
</P>
<P>
   Each team had 10 players, and each player was given a short
piece of rope. The first two players, assuming the usual
three-legged stance, tied legs together with the rope; then they
walked 50 yards to a hula hoop. The first player stepped into the
hoop with his free leg, picked it up by hand and passed it over his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Then both players lifted their common leg, passed the hoop
through to the second player's free leg so that he could then pass
the hoop over his head and place it on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Having completed the drill, the team returned to the starting
line, tied on another person and repeated the procedure. The goal
was to sequentially tie together all 10 team members, pass the hula
hoop and return to the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   Given the presence of the beer, coordination was not prevalent,
and several participants were so drunk with competitive spirit that
they failed to notice their bleeding, rope-burned ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne writes, ``The new executive awarded first place to my
team, for having the intelligence to quit soon into the game.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After surviving hours of round-robin play, Brian Brown of
Manhattan and his doubles partner found themselves in the finals of
the hotly contested tennis tournament at their company's annual
sales conference.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who no longer works for the company, writes that their
opponents in the finals included a man ``who fancied himself a
tennis pro and happened to be a director of our publishing firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Volleying with gusto and covering the net with tenacity, Brown
and his partner sensed an impending victory, made all the sweeter
by the presence of a crowd of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   The partners were on the verge of serving out the match when one
of their more senior colleagues, who had been watching from the
sidelines and sipping a drink, called time out and walked
deliberately across the court to the baseline, where Brown was
standing.
</P>
<P>
   He cupped his hands to Brown's ear and whispered: ``Are you out
of your mind? The purpose of this exercise is not to lose your
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown discussed this situation with his partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with our priorities in proper perspective,'' Brown
writes, ``we managed to snatch defeat from the jaws of victory.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is always a bright side to losing.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Economou of Poughkeepsie, N.Y., recalls the Type A lawyer
who lost his tennis match to an easygoing stockbroker by a score of
6-1, 6-2, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   As they left the court, the Type A told his opponent, ``Could
have gone either way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
