<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-0905-     09-04 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PRAISES AHERN, IRELAND ECONOMIC GROWTH AS FACTOR IN
PEACE
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ A nearly jubilant tour across Ireland
continued Friday for Bill Clinton, who used the day to turn from a
message of peace to praise for the Irish Republic's economic boom
as the ``Celtic tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many U.S. and British officials have cited the
republic's recent economic growth as an essential factor that
created an environment that favored the peace process. Often on
this trip, Clinton has pointed to the prospect of jobs and wealth
as one of the prizes awaiting Northern Ireland if the peace holds.
</P>
<P>
   An economic derelict just a few years ago, the republic last
year boasted a stunning 7.7 percent growth rate. In 1997, the
country recorded $12 billion in trade with the United States, an
increase of 19 percent over the previous year. Two years ago, the
per capita income here for the first time exceeded that of the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Celtic tiger is roaring and you should be very proud of
it,'' Clinton said during a speech at Gateway Inc., a large
American computer firm with operations in the Dublin suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted that 470 U.S. companies have invested in
Ireland, many of them devoted to information technology like
Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gateway and other companies, like Intel and Dell and Digital,
are strengthening Ireland's historic links to the United States and
reaching out beyond,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Gateway, Clinton was nearly playful as he and Irish leader
Bertie Ahern demonstrated a computer system that employs ``smart
cards'' and PIN numbers to affix signatures to documents. Using
laptops, the American and Irish leaders used the system to sign a
communique on technology.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton joked that he had mixed feelings about this
technological advance, saying it could lead to the virtual
president. ``Do you have any idea how much time I spend every day
signing my name?'' he joked. ``I'm going to feel utterly useless if
I can't do that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he continued to be dogged Friday by questions about his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, the
president seemed to build on his emotional success in Northern
Ireland the day before. At the beginning of the visit in Belfast
Thursday morning, he seemed tired and wan. By Friday afternoon, he
seemed to have his color back and to be in high spirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there is a little rain in the air today, it's
always sunny for me in Ireland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, Clinton met with Ahern privately and discussed
renewed progress with the stalled peace process. The leaders
discussed ways to maintain the momentum generated by the
president's visit, said a White House aide, who did not elaborate.
In his public comments, Clinton heaped generous praise on Ahern for
his part in the peace process, at times appearing to embarrass the
Irish leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world owes you a debt of gratitude,'' Clinton told a
gathering of government, union, business and farming
representatives at the Royal College of Surgeons in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   The Taoiseach -- an Irish word pronounced tee-shok and meaning
chieftain -- was right beside him to hear the warm applause of his
countryfolk as Clinton sang his praises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about the role of the Taoiseach in making
this Irish peace process come to fruition,'' Clinton said. ``I just
want to say . . . you can be very proud of his leadership -- as
well as your own overwhelming vote for peace a few months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the president headed to Limerick on the island's
west coast where he is scheduled to deliver an address Saturday at
a new technology park just outside the city where Austin,
Texas-based Dell Computer Corp. has established its primary
European operation.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading back to Washington Saturday evening, the
president plans to play a round of golf at the famed course at
Ballybunion, ranked among the top dozen golf courses in the world
and known for its stiff wind, unique contours and graveyard hazard
that has confounded such golf greats as Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was been given a 250-to-one chance of shooting a
hole-in-one at the golfing mecca by Paddy Power, Ireland's leading
bookmaker, on Friday. Power predicted Clinton would be the weaker
of his foursome -- which includes club captain Brian McCarthy,
Finance Minister Charlie McCreevy and former foreign minister Dick
Spring, who will partner Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president was forced to cancel his first date with
Ballybunion due to the conflict in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
