<HEADER>
A9600 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINDING-A-FAMILY-LIFE     09-04 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINDING-A-FAMILY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY PERSONAL SEARCH FOR FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW BLUM 
 c.1998 Andrew Blum 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   A couple of years ago, on my 42nd birthday, I got my first ever
card from my biological mother.
</P>
<P>
   Like about 5 million American adults, I am adopted. I was born
in Chicago and adopted through an adoption agency. My parents told
me around age 10, but knowing I was adopted didn't sink in, at
least on a conscious level. It did not start to bother me until I
reached my 20s.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, your parents are your parents. But if you're
adopted it's not that simple: There's curiosity combined with a gut
emotion _ the sense of being detached your whole life, the wanting
to know who you are more than anything else in the world, and the
outright longing to see a real life relative in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   For me, no matter how much I loved my family, I never knew my
roots. Even now, in 1998, after having found two-thirds of my
biological family, I can't find my father.
</P>
<P>
   What I have learned is that finding answers isn't easy. In this
country, compared to several other nations, adoption records are
largely sealed.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 27, I asked my parents for my adoption papers. They
contained a starting point -- my birth mother's name. (Her name is
Anne; I am withholding her last name.) I wrote the agency, naively
assuming it would tell me everything. I didn't know I had begun a
15-year, on-again, off-again search.
</P>
<P>
   The agency was happy to share my history: I learned my parents
were of Polish, Russian and German ancestry; my mother operated a
Comptometer (an accounting machine used in offices in the 1950s);
my father served in the U.S. Navy. But that is about all I learned,
for without a court order, the agency would divulge no names.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, I put the search on hold, reaching out occasionally
to attend a workshop or pick up a book. A few years later, I became
a father myself. My girlfriend became pregnant, choosing single
motherhood, and I did not see my daughter for months after her
birth.
</P>
<P>
   When I finally did, I was overwhelmed by emotions I had denied
over the years. At family reunions I had felt detached, totally
unrelated to the ``relatives'' around me. But now I was holding my
own daughter, the first blood relative I had ever encountered. She
had my blue eyes, my dimples, my big ears.
</P>
<P>
   I had to finish searching. I recontacted the agency. It had
become so deluged with inquiries it had created a post-adoption
department. This seemed promising, but once again, shock. I learned
I had a half-sister 18 months older than I. She was adopted through
another agency, which had lost contact with our mother, and so
could release nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred this time, I was ready to go on. After seeing a TV
segment on a woman running online adoption bulletin board, I was
referred to a Chicago adoption searcher. The searcher, who declined
to be identified for this article, did not reveal her methods. But
I understood they were legal, via public records and phone. She
charged an initial fee of $50, and my payments to her and other
parties eventually amounted to $700.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly learned Anne had been married and traced her last
address. But there was bad news, too: Anne had been hospitalized
after a fall, and was now in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   I reached Anne's doctor, got the home's name, then wrote a
letter I had written a million times in my head. It began: ``You
don't know me, but I believe I am your biological son. I've been
waiting a long time to find you and now I have....''
</P>
<P>
   Days passed and no response. I wondered if I had written to the
wrong person, or worse, she wanted no contact with me.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I picked up the telephone and dialed. A voice came on
the line, apprehensive at first, then pleased. ``What took you so
long?'' she asked. She had gotten my letter, but had not yet mailed
a response. We arranged to finally meet in person.
</P>
<P>
   While that meeting loomed, I got another call from my searcher:
She had found my half-sister, Karen, and had given her my number.
Presently I had a call from pleasant-sounding young woman in
suburban Chicago. ``This is Karen,'' she said. I nearly dropped the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Anne had existed in my mind, but Karen was a totally new being.
Thrilled, we wondered how to start a relationship. We picked a
weekend, and I was on my way.
</P>
<P>
   I flew to Chicago, staying with a friend. I slept poorly and
woke early. It was a cool spring day and my friend lent me his car.
I imagined Anne as a young, beautiful woman giving me a big hug.
Neither, of course, happened.
</P>
<P>
   Anne was an elfin 66-year-old, with a walker, but I could see me
in her: eyes, ears, fair skin. The agency told me she was the only
child of a divorce. But there were confusing, contradictory and
vague references to her health and family. It was frustrating to
find her and still be clueless.
</P>
<P>
   I took Anne to lunch. While the nursing home was depressing, I
was happy to see the restaurant owner knew Anne. I learned she was
married for 12 years to a man now deceased, had lived on her own
and done office jobs and telephone sales.
</P>
<P>
   She never directly said why she gave me up, and I didn't press
her. Over lunch, she pulled out an article from Parade, in which a
birth mother said it was best her baby be adopted because she could
not care for her. ``I saved this for you,'' Anne said. The woman
said she looked forward to when her daughter found her, if she
chose.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, I took Anne home, and later met Karen, her husband
and son. As with Anne, I saw a resemblance to Karen. We hugged.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Karen, her husband and I took Anne to lunch. She
told us the family history and showed pictures. She could not
recall our fathers but we listened anyway, noting names of male
friends. ``He might have been in the Navy,'' Anne said of one.
</P>
<P>
   Back in her room, Anne's memorabilia got to me: a picture of my
grandfather, Hyman, with my big ears. He was in the military, too,
a painter, decorator and machinist. And his 1963 death notice.
``Are you OK?'' Karen asked. ``No,'' I said, tears welling up. It
was time to go.
</P>
<P>
   I continued trying to find my biological father, fighting
through one bureaucratic barrier after another, to no avail. The
experience, though, was worthwhile. In Chicago I visited the agency
that had placed me with my parents. In one room there were pictures
of many children like myself. I was moved to leave a photo there of
me and my new daughter.
</P>
<P>
   I'm on my own now. I have in my possession now a note, signed by
my biological mother. It says: ``Love, your Mom Anne.'' Indeed I
have a mother. But I hope Anne understands that although I have a
primal feeling for her, she is not my mom. I've tried to act
normal, staying in touch. But I can't help feeling that if it had
not taken years to find Anne, she might not be in the nursing home.
She might remember more of who my father was, and how I might find
him. She, he and I might now all be friends.
</P>
<P>
   As Karen said at the end of our first meeting, ``The system
robbed us of all that time.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right. In the end I got the agency to release my father's
name to Anne, and tried finding him, yet it's like he never
existed. I know he's out there, but now it's time to let go.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; (Andrew Blum, born and adopted in Chicago, now lives in the
Northeast.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
