r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOLLOW-CAMPAIGN-MONEY     09-04 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLLOW-CAMPAIGN-MONEY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK CAMPAIGN CONTRIBUTIONS FROM HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 &HT;    
 Includes a 50-word sidebar of Web sites. 
 By JERI CLAUSING  
 c.1998 New York Times 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights; EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPT. 9) &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Following the money in politics used to be a job best left to
campaign operatives and investigative reporters. At least one
public interest group is hoping to change that situation, by
creating a database-driven Web site that makes tracking political
contributions this election season almost as easy as checking your
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Center for Responsive Politics launched a new
resource that offers detailed campaign finance profiles for every
congressional candidate in the country, challengers as well as
incumbents. The database is updated every month with the latest
filings from the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   While the Center, a nonprofit non-partisan group based in
Washington, D.C., has been around for more than a decade, it has
primarily been a tool for journalists, providing campaign
contribution data for computer-assisted reporting projects. The new
project is the most ambitious it has ever launched, with the goal
of making the information easily accessible to the average voter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real idea here is to spread the power, on the assumption
that information is power and there is too much of it in Washington
and not enough everywhere else'' said Larry Makinson, executive
director of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers a do-it-yourself congressional investigation
kit, allowing users to search all federal campaign contributions by
donor or recipient, track the sources of contributions to every
congressional candidate in the country by industry or interest
group, identify the recipients of contributions from political
action commmittees and see how much money interest groups spent
lobbying Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can search for the sources of contributions by
industry, metropolitan area and zip code. For example, in Speaker
of the House Newt Gingrich's home state of Georgia, the most
generous political action committee (PAC) this election cycle is
the United Parcel Service, which so far has given $922,802 to
congressional candidates, 77 percent of that amount to Republicans.
In Gingrich's District 6 race, he has raised $4.9 million, 14
percent of that from PACs. The largest single donation Gingrich has
received so far was $12,000 from the Coca Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also offers comparisons of in-state vs.
out-of-state fund-raising by the candidates and a scorecard showing
how well each candidate is complying with the legal requirement to
identify the employer and occupation of individual contributors.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Center, Paul Hendrie, said the site receives
about 1,500 visits a day, and that traffic has been increasing
since the start of the campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   The CRP Web site is not the first to offer this type of
information. The FEC and other private Web sites have posted data
from FEC filings online for years. The difference is in how the
information is organized and displayed, so that users do not have
to be campaign data experts to figure out how to interpret the
contribution documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every contribution that comes in to a candidate or political
party, we try to categorize it by industry. Then we try to
translate that,'' Makinson said. ``We try to see what the patterns
are. Because if you really want to understand what politicians are
going to do after they are elected, find out who is paying for
their campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center has also made its database available to other Web
sites. One site that takes advantage of such a partnership is
Project Vote Smart, a campaign watchdog group that has one of the
most comprehensive campaign information sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Besides campaign finance data, Project Vote Smart offers
candidate biographies, issue positions, voting records and
candidate evaluations by special interests. Heather Holdridge,
director of Project Vote Smart's reporter resource center, said the
CRP database supplements that package with the latest available
numbers from campaign finance reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it every day,'' Holdridge said. ``I think that CRP is by
far one of the best sites for federal campaign finance information.
... It's very comprehensive and easy to use.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the campaign finance data, the Center For
Responsive Politics has created a database of all reported
privately financed House and Senate travel for 1997. It is the
first computer database of Congressional travel, which was compiled
by hand from paper records lawmakers are required to file with the
clerk of the House and the secretary of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Private interests provided members of the 105th Congress and
their staffs with some $6.4 million in free travel during 1997. The
Center's Web site provides rankings of the biggest travelers,
leading trip sponsors and most popular destination. From the Web
site, users can also search the records by the name of a lawmaker,
sponsoring organization or destination.
</P>
<P>
   For example the database shows that Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, a Mississippi Republican, took just one sponsored trip in
1997, traveling to White Sulphur Springs, W. Va., to address the
Grocery Manufacturers of America. The three-day trip cost
$3,561.89. Senator John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican, took the
most trips, 20; while Newt Gingrich took the most expensive trip --
a $33,141 excursion to give a speech in London, which was financed
by ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Jeri Clausing, based in Washington, D.C., covers government and
Internet policy issues for CyberTimes.)
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 The New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Center for Responsive Politics:www.crp.org/
</P>
<P>
   _ Federal Election Commission: fec.gov/
</P>
<P>
   _ Project Vote Smart: vote-smart.org/
</P>
