<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATE-HARVEST-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE THAT LATE HARVEST
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By SUSAN MCCLURE &QL; 
 &UR; North American rights except Chicago &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes, ripe red peppers and eggplants are still in the
garden, but they won't be for long.
</P>
<P>
   When frost strikes, these and other tender crops will wither. So
bring them indoors now and stock them away for later when their
garden fresh flavor will be especially delightful. Here are some
tips for handling your final harvest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Green Tomatoes: &LR;  You can pick firm and unblemished green
tomatoes to keep in the refrigerator for several weeks, sometimes
even longer. They are good to slice and sautee or to bake sprinkled
with brown sugar and cinnamon. You also can try root cellaring
them. Wrap them in newspaper and store in a cool cellar for a month
or more. Some of the tomatoes probably will rot but others may stay
good for quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ripe Tomatoes: &LR;  Vine ripened, homegrown tomatoes should be
cherished because they are about to become impossible to find.
Enjoy them on salads, sandwiches, or in stir fries, on pasta, or
try grilling them, as detailed in a accompanying recipes. On any
tomato plant, you'll probably find tomatoes that have begun turning
red, but won't be able to finish outdoors. Set them on a warm
kitchen counter and they will brighten up but probably won't be as
delicious as tomatoes that were fully ripe before picking.
</P>
<P>
   Other extra tomatoes are well worth preserving. You can cut them
into quarters and freeze them in freezer bags to use in winter
casseroles, stews, and soups. Or plop them into boiling water for a
minute or until the skin loosens and cracks, then peel the skin
off. Cut these tomatoes into quarters and boil at low heat for an
hour or so. Stir often and when the tomato wedges turn into
slightly thick sauce, you can freeze it for spaghetti or pizza
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dried Tomatoes: &LR;  If you enjoy the intense, concentrated flavor
of sun-dried tomatoes, sold in the upscale part of the grocery
store, you'll be glad to know that you can make them at home with a
dehydrator.
</P>
<P>
   ** Lima Beans: Because they take a long time to develop, lima
beans often aren't ready to harvest until the end of the growing
season. Shell them out of the pod, steam lightly, and enjoy their
slightly nutty, fresh flavor with a little butter.
</P>
<P>
   Extra lima beans are easy to freeze after blanching or quick
boiling to help preserve quality. Blanch small beans for 2 minutes,
medium sized beans for 3 minutes, and large beans for 4 minutes.
Quick cool and freeze in freezer bags. You also can blend lima
beans into salads and casseroles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eggplants: &LR;  These require special treatment to maintain quality
when frozen. Peel off the skin, slice, dip in beaten egg, and cover
with bread crumbs. Bake on a greased cookie sheet at 325 degrees
until slightly tender. Pack into freezer bags. Now you have
ready-to-use breaded eggplants, wonderful topped with tomato and
cheese like mini-pizzas or made into eggplant parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Peppers: &LR;  Like tomatoes, peppers are among the easiest
vegetables to store. Simply slice them up, pack into freezer bags,
and freeze. You also can roast succulent peppers like bell, banana,
and chili peppers. Set them under the broiler until the skin chars,
often accompanied by a popping sound as the skin breaks free from
the flesh. Turn the peppers until charred all the way around. Let
them cool then peel off the skin. Roasted peppers are great on
salads, pasta, pizza, sandwiches, and also can be frozen.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure is a free-lance writer based in Valparaiso,
Ind.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
