<HEADER>
A9604 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANDEM-BIKES-LIFEBEAT     09-04 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANDEM-BIKES-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXERCISE BUILT FOR TWO
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 &HT;    
 Includes photo of a couple riding a tandem bicycle near Solvang,
Calif. 
 By KEN MCALPINE 
 c.1998 Ken McAlpine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Riding a tandem bicycle might seem a simple thing -- two people
take up one bicycle, providing themselves the opportunity to mesh
together in synchronized idyll or plunge off into roadside
shrubbery.
</P>
<P>
   Well, on a simple level a tandem is just a bicycle built for
two. But as anyone who has ever ridden a tandem will tell you, the
activity goes deeper than that. Riding a tandem can be a process of
discovery, some of it wonderful, some of it adrenal jolting, much
of it surprising.
</P>
<P>
   First surprise: Tandems are no longer clunky things piloted by
sunburnt tourists lacking the motor skills necessary to ride a bike
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's tandems are lightweight, they have lots of speeds
--21, 24 and even 27 different gears -- and they're great fun to
ride,'' said Jack Goertz, editor of the tandem magazine DoubleTalk
and a tandem rider of nearly 30 years. ``Two people can ride a
tandem in relative comfort for hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Like every tandem rider I talked to, Goertz was lavish in his
praise. Tandem bicycling, said Goertz, offered all the physical
benefits of conventional cycling -- a great cardiovascular and
calorie burning workout in the great outdoors. Plus, said Goertz,
with two riders you could go faster and farther.
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest attraction -- and the one that explained why
tandem sales are on the upswing -- was the simplest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tandem allows couples of different abilities to ride
together,'' said Goertz. ``It gives you the chance to do something
with someone you really enjoy being with.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a tandem was the easy part. I called my friend Jon
Avery. Jon owns Open Air Bicycles, a successful bike store in
Ventura, Calif., where we both live. He'd also been convinced
enough of the merits of tandems to buy one of his own several years
back. Sure, he said. I could borrow it.
</P>
<P>
   When Jon wheeled the tandem into our driveway I had to admit it
was a beautiful thing, a sleek expanse of polished purple tubing,
gleaming spokes and nearly two sets of everything -- from the water
bottle holders to the scimitar-curved racing handlebars. The bike
reeked of performance and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it also cost him nearly $3,000, Jon started by
giving me advice. Riding a tandem was like riding a regular bike,
he explained, but different too. Even though his tandem was
surprisingly light (just less than 40 pounds) it was still nearly
eight feet long and weighted down by two riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a tandem things happen a bit slower,'' Jon explained. ``You
take the turns a little bit wider. Because of all the momentum,
slowing down isn't as quick. It's like driving a truck with a
trailer. Tandems aren't hard to ride, but they take some
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   I listened, but frankly I found this seminar mildly insulting.
Jon meant well. But on numerous occasions I had seen him wheel by
our house with his most frequent tandem partner, his 8-year-old
daughter Hadley.
</P>
<P>
   Jon also rode with his wife Hope, an experience they found
enjoyable and unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope and I have had some of our best conversations on the
tandem,'' said Jon. ``There's no interruptions, no phone, nothing
else to interfere. We can go for an hour long bike ride and get
more talking in than we do in days.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of extended time alone with my wife Kathy sounded
wonderful, but I'd have to get her alone long enough to ask. With
two small boys and two overworked phones, our conversation takes
place in snippets, bookmarked by squealing and crashing, and heard
only because it's shouted from different rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of several days I conveyed my proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only has one set of brakes?'' Kathy said. ``I'm not going
with you''.
</P>
<P>
   Actually the rider up front, the captain in tandem-speak, pretty
much controls everything. Braking, shifting, pedaling and steering,
it's all in the captain's hands, while the rider in the rear,
dubbed the stoker, proceeds along rudderless.
</P>
<P>
   This presented a psychological hurdle too. My wife is giving and
kind and possessed of innumerable other sweet qualities that have
made me the happiest man alive. But when it comes to piloting our
relationship, there's little doubt who is the captain.
</P>
<P>
   Still Kathy said she was willing to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just for today. When we scrape Jon's bike up I don't want to
be blamed.''
</P>
<P>
   We set out on a sharp, fall day, and immediately discovered that
tandem riding does present challenges. Getting on the bike, for
one. Theoretically, mounting a tandem goes like this. The captain
straddles the bike, both feet firmly planted on the ground. Then
the stoker mounts up behind. When the stoker is balanced, feet in
the pedals, the captain pushes the bike forward and off they roll,
straight as an arrow.
</P>
<P>
   In practice there is some wobbling involved. Lots of wobbling if
the captain is unsure of himself and takes his sweet time getting
the bike up to speed. Behind me, I could hear high pitched noises
that sounded like one of those squeeze toys being frantically
pumped.
</P>
<P>
   When we finally got rolling, Kathy quickly found her tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see anything back here,'' she said. ``Hey! Can you see
that pole? Do you know how the brakes work? Maybe I should just
shut my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually there was too much to see. We had chosen to ride a
local bike path wending up to the small town of Ojai. The path
paralled a road, but curved away frequently to wend through the
woods.
</P>
<P>
   We had lived here for 12 years, driven the adjacent road
hundreds of times. Now we rolled quietly past creeks that kinked
through a thick tumble of birch, elm and oak, their leaves muted
red and squinty-bright yellow. When the woods cleared, we looked
out to a sweep of green pastures running up into folded, blue
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know this existed,'' Kathy said softly.
</P>
<P>
   True, we would have seen the same things had we ridden
conventional bikes. But it was a lot more fun linked together. For
one thing, Kathy couldn't ride off and leave me. But there was
something more. Feeling the bike surge beneath us, the two of us
working to orchestrate its ebb and flow, promoted a strange sense
of intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   We discovered each other too. When we rode fast, the wind
whopped in our ears. When we didn't, we talked about dream houses,
college friends, funny memories, and why pealing church bells have
a special timbre on a crisp day.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a long time since we'd been this close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remind me to shave the back of your neck,'' said Kathy.
</P>
<P>
   And riding the tandem quickly became as easy as, well, riding a
bike. There were a few dicey moments, sure, like suddenly finding
ourselves in a flood of gym class joggers from a nearby high
school. But we both gained confidence quickly. We left the bike
path and spun down back roads. We stopped, and started up,
wobble-free. Gliding along a sun dappled stretch of road I heard
Kathy singing, and saw her shadow behind me, arms pumping up and
down like some antic jogger.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't ride far, twenty-three miles in all. And, except for
an occasional sprint to feel the power of two, we didn't ride hard.
Jon had advised us to take it easy and make our first ride a
pleasant one. We took his advice seriously. We stopped for lunch.
We stopped for wary pedestrians. We let time seep away. We nearly
got swallowed by night.
</P>
<P>
   Which was nice. Because that's how we found ourselves swooping
alone through ghost shadows of cool and real shadows of flicking
light, the final foggy, low-beam remnants of a setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   It was our wonderful secret, immediate and complete.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken McAlpine is a free-lance writer based in Ventura, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
