r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-BALLPARKS-2TAKES-     09-04 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BALLPARKS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES BEGIN TO SOUR ON PUBLIC FINANCING FOR BALLPARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For evidence of skepticism about the community
value of new ballparks and stadiums, consider Round Rock, Texas,
where folks are looking a gift horse in the mouth, even though it's
offered by famous fireballer Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's investment group has purchased the Jackson (Miss.)
Generals of the AA Southern Association, plans to move the team to
Round Rock for the 2000 season and has pledged to put up about $6
million for a proposed $13 million ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Round Rock City Council was keen to accept Ryan's offer, but
a grass-roots petition drive has forced a Nov. 3 vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just corporate welfare,'' said David Oatman, one of the
petition campaign leaders. ``They want to use hotel-motel tax for
the city share, but the downside is there's not enough of it. Those
hotels don't exist,'' he said. ``This area loves baseball, but
we've got an even chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by San Francisco, where a flinty electorate has virtually
closed the public purse to the Giants and the 49ers, cities across
the country are requiring sports franchise owners to share in the
cost of the new ballparks and stadiums they say they need to remain
economically viable.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, the Padres are trying to persuade voters to accept
a deal in which the team contributes $115 million, or 28 percent of
the cost of a $411 million ballpark. The team also commits to
redevelop the downtown area where the stadium is to be built.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, is on the Nov. 3 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, the Pirates and Steelers _ beaten in attempts to
fund a new ballpark and stadium through a regional sales-tax
increase _ have pledged to contribute $40 million and $50 million,
respectively, toward building their projects.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the legislature recently told New England
Patriots owner Robert Kraft to lump it when he rejected an offer of
$50 million in state infrastructure spending for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public sentiment has turned against professional sports teams
and this willy-nilly thing they have of moving franchises around
like snake-oil salesmen,'' said Robert Baade, an economist at Lake
Forest College in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesotans said to the Twins' owners, `if you want to go, go.
Here's the door,''' Baade said. ``Maybe the lesson in this is that
cities have more in the way of power than they think they have when
they stand up to teams.''
</P>
<P>
   No city has stood up with greater rigidity than San Francisco,
where the Giants _ after a decade of hearing voters say no to
public financing _ are building the first privately financed major
league ballpark in 35 years and the 49ers are struggling with a
stadium and mall package that may be too rich for the developer.
</P>
<P>
   In making a bold move to finance a major-league ballpark
privately, Giants President and Managing General Partner Peter
Magowan ``has shifted the scale a bit, but he's still way out on a
limb,'' said sports economist Andrew Zimbalist of Smith College in
Massachusetts. He is author of ``Baseball and Billions.''
</P>
<P>
   Magowan ``has had an impact, but not in the form of emulation,''
Zimbalist said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Zimbalist acknowledged, ``the trend is to get some
private financing,'' although ``you almost never have the case
where the owner actually takes money out of his pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   The usual scenario is that ``the owner gives back a piece of the
revenue from the facility that is built for him with public
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Baer, executive vice president of the San Francisco
Giants, believes that ``there is a prevailing view among
municipalities that at a minimum there should be some form of
private contribution. The hybrid structure is becoming the dominant
form.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are raising $136 million _ through charter seat
sales, concession rights and sponsorships _ and blending it with
$170 million in loans to finance Pacific Bell Park, which is
scheduled to open in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While he thinks the Giants' financing plan has encouraged an
attitudinal shift and acceptance of the hybrid model among team
owners, Baer acknowledged that San Francisco is an unusual case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a couple of other places around the country have the
combination of taxpayer sentiment and the ability of the team
financially to allow for a privately built ballpark,'' he said.
``We have a rather large market, combined with high disposable
income and a rich tradition of Giants baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the arguments advanced by the San Diego Padres
for substantial public financing of a new ballpark was that the
team has neither the media market nor corporate base to foot the
entire bill.
</P>
<P>
   Padres President Larry Lucchino, who was president of the
Baltimore Orioles at the birth of the publicly financed Oriole Park
at Camden Yards, said the deal struck with San Diego is no
softball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that by combining a ballpark and a major
redevelopment project, we have increased the degree of difficulty''
for making it all happen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That difficulty is enhanced by the skeptical attitude of the
influential San Diego County Taxpayers Association, which has yet
to take a position on the ballpark ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so bloody complicated we're still trying to understand
it,'' said Scott Barnett, executive director of the association.
``A lot of the money they're supposed to put up isn't really
private. For instance, the city is giving them five lots worth $10
million, and they count that as private. It seems like a kind of
clever accounting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
