<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BALLPARKS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO: x x x accounting,'' he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rodney Fort, a sports economist at Washington State University
and author of ``Pay Dirt,'' said Seattle Seahawks owner Paul Allen
appears to have perfected a new model of private financing that
will cost him nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Allen is obligated to provide $100 million of the $400 million
being spent for a new Seahawks stadium, ``but not a penny is coming
out of his pocket. The stadium is owned by the King County Stadium
Authority, and Allen has the rights to everything in the stadium
... and the revenues will go to the Seahawks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only trend is being driven by the profitability of
sports,'' Fort said. ``As long as it looks like the teams are
making money, public officials are going to expect them to pay a
part.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York is the scene an intriguing ballpark financing drama,
because the Yankees and Mets are angling for new facilities which
would be heavily financed by taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times _ citing the private financing success of the
Giants _ suggested in an editorial that the teams may be
overreaching: ``When club owners in lesser markets raise huge
amounts of private capital to finance stadiums, owners and
politicians in New York have to explain why that will not work
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In a study released last week, University of California at
Berkeley scholar Jack Sylvan reported cities that build expensive
stadiums and ballparks to attract sports teams derive little
economic benefit from them.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Sylvan said in an interview, such facilities
exercise a hard-to-resist fascination because of ``the
intangibles'' and cachet that cities believe they bring.
</P>
<P>
   That is what worries Round Rock's Oatman in the campaign against
$7 million in public financing for a new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, major league baseball's all-time strikeout leader and a
sure-fire inductee into the Hall of Fame when he becomes eligible
next year, has turned his city's head, Oatman believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big problems we're facing is that the city
hierarchy is totally star-struck. They can't think rationally,'' he
said. ``They don't seem to realize that Nolan Ryan is a
businessman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
