<HEADLINE>
ROSEANNE BARR JOINS THE TALKS SHOW WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Roseanne Barr. 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    With Oprah and Rosie, Jerry and Jennie, Howie Mandell, Donny and
Marie and who knows who else, it's getting pretty crowded in the
daytime TV talk show marketplace. But room can always be found for
a tough contender with muscle. And they don't come any tougher than
Roseanne Barr.
 &HT;    King World Productions obviously thinks so. They've paid the
lady handsomely to jump into the daytime ring with the ``Roseanne
Show'' which debuts Sept. 14.
 &HT;    What Barr has going for her is enormous recognition based on
almost a decade as Roseanne Conner, America's favorite blue collar
mom. After nine years on ABC the Conners hit the lottery jackpot
and the working class stiffs ended up as the filthy rich. The saga
was complete. It was, Barr decided, time to move on.
 &HT;    Looking trim and pretty in sandals, white pants and a simple
blouse top, and wearing her hair cut short, Barr showed up for
breakfast one morning recently at her manager Jeff Wald's
26th-floor Century City office to try to explain why she's decided
to become the newest entry in the talk show wars.
 &HT;    ``I wanted a change and felt that talk is a great way for me to
communicate with my audience directly,'' she said. ``No scripts.
Just me, my guests and the audience. When I watch other people who
did talk shows before me, there were some great, great ones.
Particularly Johnny Carson who I'd do anything to get on my show.''
 &HT;    Even though she agrees the talk show market is crowded she
doesn't fear entering the fray. ``There are a lot of shows on TV
that show us how low we can go. I'd like to show how high we can
go. I won't have a sidekick. But I do pick a pet from the audience
for each show who gets their easy chair and gets treated better
than the rest of the audience. We'll go out to meet people. I
answer questions and do a little monologue about whatever I want to
talk about that day.''
 &HT;    She knows what she'll have no time for: ``I don't want any
fist-fighting or people who sleep with their daughter's boyfriends.
I'm not going to have any of that _ unless they're famous.''
 &HT;    She laughs, then promises the her show will be ``more Donahue
than anything else.''
 &HT;    She'd love to have Winfrey on her first show, she adds. ``She's
a class act, a role model and I'm totally inspired by her. I called
her and Rosie when I decided to do my show and they gave me
personal advice. Mostly it was to be myself and have fun.''
 &HT;    The wisecracking, hard-edged Barr came to us first via stand up
in the early '80s with lines like: ``He's always asking, 'Where's
my socks? Where's my keys?' Men think the uterus is a tracking
device.'''
 &HT;    It was a fresh voice, straight from the neglected working class.
Donna Reed she wasn't. And we loved her for it until the tales of
her real domestic life kept getting in the way.
 &HT;    ``We're everybody's nightmare,'' she once said at the height of
her raucous divorce from actor Tom Arnold. ``Rich, white trash.''
 &HT;    But she feels that because she fought the media's attacks on her
weight and her lifestyle she was targeted in the final ``Roseanne''
season. A l997 Washington Post article declared, ``The decline
began when Barr lost weight, had a face lift, and continued when
the Conners won the lottery.''
 &HT;    Was that unfair? ``Stupid,'' she says, nibbling a blueberry
muffin washed down with black coffee. ``It's all the tabloid
mentality that filtered up from the very bottom of journalism to
the top. I was able to see things that started in the National
Enquirer quoted in the New York Times and it blew my mind.''
 &HT;    When she appeared in July at the gathering of TV critics from
around the country in Pasadena, the scribes found her remarkably
subdued. Was this the new Roseanne? ``No. It's the real me,'' she
says without a smile, ``unfettered by the opinions of other people.
People are always shocked when they meet me. They always say, 'Hey,
you're not like it said in The Enquirer.' I never was actually. In
real life I'm very shy.''
 &HT;    Since leaving the weekly sitcom field Barr says she's been
playing full-time mom to her kids, from 3-year-old Buck from her
marriage to Thomas, to her son Jake, 20, and her three daughters
who are 22, 23, and 27.
 &HT;    ``I put all my energy into my kids, getting them into college,
getting their own places to live, their own cars, their own
insurance. The last year was all for my kids. I think I'm a better
mom this time around.''
 &HT;    You have to wonder. Being Barr's kid during the worst of her
continuing saga can't have been the easiest path through
adolescence. ``This time with Buck,'' she says, ``I used my four
grown kids as nannies and that was just a great experience. I
brought them in to help me correct the mistakes I made the first
time. It was a very healing year for all of us. And we got real
close.''
 &HT;    The daily talk show is a grueling contest, as Magic Johnson and
scores of predecessors have learned. ``I often ask myself why I'm
doing this,'' Barr admits. ``I was ready because I had completed
the whole thing I wanted to do on `Roseanne,' but I still had more
things to say. I wasn't ready to go out to pasture just yet.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based
<TEXT>
reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</TEXT>
