<TEXT>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- REACT. What sort of reaction are Connecticut
lawmakers getting from constituents about Sen. Lieberman's speech
last night? (Possible.) Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- COLUMN. Weekly column with U.S. Reps. Dan Miller,
R-Bradenton and Porter Goss, R-Sanibel. Williams
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- MAX. U.S. Sen. Max Cleland Friday condemned President
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, but stopped well short
of calling for impeachment or resignation. Williams
</P>
<P>
   -- AGENDA. Tritium and managed-care reform highlight the agendas
of Augusta-area Reps. Charlie Norwood and Lindsey Graham in the
waning weeks of the 105th Congress. Williams
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- RADAR. Over the next several years, roads in
Northwest Indiana are going to start talking. A new safety system
being field tested in more than 20 states, including Indiana,
communicates with a car's radar detector, updating and warning
motorists of dangerous road conditions. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- POLL. Campaign reform advocates had hoped a poll they
released this week would sway U.S. Sen. Mike Dewine's opinion in an
expected vote on campaign finance next week. But the move appears
to have fallen short of the mark, as Dewine said the legislation
being pushed by the advocates is the wrong kind of reform. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- VOINOVICH. Ohio Gov. George Voinovich is one of the
highest-spending, pro-taxes governors in the country, according to
a report released this week by a Libertarian think tank. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- SPEND. Rep. James Traficant (D-Youngstown) remained one of
the biggest office spenders in Ohio's delegation. The Youngstown
representative spent the second-highest amount, $434,000 -- just
less than Rep. Dennis Kucinich, whose office expended $435,000.
Most of Traficant's expenses were due to high salaries, a fact
which attracted criticism from at least one congressional watchdog
group. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- FUND. Richard Lehman, 43, of Ferndale made a
spontaneous decision late last year. An engineering geologist who
has been on workman's disability for two years, Lehman became fed
up one day when watching another television news report about
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation. So he called the
White House to ask what he could do, and soon he was in touch with
the president's legal defense fund. He quickly cut a check for
$100, the first political donation of his life, but just one of
more than 17,000 donations made to the Clinton Legal Expense Trust.
A handful of Cambria County-area residents joined Lehman, as did
more than 350 Pennsylvanians. And by and large, they still support
President Clinton. Kane
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- SENSENBRENNER. He's the most senior member of the
Wisconsin delegation and hasn't faced major opposition in an
election since 1978. Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., will play a
pivotal role in the upcoming impeachment inquiry of President
Clinton as a member of the Judiciary Committee. (Working.) Marlin
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
