<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9635 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-04 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAN BURTON WATCHES FOR CRACKS IN A GLASS HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, well. Somebody is investigating Rep. Dan Burton's sex
life.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't happen to a nicer guy.
</P>
<P>
   Burton is the Indiana Republican who called President Clinton a
``scumbag'' and made it perfectly clear that he considers Clinton
morally unfit to hold the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   Now we hear reports that Vanity Fair magazine has been examining
Burton's background in pursuit of what Burton calls a ``scandal
story.'' With the media posse nipping at his heels, the
sanctimonious congressman is suddenly admitting to ``rough spots''
in his 38-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, Burton will be confessing that he caused
pain in his marriage. He'll be confirming that he misled people,
including even his wife. He might even concede that he indulged in
relationships that were not appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Such things can happen when politicians start rummaging around
in other politicians' dirty laundry. This must be what the
old-timers meant when they talked about the pot calling the kettle
black.
</P>
<P>
   The cliches just scream to be heard. What goes around comes
around. You reap what you sow. People who live in glass houses...
</P>
<P>
   Burton attempted to pre-empt the scandal by issuing a _ pardon
the expression _ blanket apology.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Associated Press, Burton said at a town hall
meeting in Frankfort, Ind., ``Anything you read in the paper that I
should be accountable for, I apologize in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   And we thought Clinton's apology was vague.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the catch-all nature of his pre-scandal apology, Burton
evidently has committed enough private indiscretions that he isn't
sure which one _ or ones _ that Vanity Fair is investigating.
Wouldn't be ironic if Burton has participated in so many ``not
appropriate'' relationships that he makes Clinton look like a monk?
</P>
<P>
   After all, you'd have to figure that if Burton had strayed only
a time or two, he would know exactly what Vanity Fair was working
on. You'd have to figure that he could have offered a more specific
apology.
</P>
<P>
   Burton was spouting off the other day about how he will ``own
up'' to his sins if and when any bad behavior is reported by the
media. Burton said he will do the right thing _ not lie, mislead
and dissemble, as Clinton has done.
</P>
<P>
   Swell. But if Burton truly wants to demonstrate that he's a man
of integrity _ something, he has said, that Clinton is not _ then
why should he wait until the other shoe drops to ``own up'' to
whatever it is that he's done? Why not ``own up'' now, instead of
waiting to find out what Vanity Fair or other media scandalmongers
have uncovered?
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, why doesn't Burton call a news conference,
admit to all the inappropriate conduct that the media might be
inclined to expose, and apologize for each and every indiscretion?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is obvious. Like any rational human being, he'd
rather not reveal any secrets unless he has to. Like anyone who
cherishes his privacy _ like Clinton, even _ Burton believes that
his private life should be private. Or as private as he can keep
it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Burton blames Vanity Fair's interest in his
sexual history on the Clinton White House, suggesting that the
president's henchmen are trying to intimidate him because he is
chairman of the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee and
in that capacity is investigating allegations of campaign finance
violations by the 1996 Clinton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The AP reported that Burton's brother, a state representative,
pointed out that ex-Clinton press secretary Dee Dee Myers works for
Vanity Fair. The magazine dismissed as ``totally ludicrous'' the
suggestion that it might be hauling water for the Clintonites.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, almost nothing is totally ludicrous where the Clinton
White House is concerned. But Burton is learning the hard way what
he should have known about politics: If a congressman wants to call
the president a ``scumbag,'' the congressman's glass house had
better be bulletproof.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
