<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9641 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-APES-635-SFCHRON &LR;      09-04 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-APES-635-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WASTELAND POPULATED BY BIRDS AND APES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now we've surely all sent away for our personal Singing Bird
Clocks (``Mommy, Mommy, that's an oriole!'') for only $19.99 plus
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Singing Bird Clock commercials seem to be doing a heap to keep
PAX TV in chirping fettle.
</P>
<P>
   These educational clocks, which turn little girls into annoying
pests (``Mommy, Mommy, it's a pterodactyl!''), might not be
available in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe they are. I say that only to avoid phone calls
from hundreds of outraged proprietors of Singing Bird Clock
boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. Television. A visual medium, pervasive in the second half
of the 20th century, in which transient images of boring programs
are sent over the electromagnetic spectrum, or shoved into cables,
so that time can be killed and brain cells can evaporate like
raindrops in a desert.
</P>
<P>
   Which is about how I see ``Behind the Planet of the Apes''
(Sunday on American Movie Classics), a documentary that asks us to
believe that those ape movies were Hollywood classics.
</P>
<P>
   AMC, an otherwise agreeable cable channel, is surrounding the
documentary with one ``Planet of the Apes'' movie after another on
Sunday and Monday, until you may feel like a Singing Bird Clock
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary is hosted by Roddy McDowell, who has always been
a curious mixture of erudition and irrelevance.
</P>
<P>
   It's supposed to be two hours long. I say supposed to be because
I put the damn thing on _ last week, maybe? _ and it never ended.
</P>
<P>
   My Singing Bird Clock could have spun through spectra of
feathered vertebrates while Roddy clucked along on that tape.
</P>
<P>
   I gave up somewhere around the third sequel. McDowell seemed
bent on reliving every ``Planet of the Apes'' film and two TV
series.
</P>
<P>
   To me, ``Planet of the Apes'' was a bunch of actors in monkey
suits chasing a half-naked Charlton Heston with nets.
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably what thousands of deer would love to do, now
that Heston is president of the National Rifle Association. But
that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that's clear is that ``Planet of the Apes'' was quite
an industry from the first movie in 1968 to the TV cartoon show in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that political satire wasn't cycling through a subtle
period in 1968. Geez, you mean ``Planet of the Apes'' cleverly
turned the tables and taught us how it felt to be the underdog?
Smack my chops!
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Zanuck, who ran the 20th Century Fox studio at the
time, insists he didn't have a clue that the movie was anything but
pure sci-fi entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Statue of Liberty planted in Zuma Beach, in the film's final
scene? Not a political statement, Zanuck says. It was just a little
something to titillate the audience. This man ran a studio?
</P>
<P>
   If you care about these things, you can learn that Maurice
Evans' role as the orangutan in chief was originally slotted for
Edward G. Robinson, that Orson Welles declined the role of a
gorilla military leader in ``Beneath the Planet of the Apes'' and
that the ape revolt in ``Conquest of the Planet of the Apes'' was
modeled after the 1965 Watts riot in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   There, aren't you richer for that?
</P>
<P>
   This one is interesting, though. A caste system developed,
unintendedly, during filming. Actors in gorilla suits ate lunch
with other gorillas. Orangutans ate with orangutans. Chimps with
chimps.
</P>
<P>
   Singing Bird Clock owners probably would have confined
themselves to other Singing Bird Clock owners, ignoring Talking
Bird Clock owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no explanation for that whatsoever,'' Heston jokes
about the monkeys fraternizing only with like monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he did, you couldn't force it out of him at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
