<HEADLINE>
LOW-COST POWER COMES AS A SHOCK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scanning the newspaper computer ads has turned into an exercise
in reverse sticker shock. Even though it's part of my job to keep
tabs on what's happening with PC prices, I'm always stunned and
amazed at the amount of power $1,000 will buy you today.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, the standard for a sub-$1,000 computer was
a processor that ran in the 233- to 266-megahertz range. Now, with
competition heating up among chip makers, an increasing number of
low-cost computersrun at 300 megahertz or faster.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions that 400-megahertz systems will be selling for
around or below $1,000 by Christmas boggle the mind. But for now,
you'll have to ``settle'' for bargains like these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Aptiva E3N, $999, IBM. &UR;  &LR; Big Blue was a latecomer to the cheap
personal computer party. But IBM has staged a comeback with its E
series of Aptiva PCs.
</P>
<P>
   This Aptiva comes with a 300-megahertz Advanced Micro Devices
K6-2 chip, which has the 3D Now! extensions to help improve 3-D
graphics performance. This isn't automatic, however _ software
developers must write their programs to take advantage of the
chip's features, and AMD is working to convince game companies to
support 3D Now!
</P>
<P>
   The E3N comes with a whopping 64 megabytes of memory, a
six-gigabyte hard drive, a 56K fax modem, an ATI Rage Pro AGP video
card and a 32X CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a 100-megahertz system bus, which refers to the
speed at which information travels between the main chip and other
hardware devices. The model I tried, however, was a pre-production
unit and didn't have this feature. Indeed, the E3N felt a bit
sluggish at times; I would have liked to have tried it with the
faster system board.
</P>
<P>
   AMD has been showing off its K6-2's capabilities by creating a
special version of id Software's Quake II that works with 3D Now! I
ran both the K6 and the standard versions, and there was a
noticeable improvement in speed when using the former.
</P>
<P>
   The Aptiva has a couple of interesting programs on it that will
be a boon for novices. An ``Aptiva Adventure'' module configures
Norton Antivirus and some on-screen navigation tools that make it
easier to access the computer's features. A configuration tracker
takes a snapshot of your system when it's healthy, so you can
restore it to working order if something goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   There are two shortcomings to E3N, however. First, it has a
single, shared ISA and PCI expansion slot. That means you can add
just one card to it. Although this would be a nice, affordable game
machine, adding a Voodoo2 add-on 3-D video card means you can't
also add a network card for multiplayer competition. Choose one or
the other, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if you decide to stick with the ATI video card for your
3-D needs, it's got only two megabytes of video memory, which
limits resolution and color depth capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ NEC Ready 9883, $1,099, NEC/Packard Bell. Intel Corp.'s
Celeron processor got a bad rap when it first came out, because
early models lacked a level 2 cache, a kind of buffer that boosts
the speed of data moving into and out of the chip.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel's latest Celerons have this cache feature, and their
performance now rivals that of the more celebrated _ and more
expensive _ Pentium II chips. In fact, some analysts have wondered
why consumers now would even consider a Pentium II system, when the
Celeron-based machines have comparable performance at much lower
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Ready 9883 uses the 333-megahertz Celeron chip, and it's
easily the peppiest low-cost PC I've tried yet. This machine
handled everything I threw at it flawlessly, despite the fact that
its system bus is only 66 megahertz. I put a Creative Labs 3D
Blaster Voodoo2 card in it, with 12 megabytes of video memory, and
it ran Quake II incredibly smoothly, even at a resolution of
800-by-600 pixels. And it did not require a specially tweaked
version.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes with 64 megabytes of memory; a 6.4-gigabyte hard
drive; a 56K fax modem; and a 32X CD-ROM drive. Like the E3N, it
uses the ATI Rage Pro AGP video card, but this one has four
megabytes of video memory instead of just two. It also is much more
expandable, with two PCI slots and an ISA slot.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Aptiva, the Ready 9883 has an on-screen utility for
working with features and setting preferences. One of those buttons
is an instant connection to the Internet that automatically knows
your preferred onramp. For example, if you have an America Online
account, clicking the Internet Connect button launches the AOL
software.
</P>
<P>
   This computer really is one of the best buys I've seen so far in
the low-price class. Why wait till Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
