<HEADLINE>
GARDENING: NOT ALL THE BEST ASTERS WERE EDUCATED IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    In the garden, as elsewhere, refinement is often viewed as a
plus. Take New England and New York asters, for example. Among the
first plants to catch the eyes of European settlers, they were sent
abroad about 300 years ago and went to finishing school in the
hands of British and German nurserymen.
 &HT;    Hundreds of well-bred cultivars were created, featuring colors
ranging from pure white to rich purple and European names like
``Nesthakchen'' and ``Alma Potschke.'' Their undisputed beauty in
late-season borders, however, requires much upkeep, as they are
prone to mildew and wilts, form dense clumps requiring division
every two to three years and often need staking.
 &HT;    Those are not traits that I want. Rather, I choose plants that
are not only attractive but also easy to care for. Thus, my borders
in central New Jersey are filled with ``common asters,'' the
overlooked ones that remained rooted at home.
 &HT;    Sky blue aster (A. azureus) is the first to flower, usually by
mid-August. The popular name is misleading because the flower is
actually a pale, almost purplish blue rather than the rich blue of
a clear sky. The rays _ or petals as they are popularly known _
surround a sunny yellow central disk.
 &HT;    When cut back in June, sky blue aster forms a bushy two-foot
clump of one-inch flowers that open for almost a month. Left on its
own, it reaches almost four feet and lightly flops among other
flowers. I pair it with boltonia (B. asteroides), a white-flowered
aster relative, and the two form a graceful end-of-summer
combination in borders outdoors and arrangements indoors.
 &HT;    Umbellatus aster (A. umbellatus) is the longest blooming and
perhaps least known of these plants. Sometimes called flat-topped
aster, a name that in no way conveys its beauty, it bears masses of
creamy white three-quarter-inch flowers. Resembling petite daisies,
these asters start their six to seven weeks of bloom in mid- to
late August.
 &HT;    Umbellatus aster can be used in many ways. In early June, I cut
back a six-foot-long planting to about 14 inches. This encourages
intense branching, so that when blooming starts, I have the
equivalent of an unstaked, three-foot-tall flowering hedge.
 &HT;    In my white garden, the asters are between a six-foot fence and
a Diana rose of Sharon (Hibiscus syriacus ``Diana''). Here the
asters, buttressed by the shrub, soar well over six feet and create
further privacy. Their flowers bob among Diana's lustrous
three-inch white blossoms, creating a plant fence that features
contrasts in flower shape and size.
 &HT;    Calico aster (A. lateriflorus var. horizontalis) tops off at
three feet and needs neither staking nor cutting back. It is
unusual in that it features color in both foliage and flowers.
 &HT;    The tips of the leaves, which branch off the sturdy horizontal
stems, become tinged with a purplish hue in mid-September. These
leaves peek out from the myriad half-inch blush white to pale lilac
flowers, each with a rose-colored disk, that cover the stems and
appear from mid-September into the first week or two of October.
 &HT;    Calico aster is perfect for anyone who wants a soft, pastel
presence in the garden at a fiery-colored time of year.
 &HT;    In my borders, the sky blue, umbellatus and calico asters are in
full sun, where they perform best. When heath aster (A. ericoides)
is similarly placed, it forms a dense, thick mound packed with
sprays of flowers that rival those of a heath in full bloom.
 &HT;    Given its tolerance of dry situations, however, I decided to
experiment and planted it in a tree-shrouded spot that receives no
more than two hours of morning sun. It has been happy there for
seven years now, growing about two feet tall and featuring open,
airy stems profusely dotted with half-inch white flowers for almost
three weeks, starting shortly after Labor Day.
 &HT;    White wood aster (A. divaricatus) is an outstanding dry shade
plant. Nevertheless, despite being sent abroad well over a century
ago and being used by Gertrude Jekyll in her fall borders in
England, it has yet to become popular with European breeders or
American gardeners.
 &HT;    It is one of those plants that are just too easy to grow. And to
be honest, until it bursts forth with its late-season flowers, it
is rather bland and inconspicuous. (If I had the naturally
occurring form with dark purple stems, I might change this
assessment.) Starting in late August, however, this plant earns its
presence with its five-week display of abundant one-inch flowers
with white rays and purple centers surrounding a small yellow disk.
 &HT;    Once you incorporate one or more of these widely adaptable,
no-maintenance ``common asters,'' you might agree that refinement
is needed not in their appearance but rather in the eyes of
gardeners.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Asters are available by mail from Forest Farm, 990 Tetherow
Road, Williams, Ore. 97544, (541) 846-7269, catalog, $4; Prairie
Nursery, PO Box 306, Westfield, Wis. 53964, (800) 476-9453, free
catalog, and Primrose Path, RD 2, Box 110, Scottdale, Pa. 15683,
(724) 887-6756, catalog, $2.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    THIS WEEK: SEEDS TO SAVE, SEEDS TO SUPPRESS 
 &HT;    By PATRICIA JONAS
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Save seed of heirloom vegetables and climbing vines like
hyacinth bean. Pods of beans and peas left to dry on the vine give
up their seed easily when rubbed gently. Store seed in labeled,
airtight moisture-free containers like 35-mm film canisters.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ignore weeds in the garden. They will produce abundant
seed that will remain dormant in the soil over winter, so pulling
up or cutting off seed heads will save weeding next year.
</P>
<P>
   If you are ordering bulbs to naturalize in a lawn, good choices
are masses of small, very early-blooming bulbs like snow crocus
(Crocus chrysanthus), spring snowflake (Leucojum vernum),
glory-of-the-snow (Chionodoxa luciliae) and the English favorite,
snowdrop (Galanthus nivalis).
</P>
<P>
   In spring, if the mower is set high and the first mowing
postponed several weeks, they will thrive and multiply. Plant these
bulbs when they arrive, but hold off on tulips until the end of
October or later.
</P>
</TEXT>
