<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A MOLEHILL OUT OF A MOUNTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, September 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The choice for the trip was between a large, luxury, four-door
with juice drive or a sporty coupe with a five-speed manual _ which
means it was no choice at all. This trip entailed a ride to the
home of the wildest weather on the continent to accompany a team
celebrating the 99th anniversary of an automotive landmark: the
first automobile ascent to the top of New Hampshire's 6,288-foot
Mount Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was Aug. 31, 1899, when Freelan Oscar Stanley, with his wife,
Flora, took the tiller of a Locomobile steamer and made the
perilous ascent up New England's highest mountain. If the ascent
was rough, the descent was even more problematical _ how does one
guide a car with virtually no brakes 7.6 miles down an average 12
percent grade? Flora remarked in her diary that it was ``easy as
falling off a log.'' Rumor has it that F.O. Stanley dragged a log
to slow the car on the descent.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is Monday, Aug. 31, 1998, and Brent Campbell and Norm
Shanklin are preparing to commemorate the Stanley feat by taking
Campbell's 1908 Gentleman's Speedy Racer, a 20-horsepower Stanley
Steamer, up the Mount Washington Auto Road. It is sunny and mild
where we stand, 4,600 feet below the peak, listening to the hiss of
the burner. At the summit, dark clouds scud across the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Your columnist is somewhat grateful that the Stanley racer has
but two seats, both of them occupied; I will ascend ahead and
follow the steamer from the four-mile mark in an Acura 2.3 CL, that
sporty little coupe _ with a proper heater, air conditioning, seat
belts, air bags, and a windshield, all of which are lacking in the
Stanley. With me is Stanley Museum director Susan S. Davis, who
will photograph the event.
</P>
<P>
   The Auto Road is a private road, built in the middle of the last
century, an engineering marvel in its day. Today, if you have the
right car _ some automatics are unfit for the descent _ you can pay
the toll and, if you are smart, read the instructions and listen to
the instructional tape or CD provided. Or, if you have the wrong
car or simply prefer, you may pay the fare and take the stage, a
comfortable van professionally driven, to the summit and back.
</P>
<P>
   The four-mile ascent to the initial observation point is a piece
of cake for the Acura CL _ and a good deal of fun, too, as manners
prevail on the trail. Descenders have the right of way; slow
ascenders pull off to allow faster vehicles to pass. The ascent is
in second gear, at modest speed and fairly high r.p.m., although
the twists and turns of the road make it seem as if we're ascending
at a breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   At the four-mile overlook,the view is breathtaking and the wind
is fierce. In the distance, I can hear the Stanley's pumps
chattering; as it nears, the nearly silent chuffing of the steam
engine becomes audible, then suddenly the gray car spurts into
sight rounding a bend _ Shanklin is now driving, having switched
with Campbell on the fly!
</P>
<P>
   As the steamer passes up the slope, I ease the Acura onto the
path, and Davis climbs through the sunroof to capture the ascent on
film. The pavement ends, the road narrows, the view is spectacular,
I see no guardrails _ this is no place for an acrophobe.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it is difficult to hold the Acura behind the steamer
as it slows on very steep grades _ here the steamer has the
advantage in full torque at negligible r.p.m. At other times, it is
difficult to keep pace with the Stanley as it gallops without
transmission to hinder it.
</P>
<P>
   At the summit, we lose sight of virtually everything as dense
fog shrouds the mountaintop. It is windy, cold; we have passed from
late summer to early winter. The steamer has made the ascent in 28
minutes, 30 seconds, give or take a second or two.
</P>
<P>
   The fog lifts, the sun beams, it is time for the descent. How
does one guide a steamer with rear-only mechanical brakes down the
mountain? ``We lower it with another car and a tow strap,''
Shanklin says. Which car? Shanklin produces a nylon tow strap,
passes it around the rear axle of the Stanley, protecting the paint
with sheepskin guides. ``Nice of you to bring the right car,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Acura has a tow hook amidships up front underneath _ it's
purpose is to hold the car fast to the deck of a ship en route from
Japan. I hand Shanklin the keys and take to the passenger seat;
Davis climbs into the Stanley. I am sitting a few inches from the
edge of the road, the edge of the world up here. With occasional
stops to cool the brakes, the long, slow descent is another piece
of cake, albeit a boring slice.
</P>
<P>
   The Acura 2.3 CL with its premium package of leather, is $23,360
plus $435 delivery for a jaunty little car with a 2.254-liter,
16-valve, four-cylinder engine and manual gear box. For a bit more
money, it becomes the 3.0 CL with a V-6 engine _ automataic
transmissions are available, at a price. The car is well equipped
with all the niceties, fancy radio, and speed-sensitive steering.
The glove box is small, but that premium package includes pockets
in the seat backs and a covered bin between the seats _ its lid is
an armrest partially obscuring one of two cupholders in front of
it. Adults will fit in the rear. Handling is very good,
acceleration is good off the mark, but the little engine is
somewhat anemic, tops out early _ passing is best done in third
gear, borders on hopeless in fourth. Forget fifth. Fuel mileage is
very good; the CL posted 28.95 miles per gallon for 1,001 miles
traveled _ including the mountaineering. Anyhow, if you're in the
neighborhood of Gorham, N.H., next Aug. 31, the Stanley Steamers
will be back in force, and a '99 Locomobile is being readied for
another run to the clouds 100 years after F.O. and Flora Stanley
made a molehill of a mountain to prove that the automobile was here
to stay _ but, alas, it was not to be as a steamer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
