<SLUG> BC-RECESSION-STYLE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELL THE RANGE ROVER; IT'S FORD TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So, the long slide begins. This time, though, instead
of being boiled in oil, like they were in 1987, investors look as
though they will get a slow poaching. If 1987 was a head-on at 60
miles per hour, 1998 is more like running out of gas on the Garden
State just after you enter the express lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 100 points here, 100 points there _ pretty soon it begins
to add up, and the formerly flush will have to start trading down.
After nearly seven fat years on Wall Street, America may be poised
for a life-style retooling.
</P>
<P>
   It will be subtle. Chastened by the last market crash, the Wall
Street winners spent their cash with a lot less flash this time
around. There are no swaggering figures on the scale of Michael
Milken, Donald Trump or Ivan Boesky. There was less cocaine, more
Deepak Chopra.
</P>
<P>
   The arrogance of the 1980s gave way to humble gratitude in the
'90s. America enjoyed the party for as long as it lasted, but
always there was the nagging sense that midnight would arrive, the
lights would dim and everyone would have to go home. It was fun
while it lasted, but it had to end, and the end, in retrospect,
could have been predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Hemlines, historically an accurate leading economic indicator,
plunged right down to the ankles this spring, anticipating the
Dow's dive. And could it have been anything other than an omen when
several Manhattan restaurateurs were rounded up last month for
selling illicit Cuban cigars, the very emblem of the '90s-style
Master of the Universe?
</P>
<P>
   No one is going to be trading in a Cohibo for a Tiparillo, but
adjustments will be made. The signature '90s car, the sport utility
vehicle, will not go away, but the proud owner of a road-ruling
Range Rover 4.0 may sneakily consider downsizing to a Ford
Explorer. And if the market continues to contract, there's always a
Kia Sportage. Have your eye on a Porsche 911? Try thinking
Volkswagen Bug. Same basic shape.
</P>
<P>
   At Manhattan's top steakhouses, the double magnums of Petrus
will go back to the wine cellar. Instead, several sommeliers around
town predict, the bonus babies who pushed the Bordeaux prices
straight through the roof will return to comfort wines. ``They'll
go back to California, to wines like Beringer Private Reserve
Cabernet, or anything by Phelps,'' said Andrea Immer, the wine
director at Windows on the World. ``When you're in a depressed
state of mind, you don't get experimental.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Johnnes, the wine director at Montrachet, looks into his
crystal ball and sees strange things. For the cult wines of the
'90s, he said, look to Spain or Chile, where they turn out wines
Wall Street wouldn't gargle with a year ago. ``They might want to
look for the boutique beers out of Belgium,'' he added helpfully.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Although their wine sales might sag at the top end, restaurants
could do well out of a market correction. ``Good food is one of the
last things you give up,'' Clark Wolf, a restaurant consultant,
said. ``You're more likely to give up your trip to that clever
little island off the coast of whatever, so we may actually see
more restaurant-going.''
</P>
<P>
   But count on the menu to change as foodies come eye-to-eye with
a bear market. New Yorkers have been gobbling foie gras and
truffles fast enough to create shortages. A more chaste cuisine may
lie around the corner, not the comfort food of the early '90s but
less indulgent fare. ``We are going to find new peasant foods,''
Wolf predicted. ``I see herbs. I see turkey burgers.''
</P>
<P>
   If it does nothing else, a punctured Dow could thin out the
surplus population of cell phones, easing the pressure on area
codes and eliminating the widespread pretraumatic stress syndrome
associated with potential loss of one's 212 status. With luck, ugly
additions like 908, 773 and 847 could be recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, the market should let the air out of grossly
distended Internet stocks. The '80s had junk bonds. The '90s have
Yahoo and Amazon.com. and, if ever a scapegoat figure is going to
emerge from the current mess, Bill Gates, supreme lord of the Net,
could be it. The Justice Department's antitrust case against
Microsoft comes up soon, and a comeuppance for its chief executive,
Gates could ease a lot of social tension.
</P>
<P>
   Gates replaced ``greed is good,'' Gordon Gekko's famous '80s
mantra, with a shambling, Jimmy Stewart style. There's a lot of
free-floating anxiety in the air. Gates could be the man for the
moment, a lightning rod for a lot of bad feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion looks as if it's right on the money, or lack of it.
Although riding a wave of prosperity, designers hedged their bets
for this fall, sneaking in more luxurious fabrics, fondling a
little fur, but keeping the look dressed-down. It's a lot easier to
climb down from cashmere than a Christian Lacroix pouf skirt, the
image of '80s excess. As though anticipating the recessionary mood,
designers from Marc Jacobs to Calvin Klein have invested in a new
color this season: gray. Gray is perfect. It suggests mild
depression rather than black despair.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, someone ought to check in on Ira Rennert, the
reclusive industrialist, out there in Bridgehampton. Is that house
he is planning still going to be 72,000 square feet? Or is he maybe
thinking of a nice four-bedroom Cape Cod?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
