<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFINISH WORN COUNTER STRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The strip of oak edging along my kitchen counters are nice,
but the strip in front of the sink is wearing, and the oak is
showing through and is dirty. How can I clean it, stain it the
proper color, and finish it? Can I apply a finish that will last
more than three years?
</P>
<P>
   PEG FORBES, Franklin, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The wood strips, being varnished, do not stand up to abrasion
and water for long. To refinish, try redoing just the worn area,
although getting it to match the rest of the strip in color and
finish is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, sand the area to the bare wood, apply a light oak
or similar stain to try to match the original, and finish off with
varnish. The only problem is that being three years old, the finish
is probably water-based polyurethane, so you will have to use
water-based polyurethane to finish, because oil-based polyurethane
is incompatible with the water-based. Apply at least three coats,
more if possible. The water-based polyurethane does not stand up to
wear and tear very well.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a more durable finish, you have to sand the entire
strip to the bare oak and restain. If you get every bit of finish
off, you can use an oil-based polyurethane; it is much better, in
my opinion, than the water-based; apply two or three coats of high
gloss for a finish that will last more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having a rubber roof put on my shed dormer, which has a
shallow pitch, too shallow for shingles. Should I put in a ridge
vent where the shallow dormer roof and the opposite roof meet? The
opposite roof is steeper than the dormer roof, but I am concerned
about the vent leaking on the shallow side.
</P>
<P>
   JOYCE RILEY, Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You have a legitimate concern, because blowing water is more
likely to get into the shallow side, despite the baffles that ridge
vents have. But there is an answer. Put in the ridge vent, but cut
the roof sheathing only on the steep side of the ridge. Keep the
shallow side of the ridge closed, and you'll get no leaks. The vent
will do just half its duty, but half is a sight better than not at
all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh oh, we've been caught using a brand name the wrong way. Last
Sunday we mentioned Ice &AMP; Water Shield on a roof as a protection
against leaking from ice dams. It's a strip of rubberized material
applied along the eave edge of a roof.
</P>
<P>
   Mark DerMugrditchian called to say the information is correct,
but the use of Ice &AMP; Water Shield is not. The correct use is W.R.
Grace's Ice &AMP; Water Shield; it is the copyrighted word for the
rubberized sheet material pioneerd by W.R. Grace, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Good point, Mark, and thank you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. During the hurricane scare, somehow or other paraffin oil
spilled in the car, and does it ever smell! It soaked the carpeting
in the back of an old station wagon, and the carpet is not
removable. A week ago, a friend used Joy to break down the oil, but
the smell remains. Can I ever get rid of it?
</P>
<P>
   A.P.L., Woods Hole, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Paraffin oil certainly does stink, because it is petroleum
based, much like kerosene or paint thinner, or, heaven forbid,
diesel or heating oil, which really does reek.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope. If the oil is fresh, simply pile a whole
bunch of an absorbent such as baking soda on it. Leave it for an
hour (you will probably see it changing color as it absorbs the
oil), sweep it up, and throw it away. Repeat as necessary. The Joy
emulsified the oil to make it easier to be absorbed. If the
absorbent doesn't seem to be doing much good, wet the oil with a
solution of detergent and water, then apply the absorbent. The
absorbent works best if the material being absorbed is liquid. You
can use Speedy Dry or cat box litter (both are absorbent clays)
instead of baking soda.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a wood storm door with an arched top, to match the
front door of my house. Trouble is, it is solid, without a window,
and is not very inviting. I would like to replace it with an
arched-top wood storm with windows. But where can I find one?
</P>
<P>
   A NEW ENGLAND CALLER
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We looked and looked and came up with these possible sources:
</P>
<P>
   Elegant Entries, 45 Water St., Worcester, MA 01604,
508-755-5237. While they specialize in regular doors, they might
make a storm to order.
</P>
<P>
   Curved tops and other shapes by Allied Windows, 2724 West
McMicken Ave., Cincinatti, OH 45214. They might also make doors.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's Old House Store, Waukeshaw, Wisc., 414-542-0134.
</P>
<P>
   Half-round-top aluminum storm door to cover round-topped main
door. Made by Walco-Chase, Waltham Aluminum, 250 Calvary St.,
Waltham, MA 02154.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration Resources of Hanover, 781-878-3794.
</P>
<P>
   Could you build a window into the present round-topped door?
It's just a thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
