<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LURIE-NOVELS-770&AMP;ADD-     09-04 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LURIE-NOVELS-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDIES OF MANNERS, LACED WITH MORALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alison Lurie is a transoceanic novelist, equally at home on both
sides of the Atlantic, but with an even greater following in
England than in the United States. Although she lives most of the
year in Ithaca, N.Y., where she teaches children's literature at
Cornell University, she keeps an apartment in London. She also has
a home in Key West, Fla., the setting of her new novel, ``The Last
Resort,'' and for her a kind of neverland where fantasies are made
real.
</P>
<P>
   It has often been said that she writes comedies of manners.
That, she admitted in a recent interview, is more accurate than
saying she writes ``tragedies of morals.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that her novels are comedies of manners and morals,
which explore the lives of the literati and the relationships
between the sexes in academia. In that sense, she has more in
common with English authors from Evelyn Waugh to David Lodge than
she does with many of her American contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   The central character in ``The Last Resort'' is Jenny Walker,
whose husband, Wilkie, is a famous nature writer suffering a
late-in-life depression. Jenny, Wilkie's dutiful researcher and
all-around literary aide, persuades him to go to Key West in the
hope of returning him to his writing. As often happens in Lurie
novels, it is the female character who makes the discoveries, Jenny
finding a sense of self beyond her role as wife and mother.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who is 71, indicated that in writing the book she
was fully prepared for feminists who might criticize Jenny for
being so subservient to her spouse. Looking back on her own youth,
she said she grew up during a period ``when a woman who didn't
devote herself to a husband and family was not a real woman.'' Now,
she added, ``a woman who doesn't have a career is not a real
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Lurie, ``the pendulum has swung too far.'' Her aim was
to restore the balance, letting Jenny choose her own path even as
it includes a brief romance with another woman.
</P>
<P>
   The lesbian in her book is a partial answer to complaints she
received about an earlier novel, ``The Truth About Loren Jones'':
``There was a gay woman in it who was not very admirable.'' As is
often the case in her books, she has assembled a colorful cast of
minor characters whose lives intersect on several levels.
</P>
<P>
   In The New York Times Book Review, Francine Prose called ``The
Last Resort'' a ``sparkling, smart new novel,'' in which the author
``has selected a dozen or so exemplary types, added some highly
volatile elements and put them out to sizzle in a paradoxically
balmy and claustrophobic setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lurie's other principal reason for writing ``The Last
Resort'' was, she said, to deal with ``a fear of not being in
control of your life, about what it's like to grow old.'' That part
focuses on Wilkie, the aging environmentalist: ``He feels that what
he's done has had no effect, which is a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about Wilkie's fate brought the author around to the
subject of fame. ``Norman Podhoretz once wrote this book explaining
that the way to become well known was to attack people who are well
known. But if you limit yourself to attacks, after a while you look
around and there's nothing but smashed lumber and broken stones,
and you haven't built anything. There you are standing in the
debris and nobody's interested anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Following her own direction, Ms. Lurie has created a relatively
small but clearly defined, affirmative body of work, 10 books of
fiction along with several works of nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   The novels are a connected series of close looks at Americans in
her time. As with David Lodge and others, Ms. Lurie writes about a
floating cast of characters. Even as the books move to Key West
from Corinth University (a stand-in for Cornell) in ``The War
Between the Tates'' and London for her Pulitzer Prize-winning
``Foreign Affairs,'' people reappear.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of characters' finding lives in different books is, she
said, one point in favor of Balzac over Dickens, whose characters
do not return even when the books take place at the same time in
the same part of London. ``Nobody you know is there,'' she said,
with a tinge of regret.
</P>
<P>
   In the four decades she has been writing novels, Ms. Lurie's
characters have grown up, married, divorced and remarried _ as has
the author. She is married for the second time and has three adult
sons.
</P>
<P>
   To her readers, characters have become old friends. ``It's like
real life,'' she said. ``People you knew in high school will turn
up again.'' To avoid making mistakes of genealogy, the author has
created a chart for use as a family tree.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For example, Barbie Mumpson, who had a small role in ``Foreign
Affairs,'' is one of the characters who finds renewal in Key West
in the new book, and there is every indication that she might be
heard from again in a future Lurie novel.
</P>
<P>
   The longest-running character is probably Leonard Zimmern, L.D.
Zimmern, known as Lennie, a cynical literary critic who seems to
pop up in most of her books and has something snappish to say about
anyone else who happens to be a writer.
</P>
<P>
   Lennie's lineage can be traced from ``Real People'' (a 1969
novel about an artists' colony) through ``The Truth About Lorin
Jones'' (the title character is his half-sister) to ``The Last
Resort,'' in which he makes a cameo appearance. ``As usual,''
writes Ms. Lurie, ``he was wearing an old denim work shirt and a
skeptical, penetrating expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the origin of Lennie, she said, ``He's the dark side
of my character.'' Then she admitted that as an intellectual he was
a bit like Alfred Kazin or Irving Howe: ``I think that, like Kazin,
Lennie is getting a little nicer in his old age.''
</P>
<P>
   The impulse to inject Lennie Zimmern into her books is
irresistible, she said. With his stern, high literary demands, he
plays the role of devil's advocate who ``stirs up trouble wherever
he goes.'' Ms. Lurie said her instinct as a writer was ``to make
things turn out right for people I know and care about.'' Lennie's
presence assures that the books will have a certain edge of irony.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether she would ever write a book with Lennie as
the central character, she explained that she already had _ her
first novel, unpublished and jettisoned. Lennie has gone on to have
a long history in other people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   What would Lennie say if, as a critic, he were called upon to
review ``The Last Resort''? He might read it, Ms. Lurie said, but,
as with his role models, he would not deign to review it. If he
were asked to comment, she said, ``I expect he would say that it's
a really good book to take to the beach.'' She added, ``That's
assuming he didn't know he was in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
