s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-ISUZU-ART-     09-04 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-ISUZU-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'98 ISUZU AMIGO: A BRAWNY LITTLE BRUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mini-sport utilities are for poseurs who covet the look, not the
function. Face it: the real appeal of the wildly popular Subaru
Forester, Toyota RAV4 and Honda CRV is comfort, splendid road
manners and a great view of traffic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One significant exception has been the Jeep Wrangler, the Jeep
closest in spirit to the tough, simple general-purpose vehicles
that landed with the Allies at Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Wrangler has to make room for some newcomers, including
the Isuzu Amigo, a brawny little two-door beast with serious
off-road capability and impressive V6 power to match. The downside
is a harsh ride, wretched side vision and sticker shock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Isuzu Amigo made its debut in 1989 as a stripped-down
utility for the young at heart. It was noisy and underpowered, and
the canvas roof over what would otherwise have been the rear of a
very small pick-up truck offered minimal protection against the
elements.
</P>
<P>
   But it was cheap as four-wheel-drive vehicles go, cute and a
great hit with people in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The new 1998 Amigo (the old model rode into the sunset in 1994)
still comes with a canvas top and soft plastic windows in the back.
But a hard-roof option is planned as a 1999 model. Both versions
offer more of what appealed to buyers of the old Amigo, plus an
optional dose of muscle and luxury.
</P>
<P>
   The base model has a 2.2 liter, 130 horsepower, four-cylinder
engine, lean for a 3,335-pound truck. But the optional 3.2-liter,
205-horsepower aluminum V6, producing 214 pounds of torque at a
modest 3,000 rpm, provides oomph.
</P>
<P>
   All that power could be downright dangerous hitched to the
primitive suspension of the earlier-generation Amigo. But the Isuzu
engineers did their homework: while the vehicle feels heavy, it
accelerates out of corners with impressive stability and only
modest body roll. Anti-lock brakes and a somewhat mushy five-speed
manual gearbox are standard.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't try to navigate the Great Dismal Swamp in my test
vehicle. It was fine, though, on poorly maintained dirt roads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Amigo is noisy at highway speeds, with the canvas top
chattering in the wind. The stiff shocks guarantee that you feel
every bump. And the backseat resembles a church pew, with the
saving grace that it folds down easily to add cargo capacity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the front seats are comfy and supportive. The fit and finish
are up to Japanese standards _ though the truck is manufactured in
Indiana. And the stereo speakers are a cut above economy grade.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the busy, bumpy highway ride, the Amigo's only big
fault is the big rear ``C'' pillars that stiffen the frame but
create huge blind spots on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Check that: there's also the price. While a two-wheel-drive
version can be had for a shade more than $15,000, four-wheel drive
and the V6 engine push it close to $20,000. A lot of money for your
average surfer dude.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A versatile mini-ute, aimed at the macho end of
the youth market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
