<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9778 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLPAPER-MAGAZINE$AD     09-04 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLPAPER-MAGAZINE$ADV06-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WALLPAPER GENERATION: SELLING OUT, PARING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If a tabloid television talk show decided to visit
downtown Manhattan, Kelly Galligan and Ed Briggs _ proudly seated
on a recently bought 1950s square-cornered sofa in their apartment
_ would make ideal guests for an episode called ``We Traded the
Grunge Life for an Eames Chair.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple admit, sheepishly, that they were once slackers who
blasted Nirvana and made a pact to stay unemployed during the Gulf
War so they could watch CNN. Today, Ms. Galligan is gainfully
working at a new-media production company in Silicon Alley and
Briggs works in the art department of the television show ``Law and
Order.''
</P>
<P>
   And like a large number of their fellow downtowners, they've
chosen mid-century modernism _ the industrial, futuristic design
style of the 1950s and '60s _ to mark their transition to
affluence.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a Calvin Klein tank top, slim jeans and black rubber
Adidas sandals, Ms. Galligan, 31, described how one day they put
their funky votive candles and wrought-iron bed into storage and
painted their natural-wood floors a lacquered black. They filled
their Chelsea apartment with such modernica as a fiberglass '50s
Tulip chair by Eero Saarinen, a shag rug, an amoeba-shaped coffee
table and two space-age chrome lamps they found on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the Change,'' Briggs, 46, said. ``A lot of our
friends have gone through it, too. They show up for work one day
wearing yellow-tinted prescription glasses, the next day it's Gucci
loafers and finally the long hair gets chopped off.''
</P>
<P>
   A wave of downtowners who once embodied the ``Rent'' life style,
partial to thrift-store fashions and long hours at coffee houses,
has been transformed into an upwardly mobile, entrepreneurial
crowd. They can be described as the Wallpaper Generation, after the
two-year-old design and life-style magazine that has given an
ultra-hip spin to the retro-future look of the postwar decades. It
is a generation that breathes technology, fast travel and designer
labels.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, it wants to be stylishly poised for the millennium _
in '70s-inspired Gucci clothes, conducting international business
on a tiny Motorola cell phone, while lounging on a Florence Knoll
sofa, circa 1954, like the one in Tom Ford's Paris apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them global nomads,'' said Tyler Brule, 29, the editor
in chief of Wallpaper. ``Whether they're a West Coast snowboarder,
a copy writer for a hot advertising firm in Stockholm or a grunge
kid working in an indie record shop that suddenly got a film deal,
there's a degree of affluence all of a sudden. They're a young
international group that grew up moving around without any
possessions, and now they need advice on how to live a
sophisticated life style.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Details magazine in the late '80s and Wired in the early
'90s, Wallpaper, which is based in London, has momentarily captured
the mind-set of Generation X. It has a small circulation _ 85,000,
including 30,000 in the United States _ but its influence far
outweighs the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In many a downtown apartment, it is the only magazine on the
(boomerang shaped) coffee table. It's a name to drop at rooftop
parties and in other magazines' editorial meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from its first issue in September 1996, it attracted the
covetous attentions of publishing giants like Conde Nast and Time
Warner, and Time ultimately bought it, increasing its sporadic
publication to eight times a year. The latest issue, at 334 pages
the fattest ever, drips with ads for Prada clothes, Bulgari watches
and Smirnoff Black vodka.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Wallpaper first came out, it was like, `Why didn't I
think of that before?''' said Sean MacPherson, who owns stylish Los
Angeles night spots like Bar Marmont and El Carmen's and is also an
avid collector of modernist furniture. ``It's such an obvious idea.
If you take the idea of a tribe, where I can fly to New York City
and have more in common with someone I meet at a restaurant than my
next door neighbor, there's definitely a Wallpaper tribe.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine goes beyond traditional shelter publications by
photographing fictitious living rooms inhabited by terminally hip
models, wearing the latest fashions and dining on stylish but
birdlike meals. For the magazine's newly arrived readers, every
item, down to the wine in the glasses and the ambient-style music
on the DVD player, is listed, with prices and store information.
</P>
<P>
   But Brule maintains that the Wallpaper Generation is not just
the latest wave of yuppies. ``Our readers are not corporate _
they're entrepreneurs,'' he said. ``They would never spend all day
hung over behind a computer like in `Bright Lights, Big City,'
because most of them are self-employed or working at small
companies.'' The prototypical Wallpaper interior seems to be the
first-class lounge of an international airport.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine did not create the revival of mid-century modernist
design, which includes Scandinavian modern masters like Arne
Jacobsen and Alvar Aalto and Americans like Eero Saarinen, Florence
Knoll and Charles and Ray Eames. These visionaries used wartime
technology _ materials like fiberglass and foam rubber, and
techniques for bending plywood and molding plastics _ to make
furniture that was streamlined and easy to mass produce.
</P>
<P>
   There was a naive optimism about the future in the aluminum
lamps and stacking plastic chairs, and the look was echoed in the
Jetsonesque imagery of pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Its rediscovery by furniture dealers and collectors _ embraced
with a hipster's wink _ has been gaining momentum for several
years, and lately it has shown up everywhere from music videos to
downtown clubs. Seeking evidence? In Hollywood, Tom Ford of Gucci,
the actor Vincent Gallo, the actress Kelly Lynch and Eli Bonerz,
who owns X-Large Clothing with Mike D of the Beastie Boys, have all
bought glass-walled houses by mid-century modern architects like
John Lautner and Richard Neutra.
</P>
<P>
   In the film ``Men in Black,'' the headquarters building was
based in part on Saarinen's gull-winged TWA jetport at Kennedy
airport, and the set was decorated with Jacobsen's sensuously
futuristic Egg chairs from 1957.
</P>
<P>
   In the Queen Latifah current video, ``Bananas,'' there is a
Peter Ghyczy '60s Egg Garden chair, and in Missy Elliot's video for
``Beat Me 911,'' there is a fiberglass Gyro chair by Eero Aarnio.
The pieces are an ``easy read for a futuristic moment,'' said Paul
Hunter, the director of Queen Latifah's video.
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper, if it didn't create the trend, had peerless timing.
``It's sort of a chicken-before-the-egg question,'' said Matt
Hanna, 31, an editor at VH1, sitting on an egg-shaped cushion at
Cafeteria, a modernist-inspired restaurant in Chelsea. ``I've
always been a Wallpaper kind of guy. I just didn't know it till the
magazine came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarcely a year ago, cool Soho lounges like Spy and Wax were
furnished with Victorian velvet couches and dripping candles.
Today, clubs of the moment, including Veruka, Lot 61, Bond Street
and Moomba, have all embraced mid-century modernism. Lot 61's
blocklike rubber seating was made in the '50s for a mental
hospital. The new restaurant Bottino in the West Chelsea art
district has 100 vintage Eames chairs. And Cafeteria, co-owned by
the clothing designer Victor Alfaro, has '50s-inspired patio
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
