<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-STOCKS-$ADV07     09-04 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-STOCKS-$ADV07-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE STOCK MARKET ADVICE YOU'VE BEEN SEEKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of you, I know, have been shocked (and possibly appalled)
in recent weeks by the exuberant wildness of the stock market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At one point, for instance, you saw the Dow Jones Industrial
Average lop most of 2,000 points off the record high it reached in
mid-July, and now you are asking hard questions. For instance: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ What exactly is the stock market? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Where is Wall Street? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Say, this subject doesn't have something to do with money,
does it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the most frequent question of all: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Is now the time for me, in the context of my 401(k), to
syndicate my equity, which is mostly in leveraged junk bonds, into
securities-backed, factory-authorized sinking debentures of fully
invested small-cap futures contracts? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least that one's easy. You should definitely do that _
unless, of course, your tax bracket is between 1 and 100. In that
case, consider buying puts and calls in the global-exposure options
pit. Duh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for your other questions, well, the space I have here doesn't
come close to what would be required for full (and maybe even
helpful) answers. So instead, as usual, you will get incomplete,
misleading and ridiculous ideas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That, however, will make my answers seem quite familiar to you
because they will resemble those you've been getting from your
brokers, bankers and financial advisers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, if you are going to be an investor in this kind of
ticklish market, you need to determine your risk tolerance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, you are tempted to yell at your canary and
slit your cat's wrists (if any) when the S&AMP;P 500 average (S&AMP;P
stands for Stocks &AMP; Provisions) drops 10 points, you may be better
off putting your money into nincompoop long-term investments like
non-interest-bearing checking accounts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' you ask, ``how will that make me any money?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, you may not exactly make any money, in the commonly
thought of meaning of those words, but you won't have to buy a
calculator to keep track of your earnings. And you won't have to
pay fees to stock brokers. Besides all that, Uncle Sam will get no
part of your earnings, there being none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If, in mid-July, when the Dow Jones Industrial Average was in
the 9,300 range, you had inherited, say, $10,000 and put all of it
into a stupid interest-free checking account and spent none of it,
you'd still have $10,000 today. Which, given minimal inflation,
would be worth about $9,994.78. Give or take a five spot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you'd put your $10,000 into an S&AMP;P index
fund, you would have felt as if you'd lost your shirt the day the
market dropped 512 points, and you'd be crying about it and
generally making a pest of yourself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a year from now when the Dow Jones Industrial Average
is above 10,000 (oh, it will too be), your $10,000 will be worth a
lot more, whereas your numskull checking account, if you haven't
spent any of it, will be worth maybe $9,988 or something and you'd
be crying and generally making a pest of yourself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You know, as I think about your reaction to this whole thing,
you aren't looking very good. In fact, you're turning into someone
I'd frankly rather not know. And if you don't shape up soon I'm
going to quit giving you this quality financial advice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I'm glad I'm not in the investment advice business. I'd
have to put up whiny, unsatisfied clients. As a columnist I simply
have to put up with whiny, unsatisfied readers. But the most I'm
costing them is 50 cents a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column for release Monday, Sept. 7, and after.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
