<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLPAPER-MAGAZINE-$A     09-04 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLPAPER-MAGAZINE-$ADV06-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: patio chairs.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even Stone Gossard, a guitarist for Pearl Jam, one of the last
surviving grunge acts, is a co-owner of a new modernist-inspired
club, ARO.space, in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely wanted to move away from that
found-in-a-thrift-shop look,'' said David Schefer, who designed
Moomba and Veruka.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Look, 32, an architect who was sipping an oversize
cosmopolitan at Standard in the East Village, another hot spot that
has adopted the style, explained it this way: ``Try to imagine that
downtown was a big college town. Now, it's grown up and wants to be
more responsible and clean.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bond Street, which looks like a Zen version of a Gucci ad,
with spare dark tables and muted olive banquettes, a stylist in a
black Daryl K T-shirt who goes by the single name Sabrina rested
her chopsticks next to the tiny sushi roll she was sharing with a
friend. ``It's very Wallpaper, isn't it?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, furniture and interior design have acquired a hipness
once reserved for fashion designers and alternative music. At Form
and Function, a new store at 95 Vandam St. that sells rare Eames
pieces and vintage electronics like the first-ever Walkman-style
headset from 1970, Fred Schneider of the B-52s rock band is an
owner; shoppers include musicians like Moby and Mike D.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Rolling Stone interview, Mike D said Wallpaper is
one of the only magazines he subscribes to, and he mused about
starting a line of home accessories.
</P>
<P>
   The most unlikely crowd is gravitating to the Wallpaper look. On
television monitors facing Lafayette Street from Supreme, a
skateboard shop, educational films by the Eameses are shown. ``The
cool furniture just sticks out,'' said James Jebbia, the owner of
Supreme, as well as of Stussy, a major skateboard and hip-hop
clothing line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many skate graphics and logos are influenced by the simplicity
and humor of Eames or Nelson,'' Jebbia, a collector of modernist
furniture, maintained. ``When my friends come in from Japan or
London, the first thing they want to do is check out the fresh
modern furniture stores downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly many admiring the Eameses through the window of
Supreme have no clue to the historical place of their work. And
that seems true of many members of the Wallpaper Generation. Jim
Walrod, 33, a co-owner of Form and Function, said the appeal of
mid-century modernism to Generation X, even those without knowledge
of its origins, is natural because of ``an invisible reference
point'' young people acquired after years of exposure to the art
direction of old movies and television shows, not to mention the
teak and stainless-steel contents of their parents' living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids with no design training will walk over to a Swan chair or
an old radio and just start smiling,'' Walrod said. ``They don't
know why they're interested, but it's probably because they saw it
on `Logan's Run' or at their aunt's house.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Morales, 28, who recently quit his job at Stussy to
become a full-time modernist furniture dealer, echoed the point.
``It's like the furniture belongs to our generation even though it
was made 40 or 50 years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Frankie Inglese, a downtown deejay who has stocked his space
age bachelor pad with vintage electronics, traces his love of space
age design to mid-60's album covers. ``It's nearly the year 2000,''
he said. ``We have great technology, like cell phones, the Internet
and digital cameras. But we're still sitting on eyesores by Ikea.
This is not what the future was supposed to look like.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year and a half, older downtown stores specializing
in industrial modernist design like Moss and Troy have been joined
by a slew of newcomers, including Ace (295 Elizabeth St.),
Re-Generation (38 Renwick St.), Antik (104 Franklin St.), Twenty
(20 Prince St.), and R 20th Century Design, which is at 326 Wythe
Ave. in Williamsburg, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Snyderman, 28, and Zesty Meyers, 29, opened R 20th Century
Design in a lonely industrial neighborhood eight months ago and
were featured in Wallpaper almost immediately. On a recent Saturday
afternoon, the store was packed with tattooed artists and other
young people marveling at an aqua George Nelson daybed priced at
$3,750. Snyderman said he couldn't get over how well the store is
doing, considering the typical resident of the area is supposed to
be a starving artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first there was some neighborhood resentment because our
store was sort of slick looking and expensive,'' Snyderman, who set
up a layaway plan, said. ``But now people just want to know what
the stuff is.''
</P>
<P>
   As modernist design becomes trendier, some of its longtime
champions are skeptical of the newly converted. ``It's like New
Balance sneakers,'' said Serge Becker, a co-owner of Bowery Bar,
who plans to open a new nightclub at the Joseph Papp Public Theater
this fall, which he has designed in 1930s Italian-modern style.
(Think cork walls and Perelli rubber floors.) ``Soon, people will
get sick of it and the people that liked it all along will be
left,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The London press has recently proclaimed the end of the buzz
about Wallpaper. The magazine is an easy target for critics of its
achingly hip fashion models either posing amid lavishly priced
interiors or racing to catch the Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if you can't be cool unless you can afford to fly
first class on your own private jet with the perfect modernist
interior,'' said Mike Mills, a graphic designer for hipster bands
like the Beastie Boys, Cibo Mato and Air, who has lectured on the
Eameses to college students. ``A better magazine would have
furniture that cost under $20 and where jet-set meant Tower Air.
It's very un-Eames-like.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Doige, a set designer who works for Calvin Klein, said he
wouldn't dream of using modernist furniture again because
``everyone and their grandmother is using it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see a Citibank commercial that has all modernist
furniture, then you know it's time to try something else,'' he
said. ``Next season, I'm going to try the Dada look: lots of shapes
but no recognizable props.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, at Form and Function, Walrod predicted that the look and
the life style have plenty of mileage left in them.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling a television commercial for L'Oreal Preference with
Heather Locklear tossing her blond mane while seated in a luscious
purple 50's Egg chair, he said, ``If I was a kid and saw that, I'd
be so happy I'd start investigating modernism immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
