<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9787 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-$ADV     09-04 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-$ADV05 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHO RULES RUSSIA? FOLLOW THE MONEY
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In Frankenstein fashion, the politically powerful
business barons of Russia have created a monster that threatens
their stature and clout.
</P>
<P>
   In the tangled world of Russian politics, their scheme last
month appeared to be fairly straightforward: push the ailing
President Boris Yeltsin to return their friend Viktor Chernomyrdin
to power and thus make it easier for Russia's big businessmen to
weather the economic tempest swamping the country.
</P>
<P>
   The small group of financiers and industrialists, collectively
known as the ``oligarchs,'' have over the years helped keep Yeltsin
in power, and in turn profited wildly on the economic policies --
and the lack of rules -- since the Soviet Union disintegrated in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and media billionaire Boris Berezovsky, 52, was widely
credited as the chief mastermind of Yeltsin's Aug. 23 decision to
fire the previous government and promote Chernomyrdin as the new
prime minister. Chernomyrdin had been prime minister from December
1992 until May of this year, when most of the oligarchy accumulated
their wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Berezovsky and others find themselves threatened with the
double whammy of economic turmoil and a political impasse.
</P>
<P>
   In the current crisis, the oligarchs are having to compete with
another faction -- the Communist-led parliament, flexing its muscle
as never before to seek a power-sharing deal with Yeltsin as a
result of the president's weakening stature.
</P>
<P>
   Russian media reports this week also said some prominent
businessmen were hedging their bets, holding talks with Yeltsin's
opposition on alternatives to Chernomyrdin should he not receive
confirmation from the Duma, the lower house of parliament. A second
confirmation vote is scheduled for Monday after the Communist-led
Duma overwhelming rejected a first attempt on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing anything and everything they can to push
Chernomyrdin and avoid another candidate for prime minister. Their
power and in some cases their empires are at risk. Everything was
at stake with Yeltsin, and when Yeltsin faltered, they pushed
Chernomyrdin. Now he is in trouble and they are worried,'' said
political analyst Sergei Kolmakov.
</P>
<P>
   They are troubled primarily, according to analysts, over the
potential that Yuri Luzhkov, the mayor of Moscow and himself a
rival oligarch, could ascend in the current political vacuum to
replace either Chernomyrdin or Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that distress was an interview Berezovsky gave Sept.
2 to a Moscow radio station in which he said that Yeltsin should
resign if the current political impasse continues and a ``strong
authority'' is not created. The implication being that if this deal
for Chernomyrdin falls through, the tycoons will abandon Yeltsin
and look for a better one, Kolmakov said.
</P>
<P>
   How far and wide this loose association of businessmen cooperate
on political affairs is a matter of much speculation in Moscow.
Their financial interests bind them, but they are not a monolith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berezovsky is not participating in this like the general
secretary of a party of oligarchs, but as a political adviser to,
first of all, Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin,'' said Sergei Markov,
director of the Institute of Political Studies in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   If any confirmation were needed of Berezovsky's prominence in
the current political and economic crisis, consider this: When
President Clinton and his team came to Moscow for the summit with
Yeltsin, a key presidential adviser, deputy treasury secretary
Larry Summers, peeled off for private talks with Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's wealthiest men, the oligarchs include figures like
Vladimir Potanin, the 37-year-old chairman of Uneximbank; Mikhail
Khodorkovsky, 35, of Bank Menatep and on the board of ORT, a
television station owned in part by Berezovsky; and Vladimir
Gusinsky, 45, of Most-Bank and a magazine publisher.
</P>
<P>
   They and others, numbering fewer than a dozen in all, are a
group of sharp-witted risk-takers. The oligarchs made their wealth
carving up the assets of the Soviet Union with the help of the
cronyism and unregulated finance of new Russia, a moneymaking
manner often compared to America's 19th-century robber barons.
</P>
<P>
   But the current economic chaos has taken its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gusinsky, Potanin and Khodorkovsky merged their
banks in order to reduce their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Smolensky, chairman of SBS-Agro Bank, and Vladimir
Vinogradov, president of Inkombank, have seen government
intervention in their banks' management in the past two weeks after
huge losses resulting from their rambunctious trading in Russian
treasury bills and foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Berezovsky who gets -- and often himself demands --
the greatest share of media attention, sometimes publicly bragging
about his ability to manipulate Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated worth of $3 billion, Berezovsky and a handful
of other oligarchs banded together in 1996 to support Yeltsin, who
was trailing badly in his reelection campaign against Communist
leader Gennady Zyuganov. They poured millions of dollars into his
campaign and assured favorable coverage in their newspapers and on
their TV stations.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, a former mathematician who began building his empire
with car dealerships, also reportedly financed a 1994 publication
of Yeltsin's memoirs and guaranteed the president monthly royalties
of $16,000. The He is also said to give lavish gifts of jewelry to
the women in Yeltsin's family.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Berezovsky became particularly close to
Yeltsin's daughter and chief image-maker, Tatyana Dyachenko; the
presidential chief of staff, Valentin Yumashev; and deputy chief of
staff, Igor Shabdurasalov.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no government. The president is a non-factor. At the
moment the country is being run by them,'' said Vyacheslav Nikonov,
director of the Politica Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Reports in the Russian media said the billionaire businessman
secretly met with Chernomyrdin and Shabdurasalov in the French
resort of Cannes to hatch the scheme to oust previous prime
minister Sergei Kiriyenko after only five months in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Berezovsky was credited with orchestrating
Chernomyrdin's ouster in March and bringing in the little-known
reformer Kiriyenko. (A depiction that Berezovsky encouraged at the
time, but which he now denies). But as the financial crisis
worsened, and Kiriyenko proposed serious measures to deal with it
-- steps that would have threatened the assets of the oligarchy --
reportedly Yeltsin was urged to make the change.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Berezovsky also had run-ins with two of
Yeltsin's chief advisers and young economic reformers, Anatoly
Chubais and Boris Nemtsov. Both are now gone from government.
</P>
<P>
   After the government sacking two weeks ago, the newspaper Russky
Telegraf, which competes with Berezovsky's Nezavisimaya Gazeta,
headlined a front-page editorial: ``Berezovsky Is Now Our
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
