time, but which he now denies). But as the financial crisis
worsened, and Kiriyenko proposed serious measures to deal with it
-- steps that would have threatened the assets of the oligarchy --
reportedly Yeltsin was urged to make the change.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Berezovsky also had run-ins with two of
Yeltsin's chief advisers and young economic reformers, Anatoly
Chubais and Boris Nemtsov. Both are now gone from government.
</P>
<P>
   After the government sacking two weeks ago, the newspaper Russky
Telegraf, which competes with Berezovsky's Nezavisimaya Gazeta,
headlined a front-page editorial: ``Berezovsky Is Now Our
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
