u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-1STLD-W     09-04 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS FEAR DESERTION OF WOMEN THIS NOVEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: NEW LEDE, new material in grafs 4, 5, 6 and 12, minor edits
throughout)  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid a rising chorus of Democrats chastising
President Clinton, party loyalists fear that women voters _ a key
component of the Democratic base _ will stay home this November out
of disgust over the Bill-and-Monica debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats acknowledge that President Clinton's lying about his
sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
could jeopardize the party's hope of a net gain of 11 seats needed
to take the House of Representatives away from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many Republicans are predicting a GOP gain of a dozen
or so House seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nightmare,'' said former Rep. Patricia Schroeder,
D-Colo., last Friday, a day after Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.,
an influential Clinton ally, called the president's conduct
``immoral'' and ``disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was the latest among prominent Democrats to publicly
castigate Clinton. Sens. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, Daniel Patrick
Moynihan of New York and Dianne Feinstein of California spoke out
last month, with Feinstein saying her faith in the president had
been ``badly shattered.'' A week before Leiberman's stunning
comments on the Senate floor, House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt called Clinton's behavior ``reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In their gut, elected Democrats are just dying over this
because they are aware of harmful it could be,'' Schroeder said.
``And an awful lot of women are going to start saying, `Wait a
minute. Have we totally lost our moral compass?' This is very
harmful.''
</P>
<P>
   Another element of the Democrats' nightmare scenario: If
Democratic women avoid the polls and Republican voters are
energized, the GOP could rack up a 60-vote filibuster-proof
majority in the Senate. Now its lead is 55 to 45. Such a victory
would solidify Republican control on many crucial legislative
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that women within the party want to get past this
and go on,'' said Linda Cacchione, Colorado Democratic Party vice
chairwoman. ``But I think there is a real dismay among women that
this (the Clinton scandal) has gone on so long and they find
themselves having to explain things to young children that they'd
rather not.''
</P>
<P>
   Cacchione expressed optimism that in Colorado at least, women
will turn out to vote for two female Democrats running for major
offices, U.S. Senate candidate Dottie Lamm and gubernatorial
candidate Gail Schoettler.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Cohen, spokeswoman for Emily's List, which raised $6.5
million in the 1996 election cycle for Democratic women candidates
who favor abortion rights, said, ``I don't think anyone believes
voters will go into the polls and vote on the basis of Monica
Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she added, the brouhaha over Clinton's seven-month
denial of the Lewinsky affair followed by his admission that he had
lied may drown out discussion of other issues. ``If voters are not
aware of what the debate (on these issues) is about, there's not a
lot of incentive to go to polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Low turnout by women could spell trouble for the re-election
bids of three Democratic female senators _ Patty Murray of
Washington, Barbara Boxer of California, and Carol Moseley-Braun of
Illinois. All three were elected with Clinton in 1992, in what
became known as ``the year of the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Metcalf, vice chairwoman of the Democratic Party in
Vermont, sees a female division on Clinton that she describes as
``a generational thing.'' Older women are more astonished and
disheartened by Clinton's behavior, she said. But middle-aged and
younger women, ``who grew up when things were much looser, are more
`been there, done that,''' she said. ``So they're quicker to say,
`Let's put this behind us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are looking at how Clinton's troubles might help
them. Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster, said a survey he took
since Clinton's Aug. 17 admission showed a 4-percentage-point drop
among women, Republicans and Democrats, who said they are likely to
vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, 53 percent of women said they expected to vote,
compared with 57 percent in a poll taken before Clinton's
confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see women voting Republican who otherwise would have
voted Democrat,'' Luntz said. ``But I do see women staying home
rather than voting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Stone of Republicans for Choice, which during the 1996
election cycle raised $1 million for moderate Republicans who
support abortion rights, sees a possible benefit for centrist GOP
candidates. ``If Clinton-type voters are going to get discouraged,
the only Republican they'd vote for is our kind,'' she said. ``So
if they turn out at all, it's to our benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Turnout in off-year national elections has for the most part
dropped steadily since 1966, when it reached its high mark of 48.8
percent of the voting-age population, according to Curtis Gans,
director of the Committee for the Study of the American Electorate.
Gans said he expects turnout this November to be no higher than 36
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In small-turnout elections, a party that energizes its base of
support can expect to do well, but its chances can be doomed if a
key part of its base stays home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a presidential year, women's votes gave Clinton a
second term, even though Democrats failed to retake the House and
Senate, which the Republicans had captured in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   GOP candidate Bob Dole won 44 percent of the male vote, and
Clinton took 43 percent, a gap of only 1 point. But Clinton rolled
up the female vote by a whopping 54 percent compared with Dole's
meager 38 percent, a 16-point gap.
</P>
<P>
   Women voted for Clinton because of his support for abortion
rights, his appointment of women to high government posts and his
leadership in passing the 1993 Family and Medical Leave Act, which
gives employees up to 12 weeks unpaid leave for medical emergencies
and childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   But relations between women and Democrats have not always been
solid. Some analysts attribute the GOP's 1994 congressional victory
to women staying home out of disappointment over Clinton's botched
health care plan and charges by Paula Corbin Jones that he had
sexually harassed her when he was Arkansas governor and she was a
low-ranking state employee.
</P>
<P>
   That year 38.8 percent of the voting-age population went to the
polls, with 54 percent of women supporting Democratic candidates
and 46 percent voting for Republicans, according to exit polls
cited by Carll Everett Ladd of the Roper Center for Public Opinion
Research.
</P>
<P>
   That was an 8-point gap. Meanwhile, 57 percent of men voted for
Republicans and 43 percent voted for Democrats _ a 14-point gap.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson appears to be that whichever side gets a lion's share
of either gender's vote is the winner. For Democrats, there is no
chance for victory without big support from women.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, other national and international issues _ terrorism,
gyrations on Wall Street and the impact of Russian and Asian
financial turmoil on the U.S. economy _ could cloud the electoral
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton-Lewinsky matter remains the Democrats' biggest
headache. ``My first gut reaction is that none of this should fall
out on members of Congress,'' Schroeder said. ``What were any of
them going to do about it? They aren't hall monitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she added, ``If congressional Democrats paid the
price in '94, who's to say you don't have a rerun in '98?''
</P>
</TEXT>
