<HEADLINE>
CATS, FOXES TARGETED TO PROTECT ENDANGERED SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EVE MITCHELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ Life on the levee could soon turn deadly
for stray cats, raccoons, red foxes and skunks when a trap-and-kill
plan to protect two federally endangered species starts next month.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say they had no choice but to sign the five-year
agreement to allow the federal predator-management program in the
Redwood Shores neighborhood. The program is required by the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service, the Army Corps of Engineers and the Bay
Conservation and Development Commission as a condition of a permit
to raise the local levees to federal flood-control standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am personally opposed to doing it,'' said City Manager Ed
Everett. ``The trapping and killing of foxes or raccoons or any
animal to save another animal is to mess with the natural process.
There is a food chain. I think this is a misguided approach. There
is probably a better solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Endangered Species Act, nonnative predator species can
be killed if they pose a threat to endangered animals. In this
case, the program is intended to increase the survival rate of the
California clapper rail and salt marsh harvest mouse, both
endangered species found in the Redwood Shores area.
</P>
<P>
   The program will target red foxes, raccoons, skunks, and feral
cats and be focused on the levee along San Francisco Bay, an area
that is home to both the protected and targeted animals. Public
access to the area will be restricted, according to a city report.
</P>
<P>
   The predator-management program will be carried out by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture, which embarked on a similar effort to
rid the former Alameda Naval Air Station of feral cats and other
nonnative predators viewed as a threat to the least tern, an
endangered seabird.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Thabault, a deputy assistant field supervisor with the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife office in Sacramento, said the plan is necessary
because the improved levee system will lead to increased
development and, in turn, attract more predator species.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Redwood Shores area is a really important area for the
clapper rail,'' he said, adding that with development comes
increased human habitation and garbage, which draws predators such
as red foxes and raccoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Development) has a devastating impact on the clapper rail
population. Mostly, we're worried about the red fox. Skunks,
raccoons and foxes all prey on eggs and the foxes also prey on the
birds,'' Thabault said. ``Cats will prey on both the birds and the
eggs. We don't mandate euthanasia. We just mandate removal.''
</P>
<P>
   After the animals are lured into baited traps, they will be
euthanized by lethal injection, said Peter Vorametsanti, the city's
senior civil engineer. If a cat or other domestic animal is
trapped, workers will look for a collar or micro-chip
identification to make sure the animal is not someone's pet.
Vorametsanti said he has not seen feral cat colonies in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Coette Schmidt, a founder of the Peninsula-based Homeless Cat
Network, said she does plan to survey the area for feral cats in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're not thrilled with it,'' said Schmidt, whose
organization works with the Peninsula Humane Society to humanely
manage feral cats through trapping, testing, vaccination, spaying
and neutering and releasing felines back to colonies tended by
volunteers. In some cases, cats that can be socialized are adopted.
</P>
<P>
   City Council members voted 4-1 Monday to approve the agreement
for the predator-management program.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officials will evaluate the program annually to
determine whether it should continue.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the levee upgrade began about three months ago and is
expected to be completed by the end of next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
