<HEADLINE>
CBS' 49ERS ALUMNI WON'T GET TO CUT THEIR TEETH ON COWBOYS 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS makes its return to professional football official Sunday
and, at least as far as Cowboys' fans are concerned, it's a good
thing the Eye's going to be trained on the American Football
Conference and not the National.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a pregame show whose hosts are, among others, George
Seifert and Brent Jones, two notable Cowboys tormentors of recent
vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the No. 2 play-by-play team that features as its
color man Randy Cross. You'll vaguely recall him blowing holes in
the Dallas defensive line a time or two.
</P>
<P>
   Objective though these new-sprung journalists might try to be,
it's hard to believe they'd give Chan and company an even break,
especially if they happened to be pitted against those 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   At least Cross is balanced in the booth by old buddy Verne
Lundquist, who must have a blue star somewhere in his closet, even
years after departing Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Seifert and Jones, who will appear on the ``NFL
Today'' pregame show, and Cross, who will be calling games, will
mostly be making their points about the Patriots and the Jets, the
Steelers and the Raiders. Judging from ``The NFL Today'''s
preseason tune-up on Aug. 27 (the Thursday night exhibition between
the Cowboys and Jaguars) they ought to do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   The old coach gave signs that the wit he flashed in those
singing TV commercials a couple years ago was the real George _ not
the drab guy behind the dark glasses who has stalked NFL sidelines
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Allen, basically another West Coaster, also looked at
ease. His intelligence should shine through on the hourlong pregame
and during the rapid-fire halftime highlights segments.
</P>
<P>
   Jones seemed a bit overactive in his debut, but that could
easily morph into mere enthusiasm once he has had a few Sundays in
front of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   All will benefit greatly from the pass-the-rock skills of
pre-eminent studio host Jim Nantz.
</P>
<P>
   They'll depend a lot on this wily veteran, too, since, with his
lonely exception, they're all TV novices. That has everybody a bit
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all a little jittery going into this thing,'' Nance
admitted last week.
</P>
<P>
   Part of those jitters come from excitement. CBS is thrilled to
have the NFL back after punting its NFC rights to Fox in the
previous network negotiations. The return came at a monumental
price _ some would say too high a price _ but at least CBS Sports
can again hold its head high as a major player in the world of
sports broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives, including sports division president Sean
McManus, are cautioning viewers not to expect too much out of the
box, especially from ``The NFL Today'', which is the
highest-profile element of the network's football Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going against two very well-produced pregame shows \Rat
Fox and ESPN\S,'' McManus said. ``It takes a while for these shows
to evolve. I would hope everyone would watch us with an open
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Nantz agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to hitting our stride at some point in the
season,'' he said. ``It's going to be a slow process. It's not just
going to happen right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Nantz said viewers will need time to adjust to CBS' new pregame
show, like the way they needed time to catch on to the ways of
another famous TV ensemble: the characters of ``Seinfeld''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the first time you saw it,'' Nantz said, ``you
wondered, `Who's that guy Kramer? Why does he come running through
the door? Who's that neurotic guy George?'''
</P>
<P>
   All that said, Nantz added that rehearsals ``so far have gone
extremely well. It's a jittery feeling,'' he said, ``but a good
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus said one of his network's strengths will be its ``very
fresh and contemporary outlook on the NFL.'' That freshness will
come mainly from Allen, Jones and Seifert, he said, all being
recently of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a nifty studio set for ``The NFL Today'', CBS
folks say, as well as ``cutting edge'' in-game graphics and
technology, plus a premier No. 1 play-by-play team in Greg Gumbel
and Phil Simms, who will battle Fox's Pat Summerall and John Madden
for Sunday Supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   But back to ``The NFL Today''. For purposes of fairness, it
should be noted that the old 49ers did right by the Cowboys in that
preseason broadcast. Seifert downplayed the winless exhibition
campaign while reporter Bonnie Bernstein (who played for ESPN, not
San Francisco) went toe-to-toe with Jerry Jones in a halftime
interview, though with little success.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, considering Dallas' prospects, those might be the
nicest words anybody at Fox utters this year about the Cowboys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1643EDT &QL; 
