<HEADER>
A9818 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GALLO-TEX     09-04 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GALLO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLO'S HUMOR: OUTSPOKEN INDIE FILMMAKER SPEWS VENOM, WIT,
SUBVERSIVE ART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vincent Gallo can't seem to help himself. He has led an
incredible life: Among his accomplishments, he played in a downtown
New York band with Jean Michel Basquiat. But the achievement _
probably not exactly the word he'd like to hear used in this case _
that most people mention is his brief period as a Calvin Klein
model. In the recent past _ like yesterday, maybe _ he'd probably
have gone a little ballistic about this being brought up, but he's
a little sanguine now. His film ``Buffalo 66,'' which he wrote,
directed, starred in and composed the music for, was recently the
No. 1 independent film in Los Angeles. But clearly, that's not
enough for this wiry, voluble talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm broke, and I have no future,'' he says in a matter-of-fact
manner. ``Why? Because I've said shocking things in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   This sounds overstated, but with Gallo, it is true. A
conversation with him is wide-ranging and passionate. He has a
sense of humor about himself; a good chunk of his comments are
self-deprecating. But the words often sound as if they were fired
from a nail gun; it's as if some accident damaged his superego, so
that the first thing he thinks comes right out of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent issue of the Village Voice, for example, he browbeat
Christina Ricci for mentioning ``The Opposite of Sex'' instead of
``Buffalo 66'' in her interviews. (After meeting him, though, you
can see how there might be something slightly ingratiating about
his abuse.) And there's the crack he made about Skeet Ulrich, which
was that if life were really like a party, Ulrich wouldn't get past
the doorman. ``Yeah,'' Gallo says, resignedly, ``I did say that.
Poor Skeet. But he's really terrible.'' Or, while trying to be on
his best behavior in a conversation about innovators, Gallo blasts
Quentin Tarantino as ``a rip-off artist.'' It's quotes like that
that make Gallo believe he'll never be hired by a major studio.
``That's why Walt Disney will never hire me, ever. Those suits,
they never forget anything, so it's over for me.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if money is the great equalizer _ whether if he
creates enough profit with ``Buffalo 66,'' the suits would gladly
subject themselves to his abuse for future profits _ Gallo
fervently disagrees. ``The kind of money that it would take to
interest those bean-counters would be profound. It would not be
having the hot film in an art house theater. My film is the No. 1
independent box office film. There's nothing about the film I
didn't control. (But) I haven't been offered a job as a (production
assistant) since the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo wouldn't take such a low-level job, would he? ``You'd be
surprised. For the right price ...,'' he says, joking. ``I'm in
trouble right now. I mean, I had to borrow a car to get here
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his occasional joking and vitriolic attacks on other
people, Gallo does believe in what he says. For Gallo, life and
creativity are about making subversive art, about challenging
himself. It's what he struggled to do with the oddball verite
comedy ``Buffalo 66,'' obviously a personal film.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who know me _ even people who don't know me _ feel that
the film is autobiographical, that I'm probably playing myself in
the film. What I'm really playing is my father. Or what I would
have become, if I'd let my father's heavy impact stay in my life.
And what I play in the last five minutes of the film is me on a
really good day. I'd like to get 12 of my most complicated, bizarre
friends together _ and there are many of them like that _ and I
would like to have a dinner party with them all. But the only way
they could come is if they brought their mother and father. And
film that, make a documentary. Every time I meet my friends'
parents, it's just brilliant, it's just genius.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation skitters all over the place, eventually coming
to his third-person description of his darker side, the ``bad''
Vincent Gallo. ``He's unforgiving, and vindictive beyond belief,''
Gallo says, rifling off his liabilities. ``Relentlessly vindictive
and unforgiving, and resentful of feeling ... well, victimized. If
I get photographed by a photographer, and he picks the wrong photo
of me, in some way, at some point in my life _ in my mind _ I'm
gonna punish him. And I'm rigorous, because I have a long list.''
His eyes go wide, and he shakes his head. ``I have two books in my
house. One is every money transaction I've made since I was 13
years old. I need to evaluate in a daily way exactly where I stand.
The other book is every person who's done something against me.''
</P>
<P>
   These vendettas have seemingly become his raison d'etre. His
shaggy mane goes up and down in agreement: ``You're looking to be
disappointed, because you're comfortable in disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
