<HEADLINE>
'99 KIA SPORTAGE: NOT READY FOR PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's cheap, it's cute, and the top comes off. What's not to
like? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too much, alas. For while the 1999 Kia Sportage two-door
convertible is certainly ready to deliver fun, fun, fun for the
beach-blanket crowd, there's no mistaking it for the more polished,
car-like miniature sport utilities from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Those who keep track of the many new sport utility vehicles
already know about the South Korean-made, four-door Kia Sportage,
which landed in showrooms on the East Coast over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   It looks a lot like the small sport-utes from Honda, Subaru and
Toyota that are built on the frames of compact cars. But the
Sportage offers neither the soft ride nor the careful finish that
distinguishes the Japanese offerings. Of course, it doesn't match
their window stickers, either, which can run above $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kia is offering a twist on its previous formula, with a
shorter, racier, al fresco version of the Sportage _ one aimed at
younger drivers more likely to identify with the style than the
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Start with some positives. The two-door Sportage is 14 inches
shorter than the four-door but just as tall and wide, giving it a
macho, sawed-off, beach buggy swagger. A generous 7.9 inches of
ground clearance and a tough suspension make off-road use a
realistic option.
</P>
<P>
   The nicely proportioned captain's chairs in front offer a great
view of the road. And while the back seat is a squeeze for adults,
entry is relatively easy and the convertible half-top _ there is a
solid roof over the front seats _ offers compensation in the form
of blue sky and breeze.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, Kia has not stinted on amenities that usually
come as options on vehicles with a sticker price of $13,995 _ and
maybe far less after on-again, off-again rebates. Power windows,
locks and mirrors are standard equipment, as are intermittent
windshield wipers, a tachometer, a theft-deterrent system, front
disk brakes and a full-size spare tire.
</P>
<P>
   It even includes a third air bag, positioned at the driver's
knees to prevent ``submarining'' and thus maximize the efficacy of
the air bag mounted in the steering wheel hub. Air-conditioning
($900) and the radio-CD player ($545) are the only must-have
extras.
</P>
<P>
   The two-door Sportage comes with rear drive and a four-speed
automatic transmission, or, for an extra $500, with four-wheel
drive and a five-speed manual. (Sorry, you can't mix and match.)
Both versions are equipped with a 16-valve, 4-cylinder, 2-liter
engine that puts out a maximum of 130 horsepower and 127
foot-pounds of torque. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I tested only the rear-drive, automatic transmission, which is
probably less peppy and certainly less versatile than the
four-wheel drive with stick shift. Still, the Sportage seemed
powerful enough, shifting with a thud around 5,000 rpm under full
throttle.
</P>
<P>
   Engine noise is high, which hardly matters because that
cacophony is drowned out by the chatter of the canvas top.
</P>
<P>
   Handling is a mixed bag. While the wide track and short
wheelbase (11 inches shorter than the four-door version) do give
the Sportage a nimble feel at low speeds, the poorly damped coil
springs are bouncy on rough roads.
</P>
<P>
   The Sportage's brakes are responsive and don't fade much with
hard use _ a real achievement in view of the hefty 3,100-pound curb
weight and the drum brakes at the rear wheels. Anti-lock braking is
available as a $495 option.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the canvas top and flexible plastic rear window is a
relatively simple, five-minute chore. But I'd hate to try to put
them back together in the middle of a rainstorm. And even when it
is properly attached, the canvas leaks a breeze at 60 miles an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   The primary appeal of the Sportage convertible is its
devil-may-care looks, off-road capability and low price. But the
sacrifices, in terms of ride, handling and fit and finish, are
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Definitely not your father's Toyota.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
