<SLUG> BC-KNOCK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KNOCK OFF': A FILM THAT LIVES UP TO ITS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was a film ever more appropriately titled than ``Knock Off''?
</P>
<P>
   This latest Jean Claude Van Damme vehicle, which ostensibly
takes its name from the cheap imitations of brand-name clothing and
other goods manufactured in Hong Kong, is actually one itself.
</P>
<P>
   With standard-issue villains like former KGB agents working for
the Russian Mafia and CIA baddies scheming to hold whole countries
for ransom, ``Knock Off'' runs breathlessly over land and water in
familiar comic-book fashion, offering more action than sense and
next to nothing in the way of suspense, humor or romance.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tsui Hark, a veteran of Hong Kong action films, and
written by Steven E. de Souza, whose credits include ``Die Hard''
and ``48 Hrs.,'' ``Knock Off'' deadens the brain with its
convoluted plot, and then tries to revive its victims with its
stunts and shootouts.
</P>
<P>
   As the plot goes, the Russian Mafia is planting tiny
``nanobombs'' in everything from children's toys to the buttons on
blue jeans manufactured in Hong Kong. The evildoers are in league
with a traitorous CIA section chief (Paul Sorvino). Once the goods
are shipped abroad and bought, he intends to threaten whole
countries with destruction unless he gets his $100 million a month
ransom payment.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the British turnover of Hong Kong to China in
1997, enter Van Damme as Marcus Ray, rogue of the rag trade, who,
for no reason the film ever makes clear, sets clothing models into
a tizzy.
</P>
<P>
   A partner with Tommy Hendricks (Rob Schneider) in the operation
of the Hong Kong offices of an American company called V Six Jeans,
he is apparently trying to overcome his traumatic childhood as an
orphan (the son of doctors, of course) and his more recent past as
a shady Hong Kong character.
</P>
<P>
   But just as all seems to be going well (Marcus even has one of
those BMW sports cars introduced in films by James Bond), an
attempt is made to murder his buddy Eddie (Wyman Wong), who runs
the factory that manufactures the jeans.
</P>
<P>
   And soon afterward, Karen (Lela Rochon), announcing herself to
be an executive vice president of V Six, informs him that the
company has been ripped off to the tune of more than $4 million
because some of the jeans shipped out of Eddie's factory are
knockoffs made of inferior denim.
</P>
<P>
   Now faced with fraud charges, Marcus is soon up to his thick
skull in people who would like to see him dead. Of course, no
matter how many guns, knives and bombs they have, they can't kill
him; but every time he fires a shot, even while flying through the
air, one of them drops. Van Damme, who has never been known for the
subtlety of his acting, achieves no new heights in ``Knock Off.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the swift action defeats the efforts of the eye to
distill its sense, but many of the locations _ a Hong Kong
wholesale fruit market, the eye-catching harbor, the skyscrapers
and the busy streets and people _ are a generous compensation for
watching the rest of this unsurprising exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock Off'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes foul language and violence, all of
it as unoriginal as the rest of the film.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: `KNOCK OFF'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tsui Hark; written by Steven E. deSouza; director of
photography, Arthur Wong; edited by Mak Chi Sin; music by Ron Mael
and Russell Mael; production designers, James Leung and Bill Lui;
produced by Nansun Shi; released by Tri-Star Pictures. Running
time: 110 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jean-Claude Van Damme (Marcus Ray), Rob Schneider (Tommy
Hendricks), Paul Sorvino (Johannson), Lela Rochon (Karen Leigh),
Michael Wong (Lieutenant Han), Carman Lee (Ling Ho), Glen Chin
(Skinny) and Jeff Wolfe (Skar).
</P>
</TEXT>
