<HEADLINE>
IF IT SMELLS LIKE A GUN TAX, IT'S A GUN TAX
</HEADLINE>
 (Resending to correct garbles) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most folks are familiar with the old ``if it looks like a duck,
walks like a duck, quacks like a duck, then it must be a duck''
analogy. A governmental version of that goes: ``If it looks like a
tax, acts like a tax and hurts like a tax, call it anything you
like _ even a user fee _ but it's still a tax.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of full disclosure, this is not original
thinking. A column-writing colleague first used it years ago to
take a local municipality to task about water rates, if memory
serves me. It fits perfectly the ongoing debate about the National
Instant Criminal Background Check System.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice has proposed that federally licensed
firearms dealers be assessed a ``user fee'' each time the FBI
processes a background check on a prospective gun buyer after Nov.
30. The gun dealer, naturally, will pass that tax ... uh, check
that _ ``user fee'' ... on to the purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI contends that the $200 million that was appropriated to
it under the 1993 Brady Act can only be used to improve the
criminal history record systems in the states, and not to perform
the individual background checks that will become law Dec. 1. And
because it will cost upward of $91.6 million next year to run the
NICS Operations Center, a $14 ``user fee'' will be necessary to
cover the costs of the estimated 6.7 million inquiries per year.
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the topic of names ... the full name of the Brady
Act is the Brady Handgun Violence Protection Act. But don't any of
you long-gun devotees think you'll be exempt from being treated
like a felon. As of Dec. 1, sportsmen and hunters desiring to
purchase rifles and shotguns will be subjected to the same
background check _ and tax _ as those wishing to purchase a
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Justice's proposed rule for the
instant checks, the FBI has the ``authority to establish, collect
and retain fees for processing name checks for non-criminal justice
purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold the phone right here. Why would we be doing this if it
wasn't for the purposes of criminal justice? Sarah Brady, Handgun
Control Inc. and other proponents of the Brady Act have long
advocated that the law was meant to keep known bad people from
doing unknown bad things with guns. If attempting to keep convicted
felons from buying a gun is a non-criminal justice process, I'll be
the first to quack like a duck.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the way that the FBI ``doesn't'' enforce the law
amounts to a non-criminal justice process, I suppose. Handgun
Control Inc. enjoys trotting out numbers from the Bureau of Justice
Statistics that say more than 242,000 handgun applications were
rejected in 1994-97, the assumption being that thousands of bad
people who had reasons to lie on their forms were kept from buying
handguns. During that same time, only 599 were convicted of
supplying false information on the forms, according to the U.S.
Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it's likely that thousands of the rejectees filled
out the forms incorrectly, not necessarily falsely. But that's not
a very sexy explanation, and the anti-gun side can't get much
mileage out of that.
</P>
<P>
   The clock is ticking on the public comments period on the
proposed rule that will establish the gun tax. It's a bad rule;
Congress should appropriate the money needed for law enforcement
efforts and not tax a targeted group of citizens who are just
trying to exercise their right under the Second Amendment. Anyone
who shares that opinion should let the feds know, in writing, on or
before Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Send letters to Emmet A. Rathbun, Unit Chief, Federal Bureau of
Investigation, CJIS Division, Module C-3, 1000 Custer Hollow Road,
Clarksburg, W.V. 26306-0147.
</P>
<P>
   And while you're at it, send a copy to your congressional
representative. They love to hear from voters _ especially at
election time.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is a senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
