<HEADLINE>
BROWN VOWS TO TACKLE SAN FRANCISCO'S TRANSIT PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 and TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, who had vowed to fix public
transportation problems within 100 days of taking office, has
reiterated his promise to turn the troubled municipal transit
agency around.
</P>
<P>
   The latest pledge came with the unveiling of a plan Thursday
that is intended to make the Muni Metro operation more effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be able to get efficiency out of this system like
you're never seen before,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief component of the plan, which was launched with
apparent success for the Thursday-morning commute, removes
streetcars that aren't compatible with a new automated control
system from the underground Metro system. Twenty trains will be
taken out of tunnel service, bringing the maximum number operating
at one time to between 67 and 75.
</P>
<P>
   To test the new procedure, Brown raced the Muni Metro down
Market Street at rush hour Thursday morning. The mayor set out on
foot from Civic Center station to see if he could beat the train to
the Embarcadero stop. His walk, according to staff members, took 21
minutes. The train, on which an aide was riding, beat him by more
than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It is Brown's hope that even with the reduced fleet, the
operation will run more smoothly and put an end to the delays that
have plagued passengers and put him on the political hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   But, acknowledged Muni spokesman P.J. Johnston, there's a
potential price: comfort. The trains, he said, are likely to be
more crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have sacrificed in physical space, we have gained in
frequency and efficiency and movement,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Under intense pressure from agitated riders to improve the
heavily used Metro, Muni is instituting several other do-or-die
remedies. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mechanics and technicians will be stationed in the tunnels so
they're never more than three minutes away when a train breaks
down, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extra Muni workers will be available in the stations to alert
passengers to delays and help direct them to alternative
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   _ An above-ground, backup shuttle system will be available in
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying in every way to speed the repair of any glitch
that's created,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The automated system, put into operation nearly two weeks ago,
is supposed to double the number of trains that can run through the
tunnel at one time. A series of glitches has severely hampered that
effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0257 </DOCNO>
