<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Sept. 6,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUPPET-FESTIVAL (New York &UR; )  &LR; _ There has been a great increase
in this high-art notion of adult puppet theater in the United
States over the last 20 years as vanguard American artists have
turned to the medium, and as work from countries where puppetry was
never ghettoized for children has been brought to the New York
stage. The most important venue for new puppet work is the biennial
International Festival of Puppet Theater, produced by Cheryl
Henson, Leslee Asch and the Henson Foundation. The fourth festival
opens Wednesday. By Andrew Solomon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOBOYZ-MOVIES (Los Angeles) _ It has been said that anyone
could produce a movie: all you needed was money, the ability to
hire good people and very good, or very bad, taste (as long as you
were consistent). But to direct one you surely needed concrete
experience, every John Ford and Preston Sturges move at the ready
and a proven ability to handle actors. Well, that was then but
maybe not now, when a new generation of aspiring movie makers are
getting incredible opportunities based largely on razzle-dazzle.
And when overnight successes like the brothers Peter and Bobby
Farrelly (``Dumb and Dumber'' and ``There's Something About Mary,''
which together have so far earned $150 million) are flaunting their
lack of knowledge and style rather than kissing the studio grounds
on which Billy Wilder once walked. By Michelle Willens. (Moved). &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HANDSPRING-PUPPET-THEATER (Johnannesburg, South Africa) _ Basil
Jones and Adrian Kohler, founders of the Handspring Puppet Company,
will lead off the International Festival of Puppet Theater in New
York with ``Ubu and the Truth Commission.'' The two men are South
Africa's premier puppeteers. By Donald G. McNeil Jr. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MULTI-ACT-BALLETS (Undated) _ Today, when abstractions dominate
many ballet repertories, it's tempting to proclaim plots
unimportant. Dance is an art of movement, and the best story in the
world cannot disguise unimaginative choreography. Nevertheless,
should choreographers wish to tell tales, good stories can help
make good choreography look even better. This is especially true of
full-evening productions. Recent months have offered several
imposing multi-act story ballets, ranging from Marius Petipa's
19th-century blendings of classicism and exoticism to Boris
Eifman's contemporary balletic expressionism. By Jack Anderson.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   EQUESTRIAN-DANCE (Paris) _ Equestrian art may be as old as
ancient Greece, but Bartabas, the founder and director of the
Paris-based Zingaro Equestrian Theater, still likes to think he is
doing something new. He may well be right. Carving a niche for
himself somewhere between the classical dressage of, say, Vienna's
legendary Spanish Riding School and the athletic antics of circus
horses, the 41-year-old Frenchman has created an equestrian show
that underlines the emotional power of horses. By Alan Riding.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HANDEL-OPERAS (New York) _ Handel has changed. For pretty much
two centuries after his death, in 1759, he was remembered primarily
as a composer of oratorios, anthems, concertos, suites and sonatas:
music that bolstered a gentlemanly image of magnificence and
decisiveness. His operas, so much more pliant and equivocal in
tone, were largely forgotten until the 1920s. On Friday, the second
night of its new season, the New York City Opera will present
Handel's ``Partenope'' in a production introduced at Glimmerglass
during the summer, and two new recordings of other Handel operas
have just appeared on the Virgin Veritas label. By Paul Griffiths.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TANGLEWOOD-TEACHERS (Undated) _ Teachers come in different
shapes and sizes, and finding the right fit might sort out some of
the educational controversies going on at the Tanglewood Festival
up in Lenox, Mass. The troubles have been well rehearsed in these
pages, and are not likely to go away when the season ends this
weekend. Have Tanglewood's long-respected summer programs been
emasculated by dismissals and resignations, or have they been
reinvigorated by a new involvement on the part of the Boston
Symphony and its music director, Seiji Ozawa? By Bernard Holland.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COURTNEY-LOVE-MUSIC (Undated) _ Courtney Love's songs for Hole
on the band's third album, ``Celebrity Skin'' (Geffen), are bound
to be heard in the context of a life made for tabloid headlines.
Ms. Love is a former stripper turned punk singer and the widow of a
suicidal, heroin-using, million-selling rock star, Kurt Cobain.
After his death in 1994, she went on turn herself into a surgically
altered, couture-wearing, Oscar-nominated actress, apparently
becoming the kind of Hollywood figure that many of her punky
original fans detested. By Jon Pareles. (Moved). &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EMMYLOU-HARRIS-MUSIC (Undated) _ Emmylou Harris has always
zigged when the rest of the music world has zagged. But after doing
country long before it was remotely cool, and then getting exiled
by country radio along with virtually everyone else over 40, she
seems more adept than ever at finding the seams between the
formulas emanating from Nashville and the commercial no man's land,
vaguely known as alternative country, outside the Nashville
mainstream. By Peter Applebome. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTO-PUJOL-ART (New York) _ Moody, meticulously staged and
filled with introspective symbolism, the room-size works of Ernesto
Pujol have been fixtures on the international art circuit in recent
years and, in the eyes of many, examples of installation art at its
most evocative. In his newest work, he has branched off into
fine-art photography, and the Linda Kirkland Gallery will present
his first photographic efforts in a group show titled ``Some Like
It Hot'' _ hot as in sexy, seductive or fetishistic. The exhibition
opens Saturday and runs through Oct. 17. By Edward M. Gomez.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES-INGO-FREED-ARCH (Washington) _ Bad things happen to good
architects. James Ingo Freed is the man who designed the United
States Holocaust Memorial Museum, one of the most powerful
buildings of our time. It gives me no pleasure to report that
Freed's most recent project, the Ronald Reagan Building, is a
disappointing piece of work. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MARSHALL-MEMENTOS-ART (Undated) _ Kerry James Marshall, the
black artist whose paintings depict the civil rights struggle of
the 1960s, will have his first New York exhibition at the Brooklyn
Museum entitled ``Mementos.'' By Barry Schwabsky. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EARTH-TO-MOON-TV (Undated) _ Next month, on its Signature
channel, HBO will rebroadcast ``From the Earth to the Moon,'' which
was nominated for 17 Emmy Awards (to be presented next Sunday).
Columbia House Video Library has released the series to its
members. By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT-SMIGEL-TV (New York) _ Robert Smigel, who does Bill
Clinton's voice on the Conan O'Brien show, real occupation is
writing cartoons for ``Saturday Night Live.'' ``It's more like a
hobby, the stuff I do with Conan,'' says Smigel, 38, who lives in
Manhattan. ``It's just vaudeville.'' By Anita Gates. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CONAN-O'BRIEN-TV (Undated) _ In 1993, only one person in America
could possibly have foreseen the day when Conan O'Brien would be so
popular on late-night television that NBC would hand him an hour of
prime time to celebrate his fifth anniversary on the air: Conan
O'Brien _ in his wildest dreams. But if anybody has earned the
right to have his wildest dreams taken seriously it is O'Brien, 35,
who will indeed see that once stupefyingly unlikely event come to
pass on Sept. 16, when ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien'' hits the
big time. Right there at 10 p.m., where ``Law and Order'' usually
presides, it is going to be Conan, front and center, the man of the
hour, the host, the star. By Bill Carter. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCRIMSHAWING-ANTIQUES (New York) _ The hardy seamen who took up
scrimshawing to pass the time during long voyages in search of
whales more than a century ago would probably be dismayed to learn
that their handiwork had been enlisted in the cause of feminism.
But consider the evidence. The finely engraved teeth, the whalebone
pie crimpers, bodkins and busks that they made as gifts for their
wives and sweethearts back home were tokens of affection that in
the sexual politics of today might be construed as the actions of
tough guys wanting to show their soft side. An exhibition of 52
pieces of scrimshaw is currently at Snug Harbor Cultural Center's
Newhouse Center for Contemporary Art on Staten Island. By Fletcher
Roberts. (Moved).
</P>
