<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9915 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICKEN-RECIPES-COX     09-04 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Skillet Southern-fried classic
</P>
<P>
   (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 6: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Auchmutey
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   No dish in the canon of Southern cooking has as many variations
as fried chicken. The first recipe for it appeared in the first
Southern cookbook, the 1828 edition of Mary Randolph's ``The
Virginia Housewife.'' Since then, countless permutations have been
tried and passed down through the generations.
</P>
<P>
   The variables are legion: What size should the hen be? Do you
soak the pieces in salt water or buttermilk or something else? How
do you bread the chicken? Season it? Do you pan-fry, deep-fry or
fry at all? How deep should the oil be? Should you use shortening?
Vegetable oil? Peanut oil? Do you cover the skillet, and how long?
What kind of gravy do you make, and what do you pour it over? (Not
the chicken, please.) And what's the proper way to eat it?
</P>
<P>
   That last one's actually easy. Years ago, Gainesville, Georgia,
one of the centers of the American poultry industry, passed a law
making it illegal to eat fried chicken with anything other than
your fingers. As far we know, no one has been arrested for using a
knife and fork _ but it sure looks funny.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Real Southern Fried Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   My sister-in-law Lucy is the best chicken fryer I know. When I
called her to ask how she did it, she laughed and said, ``Go out in
the yard, get a plump hen and wring its neck.'' She grew up eating
chicken that fresh. Now she buys it like most of us, at the grocery
store, where she looks for the smallest fryer (never more than 3
pounds) because it'll probably be the tenderest. You'll likely have
to cut up the bird yourself if you want a pully bone, the meaty
morsel from the chest that others call a wishbone. Here's how you
cook it.
</P>
<P>
   1fryer (2 1/2-3 pounds), cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   Buttermilk to cover
</P>
<P>
   1cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Canola oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon bacon fat
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken pieces, pat dry and place in casserole dish. Cover
with buttermilk and soak at least 2 hours in refrigerator. Remove
dish and let chicken come close to room temperature (no longer than
2 hours) before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, pepper and salt in a bowl or paper bag. Remove
chicken from dish, letting buttermilk drip off, and dredge each
piece (or shake it in the bag) to coat evenly with flour and
seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Place bacon fat in a 12-inch (or larger) skillet with enough
canola oil to cover 1/2 inch deep. Over medium-high heat, bring oil
to point that a drop of water flicked into it sizzles (about 350
degrees). Lower heat to medium and arrange chicken pieces in
skillet, skin side down, being careful not to overcrowd. Fry 5 to
10 minutes on each side, with lid on. Remove lid and fry each side
another 5 to 10 minutes, until crust is crispy and golden. Drain on
wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Cooking times vary by size of piece, whether the meat is
white or dark, type of skillet and temperature of the oil (which is
difficult to keep steady). All of which is to say, keep an eye on
the chicken and regulate the heat so the inside gets done before
the outside gets overdone.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 512 calories, 34 grams protein, 33 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 59), 16 grams carbohydrates, 106
milligrams cholesterol, 1,296 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Cream Gravy
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 cups Preparation and cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: X minutes
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons oil from skillet
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Discard all but 2 tablespoons of oil from the skillet. (Be sure
to leave the crispy brown pieces, for flavor.) Over medium-high
heat, whisk in flour until it turns medium-brown. Gradually pour in
milk, stirring until gravy comes to a boil. Reduce heat and simmer
for at least 2 minutes, or until it reaches a creamy texture. As
you're cooking, taste the gravy and add salt and pepper as needed.
Serve over mashed potatoes or rice.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 19 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 1 gram
fat (percent calories from fat, 66), 1 gram carbohydrates, 2
milligrams cholesterol, 8 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
