<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Constructive criticism goes a little awry
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 6: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a blow to the old ego when you find out you're not a gifted
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   I have a young relative whose children needed supervision while
they brushed their teeth, their dentist said. She undertook to sit
with them night and morning and make sure they scrubbed the teeth.
</P>
<P>
   My heart went out to her 13-year-old, who put up his toothbrush
and headed for bed, saying over his shoulder, ``Goodnight,
warden!''
</P>
<P>
   The feisty young waitress at a picturesque Mentone, Ala.,
deli-restaurant wasn't so philosophical when I undertook to
instruct her.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, I interviewed a noted restaurateur who had just moved
south and was doing his best to enlighten and sustain the locals.
</P>
<P>
   He told me that he found Southerners troublesome because we are
unhandily polite. If we don't like his food, we won't tell him, and
we'll leave and never come back. New Englanders, on the other hand,
will make their criticism known _ in the politest terms _ and go
away, but come back again to see if things have improved.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of that as my daughter and I sat on the little open
porch outside a log cabin on Mentone's main street. (I think they
have only one.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a beautiful day, cool and bright, and we had feasted our
eyes on some incomparable scenery. We were only moderately hungry.
(A lady who runs a grocery-filling station had sold us some
homemade peanut brittle, which was so good we ate it as we
traveled.)
</P>
<P>
   My daughter ordered a sandwich and a Coke; I ordered a cup of
pinto beans, corn bread and iced tea. The drinks were fine,
although I abhor to have them served in pint fruit jars. But the
rest of the food was inedible.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, who paid, would have been horrified at complaining
to management. But I thought the place was so charming, the
waitress so cute and obliging, I wanted to help them out. Teach
them, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   The child thanked us and apologized as she collected our dishes
and the untouched food. I tried to explain that I hoped they would
use a better corn bread recipe. I even offered mine. But the
atmosphere was decidedly cool when we left.
</P>
<P>
   The theory that it's unseemly to complain is pretty general, I
expect, and I may never attempt to instruct another restaurant
operator.
</P>
<P>
   But I did like Mentone, the pretty little town across the
Georgia line in northernmost Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   It seems relatively undiscovered and unsettled, although any
road you take _ and they have some pretty ones, paved and unpaved _
leads to a magnificent mountain view and some wonderful houses. We
liked the old ones, weather-stained and tin-roofed, but there are a
lot of new ones, too _ subdivisions yet.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter would like a second home in the Mentone area, but I
think it is just a dream.
</P>
<P>
   We conferred with another delightful young woman, a real estate
agent named Angela, who operates in the lower half of one of the
log cabins. She had pictures of pretty old houses and wonderful
woodland and lakeside views _ all sold.
</P>
<P>
   For fun on the way home, we toured Menlo across the Georgia
line, a jewel of a little town, which apparently has only one house
to sell _ a two-story frame, needing painting, $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
