<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWNSIZING-CONDO-COX     09-04 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNSIZING-CONDO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jill Vantosh simplifies her lifestyle by stripping a condo to
the bone
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_When Jill Vantosh talks about paring down, take her
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years of living in a large traditional home, the
Atlanta interior designer and her husband, Jeff, went the route of
many other middle-aged empty nesters: They downsized to a condo.
</P>
<P>
   But moving to the Buckhead unit last winter involved far more
than sorting, selling and storing belongings.
</P>
<P>
   The designer seized an opportunity to create a streamlined
interior that emphasizes a few of her favorite things _ including
concrete. Vantosh stripped the second-floor unit of the 1950s red
brick building to its concrete bones, from floor to ceiling, then
extended the concrete to the kitchen countertops. The result is a
clean, industrial look made warm and inviting by juxtaposing the
unpainted beams and chrome furnishings with oak floors and rich
cabin-
</P>
<P>
   etry.
</P>
<P>
   Like the move, the renovation was a gamble _ the kind of risk
the designer's known for embracing _ but one that's paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always trying to simplify,'' Vantosh said, ``but I have
this real high level of energy when it comes to design.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer, who during her 26-year career has earned a
reputation for being avant-garde, relishes experimentation. ``I'm
open-minded, always looking for new ways to skin a cat,'' she said.
``If you're going to work in such a creative field, it just seems
such a waste not to reach out and go the step further. I try to
teach my clients to experiment, too, because if you don't, you
don't grow.''
</P>
<P>
   And growth is something the former schoolteacher-turned-designer
knows all about. Among her high-profile clients is actress and
former Atlantan Halle Berry.
</P>
<P>
   After earning an education degree at the University of Georgia
and marrying commerical real estate broker Jeff Vantosh, she taught
for four years before deciding to sell real estate. She began to
help friends decorate their homes, and after taking courses in
engineering, drafting and design, entered the field full time.
``Nobody can teach you what you see inside your head,'' she said,
``but I still had to learn the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of it came from working for an architect and builders while
playing mom to Aaron, 27, and Beth, 26. ``It was really tough on my
family,'' Vantosh recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Her projects began as children's rooms and small offices, then
evolved into commercial work and model homes. She later opened a
furnishings and accessories store, Vantosh Details, in Buckhead's
West Village but closed it last spring to refocus on design.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have come to know me as contemporary because I'm 'out
there,' though that doesn't mean I don't love and use antiques,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Vantosh once raised a few eyebrows in traditional-minded
Atlanta with a room she created for a decorator show house by
covering its walls in corrugated cardboard and aluminum strapping.
</P>
<P>
   Such experimentation with materials and furnishings doesn't have
to be expensive, she said. Client Sandy Hartman was prepared to buy
all new furniture for the contemporary house she built in Buckhead
last spring. ``What I liked about Jill is she didn't push for that
like other designers,'' Hartman said. ``She said, 'Let's work with
some of the things you already have.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her trust in Vantosh's instincts led her to agree when the
designer suggested incorporating concrete in a stairwell and wet
bar. It's a look she would emphasize in her Peachtree Road condo.
</P>
<P>
   A few of my favorite things. Besides an in-town location, the
Vantoshes' priority in downsizing was ``finding something I could
tear up without feeling guilty,'' she said. ``We'd find all these
really nice houses, but I wanted the next place to be my
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the couple found their unit in the ``eyebrow
building,'' as it's known because of the curved awning, they had
sold their home and were renting an apartment. That proved a
blessing because the small apartment not only removed them from the
chaos of renovation but forced them to take a hard look at their
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, but I didn't want clutter,'' said Vantosh,
aiming for a minimal decor. ``I had had walls of Aaron's baseball
pictures and all of Beth's things from school, so we went through
and picked the most sentimental things we wanted to keep.''
</P>
<P>
   After selling many of their furnishings in yard sales or at her
store, they bought new pieces that would enhance the new home's
modern architecture. ``I wanted to live here because of the
ceilings,'' Vantosh said of its concrete construction. ``I knew the
structure and what I could do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-month project included converting a third bedroom to a
living room by removing its blocked walls and creating an
``L-shaped'' open space that flows into the dining room and den. A
kitchen wall was lowered to leave only a partition between it and
the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Ceilings were stripped of their tile to expose concrete as were
the hardwood floors, which proved a real challenge because tar had
to be removed before they could be cleaned and sealed. To define
spaces within the open interior, Vantosh covered some floors with
light oak and left others unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd seen concrete countertops and thought, 'How perfect!' ''
Vantosh said. ``You can do so much with it _ stains, paint, shells
and rocks _ that people are starting to experiment with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of uneven walls, a section had to be poured on site,
creating quite a mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff was a little concerned about all the concrete but
supportive,'' Vantosh said. He joking asked how he'd be able to
tell when the project was complete.
</P>
<P>
   The concrete walls also made wiring difficult. Soffits were
added to hide electrical, sound and plumbing systems, and oak
storage cabinets were built to cover unsightly heat-and-air units
beneath the windows. The cabinets also reduced the need for
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   In editing their belongings for a smaller space, Vantosh proved
that sentimental items don't have to be cast aside to make room for
more treasured pieces. A childhood painting by her daughter hangs
in the master bedroom, while family photos and framed displays of
her infants' hospital gowns find a home on the powder room walls.
</P>
<P>
   Vantosh is the first to admit downsizing is difficult but forces
homeowners to focus on what's important. ``Not enough people are
willing to let their personality show. They get stuck on rules,''
she said. ``Simplifying is a risk worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   JILL VANTOSH
</P>
<P>
   -- Vitals: Atlanta native, 50, owner of VanTosh &AMP; Associates
</P>
<P>
   -- Clients: Actress Halle Berry (three homes), Atlanta Braves
and Atlanta Hawks execs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Favorite bargain spot: Cheshire Bridge Road antiques shops.
</P>
<P>
   -- Biggest design goof: An upholstered bed too large to fit up a
client's stairs, which had to be cut apart and reassembled.
</P>
<P>
   -- Decorating advice: ``Have a plan. Buy things that are good
and lasting. Don't believe you have to have it all at once. Less is
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
