</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDCHICKEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Kentucky, Col. Sanders and his finger-lickin' legacy are
something to celebrate
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 6: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON, Ky. _It's a good thing the Big Chicken doesn't face
north. If it did, the Marietta, Georgia landmark with the movable
beak and rolling eyes might really start squawking. Because people
here in Kentucky have come up with something that fryers of all
sizes should fear: a big skillet.
</P>
<P>
   The World's Biggest Frying Skillet _ we'll take their word for
it _ weighs 700 pounds and comes in four wedge-shaped segments that
each take three men to hoist. It stretches 10 1/2 feet across, not
counting the 8-foot handle, and holds almost 200 gallons of cooking
oil that propane jets take an hour to heat up. Watching the skillet
in action under a festival tent, burners blasting, chicken hissing,
you think not so much of Sunday dinner as the day shift at a pig
iron furnace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need an engineer for this job, not a cook,'' says Harold
Smith of the London Bucket Co., which forged the magnificent pan.
</P>
<P>
   Every September, Smith and company drag the skillet out of
storage and reassemble it to feed the crowds at London's World
Chicken Festival. Chew on that name a moment: not the London
Chicken Festival or the Kentucky Chicken Festival _ the World
Chicken Festival. Where does a town in a state that produces a
smidgen of the poultry produced in Georgia or Arkansas get off
staging an event with such a preposterously boastful name? The
justification lies in a former resident who made good, a tough old
bird named Harland Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Before he became a corporate logo, Col. Sanders was a real man
who moved from his native Indiana, got one of those honorary
Kentucky colonel certificates and opened a cafe and tourist court
on the U.S. highway between London and the next town south, Corbin.
In the 1950s, when I-75 bypassed his business, he took to the road
in a white linen suit and black string tie and started selling
franchises. Americans were just beginning to discover that they had
less time for cooking, and the dapper gent with the cane got in on
the ground floor of the meal-replacement industry. By the time he
died in 1980, the man and the chicken were internationally
renowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine the Colonel and Muhammad Ali are the two most
recognizable people in the world,'' says one of the festival's
planners, Caner Cornett, who may not be far off in his assessment
of Kentucky's famous sons.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so high on the Colonel and his food, though.
There are those who feel that Kentucky Fried Chicken and its
fast-food brethren are to traditional Southern fried chicken what a
plastic-wrapped pecan log is to freshly baked pecan pie. It's
convenient, maybe even tasty, but it ain't the real thing. As any
purist can tell you, authentic fried chicken _ the kind Southerners
have been fixing for the preacher since before the Civil War _
doesn't come out of a deep fryer or an oven or some industrial-size
cooking contraption. It's pan-fried in a black iron skillet heavy
enough to dent the linoleum.
</P>
<P>
   You don't find that kind of chicken as much anymore. ``I'm
afraid it's becoming one of the lost arts of Southern cooking,''
says Ronni Lundy, a Kentuckian who wrote the cookbook ``Shuck
Beans, Stack Cakes and Honest Fried Chicken.'' She believes home
cooks have shied away from fried chicken because it's messy and
time-consuming, not to mention fattening. As for restaurant
chicken, most of it is deep-fried these days, like potatoes, a
faster method that makes for crispy crust but often overcooks and
dries out the meat inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's become the benchmark for chicken,'' says Lundy, who,
unlike Sanders, was actually born in Corbin. ``I'm not a fan of the
Colonel's. It saddens me that Kentucky cooking is so identified
with fast food.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no escaping the Colonel and his legacy at the chicken
festival. London, a pleasant town of 4,000 in the low mountains on
the edge of Daniel Boone National Forest, started the celebration
eight years ago to capitalize on Sanders' fame. His face is
plastered on the front of the festival program. One of the main
events is a Harland Sanders look-alike contest; Robert M. Thompson
of Lawrenceburg, Ky., who grew a white goatee after he retired from
IBM, has won it the last two times. ``I saw the Colonel drive by in
his white limousine once, and he waved at me,'' he says. ``I always
try to represent him in a way that does honor to his memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Other remembrances aren't as fond. One year at the festival,
several of Sanders' former employees were asked to get up on stage
and answer questions about rubbing wings with the legend. ``They
wouldn't do it,'' says the festival's Cornett. ``They said he was a
difficult old man to work for, and they didn't want to talk about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Local gossip has it that one of those employees, a cook, was the
true creator of Sanders' original recipe. ``Everyone knows where it
came from,'' says Judy Nicholson of the tourism bureau, ``but we
don't talk about it too much because the Colonel's a god down this
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there's a shrine. Twelve miles south of London, on a
two-lane stretch of U.S. 25 in Corbin, the old Sanders Cafe has
been restored to 1940 condition and converted into a museum. The
white frame cottage with the steep dark-shingled roof adjoins a
sleekly modern KFC. Inside, the dining room opens onto exhibits of
artifacts and memorabilia like a flier from his unsuccessful 1951
run for the state Senate (as a Republican) and the cover of a rare
1960s recording, ``Christmas Eve With Col. Sanders,'' showing him
in Santa cap as he naps next to a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the old kitchen, too, where those ``11 secret herbs
and spices'' were first mixed and where the Colonel perfected a
new, speedier way to cook chicken at the massive Vulcan range. His
revolutionary technique used the same oil but a different utensil,
a pressure cooker. One of them is sitting next to the stove, beside
the old technology he bypassed like a slow two-lane _ a cast-iron
skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the two of them together, it suddenly occurs to you that
the most famous fried chicken in the world is not, strictly
speaking, fried.
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: ALSO SEE CHICKEN-RECIPES-COX)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
