<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUES-LABOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With the right attitude, any job can be a ministry, making the
world brighter for co-workers, customers
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_A few years ago author Michael Toms found himself with
three hours to kill at an airport in the Midwest. Wandering the
corridors, he heard singing and followed the voice to what turned
out to be a shoeshine stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man shining shoes was happily singing, laughing and
generally uplifting the spirits of all who came within his orbit,''
Toms wrote in ``True Work _ The Sacred Dimension to Earning a
Living'' (Bell Tower, 1998, $21), a book he co-wrote with his wife,
Justine Willis Toms. ``I had my shoes shined and remained there for
about an hour, basking in the positive energy this man exuded
through his dedication and singular artistry.''
</P>
<P>
   In these days of often surly service _ if what many businesses
provide can be called service at all _ an encounter such as Toms'
is memorable.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation celebrates Labor Day weekend, the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution asked readers about workers who make the world
brighter for their colleagues and their customers. We heard about
Edith Heath who does shampoos at a Buckhead salon and Charley
Lindsey who drives a school bus.
</P>
<P>
   Ola W. Reynolds, a salesclerk at Saks Fifth Avenue at Phipps
Plaza, makes shopping a pleasure, two of her customers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen her not be happy,'' says Carlette Iredale.
``She turns away the wrath of angry customers with a kind word.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always polite,'' says Edith Fairfield.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, 55, who has worked at the store for 28 years, says
simply: ``I treat everybody the way I want to be treated. That's
just something I was taught as a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   She credits her parents (her mother was a housewife and her
father a farmer) and her Baptist faith for her attitude toward
other people. ``You can't be taught customer service,'' she said.
``It's part of who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jennings, 41, assistant to Laura Leathers in the Freedom of
Information office of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, ``is never anything less than cordial and courteous''
to fellow workers and to the public, says Leathers. ``If you ask
her to do something, she's very willing to do it. If she thinks of
a way to help that you haven't thought of, she'll suggest it.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Jennings, ``I've sat on the other side of the fence. I've
had to deal with federal offices and federal agencies. I remind
myself how frustrating it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Her philosophy, Jennings says, is that ``you make the day what
it is. You can have a bad day or you can make it a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Any job can be a ministry if it's done with the right attitude,
says Rabbi Jeffrey K. Salkin, author of ``Being God's Partner _ How
to Find the Hidden Link Between Spirituality and Your Work''
(Jewish Lights Publishing, $19.95). ``We need to judge ourselves
not by what we do but by the meaning we bring to it,'' says Salkin,
spiritual leader of the Community Synagogue, a 630-family Reform
congregation in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met taxi drivers who believe they have holy jobs because
they are the connective tissue that makes the world go around. They
believe they could be taking someone, if not on a ride, on a
journey, and if not on a journey, on a mission. I've met sanitation
workers who believe their role in life is to keep the world clean.
I've met movers who believe that their role in life is to get
people where they need to be and to help them midwife a new life.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge for workers, whatever their work, is to
determine how their values intersect with their jobs, the rabbi
says. ``I ask them to think about the things they most cherish, the
ideals they find holiest, the religious motivations they may have,
and I ask them to discover how their work reflects what they are
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hebrew, the word avodah means both work and worship, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve a balance between values and work, Justine Toms says
she tries to begin each day with a prayer of gratitude, ``and after
that, to dedicate our day, all my actions and all my words, to the
benefit of something greater than myself.''
</P>
<P>
   With her husband, she founded New Dimensions Radio and New
Dimensions Foundation. They live in rural California.
</P>
<P>
   Her other bits of advice include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Tell the truth with kindness. ``Our words affect others in
very deep ways,'' she said. ``If you can't speak the truth with
kindness, then don't speak at all.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't make assumptions, ask questions. Assumptions often lead
people to take things personally that aren't meant that way at all.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ask, ``How can I be of help?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Always do your best. ``Have energy and enthusiasm for
wherever you are. You never know where it might lead or who's
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
