<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALUES-LABOR-PEOPLE-C     09-04 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUES-LABOR-PEOPLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labors of Love: Six metro Atlantans who find meaning and passion
on the job
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDWARD SEA
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 39
</P>
<P>
   -- Home: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Married with four children
</P>
<P>
   -- Job: Distribution and window clerk, an Atlanta post office
</P>
<P>
   -- Nominated by: Customer Sylvia Schwartz. ``His demeanor, his
willingness to help and his cheerfulness are outstanding. We look
forward to going to the post office now in hopes we will see him.
If he's not there, we're disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal point of view: Sea has worked at the post office for
only eight months, but in that time he has made an impression.
``He's one of the best employees I've ever had,'' says his
supervisor, Jackie McLloyd.
</P>
<P>
   Sea, a native of Vienna, Ga., retired from the Air Force, then
opened his own import-export business in El Paso, Texas. The postal
job in Sandy Springs ``was a chance to get back closer to home,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   He sorts mail for carriers and works with the public selling
stamps and weighing parcels and letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a people person,'' says Sea. ``We are a service-oriented
business. If I can get you in and out of here efficiently, that's
great. ... If you come into this post office with an attitude, it's
human nature for people to strike back. ... Sometimes it might be
warranted, sometimes it might not be. If two people get into a
confrontation and you both get heated, you're not going to get
anything resolved. If you're not part of the solution, you're part
of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   CHARLEY LINDSEY
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 65
</P>
<P>
   -- Home: Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Married with three children, four grandchildren
</P>
<P>
   -- Job: School bus driver, Fulton County(Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Nominated by: Parent Joni Pelta. ``He is terrific. He's
always bright and cheerful, even when it's raining. He conveys a
sense of warmth and appreciation to the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal point of view: Lindsey, who drives a small group of
special education children to New Prospect Elementary School in
north Fulton County, has two rules on his bus: ``Be careful and be
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   He is in business for himself and first began driving a school
bus five years ago for the health insurance he could get through
the Fulton County school system. He continues to drive because of
the relationship he has with the children. ``The thing about school
bus driving is the kids. That's what makes it addictive. They
appreciate you. They love you,'' he says. ``As long as I can pass
the physical, I'll probably keep driving.''
</P>
<P>
   His first Christmas on the job, a young girl from Haiti wrote
him a note, calling him ``the nicest person'' she had met in her
four years at school. ``All I had done was give her common courtesy
and respect,'' he says. ``I may have driven around the block when
she was late once, but I thought it was amazing that the things we
should all do _ treat people with respect and courtesy _ would draw
that much attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving a school bus gives Lindsey ``a sense of community,'' he
says. ``You feel like you're in there contributing with the
policeman, the fireman and the power company people _ the people
who make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith, Bible play role in approach
</P>
<P>
   EDITH HEATH
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 60
</P>
<P>
   -- Home: Southwest Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Married with two children and two grandchildren
</P>
<P>
   -- Job: Assistant, Who's Who Hair Salon in Buckhead
</P>
<P>
   -- Nominated by: Co-worker Audrey Faucett. ``Her job as a
shampoo person is as basic as you can get. What she brings to her
profession is a genuine humbleness that will make the most arrogant
person mild. She has a joy in what she does and that is helping
others.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal point of view: For 25 years, Heath has worked in
beauty salons, including 11 years at her current salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' she says. ``I like meeting different people, our
clients. I like what I do. I try to be nice to them, try to take
care of the old people.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath, a Baptist, said her faith and the Bible play a role in
her approach to her job. ``I just treat people the way I want to be
treated.''
</P>
<P>
   CAROL BROWN
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 49
</P>
<P>
   -- Home: Villa Rica, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Five children, seven grandchildren
</P>
<P>
   -- Job: Office cleaner at Geiger International Furniture
Manufacturers in southwest Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   -- Nominated by: Office employee Cori Harth. ``She has problems
of her own but you would never know it. She's interested in
everyone else. She leaves surprise candy and little smiley faces on
our computers. I'm fighting cancer and she put together the most
thoughtful basket for me you could ever put together. She just has
a way with people. She makes you believe in the goodness of human
beings.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal point of view: For most of her 10 years at Geiger,
Brown worked in the plant making furniture. About two years ago,
she moved to cleaning the front office from 3:30 p.m. to midnight.
``I'm getting a little older now, and I needed not to maybe lift as
many heavy things as I was in the manufacturing part.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some people might consider janitorial work menial,
Brown says she enjoys it. ``I've always liked cleaning,'' she says.
``I think it's important. I think it's neat for me to look at
something and see that it's as clean as it can be, whether it be
home or here. I think things need to be kind of neat and tidy. It's
a great way to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown expresses a great deal of affection for the workers in the
offices and cubicles she cleans. ``Sometimes, meeting a deadline,
they're really kind of under the gun and working a lot of hours,''
she says. ``Sometimes I can do just a little something, anything,
to say hello and let them know they're appreciated because they
really do work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown credits her parents and her Christian faith for her
outlook. Her parents, she says, ``instilled in me that you really
do need to work in life, that it's not just a free ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Her religion teaches her ``that it's important to be as kind to
people as you possibly can, as in the golden rule,'' she says.
``God has a purpose for everyone. Not everyone can be a rocket
scientist.''
</P>
<P>
   WANDA WHITE
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 43
</P>
<P>
   -- Home: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Divorced, two children
</P>
<P>
   -- Job: Receptionist and switchboard operator, WALR radio
</P>
<P>
   -- Nominated by: Media representative DeNatalie Phillips. ``She
is definitely a bright light. I am in media relations so I spend a
lot of time with media outlets and I've seen her in different
environments. She is a bright light. Everybody is attracted to her.
People just want to be around her. She's a patient and caring
person.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal point of view: ``I try to treat people the same,''
says White, who estimates that she answers as many as 800 telephone
calls a day. ``No one is better than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   White got into radio in 1989 when a temporary agency sent her to
work at WAOK and V-103. She was hired full time and worked at the
stations until 1993, when she left to care for her grandmother,
whose health was failing. She returned in 1995. She took her
present job in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about radio is the fact that it's an arena where
anything can go,'' she says during a conversation constantly
interrupted by telephone calls. ``I ask God every day to intercede
and let me do his will and not mine. ... It gives me a chance to
try to show the realness in the industry. You don't have to be
fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Callers ask anything and everything, but White says ``there is
no stupid question.'' She tries to be familiar with the station's
public service announcements and programming. ``If I can help a
person from the switchboard and they don't have to go through a
third person, I've done my job,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``BIG'' JOHN GOINES
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 50
</P>
<P>
   -- Home: Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   -- Family: Married, four children
</P>
<P>
   -- Job: Technician, Baranco Pontiac GMC
</P>
<P>
   -- Nominated by: Customer Ann Kimbrough. ``Getting your car
repaired is a pain. It's costly and time consuming. However, 'Big'
John Goines at Baranco Pontiac GMC takes extra care. He gave me an
unusual and welcome feeling of comfort and calmness each and every
time I had my car serviced.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal point of view: Goines, who was born on a farm in
Alabama, says he became interested in vehicle repair because of his
father's problems with farm equipment. ``My dad had farm tractors
and trucks,'' he says. ``He would hire people to come out and work
on those things. He would pay a lot of money, but people would come
when they wanted to and wouldn't always do the job right. One of
the things that drove me into being a technician was that I wanted
to help my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Goines has been working on General Motors cars for 26 years, 17
at an Oldsmobile dealership in New Orleans and 11 with Baranco in
metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customer is always first,'' he says. ``The customer is the
one that keeps this business open and going.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers can get angry if a job is not well done and if they
can't get the information they need about the status of their car,
he said. ``I don't have nasty customers,'' he says. ``I don't
promise nothing I can't deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   While Goines' job is important, he says, it is not his first
priority. ``I always put God first, then my family, then my job. If
you take things in that order, it always works out good for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
