<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTELLECTUALS-LABOR-2     09-04 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTELLECTUALS-LABOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR AND THE LEFT: GETTING COZY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Ideas)  
(lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last three decades, two groups that should be obvious
bedfellows _ the labor movement and leftist intellectuals _ have
far more often acted as enemies than as allies.
</P>
<P>
   Close partners throughout the first half of this century, these
two had an ugly breakup in the 1960s over Vietnam, integration and
the vehemence of Cold War anti-communism.
</P>
<P>
   But with the end of the Cold War and with leadership changes in
the house of labor, unions and left-of-center intellectuals have
concluded that they might have a lot in common after all. Eager to
counter the rise of the right and growing corporate dominance of
the economy and culture, labor and the left have attempted a
reconciliation over the last two years. To what degree this
rapprochement will succeed, however, very much remains an open
question.
</P>
<P>
   In candid moments, several intellectuals who have fostered the
reconciliation acknowledge that one of their main goals is to end
their exile from power and the public policy arena.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, liberal-left thinkers like Arthur Schlesinger Jr.,
John Kenneth Galbraith and Michael Harrington had the White House's
ear, but by the 1980s, the right was clearly winning the war of
ideas as much of its agenda gained acceptance even with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago the AFL-CIO, preoccupied with toppling communism
overseas, added insult to the left's insignificance by allying
itself with neoconservative intellectuals _ the nemesis of labor's
new-found friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way out of the ghetto, out of marginalization, a way
to once again have our ideas taken seriously and to move public
policy and the cultural values of the country in what we think is a
more progressive direction,'' said Steven Fraser, who wrote a
biography of Sidney Hillman, president of the Amalgamated Clothing
Workers, and was a prime mover in bringing left intellectuals and
labor back together.
</P>
<P>
   These labor-friendly academics, writers and artists often call
themselves social democrats; they include veterans of Students for
a Democratic Society, graduates of the Berkeley Free Speech
Movement and disciples of the socialist leaders Norman Thomas and
Michael Harrington. There is also a smattering of red-diaper babies
and of academics who were pulled left by the civil rights movement
and legendary labor leaders like Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   This pro-labor group first banded together publicly in January
1996, three months after John Sweeney was elected AFL-CIO
president, promising to help lift the poorest workers and to expand
labor's influence and size after decades of decline. Encouraged by
Sweeney's approach, more than 30 prominent intellectuals signed a
letter to the New York Review of Books vowing to support labor's
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   This who's who of left-of-center thinkers and writers included
Paul Berman, Barbara Ehrenreich, Betty Friedan, Henry Louis Gates
Jr., Robert Heilbroner, Jonathan Kozol, Richard Rorty, Arthur
Schlesinger Jr., Cornel West and the late Alfred Kazin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the revitalization of the American labor movement
can fashion a new politics of social solidarity and economic
justice, and reverse the country's descent into the kind of
mean-spirited selfishness that so discolors the contemporary
political scene,'' they wrote. ``It is the most heartening
development in our nation's political life since the heyday of the
civil rights movement a third of a century ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Leftist intellectuals and labor both want a country with less
corporate dominance, with more social protections and with more
democratic participation in government and in the workplace. Both
want American workers to have more security and a fairer share of
the nation's economic wealth, leading both to support universal
health insurance and a higher minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   These writers and university professors have been following a
tradition that dates from organized labor's formative years in the
late 1800s all the way through its heyday in the 1930s and 1940s.
In those years, luminaries like the philosopher John Dewey, the
economist Charles Beard and the novelists Upton Sinclair, Theodore
Dreiser and John Dos Passos wrote books and essays that furthered
labor's cause.
</P>
<P>
   These intellectuals are responding to appeals from Dewey and
Richard Rorty, widely considered the United States' leading living
philosopher and a champion of the labor-left alliance, that
intellectuals are too inward-looking and should not ignore social
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1960, if you were on the left, the left was always asking,
`What is the vehicle, to increase power?''' said Nelson
Lichtenstein, a University of Virginia history professor and a
biographer of Walter Reuther, the auto workers' leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee and
the civil rights movement were unquestionably the dynamic movement
that one had to orient to. Today, to the extent there's any
movement that has the potential for dynamic possibilities, it's the
labor movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to build a social movement, Sweeney has encouraged the
alliance with intellectuals, as well as ones with civil rights
groups, women's organizations and religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor movement needs to win the war of ideas in addition
to other wars that are going on,'' said Robert Welsh, Sweeney's
executive assistant and his liaison with intellectuals. ``The whole
conversation with progressive scholars, writers and artists is
critically important to having a vibrant, outward-looking labor
movement as opposed to an inward-looking, moribund one.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some union leaders quietly share the sentiment of
Samuel Gompers, the founder of the American Federation of Labor,
who feared that aloof intellectuals, often with a utopian bent,
might be more hindrance than help.
</P>
<P>
   And not surprisingly, the neoconservatives who were labor's
friends a decade ago ridicule the intellectual left as desperate
midgets eager to piggyback on the labor giant so they once again
can be seen and heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a new strategy,'' said Norman Podhoretz, one of the
fathers of neoconservatism. ``What you have is a movement with all
of these warm bodies and a big treasury, and if you're a small
splinter group somewhere on the left, it's not a bad idea to hook
up with a movement like that. I do not believe there is much good
that will come of this alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   For many intellectuals, however, their new embrace of labor
gives them an opportunity to climb down from the ivory tower and
ally their yin with a brawny, powerful yang that they have long
envied from afar.
</P>
<P>
   And while the intellectuals talk repeatedly about how their goal
is to help the less fortunate, a few admit to some self-interest in
forming the alliance. With universities relying increasingly on
low-paid adjuncts to teach classes, many academics say they need to
join arms with labor to prevent their own exploitation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We as academics are increasingly under attack and are
experiencing many of the same problems that workers are, workers
who are paid much less than we are,'' said Daniel Clawson, a
sociology professor at Smith College. ``It's difficult to see how
we can solve our problems without alliances and support. If we talk
about part-time and contingent workers, it's not only UPS and the
Teamsters. It's what's happening in the universities.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the most tangible fruits of the alliance have been two
dozen teach-ins at universities around the country. There, scholars
and union leaders have dissected and denounced stagnating wages,
growing corporate might, globalization's squeeze on workers and
management's offensive against unionization drives.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent refrain at these teach-ins is that something is badly
awry in this richest of nations when millions of full-time workers
remain caught below the poverty line, and the percentage of workers
without health insurance and pensions is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teach-ins make labor issues more salient in the minds of
students,'' said Eric Foner, a Columbia University history
professor who was master of ceremonies at the first labor teach-in,
a standing-room-only affair at Columbia in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many students here have never met a member of a labor union
except the person who cleans up on campus. These are students
coming from rather privileged backgrounds, and it's important for
them to be exposed to some of the reasons why the labor movement is
so vital.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the teach-ins, the alliance has helped funnel hundreds
of students into the labor movement to work as organizers. These
intellectuals have formed an organization: Scholars, Artists and
Writers for Social Justice, with 1,500 members and an acronym
pronounced ``sausage.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has encouraged members to write pro-labor Op-Ed pieces
and has pulled scores of pro-union academics together at the annual
meetings of the nation's sociologists and political scientists.
</P>
<P>
   This alliance has not taken the world by storm, however, as the
left (intellectual and otherwise) continues to languish and labor
remains far less potent than a half-century ago when John L. Lewis,
the thundering president of the Congress of Industrial
Organizations, was as well known as Bill Gates is today.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the movers behind the alliance, like Fraser and
Foner, voice disappointment that the partnership has not captured
the nation's attention and that labor has still not climbed back
onto center stage in politics and social policy. Their goal is to
make labor as vocal and powerful as it was a half-century ago, but
with unions representing 14 percent of all workers, down from 35
percent, that will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Labor and their intellectual friends also face an uphill battle
because globalization and the Gingrich revolution have repeatedly
thrown unions on the defensive. In addition, the campaign-finance
scandal in the Teamsters and other eruptions of union corruption
have tarred unions badly just as they are trying to win more
members and public backing.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Bell, the Harvard sociologist and longtime student of
unions, said he doubted the labor-left alliance would amount to
much. ``For the intellectuals, it's a lot of wishful thinking. I
don't mean that in an invidious way,'' he said. ``The real test
will be whether labor has the ability to expand its numbers. Simply
becoming more rhetorical and becoming more active politically is
not in and of itself enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
