<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV08-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO SLOW ON PRIVATIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Sept. 8)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ No investor likes to see the stock market tumble
into the cellar, but the terrifying turmoil on Wall Street these
past week may have done the nation an unanticipated favor.
</P>
<P>
   It sent a powerful warning to Congress to put a cork in all that
bubbly enthusiasm for privatizing Social Security by getting
workers to invest the tax money that now goes to the federal system
into private stock portfolios instead.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security financing will be overstretched in 15 years,
when the baby boomer generation retires. There has been a great
deal of scare talk about the drastic reductions in benefits that
will result unless dramatic reforms are made in the system.
</P>
<P>
   But Social Security comes with a government promise of
permanency that Americans are accustomed to rely on. Social
Security now pledges a specified benefit to 44 million elderly and
disabled citizens, creating a fundamental base of family stability
that makes a peaceful democracy possible.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the politicians will fix the threatened insolvency
within the federal system because they will have to do so or lose
their jobs. The elderly, unlike the young, vote in droves.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to increase taxes or slash benefits, Congress has been
flirting with the notion of throwing the old folks into the free
market. In part this seemed desirable because Wall Street was
enjoying a long, successful run, climbing an average of 10 percent
a year over the past century. Conservatives have always opposed the
concept of Social Security anyway, but the current argument has
been that retirees would be better off depending on stocks than an
always-overburdened federal treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The falling stock market, however, had the shock value of a cold
shower. While the federal government is ultimately accountable to
the voters, Wall Street is not accountable to anyone. Investments
made in Wall Street can be risky, particularly for elderly people
unfamiliar with stocks and vulnerable to bad financial advice from
inept brokers.
</P>
<P>
   What if the Social Security system had been privatized and
retirees were forced to watch their pensions collapse last week as
the market went into a tailspin? The plunge on Aug. 31 wiped out
more than $2.3 trillion (that's with a t) in market wealth since
the Dow peaked in July. And lots more was lost over the following
week as stocks went up and down, but mostly down.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the panic of old folks when they realized they would
have to live on a mere fraction of what they had anticipated. How
could they pay their bills?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the horror of middle-aged children suddenly facing the
prospect of supporting penniless parents they had thought were
independent. The younger generation has its own bills.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the drop in income of employees of stores, cruise lines
and beauty salons that depend on spending by elderly couples with
both leisure and financial flexibility. They have bills too.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market may recover, or it may not. Even if it does,
the psychological jolt to elderly hearts is unnecessary and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   We have just had an object lesson in the fact that pensions are
one area in which experimenting with privatization is politically
and socially dangerous. Whether it would be a fully private system
in which beneficiaries make their own investment decisions or a
combination of government and private accounts, this is a bad idea
whose time has not come. And hopefully will never come.
</P>
<P>
   Many pension plans are invested in mutual funds, equities,
stocks and other securities. But the decisions are made by experts
who are responsible for balancing profit and risk and monitoring
the results.
</P>
<P>
   Telling the elderly they are on their own in the puzzling
financial wilderness that is the stock market is quite another
thing. It is not realistic to expect many of them to master the
nuances of when and what to buy or sell.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street collapse also sent another message about the
importance of protecting individual pension plans from the whims of
the entwined international markets.
</P>
<P>
   It confirmed the political wisdom of President Clinton's veto
three years ago of a Republican measure that would have allowed
corporations to withdraw ``surplus'' money from their workers'
pension plans for any purpose they pleased, including raising
executive salaries. In his 1996 State of the Union address, Clinton
pledged to veto this heartless, reckless scheme a second time
should it reappear. It has not.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted ``surplus'' represents the value of pension funds
invested in mutual and other funds above the necessary amount
estimated to meet retiree needs. That's fine when the market is
high. But when the market goes south, the ``surplus'' is lost _ and
is unrecoverable if previously frittered away for some other
corporate purpose. Either the retirees are out of luck or the
taxpayers must make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Safe pensions, whether Social Security or private corporate
funds accumulated from deferred wages, are essential to the
well-being of the nation. And tying them too closely to the
vagaries of the stock market is not the way to secure their future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
