<HEADER>
A9998 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADY-PITCHER-$ADV06-N     09-04 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADY-PITCHER-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILA BORDERS: A PITCHER WHO'S IN A LEAGUE OF HER OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)  
 (bl)  
 By NEAL KARLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While pampered millionaire ballplayers chased home-run records
this summer, much of the Upper Midwest was enthralled by a 5-foot,
8-inch, 140-pound pitcher with a shoulder-length ponytail and a
uniform that read ``Duluth.'' Playing for about $1,000 a month, Ila
Borders, the first woman ever to make the roster of a men's
professional baseball team, electrified this chilly Minnesota town
on Lake Superior.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in a minor league several light-years removed in pay
and perks from what players call ``the Show'' _ the major leagues _
Ms. Borders, 23, proved to be a phenom just the same against teams
like the Sioux Falls Canaries and the Fargo Redhawks. Fans greet
her with the kind of outgoing warmth remarkable for a Midwestern
populace akin to the staid citizens of Garrison Keillor's Lake
Wobegone.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Ms. Borders played in the seven other towns, in
addition to Duluth, that make up the Northern League, her mere
warm-up pitches were met by thousands chanting ``I-la, I-la,
I-la.'' When she took the pitching mound, she was greeted by
standing ovations and public-address systems blaring the Doors'
``Don't You Love Her Madly?'' or Roy Orbison's ``Pretty Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Her popularity was due not just to the fact that she is, as S.J.
Perelman would have put it, ``button cute.'' Ms. Borders can
actually pitch. ``It still gives me chicken skin when I hear
everybody cheering me on like that,'' she said Wednesday in Duluth,
before the final game of the season. ``But I wouldn't be here if I
didn't think I could make it all the way. I've known since I was 10
I wanted to play in the major leagues, and this is no publicity
stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   She worked hard to tamp down the hype. She turned down two
offers to appear on ``The Tonight Show,'' as well as guest shots
with David Letterman and Rosie O'Donnell. Although Ms. Borders
agreed to be featured on ``60 Minutes,'' she ignored Mike Wallace
after he had the temerity to approach her in the Duluth locker room
last month after she'd already put on her game face shortly before
taking the mound against the Sioux City Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked at me,'' Wallace recounted for The Duluth News
Tribune , ``like I was a hair in her soup.'' He stayed an extra day
and got his interview when Ms. Borders wasn't scheduled to pitch
(the segment is due to be telecast around World Series time.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Borders hasn't always been so popular. The only girl playing
Little League baseball in La Habra, Calif., she was routinely
plunked in the head when she came to bat. In junior high school,
she sued to play baseball on the boys' team. Playing for Southern
California College, where she was the first woman to receive a
baseball scholarship _ there or at any other college _ she once had
another woman come after her with a knife because Ms. Borders had
struck out her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Moss, a coach for the St. Paul Saints of the Northern
League, discovered her. Invited to try out for the Saints in 1997,
she made the team, taking the last available pitcher's slot. After
a few rocky outings, she was traded within the league by the
first-place Saints to the last-place Duluth Dukes. There, the
rookie could work on her pitching while escaping the media
microscope in the league's largest city. Pitching 15 games, she
finished last season with no wins and no losses, a statistical
ghost. But Duluth came back at midseason and went on to win the
league championship. During the playoffs Ms. Borders pitched a key
scoreless inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were pitchers with worse statistics,'' she said. ``I
wasn't embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was her team. ``I wanted her back for 1998,'' said Jim
Wadley, the owner of the Duluth Dukes who has a daughter who
wrestled on her high school's boys' team. ``Ila's rookie season was
really just an extended spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Borders returned to Duluth last May to find the city had
taken her to its heart. True, she still had to put on her uniform
before the games and to shower after them at the home where she
boards near the stadium. And she still had to yell
``Housekeeping!'' as a put-your-pants-on warning before entering
her own team's locker room. But there has been no whining. ``My
teammates have all been great,'' she said. ``You're not going to
hear me complain about anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been true of everyone in the league. This season,
Ms. Borders pitched six scoreless innings against Sioux Falls,
becoming the first woman ever to win a game in a professional men's
league. Even so, Sioux City's manager complained on the radio that
Ms. Borders shouldn't be playing at all.
</P>
<P>
   Talk reached Duluth's front office that Fargo's manager might
forfeit the game if his team had to face Ms. Borders, a Dukes
spokesman said. The manager didn't forfeit, and Ms. Borders
silenced the critics by pitching six shutout innings in Fargo,
giving up only four hits before leaving with a 2-0 lead. (The Dukes
eventually lost.)
</P>
<P>
   Few others in the league seemed to have problems. Even the St.
Paul Saints, who had exiled her to Duluth in 1997, printed a
pagelong ode to Ms. Borders in their 1998 yearbook. It included
these lines:
</P>
<P>
   On the heads of the thousands of baseball-capped girls
</P>
<P>
   a new style had begun
</P>
<P>
   not driven by Saks or Fifth Avenue sales
</P>
<P>
   but by Ila.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as she prepared for her final start by stretching in
the Duluth outfield, dozens of children hung over the fence, as
many boys as girls, proffering baseballs for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ila is so cool,'' said Mike Lewis, 9, watching her bend like
Gumby. ``She's the best pitcher on the Dukes, and she's so nice. I
got my picture taken with her, and she autographed it, and then she
said she'd like a copy of the photo, which I got to her.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd behind the fence cheered each of their heroine's
stretches. ``Ila is my favorite, no question, because she shows you
can just do it,'' said Dradasha Wittmay, 13, her own ponytail
flowing out from a baseball cap in what she called ``Ila style.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon Ms. Borders was on the mound, where she put in five
innings, giving up a reasonable three runs against Thunder Bay.
Along the way, she was cheered like a benevolent queen from the
crowd shoehorned into Wade Stadium, a bucolic 4,000-seat brick
ballpark built by the WPA.
</P>
<P>
   There was joy in her steps as she raced back to the dugout after
her last performance of the year, receiving a standing ovation. Her
final statistics: one win, four losses. Not great, but not
horrific, either. She expects her quest for a major league start to
take years. Wadley, the team owner, said he would pick up her
contract for next year. He also pooh-poohs any notion that Ila
Borders is an excuse worthy of P.T. just to get 'em into the tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ila is going to make the big leagues,'' Wadley said. ``She's
going to be like Jackie Robinson being the first black man to play
in the majors, or Chuck Yeager being the first to break the sound
barrier. She'll be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that her second season is over, Ms. Borders is anxious for
the next one. ``This is no joke,'' she said. ``I don't want to live
my life as someone's idea of a stunt. I'm here on my road to making
the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the parking lot, the children waited until after the game
for their heroine, still in uniform, to emerge from the stadium and
sign, smile and talk. And she stayed until the last child went
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
