<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OYSTERS-RECALL-$ADV6-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HARVESTERS URGE PROBE OF BALLAST WATER AS SOURCE IN TAINTED
OYSTER OUTBREAK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Sept. 6) 
 
By CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ About four years ago, after detecting cholera bacteria
in oysters from Alabama's Mobile Bay, scientists traced it to water
dumped from ships that had been to Peru, where a major outbreak had
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar instance, the U.S. Coast Guard in 1990 issued an
order barring ships from emptying water from their ballast tanks
into the Great Lakes. The ban came in response to an infestation of
zebra mussels that had caused problems for decades _ clogging water
intake pipes, nearly destroying the native clam population and
costing the area economy billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   That outbreak, too, was linked to ballast water that had been
taken on in foreign ports to stabilize ships and then dumped in
U.S. waters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Texas oyster harvesters want an investigation into whether
the bacteria that made 419 people ill this summer from eating raw
Galveston Bay oysters might also have come from water discharged
from ships.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Food and Drug Administration marine biologist Dr. George
Hofkin, who is studying the Texas outbreak, believes such a
connection is a strong possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The specific strain of bacteria that made people ill has never
before been detected in Galveston Bay, but it is common in Japan,
India and Taiwan,'' Hofkin said. ``It is something that needs to be
looked into.''
</P>
<P>
   New technology, including the ability to type genes, has made
the bacteria trails easier to follow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Galveston Bay outbreak, which set a national record, was
first traced to ``Vibrio parahaemolyticus'' _ a bacterium that
occurs naturally in all waters of the world _ and then narrowed
down to a specific virulent strain called ``03:K6,'' which never
before had been detected in U.S. waters but is common in Southeast
Asian waters.
</P>
<P>
   The strain was the only type of ``Vibrio'' confirmed in those
who became ill from eating raw oysters from Galveston Bay, said Dr.
Bruce Elliott, who heads the state's microbiology lab in Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bay was closed to harvesting more than two months ago
because of the outbreak, authorities have not been able to find any
sign of this strain in oyster samples taken from the bay. Federal
and state officials are testing an additional 90 samples. If no
contaminants are found, harvesting may resume within about a week.
</P>
<P>
   The impact from the outbreak has been devastating, and the
question remains as to what caused it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did 419 people from 10 states become ill with flulike
symptoms such as diarrhea, vomiting and headaches after eating the
raw oysters, but the outbreak also has pushed Texas' $33 million
oyster industry to the brink of financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's on the verge of bankruptcy. This has halted a
complete industry. It's a disaster,'' said Lisa Halili, who with
her husband, Johnny, employs 300 people at their oyster processing
business in San Leon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crippled us so badly that we're not sure we'll ever
recover because of all the bad publicity that is giving the Texas
oyster an undeserved black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact has been felt nationwide, because more than half of
the oysters eaten raw in this country come from Texas, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   But what frustrates oyster harvesters most is that if the
bacteria tainting their oysters came from ships' ballast water,
safety precautions might have prevented the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real selfish for someone to cause this much misery for
someone else,'' said Halili, who chairs the Gulf Oyster Industry
Council. ``Something needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are voicing a growing concern that ballast water may
be providing a pathway for exotic species to be introduced into
areas where they never have been, thus upsetting the ecological
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming a big international issue,'' said Bob Peoples,
executive secretary of a federal task force set up in 1990 to
prevent the introduction and spread of nonindigenous marine
species. ``Sometimes it takes just the right window of opportunity
for these new species to become viable. They may have been
repeatedly introduced until the temperature and salinity conditions
are just right for them to take hold.''
</P>
<P>
   A drought and unusually high temperatures increased the salinity
in Galveston Bay this year, creating ideal conditions in which the
``03:K6'' strain thrives, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples said the cholera detected about four years ago in Mobile
Bay oysters temporarily baffled the national Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hofkin, the FDA marine biologist, was aware of a cholera
outbreak in South America so he decided to sample the ballast water
from ships that were coming in from areas where cholera had been
reported. He said researchers found the bacteria in the ballast
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved the route,'' Hofkin said. ``Luckily, it went away as
fast as it came, without anybody getting sick.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Great Lakes, the introduction of the zebra mussel did
take a toll, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists first warned about the zebra trouble in the
1920s,'' said Lt. Pat McKeown of Coast Guard's environmental
standards department in Washington, D.C. ``But it didn't create a
breeding problem until the 1980s. This mussel attaches itself to
things and must now be constantly scraped from water supply pipes.
It has also consumed much of the food and made it difficult to find
native clams that are still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   After much research, the Coast Guard adopted the 1990
requirement that ships bound for the Great Lakes dump at least 85
percent of their ballast water and replace it with water from the
open seas _ at least 200 miles from shore and 2,000 meters deep.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of metric tons of water can be carried in the
ballasts of one vessel, noted a Coast Guard report.
</P>
<P>
   ``By exchanging its ballast water while at sea, exotic organisms
from other ports-of-call will be replaced with ocean organisms used
to high salinity that usually can't cross into coastal areas and
survive,'' McKeown said.
</P>
<P>
   The International Maritime Organization also recommends this
water exchange system, but it does not require it, said McKeown and
Peoples.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Coast Guard wants more information about ballast
water and is considering a mandatory reporting rule to see how many
ships are complying with the voluntary rule and where each ship's
ballast water originated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received pages and pages of comments on this proposed
rule. Now we are reviewing and evaluating them,'' McKeown said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Peoples' task force is working to revise maritime
regulations to make the water exchange mandatory, but the earliest
effective date would be in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exchange will help, but it is not a foolproof system that
will eliminate the problem 100 percent,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Maritime officials also are seeking alternatives to rid ballast
water of organisms, such as using filtration systems, ultraviolet
light or chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a long time to determine what caused the Galveston
Bay outbreak, said the Texas Department of Health's seafood safety
spokesman, Kirk Wiles of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that that bacterial strain is a common
seafood contaminant in Southeast Asia, where thousands contract the
flulike symptoms each year, Wiles said scientists may never know
for sure whether the Galveston Bay bug came from there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
