Clinton's reputation won't hurt his efforts to raise $18 million in
big contributions at ``unity events'' in August through October.
They're depending on him to help offset similar efforts by the
Republican party. The chief House GOP fund-raiser, Rep. John Linder
of Georgia, says the GOP has already raised more than $17 millio
toward its goal of $37 million in big gifts during the same period.
Both parties are getting a lot of those funds from favor-seekers
giving the kind of ``soft-money'' contributions that would be
outlawed under a campaign finance bill that Sens. McCain and
Feingold promise to bring to the Senate floor for a vote between
Monday Sept. 7 and Friday Sept. 11. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
