<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Sept. 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tropical moisture will continue to invade the Southwest on
Saturday as a sluggish low pressure system several thousand feet
above southern California draws humid air northward from Mexico and
the Gulf of California. Scattered showers and thunderstorms, some
heavy, will develop across parts of southern and western New
Mexico, Arizona, Nevada, Utah and California. Storms are more
likely to form over or near mountains, particularly those that
receive at least some partial sunshine, which will, in turn,
destabilize the atmosphere. Flash flooding is likely in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a surge of hot air will trespass into the upper
Middle West ahead of a cool front dipping down from Canada.
Isolated showers and thundershowers may develop along the front in
parts of upper Michigan, Wisconsin and northern Minnesota later
Saturday. Only a few storms are expected to develop, however,
because very warm air a few thousand feet above the ground will act
like a lid to suppress the growth of cumulus clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Pockets of valley fog will veil the river and mountain valleys
of the Northeast on Saturday morning. Once fog dissipates, abundant
sunshine will boost afternoon temperatures toward or slightly above
seasonal levels. A warming trend will continue Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will flare across parts of
southern Florida on Saturday as prevailing winds from the
east-southeast continue to import tropical moisture. Farther north,
hot weather will build across the Southeast and Gulf Coast.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hottest Day &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mercury soared to 107 degrees Thursday afternoon at the Will
Rogers World Airport in Oklahoma City, officially marking the
city's highest temperature ever recorded in September. Despite the
widely publicized heat wave across the Plains this summer, Thursday
staked a claim as the hottest day of 1998, matching the extreme
heat on July 26 and August 2. The all-time September record was
wind-aided. A ribbon of southwesterly winds was warmed upon descent
from the Rockies, boosting temperatures several degrees to the
unprecedented September reading. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
