<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0073 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-PSYCHOLOGY-ART     09-04 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PSYCHOLOGY-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE LAPTOP, WILL TRACK EACH BLIP IN THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many other investors, Allen Page, 31, a packaging salesman
in Pasadena, Calif., had a bad week last week. But if not for his
cellular phone, his laptop, his Internet account and his pager-like
device that receives stock prices, it could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding his portable electronic arsenal, Page was able to limit
the damage by exercising options on beaten-down stocks, sometimes
trading from the shoulder of the freeway between sales calls with
his laptop plugged into his cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Page is part of a rapidly swelling contingent of investors who
keep an open line to their financial position as they go about
their daily lives. He is in a position to know: ``Sixty percent of
my customers are hooked up on the Internet, and I can walk in the
office and ask them the price of a stock and they'll tell me what
it is,'' he said. ``It's scary. It wasn't like that a year and a
half ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Most investors who track the movements of their stocks on the
Internet _ about three million now have on-line brokerage accounts
_ are enthusiastic about the virtues of expanded access to
information. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  But in a time of market volatility, some on-line investors
warn that such close contact with the ups and downs of a portfolio
can have an emotional effect that is not always beneficial to
strategic reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who are on line trade more often than those who are
not, for example. According to E-Trade, the on-line brokerage firm,
its customers average 25 trades a year, far more than the typical
customer of a full-commission brokerage firm, who trades once or
twice a year, or customers of a discount brokerage firm who trade
four to six times a year. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Part of the reason is that on-line brokerage firms typically
charge much lower commissions than traditional ones, a feature that
would naturally attract more active traders.
</P>
<P>
   But even for investors who trade through human brokers,
monitoring a stock in real time on line can induce decisions more
hasty than wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just something about watching it live, where you feel
an immediacy and an urgency to do something, more than if you came
home at the end of the day and looked at it in the paper,'' said
Jeffrey Mitchell, 38, who has lost money by not waiting an extra
hour to see what happened to a stock. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Mitchell, of Westport, Conn., runs a software company and
calls his broker when he sees opportunities on line.
 &UR;  &LR; In addition to hair-trigger trading, the Internet offers investors
another double-edged sword: on-line discussion groups.
</P>
<P>
   Many ``tips'' posted on line have been exposed as erroneous or
even fraudulent. But there is a subtler danger: the psychological
attachment, or aversion, an investor can develop for a stock that
is the subject of debate on financial World Wide Web sites like
Silicon Investor or The Motley Fool.
</P>
<P>
   Posting a comment about a stock puts personal credibility and
pride on the line, not just money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you buy a stock and talk about it on Silicon Investor, it
becomes more than just a stock,'' Mitchell said. ``You become
polarized on the Internet, and then you feel, by selling or
shorting, you are giving in to the dark side.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mitchell and others said they found that on-line
discussions bolstered their confidence about investment choices.
And soaking in the rhythm of the market through cyberspace clearly
gives individual investors new ways to participate directly in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Levinson, the president of E-Trade, attributed some of the
intraday volatility seen in the market early last week to the
ability of on-line investors to react swiftly to the market's
gyrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that consumers can get information so readily, they can
take advantage of a downward movement and buy into it, or an upward
movement and sell into it,'' Ms. Levinson said. ``There's more
confidence and comfort when you can see your stock and watch it
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gardner, co-founder of the Motley Fool, one of the oldest
investment sites on the Internet, said that the more information
individual investors had access to, the better off they were, even
if they lost some money along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can misuse their freedom,'' Gardner said. ``But the
long-term benefit of knowing this stuff, having information, being
able to ask questions far outweighs the effect of a person who sees
they're down 12 percent and makes a foolish decision.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line investors appear to be climbing a learning curve. Dr.
Jacob Snyder, 39, who lives in Kotzebue, Alaska, said his strategy
had evolved since he opened an on-line brokerage account with
Charles Schwab three years ago and began participating in
discussion groups on Silicon Investor.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that no one in his town of 2,000 was interested in
talking with him face to face about the merits of Intel or Applied
Materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of last year I discovered that I had a lot of
short-term gains and short-term losses that exactly balanced out,''
Snyder said. ``I decided I was acting too quickly. So I've forced
myself to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, last Monday, as he listened to the news of the market
slide while traveling to visit his brother on Washington's Olympic
Peninsula, Snyder was eager to log on to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had bought myself a bunch of shorts to hedge my position,''
he said, meaning that he had protected himself against falling
prices by selling borrowed shares of some stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So as soon as I arrived, I signed on.'' He then took advantage
of the market's dive to close his position profitably.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
