<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, Sept. 4 -- The following chart shows how senators voted
on key bills and amendments within the last week. A ``Y'' means the
member voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the member voted
against the measure; a ``?'' means the member did not vote; and a
``P'' means the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday passed, 87 to 3, an $8.45 billion spending
bill for military construction projects. Allocating funds for
housing and construction projects and costs associated with base
closings, the bill falls $760 million below last year's version.
Supporters said the bill sufficiently addresses the needs of
military bases. Opponents said the bill was loaded down with
unnecessary ``pork'' items. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: TREATY
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday passed, 49 to 44, a bill that would
provide $29 million to fund a commission that would oversee
compliance with the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which bans the
testing of nuclear weapons. Although the bill passed, the close
vote indicates the treaty may not gain the two-thirds support
needed for ratification by the United States. Supporters said it is
in the security interest of the nation to support funding for the
treaty. Opponents said it was premature to fund the treaty before
it had been internationally ratified. A ``yes'' vote favors funding
the treaty commission.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: TREASURY
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday passed, 91 to 5, a $29.9 billion spending
bill for the Treasury Department, Executive Office of the President
and U.S. Postal Service. Debate of the bill was halted in July due
to controversy surrounding a Republican amendment that would have
limited the terms of the staff director and general counsel for the
Federal Elections Commission. Under a compromise, the terms of the
current staff director and general counsel are not limited, but
future service is set at six years. Supporters said the spending
bill meets the needs of the Treasury Department and other related
agencies. No one rose in opposition to the bill. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE NO HOUSE VOTES THIS WEEK.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance record tracks the cumulative attendance of
members to date when they are physically present for roll call
votes.
</P>
