<HEADER>
A0093 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-FUND-RAISERS-A     09-04 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-FUND-RAISERS-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A FIGHT AGAINST CANCER FASHIONABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not every day that Donna Karan acts as a stylist
for anyone but a runway model. But on an August afternoon on Terry
Lane in East Hampton, Ms. Karan found herself at the home of
Elizabeth Tilberis, the editor in chief of Harper's Bazaar,
counseling women on what to buy and how to wear it, and draping her
sweaters over Hamptons-tan passers-by with the ardor of a Soho
street vendor. The event was a garage sale to benefit the Ovarian
Cancer Research Fund, an organization presided over by Ms.
Tilberis.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of almost 400 that haggled over Cindy Crawford's blue
jeans and Ms. Tilberis' hand-me-down Chanel handbags included
dozens of celebrities like Patrick Demarchelier, Isaac Mizrahi and
the models-in-love Esther Canadas and Mark Vanderloo, whose names
were all but guaranteed to turn up in gossip columns. ``If a light
could turn on and shine brightly on ovarian cancer, I'd be very,
very happy,'' Ms. Tilberis said from her Hamptons house last week.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the cause that could. Because of the advocacy of the
socially prominent and well-connected Ms. Tilberis and a handful of
grass-roots organizations, along with recent developments in
diagnosis and treatment, ovarian cancer has finally begun to make
inroads into the charitable arena dominated by _ there is no
delicate way to put it _ more easily marketed diseases like breast
cancer and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Ms. Tilberis will be a host of a fund-raiser at Saks
Fifth Avenue in New York that will raise money for the Ovarian
Cancer Research Fund while promoting the clothing lines of a
battalion of British designers sold by Saks. Ms. Tilberis is
lending her magazine's mailing list of fashion insiders, and Saks
is contributing $50,000 to her cause. The invited guests include
designer Alexander McQueen, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and actress
Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Later in September, Ms. Tilberis and actress Meryl Streep will
be the hosts of the New York premiere of the MCA/Universal film
``One True Thing,'' also for the benefit of the ovarian cancer
fund, and plans are under way for ``the requisite gala in
December,'' as Ms. Tilberis put it.
</P>
<P>
   The publication in March of her memoir, ``No Time to Die''
(Little, Brown) _ about her own continuing struggle with ovarian
cancer _ also focused attention on the issue. It was excerpted in
Good Housekeeping, and Walt Disney Co. plans to turn it into a
television movie.
</P>
<P>
   In all this, Ms. Tilberis is quite candidly using her position
atop a highly visible fashion magazine to link ovarian cancer with
the boldface names that are the quickest way to generate heat and
light these days _ whether for an Oscar gown, a restaurant or a
charitable cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, it's essential,'' she said. ``You've got to have a name
out there if you're going to get it dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her models is the effort behind breast cancer
fund-raising, which has raised tens of millions in the 1990s, in no
small part because of the glamour and financial support of people
like Ralph Lauren, Ronald O. Perelman and Evelyn Lauder.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to say you want to make ovarian cancer a chic cause.
Making that happen, however, is a tough job, largely because of the
disease's insidiousness: it is the most lethal cancer among women.
It is diagnosed in about 24,500 American women every year, and they
face daunting odds: three out of four die within five years of
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible, but most people don't survive long enough to
become celebrated spokespeople,'' said Anne Kolker, director of the
Ovarian Cancer National Alliance in Washington, an umbrella group.
``One of my colleagues spoke to somebody about this and she said,
`Gee, why isn't there the same level of advocacy for ovarian
cancer?' And the answer was because none of us lives long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tilberis, whose cancer was diagnosed four years ago, when
she was 46, has had surgery, chemotherapy and a marrow transplant.
She is in good health now, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In December, she presided over the first benefit for the Ovarian
Cancer Research Fund, which raised $750,000 and landed her cause in
the pages of In Style magazine. Altogether, her group has raised
more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   While breast cancer is more common _ afflicting about 180,000
American women each year _ breast cancer survival rates are higher.
The number of deaths from ovarian cancer is about half that of
breast cancer, said Dr. Robert Young, president of the Fox Chase
Cancer Center in Philadelphia. He said about 50,000 women die of
breast cancer each year, and 20,000 of ovarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make rough estimates comparing mortality and the amount
of research funding, the funding falls short,'' he said. ``It seems
to me that for ovarian cancer there ought to be targeted funding in
the neighborhood of $50 million to $60 million, and we're far short
of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the forgotten women's cancer. We've got to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the most crass terms, it is harder to enlist donors and
government sources of financing against ovarian cancer than other
diseases. It presents no easy symbol of feminine beauty and
potential frailty like the breast. In fact, there aren't even any
great colors left for a ribbon. (Ms. Tilberis' group is using
teal.)
</P>
<P>
   But in small ways, the movement is growing. President Clinton
has been asked to declare this month Ovarian Cancer Awareness
Month. Last year, the Ovarian Cancer National Alliance was
organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're beginning to see a new awareness, more activities and
more attention being focused on ovarian cancer,'' said Betty
Reiser, the director of the ovarian cancer program at Share, a
women's cancer advocacy group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an easily detectable disease. A routine annual Pap
smear detects cervical cancer, not ovarian cancer. Women cannot
examine their own ovaries every month, as they can their breasts.
And the symptoms of ovarian cancer are hardly distinguishable from
those suffered after a bout of food poisoning, a typical menstrual
period or a stressful day at the office: abdominal bloating,
indigestion, fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   There are usually no detectable symptoms in the early stages. To
diagnose ovarian cancer, patients must have a sonogram followed in
most cases by abdominal surgery. The blood test in current use _
called CA125 _ is not reliable in detecting early ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society reports that more than two-thirds of
the women who discover that they have ovarian cancer each year find
that it is already in Stage 4, when five-year survival rates hover
around 25 percent. If the cancer is discovered in Stage 1, survival
rates soar to 93 percent. One of the most urgent causes of the
ovarian cancer movement is to push for research that will speed
early diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The Journal of the American Medical Association
published a study by researchers at the Cleveland Clinic who
announced a new blood test for early detection that is more
sensitive and effective than any now available. (It is not yet
available to the public, however.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is finally national attention being focused on the
disease,'' Ms. Kolker of the national alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates in the fight against ovarian cancer maintain that
Ms. Tilberis doesn't deserve much credit for bringing attention to
the disease. Gail Hayward, the president of the National Ovarian
Cancer Coalition in Pompano Beach, Fla., said that grass-roots
organizations directed the spotlight to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think this recent awareness began because NOCC
began in 1993 and has sent out thousands and thousands of packages
of information and had millions of people visit our Web site and
done thousands and thousands of hours of work,'' Mrs. Hayward said.
``We are the underpinnings for the celebrity people. We came
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond, Ms. Tilberis said: ``She's right. The
underpinnings are at the heart of the charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But unless you can come out with a book or be a famous face
like Pierce Brosnan or someone . . . '' Her voice trailed off.
``It's great to be a support group. It's great to be one of those
smaller charities that will pass information around about the
newest chemotherapies or teas to drink or sharks' cartilage, but
what we're trying to do is attract enough attention to get the
18-year-old to listen. And you need a face for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0905-     09-04 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHERNOMYRDIN CALLS FOR ``ECONOMIC DICTATORSHIP'' AS KREMLIN,
COMMUNISTS TALK
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-BOX-0905.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Ignoring pleas coming just two days earlier from
President Clinton to avoid inflationary policies and state control
of the economy, President Boris Yeltsin's interim government
announced plans for an ``economic dictatorship'' that among other
steps will print more money to cope with the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin offered his plan to
deal with the worsening economic turmoil in a speech before
parliament, as the value of the ruble again fell sharply on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The tough talk was clearly a bid to win support for his
confirmation from the Communist-dominated Duma, parliament's lower
house, as Russia continues to operate without a permanent
government.
</P>
<P>
   The State Duma postponed a planned vote Friday on Chernomyrdin's
confirmation to allow negotiations over the weekend on Kremlin
proposals for an unprecedented power-sharing arrangement with the
Communist-led parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma was set to vote Chernomyrdin down for a second time,
prolonging Russia's political chaos as the economy withers. The
vote was rescheduled for Monday afternoon, after opposition leaders
attend talks with Yeltsin at the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said Friday that his party
would continue to oppose Chernomyrdin and seek an alternative
compromise candidate for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin repeated his support Friday for Chernomyrdin, who
served as prime minister from 1992 until March of this year and is
widely blamed for helping to create the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Chernomyrdin proposed an aggressive economic crisis
plan that includes printing money to help pay Russia's debts,
linking the ruble to the country's gold and foreign reserves and
establishing a state board to oversee the currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the government seemed ready to risk
hyper-inflation for the sake of bailing out shaky banks and paying
back wages to millions of workers -- albeit in significantly
devalued rubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inflation will go up very sharply. There will be further
turmoil in the economy, living standards will be cut,'' warned
Gunnar Tersman of the Russian-European Center for Economic Policy,
a think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly seems like in the short-run they are going to
bail out the banks to a considerable degree by giving them cheap
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Fyodorov, a co-author of the
economic plan, conceded in a Russian television interview that
prices will rise as a result of the policy. But he said it was
important for Russia to clear its mounting debt in order to
stabilize the economy and return to the pursuit of market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the ruble stood at 6.2 to the U.S. dollar, and
plunged to a close of 16.99 at the official rate Friday. On the
street, the ruble was trading as low as 20 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer prices also have continued to rise -- as much as 50
percent on some items -- and some markets reported food shortages.
Inflation rose to 15 percent in August, up from 0.2 percent in
July, the government reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While pumping more rubles into the economy would increase the
money supply, it also would weaken the currency's value and reduce
the spending power of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is scheduled to receive a $4.3 billion loan from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Sept. 15, part of a $22.6
billion bail-out package announced in July. But the IMF and Western
leaders, including Clinton who was in Moscow this week for a summit
with Yeltsin, have warned Russia that the aid will stop if market
reforms do not continue.
</P>
<P>
   Russia experienced massive inflation after the Soviet Union
collapsed in 1991, wiping out the savings of many Russians and
reducing much of the middle class into poverty in a matter of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that all savings will be lost in the coming weeks
or months and we will return to 1992. And it is very difficult to
survive 1992 twice, so nobody knows what it may lead to,'' said
Vyacheslav Nikonov, director of the Politica(CQ) Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, representatives from the Duma and the Kremlin were
expected to negotiate throughout the weekend in an effort to
overcome their political impasse.
</P>
<P>
   If the Duma rejects Chernomyrdin a second time, Yeltsin has the
option of proposing him a third time, or choosing a new candidate.
If the Duma votes against Yeltsin's choice a third time, the
president can call new Duma elections
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that on Monday the Duma will vote against Chernomyrdin
and then both sides will be searching for a compromise,'' said
Sergei Markov, director of the Moscow-based Institute of Political
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The upper house, the Federation Council, on Friday held a
largely symbolic vote in favor of Chernomyrdin. While it has no
constitutional force, the vote was added pressure on the Duma as
the upper house -- which consists of governors from Russia's
regions -- signaled it is supporting Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
