<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT IN A WEB OF ODD AUDIBLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: About two months ago, while on the Net, I
started to get peculiar sounds through my speaker system. They were
distinct cries for help. Since that time on two occasions I heard
very realistic cat fights and, just the other day, ghoulish
laughter. My service provider says he has no complaints from other
customers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Haunted
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HAUNTED: Maybe the other customers had been sticking to
their drug regimens like the nice doctors told them to. Hey, don't
get all weirded out, Haunted. I can think of about four
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe dweebs embedded those sounds in their Web pages because
they thought it would be way cool to freak out casual surfers.
Sticking sound on a page is something any reasonably well-trained
monkey can do: You just add the appropriate line of code in the
hypertext document that displays your page and upload it and an
accompanying sound clip file to the server where the rest of your
Web stuff is stored.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe somebody's woofing you. Maybe they loaded a bunch of
scary sound clips on your computer to signal certain system events.
OK, it's funny, but not too imaginative.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, certain unshielded speakers can pick up radio or
television waves and play them, but I thought ``The Fighting Cats
Hour'' had been canceled two seasons ago. Maybe I'm thinking of
that whole nasty Norville-Pauley business.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility is something you beings of this earthly
realm are not prepared to learn about. Just ignore anything you
think you hear. And that ghoulish laughter? Don't worry. That was
just me.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: i saw your article and was offended by the way
you were talking about hackers.Don't worry im not going to do
anything like send a virus to you but you shouldn't talk about
hackers that way the hobbie is expanding infact im a recruiter for
the world wide hacking group ``oo7'' yah call me elite if u want
but what im trying to say is dont talk about hackers the way you
did because i gaurantee at least 100 hackers saw that and i also
bet you will recieve many spam e-mails, virii, viruses, mail
bombs,and the most elite hacking aspect cracking all of your system
passwords i also would be glad to help with your security if u
would like cause i not only hack but i am a network manager.
</P>
<P>
   _ ..ooOCoD36X60oo..
</P>
<P>
   DEAR OO: Ooooooh! Now I'm really scared! Actually, what's really
frightening is that a functional illiterate is recruiting a whole
army of people who think that the degree to which they harm other
people is some measure of their own worth.
</P>
<P>
   The original hackers did no such harm. They broke into systems
to see if it could be done, then left things untouched. Somewhere
along the line, tiny-minded hangers-on _ hacker wannabes _ decided
it would be really funny to see how much damage they could do
building their own spurious ``legends.'' Let me say this slowly:
Out here in the real world, we're not impressed with your juvenile
pranks. Elite? Try ``pathetic.'' Why don't you just grow up and
take a remedial English course?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, by the way, I traced your e-mail and have informed your boss
about your ``hobbie.'' Your own computer is now being monitored.
You know, your password was really easy to guess, too.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID SOFTWARE TRICK: In Windows 98 and the ``B'' version of
95, select the 3D Text screensaver. Type in ``volcano'' for the
text and watch it cycle through different volcano names. (Thanks
and a tip o' the chapeau to Gordon Sandlin III.)
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay wants to hear about
your stupid software trick, too. He can be reached at
drbombay(AT)star-telegram.com or via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax: (817) 390-7257.
His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
