A0136 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-460&AMP;A     09-04 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APOLOGIZES FOR RELATIONSHIP WITH LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ President Clinton, forced again on this
five-day foreign trip to confront questions about the Lewinsky
scandal, said Friday that he ``basically'' agreed with Sen. Joseph
Lieberman who on Thursday criticized the president's conduct as
``immoral'' and ``disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time, Clinton said that he was ``very sorry
about'' his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, describing it as
``indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   In a picture-taking session Friday morning with the prime
minister of Ireland, Bertie Ahern, Clinton was asked about
Lieberman's remarks on the floor of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been briefed on them and basically I agree with what he
said,'' Clinton said. He was clearly prepared for the questions and
his manner displayed no suggestion of unease or defensiveness; he
stood casually with his hands clasped behind his back as Ahern
looked on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already said that I made a bad mistake, it was
indefensible and I'm sorry about it,'' Clinton said. ``So I have
nothing else to say except that I can't disagree with anyone else
who wants to be critical of what I have already acknowledged was
indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed further by reporters, Clinton added: ``There's nothing
that he or anyone else could say in a personally critical way that
I _ that I don't imagine that I would disagree with, since I have
already said it myself, to myself. And I'm very sorry about it.
There's nothing else I could say.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington on Friday, Lieberman said he appreciated Clinton's
apology, but added that the president would have to say more. ``It
doesn't end with a single statement,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said after the president spoke that his remarks were part
of a deliberate effort to convey remorse and to placate critics who
say that Clinton has not sufficiently apologized for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   The critics _ many in the president's own party _ have said that
Clinton has inflamed the crisis by continuing to attack Kenneth
Starr, the independent counsel whose investigation brought the
Lewinsky matter and Clinton's lies about it to light. Clinton made
no reference on Friday to the investigation that threatens his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman suggested on Thursday that Clinton's transgressions
were so severe that the Senate might feel compelled to formally
condemn them, in a vote of censure or other official action.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded: ``I just don't want to comment on that. I
shouldn't be commenting on that while I'm on this trip, and I don't
think that _ my understanding is that was not a decision that was
made or advocated clearly yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If that's not an issue, I don't want to make it one,
one way or the other. I don't think that's appropriate right now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the second time on this trip to Russia and Ireland,
Clinton's comments on the Lewinsky matter overshadowed the scripted
message of the day, which on Friday was supposed to be on progress
toward peace in Northern Ireland and prospects for economic growth
in the Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton faced questions on the affair in a Kremlin
press conference with Boris Yeltsin, the besieged president of
Russia. On that occasion, Clinton said he believed he had already
expressed his ``profound regret to all who were hurt'' by the
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Clinton knew he would confront the issue again
Friday after Lieberman's statement on Thursday. Erskine Bowles, the
White House chief of staff, tried to persuade Lieberman to delay
his remarks until after Clinton returned to Washington on Saturday
night, but Lieberman declined, according to Mike McCurry, the White
House press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Washington, Clinton spoke to Lieberman about the
senator's concerns, but he, too, failed to persuade Lieberman to
withhold judgment, McCurry said. Clinton, the aides said, chose his
words carefully on Friday as part of a strategy to apologize for
his actions, without offering any fuller explanation for them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went to bed Thursday night unaware of Lieberman's
comments, according to McCurry. The president was briefed on the
statement Friday morning and discussed possible responses with
Bowles and other senior advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made very clear how he wanted to respond, and that's what
he did,'' McCurry said. He added that there was no special
significance in the president's saying he was ``sorry'' twice in
his responses Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes that that's what he's been saying all along,''
McCurry said. ``Saying you're sorry means you're sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president knows that his further statement of regret
would not put the matter to rest, McCurry added. ``He's got a very
realistic outlook'' on Starr's investigation, on the continuing
debate in Congress and among the public about the Lewinsky
relationship, and on the certainty that he will continue to face
questions from the media about this issue at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president has been calling Democratic leaders
and other supporters in hopes of preventing further desertions like
Lieberman's. But the job of repairing the breach with members of
his party, and the public, will not be easy and will not be
accomplished quickly, McCurry acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president clearly does not believe that one
conversation, one statement, one speech is going to be sufficient
in addressing this matter the way he wants to, and he intends to
keep addressing it both personally and, to the degree he needs to,
publicly, as he sees fit,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said that there has been no discussion ``whatsoever''
among Clinton and his advisers about the president resigning.
</P>
<P>
   The president said in April that he would ``never'' resign.
Asked if Clinton had reconsidered in light of recent revelations,
McCurry replied, ``I am confident his attitude has not changed on
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
