<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGWIRE-ESSAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY BIG MAC'S HOME-RUN MOMENT WILL MOVE US TO TEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's unfortunate that I will react in the most unrugged way
possible when Mark McGwire hits his 62nd home run. When the St.
Louis Cardinal slugger surpasses Roger Maris' home-run record, I'm
sure I will choke up, perhaps even shed a drop or two of saline
water from the areas immediately left and right of my nose. Not a
fitting way to honor history's most stalwart, gifted home-run
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be helped. McGwire's breaking the record is that
important to me. (The Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa may well break it,
too, or even surpass Big Mac by season's end, and this entire essay
would then be equally true for his feat.) In fact, McGwire's
pending feat may be the most meaningful one that my generation of
sports fans will witness.
</P>
