   Funny though it is, it's rather easy to explain a man's (and
woman's) fascination with sports, and many books have been written
that do so. Sporting events, seasons and careers are
quick-and-dirty metaphors for life, as too many cliche-infested
speeches have reminded us. Football and war, you may have heard,
are oh-so-very similar, as ``North Dallas Forty'' and ``Saving
Private Ryan'' remind us. Baseball is particularly susceptible to
such comparisons: Like life, baseball is not governed by a time
clock; its languid pace and sudden bursts of excitement neatly
mirror our lives. (Well, not my life, which is in the third inning
of a scoreless game, but you get the picture.)
</P>
<P>
   All or none of this may be true. But what is certain is that 25
years of the day-to-day insanity of being a baseball fan _ reading
the box scores, listening to the pre-game show for lineup changes,
staying until the end of a 13-1 ballgame, punching someone who
tells you the designated hitter was a good innovation _ will soon
pay off for me and others like me. We did not see Babe Ruth play,
you understand. Gen X-ers were not around to see Maris break the
Babe's record.
</P>
<P>
   But that's ridiculous, you say. You have watched Michael Jordan,
who is (along with Pele) the greatest professional athlete in the
history of sports. Even in baseball, you saw Nolan Ryan throw his
5,000th strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   True but irrelevant. Jordan's is a lifetime achievement _ and a
subjective one at that. There are still those, for example, who say
that Wilt Chamberlain is basketball's greatest all-time player.
Ryan's feat is quantifiable, but again one accomplished during a
20-year period. It is no less awesome, but its impact on people who
are not true sports fans was negligible, at best.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire is hitting home runs, which is the most
recognizable feat in sports. The home run is THE metaphor most
Americans immediately understand and appreciate: It is majestic,
powerful, graceful and simple. It is what we all strive to be, an
act of compact force and clarity that defines what we want out of
our games and our athletic stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm chasing history,'' McGwire said this week, and I'm
glad he's acknowledging the importance of his home-run quest. I
don't want anyone, least of all him, to diminish the excitement
building for those of us who had to settle for Jim Rice instead of
Roger Maris, for Albert Belle instead of the Babe.
</P>
<P>
   I look forward to someday being able to bore my grandchildren
with the tale of Big Mac going Big Fly 62 (or more) times. I can
explain why my memory of his breaking that record is special and
how I hope they will one day understand. I will tell them that in
my mind's eye, I still clearly see Mark McGwire, and he is swinging
away.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
