<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0155 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-630&AMP;A     09-04 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA POSTPONES VOTE ON NEW GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian Parliament Friday put off until Monday a
critical vote on a new government, buying more time for political
horsetrading as the country's economic crisis worsened.
</P>
<P>
   With the central bank unable to summon the foreign currency
reserves to defend the ruble, its value fell sharply again Friday.
Inflation for the month of August was reported at 15 percent, an
official figure that paled next to the severe price increases
Russians saw this week as they scoured stores for vanishing
supplies of domestic staples and imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for ways to avert another showdown, the Parliament's
lower house Friday accepted President Boris Yeltsin's last-minute
offer to reopen talks on a power-sharing agreement, and delayed its
second vote on the nomination of Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime
minister. Chernomyrdin's nomination was defeated on its first try
last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But hopes for an easy breakthrough in Russia's 12-day-long
political deadlock flickered Friday when the leader of the
Communist Party _ which holds the biggest bloc of votes in the
lower house _ said he would refuse to sign any political agreement,
and would continue to oppose Chernomyrdin's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to consider any agreement on Monday,'' said
Gennadi Zyuganov. ``We won't sign anything. It's pointless.''
</P>
<P>
   Although opposition leaders have said they will present Yeltsin
with their own list of prime minister candidates on Monday, Yeltsin
_ as yet _ has shown no signs of backing away from his choice of
Chernomyrdin. A third rejection of the president's nominee by
Parliament would require Yeltsin to disband the lower house of
Parliament, known as the Duma, and call for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The country's mounting frustration and impatience with its
dawdling political leaders Friday finally penetrated the halls of
the Duma building, a giant structure of concrete and granite that
once housed the Soviet State Planning Agency.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation of striking miners, who have been camped for
several months outside the Russian government building in a nonstop
protest against unpaid wages, flashed guest passes at the security
guards at the Duma and briefly occupied its grand staircase,
rhythmically banging their miners' helmets against the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the flamboyant ultranational leader who
Thursday announced he would swing his 51 parliamentary deputies
behind Chernomyrdin's candidacy, also staged his own eruption from
the floor of the lower house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollar rate is already almost 20 rubles, and there are
lines at food stores even in Moscow,'' he shouted into the
microphone. ``Everything is being swept away, and then we will be
blamed. Either we will be disbanded, or we approve Chernomyrdin,
but we will be accused of exploding the ruble.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruble _ which was pegged at 6.2 to the dollar three weeks
ago _ fell Friday to 16.9, although stores and currency offices
around the city were trading at even lower rates. In another sign
of the widening crack in Russia's financial system, another major
bank, Inkombank, was taken under the temporary supervision of the
central bank, following similar orders imposed last week on
SBS-Agro, the country's second largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup against Chernomyrdin in the lower house did not
change Friday, even after he picked up an endorsement from a
majority in the Parliament's upper house, which is made up of
leaders from Russia's 89 regions.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did his speech, outlining a program of economic measures to
bring Russia out of its crisis, seem to sway anyone. If anything,
the program, which calls for a gradual easing into a harsh regime
of financial austerity, or ``economic dictatorship,'' was largely
ignored Friday as the debate focused on the search for a political
compromise.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, both Chernomyrdin and his supporters Friday said they
thought his chances for confirmation Monday had improved. As the
days go by, deputies from small left-wing parties, pressed by an
increasingly unhappy electorate and by regional bosses who want to
see a government move into Russia's widening political void, may
choose a face-saving way out of the impasse. They could also be
swayed by promises of ministerial portfolios, although such offers
have less value than usual, given the difficulties any government
would face in Russia today.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's offer to restart talks that had collapsed last weekend
signaled that he is still looking for ways to avoid the kind of
confrontation that could come with a disbanding of Parliament. In
1993, such a confrontation led to an aborted mutiny, and Yeltsin's
order to shell the Parliament building.
</P>
<P>
   On the table Monday when Yeltsin meets with leaders from both
houses of Parliament will be a political agreement that calls for a
redistribution of the considerable powers assigned to the president
under the 1993 constitution, which he himself crafted. The
agreement also spells out a political cease-fire, imposed on both
the Parliament and the president, designed to stop the kind of
brinkmanship that has brought Russia to a crisis point so many
times in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   To back up his peace offer, the president Friday submitted a law
that would amend the constitutional framework for the Russian
government, giving Parliament more say in the appointment of
cabinets _ a point that the Communists had pressed in negotiations
last weekend. Other parts of the political agreement call for a
moratorium on no-confidence votes against the government and a halt
to impeachment proceedings against Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party backed out of a similar agreement last
Sunday, setting the groundwork for the rejection Monday of
Chernomyrdin. Their reasons for backtracking still remain unclear,
but most analysts say that they probably see greater political
advantage in staying clear of an unpopular government and an
increasingly unpopular president. According to a recent poll of
1,500 citizens taken by the Social Opinion research group, 66
percent said Yeltsin should resign.
</P>
<P>
   If impeachment proceedings are initiated next week in the lower
house, as Communist deputies have threatened, it could run into a
constitutional logjam and explode into another confrontation. Under
the Russian constitution, a president cannot disband the lower
house once it has begun impeachment proceedings, whereas the same
constitution compels the president to disband the Parliament if it
rejects his choice for prime minister three times. If both events
happen at once, the issue is referred to the courts _ a recipe for
either more paralysis or more conflict.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario, now openly discussed, would allow Yeltsin to
disband the Parliament and then postpone the date for new
elections, using the argument that the country cannot afford them
to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Had the lower house held its second vote on Chernomyrdin's
candidacy Friday as expected, he would have surely gone down to
defeat again, setting the stage for a third vote in another week.
Given the urgency of the economic crisis, Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin
have tried to raise the stakes for the second vote, in order to
avoiding dragging the political battle on for another week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
