<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVANGELIST IS KEEPING `IN TOUCH' WITH THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Charles Stanley, pastor of the 14,000-member First
Baptist Church of Atlanta, has had an amazing rise as a television
and radio evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   He started small, with his weekly sermons televised only in
Atlanta in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I let Pat Robertson have our tapes to play on the
Christian Broadcasting Network in 1978,'' Stanley said this week.
And his ``In Touch'' programs began to spread slowly around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Now his programs are seen or heard in about 250 nations, Stanley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord has just opened door after door,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the televangelist scandals of the mid-1980s slowed the
growth of his broadcast ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get into issues much,'' he said. ``I just preach Bible
truths. And I distance myself from finances of the church or the
television ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who served twice as president of the Southern Baptist
Convention, helped move that denomination in a conservative
direction.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't get involved in this year's convention in Salt
Lake City when Baptists passed a controversial resolution on family
which stated that wives should submit graciously to their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe the Bible says that the husband is the head of
the home,'' said Stanley. ``But he has to be a loving husband, not
dictatorial.''
</P>
<P>
   His basic interests now are his broadcast ministry and his
Atlanta church. The congregation has moved from near downtown
Atlanta to the outskirts of the city. It is meeting in a
300,000-square-foot converted office building, but a new sanctuary
will be built as soon as the downtown property is sold, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And his ``In Touch'' programs are available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pull up a sermon any time of the day or night,'' he
said. ``We've had over 7 million hits on the Internet so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web address is www.intouch.com.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley has had a number of books published. His latest,
released this month by Thomas Nelson, is ``Enter His Gates,'' a
series of devotionals for each month based on the 12 gates of the
old city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other devotional books are ``A Touch of His
Goodness,'' ``A Touch of His Freedom,'' ``A Touch of His Wisdom''
and ``A Touch of His Love.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the secret of Stanley's popularity?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hurting and looking for answers,'' said Stanley.
``Whether they feel a sense of rejection or whether they feel lost
in sin, I'm teaching the word of God in simple fashion. And it is
meeting people's needs and hurts where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's career hasn't been without difficulties. His biggest
challenge came three years ago with his highly publicized marital
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Anna, twice filed for divorce, saying Stanley cared
more for his ministry than for her. She later withdrew the
petitions. The two are still separated, however.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's position as pastor of First Baptist, Atlanta, was
threatened at the time. Many Baptists believe a divorce
disqualifies a person from being pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a painful experience, Stanley said it has
sensitized him to people in similar situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep going on,'' he said. ``I've learned a
lot from it. I think the whole experience has made me more
understanding of people in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   And even that may have added to his television and radio
audiences, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's caused a lot of people to start listening to
me,'' said Stanley. ``A lot of people figured I had it all
together, but now they know how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I believe God has taken a bad situation and used it
for good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
