<HEADLINE>
READERS GET THEIR OWN SAY FOR THE HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the interest of getting a running start on
the last long weekend of summer, this is a good time to dip into
the ol' mailbag and let the readers do the work of writing today's
column.
</P>
<P>
   Our lead-off helper will be a Kansas City, Kan., woman who takes
issue with a recent column contending that politicians don't do
``the work of the people,'' but work more for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's job is to protect us from...the greed...of
business....Corporations are a much bigger `brother' than
government, largely because they can keep their objectives and
activities secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Distrustful:
</P>
<P>
   Your faith is misplaced. Business isn't the evil thing you
perceive it to be. Have you ever considered what you or government
could accomplish without business? No business, no jobs. Business
provides the products you want and need and the services you
require daily. Without business there would be no individual or
corporate tax revenues for government to redistribute to the
consumers of its goodies. Moreover, have you ever thought about the
things government can do to you that business can't? Government can
put you in jail, confiscate your property, force you to do things
that aren't in your best interest to do, and take your money
against your will. Business can't do any of these things. As for
keeping secrets, government is at least as good at that as
business. Maybe more so.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of government's abilities to serve the people, another
recent column decried the legacy of Soviet-style communism, which
has left Russian business largely ineffective as the country tries
to create a market economy. A Johnson County reader responds to the
observation that few, if any, imports ever bear the inscription
``Made in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here are three examples of (Russian-made products) I have some
familiarity with: vacuum tubes. Yes, the `hollow state' devices are
still in demand. Small signal types have not been made in the
United States for some time....(The) best imports are from Russia.
(Another is) world's best .22-caliber ammunition. Up until the '94
Olympics, the Russian stuff absolutely dominated the
competition...world-class product (but) poor export distribution,
(so) I cannot buy the stuff anywhere....(Also) vodka, several
brands, that seem to be world-class.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Informative:
</P>
<P>
   Veddy interesting. Your examples seem to strengthen my argument
that Russia is a far piece from transforming itself into a dynamic
producer of standout consumer goods for high-consumption economies.
The fact that they are big in the vacuum tube business leads to a
question of whether they're also major producers of eight-track
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   As long as we're talking about government and business, here's
an interesting take on the nonmarketable Treasury securities in the
Social Security ``trust'' fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``(T)he giant con behind the Social Security `surplus' (is)
probably the most successful fraud ever perpetrated on an
unsuspecting public. The analogy I like to use...is this: I can
make you a millionaire instantly! I'll just give you an IOU for a
million dollars. You can then go put it in a safe-deposit box and
list it as an asset. You're a millionaire! Listing the IOU as an
asset is fundamentally what the government is doing with this
`trust fund.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Perspicacious:
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the insight. Couldn't have analogized it better
myself.
</P>
<P>
   Keep them cards and letters comin', hear?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
