<SLUG> BC-CARS-ENVIRON-GUIDE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUIDE TO CLEANER DRIVING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICKEY MEECE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many consumers want to know the size of a car's engine, its
horsepower, how fast it races from 0 to 60 miles an hour. They're
interested in the number of pockets, compartments and cup holders.
But do they really care about the environmental impact of the
vehicle they're thinking of buying?
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring many signs of environmental apathy, the American
Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy has published the ``Green
Guide to Cars and Trucks,'' which ranks all 1998 models for
environmental friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   The higher a vehicle's ``green score'' on a scale of 0 to 100,
the higher its environmental friendliness over its lifetime. (The
average green score for 1998 was 21.) Each model is also assessed a
ranking by class.
</P>
<P>
   The objective, according to the book's authors, John DeCicco,
senior associate of the Washington-based nonprofit group, and
Martin Thomas, a research assistant, was to urge consumers to
consider environmental factors as they would price, safety and
styling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know people do have environmental sensibilities,'' DeCicco
said, but such information has not been available to them. The
guide thus fills a void, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 108-page soft-cover guide is available from the group for
$8.95, plus $5 for shipping and handling. More information is
available by calling (202) 429-0063 or on the Web site,
www.aceee.org/greenguide. A guide for 1999 models will be published
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The authors used data on tailpipe emissions and fuel economy,
along with an estimate of pollutants emitted during the
manufacturing process, to come up with an environmental damage
index. The index was then converted to a green score.
</P>
<P>
   All things being equal, the authors said, consumers could choose
cars with the highest green score. For example, Thomas said, ``even
this year and model year 1999, you can walk into dealerships and
look at four different versions of the Ford Escort.'' The same is
true of Honda Civics, he said, adding that the car that one picks
``does make a difference on the environment.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
