<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-PRICES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTORISTS BENEFITING FROM NATIONWIDE DECREASE IN GASOLINE PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Motorists out and about this Labor Day
weekend will be burning the cheapest gasoline, adjusted for
inflation, since at least World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to abundant supplies, the average price for self-service
gas in the Kansas City area this weekend is 94.1 cents a gallon.
That's about 30 cents a gallon less than Labor Day weekend a year
ago, according to the latest survey by the AAA Automobile Club of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, AAA said, the average price is $1.08 a gallon, down
18.9 cents from a year ago. In nominal terms, motorists enjoy the
lowest gasoline prices in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The news is even better for consumers when prices are adjusted
for inflation. Mike Shanahan, a spokesman for the American
Petroleum Institute in Washington, said gasoline prices are at
their lowest inflation-adjusted level since such statistics started
being compiled before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern motorists in particular are benefiting from economic
factors that have pushed down gasoline prices, according to the AAA
and the American Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Ackerman, a Blue Springs, Mo., motorist gassing up
Thursday, said that in his travels through the Midwest, ``Kansas
City has been one of the low ones'' in terms of price.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said he can remember paying well over $1 a gallon this
time a year ago, ``but I don't like to remember those kinds of
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The average gas price in the Midwest is $1.04 a gallon. Only the
Southwest, at $1.03 a gallon, and the Southeast, at 98 cents a
gallon, have lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   The West is the most expensive, with an average price of $1.22 a
gallon. That's followed by New England at $1.08, the Mid-Atlantic
at $1.06 and the Great Lakes at $1.05.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where motorists drive in the United States, gas prices
are a fraction of those in most other industrialized nations, which
routinely tax gas far more heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Sharply lower gas prices are due to a 10 percent increase in
crude oil supplies compared with a year ago and a decrease in
worldwide demand caused by the Asian financial crisis, said Mike
Right, spokesman for AAA in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major factor is the strength of the supply,'' he said.
``There is an abundance of crude oil and finished product.''
</P>
<P>
   Abundant supplies are partly a result of a decision last
November by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
increase oil production. Shortly afterward, Asia's economic woes
hit.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Iraq recently was permitted to sell crude oil on
the world market after several years of sanctions. And despite cuts
in daily production by OPEC, several members have been exceeding
the quota.
</P>
<P>
   Also, said Shanahan, Midwest states had a warmer winter than
expected and used less heating oil, adding more product on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts projected that with gasoline at such low rates,
motorists would take advantage and do more driving this summer. But
gasoline consumption did not meet those expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economists thought people would see prices so low they would
drive more,'' Shanahan said. ``It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The AAA estimates that nearly 37 million Americans will take
trips of 100 miles or more this Labor Day, up 5 percent from last
year, but not nearly enough to offset double-digit growth in
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline supplies are being boosted, in part, by improved
technology that allows for cheaper oil exploration and extraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like MRI technology _ 3-D pictures,'' Shanahan said. ``It
costs less to find and get it out of the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting glut has caused crude oil prices to fall far below
levels a year ago, Right said.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices are about $13.33 a barrel, compared with nearly
$20 a barrel a year ago. The wholesale price of gasoline is about
40 cents a gallon, compared with 70 cents a gallon a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Right noted that Saudi Arabia recently said it would cut
production, and several American refineries said they also would
cut back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, with a 10 percent level over last year, there is an
awful lot of product out there,'' Right said. ``But efforts to
bring supply and demand in line eventually will bring prices up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
