<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-MISSILE-520&AMP;AD     09-04 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-MISSILE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA SAYS IT WAS WRONGLY ACCUSED OF TESTING A MISSILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ North Korea said Friday that the purpose of its
launching on Monday of a two-stage rocket was to carry a satellite
into orbit, not to test a missile. It denounced Japan and other
countries for jumping to the conclusion that it was launching a new
class of missile.
</P>
<P>
   Military and scientific experts in the United States, Japan and
South Korea immediately began reviewing their data, but their
initial reaction to the North Korean announcement was deep
skepticism. Officials said that they had not detected any new
satellite and that they were reasonably sure that what they had
monitored was a missile test.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said that if it had been a
satellite, Japanese technology should have been able to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, we cannot consider that this was a launch of a
satellite,'' a Japanese National Defense Agency official told NHK
television in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The launching of the two-stage rocket caused deep alarm in Japan
and provoked a chorus of denunciation in Tokyo and Washington. The
rocket passed over Japan, with the first stage dropping into the
sea before reaching Japan and the second stage dropping in the
ocean on the other side, and the idea of a North Korean rocket
whizzing overhead gave the Japanese people a new and more immediate
sense of their vulnerability to enemy missiles.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's missiles are not considered particularly useful
militarily, because they are quite inaccurate and could not
dependably hit their targets. But the test provoked concern among
some experts because it suggested that the missiles could now, for
the first time, reach any part of Japan, including Tokyo, and
because it indicated that North Korea had worked out the technology
for multi-stage rocketry.
</P>
<P>
   That may mean an initial range of about 1,000 miles for a
one-ton payload, but by improving the technology and lightening the
load, North Korea might in the coming years develop
intercontinental ballistic missiles and threaten U.S. soil. Since
North Korea is believed to have some nuclear weapons and huge
stocks of chemical weapons, the missile technology has aroused
fears of the payload that the missiles could carry.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket launching on Monday came at a time of growing
international exasperation with North Korea, and politicians in
Tokyo and Washington alike seemed ready to put more pressure on the
North Korean government. North Korea had not previously commented
on the launching, although it had complained that Japanese critics
did not know what they were talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our scientists and technicians have succeeded in launching the
first artificial satellite aboard a multi-stage rocket into
orbit,'' the official Korean Central News Agency declared in
Friday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The satellite is now transmitting the melody of the immortal
revolutionary hymns Song of General Kim Il Sung and Song of General
Kim Jong Il,'' the dispatch said. Kim Il Sung, who died in 1994,
was North Korea's longtime ruler. His son, Kim Jong Il, now rules
the country and is expected to be appointed president in the coming
days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The successful launching of the first artificial satellite in
the DPRK,'' the wire said, referring to North Korea, ``greatly
encourages the Korean people in the efforts to build a powerful
socialist state under the wise leadership of the Great Leader Kim
Jong Il.''
</P>
<P>
   Although North Korea has almost no credibility among neighboring
countries, officials did not quite rule out the possibility that
North Korea was telling the truth about a satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been able to verify whether North Korea fired its
missile for satellite purposes,'' said Kim Young Min, a spokesman
for South Korea's Unification Ministry. ``I don't think we will be
able to verify that fact in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a senior government official said there was no
question that North Korea fired a Taepodong-1 missile on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said that even if the missile did
carry a satellite, the launching remained a grave concern for the
administration because of the technological advances it
demonstrated. ``No matter the purpose, it demonstrated the
capability to deliver a weapons payload against surface targets at
medium ranges,'' the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
