<P>
   SUNDAY MARKETS PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   The AJC is planning a package for this Sunday examining whether
the stock market volatility has altered consumer behavior, as well
as the plans of businesses that are directly affected by the whims
of consumers. Early reporting indicates that consumer confidence is
eroding, but other forces are probably more important than concerns
about the market. There's no doubt, however, that the market news
will reinforce some negative trends that were already at work. A
budget with all of the stories and visual elements that will run in
this package will move on the Cox wire. A CoxNet repackaged page
has been created and posted on the Cox server. Please call CoxNet
at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CLINTON _ LIMERICK, Ireland _ Spot coverage of Day Three
(final day) of President Clinton's visit to Northern
Ireland/Ireland; speech in Limerick; afternoon golf; wrap-up of
trip. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving SPOT Saturday, Sept. 5, for use Sunday, Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONER-BERENSON _ MIAMI _ ``President Clinton visited with
Monica Lewinsky on 37 occasions, but he can't see us once,'' said
Mark Berenson, his voice trembling with anger. For the last two and
a half years, the New Yorker and his wife, Rhoda Berenson, have
worked to free their daughter, Lori Berenson, from a windowless
prison some 500 miles outside Lima, Peru, where she's serving a
life sentence for treason. The 28-year-old MIT graduate was
convicted in 1996 of plotting to take over Peru's Congress by
hooded judges during a secret trial. The Berensons have tried
repeatedly to see Clinton, who has asked Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori to review their daughter's case. I will visit in New York
with the couple, who will be just back from a visit with their
daughter at the prison, located 12,700 feet above sea level. I will
also visit with other members of Lori Berenson's family, who live
in Palm Beach, Florida. Story will focus on the family's plight to
win their daughter's freedom, and where Lori Berenson's case stands
now. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With information for a locator map.
</P>
<P>
   With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Tuesday, Sept. 1, for use Sunday, Sept. 6 and
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   POOR-SUBURBS _ WASHINGTON _ The economy is booming, but not for
everybody. Two decades of declining wages have squeezed the middle
class and flattened the poor. Nowhere is this trend more apparent
than in suburbia, where the Cleavers have given way to the Joads,
with little or no social safety net left. (Shepard and Jaspin, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   POOR-DATA- _ Graphics material.
