<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH _ Chapel Hill think tank MDC's latest State of the South
report concludes that old problems and new pressures in
immigration, education, the work force and families threaten the
South's dynamic growth. We visit Hickory, N.C., to talk with people
at Catawba Valley Community College who are caught up in these
changes. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHBOX _ Chart showing that while the percentage of white men
in the labor force in the South has declined in the past 21 years,
the percentage of Hispanic men and women has doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-GAMBLING _ EUPORA, Miss._She's from a two-stoplight town
west of Starkville and east of nowhere. She wears demure church
dresses, plays the piano, and works for a state legislator when
she's not taking care of her two children. And this summer,
Elizabeth Stoner has become a household name in Mississippi. She
filed an initiative in June that would put the issue of riverboat
casinos to a statewide vote, giving Mississippians a chance to kick
the casinos out. If they vote to ban gambling, the 30 riverboats
docked in eight counties along the Mississippi River and the Gulf
Coast would have two years to shut down. (Rochell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BINGO _ ROCK HILL, S.C. - The Indian tribe that didn't really
want to open a bingo parlor because of religious beliefs is now
raking in about $2 million a month at the largest bingo operation
on the Eastern Seaboard. Located in a former Sears Roebuck store on
the edge of this college town, Catawba Bingo offers games every day
except Sunday, luring thousands of folks from all over the
Southeast. On Big Games days, twice each month, the payout is
$200,000 with one game worth $50,000. Folks arrive as early as 10
a.m. for the start of the 1 p.m. games. ``We're doing quite well,''
said Wanda George Warren, the Catawba Indian Nation's executive
director. (Riddle, AJC freelancer; not for use by NYT clients).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   LABOR _ The labor movement in the Miami Valley and United States
has been on the decline for about two decades. Nearly every major
independent union has seen a drastic decline in membership while
battling with massive private employers like the General Motors
Corp. In fact, some labor experts believe the labor movement is
nothing but a myth. And results from a recent Dayton Daily
News/Springfield News-Sun poll show residents also believe unions
are losing power. Nearly half of the poll's 503 respondents believe
labor unions will become weaker in the Miami Valley over the next
10 years. And nearly 80 percent of the people polled believe
companies will continue to export more jobs during the same period.
The poll shows that people in the Dayton-area are becoming less
sympathetic towards labor unions. We talk with poll respondents,
labor leaders, workers, labor experts and others about the problems
facing unions and what organized labor is doing to reverse its
decline in membership and support. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News).
50-60. WITH GRAPHICS (About 10 graphics with poll results, mugs of
poll respondents and photos of AFL-CIO labor rally).
</P>
<P>
   GM _ Who got hurt most by the recent United Auto Workers strike
against the General Motors Corp in Flint, Mich.? The automaker and
company endured about the same amount of pain, according to Miami
Valley residents responding to the Dayton Daily News/Springfield
News-Sun labor poll. Surprisingly, more people from union
households believe one of the costliest strikes in U.S. history
hurt the UAW more than the company. The poll results reflect the
opinions of most labor and Wall Street analysts who said neither
side won the 54-day strike labor dispute which idled nearly 200,000
workers and shut down GM's North American production. (Wagner,
Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WORKERS-GOODBAD _ American workers have never had it so good. So
why do so many of them feel so bad? (Joyner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   PEREGRINEFALCONS _ What does it take to bring an endangered
species back from the brink of extinction? Georgia's work restoring
local populations of peregrine falcons offers some insight, and
points the way to future initiatives aimed at expanding populations
of rare species. A behind-the-scenes look at the program and the
people who made it work. (Seabrook , Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDCHICKEN _ Tasting the South. Every September, Harold Smith
and company drag the World's Biggest Frying Skillet (it weighs 700
pounds and comes in four wedge-shaped segments that each take three
men to hoist) out of storage and reassemble it to feed the crowds
at London's World Chicken Festival. Chew on that name a moment: not
the London Chicken Festival or the Kentucky Chicken Festival _ the
World Chicken Festival. Where does a town in a state that produces
a smigen of the poultry produced in Georgia or Arkansas get off
staging an event with such a preposterously boastful name? The
justification lies in a former resident who made good, a tough old
bird named Harland Sanders. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH LAYOUT and COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDCHICKEN-RECIPES _ Recipes to go with main bar on fried
chicken. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH LAYOUT
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-BOOK _ In the summer of 1947, fellow Emory University
graduates James A. Mackay and Calvin Kytle embarked on a statewide
fact-finding mission spurred by the bizarre turn of political
events after Georgia's 1946 Democratic primary. A half century
after they documented the influence of money in state politics, the
two authors of the newly published ''Who Runs Georgia?'' say their
research foreshadowed the national debate over campaign finance
reform. Mackay, 79, is a retired Georgia state legislator and U.S.
congressman. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
