<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S VISIT TO DUBLIN IS MORE LOW-KEY THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ Harassed but smiling and even joking,
President Clinton returned to Dublin on Friday, as he promised he
would on his first trip here in December 1995. But Friday's visit
was very different.
</P>
<P>
   The last time, he was thunderously cheered by thousands as he
spoke at College Green, near Trinity College, of the possibility of
a new peace in Northern Ireland. The sun was shining and his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, stood by him and waved to the crowd, which
waved hundreds of American flags back at them.
</P>
<P>
   He was an American hero, with some Irish roots who reminded many
Irish people of President John F. Kennedy: youthful, handsome,
articulate.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at a reception for labor leaders and business
executives, Clinton looked back fondly to that visit, saying ``it's
great to be back in Dublin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there is a little rain in the air today,'' he
continued, ``it's always bright and sunny for me here. The day that
we were in College Green in 1995 will go down for me as one of the
great days of my presidency and, indeed, one of the great days of
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Clinton did not go out in the cold rain to shake
hands. He attended only indoor events with Irish politicians and a
few hundred workers at a American-owned computer factory. Mrs.
Clinton was either missing or out of television camera range.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, the president was warmly applauded, and none of
the Irish people he met brought up awkward personal questions or
made complaints about his order for a missile attack on a
pharmaceutical plant in the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government and most Irish men and women apparently
felt it would be churlish to attack Clinton for his relationship
with Monica Lewinsky. Callers to radio talk shows said they were
happy he was back, that without him there would be no peace in
Northern Ireland, and that his peace effort had in effect saved
several hundred lives.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing about the visit that bothered them, it seemed,
were the traffic jams in downtown Dublin caused by the closing of
main thoroughfares for security. In central Dublin, manhole covers
were being sealed and street-light poles taped shut with steel
bands to prevent the implantation of bombs. People looking out a
window at the motorcade said they had been told by Americans with
short hair and in dark suits that it was all right to look, but not
to open the window.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen people stood across from government Buildings, where
Clinton met Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, and waved signs of
protest over the Sudan bombing, which was heavily criticized here.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Times, which often criticizes U.S. policy, said in an
editorial that Ahern should have expressed reservations about the
Sudan attack in his meeting with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Deputy National Security Adviser Jim Steinberg said he had
no knowledge that Ahern had done so, asserting only that the prime
minister had expressed understanding of the responsibility the
United States has to combat terrorism around the world. Of the
Lewinsky issue, the newspaper said that ``most Irish people would
share the general view in Europe that the affair has been abused by
his opponents and blown out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's visit, Clinton used Irish writers to make some
of his points, quoting James Joyce, for example: ``History is a
nightmare from which I am trying to awaken.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Gateway computer factory, Clinton was greeted with
several hundred cheering, flag-waving employees, a faint reminder
of the thousands in the streets on the first visit.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton and Ahern issued an electronic communique using
``smart cards,'' Clinton tried a joke: He said nowadays everything
is done by computer and that in the future ``we'll have virtual
presidents, virtual Prime Ministers, virtual everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Foreign Minister Dick Spring had some kind words
discussing the golf he is scheduled to play with Clinton on
Saturday in Ballybunnion, in the west of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his handicap is 13 or 14,'' said Spring, a good
golfer. Asked if he would ever consider playing poorly to let the
visitor win, Spring said, ``I don't think so. There will be honor
among politicians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
