<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: TRASH, FROGS, SPIEGEL, SNOWBALLS, SURFING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trash Is Her Bag
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trash inspired Leah Singer to start her own
newspaper. Working as a freelance graphic artist, she was
captivated by Rubyliths _ orange acrylic masking films used by
commercial artists to make silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   She dug some out of a wastebasket and, she said, ``fell in love
with them _ they were so strange.'' She collected silhouettes
including a Buddha, a roller skater and a woman with a gun, and
produced 1,000 copies of a 16-page all-graphics ``newspaper''
called Copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are accessible and cheap, and yet they hold so much
meaning,'' Ms. Singer said. Copy, printed on newsprint, sells for
$8 in outlets like Printed Matter (77 Wooster St., near Spring
Street) and Alleged Gallery (28 Prince St., near Mott Street;
closed until Sept. 14).
</P>
<P>
   But the idea has expanded. She started silk-screening the
silhouettes on canvas bags. (If public television can have tote
bags, why not Copy?)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had them for two or three months, and I've sold more
than 50,'' said Aaron Rose, owner of Alleged, to ``everyone from
young fashionable kids to tourists to fashion ladies.'' Steven
Meisel stopped by Alleged twice for photo shoots, and twice the
bags appeared in fashion photos in American Vogue and Italian
Vogue. The gnomic images of the gun girl and the Buddha are popular
with Japanese tourists in San Francisco, where the bags are $20 at
the Mac clothing store. Bags can be ordered from Ms. Singer at
(212) 587-1337.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA LEE
</P>
<P>
   Frogs Hit the Charts
</P>
<P>
   Cold-blooded they may be, but frogs have never been hotter. In
May, alarm over frog populations caused Congress to form the Task
Force for Amphibian Decline and Deformities. Now frogs are going
from popular cause to radio sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Folkways Smithsonian has just rereleased ``Sounds of North
American Frogs'' _ field recordings that include the sounds of 57
species, among them the confident growl of the Florida gopher frog
and the paranoid honk of the green tree frog.
</P>
<P>
   The odd selection, first issued in 1958, is getting rotations on
a few rock stations and is No. 166 on the College Music Journal's
current chart (sandwiched between Arab Strap's ``Philophobia'' and
the Dave Matthews Band's ``Before These Crowded Streets''). Tony
Seeger, the Folkways curator and director, can't believe the
response, nor figure out what artist or genre to list the disk
under. ``It's certainly not folk,'' he said. ``It isn't rock. We
thought we'd put it under Various Amphibians.''
</P>
<P>
   Folkways has been approached by one composer who wants to
include frog sounds in his next piece, but he's not the first. The
hip-hop turntable team known as the Invisibl Scratch Piklz beat him
to it with the repetitive croak on its coming release ``The Friggar
Shiggar Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidewalk Snowball Fete
</P>
<P>
   The lines formed as usual on a recent summer night outside Bond
Street and Bowery Bar. What was unexpected was the action around
the corner, on the patch of sidewalk in front of Guru, a
flavored-snowball stand. On some Thursdays, Mary Frey, Guru's
owner, hauls out a turntable and transforms this dark industrial
stretch of Lafayette Street into a yard-style party, where players
on the downtown scene like the Beastie Boys and Chloe Sevigny hang
out, listen to dub music and help themselves to free pomegranate
and coconut snowballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just friends, really,'' said Ms. Frey, describing a
recent Guru crowd that included Mario Sorrenti, a fashion
photographer; the former Deee-Lite singer Lady Miss Kier; Mary
Schecter, a rock-star stylist, and Ms. Frey's four-year-old
Rottweiler, for whom Guru is named.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frey used to work the door at nightclubs like Save the
Robots, but Guru has a door policy more akin to yard parties in her
native New Orleans: no velvet ropes, no cover charge. Celebrities
are more likely to arrive by skateboard than limousine.
</P>
<P>
   But without a VIP room, how to keep the party from being overrun
by passers-by? ``Whoever feels it knows it,'' said Joe Hova, who is
Guru's deejay and was a childhood friend of Ms. Frey. ``And if it
gets too crowded, we skip a few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   TO DIAL FOR: `ELEMENTS,' FROM SPIEGEL
</P>
<P>
   87 pages; Rapid City, S.D.; (800) 778-5555
</P>
<P>
   Preface: Spiegel, the Midwestern mail-order pioneer, is updating
its image to attract the Pottery Barn crowd with this new catalog
of Asian-influenced furnishings and loose-fitting clothing designed
by Lisa Versacio, formerly of Liz Claiborne.
</P>
<P>
   Esthetic hook: Suburban Zen.
</P>
<P>
   Frequency: Every six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sample prose: ``Sensual fabrics and colors lift the spirit &QL; 
providing balance in a world surrounded by chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Sample colors: henna and sweet pea.
</P>
<P>
   Most expensive item: brown velvet sofa on wheels, $1,498.
</P>
<P>
   What you'll find inside: Scented candles ($36), velvet beanbag
chairs ($168), gem-tone acrylic and wool throws ($98), the book ``A
Room of Her Own: Women's Personal Spaces'' ($30).
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to end up at a garage sale: aluminum tray ($68).
</P>
<P>
   The look: Mood lighting, a seraglio by candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   Mailing list: 2.5 million of ``the best Spiegel customers,''
said a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Surf on Seventh
</P>
<P>
   Seventh Avenue's going surfing. Designers, stylists and fashion
executives are catching the surf craze, and not just by making
beachy clothes. Camp Pascowitz, a family-run surf camp at San
Onofre State Beach in California, counts movie executives and rock
stars (Perry Farrell, Chris Isaak, Flea and his daughter) among its
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   But now it is noticing an influx of would-be boarders from the
East Coast, particularly the garment trade, said Izzy Pascowitz,
the owner. ``We've had this huge draw of fashion people,'' he said.
``Editors, executives from Versace and Louis Vuitton, the marketing
director of Hugo Boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Stylish New Yorkers aren't the only ones who have realized that
just looking like a surfer doesn't cut it anymore. Any day now the
Pascowitzes are expecting the beach-blond Hanson family. ``They
look like such surfers,'' Pascowitz said of the band, which is from
Oklahoma. ``It's a pity they don't actually surf.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
