<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MORAL05-COX     09-04 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MORAL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: LIEBERMAN STANDARD WOULD RAISE MORAL BAR FOR OFFICE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman's admonishments that the
president has no private life and must stand as a moral exemplar
carry profound implications for those who hold and seek the
nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   With one sobering speech from the Senate floor, the longtime
ally of President Clinton lifted the White House sex and deception
scandal beyond party and politics to what the Connecticut Democrat
called the ``bright lines of right and wrong in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, he implicitly offered Americans a choice between
two standards for their president.
</P>
<P>
   The public can choose to brush aside Clinton's admitted
misconduct with a former White House intern as irrelevant so long
as they approve of his administration of national and international
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Lieberman urged in impassioned words Thursday, they can
accept that a ripple effect goes from the White House to the
children who are now asking their parents troubling questions about
the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is a role model who, because of his prominence
and the moral authority that emanates from his office, sets
standards of behavior for the people he serves,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has insisted that he is entitled to some
privacy, his friend declared that no president has a private life
in these times of all-news 24-hour cable networks. Moreover,
Lieberman said that the personal example is essential now that
``our society's standards are sinking, that our common moral code
is deteriorating and that our public life is coarsening.''
</P>
<P>
   By that reasoning, the president becomes responsible not just
for public policy on taxes and budgets and diplomacy, but for
setting the tone to counter disintegrating families and
out-of-wedlock births that now account for almost one in every
three new babies. He helps set the example for sexual mores of
teenagers and adults.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman blasted Clinton for behavior that ``sends a message of
what is acceptable behavior to the larger American family,
particularly to our children, which is as influential as the
negative messages communicated by the entertainment culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lieberman model, if accepted by the public, would raise the
bar of qualifications for presidents, recalling predictions made
earlier this year by William Bennett, who served in two Republican
cabinets and has written extensively on public morality. Soon after
the news first broke of the sexual liaison between Clinton and
former-intern Monica Lewinsky, Bennett said that the heightened
scrutiny of character means that any Republican who seeks the
presidency in 2000 had better have been faithful in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've committed adultery, I don't think you're going to
get the nomination,'' he said, citing the increased scrutiny of
candidates in the aftermath of the Clinton sex controversy.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some past presidents have not held to high standards
of personal conduct. John F. Kennedy, his former Secret Service
guards have now revealed, brought prostitutes into the White House,
and his escapades with a Mafia girlfriend are well documented.
Lyndon B. Johnson is widely quoted as bragging that he had more
infidelities than Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But in those cases the public was unaware of the
behind-the-scenes conduct until much later. In the Clinton case,
the behavior has already been disclosed in increasingly grim
detail, forcing the public to make the difficult judgment on what
it expects from its chief executive while he's still in office. The
public's verdict now will set the rules not only for this president
but for future ones.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
