<HEADLINE>
TIGHT ENDS SHARPE, COATES NO LONGER UNKNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; DOVE VALLEY, Colo. _ At first, Shannon Sharpe said he was too
busy to sit and talk. This brought a chuckle. Are the Rocky
Mountains too tall to climb? Too steep to ski? There are certain
givens in Denver, and Shannon Sharpe talking is more of a certainty
than snow falling upon Vail or Aspen.
</P>
<P>
   But then the subject of Ben Coates was brought up, and 15
minutes later, Shannon Sharpe was still talking. Coates and Sharpe
not only are the two best tight ends in football but the closest of
pals. Coates is ``my closest friend in the NFL,'' Sharpe said,
``outside of the guys here in this locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   The friendship goes back more than a decade, to when Sharpe took
Coates on his recruiting trip to Sharpe's school, Savannah State,
and gave Coates the obligatory tour of the tiny campus in Georgia.
He added some typical Shannon Sharpe words. ``I told Ben he'd be
making a very wise decision not coming because he'd be sitting on
the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   More chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Two unknown tight ends at an unknown school who, less than a
decade later, would become the best in football, Sharpe with the
Broncos and Coates with their opponents in Monday night's season
opener, the Patriots? This needed elaboration. Sharpe, the
extrovert's extrovert, now was more true to his nature and told
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hung around,'' said Sharpe of that recruiting trip,
``and I pretty much joked. I've been joking all my life. I was
clowning around with a few guys, but I also gave Ben the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Ben the coaches were going to be moving me to tight end
and I told Ben I wasn't about to sit on the bench because I had sat
on the bench pretty much my freshman year,'' said Sharpe. ``And I
knew they were going to move me to tight end my sophomore year, so
I was pretty honest with Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   How honest?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Ben, `If you come here, unless you plan on moving
outside (to wide receiver), the likelihood of you starting is not
very good,''' Sharpe went on. ``I told Ben, `I'm going to be honest
with you _ I don't think you can beat me out.' So Ben made a great
decision going to Livingstone (College in North Carolina).''
</P>
<P>
   So Sharpe had the tight end position to himself at Savannah
State and Coates made his mark at tiny Livingstone, and the two
teams never met on the football field. Good thing, too, joked
Sharpe, ``because my team would have killed his.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, the two unknowns from the unknown colleges were
drafted, Sharpe in the seventh round in 1990, Coates in the fifth
round in 1992. Sharpe said he never dreamed that he would become
what he became with the Broncos, just as he never thought Coates
would become what he became with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to small schools like we did, you have desires
just like the guy who goes to Nebraska and just like the guy who
goes to Penn State,'' said Sharpe. Here he punctuated each word
with emotion: ``... But you know ... you ... have ... to ... be ...
so ... much ... better ... than those guys just to get a little
mention.''
</P>
<P>
   If he and Coates had put up similar numbers at major football
schools, they both would have been first-round picks, said Sharpe.
``But just to get (pro scouts) to come down to schools like ours
and time you in the 40, just to get guys to come on down and watch
you on film ... so Ben going to Livingstone, which is smaller than
even Savannah State, no way in my mind did I ever think that him _
or myself _ would be in the position we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Coates ``talk all the time'' about how far they've come,
Sharpe said, and ``we realize that guys coming from smaller schools
have to work harder. We have no problem with that. We didn't have
the boosters giving us cars. We didn't have the luxuries that the
Division 1 schools have.'' So when they got to their pro camps, he
and Coates ``wanted to show we deserved to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is quite obvious.
</P>
<P>
   But even now, years after becoming John Elway's favorite target
and years after being recognized as one of the NFL's best, Sharpe
still feels that old insecurity that comes with being the product
of a small school. ``I still feel I have to go out there week in
and week out and show everybody that I'm still a good football
player and I deserve to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Sharpe had told the world how he had put Coates on the
straight and narrow by advising him he had no shot to play at
Savannah State, Sharpe was asked if Coates ever had given him
anything. ``Advice,'' said Sharpe with a laugh. ```Stay out of
trouble.'''
</P>
<P>
   And who is the better of the two, an argument that has divided
pro football for years?
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, as usual, was quick on the draw with his reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Ben are every competitive and we always talk about
it,'' he said. ``And I always say to Ben, `As long as my team wins,
I'm the better tight end.' So no matter what he says _ Ben can
catch 200 passes, but if my team beats his, I'm the better tight
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
