u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NOTRE-DAME-BOS &LR;      09-04 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTRE-DAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME FIGHTING IMAGE AS WELL AS MICHIGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ They held a pep rally here Friday night, as
they do before every Notre Dame home game. It featured the usual
words, fight songs, brave talk about beating the visitor _ in this
case, Michigan in the season opener Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If you looked around the stadium and the campus that still is
one of the most serene spots anywhere, you would think that not a
whole lot has changed at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   You would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The past several months have been tumultuous. Instead of pep
rallies, we were told of peep shows. Instead of fight songs, we
heard of lawsuits being filed, charges and countercharges
exchanged, and dirty laundry hanging all over the Golden Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom in the glorious history of Irish football has the
beginning of a season been so welcomed, so anticipated. And it's
not because the Irish will challenge for the national championship.
A decade after its last national title, Notre Dame football is
still renovating.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a far more attractive diversion than the events
of the last several months.
</P>
<P>
   The tawdry saga started with an ugly age discrimination suit
filed by former offensive line coach Joe Moore when new head coach
Bob Davie fired him last season.
</P>
<P>
   In court testimony, it was revealed that Davie had questioned
his predecessor, Lou Holtz's, mental stability, and that members of
the football team had been peeping Toms while two cheerleaders were
engaging in sex on the team's trip to Ireland two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   After that coutroom episode came charges that Fighting Irish
players had accepted gifts from a booster, which led to
embezzlement charges against Kimberly Dunbar, who the NCAA
determined had been acting as a school representative while a
member of the now-disbanded Notre Dame Quarterback Club.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of college athletics' sleazy side, this was not a
stop-the-presses situation. Lots of little things added up to a
large blemish. Happens a lot in big-time college sports. But the
perception had been that Notre Dame was different, better if you
will, able to stay above the slime and still compete at the highest
level.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame maintains that its athletic mission has not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a situation where the program has fallen apart,''
said athletic director Mike Wadsworth, who nevertheless has had to
do some severe damage control in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth says that in one sense, Notre Dame was in a no-win
situation, particularly in the case involving Moore, which did more
damage through the revelations in court than through the judgment
against the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had settled (without a trial), some people woud have
called it hush money,'' said Wadsworth. ``They would have said,
`Here's a school so paranoid about nobody knowing what's going on
on their campus and trying to conceal it that they will let
themselves be held up.' That to me would be tarnishing the dome.
That to me would have been a very unhealthy position to have. To
me, that would have been the story.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of all this was Davie, Notre Dame's second-year
coach, coming off a 7-6 debut and telling people that the cupboard
when he took over from Holtz had not exactly been overstocked.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the public relations hits, Davie did not want to
deal with any more distractions. Talking about his football
problems was almost a relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things around here are a lot better than people might think,''
he said. ``That's the one good thing about being around the
players. It provides a source of reality. We do focus on the things
that are most important, and that's putting a football team on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   In a perverse way, what happened over the spring and summer may
have helped the football team, especially if the coaching staff
develops an us-against-them mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Notre Dame held up to a higher standard?'' said offensive
tackle Mike Rosenthal, who was put in the awkward position of
giving damaging testimony against Davie in the Moore suit. ``I hold
myself to a higher standard, and everyone who comes here does the
same. It's not that we think we're better. It's just important to
the people who come here to try to be the best in everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Notre Dame, everything is in the spotlight. Everything that
happens gets magnified. That's the good and the bad. If you're
going to accept the good, you have to accept the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth says he has learned some lessons in the past several
months. ``The basic program hasn't changed,'' he said. ``Bob Davie
through all of this has borne out what we expected from Bob from
the time we hired him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Wadsworth paused. ``What it does make you is very careful
of the quality of people you have on your staff,'' he said. ``You
have to have people you can be very open with. If you've got the
right people, then you're not going to be second-guessed about what
you say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is that if somebody has done something wrong,
you get rid of them. You don't live with it. Because if you live
with it, ultimately, then it's going to be a huge embarrassment to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie says he is wiser than he was a year ago, if not wearier.
``You learn to worry about the things you can control,'' he said.
``There are certain things you can't change. I want to feel good. I
want to look at the future and be positive. There is no sense
looking in the past because we can't change it. We really do have a
lot of positives going for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie knows that beginning this afternoon, Notre Dame's
motivation for winning will be obvious each week. ``We've got a
schedule, the first four teams beat us (last season),'' he said.
``That ought to motivate us. We've worked our tails off.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many people expect much from the Irish this season, although
they still are ranked in the Top 25. Davie says that is fine with
him. Better to overchieve in people's minds than underachieve.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first test of how Notre Dame has weathered its
spring and summer of discontent. Michigan is not only the defending
national cochampion but a longtime rival with Top 10 talent. If
nothing else, the game will give Irish followers something to focus
on other than the sideshows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
