<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-04 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER HAS BIG SHOES TO FILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Even now, two seasons after his departure,
we are sometimes reminded of the influence Bill Parcells wielded in
New England. Consider the case of Tony Carter, the 5-foot-11-inch,
235-pound fullback from the Chicago Bears whom the Patriots signed
as a free agent during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Carter and whom do you think of? You think of Sam Gash.
You realize that Carter is replacing Gash, who became something of
an icon in these parts simply because Parcells singled him out in
his postgame speech after the Patriots won the AFC championship in
1997, saluting Gash's contributions even though he had been injured
late in the season and had been unable to participate in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Before Parcells extolled him on the field at Foxboro Stadium,
Gash was considered a good player, a rugged blocker who wore down
linebackers and helped make the running game go. Still, he was just
another blue-collar, hardworking player.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells's words raised the bar for Gash, who was unable to live
up to such a lofty endorsement after he returned from his injury
and eventually departed to the Buffalo Bills as a free agent. It
also raises the bar for Carter, who knew Gash only as a player
other NFL fullbacks respected. Carter knew nothing of Parcells's
fondness for Gash, nor did he know that much of the current
Patriots coaching staff had a less glowing opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of it mattered. Carter had his own problems, having
been replaced as a starter in Chicago by Raymont Harris. He wanted
to go somewhere he could be a pure fullback again, a place where he
might even get to carry the ball from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Carter signed a three-year deal worth $2.7
million with an $800,000 bonus last spring after the Patriots
decided they did not want to pay Gash anywhere near that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Carter considered Buffalo as his other option in
urestricted free agency but wanted to cast his lot with a
legitimate contender after his experience with the woeful Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's the front man for an inexperienced running corps, but a
big part of the Patriots' attack.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is not considered a Gash-type fullback who can wear down
the opposition, though a couple of the players he blocked in the
exhibition season are still trying to find the license number of
the truck that hit them.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking was ``something I've been asked to work on more when I
came to Chicago,'' said the former University of Minnesota star.
``I've been working on it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   When he signed with the Patriots, he thought he would be the
lead blocker for Curtis Martin. But Martin went to the New York
Jets after the Patriots failed to match an offer sheet to the
restricted free agent. Now Carter will be trying to clear the way
for Sedrick Shaw, who will start Monday night's season opener in
Denver, and rookie Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The fullback-halfback relationship is important. Martin relied
on Gash to blast into the defensive line and pick off a linebacker.
Now Shaw and Edwards rely on Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to do my job with the same mentality,'' said
Carter. ``It makes it a little easier. The longer you play with
somebody, the better you work together. You get that feeling that
you know what the other guy is going to do before he even does it.
We're still working on that end of it with the two new guys. But
the longer we're together, that will come naturally in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates have already commented on Carter's toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Tony was a good blocker because we had seen enough of
him in games to see that,'' said Bobby Grier, the Patriots' vice
president of player personnel, ``but we didn't know what an animal
he was on special teams. That part has been an eye-opener to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier said that in the new Ernie Zampese offense, Carter won't
be in on every play, which will give him time to rest for
special-team cover situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's some wear and tear, but I'll be limited on special-teams
plays,'' said Carter. ``With the role I'm asked to play, I'll be in
there 5-10 plays per game, so it shouldn't be too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots feel Carter is a better receiver than Gash. Carter
seems to be able to gain more after the catch than Gash, though two
years ago, Gash led the team in that category and in 1997, Carter
had an off year with 24 catches for 152 yards in the reconfigured
Bears offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to catch a lot of passes in the backfield,'' said
Carter. ``We've been trying to get the ball downfield and stretch
the defenses. But as the season starts, I hope to be able to catch
a few passes and contribute that way. I think that's a strong part
of my game that will develop in time as Drew (Bledsoe) gets used to
me and I prove that I can catch the ball and do something with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also used Carter a couple of times in the
exhibition season on running plays. Since most of the running plays
are derived from the Dallas offense Zampese used to oversee, Carter
is basically New England's answer to Daryl ``Moose'' Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a whole lot of running plays, but there's a
few,'' said Carter. ``It's a matter of whether or not they'll call
them. Hopefully, I'll get a chance to do some of that. I could
definitely contribute like that where I could stuff it up there on
third and 1 and keep a drive alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little unexpected for a fullback to run with the ball
in this league now because fullbacks are basically blockers. But I
I think it helps level off the offense and balances things out and
keeps the defense guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter hasn't been involved in many games like the one coming up
in Denver, but ``as a player, those are the games you want to play
in,'' he said. ``It's Monday night, everybody's watching, and
they're the world champions. We can show them and the country
something about us with the way we perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter can show a lot about himself as well. The Patriots say
they don't have to worry about the fullback position. But the true
test is ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
