<SLUG> BC-NH-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAHEEN BACKS CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT IN SCHOOL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Governor Jeanne Shaheen reversed course Friday
and supported a constitutional amendment that would avert a fiscal
crisis over school funding while avoiding the kind of broad-based
tax the state has long scorned.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment proposed by Republican House
Speaker Donna Sytek of Salem would preserve New Hampshire's
reliance on local property taxes, which now fund 90 percent of the
cost of public education. The state Supreme Court last year ruled
that that system is illegal because it has resulted in poor
communities paying tax rates up to 15 times higher than the rates
paid in the wealthiest towns to fund the costs of education.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, which must be passed by three-fifths of the
Legislature and two-thirds of the voters in November, also calls
for roughly doubling the state's limited aid to schools. That aid
would be targeted to property-poor &UR;  &LR; communities.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen, who in the past has said that amending the constitution
was the wrong approach, blamed a legislative logjam for forcing her
to change her position.
</P>
<P>
   ``If local school property taxes cannot be set or collected,
communities will not be able to fund public education in the next
school year,'' Shaheen said at a news conference at the State House
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``School districts will not be able to issue bonds to fund
capital improvements. School districts will not be able to issue
tax anticipation notes to cover school expenses. This would cause a
fiscal crisis for our communities. We cannot let that happen,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court &UR;  &LR; has given the Legislature until April 1999 to
enact a school funding system under which taxes would be
``reasonable and proportional.'' Shaheen's own proposal _ the
Advancing Better Classrooms Plan _ was also found to be
unconstitutional in an advisory opinion issued by the high court
last June.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ABC Plan would allowed wealthy towns to keep low
tax rates. Poor towns would be helped by state revenue from taxes
on alcohol and cigarette sales and other sources. But because the
ABC Plan reduced but did not eliminate the tax disparities between
rich and poor communities, it would not be legal, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen defended her plan again Friday. ``I believe the ABC Plan
would have been found constitutional by the Supreme Court if it had
been passed by the Senate and signed into law.'' The state Senate,
however, voted against the plan after the court's ruling, which led
to the current impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the current Legislature believes that the
choice is now between a constitutional amendment or a new
broad-based tax. It's time to break the gridlock,'' Shahee said.
</P>
<P>
   With Election Day _ Nov. 3 _ less than two months away,
persuading two-thirds of the electorate to amend the constitution
may prove a challenge. Three of the four Republicans seeking to
oppose Shaheen support a constitutional amendment. The fourth has
actively campaigned against any move to change the constitution,
favoring instead a statewide property tax to deal with disparities
among communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say,'' said Shaheen spokesman Douglas Hattaway
when asked what the governor's support will do for the amendment's
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will vote for it. I think people will be relieved that
progress is being made on the issue,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the governor had any back-up plan to resolve the crisis
should the amendment fail, Hattaway said, ``She is going to work as
hard as she can to make it pass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
