<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWSEASON-AZR &LR;      09-04 1733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC STILL RULES IN NEW LINEUP  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
 SEASON-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Newsmagazines just keep eating away at prime time, and
when you consider the staggering failure rate of comedies and
dramas, it's no wonder.
</P>
<P>
   You can count the survivors from broadcast TV's 1997 freshman
class on one hand (``Veronica's Closet,'' ``Working,'' ``Dharma &AMP;
Greg,'' ``Ally McBeal'') with the thumb left over.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be needing that thumb soon. Although most new TV shows
are born to die, there will be more survivors this season compared
with the past few.
</P>
<P>
   As the countdown continues to the official start of the 1998-99
TV season (Sept. 21, according to Nielsen Media Research) and a
boffo premiere week (with more than a dozen shows making their
debuts, plus dozens more fresh _ finally! _ episodes of returning
series), let's grab some face time with some of the men and woman
who make the prime time schedules for the broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   Starting, of course, at the top. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NBC  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warren Littlefield picks the programs for the peacock network,
and he's riding an unprecedented wave of ratings success.
</P>
<P>
   This season, however, NBC must get by without ``Seinfeld'' or
the promotional platform of professional football. It also faces
the final go-round for ``Mad About You'' and ``ER's'' George
Clooney, significant cast changes in ``Law &AMP; Order'' and
``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' and questions about its most
high-profile new series, ``Encore! Encore!''
</P>
<P>
   To Littlefield, zero ratings slippage this season would be
``sensational.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is really to hold'' the existing audience, he said in
a recent meeting with TV critics.
</P>
<P>
   Not growing it. Not piling on more runaway ratings victories.
When no-growth is good news, you know the business is depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NBC rules TV Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier,'' the best show on TV even during the ``Seinfeld''
years, moves into the 8 p.m. Thursday time slot. And the cast and
creative crew behind ``ER,'' bolstered by massive pay increases,
should be poised to deliver another heart-stopping (and
re-starting) season.
</P>
<P>
   On the comedy front, ``Just Shoot Me'' and ``Working'' have done
big numbers during rerun season. The network's ``Will &AMP; Grace'' has
the elements to be a breakout success.
</P>
<P>
   And if all else fails, Littlefield can call the boiler room and
have 'em crank up another hour of ``Dateline NBC,'' which this fall
will be seen five nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CBS  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ready! Set! Hung one! Hung two! Hike!
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, president and chief executive of CBS Television,
will work with the promotional pro football platform that
Littlefield lost, and has scheduled accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the wholesome but aging feel-good series ``Dr. Quinn,
``Medicine Woman.'' In its place, Moonves offers ``Martial Law.''
Featuring the glowering Sammo Hung (who can't seem to pose for a
publicity shot without making a menacing fist), ``Martial Law''
isn't about feel good. It's about feel bad. As in making bad guys
feel that way by pounding them with your flying feet.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, pro football isn't about feel good, either. It's
a ticket to the young male viewers who all but abandoned CBS when
the network lost football in mid-decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't overestimate what football's going to do for
us,'' Moonves said. ``We discovered in our research that men age 35
and younger weren't watching anything on CBS over the last four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS has also likely found some young-male appeal in the new
series ``Buddy Faro,'' starring Dennis Farina as a private eye
stuck in a '70s time warp. Moonves counts the continuing ``JAG'' as
another dude-appeal show, and the new ``Brian Benben Show'' could
be considered a maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the CBS ship, so recently run aground by aging shows
and creaky audience demographics, continues to slowly turn. Without
completely abandoning the network's long-standing core audience of
older viewers, Moonves must attract more younger viewers to his
programing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to program for all audiences, and our current
lineup . . . reflects that,'' he said. ``We have edgy comedies,
with ``Brian Benben,'' family comedies with ``Cosby'' and ``The
Nanny,'' mature dramas in ``Chicago Hope'' and family dramas in
``Touched by an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   And, this year, pro football and that unhappy Mr. Hung. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ABC  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of this network's most promising new shows _ late-summer
start-ups ``Maximum Bob'' and ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?'' _ are
already airing, so does the ailing ABC have anything to look
forward to?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, surprisingly, is yep.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night comedy newcomers ``The Hughleys'' and ``Sports
Night'' have serious potential. The Saturday night remake of
``Fantasy Island,'' believe it or not, will be intriguing at the
least. And its lead-out, ``Cupid,'' could be flat-out great.
</P>
<P>
   ABC also has continuing greatness in ``The Practice'' and ``Spin
City,'' continuing pretty goodness in ``The Drew Carey Show,''
``Home Improvement'' and ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' and the
sure-to-be-buzzy Jimmy Smits-to-Rick Schroder transition on ``NYPD
Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on its sad treatment of ``Nothing Sacred'' last season,
however, ABC can't necessarily be trusted to handle greatness or
near-greatness. ABC is also giving us a truly looney drama titled
``Vengeance Unlimited,'' starring Michael Madsen as a borderline
insane vigilante. ``Violence Unlimited'' is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   And there's that lingering ``TV is Good'' promo campaign, which
is clever but ultimately insulting to both TV fans and TV haters
alike.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fox  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His most promising new show (``Futurama,'' from ``Simpsons''
creator Matt Groening) won't be on the air until mid-season, so
Peter Roth, president of Fox Entertainment Group, instead pitched
the cause of year-round series development.
</P>
<P>
   The true fall-season scramble runs from February to May, as
networks compete for fresh concepts, producers, writers and stars
for their new fall shows. Because of expanding cable and broadcast
demands for programing, creative resources are spread way thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention is to have a much more effective, better system
where we can spread the talent pool out more effectively, and I
hope finally offer for all of us simply better, more compelling
viewing for the consumer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better supporting evidence for Roth's campaign than
his own new schedule.
</P>
<P>
   You know, ``Holding the Baby.'' (It was the first new show to
premiere, which gives it an excellent shot at being the first show
to be canned.)
</P>
<P>
   The one you may not know yet is ``Costello,'' a Tuesday night
sitcom that will be the TV equivalent of that cool sound modems
make when they're connecting to a network.
</P>
<P>
   There are more where that came from. Plus, new episodes of ``The
X-Files'' don't start until Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The lone potentially unawful new Fox series, ``That 70's Show,''
has already debuted to decent ratings. It will have to overcome its
awful title and thin premise (a flashback to teen life in That
Decade), but the cast is cool.
</P>
<P>
   In his address and Q&AMP;A session with the critics, Roth used the
word ``compelling'' 17 times, edging ``distinctive'' (nine times),
``worthwhile'' (six), ``well-crafted'' (five), ``daring'' (three)
``unique'' (three), ``bold'' (two), ``different'' (two) and
``eventful'' (two) in the superlative ratings race. (I didn't count
'em, but someone from the trade journal ``Electronic Media'' did.)
</P>
<P>
   This from a guy who's breaking up a great Sunday night lineup by
moving ``King of the Hill'' to Tuesday. Except for an occasional
moment on ``That 70's Show,'' none of his fancy words fits Fox
newcomers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WB  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The start-up network has the most anxiously awaited new series
(``Felicity'') and an apparent lock (with shows such as ``Buffy,
the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Dawson's Creek'') on America's teen
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   As a piece of the Time Warner media empire, the WB occupies a
lower rung on the massive corporation's womb-to-tomb viewership
ladder (just after the Cartoon Network, but well before CNN) and
has yet to turn a profit, but the bucks are starting to roll in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at some of the most competitive marketing areas _
the sneakers, the movies, fast food, beverages, computers _ all
these really hot marketing areas, they tend to be very focused on
younger people today,'' said Jamie Kellner, the WB's chief
executive. ``I think it's the battleground, in effect, of the
future of marketing in our country.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the networks will eventually select certain targets,
and try to attack those targets, and be very specific towards those
groups of people. And advertisers are going to do the exact same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he really say ``sneakers''? &QL; 
 &QL; 
UPN  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother with the target talk around Dean Valentine, chief
executive and president of UPN, the other start-up network. (Pax TV
won't officially inherit this designation until it becomes
available in the Valley.)
</P>
<P>
   Valentine met the critics to say that he's programing a big-tent
network. It's still a comparatively small big tent, for now, but
UPN has ambitions to become a full-service TV entertainment
provider.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's got a new sitcom about a New York transit cop
(``DiResta''), a new sitcom with a cute kid (``Guys Like Us'') and
a period drama about Kentucky horse folk (``Legacy''). Plus he's
got the continuing ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' which incorporates alien
species into the grand programing parade.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he disagrees with the narrowcasting approach
``profoundly, on every level.''
</P>
<P>
   On a business level, narrowcasting makes sense only for cable
nets that can add income from cable operators to their target-niche
advertising sales, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a larger and more social point of view, I believe that
there has to be something that brings Americans together. I think
people are always looking for a great story that they can talk
about the next day at the infamous water cooler.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for compelling stories to share, and in a
world where everything is fractionalized, and 18-year-olds are
watching the 18-year-old network and 26-year-olds are watching the
26-year-old network, I think there's fewer and fewer things to talk
about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
