<HEADLINE>
COMPARABLE BEAUTY AT DRUGSTORE PRICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Upscale cosmetics are swell, for sure, but
drugstore beauty has its charm. And it's mainly low prices.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, this week at Rite Aid in Woodland Hills, Miz
Hottips noticed that L'Oreal's new Espresso lipstick for $7.59 is a
dead ringer for Chanel's new fall lipstick shade at one third the
cost.
</P>
<P>
   And although she loves Chanel's new body gloss for $25, she
found a similar version by Fetish for $3.79.
</P>
<P>
   Major department stores carry a cool kit with CD packaging that
contains tiny decals for your nails for $20, but you can buy
packages of similar decals (the champagne bottle and party favors
images are way-cool) by Cosmar for $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   Those same upscale stores offer trendy hair mascaras for about
$20 to produce temporary color highlights, but there's a drug store
version called Hair Color Candy Pomade, for $4.99.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea from the drugstore is Pond's Cucumber Eye
Treatments to diminish eye puffiness. The pads treated with
chamomile extract, aloe gel, orange peel and rose hips, actually
look and smell like cucumbers and work great if you keep the jar in
the fridge. They're $7.99.
</P>
<P>
   Miz Hot Tips also discovered some trendy Euro-wire earrings with
little jet beads for $3.99, and jeweled barrettes and hair pins for
$5.50, compared to those at Nordstrom and other stores for $20 to
$30.
</P>
<P>
   EMMY TRIVIA: So, when you're huddled with friends in front of
the tube on Sept. 13 to watch the 50th annual prime-time Emmy
Awards, don't feel too bad for the nominees who don't win. Miz Hot
Tips learned they all receive gifts, including a huge basketful of
Laila fragrance products made from Norwegian wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to feel like a star, you can find the statusy scent
at Neiman Marcus in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   And just so you'll be up to speed on Emmy trivia, check out the
new book ``The Best in Television: Fifty Years of Emmys'' (General
Publishing Group; $30) by Morrie Gelman and Gene Accas. It's packed
with behind-the-scenes anecdotes, personal interviews and fashion
photos.
</P>
<P>
   HIPSTER ALERT: Always wanted to get into those swank L.A. clubs
where the stars hang out, but never even made it to the front of
the line?
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Megastores in Burbank and West Hollywood are offering
free MTV Ignition Key Cards that will give you front-of-the-line
privileges now through Thursday at the Derby, the Garage, Garden of
Eden, the Gig, Hollywood Athletic Club (former home of the Emmy
Awards), Luna Park, Martini Lounge, Opium Den and the Troubadour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0260 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGHLEY-TV-LADN     09-04 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGHLEY-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL LIFE WITH THE HUGHLEYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; It was late on Christmas Eve when D.L. Hughley
sneaked out to set up his surprise gift to his then 7-year-old son
Kyle.
</P>
<P>
   A basketball hoop. Something extra special, because this wasn't
just any Christmas. This would be the first one the family would
spend in West Hills after moving from Baldwin Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Hughley was struggling with the 10-foot monster late into the
night when, out of the darkness, came his neighbor Jim, a ratchet
set in hand and eager to help.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 a.m., the basket was in place in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle was psyched. The homeowner's association wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Hughley received a $1,000 fine for breaking one of
the Codes, Covenants and Restrictions that govern everything from
maximum height for shrubs to how many hours a car is allowed to be
parked in a driveway in his new neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Hughley said. ``They hadn't even
given me a copy of the CC and Rs yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't fight the basketball ban, though. In between games,
the hoop now rests on its back alongside Hughley's pool. But it
wasn't a total loss.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,000 experience two years ago gave Hughley both a new
friend he thought he'd never have !ital!and!off! the added bonus of
a story line interesting enough for the network to order his new
sitcom, ``The Hughleys,'' which premieres on ABC at 8:30 p.m. Sept.
22.
</P>
<P>
   Parallels between D.L. Hughley and his TV character, Darryl
Hughley, are not accidental. The half-hour show is more than
loosely based on Hughley's life.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Darryl moved from the inner city to West Hills.
D.L., who grew up at 135th Street and Avalon Boulevard, near
Compton, moved from a 900-square-foot home in Baldwin Hills to a
4,400-square-foot, five-bedroom, four-bath house with a swimming
pool, a view and a three-car garage that shelters his new Lexus
sport utility vehicle, a Lexus sedan and a Mercedes sedan in a tony
planned community.
</P>
<P>
   His TV persona grapples with the race dilemma when his daughter
chooses a white doll over a black doll. The real-life Hughley, much
like the television Hughley, was embarrassed when his daughter
picked the white doll and he later found out it was because the
white doll came with more outfits than the black one.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl voices fears that his children are spoiled and may not
grow up to be good people because they haven't had to face the
struggles that made Darryl the man he is. D.L. Hughley tries to
prevent the same thing from happening to his children _ Ryan, 11;
Kyle, now 9; and Tyler, 7 _ by making sure they know how fortunate
they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do a show that's true to his life, and is a really
funny family show,'' said Matt Wickline, executive producer of the
show. ``When we do deal with race, we try to do it in an
intelligent way, not just do it for the sake of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike real life, every dilemma in the sitcom ends with a
laugh. The hardships and conflicts last less than 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this show at the end of this experience for people to
come away and laugh,'' Hughley said. ``You know, I'm not trying to
do a show that, at the end of it, people wonder what they were
taught. I'm there particularly to speak from a voice that was my
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition to a new neighborhood _ for that matter, a new
lifestyle _ hasn't been as tidy and simple as reciting that
clarifying moral of the story at the end of a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Hughleys get to wallow in the lap of luxury now. The
home with an open floor plan is tastefully decorated in neutral
colors, with traditional and modern African art adorning the walls
_ a far cry from the crammed confines of their last house.
</P>
<P>
   George and Weezy never had it so good.
</P>
<P>
   But the new home also has raised Hughley's awareness of the
inequities dealt to those who can't afford the good life.
</P>
<P>
   The new neighborhood has a milkman, Hughes Market sent a voucher
for $300 in groceries (``Nobody gave me groceries when I was
poor,'' he said), and the Young Republicans sent a welcome letter
(``If they only knew. ...'')
</P>
<P>
   And where there wasn't special treatment based on economic
strata, Hughley faced what he's convinced was clear and simple
racial prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Hughley and his wife, LaDonna, visited their dream house one day
while it was under construction, only to be snapped right back into
an ugly reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in there wearing a baseball hat and jeans, and the guy
laying the carpet was a rude cat. He said, `You can't be in here.'
I told him, `I'm Mr. Hughley, and whether I am or not, you
shouldn't speak that way at all.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Never one to let an injustice go by, Hughley walked into the
development's office and, soon after, another man was laying
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Hughley has learned to mellow somewhat, and has begun
to see past his own racial prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   When an elderly neighbor asked him to take in her trash cans
shortly after he moved in, the over-sensitive Hughley thought it
was because he was black. It turned out to be because she was old.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he realizes that his neighborhood, like so many others,
resembles the United Nations. One family is Taiwanese, another
Jewish, one is Chinese and another is from Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   To Hughley, these are not people from different ethnic
backgrounds anymore. They're simply young families at the same
stage of life as he is, all starting to gain success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was determined when I first moved here not to make any
friends,'' Hughley said. ``I was just going to go to work and do my
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But that Christmas Eve night, with Jim helping out, would be the
first of many friendships the Hughleys were about to make.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Hughleys have become the unofficial welcome wagon for
any African-American family considering buying in the neighborhood.
It's a comical scene to him and his wife as they remember going
around to meet other similar families when they were shopping in
the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has changed my picture of what race is in this country,''
Hughley said. ``For a long time, I thought black folk were the
poster children for poverty in this country. I grew up thinking all
white people were rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even knew white people lived in Los Angeles. I watched
`Price Is Right,' and they would say, `We live in L.A.' and I'd go,
`I've never seen you around here.' That was true. I never saw white
people until I was 19 years old and I went to the other side of the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, back on the !ital!other!off! side of the city, where
his mother still lives, many from his old neighborhood have shunned
him, accusing him of being a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   While he's brought three of his longtime friends along and
gotten them jobs, people he hasn't seen since high school go around
calling him stuck up. His own aunt refused to talk to him, Hughely
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when people cross social and economic lines,'' Hughley
said, ``it makes people look where they are at. People have always
bused their kids to school in these neighborhoods to get them every
advantage, but they won't live here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hypocritical. Some kids spend five hours a day on a bus.
I think my kids can be doing more productive things than being on a
bus.''
</P>
<P>
   From that serious observation on the effects of self-imposed
social barriers comes, believe it or not, more fodder for a funny
sitcom story line _ the things you miss out on while you're stuck
with an extended commute. For Darryl Hughley, it's his sex life
that suffers.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of seeing snippets of their real life recast as
sitcom one-liners is still new to the Hughley family. His daughter,
Tyler, asked him if he will be leaving them for his television
family. LaDonna interrupted a recent interview at the family home
to report that ``Monday Night Football'' announcer Al Michaels had
just promoted ``The Hughleys.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all unique for now, but the issues Hughley tackles in his
sitcom have been around for a long time and will not likely go away
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When black people move up,'' Hughley said, ``they have to
leave the experiences that they had and move around people who look
a lot different than they do, for the most part. When white people
tend to move up, they move around people who tend to look just like
them. ... (The show) comes from my experience. And you know what?
The one thing that I have always been able to maintain is that even
though these experiences may make people uncomfortable, we all
recognize something about the show. We all do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
