<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST WEEKEND'S FOOTBALL A GRAND SLAM FOR NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's how much the alleged renewed interest in baseball because
of a home run-hitting contest has hurt the National Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in history, all 15 games will be sold out on
this opening weekend. For the first time in NFL history, more than
1 million fans will attend the games. And it's only the opening
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the NFL is so unconcerned about the home run-hitting
contest that when Fox TV asked permission to cut into the St. Louis
Rams-Dallas Cowboys game to show Mark McGwire's at-bats as he
threatens to break Roger Maris's record of 61, the NFL said, ``Go
right ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   So when McGwire is at the plate, the football and baseball games
will share a split screen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A solid source says Larry Bird has picked the man to present him
to the Hall of Fame for induction next spring in Springfield, Mass.
_ Bill Walton. Walton and Bird were close when they played together
on the Celtics, and the rule is that the presenter must also be a
Hall of Famer. Walton is ... When Harry Sinden and Ray Bourque get
down to talking about the future for the Bruins' great, they'll
also discuss the possibility of Bourque working for the team in
some capacity after his playing career. The Bruins want Bourque to
finish his career in Boston and hope to make his final years as a
player part of an overall financial package ... Pete Carroll has
three ``musts'' for the Patriots to win in Denver Monday night.
One: ``Find some way to stop their running game.'' Two: ``Eliminate
big plays in the passing game and special teams. Keep their wide
receivers in front of us to make them work the ball up the field.
Don't let their returners (Darrien Gordon is one of the best ever)
make big plays to get field position on us.'' Three: ``Take
advantage of our big-play opportunities on offense and score points
any way we can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's an updated Denver scouting report from two sources. The
first is from a pro scout for an NFC team who has followed the
Broncos through the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Shanahan was concerned about a letdown after they won the
Super Bowl, and he has done a great job of not letting it happen.
These guys have practiced very hard in training camp and played the
preseason games with great intensity. I think they are just as good
as they were a year ago. The theme seems to be, `Let's win one for
John (Elway).'
</P>
<P>
   ``They have very tall receivers, and this might hurt the
Patriots. In every matchup, the Denver wide receivers will have a
big height advantage over the Patriot corners. A great matchup will
be (Shannon) Sharpe against (Lawyer) Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Denver offensive line is going through some changes, but
Alex Gibbs is as good as any offensive line coach in the business.
The guy is terrific. They have some new guys but they have played
well. Their defense has eight linemen and they will change them all
the time. This is a big plus for them at altitude in that stadium.
They keep their guys fresh. Your guys start to fade unless you can
have that many yourself to keep substituting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots will have a problem if they try to stack it (the
defense) against the running game to stop (Terrell) Davis. The
Broncos are executing the passing game well. Elway looks sharp. He
will have the chance to audibilize at the line of scrimmage to
change the play. (Drew) Bledsoe won't. The crowd will be too loud.
So when the Patriots make the call in the huddle, it better be the
right one because they won't have a chance to change it. I think
Denver might come out in a three-receiver set _ (Ed) McCaffrey,
(Rod) Smith, and (Marcus) Nash _ and work over whoever the Patriots
bring in at the other corner (Chris Canty) and the nickel back.''
</P>
<P>
   An NFC coach, who is well versed on Denver, offers this
assesssment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a well-coached, very deep football team. They have
guys coming off the bench who could start on other teams. Mike has
a terrific offensive mind. Very creative. (Coordinator) Greg
Robinson is the perfect complement for him on defense. As a group,
this whole team _ coaches, players _ all trust one another. The
players think the coaches will put them in position to win, and on
the field, the players trust each other. They don't feel that they
have to run around and make plays on their own and gamble on
getting out of position.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino had a charity golf tournament two weeks ago that
topped anything ever done in the Boston area by a sports celebrity.
The night before the tourney, Pitino had an auction at Mistral,
Boston's most upscale eatery, and raised $238,000. Most of the
money came from his Kentucky friends, who showed the locals how to
dig deep. Overall, the tourney netted more than $350,000 ($10,000 a
foursome), and all the net proceeds will go back to children's
charities in the name of Rick's late son, Daniel ... Sinden on Cam
Neely's possible comeback: ``I would love to see that happen.
Nothing could make me happier. I'm thrilled that he is able to work
out to a point where he doesn't have the pain he had when he had to
stop playing. It would be unbelievable to see him play for the
Bruins again, but to me, that would be a miracle. Cam not only
hasn't played the last two seasons, he missed many of the games in
the years before that. I wish him nothing but the best.''
Meanwhile, the Bruins are still in court fighting an insurance
company over the payments made to Neely when he was forced to
retire. The Bruins have paid Neely in full. But the insurance
company is trying not to pay off on the policy the Bruins had on
Neely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though the kid is costing him a lot of money, Joe Gibbs is
a Jeff Gordon fan. Gibbs, the Hall of Fame football coach, now owns
a string of racing teams, including a Winston Cup outfit that
competes with Gordon on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``His crew chief is a friend of mine,'' said Gibbs after Gordon
won last week's race in Louon, N.H., ``and he asked me one time why
they (the fans) boo Jeff so much. I told him this. Jeff probably
has the largest group of fans rooting for him of any driver. Let's
say that is 20 percent. That means the other 80 percent are going
against him because they are rooting for other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon is just so good. He is special. There are only a
handful of guys in the world that have the feel for a race car that
this kid does, and it shows. He's young, good-looking, and wins all
the races. He and his crew have it going. All of the decisions they
seem to be making at crucial times in the races seem to be the
right ones. We (the team for driver Bobby Labonte) have been right
there with him in three or four of these races and they just beat
us. These things run in circles. His team has the right chemistry.
What they are doing is fantastic. In football, you just have to
beat one other team each weekend. In NASCAR, you have to beat 40
other teams each weekend. It's a lot tougher to win here than it is
in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do you think the chances are that Roger Clemens will end up
with some team that will pay him more money next season? Clemens
says that even though he is content in Toronto, he would accept a
trade next season if it would help the Blue Jays. Of course, this
has nothing to do with the fact that Roger has collected the big
money already from his Toronto contract, which included a large
bonus up front. If he stayed in Toronto, he wouldn't be worth what
he could get in the open market coming off two sensational seasons
in which he unquestionably has been the best pitcher in baseball.
With a new club, Roger could get another bonus plus a bump in his
base pay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nice story today. Khalid Riley, one of the 70 football players
shortchanged when Boston University terminated the program last
year, will line up as a starter for the University of Connecticut
against Colgate. And he will have a chance to play against his
brother Ameer, a Colgate defensive back. A large contingent from
his hometown of Norwood is on the way to the game ... And two weeks
from today, when Nevada-Las Vegas travels to Wisconsin, the two
White brothers will face each other. Former Harvard quarterback
Brian White coaches the offensive backs at Wisconsin. Brother
Christoper coaches the linebackers at UNLV. Their father, Don,
played QB at Notre Dame and now teaches in Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
