</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDINGS DETAIL FINAL MANEUVERINGS OF DOOMED AIRLINER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia -- As grieving family members from the
United States and Europe started gathering on this fog-shrouded
shore Friday to mourn loved ones lost in the crash of Swissair
Flight 111, searchers continued the grim task of plucking bodies
and wreckage from heavy seas that hampered the massive recovery
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials revealed that recordings of the final radio
communications from the doomed plane showed the pilot made looping
``orbits'' over land and sea while dumping tons of fuel in
preparation for an emergency landing at Halifax International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The last-ditch maneuverings occurred in the final minutes of a
tragedy that started when the pilot sent his first emergency
broadcast at 9:14 p.m Eastern time Wednesday, roughly 15 minutes
before the passenger craft plunged into the cold Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot indicated that he had an emergency condition and
that he was going to land,'' said Vic Gerden, the Canadian
Transportation Safety Board. ``It would have been very risky to
land with that amount of fuel aboard. So he was dumping fuel while
making an orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials angrily dismissed media reports that the pilot started
a turn toward Boston before being diverted to Halifax. The reports
suggested that precious time was lost that might have made the
difference between life and death for the 229 passengers and crew
members aboard, all of whom were killed in crash.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden confirmed that Swissair pilot Urs Zimmermann initially
suggested reversing course for Boston after reporting smoke aboard
the MD-11 jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were offered the information that Halifax was closer, and
the crew elected to fly to Halifax,'' said Gerden. ``The only turns
made were toward Halifax.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight was 58 miles southwest of Halifax airport when the
pilot issued a ``Pan-Pan-Pan'' warning, indicating a dangerous
condition aboard. Because the plane had to descend from a cruising
altitude of 33,000 feet -- as well as dump fuel -- it took a
quarter-hour to close the relatively short distance. Officials have
placed the time of the crash between 9:28 and 9:30, although there
still seemed some confusion as to time sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Zimmermann and his flight crew were operating the
craft while smoke filled the cockpit. It was unclear whether there
was smoke in the main cabin, although passengers had donned
emergency gear.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before hitting the water, the three-engine
McDonnell-Douglas aircraft was flying so low that it sheared off
the top of a 16-foot buoy marking a shipping channel.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said the pilot never issued a call of ``Mayday,'' the
signal for the most serious of emergencies in which a crash is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was clear that he had an emergency aboard and that he
was going to land,'' Gerden said. ``The recordings show they were
dealing with the situation in a very professional way.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the around-the-clock search under way a few miles
offshore from this tiny fishing village Friday officially shifted
from a ``rescue effort'' - with the emphasis on seeking survivors -
to a salvage mission.
</P>
<P>
   The change represented formal acknowledgement of what searchers
had known but were reluctant to admit: There is no chance that
anyone lived through the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to abandon hope, but it's necessary,'' said
Lt.-Commander Glenn Chamberlain, a Canadian naval officer assigned
to the Halifax-based Rescue Coordination Center.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts will now focus on recovering bodies and probing the
cause of a disaster believed to be an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Joining scores of vessels and aircraft already scouring the
seas, a Canadian submarine probed the depths seeking flight
recorders and other instruments that might explain what caused the
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary examinations of wreckage recovered so far has shown
no sign of burning or scorching, suggesting that the three-engine
jetcraft was not brought down by an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication of fire on the parts we've seen,''
Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials in Canada, the US and Switzerland have played
down the possibility of a terrorist bomb, Royal Canadian Mounted
Police explosives experts are on the scene looking for any sign of
a blast.
</P>
<P>
   In an eerie coincidence Friday, a Boeing 757 en route from
Toronto to Scotland was forced to make an emergency landing at a
Canadian military base after the pilot reported smelling fumes in
the cockpit. The Royal Airlines flight, with 225 people aboard,
touched down safely in Goose Bay, Labrador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's on the ground safe,'' Capt. David Muralt, pilot for
the Montreal-based charter airline, told the Canadian Press news
agency. ``And everyone's very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood was far less cheerful 600 miles to the south as tides
and wind started pushing corpses and body parts ashore on islands
and bayfronts in the vicinity of Peggy's Cove. Soldiers combed
miles of the rugged coast, stuffing human remnants into black
plastic body bags.
</P>
<P>
   Flotsam ranging from postcards to baby bottles was still spread
for miles over waters smeared with aviation fuel. Roughly 100
suitcases have been pulled from the water.
</P>
<P>
   As family members of the victims arrived in Nova Scotia aboard
free flights provided by Swissair, investigators made a determined
effort to play down the grisly discoveries of body parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with remains and partial remains,'' said Cpl.
Frank Skidmore of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police. ``The fact
that we have some 60 body bags containing remains doesn't mean we
have 60 bodies. Out of respect for the families, we're not going to
be providing explicit details of what we are finding.''
</P>
<P>
   A Swissair official, Philippe Bruggisser, said that the only
body found more or less whole so far is that of an infant.
</P>
<P>
   Some family members face the terrible task of picking out
spouses, siblings, parents or children at the makeshift morgue at
Shearwater military base, near Halifax, where 20 forensic doctors
and dentists are examining -- and reassembling -- bodies both to
speed identification and gain information about possible causes of
the crash.
</P>
<P>
   None of the bodies recovered so far has been officially
identified. Medical officials said most victims appeared to have
died from traumatic injures as the result of huge impact.
</P>
<P>
   But many families arrived in Nova Scotia Friday simply to make a
sad pilgrimage to the site where they had lost so much.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the hundreds of mourners will not visit the
site until Saturday, a few families gathered on a rocky outcropping
by the edge of the sea Friday afternoon, gazing off across the gray
waters where Canadian naval ships and Coast Guard vessels rose and
fell on seven-foot swells as crews labored to hoist bits and pieces
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   When weather permitted, military helicopters carried wreckage
and bodies back to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're finding ourselves turned from the scene by thunder
showers,'' said Lt. Erin O'Toole, one of hundreds of Canadian
aviators, soldiers and sailors deployed on the salvage mission.
``It's frustrating. The weather is making a difficult job even more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Bouchard, chairman of Canada's Transportation Safety
Board, said that searchers want badly to find large sections of
fuselage in waters that range from 70 to 150 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed disappointment that the naval submarine HMCS
Okanagan, an aging vessel pulled from retirement to perform one
last mission, failed in its first attempt to detect flight
recorders and other instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not yet received any signal from the body of the
aircraft,'' said Bouchard. ``What we want most urgently is to find
the black box recorders. But also if we find a very, very big piece
of the aircraft, it could give us some important information about
what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the relatively few bodies that have been
recovered suggest that a large section of fuselage might have
remained largely intact and may contain many of the victims as well
as flight recorders. However, they backed down on earlier
statements that big section of plane had been detected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sonar search is showing a lot of large objects, but there
are many shipwrecks from years and centuries past, as well as
underwater geographic features, so we don't know what we're
seeing,'' said Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   A small submersible search vessel equipped with video cameras
was flown to the scene late Friday, and more than 40 military
deepwater divers were preparing to explore the search area.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the largest fragment pulled from the sea ``is only about
the size of a small car's roof,'' said Lt.-Commander Jacques
Fauteux.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair announced that there were only 132 Americans aboard the
ill-fated craft, not the 137 the airline reported Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1941EDT &QL; 
