<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON05-COX     09-04 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON RETURNS HOME 'SORRY,' BUT WITH BATTLES STILL AHEAD
 &HT;    780&AMP;add
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An embattled President Clinton returns Saturday
from a week abroad to face increasingly restive voices within his
own party and a potentially damaging report as early as next week
from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats moved to distance themselves from Clinton, not even
the president's admission Friday that he was ''very sorry'' about
his affair with Monica Lewinsky satisfied some of his party
colleagues, who fear the political fallout from the scandal in the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials conceded that the president had a long
road ahead of him in trying to repair the damage the scandal has
done to his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president clearly does not believe that one conversation,
one statement, one speech is going to be sufficient in addressing
this matter the way he wants to,'' White House spokesman Michael
McCurry told reporters traveling with Clinton in Dublin, Ireland.
''He intends to keep addressing it both personally and, to the
degree he needs to, publicly, as he sees fit.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said, however, there is no ''concrete plan'' for trying
to contain the fallout from the Lewinsky scandal, adding ''the
president is taking it one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the scandal dogged Clinton on Friday as he posed
for news photographers with Prime Minister Bertie Ahern in Dublin.
Asked to respond to withering criticism from fellow Democrats,
Clinton said for the first time that he was ''sorry'' about his
indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've already said that I made a bad mistake, it was
indefensible, and I'm sorry about it,'' Clinton said, ''so I have
nothing else to say except that I can't disagree with anyone else
who wants to be critical of what I have already acknowledged was
indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   In some of the most biting criticism of Clinton's activities to
date, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., delivered a speech on the
Senate floor Thursday in which he described Clinton's behavior as
''immoral'' and ''disgraceful,'' adding that it called for a
''public rebuke.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond to Lieberman's comments, Clinton sounded edgy
and replied, ''there's nothing that he or anyone else could say in
a personally critical way that I, that I don't imagine that I would
disagree with, since I have already said it myself, to myself. And
I'm very sorry about it. There's nothing else I could say.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's remarks touched a chord around the country and on
Capitol Hill, where lawmakers were deluged with calls from
constituents and rushed to fire off statements aligning themselves
with Lieberman's views.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president's behavior was wrong and indefensible,'' stated
Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who faces a tough battle for
re-election in November. ''I feel deep sadness personally, and for
the nation, about this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat, Max Cleland of Georgia, issued a terse
statement saying, ''I agree with Senator Lieberman's statements,
both that the president's conduct was wrong, and that members of
Congress should refrain from commenting on what action should be
taken,'' until Starr issues his report.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Democrat, Christopher Dodd of Connecticut urged
Clinton to speak formally and directly to the nation once again.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said Clinton's apology Friday ''was a step in the right
direction,'' but dribbling out contrite comments won't work.
</P>
<P>
   ''He can't go day to day just responding to reporters'
questions,'' Dodd said in a telephone interview. ''He needs to have
a conversation with the country, much more so than occurred on
August 17,'' when Clinton delivered his widely criticized
four-minute address to the nation admitting to an ''inappropriate''
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton needs to ''look the American public in the eye and speak
from the heart,'' said Dodd. ''And I don't think you can do it in a
photo op.''
</P>
<P>
   Lines into the Senate switchboard were jammed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't had a break all day,'' said one operator.
''Seventy-five percent of the calls today have been to that
office,'' she said, referring to Lieberman's line.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the moment he is surprised, and appreciative, of the way
in which his remarks have been received, and he's trying to let all
of that sink in,'' said Lieberman's press secretary, Eric
Federling, who characterized the calls as ''overwhelmingly
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders on Capitol Hill, however, said some of the
president's detractors would never be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it again, he apologized again,'' said Rep. John Lewis,
D-Ga. ''I don't know what people want him to do _ sit on
Pennsylvania Avenue in sackcloth and ashes and say, 'I repent?' I
don't know what we're demanding from this man.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he respected Lieberman's opinion but disagreed with
his decision to make remarks that might have embarrassed the
president while he represented the country abroad. Clinton visited
Moscow on Tuesday and Wednesday for a summit with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin, and continued to Northern Ireland and the Republic
of Ireland on Thursday. He was scheduled to return to Washington
late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he (Lieberman) could have waited until the president
returned home,'' said Lewis. ''No one condoned the action of the
president, but you just don't go around kicking people when they're
down.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry acknowledged that White House Chief of Staff Erskine
Bowles had urged Lieberman earlier in the week to hold off on his
criticism. In an apparent concession to those concerns, Lieberman
waited until Clinton left Moscow on Thursday, but was unwilling to
put off his remarks until after the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was scheduled to appear Sunday morning on the NBC-TV
program ``Meet the Press,'' but many other Democrats were lying low
until they return to work on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Wednesday, Starr is expected to present the House
Judiciary Committee with a report of the findings of his
eight-month investigation into allegations that Clinton conducted
an 18-month affair with Lewinsky and later urged her to lie about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied the affair when the allegations first surfaced in
January, but admitted to it in his Aug. 17 address. He has
continued to deny, however, charges that he urged anyone to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution contributed
to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
