<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0269 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-580&AMP;A     09-04 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LABOR MARKET REMAINS SOLID 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite a sagging stock market and a growing trade
deficit, America's labor market remains very solid.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported Friday that the return of workers
idled by the 54-day strike at General Motors helped to keep the
unemployment rate at 4.5 percent in August, close to its 30-year
low, and helped to swell payrolls by 365,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were not surprised by Friday's report and digested its
most obvious implication _ that it reduced the likelihood of an
immediate interest-rate cut by the Federal Reserve Board _ with
apparent equanimity. By the end of the day, stock prices had fallen
modestly in volatile trading, while the bond market had rallied.
</P>
<P>
   Disregarding the effects of the GM strike, the economy churned
out an average of 217,000 new jobs a month in July and August,
slower than the 244,000 monthly rate in the year's first half but
still a strong pace. Pay is rising at a good clip, too; hours are
up and first-time unemployment claims have fallen to a 10-year low.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of everything that's out there, the general economy
is growing at a pretty good pace,'' said Mitchell Fromstein, chief
executive of Manpower Inc., the nation's largest supplier of
temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   David Wyss, chief economist of Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, said:
``We're where we've been for the last four months. It's still a
very tight labor market.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the Fed's primary concern has been whether the
economy would slow enough to head off the threat of inflation as
companies compete for relatively scarce workers. To prevent
inflation, the Fed could raise rates. Financial troubles abroad,
though, have cast the domestic situation in a new light, raising
questions whether lower rates might be needed to encourage
Americans to keep buying products made here and abroad to head off
a downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in this report that says ease,'' said Robert
Barbera at Hoenig &AMP; Co., an investment consulting firm, in White
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The issue now is how long the U.S. labor market will stay this
robust. Job numbers provide a better look at where the economy has
been than at where it is headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as it gets,'' said Edward Yardeni, chief
economist of Deutsche Bank Securities. ``All the risks are on the
downside. If we're lucky, unemployment will stay this low. If we're
not, more of the effects of the global recession will reach us.''
</P>
<P>
   The dark spot in the otherwise bright labor picture is a
troubling weakness in manufacturing. Asia's economic woes are
starting to take a bigger bite. Although manufacturing hours rose
sharply in August, suggesting that monthly industrial production
may rise for the first time this summer, a total of 100,000 factory
jobs disappeared in July and August, even taking into account the
effects of the GM strike.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Nardone, an economist at the Labor Department, said that the
pace of job losses had doubled from the two previous months. The
biggest losses occurred among makers of clothing and electronic
equipment and in food processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturing is in a pricing recession,'' Yardeni said. ``Not
only can't they raise prices, but they're under a lot of pressure
to cut prices because of the collapse of exports to Asia. As a
result, profits are under pressure, and companies are starting to
cut back on hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger, he added, is that the weakness in manufacturing
could spread to services.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Services don't operate in a vacuum,'' Yardeni said. ``Many of
their customers are manufacturers.'' Manufacturers employ less than
15 percent of the work force, he points out, but account for 30
percent of all business activity.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everywhere else in the labor market, however, jobs
were sprouting like weeds last month.
</P>
<P>
   Services _ from day care to management consulting _ added
135,000 jobs. Temporary-help firms accounted for 42,000 of that
number, reversing a loss of a similar magnitude in July. Computer
and data processing added 11,000 jobs. Transportation and public
utilities added 24,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Finance, insurance and real estate added 13,000, substantially
less than the pace of the last year or so. Mortgage lenders
probably account for much of that gain, as low rates keep the home
loan business humming.
</P>
<P>
   A gain of 16,000 construction jobs reflects the continued boom
in the building and buying of homes. Since last fall, construction
has added 261,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Government jobs rose by a strong 57,000, although that figure
was probably exaggerated as early school starting dates in some
parts of the country complicated attempts to make seasonal
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   One-fifth of small businesses say their most pressing problem is
an inability to find enough skilled help, according to the latest
survey of the National Federation of Independent Business.
Nonetheless, hiring in August was extremely strong.
</P>
<P>
   The wage picture is positive. The increase in workers' average
hourly earnings was half a percent, or 7 cents, in August, after a
gain of two-tenths of a percent in July. But looked at for the
latest 12 months, the wage numbers have been flat for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Even though wage inflation is not accelerating, pay is rising
fast enough to grant workers some of the best gains in real income
in years.
</P>
<P>
   Fromstein of Manpower said there was a tremendous amount of job
hopping as low-wage hotel, fast-food and service workers took
advantage of the extremely tight labor market to obtain better pay.
``There just aren't enough people to fill these jobs,'' he said.
``In an economy like this, when people making $7 an hour can get a
job for a dollar more, they're getting a 15 percent raise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
