<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK POLICE GEARING UP FOR YOUTH MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOHN KIFNER and KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Intent on preventing any outbreaks of violence, the
New York City Police Department plans to saturate the site of
Saturday's planned rally in Harlem with as many as 250 officers
along each of the six blocks set aside for the event.
</P>
<P>
   And, officials said, they intend to clear the streets promptly
at the demonstration's court-ordered finish at 4 p.m., whether the
event _ being billed as the Million Youth March _ has ended or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in charge,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir declared on
the eve of the rally being led by Khallid Abdul Muhammad, who has
warned that he will bring gangs to the event. ``Large or small,
we'll have a sufficient number of personnel and a plan to ensure
that both marchers and the public are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   While Safir refused to divulge specific security plans, a senior
law enforcement official, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
said the police were preparing to station more than 1,600 officers
at the rally itself, with a nearly equal number of extra police
officers in surrounding areas. The large deployment is planned even
through city officials now expect fewer than 10,000 participants to
show up for the long-litigated rally, far fewer than even the
50,000 revised figure now offered by Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   If these numbers hold, it would mean about one officer for every
seven participants, compared with the usual deployment of one
officer for every 30 to 50 participants in similar gatherings. In
addition, police plan other precautions, such as using heavier
metal barricades instead of the more commonly used wooden ones,
which can be broken apart and used as weapons or projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent confrontations, police plan to avoid making arrests
for minor offenses during the event. And the officers will be under
tighter command than normal, with one supervisor for every four
officers, rather than the usual ratio of one supervisor to every
eight officers at other rallies, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment comes on a busy Labor Day weekend in which the
37,000-member department is expected to run up more than $1 million
in overtime costs. In addition to the Harlem rally, more than 100
other events are scheduled, including the huge Caribbean Day parade
on Monday. And the department has been stretched further by fears
of terrorism, with hundreds of officers stationed around new
concrete barricades set up around City Hall, Federal courthouses
and other government buildings in downtown Manhattan, including
police headquarters itself. The additional weekend manpower put in
place is the equivalent of adding 14,000 extra officers, said Lt.
Sean Crowley, a department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of acrimonious dialogue in which Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani repeatedly denounced the rally as a `'hate march,'' a
federal appeals court on Tuesday cleared the way for the event, but
the ruling significantly curbed the scope of the event. What
Muhammad originally envisioned as a 12-hour rally drawing 150,000
to 3 million people to a 29-block area was scaled back to four
hours along six blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the court ruling, legal skirmishes over the march
continued Friday, with city Corporation Counsel Michael Hess
releasing a letter accusing the organizers of having failed to
secure contracts or permits to build a stage or install a sound
system or arrange for electricity from Con Edison. In addition,
Hess said, the organizers were still broadcasting and distributing
material asking participants to show up at 8 a.m., rather than at
noon.
</P>
<P>
   This, the corporation counsel warned Michael Warren, the group's
lawyer was `'an unacceptable and dangerous invitation to confusion
and possible confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally is set for noon to 4 p.m. on Malcolm X Boulevard from
118th Street to 124th Street. One lane of the broad boulevard is to
be kept open with barricades as an emergency corridor for
ambulances and police and fire vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   `'The idea is to give them the six-block area from noon to 4,
like the court has ordered and then at 4 o''clock pull the plug and
say goodbye,'' a senior law enforcement official said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to inflame the crowd. But if the people want to
stand firm and not leave at 4 o'clock, then the commanders will
announce that they are taking the podium down. Once the podium is
down, officers will announce they are reopening the street for
traffic and direct people to leave for the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if they don't do that,'' he added, ``then the details will
form up and push them onto the sidewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   The official added that `'with all the rhetoric going back and
forth, the mayor's not about to say `Let's handle them with kid
gloves and go easy.' So when the time comes to move these people,
we want enough supervisors to make sure the cops handle it in as
orderly a way as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only will there be a large police presence at the rally, but
transit officials, at the urging of City Hall are shutting down
four subway stations near the rally location on the No. 2 line.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the officers assigned to the event are to be deployed
behind the barricades, maintaining a kind of perimeter, with only a
handful of community affairs officers and undercover detectives
actually in the crowd. Officials said that officers would be
stationed on rooftops to keep debris from being thrown down onto
the street, and a contingent of mounted police would be deployed
nearby in case a riot erupted. In order to avoid provocation,
officials said, police would store helmets and other riot gear out
of sight, in vans and patrol cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
