<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-HNS &LR;      09-04 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APOLOGIZES FOR AFFAIR WITH LEWINSKY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ Under fire from his own party for his behavior
and lack of contrition, President Clinton for the first time said
``I'm sorry'' for his affair with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   But still the words Friday appeared to come hesitantly and only
a day after a dramatic Senate floor address by Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., a Clinton ally, who denounced the president's behavior as
``immoral'' and worthy of a ``public rebuke.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, questioned by reporters while standing beside Irish
Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, said: ``I've already said that I made
a bad mistake, it was indefensible, and I'm sorry about it. So I
have nothing else to say except that I can't disagree with anyone
else who wants to be critical of what I have already acknowledged
was indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   But pressed with questions again, Clinton said, ``There's
nothing that he or anyone else could say in a personally critical
way that I don't imagine that I would disagree with, since I have
already said it myself to myself. And I'm very sorry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, his hands clasped behind his back, answered
questions calmly, with Ahern looking on, as the White House
anticipated questions about Lieberman's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's comments signaled a critical meltdown of support in
Congress for Clinton as the White House tries to salvage his
presidency amid calls for his resignation or impeachment.
Lieberman's remarks drew immediate praise from other key Democrats
such as Sen. Daniel Moynihan of New York and Sen. Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, in a 24-minute address, said Clinton ``apparently had
extramarital relations with an employee half his age, and did so in
the workplace, in the vicinity of the Oval Office. ... Such
behavior is not just inappropriate, it is immoral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transgressions the president has admitted to are too
consequential for us to walk away and leave the impression for our
children and our posterity that what President Clinton acknowledges
he did within the White House is acceptable behavior for our
nation's leader,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after hearing Clinton's words, Lieberman released a
statement saying only: ``I appreciate the president's comments.''
</P>
<P>
   More trouble looms for Clinton as independent counsel Kenneth
Starr prepares to turn over his report to Congress at the end of
this month. Starr since January has investigated Clinton's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky and whether he perjured himself
or obstructed justice in an attempt to cover up the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lieberman nor other Democrats called for Clinton to step
down as Republicans have. Instead, one alternative that could
gather bipartisan support would be a censure by Congress that would
allow members to condemn Clinton's behavior without forcing him
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if a censure by Congress was appropriate, Clinton said:
``I shouldn't be commenting on that while I'm on this trip. My
understanding is that was not a decision that was made or advocated
yesterday. If that's not an issue, I don't want to make it one, one
way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House spokesman, refused to expand on
Clinton's comments, but he suggested the president will have even
more to say on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president clearly does not believe that one
conversation, one statement, one speech, is going to be sufficient
in addressing this matter the way he wants to. And he intends to
keep addressing it both personally and to the degree he needs to
publicly, as he sees fit,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry mostly offered sharp, short answers to reporters'
questions. ``I don't believe it is the role of staff, on a matter
that is as intensely personal being dealt with in an intensely
public way, for us to comment, spin, amplify, comment further. The
president said what he said. It's heartfelt, and I'll just let it
stand for what it is,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, however, said Clinton will not resign.
</P>
<P>
   In his Aug. 17 address to the nation, Clinton expressed
``regret'' for misleading the public and his family with his
denials of a relationship, but he did not specifically apologize
nor did he ask for forgiveness as he has since maintained. However,
he maintained his earlier denial of a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky was ``legally accurate'' but ``wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask the president that question, I think that he
believes his tone has been consistent on this, but it's been
interpreted differently,'' McCurry said. ``He believes he's been
clear on that all along, but others take a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that some people believe he didn't address it
adequately. And I think the president understands that he has some
obligation to address the concerns that they express. And he took
very seriously, obviously, what Sen. Lieberman had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The sex scandal dogging Clinton dominated what should have been
a day for him to champion his successful policy toward peace in
Ireland. Still, the Irish provided accolades to Clinton for his
administration's efforts to secure the Good Friday peace accord
made last April.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came to Dublin to highlight the Irish Republic's booming
economy with a facility operated by computer company Gateway 2000.
He and Ahern became the first heads of state to sign a pact
digitally. Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton later flew
to Limerick, where the president will play golf Saturday at
Ballybunion Golf Club, one of the world's renowned courses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
