</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWER OIL PRICES ARE SAID TO IMPEDE IRAQ'S SUPPLY OF FOOD,
MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Sharp drops in oil prices have undermined a
program under which Iraq can sell its oil to raise money for urgent
civilian needs like food and medicine, the senior official in
charge of the program told the United Nations Security Council on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Benon Sevan, briefing the Security Council on a
report on Iraq from the U.N. secretary general, said the reduced
earnings from oil sales would mean that the United Nations could
not meet a higher nutritional target in food supplied monthly to
every Iraqi.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of millions of dollars worth of food and medicine have
been shipped to Iraq since the program began a little over a year
ago, said a U.N. spokesman in Baghdad, Eric Falt, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the largest ship to arrive in Iraq under the program,
a 52,000-ton Greek freighter, brought a shipment of American red
winter wheat. American companies have won nearly $35 million in
grain contracts with Iraq under the program.
</P>
<P>
   The ``oil for food'' program was increased substantially in
February, to $5.2 billion from $2.1 billion in oil sales every six
months. This followed growing reports of malnutrition and deaths
caused by lack of medication and medical supplies. The quantities
were fixed in a formula based on the price of oil in February.
</P>
<P>
   After subtracting money set aside for compensation to victims of
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990 and other built-in deductions,
Iraq should have had several billion dollars for aid expenditures.
But lower oil prices have reduced the expected amount available to
about $1.79 billion for this six-month period.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To complicate matters, there have been delays in the
distribution of supplies, especially medicines. In the case of
medical supplies, the Iraqi government is responsible for
distribution in the center and south of the country but not in the
Kurdish areas of the north, where the United Nations does the job.
The reasons cited in the report included poor communications with
health centers, Iraq's extended quality control testing of imports,
and the tendency of Iraqi officials to hold back stocks for what
they say are emergency needs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Iraq is not able to pump all the oil permitted under
the expanded agreement because of the run-down condition of its oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of increasing the volume of oil sales to compensate in
some part for the lower prices have not been met because of delays
in approving contracts for spare parts. The delays are taking place
in the Security Council's sanctions committee on Iraq, where the
United States has challenged contracts despite the recommendation
of oil experts hired by the United Nations to review Iraqi
purchases. Iraq is often suspected of trying to import items beyond
what it needs. The country has been under stringent sanctions for
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole program is being run in a politically suspicious
atmosphere,'' Sevan said. ``and that makes it difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, who is departing as the U.S. representative to
the United Nations to become the Clinton administration's new
energy secretary, said that there was no change in U.S. support for
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is ready to assist the Iraqi people with
humanitarian needs,'' Richardson said after Sevan's briefing.
``We're ready to approve oil spare-parts contracts provided that
they deal with improving the oil delivery efficiency system for the
Iraqi people to get humanitarian assistance. For other purposes we
will not approve them _ for frivolous purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats cite as unnecessary such purchases as valves for
liquid petroleum gas tanks, which they see as intended for the
civilian market and which should be moved out of the spare parts
category. U.N. oil experts disagree, saying that the tanks are used
as sparkless, and therefore safe, mobile energy sources in the
Iraqi oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also cited Iraqi delays in distributing goods. ``The
problems with the oil for food programs do not change,'' he said.
``Iraq refuses to manage the program efficiently, in many instances
does not cooperate with the U.N. oil-for-food administrators and
continues to use the humanitarian issue as a political weapon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
