<HEADLINE>
SEASON OPENS WITH BANG-UP SCHEDULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rarely does a college football season's first full weekend offer
so many important games.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of The Associated Press' Top 25 teams play each other (and
that doesn't count Thursday night's game between No. 16 Virginia
and No. 25 Auburn). Top-ranked Ohio State has a dangerous game at
No. 11 West Virginia, and No. 5 Michigan carries its national
championship reputation to Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   But today's blockbuster lineup is more happenstance than
planning. Schedules are made years before the rankings make these
games more relevant. And don't for one moment think that a coach
wants to risk starting the season with a debilitating loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we'd rather be playing a lesser opponent at home,''
said philosophic Ohio State coach John Cooper. ``This is a payback
game; West Virginia came in here in 1986 and this returns that
game. I can't worry about playing a game like this on the road to
start the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone we play, it seems like we're their game of the year.
This is a rivalry because we're not that far away. It will be a
hostile place to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's Buckeyes have the most to lose. A loss in the opener
doesn't necessarily end national championship hopes. It just
eliminates the margin for error. One loss can be overcome; two
losses can't.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State and Michigan both carry burdens into battle. For the
Buckeyes, it's the No. 1 ranking. For the Wolverines, it's the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a bull's eye on our backs and everyone on our team
needs to raise his level of play,'' Michigan senior safety Marcus
Ray said. ``We can't let these teams catch us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notre Dame, their attitude will be that they should have beat
us last year, they were national champions, they're going to be
fired up. And we're going to have to match that.''
</P>
<P>
   A season opener has held the key to the Pacific-10 Conference
title each of the last two seasons. Arizona State (1996) and
Washington State (1997) each defeated contenders on opening day and
rode the momentum to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight in Tempe, Ariz., No. 8 Arizona State hosts No. 18
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, it's a great way to start the season,''
Arizona State coach Bruce Snyder said. ``But I don't know that any
of us prefer to open with a dramatic game. Most of us want to get
the bugs worked out a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win it, you have such great momentum and it forces
everybody else to chase you. The team that doesn't win the game is
certainly not out of it. But you need to rally your troops and it
can be kind of difficult.''
CHART WITH THIS ITEM
A ranked schedule
</P>
<P>
   The five games today where both teams are ranked in The
Associated Press Top 25: No. 1 Ohio State at No. 11 West Virginia
No. 5 Michigan at No. 22 Notre Dame No. 18 Washington at No. 8
Arizona State No. 21 Southern Mississippi at No. 13 Penn State No.
10 Tennessee at No. 17 Syracuse
\Nrailhed:Forgotten showdowns
</P>
<P>
   Two games off the national radar screens should be entertaining.
Central Florida visits Louisiana Tech, and Kentucky is at
Louisville. Last year, those teams' four quarterbacks combined for
more than eight miles of passing.
</P>
<P>
   In Ruston, La., the spotlight is a little brighter, thanks to
Louisiana Tech's season-opening loss at Nebraska. The Bulldogs'
passing combo of quarterback Tim Rattay and wide receiver Troy
Edwards drew national attention as Rattay passed for 590 yards and
four touchdowns while Edwards set an NCAA record with 405 yards
receiving.
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida quarterback Daunte Culpepper knows a little
about playing well at Nebraska. Last season he passed for 318 yards
in a 38-24 loss to the Huskers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is that Culpepper is dangerous no matter
what strategy you use,'' Louisiana Tech coach Gary Crowton said.
``Devise a defense to stop his passing and he turns into a running
back. Move up to stop the running and his passes will kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida coach Mike Kruczek won't discuss his team's
defensive plan, but he said his team wouldn't let Edwards repeat
his record-setting day. Central Florida defensive coordinator Gene
Chizik says the plan is practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody stops them, so you look for ways to slow them down,''
he said. ``You keep everything in front of you, and don't give up
the big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   In Louisville, Kentucky's record-setting quarterback Tim Couch
(a national-best 3,884 yards last season _ goes up against the
Cardinals and quarterback Chris Redman, who passed for 3,079 yards
last season.
\Nrailhed:Marketing 101
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota, which has won four Big Ten Conference games the last
four seasons, realizes it doesn't have any steak, so it's selling
sizzle. In this case, it's promoting its mascot.
</P>
<P>
   The school is airing local television spots and purchased an
eight-page regional insert in ``Sports Illustrated''. The ads try
to explain the school's ``misunderstood'' mascot, the Angry Gopher.
</P>
<P>
   For tonight's opener against Arkansas State, Minnesota is
staging a ``Halleumooya'' promotion. For $19, fans can get two game
tickets, two tickets to the state fair and two half-gallons of
milk. School officials hope for a crowd of 50,000 at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford also has a ticket deal. It's offering a money-back
guarantee on season tickets. Season tickets go for $185. The
money-back deal is for new buyers only.
</P>
<P>
   And Northwestern is making coach Gary Barnett into a Web
crawler. At 7 p.m. each Wednesday, Barnett will be available for
Internet chat at the school's Web site (www.nusports.com).
</P>
<P>
   \Nrailhed:Numerology
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hackett became the first Southern California coach in 47
years to win his debut game when the Trojans rallied to beat
Purdue, 27-17, Sunday. Jess Hill won his opener in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's 16-0 loss to Virginia on Thursday night was the
school's first shutout loss in a home opener since 1927.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, Indiana and Louisville have switched from artificial
turf to grass fields this season. Of the 112 Division I-A teams,
just 39 (or 37.5 percent) are playing on an artificial surface.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii's 27-6 loss Thursday night to No. 24 Arizona shouldn't
have come as a surprise. The game was televised on ESPN2; the
Rainbows are now 1-16-2 in nationally televised games.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State's loss to Colorado State last Saturday was its
first in school history in eight games against WAC teams.
\Nrailhed:Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State Heisman Trophy candidate J.R. Redmond hoped to be
on the field for 15 to 20 plays a game as a defensive back.
However, the junior running back might not see much action on
defense in tonight's opener against Washington. He has tendinitis
in his knees and might be limited to offense only.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Feller's California-based Pro Sports International owns the
rights to the Freedom Bowl, which was last played in 1994. Feller
has applied to the NCAA to re-certify the bowl. The target date for
the Freedom's comeback is Dec. 29, 1999 in San Francisco. Possible
opponents could come from the Pacific-10, the Big Ten or the new
league that is breaking away from the Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas athletic director Frank Broyles wants to expand
Razorback Stadium and never mind that the team rarely sells out the
current 50,000-seat capacity. Broyles wants to expand capacity to
65,000 in 2001 and to 75,000 by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Long odds to No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State opens the season at West Virginia tonight. The
Buckeyes are ranked No. 1, but they face long odds of finishing the
season on top. In the last 10 seasons, only one preseason No. 1
team won the national championship _ Florida State in 1993. Year
Preseason No. 1 Final rank, W-L Final No. 1, W-L 1988 Florida State
No. 3, 11-1-0 Notre Dame, 12-0-0 1989 Michigan No. 7, 10-2-0 Miami,
11-1-0 1990 Miami No. 3, 10-2-0 Colorado, 11-1-1 1991 Florida State
No. 4, 11-2-0 Miami, 12-0-0 1992 Miami No. 3, 11-1-0 Alabama,
