<SLUG> BC-LIBERAL-PRIEST-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST DEEMED TOO LIBERAL CELEBRATES FINAL MASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ When the Rev. James Callan celebrates his last
Mass at Corpus Christi Roman Catholic Church on Sunday, he can look
back on a 22-year ministry that packed the pews on Sundays and
created a battery of programs to help the poor, but that also moved
so far away from standard church practices regarding the roles of
women, gays and non-Catholics that he has been removed from his
job.
</P>
<P>
   Callan has told his congregation it was the Vatican that
requested he be removed from his parish. In an interview, he said
Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, head of the Vatican's powerful
Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, wrote to Rochester
Bishop Matthew Clark requesting that Callan be removed from his
parish.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark said he made the decision to remove the priest, after
asking Callan, unsuccessfully, to change certain practices to
conform with church rules. ``As diocesan bishop here,'' he said,
``I take responsibility for pastoral directions I issue and for
clergy transfers I make.'' A Vatican spokeswoman referred inquiries
back to the diocese.
</P>
<P>
   As the news has spread, Corpus Christi has emerged as the focus
of a wider debate in church circles, gaining attention as a parish
that pushed far into liberal territory in regard to sacraments and
liturgy, even as Rome was telling bishops, theologians and priests
to adhere to tradition. Callan said the parish has been contacted
by some liberal Catholic organizations expressing their support.
</P>
<P>
   During a time when Pope John Paul II has been emphatic that the
priesthood is reserved to men, Callan allowed women to play a
prominent role at the altar. He invited all people who considered
themselves followers of Jesus to partake of communion, even though
church rules generally restrict it to Catholics. And, as part of a
ministry to gay men and lesbians, he occasionally blessed same-sex
unions. ``We've tried to build an inclusive church over the
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, such actions place Corpus Christi at
Catholicism's most liberal edge, but many parishioners seem to
share this theological vision. A ``statement of faith'' by
parishioners declares that the priest's removal punishes them all
``for what we believe.'' It adds: ``As such, we see this as a
serious affront to Jesus Christ and all He stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   That the controversy is occurring here strikes some as ironic,
because Clark is counted among the diminishing number of moderates
within an increasingly conservative American Catholic hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas Reese, editor of America magazine, said the
bishop is known for an interest in ecumenical relations, a
sensitivity to issues of women in the church and a desire to
welcome homosexuals into the church. Last year, Clark held a Mass
for gay Catholics in Rochester's cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   For such actions, he has been criticized by local conservatives,
who have taken their complaints to the Vatican. One group, Citizens
for a Decent Community, called for a letter-writing campaign to
Pope John Paul II to protest a meeting the Rochester diocese will
soon host for people who minister to homosexual Catholics. ``We
urge our readers to inundate the Vatican with letters of protest
over this outrage,'' declares a flier that urges writers to ask for
Clark's removal.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Michael Macaluso Jr., said members had
also complained to Vatican officials about Callan in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, Corpus Christi was thriving. But when Callan
arrived as an assistant pastor in 1976, the 110-year-old parish
seemed on its last legs. To revive it, he launched an informal
Thursday night Mass, canceled bingo games and persuaded
parishioners to give away 12 percent from the collection plate to
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, he and a growing flock established such ministries as
a free clinic, a homeless shelter, a home for former prisoners, a
hospice and a clinic in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   The work won plaudits. In a guest column in the Rochester
Democrat and Chronicle, in which he discussed his decision to
remove Callan, Clark praised the priest for developing
``extraordinary ministries.''
</P>
<P>
   The good works also drew people from far and wide. Not everyone
who came to the church was Catholic, which pleased those who liked
the idea of a religious community with an unusually wide embrace.
``Everybody was welcome,'' said Mike Martella, 42, a commercial
real estate broker and father of four. ``There was no difference
from being Protestant, a woman, being gay, being Jewish,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bickel, 54, described the parish as ``Vatican Three'' _ a
grass-roots progression from the Second Vatican Council, which
enacted sweeping reforms in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   She made her comment after a communion service at Corpus Christi
at which the associate pastor, Mary Ramerman, presided. Ms.
Ramerman, 43, who is married with three children and holds a degree
in theology, wore what she called a banner, an emerald cloth strip
hung over one shoulder, which was given to her by parishioners five
years ago and is a garment with a certain symbolism. (Priests wear
a stole, which hangs over both shoulders as a symbol of their
ordination.)
</P>
<P>
   After delivering a homily, she invited about 100 parishioners to
receive communion, partaking of bread and wine previously blessed
by a priest. ``If you love Jesus and seek to follow Jesus, you are
welcome to come and receive the gift of his life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said one of his concerns about Corpus Christi was that the
parish was ``leaving the impression that someone other than
ordained priests are providing Eucharist.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Corpus Christi's open invitation to communion
went beyond what a priest may do in using his judgment about who
may partake. As for the blessing of same-sex unions, he said that
they went well beyond what the church allows.
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi's practices have never been secret. Callan
described the parish in a book he wrote last year, ``Can't Hold
Back the Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that having women at the altar sent the message ``that
God calls both men and women to be priests and preachers.'' As for
allowing non-Catholics to take communion, he wrote that all were
``the guests of the Lord Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning that Callan would be removed, Corpus Christi's
parishioners formed a ``media committee'' that created a videotape
and sent it to television news programs. One parishioner, Bill
Berry, 54, vice president of an advertising agency, said, ``Most
simply and succinctly, our strategy is to generate dialogue with
the Vatican.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said in interviews that the parish would continue without
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Callan said he did not know what his new assignment would be,
but he said he believed Corpus Christi represented the church's
future. ``My removal will look silly 10 years from now,'' he said.
And referring to a former television news commentator, he added,
``Like Eric Severeid used to say, `I'm a pessimist about tomorrow,
but I'm an optimist about the day after tomorrow.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he would ask the next pastor to take note of certain
concerns, such as ``the governing authority of the bishop and
accountability of the community to the bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that it was important for a parish ``to stay in
reasonable union and harmony'' with the diocese, adding, ``It is
simply not acceptable to plant your own flag without that kind of
rigorous dialogue with the whole community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
