<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0282 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-JOHNCHASE-COX     09-04 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-JOHNCHASE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Architect of his own success comes back to UT
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a career marked by firsts, John Chase has
gone from University of Texas pariah to ultimate insider.
</P>
<P>
   Chase made history at UT when he walked through the door in 1950
under the watchful gaze of federal marshals. Half a century later
at age 73, Chase is a prominent Houston architect and making
history at UT again. He was the first African American to enroll,
to be licensed as an architect in Texas, to be appointed to the
U.S. Commission of Fine Arts, to be named a UT Distinguished
Alumnus. But a milestone Chase could not have foreseen a
half-century agois this: He's the first African American president
of UT's66,000-member Ex-Students' Association.
</P>
<P>
   An admired businessman and civic leader, Chase leads an
association of manyinfluential Texans, including business and
government leaders. These well-connected alumnihave the ear of
regents, lawmakers and administrators on the UT System's 15
campuses. They understand how the university is run and financed.
They make things happen. ``I think you can achieve more by being
inside than by being outside,'' said Chase, in Austin on Thursday
to honor alumni scholarship winners. ``It's just that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two decades, Chase has been actively supporting the
alumni association, encouraging UT students to graduate and
recruiting minorities. He leads the alumni at a time when UT's
image among blacks and Hispanics has suffered and when gains in
diversity have been set back by the federal court's Hopwood ruling,
which effectivelyended affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   While the timing may be ironic, Chase was in line for the
high-profile post long before the ruling. And now he's working to
blunt its effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a happy coincidence that John is here to help us when we
need help,'' Architecture School Dean Larry Speck said.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, who took office July 1, said he will build on the work of
his predecessor, Austin attorney Larry Temple, who spearheaded the
creation of alumni-sponsored scholarships to attract minorities to
UT. At the alumni center Thursday, Chase and Temple celebrated more
than $1.09 million in alumni-sponsored scholarships given this
fall, including $443,250 in Texas Leader Scholarships to 134
students.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said it wasn't hard to reconcile two painful years he
spent at UT getting a master's degree in architecture with his
leadership of a group that had no blacks when he graduated in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you achieve anything by getting mad or getting
angry or holding grudges,'' he said. ``My effort has always been to
try to work together with people for the common good.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Chase describe him as irrepressibly positive, fun
and passionate about UT.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney John Adkins recalled how Chase and his wife
invited a group of inner-city youth to their home in the early
1980s and encouraged them to attend UT. ``He gave the most
inspiring speech I have ever heard about the value of higher
education, and it reflected a love for the university I have never
heard before,'' said Adkins, an Ex-Students' Association board
member.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, an Annapolis, Md., native, had already earned a
bachelor's degree in architecture from Hampton University in
Virginia when he came to Austin with a desire to work in the ``deep
South.'' He took a teaching job but decided to get a master's
degree in architecture.
</P>
<P>
   But first he had to await the outcome of a U.S. Supreme Court
case.
</P>
<P>
   Heman Sweatt, an African American, had sued then-UT President
T.S. Painter after being refused admission to the Law School.
Within days of the court's ordering UT to admit Sweatt, Chase
registered for classes in the spring of 1950 and made national
news.
</P>
<P>
   Sweatt enrolled that fall, several months after chase, but
dropped out after being taunted and harassed.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said he experienced some hostility and has kept hate mail
from people who said he had no business at UT. The letters were
filled with racial slurs, and some mentioned his wife, Drucie, whom
he met in Austin and married during the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks were not allowed to live in the dorms, and the Drag was
segregated. At UT football games, a row in the end zone _ the worst
seats in the stadium _ was set aside for black fans, said Chase, a
sports enthusiast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would always cheer for the black players who came in from
other schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like that cut deep and hurt _ not being able to live on
campus or go to places on the Drag to get a soda,'' he went on in a
more serious tone. ``I knew Sweatt, and if the case had been built
on me, I would not have graduated, either.''
</P>
<P>
   He felt some resentment toward UT, but it did not linger. He had
made some great friends and joined The Ex-Students' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Chase moved to Houston, which was growing, but no architect
would hire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a firm suggest I go to Africa,'' Chase said. ``I just
said, `Heck, if they won't hire me, I'll get my license and hire
myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   He became the first black architect to be licensed in Texas, in
1954, and opened his own firm. The work came.
</P>
<P>
   He designed the George R. Brown Convention Center in Houston and
about half the buildings at Texas Southern University. At UT, he
designed the parking garage at 25th and San Antonio Streets, a
$13.8 million soccer/track stadium, now under construction, and a
just-completed $12.7 millionstadium parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   Chase co-founded the National Organization of Minority
Architects and was appointed by President Carter to the U.S. Fine
Arts Commission, serving from 1976 to 1981. The commission reviews
building designs in Washington, D.C., and approves the coins used
at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   He is proud of getting the likeness of an African American
athlete on the gold coins at the Olympics in Los Angeles and for
ensuring that one of the three soldiers on a statue beside the
Vietnam Memorial represented an African American. A highlight of
his career was designing the U.S. embassy in Tunis, Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's among the top two, three or four African American
architects in the country,'' Speck said.
</P>
<P>
   Speck and others said they hope minorities will get the message
from Chase that they are wanted at UT and can succeed there.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is the message,'' Temple said. ``John, all his life, has
been a hero to young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-03-98 2304E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
