<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRISH-WOLVERINES-245&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME LEADER VOWS TO BE PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Jarious Jackson has played on the punt return
team, returned an onside kick for a touchdown and, in 28 minutes 41
seconds as Notre Dame's quarterback, managed four touchdown passes
while completing 18 of 32 attempts. He has also been upbraided on
national television by Lou Holtz, then the Fighting Irish coach,
for capping a magnificent 21-yard run with a fumble in a game that
Notre Dame had already won.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard Notre Dame fans chant for him to enter the game,
and then heard them grumble when he was tripped up for a 4-yard
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a senior, will lead Notre Dame against the defending
national champion Michigan Wolverines here Saturday. He is expected
to bury the disappointing memory of the Ron Powlus years and
resurrect the glory of the Tony Rice era, which produced a national
championship 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But he plans to emulate another Irish quarterback, Kevin
McDougal, who was probably the least glamorous player to assume one
of the nation's most glamorous positions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, McDougal, an unheralded senior, replaced Rick Mirer and
led the Irish to an 11-1 season and the brink of the national
championship. He is nowhere to be found in Notre Dame's record
books, but he still appeals to the Irish's new quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was patient and I can understand that,'' Jackson said.
``And he won, and that's what I want. I honestly didn't think it
would take this long. But it is what I came here to do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The college football season begins in earnest this weekend with
many marquee matchups, and there are missions to be fulfilled
around the country. The Ohio State Buckeyes, with their all-America
linebacker, Andy Katzenmoyer, finally declared academically
eligible, go to West Virginia determined to show that they deserve
the No. 1 ranking they received in many preseason polls.
</P>
<P>
   A young Penn State team plays host to Southern Mississippi as
the Nittany Lions try to get the two victories Joe Paterno needs to
join Bear Bryant, Pop Warner and Amos Alonzo Stagg in Division I's
300-victory club. Out west, Arizona State's national title hopes
will be tested early against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At Notre Dame Stadium, the second-year coach Bob Davie will send
out a new starting quarterback to avenge last season's loss to
Michigan. That defeat set the tone for the Irish's disappointing
7-6 season last year.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame will also be trying to return the spotlight to what
happens on the field. In one of the most difficult off seasons in
the school's history, Notre Dame lost an age discrimination suit
filed by a former coach, which made public details of player abuse
and embarrassing internal squabbling among Davie and the coaching
staff under Holtz. The program also reported itself for violating
National Collegiate Athletic Association rules involving gifts
given to a dozen players by a woman who pleaded guilty to
embezzling $1 million from her employer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his limited experience, Jackson may be the perfect
leader. As Powlus' backup, he saw how viciously both the news media
and the Notre Dame fans turned on the four-year starter when he did
not live up to expectations. Jackson also experienced a consuming
frustration as a backup, exacerbated by his own missed
opportunities when called upon.
</P>
<P>
   Highly recruited out of Tupelo, Miss., Jackson is still haunted
by the humiliation Holtz heaped on him as a sophomore after the
fumble against Purdue. Holtz followed an on-field tirade with a
summation of Jackson's performance in his post-game comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jarious Jackson's an excellent fourth-string quarterback,''
Holtz said. ``We just don't have a second- and third-string
quarterback right now.''
</P>
<P>
   By then Jackson was already calling home, wondering if he had
made a mistake. He thought of returning to one of the Mississippi
schools or to Tennessee, which recruited him to succeed Peyton
Manning. He told his mother, Karen, not to bother coming to see him
because he wasn't playing.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Jarious Sr., saw some of his own impatience in his
son. Once the roommate of the future Hall of Famer Walter Payton at
Jackson State, he transferred to Alcorn State to find playing time.
``Like me, he wanted to play now,'' Jackson Sr. said. ``I told him
to wait his turn and learn, that he would have his time to shine.''
</P>
<P>
   In the off season, Jackson added 10 pounds, worked on his
throwing and welcomed a shift in offensive philosophy by Davie. The
Irish will return to the option offense that they had abandoned
during the lead-footed Powlus' reign.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
