<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0285 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGER-JAIL-$ADV7-2TA     09-04 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-JAIL-$ADV7-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR-CROSSED CAREER: MURDER CHARGE LATEST CHAPTER IN TROUBLED LIFE
OF TEXAS SINGER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Monday, Sept. 7) 
(Attn: Nashville) 
(See optional trim) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SABINAL, Texas _ His accomplishments were nothing short of
astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   The young South Texas singer named Johnny Rodriguez was not only
an ethnic trail blazer but a prodigious hit maker, racking up 15
Top 10 country singles and releasing more than 30 albums, many on
nationally known record labels.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville fawned over the handsome Hispanic phenom, welcoming
him into the Country Music Hall of Fame's coveted Walkway of the
Stars, while Billboard magazine awarded Rodriguez its Trendsetter
Award for becoming the first Mexican-American singer to capture a
national audience.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has played Carnegie Hall, and one notable gig was the
Inaugural Ball for President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But just as surprising was the image last week of the nationally
known country star, trudging meekly out of the Uvalde County Jail
in South Texas after posting a $50,000 bond on a murder charge.
Escorted by sheriff's deputies who shielded him from enraged
relatives of a young acquaintance he is accused of killing Aug. 29,
Rodriguez looked drawn and older than his 46 years as he carried
his belongings in a plastic shopping bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when the road ahead of Johnny's tour bus was
paved in gold and platinum,'' said Casey Monahan, director of the
Texas Music Office and a former Austin music critic.
``Unfortunately, he took a few sharp turns.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not altogether unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's career has been a roller-coaster, shooting upward in
the early 1970s with a string of hugely successful country hits,
and then stymied by drug abuse, unsuccessful rehabilitation
programs, public arrests for drunkenness, and a string of failed
marriages. Of late, Rodriguez has been performing at small clubs
around Texas without a band, still packing them in but a shadow of
his past popularity, his latest record a flop.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few noted the tragic irony of last week's jailhouse
scene. After all, Rodriguez's legendary ascent to stardom and fame
were launched decades after an earlier stay in the Uvalde County
Jail.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager in 1969, Rodriguez was locked up for stealing an
expensive Angora goat from a local rancher and grilling it at a
roadside park with a group of friends. Texas Ranger Joaquin Jackson
recognized him in jail as the teen who put on impromptu singing
performances on park benches at nearby Garner State Park.
</P>
<P>
   The ranger posted bond for Rodriguez, and helped him land a job
singing in weekend Western skits at Alamo Village, the elaborate
set built in Brackettville for John Wayne's epic movie about the
fall of the Texas mission.
</P>
<P>
   Today, another Texas Ranger, Coy Smith of Uvalde, has taken an
interest in Rodriguez, too, but for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The ranger is helping Uvalde County prosecutors assemble a
murder case against Rodriguez, who is charged with the fatal
shooting of Israel ``Bosco'' Borrego, 26, early on Aug. 29. The
singer's attorney, Alan Brown of San Antonio, insists Rodriguez was
startled to find an inebriated Borrego inside his mother's Sabinal
frame house at 4:30 in the morning. Believing him to be an
intruder, Brown said, Rodriguez shot him in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Borrego's family disputes that, saying the shooting victim was a
friend of Rodriguez's who frequently stayed at the house and
partied with Rodriguez. District Attorney Tony Hackebeil said both
men had been drinking when the shooting took place. He said he
expects to present the murder case to a grand jury Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Rodriguez's supporters are confident the grand jury will
clear him of murder charges, and that the killing will not end his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody is waiting to see what the grand jury says.
If he's no-billed (no indictment returned), I don't think it's
going to hurt at all,'' said an optimistic Randy Willis, an Austin
booking agent who was Rodriguez's manager and went to junior high
school with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody in today's society can be put in a position to defend
themselves, and I believe that's what happened to Johnny,'' Willis
said. ``It's just a terrible tragedy, but again, it's not anything
anyone planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabinal residents say Rodriguez returned to his boyhood home
several months ago, and the aging home on Pickford Street was the
venue for occasional front-porch guitar-picking and drinking
parties hosted by Rodriguez. Prosecutors are now investigating an
earlier shooting incident weeks ago at the home in which the singer
allegedly shot at another local man, but did not hit him.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking and drug use are twin demons that have stalked
Rodriguez for years. He has been largely unsuccessful in
vanquishing them, and they had all but ended his once promising
career, say fellow musicians, industry executives and observers of
the country music scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid had it all. He had the looks, the personality, and he
could sing,'' said San Antonio vocalist and song writer Johnny
Bush, himself a country legend. ``He was this good-looking kid, he
had charisma like (Elvis) Presley. The girls would scream and throw
their car keys and panties on the stage, although I'm sure some of
that was arranged.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, as I watched his career progress, I watched the
alcohol and drug thing set in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes when confronted with the unexpected rigors of
stardom, Rodriguez sought shelter in substance abuse, the same
self-destructive refuge that has attracted other country stars from
Hank Williams to Johnny Cash to George Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never thought about the star route, and with that comes a
lot of pressures they never thought of. The commitments that come
with being a star, some guys never know about and they can't handle
that ... and then the worst part is standing up on a stage in a
strange part of the country you've never been to before, and baring
your soul to strangers,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to deal with it was the drugs and alcohol, and I
think that was what happened to Johnny, and it happened early.
Everything he ever made went up his nose, and his career peaked
early.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Sabinal, the slaying has shocked the small peaceful South
Texas town of 1,500 residents, located about 60 miles west of San
Antonio. Violent crime is a rarity in this close-knit farming town
shaded by enormous live oaks and pecans, where local police say the
last murder occurred two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend's slaying was especially troubling because it
involved members of the Rodriguez and Borrego clans, well-known
families who have lived here for generations, attend the same
Catholic church and go to the same public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both families were real nice. It's just a real sad deal,''
said Dora Dominguez, the town's utilities clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Sabinal, Rodriguez is the second-youngest of 10
children. His father, a former San Antonio police officer, is
deceased, and his mother is in a nursing home, acquaintances say.
Two of the singer's sisters work for the local school district, and
one brother is a member of the Sabinal City Council. Rodriguez's
older brother, Reynaldo Rodriguez, is a retired Air Force veteran
who until May was Sabinal's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed sadly resigned to the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm am (sorry), too,'' he said, ``but it's done, and you can't
do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   About two years after his unlikely discovery in the county jail,
Rodriguez left Uvalde County and boarded a plane to Nashville with
his guitar and $14 in his pocket, recalls former manager Willis.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez called country star Tom T. Hall, whom he had met while
singing in the western skits at the Alamo Village. Hall took him in
and hired Rodriguez to open his act. In 1972, the novice singer had
a hit on his hands with ``Pass Me By,'' a song written by Hall's
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Rodriguez had arrived, and he was only 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The next few years were a time of almost unlimited success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminded me of a Mexican-American Ricky Nelson,'' recalled
Rick ``Casper'' Rawls, a lead guitarist from Austin who played with
Rodriguez in the early 1970s. ``He was a good singer, really
charismatic, and he looked great. He could really deliver the
goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Rawls recalled a ``sweet guy'' who ``seemed like a very
well-grounded man. He had good family roots, and you could tell he
came from good stock.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1979 Rodriguez signed a record contract with CBS records. But
the anticipated stardom failed to materialize as Rodriguez
struggled with drug and alcohol use; the record company dropped him
in 1985. In 1987, he was clean and attempting a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I go on stage now, I wouldn't take nothin' for
nothin','' he told the Chicago Tribune in a December 1987
interview. ``You couldn't shove it down my throat. There's not a
better feeling than getting up there and being able to feel the
excitement and response. Before, I was so paranoid I didn't want to
look them in the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sobriety didn't last.
</P>
<P>
   Weslaco police arrested Rodriguez for public intoxication in
1994 in a hotel lounge, after a fight broke out between the singer
and a guitar player from Nashville. Rodriguez, who had played at a
musical festival in the Rio Grande Valley city earlier, pleaded
guilty and paid a $145 fine, Weslaco police said.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, on Jan. 10, 1995, Rodriguez married Lana
Nelson, the oldest daughter of Willie Nelson. &UR;  &LR; The couple had
separated by July, and were divorced in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, they didn't date very long. They only dated three
weeks before they got married,'' said former manager Willis, who
was the singer's best man at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rodriguez's second failed marriage. In 1977, he had wed a
Nashville airline stewardess; Tom T. Hall was best man. The couple
divorced after two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Rodriguez released his last album ``You Can Say That
Again,'' a collection of progressive country material, which
received critical acclaim but failed commercially.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was truly, really fine work,'' said Los Angeles record
executive Larry Sloven, whose HighTone Records released the album.
``Why didn't it sell? It's because of the nature of country radio
these days. It's almost impossible to get record play in any
meaningful way unless it's a record from a Nashville record company
with some 25-year-old guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Musicians who have played with Rodriguez over the years have
come to his defense, and insist he is not prone to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy must have scared the dickens out of Johnny because
that's not him. That's out of character for him to do something
like that, and I've known him since 1972,'' said Jerry Blanton, a
steel guitarist from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton, who last played with Rodriguez at a spring performance
in Corpus Christi, insists he has never witnessed any drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured one of these days I'd see him in his bad mode, but I
never saw him when he wasn't clean and ready to work,'' Blanton
said. ``He drank a little beer, and he loved to visit with
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Rodriguez remarried and the couple had a
child in April. Before a June gig in San Antonio he told the San
Antonio Express-News he was living clean and trying to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even drink around my family,'' the singer said.
``They're the best thing that's ever happened to me. I'm going to
concentrate on my music and try and mend some of the rips I've
caused over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   For the immediate future, the singer's fate lies in the hands of
a legal system that gave him a chance decades before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
