<HEADER>
A0302 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-SHORT-ART-$AD     09-04 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-SHORT-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOYS AND PERILS OF BETTING ON A FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 By NOELLE KNOX   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of the mutual funds that find themselves in good stead as
of late have something in common: big short positions.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell &AMP; Orkin Market Opportunity, for example, bet 40 percent
of its portfolio on falling stock prices, and was up 3.6 percent
from the market peak on July 17 through last Thursday, according to
Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago. Lindner
Bulwark, shoting 25 percent of its assets, saw its shares climb 5.8
percent for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Investors short a stock as a way to profit from its decline.
They borrow the shares from a broker for a small fee and sell them
on the open market. After the share price declines, they buy back
the shares at the lower market price and return them to the broker,
pocketing the difference.
</P>
<P>
   It's a risky game. If the shares rise, the investor has to buy
them back for more than he paid and take a loss. That is what
happened to William J. Nasgovitz, whose Heartland Small Cap
Contrarian fund, despite the vicious selloff in small and
micro-size stocks, has been crippled by unprofitable short
positions coupled with the overall market decline.
</P>
<P>
   The fund lost 18.7 percent from the July 17 peak through
Thursday, worse than the 17 percent loss for the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index over that period.
</P>
<P>
   Situations like this underscore why many funds swear off
shorting stocks _ and how the strategies of shorting seem as varied
as the managers who make such bets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for companies that we believe have misled investors
about their potential in the future,'' said Andrew F. Boord,
co-manager of Lindner Bulwark, &UR;  &LR; which has $28.8 million in assets
under management. ``We try to go short on those kind of stocks,
regardless of what the market does.''
</P>
<P>
   Boord loves to hate Daou Systems Inc., a San Diego-based
information technology consultant to health care companies. From a
high of $34.375 last Sept. 23, Daou's stock closed at $6.625 on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Boord, 26, started shorting shares at the beginning of the year.
By the end of June, at an average price of $18, Daou had become his
largest short position.
</P>
<P>
   Daou's earnings have met Wall Street's expectations, but Boord
said, ``When you look at how they made their numbers it's almost
laughable; it's pretty strange.'' In particular, he points to a
fast-growing line on Daou's balance sheet called ``work in
progress,'' under which Daou includes a percentage of revenues from
unbilled contracts. ``It shouldn't grow that much more than
revenues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Rieger, a spokesman for Daou, said the practice is
required under generally accepted accounting principles and was
validated by its accountants, Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   But such bookkeeping has apparently raised concern among other
investors. On Aug. 14, the company's stock plunged 31 percent on
rumors that Daou would have to restate its second-quarter earnings.
The company issued a news release defending its financial
statements. Nevertheless, the company was hit with two-class action
lawsuits contending accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   (Daou has issued a statement saying it had ``meritorious
defenses'' against the claims and planned to defend itself
vigorously.).
</P>
<P>
   Over all, however, Lindner Bulwark's numbers display the ugly
battle scars of shorting in a bull market. Since its February 1994
inception, it has lost 1.4 percent annually, on average, versus a
20.2 annual return for S&AMP;P 500. And in 1998, it has lost 1.9
percent, through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved it's very difficult selling short Wall Street's
most-loved, over-owned, and over-valued growth stocks,'' said
Nasgovitz, 53, president of Heartland Advisors, which manages $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   His Heartland Small Cap Contrarian mutual fund, with $113.4
million in assets, can hold up to 25 percent of its assets in short
positions, and was off 26.2 percent for this year as of Thursday.
On Aug. 18, Nasgovitz announced plans to merge the fund with the
$1.6 billion Heartland Value fund, which does not short stocks.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent the last few weeks buying stocks to cover some 20
short positions. On Sept. 1, he closed out a successful
300,000-share short positions on Organogenesis, which he shorted at
$18 a share and bought back at $9. And he also won big betting
against Micron Technology. He bought 85,000 shares at about $23 a
share, covering a short at $33.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he bought 100,000 shares of Compaq Computer at about
$30 a share, taking a small loss. He shorted all three companies
because he thought they were overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Nasgovitz has three shorts remaining on Heartland's books: Clear
Channel Communications, Consolidated Graphics and Dollar Tree
Stores. He sees them as trading at inflated prices, yet their
shares have continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Since its April 1995 inception, the fund has returned 5.7
percent annually on average, through Thursday, versus 11.8 percent
for its average small-cap value peer, according to Morningstar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael B. Orkin, 39, manager of Caldwell &AMP; Orkin Market
Opportunity, is a big-picture thinker. He looks at the economic
crisis in Asia and shorts large companies in the United States
involved in cyclical industries like steel, engineering and
construction that will be hurt by it.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, he also has been increasing his short positions in
companies that lend money to people with less-than-stellar credit
histories. These sub-prime lenders, as they are known, can have
problems when the economy sours and people cannot afford to pay
their debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're in a bear market now, or just a
correction,'' he said. ``But I do expect a significant bear market
between now and the next 10 years, with a 60 percent-plus
downside.''
</P>
<P>
   Orkin declined to name specific stocks that he is shorting. But
according to the fund's annual report, as of April 30 its largest
short positions were in Caterpillar and PMI Group, a mortgage
insurer. They have since fallen 19.3 and 32.1 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The fund was closed to new investors on Aug. 27, after it was
flooded with $150 million, almost doubling its assets in 10 weeks.
Small wonder: The fund has sizzled, returning 20.2 percent for the
year through Thursday, according to Morningstar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
