<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0305 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-UNION-STANDAR     09-04 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-UNION-STANDARD-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD RETURNS FOR EVERY COLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN; Ga., Md.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Mitchell Dynan is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic of MFS Union Standard Equity is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labor Day is still seen largely as a blue-collar, big-shoulders
kind of holiday, even though the overwhelming majority of its
celebrants are largely disassociated from the principles of the
organized work force.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Labor Department, there were just over 16
million union members at work in the country last year, about 14.1
percent of all workers. The proportion of union workers has been
steadily declining since 1953, when it was nearly 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these grim statistics, labor lives. Witness recent
strikes against General Motors and Bell Atlantic and the current
action against Northwest Airlines. Even the mutual fund industry is
taking labor seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, MFS Investment Management embraced an investing
strategy formulated by a member of the longshoremen's union in
Savannah, Ga., and created the Union Standard Equity fund.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Eason, a longshoreman and a trustee of his union's
pension fund, was frustrated at the sight of his pension money
being invested in companies with bad labor relations. So he
developed a number of litmus tests to determine a company's
relative labor friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invest in a list of companies that meet certain criteria
that are labor-friendly,'' said Mitchell Dynan, who has managed the
fund since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, labor unions are likely to warm to such a tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unions have always had tremendous pension power,'' said A.
Michael Lipper, president of Lipper Analytical Services. ``But I
don't think that in the past it has been used terribly effectively
for the rank and file.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the labor-friendly benchmarks for the portfolio: at least
5 percent of a company's employees must be unionized; the company
cannot be involved in a strike or lockout; it cannot make products
that are on the boycott list of the AFL-CIO; it must meet certain
health, safety and labor laws, and it must not show a pattern of
outsourcing _ the transfer of work to other companies. The fund
only buys American companies.
</P>
<P>
   Screening is done by an advisory board of senior labor
officials, academics and outside company managers; Labor Research
Inc., a division of American Capital Strategies of Bethesda, Md.,
supplies the results to Dynan.
</P>
<P>
   The list that they compile, the Labor Sensitivity Index, has a
total of about 540 stocks. Dynan culls that list to 65 to 70.
</P>
<P>
   But last December, the investment parameters were relaxed
somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until December 1997, I had to be 100 percent invested in the
companies on this list,'' Dynan said. ``At that point the board
gave me a little more flexibility, and now allows me to invest up
to 20 percent of the fund's assets in financial services and
technology, industries in which there is very little
unionization.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially created only for public and labor union pension plans,
the fund was opened to retail investors in August 1997; the minimum
investment is $1,000. It now has about $100 million under
management.
</P>
<P>
   Still, about 90 percent of the money in the fund is from unions,
including the American Federation of Musicians and Employers
pension fund, the Transportation Workers Union, and the
International Alliance of Theater Stage Employees.
</P>
<P>
   For individuals, the fund carries hefty sales charges _ a 5.75
percent maximum front-end sales charge on its class A shares, for
example. But results have been attractive. For the three years
ended Thursday, the average annual return of the fund's
institutional shares was 21.5 percent, versus 16.7 percent for the
average fund in its category of large-capitalization blend funds,
which tend to buy big-company stocks and have both value and growth
investing styles, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   While the fund lagged behind the 22.2 percent return of the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 over that period, it has beaten the index's
return so far this year _ 2.8 percent versus 2.2 percent as of
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dynan and his predecessor, William Harris, have achieved this
record by concentrating their holdings in large-cap stocks that
until recently, at least, were among the best performers in the
steady advance of major market indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Dynan also likes to see a large amount of executive and employee
ownership of a stock and prefers high-visibility companies in
``recurring revenue'' businesses, like supermarkets, which can be
fairly certain what they are going to earn over the next six to
nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Dynan also likes businesses that generate free cash, or cash
after capital spending and dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty conservative portfolio, and I want to
maintain it that way,'' Dynan said. ``That is my investment style.
Also, right now I am cautious about the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund's four biggest holdings are citadels of American
capitalism: General Electric, Bristol-Myers Squibb, Exxon and
Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Since being allowed to invest in financial-service and
high-technology companies, Dynan, who also serves as co-manager of
the Massachusetts Financial Services Investors Trust, has added
insurance companies like Allstate Insurance and Hartford Financial
Services Group and banks like U.S. Bancorp, National City Corp. and
Washington Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   He also put about 1.5 percent of the fund into Microsoft and 1
percent in BMC Software. ``Those stocks have definitely
contributed'' to the fund's performance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the market's recent downward spike is a source of concern,
Dynan said that as a buy-and-hold investor, ``I don't try and call
the market; I invest in companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting his cautious view about the economy, Dynan has
overweighted the fund in consumer staples companies, the largest
sector grouping, at nearly 20 percent of the portfolio. Industrial
cyclicals account for nearly a quarter of the portfolio, and energy
stocks are well over 10 percent, Morningstar said.
</P>
<P>
   As of late last week, Dynan said he was not selling stocks to
raise cash, despite the market's recent slide and his worries about
the effects of the Asian and Russian financial crises on corporate
earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
