A0316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-IMPEACH-COX     09-04 0205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-IMPEACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parties seek joint approach
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Christi Harlan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Democratic leader
Dick Gephardt will meet next Wednesday to review plans for
receiving a report on President Clinton from independent counsel
Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which will include Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) and ranking Democrat John Conyers of Michigan,
also will cover the impeachment process and ways to ensure that any
such proceedings are bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gephardt called Gingrich, who was on a dinosaur dig
in Montana, to set up the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's spokesman, Erik Smith, quoted the Missouri Democrat
as saying: ``If this process must begin, it is among the most
serious responsibilities Congress will undertake, and it must be
conducted in a truly bipartisan manner.''
</P>
<P>
   House rules call for an impeachment inquiry to be carried out by
the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been working on a report to Congress for some time,
but there is no indication he has yet notified Congress that it is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
