<HEADER>
A0327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-INFLATE-BOS &LR;      09-04 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INFLATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE ON PRIME MINISTER PUT OFF UNTIL MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As the ruble kept plunging and prices skyrocketed,
Russia backed away from the political abyss Friday after the
opposition-dominated lower house of parliament postponed its vote
on President Boris Yeltsin's candidate for prime minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   The State Duma, had appeared certain to reject Chernomyrdin,
which would have intensified a standoff with Yeltsin that has
already left the country without a working government as its
financial markets collapse and panic buying spreads.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Duma put off its vote until Monday after Yeltsin
agreed to hold talks with opposition leaders on giving them more of
a say in naming a new government.
</P>
<P>
   The move came after Chernomyrdin disclosed vague details of the
``economic dictatorship'' to save the Russian economy. The plan
involves stabilizing the ruble by linking it to Russia's hard
currency reserves, a concept similar to the ``currency board'' that
has been used to halt rapid currency devaluation in other
countries. Chernomyrdin's program also sought to improve tax
compliance and take on a long overdue strutural overhaul of
industry by declaring bankrupt any company that could not pay its
debts. But first, the government would increase its hard currency
reserves and then pump rubles into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   By expanding the money supply, Russia would be embarking on a
policy President Clinton and international lenders had warned
against, fearing it could lead to hyperinflation. Government
officials acknowledged that expanding the money supply was bound to
lead to an rapid increase in prices, but that the money was needed
to meet the goals of paying off workers and ending a nonpayment
crisis that has paralyzed the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   The idea sounded good enough to the upper house of parliament,
the Federation Council, which gave the acting premier a 91-17 vote
of confidence. The vote was non-binding, but it appeared to
convince the Duma, which has the final say on whether to confirm
Chernomyrdin, to postpone a showdown and enter negotiations with
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's author, acting Deputy Prime Minister Boris Fyodorov,
said by expanding the money supply, the government could pay off
its debts to workers, industry and investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to settle accounts with the past,'' Fyodorov said in
an interview on NTV television. ``Today we have an enormous
quantity of debts, the budget is not balanced. Everybody wants
(monetary) emission. Just look at parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   With a clean slate, Fyodorov said, the government could take on
long overdue efforts to overhaul industry and balance its budget by
improving tax compliance.
</P>
<P>
   A larger problem will be whether Chernomyrdin's government can
carry off the plan. Many observers blame Chernomyrdin, who was
prime minister for over five years until this March, for the
widespread graft and misuse of funds that contributed to Russia's
current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   For the new plan to work, Fyodorov said, Russia's hard currency
reserves would have to be increased from their current level of $12
billion, but he did not say where the money would come from. The
International Monetary Fund and other lenders backed a $22.6
billion loan to Russia in July, but the IMF has said it would delay
the next $4.3 billion tranche unless Russia undertook painful
stabilization measures.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of printing money to pay debts has long been advocated
by parliament, as well as some Western economists, who argue that
the Russian economy has been dangerously deflated in recent years
as the government fought to keep prices, and the ruble, stable.
Barter had replaced cash as the form of payment of choice, and
firms ignored their debts to each other, and to their employees.
The result was something commentators begin referring to a
``virtual economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The stable ruble disappeared on Aug. 17, when the government
announced it would no longer defend the currency. Since then, the
ruble has lost over two thirds of its value and Friday dropped to
around 19 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Prices have also shot up _ the government reported a 15 percent
increase in August. But in Moscow shops, a more vivid indicator of
the price rise could be found in such once abundant imported items
as instant coffee or diapers, which have tripled in recent days as
importers and wholesalers, wary of losing money on the rapidly
crumbling Russian currency, have halted shipments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
