<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS05-CO     09-04 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    LEADERS TO MEET WEDNESDAY AS CONGRESS PREPARES FOR STARR REPORT
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR AND CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Gearing up for possible impeachment proceedings
against President Clinton, the first order of business next week
will be a huddle between House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., over how best to
handle an impending report about the president in icy partisan
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the points of contention expected at that meeting
next Wednesday morning is an attempt by Republicans on the House
Judiciary Committee, responsible for overseeing any impeachment
inquiry of Clinton, to seek the power to hold any witness in
contempt of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That power, unprecedented for a member of Congress, would allow
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill, the right to order
the sergeant at arms to arrest and jail any potential witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal is startling,'' said Jim Jordan, spokesman for
the Democratic side of the Judiciary Committee. ``I feel certain
that Democratic members will have very grave concerns about the
assumption about the sweeping and unchecked power even by a member
as respected by Chairman Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans are balking at the notion. House Rules
Committee Chairman Jerry Solomon, R-NY, said he is resisting Hyde's
request because he does not think that any member ``ought to have
the right to lock up anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon and Hyde are now negotiating a resolution that would
give the Judiciary Committee the ability to review the charges set
forth in the much anticipated report from Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has spent more than $40 million on a wide-ranging probe of
the president, including whether Clinton committed perjury by lying
about an affair with a former White House intern and then
obstructing justice by trying to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be careful not to set an unfair precedent,'' said
Solomon, confirming that Hyde is seeking the contempt of Congress
power. Solomon said the resolution could be ready for a vote in his
committee as early as Thursday, but he added it all depended upon
when Starr delivered the report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully Mr. Starr will call us and let us know when we might
expect it,'' said Solomon, noting that Gingrich has had no hand in
discussing the impeachment process. Solomon released details of
what the resolution looks like now. Still subject to major changes,
it calls for giving the Judiciary Committee the sole jurisdiction
over handling the report, but an executive summary of the report
would be made available to all 435 members of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde supports issuing an executive summary, but he does not
favor making the entire report public out of respect to the
witnesses who were questioned before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, a member of the Judicaiary Committee,
said he believes the full report should be public: ``Here you have
the highest elected official in the United States, acting
inappropriately with the holder of one of the lowest offices in the
government, in the workplace, and the public has right to know all
the facts and the whole story and the whole truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wednesday meeting will include Hyde and John Conyers, the
ranking Democrat from Michigan, who has already complained about
the partisan nature of the panel. Gephardt located the speaker on a
dinosaur dig in Montana to ask for the meeting, ending what has
been described by aides as a testy period of their relationship as
the two most powerful members of the House.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is also the day that Starr is rumored to inform
Gingrich that he has completed his report.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report, even if it is delayed, is likely to overshadow
the work of the House and its members, most of whom were away from
Washington when Clinton made his Aug. 17 admission that he had lied
about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, the former White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   And that is a point of frustration for Georgia Democratic Rep.
John Lewis. He is concerned that the controversy will keep the
House from passing important legislation, such as the 13
appropriations bills that fund the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the Democrats who are privately saying they are on
the fence about supporting Clinton, Lewis said it was important for
the party to stand behind the president. ``You just don't go around
kicking someone when he's down,'' he said. ``We will stand together
on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Republican Rep. Bob Barr, who sits on the Judiciary
Committee, said that no business is as important as upholding the
congressional responsibility of making the president accountable
for lying to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming days, Barr said he is bracing for what will be an
increasingly partisan attack on the GOP by Democrats trying to
deflect attention from the scandal. ``I think we will see several
things: some individuals who will take a very partisan attack, but
I think most members will take a sober look at this. It's one thing
to talk theoretical about this, it's another to actually receive a
report which certifies that there is credible evidence of
violations.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, is not expected to
attend Wednesday's meeting, although he's in charge of rounding up
Republican votes. He may be excluded because, of all the Republican
leaders, he has staked out the strongest position on Clinton,
calling for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's staff members said they're feeling no backlash from
other House leaders for DeLay's stance, but they do suspect
retaliation from the White House: no White House tour passes have
been approved for DeLay's constituents since he called for the
president's job.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv disputed the complaint:
``Congressman DeLay has been attacking this president for 5 1/2
years, and during that time, he's gotten hundreds if not thousands
of his constituents through the White House. There is a process
here. When they apply for tickets late and don't get them, they
should know better than to cry politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
