<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-MECHANICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMWEST MECHANICS SENT HOME OVER SAFETY STICKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - America West Airlines sent 64 mechanics home in
Phoenix and two other cities early Friday because they refused to
remove stickers they were wearing that focus on mechanical safety
issues, according to Teamsters union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   At least 43 were ordered off the job in Phoenix, along with 17
in Las Vegas and four in Columbus, Ohio, Teamsters spokesman
Patrick Lacefield said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Mitch Barker said the
agency has assigned inspectors to oversee the dispute between
mechanics and the airline and expect it to be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   All of the mechanics will be back at work Saturday, America West
spokeswoman Patty Nowack said, adding that the company had no other
comment about the dispute with the mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   America West is eager to continue negotiations with the union
and is confident it will reach agreement, but the airline is not
going to negotiate in the newspaper, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The action to send the mechanics home came less than a day after
America West announced it had hired 100 more mechanics, increased
overnight work stations to 13 from four, and added two spare
aircraft to deal with a rash of flight delays and cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Goodmanson, America West president and chief executive
officer, cited the labor troubles Thursday in explaining a poor
on-time performance the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   The company's pilots criticized Goodmanson's comments in a
written statement Friday from Donald Steinman, chairman of the Air
Line Pilots Association unit at America West, which represents
1,500 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blaming the Teamsters for the airline's operational problems
demonstrates a genuine head-in-the sand approach to management,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments further the perception that America West is
unwilling to address the airline's operational problems, Steinman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowack said America West is ``sorry that Captain Steinman feels
this way, but he's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The stickers the mechanics were wearing point out the number of
mechanical problems that must be fixed before a plane is put back
in service. A minimum equipment list, or MEL, refers to each
mechanical problem.
</P>
<P>
   The stickers say ``MEL's (blank) and rising.'' The blank is
filled in with the number of MELs.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the stickers, Lacefield said, is to focus attention
on the high number of MELs that America West mechanics fix on
planes that have been serviced by outside contractors. The union,
representing about 450 mechanics, has been battling with America
West over outsourced mechanical work since 1995 when the company
laid off 375 mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   The graveyard-shift mechanics were planning to return to work
late Friday without the stickers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they have the right to wear the stickers, the
mechanics are not going to let the issue get in the way of their
jobs, Lacefield said, adding that it was a question of principle to
keep the stickers on late Thursday and early Friday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
