<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-PLANE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MD-11 JET HAS GOOD SAFETY RECORD, BUT SOME FLAWS THAT COULD POSE
FIRE HAZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-VICTIMS, CRASH-DITCH and
CRASH-SWISSAIR) 
(js) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The widebodied MD-11 jet designed by McDonnell
Douglas has been in service since 1990 and is widely regarded as
safe and reliable, but it has had its share of mechanical problems,
including some that posed fire hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot on Swissair Flight 111 reported smoke in the cockpit
to air traffic controllers before the jet crashed into the Atlantic
Ocean near Halifax, Nova Scotia on Wednesday night. How the fire
started, or where on the airplane it occurred, are not known.
</P>
<P>
   As with other models, there have been several instances in the
past of flaws in the MD-11 leading the manufacturer and the Federal
Aviation Administration to call for inspections, repairs or
alterations to prevent electrical short-circuits, fuel spills,
overheating or other potential fire hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these directives were sparked by reports of smoke or
fire in a plane while it was in service, or by the discovery during
maintenance of electrical wires that were chafed or charred or of
some other tell-tale sign of damage.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, FAA records show cases of smoke and fire in the
avionics compartment's floor area caused by electrical arcing from
chafed wire; a potential fire hazard from burning and arcing in
electrical contacts between a cable and a generator; smoke in a
cargo compartment during loading caused by damaged cables feeding
power into the plane while on the ground; damage to fuel conduits
in the fuselage; a malfunction in a vacuum waste exhaust heater
that could ignite surrounding insulation blankets in the cargo
liner; and several instances of chafing of various wire bundles
that posed the threat of electrical fires or smoke in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   FAA airworthiness directives are not binding on foreign airlines
unless the aviation agencies in those countries issue similar
orders. But most developed countries and large airlines, especially
those flying into the United States, comply with them.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also generally comply with safety and mechanical
recommendations from airplane manufacturers, known as alert service
bulletins, which normally form the basis for any FAA directives.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair spokesman Roland Breitler said Friday that the airline
routinely complies with all directives, even those that are not
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swissair always follows each directive,'' he told The
Associated Press. ``If we hear of a potential problem then we
immediately take action.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign airlines flying to and from airports in the United
States are required to meet international safety standards set by
the International Civil Aviation Organization, a U.N. agency,
although in some cases these rules are not identical to regulations
issued by the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The international rules are meant to provide a common level of
protection while preserving each nation's right to regulate and
inspect its own airlines. The FAA, in turn, reviews each foreign
nation's enforcement practices before allowing airlines from that
country to operate here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   However, many important safety regulations issued by the FAA
apply to all airlines operating in this country, agency officials
said. Among these are rules governing hazardous cargo, including
materials that might cause fires.
</P>
<P>
   After oxygen generators carried in the cargo hold of a Valujet
Airlines DC-9 in Florida in 1996 started a fire that caused the
plane to crash, killing all 110 people on board, the FAA issued a
regulation prohibiting both foreign and domestic airlines from
transporting them on passenger flights with at least one stop in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the FAA disclosed that both domestic and foreign
airlines may have unwittingly violated the rules.
</P>
<P>
   After Boeing acquired the manufacturer in 1990, it announced
that it would stop making the three-engined MD-11, which is a
larger and more efficient variant of the DC-10, in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Swissair plane that crashed was 7 years old and had flown
35,000 miles on 6,400 flights.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Transportation Safety Board, there
have been several accidents involving MD-11s. But the planes'
safety record is not significantly better or worse than other
models in widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge slats on the wings of a China Eastern Airlines
plane deployed improperly in 1993, causing the plane to buck
violently in the air over Alaska. There were several dozen injuries
and two people died in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   A fire on an American Airlines MD-11 at New York's Kennedy
Airport in 1995 forced an evacuation of the plane, injuring two.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a Federal Express cargo plane crashed, flipped over,
and burned at Newark International Airport during landing. The two
pilots and three crew members survived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
