u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     09-04 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVOTNA HEATS UP OPEN WITH WIN OVER TESTUD  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Beguilingly, the man said to Jana Novotna, ``Come up
to my castle and see me sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the man was Vaclav Havel, president of the Czech Republic
_ and leader of the movement that junked the country's Communism in
the Velvet Revolution of 1990 _ Novotna didn't have to be asked
twice. You don't get invited to a castle every day by a historic
figure.
</P>
<P>
   But Novotna is a historic figure herself: the lone righthanded
Czech female to give away the Wimbledon championship (twice) and
then decide that charity begins at home when she seized it two
months ago. Abruptly, she was the prodigal daughter-with-volley,
the kind of person presidents wish to coopt in a photo op while
everybody else coos, ``Welcome home _ all is forgiven!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt such a warm welcome coming back to Prague in all
those years (13 as a pro) that I've been playing tennis, even
though I've won big tournaments _ the (season-ending) Chase
Championship at Madison Square Garden last year. I just felt
enormous warmth from everybody,'' Novotna said Friday after a 6-2,
6-3, win over France's Sandrine Testud landed her among the US
Open's last sweet and sweltering 16.
</P>
<P>
   That is how dethroning Martina Hingis in the Wimbledon
semifinals and then flattening Nathalie Tauziat for the title
changed Novotna's life. ``Changed it in a way that I'm just feeling
incredibly relieved ... just happy over what I've achieved ... but
nevertheless, this kind of achievement pushes me to work harder, go
for more.''
</P>
<P>
   If Milan Kundera, the Czech author, wants to do her book, he'll
probably call it ``The Incredible Lightness of Being No Longer
Considered a Choker.''
</P>
<P>
   The Czechs, with their dreary history of being overrun by one
oppressor or another, most recently Germans and Russians, tend to
be pessimistic, and Novotna, despite many stellar achievements,
gave them numerous opportunities to indulge in an American
specialty: the CWBO hoot _ Can't Win Big Ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the same in our country as yours,'' said Czech
journalist Blanka Rokosova of Radio Europa 2. ``Jana came so close
to Steffi Graf in 1993 (4-1, 40-30 in the third) and Hingis in 1997
(2-0 in the third) but couldn't make it. Nobody believed she would
win when the third final came around. Nobody. She was the kind of
person we call maly clovek _ the little person who can't do the big
job. Not now.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't like the days of the historic lefthanded Czech
female, Martina Navratilova. She won so many Wimbledons that she
could have held a clearance sale on trophies. She was Can't Lose
Big Ones. But she could have gotten more warmth from a birthday
cake than the homeland. As a 1975 defector, Navratilova won
classification as a nonperson where she grew up. If Moscow's
stooges who ran Czechoslovakia had lured her to Prague Castle, it
would have been to throw a dungeon party for her, complete with leg
irons.
</P>
<P>
   Havel was a better host at the ancient castle that looms on a
crag above the capital city. Tea was served, but without hemlock.
The only cuffs were on his shirt. The country was genuinely proud
of Novotna. You could see it in her animated blue eyes and toothy
grin, the way her straight platinum tresses swished as she recalled
her own Velvet Visit and deliverance from the shackles of CWBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Havel doesn't know much about sports, but he was very kind,
complimentary. He's very pleased, like the rest of us about what a
wonderful year in sports this is for our country. First it was Petr
Korda winning the Australian Open. Then the Olympic gold medal in
hockey. Then,'' she smiled, ``me.''
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the year she's the queen on both sides of the East
River, following up her November Chase triumph in Manhattan by
crushing at Flushing?
</P>
<P>
   Winner of 25 of her last 27 matches (titles at Prague,
Eastbourne, and the Big W), Jana said, ``One enormous dream has
come true for me, but I'm still hungry for another. I was so
pleased with my forehand and net game at Wimbledon, and everything
is still together.''
</P>
<P>
   Her fans hope it stays together because nobody in this town is
better to watch. Novotna plays in daring, headlong rushes, volleys
like a laser lady, and springs toward the clouds to clout
spectacular backhand overheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if I hadn't won Wimbledon this time, I might have said
someday that I missed my chance. It's a relief that won't happen.
But I didn't worry about it this year. I was still confident. I
didn't think I was too old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interesting now, after winning, I see more respect from my
opponents. I see it on their faces. That's nice. I'm enjoying
myself more on the court. I'm more mature.''
</P>
<P>
   It is very good to see the occasional mature woman around this
nursery school. Novotna will be 30 next month, which makes her seem
like Madeleine Albright or Katharine Hepburn to the mean teens
trying to take over. Can't you hear Anna Kournikova screeching,
``Thirty! Shouldn't we chip in to send her to a nursing home?''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, kid. Just watch out for Jana's chip-and-charge. There's
still room for a woman amid the Open children's crusade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
