<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SORRY-BOS &LR;      09-04 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SORRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS APOLOGY   FOR `INDEFENSIBLE' ACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, facing a rebuke from a key
Democratic senator back home, offered _ and then repeated _ his
first explicit apology Friday for his adulterous affair with former
White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky, and termed his actions
``indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   In another awkward moment played out on an international stage,
Clinton stood beside Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern at what was
designed to be a triumphant photo opportunity. Instead, he found
himself peppered with questions over his Lewinsky affair, this time
fueled from within his own party by the strong indictment Thursday
by Senator Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I) basically agree with what he said,'' Clinton said through
a thin smile, standing in the prime minister's office in Dublin.
``I've already said that I made a bad mistake, it was indefensible,
and I'm sorry about it. So I have nothing else to say except that I
can't disagree with anyone else who wants to be critical of what I
have already acknowledged was indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, Clinton added: ``There's nothing that he or
anyone else could say in a personally critical way that I don't
imagine that I would disagree with, since I have already said it
myself, to myself. And I'm very sorry about it. There's nothing
else I could say.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said Friday he was ``grateful'' that the president had
accepted his criticism. But it was far from clear whether the
Clinton's statement would be enough to halt the effort by some in
Congress to vote to censure or impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, White House officials had actually been bracing for
Lieberman to call for a censure, which he stopped short of doing in
his speech.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Democrats, including Lieberman, said they were
waiting to see the report from independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr
before deciding whether to back a congressional vote for censure,
which amounts to a formal reprimand, but does not include any
specific punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments Friday came as part of what appears to be a
steadily rising level of remorse felt by the president, all in the
face of rising outrage for his actions within the political
community and the public at large. In his first admission, on Aug.
17, the president appeared defiant during a four-minute televised
address, challenging Starr to finish his investigation and telling
the public that his affair was private, between himself and his
family and their god.
</P>
<P>
   In Martha's Vineyard, in a complexly worded speech to a
gathering of civil rights activists on Aug. 28, Clinton struck a
softer tone, talking in more depth about offering forgiveness,
presumably to Starr, and being forgiven by the public.
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the first time Clinton explicitly used the term
``I'm sorry,'' though some White House aides insisted that an
apology was what he meant all along, and thought he was giving. For
more than two weeks, even some of Clinton's closest allies in
Washington were urging him to offer the apology and strike a less
defiant tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that he believes his tone has been consistent on this,
but it's been interpreted differently and variously by other people
commenting on it,'' said Michael McCurry, the White House press
secretary. ``I think he believes what he said today is consistent
with how he's addressed it in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a briefing with reporters in Dublin about the timing of
the president's apology, McCurry tersely replied, ``I think he said
he's sorry because he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sequence appeared remarkable. Thursday afternoon,
Lieberman took to the Senate floor to deliver a scathing speech
that the White House had been trying to postpone for days. With
several Democratic colleagues sitting in the chamber to lend
support, Lieberman was as critical of Clinton as nearly any
Republican who has spoken out in the last several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to ignore the impact of the misconduct the
president has admitted to on our children, our culture and our
national character,'' he said, adding later that Clinton had
``compromised his moral authority.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was especially stinging because of the nature of the
relationship between Lieberman and Clinton. Lieberman, a moderate
voice of moral authority, is considered a bellweather member of the
Senate, a lawmaker to whom others often look for guidance on
sensitive votes. In his second term, he is also cut from the same
political ideology as Clinton, and even succeeded Clinton as head
of the Democratic Leadership Council, a group that espouses
moderate strategies.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, his speech triggered alarms within the White
House, where there is a growing sentiment that Clinton faces at
least a censure over his affair with Lewinsky and subsequent seven
months of lies, and possibly worse, depending on what Starr
concludes in a report that may be issued to the Congress as early
as this month.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry Friday again dismissed any notion that Clinton is
contemplating his resignation. ``None whatsoever,'' he said when
asked by a reporter if Clinton had discussed the possibility with
advisers or allies.
</P>
<P>
   The apology Friday, combined with Lieberman's floor speech
Thursday, put a smudge across what was supposed to be a victorious
tour, one that took him from the province of Northern Ireland down
to the republic in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had one of his best days in recent memory Thursday,
hailed as an architect of peace at every stop. But by day's end,
much of the good feelings were washed away as aides watched
Lieberman take to the floor in the late afternoon and deliver his
devastating speech.
</P>
<P>
   For days, Clinton's most senior advisers had been trying to
persuade Lieberman to hold off on the speech until the president
returned to the United States over the weekend, White House
officials said. Clinton himself talked to Lieberman on Aug. 27,
days before flying off to Moscow for a two-day summit, imploring
him to delay the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had asked Lieberman not to say anything until after the
president left Russia, according to a source familiar with the
conversation. Lieberman agreed to wait, which led to an agonizing
five days for the senator and many drafts of his Senate floor
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman seriously considered calling for a formal censure of
Clinton, the source said, but he decided to delete such a proposal,
bowing to pressure that he wait until there is a chance to review
the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles also called Lieberman
throughout the week and asked him to wait to speak until the
president arrived back in the US, according to McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Mr. Bowles inquired whether or not Senator
Lieberman could hold off until the president was back home on US
soil,'' McCurry said. ``But the president didn't take any issue, as
you know, with Senator Lieberman's statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Clinton was said to be furious that Lieberman would
deliver the speech while Clinton was abroad and mar what Clinton
was hoping would be a triumphant day that would garner him positive
news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, he did not seem as bothered. Friday night, on a short
flight from Dublin to Limerick, where he plans to play golf
Saturday at the hallowed Ballybunion links course, Clinton relaxed
with reporters in the press cabin and compared the current trip to
Ireland with his 1995 visit, when 100,000 people turned out in
Belfast to hear him speak of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so excited last time I was here, but I loved this,'' he
said, wearing a green sweater acquired in Ireland. ``I had a
wonderful time.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his golf game, Clinton said: ``I'll be lucky if I don't lose
a dozen balls. ... I'm going to be glad to get through it. I'll
just have fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the day Friday, Clinton rededicated himself to his
Ireland triumph, meeting with Ahern in the morning, then delivering
a speech at the European facility of Gateway Computers lauding the
booming Irish economy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, back home, Democrats were worried that Lieberman's speech
_ and Clinton's acceptance of it _ will lead to a parade of party
members taking to the floor of the House and Senate to condemn
Clinton. Republicans will be even more likely to follow Lieberman's
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is bad,'' a congressional Democratic official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Lieberman has laid the
foundation and I'm afraid we're going to have a ton of Democrats
come back and feel obligated to repeat that exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Brian McGrory contributed from Ireland, Michael Kranish from
Washington).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
