<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LATE RALLY, DOW ENDS A BAD WEEK 5.1 PERCENT LOWER
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market again flirted with the bears Friday,
as the Dow Jones industrial average fell below where it closed on
Monday, the day of a 512-point plunge that shook up investors
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last half-hour, the Dow and other market measures
recovered, cutting their losses by two-thirds and more. Still, the
Dow was off 5.1 percent for the week and gave up most of Tuesday's
288-point rally. And with the 5.7 percent decline of the week
before, the Dow had its worst 10 consecutive trading days since the
two weeks before the stock market crash of 1987, according to
Birinyi Associates.
</P>
<P>
   And as investors left for the Labor Day weekend, they were still
haunted by the same problems: Russia, Asia, Latin America and their
impact on American corporate earnings. Estimates for third-quarter
profit growth show an expected 2 percent average gain from the
quarter a year earlier, down from 10 percent just two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   There was more bad news on this front as the week came to an
end. A major rating agency, Moody's Investors Service, downgraded
Brazil's credit rating Thursday, a move that led to a 6.13 percent
selloff in the Sao Paolo stock market Friday. There appears to be
no resolution in sight as to who is running Russia. And many
investors are getting more worried about the future for Latin
America, which is a market for about 15 percent of America's
exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me the most about this market is that
we don't know what all the problems are and we are not sure where
the ripples end,'' said Lazlo Birinyi of Birinyi Associates, which
manages money and tracks the market from Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a centipede market,'' he added. ``First one shoe drops,
then another and then another.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's modest selloff came amid signs that investors, on a net
basis, may have pulled money out of American stock mutual funds in
August, the first such negative flow since 1990. AMG Data Services
reported that there have been outflows for the last two weeks and
that the four-week moving average of flows is just barely positive.
Trim Tabs, another monitor of mutual fund flows, estimates that
there was an outflow of $1 billion from U.S. equity funds in
August.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which fell as much as 186 points Friday, closed down
41.97 points, or five-tenths of 1 percent, at 7,640.25. It is now
down 3.4 percent for the year. The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's index
of 500 stocks fell as much as 25.75 points, but ended down just
8.37 points, 0.9 percent, at 973.89. It is up 0.4 percent for the
year. The Nasdaq index, which is dominated by technology stocks,
dropped 5.34 points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,566.52. It was down 28
points earlier and is now off 0.2 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Small company stocks, which have been among the hardest hit this
year, rallied a little, with the Russell index of 2,000 smaller
company stocks rising 0.78 point, or 0.2 percent, to 347.07. It is
down 20.6 percent for the year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bank and other financial stocks continued to lead the market
lower, in part because of the fear that banks could be hit by much
greater losses if the financial crisis that began in July of last
year in Asia fully engulfs Latin America. ``The performance of the
financial stocks is a clear sign that there is a lot of risk out
there,'' said Douglas Cliggot, a U.S. equity strategist at J.P.
Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Citicorp, which had losses of about $200 million
related to Russia, fell 6, to 92{, and is off 31 percent in the
last two weeks. Chase Manhattan Bank, which expects $200 million in
losses because of Russia and Asia, was down 3~, to 45], and is down
29 percent in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Clark, the head of U.S. equity trading at Credit Suisse
First Boston, said that the rally in the last half-hour might have
been sparked by speculation over a pending dinner meeting in San
Francisco of Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan and Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa. ``The chatter was that there could be some good news over
the weekend,'' Clark said.
</P>
</TEXT>
