<HEADER>
A0356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORPUS-CHRISTI-TOURIS     09-04 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPUS-CHRISTI-TOURISM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPUS CHRISTI METHODICALLY BUILDS A TOURIST INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add graphics note; no other changes)  (ART ADV: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ The world surely is wide enough to hold
a few more tourist attractions, and this city of 400,000 people has
tried mightily to fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? After all, other U.S. cities have fashioned
successful tourist industries by virtue of natural setting, vision
or sometimes good luck.
</P>
<P>
   These include Branson, Mo., a year-round country music capital;
Tunica, Miss., a town that is climbing out of rank poverty with
glitzy hotels and glitzier gambling casinos; and such shopping
meccas as Potomac Mills outlet mall in Dale City, Va., which draws
more tourists than Colonial Williamsburg. Then there is Newport,
Ore., where the arrival of Keiko the whale (of ``Free Willy'' fame)
has attracted an additional 1 million visitors to the Oregon Coast
Aquarium and has the town's 9,000 residents pondering what will
become of its multimillion-dollar tourist industry after Keiko is
returned to a sea pen in its native Iceland on Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   But Corpus Christi, a socially conservative and heavily Hispanic
city, has few spectacular natural assets or claims to fame.
Instead, it has gone about its pursuit of tourism in a methodical
manner, investing millions to try to overcome some difficult
strokes of geographical misfortune. And success is already evident
in the rising number of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't ever expect to become another Orlando or Las Vegas,
because we understand what kind of tourist destination we are _
primarily a beach town,'' said Mike Crouch, director of public
affairs for the Business Alliance. ``But we hope to attract lots
more tourists and convention delegates and have them stay longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Known mostly for its oil industry, which fell on hard times
starting in the late 1980s, the city is tucked within a lovely bay
behind Padre Island on the Gulf of Mexico, way down in southeast
Texas, more than 200 miles from Houston and almost 400 miles from
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   As a former tourist official said, ``You don't get to Corpus
Christi by accident, you have to work at getting here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most air service to and from the city is on regional carriers,
and nonstops to other states are nonexistent. Even a flight to El
Paso, for example, 720 road miles away, typically takes four to six
hours, depending on connections and stops.
</P>
<P>
   Though a number of Corpus Christi hotels and attractions are
worth bragging about _ one is a life-size statue of Selena
Quintanilla Perez, 23, the Queen of Tejano, or Texas-Mexican
borderland music, who was shot dead by her fan club president in
1995 _ they are a far cry from the snazzy theme parks or casinos
that pack in the crowds elsewhere. Thus, the great bulk of Corpus
Christi tourists are still likely to come from within a 150-mile
radius.
</P>
<P>
   With its large Hispanic population and proximity to Mexico,
Corpus Christi is especially determined to attract a larger share
of the 3 million Mexican tourists and convention delegates who
spent almost $900 million in the state last year.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that city officials in set about building a
tourist industry that did more than attract penny-pinching college
students on spring break or day-trippers to its many beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Dead set against the ``build it and they'll come'' mentality,
Corpus Christi officials have been careful to order economic impact
studies before plunking down a dime to buy attractions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the go-ahead for a $33 million aquarium, which
opened in 1990, was given only after studies projected that it
would make money _ and after a look at the success of Baltimore's
aquarium and Inner Harbor. Averaging about 440,000 visitors a year,
the aquarium is now credited with adding $50 million a year to
Corpus Christi's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The city also shelled out $4.1 million for the World War II
aircraft carrier USS Lexington after spirited bidding with Quincy,
Mass., and Mobile, Ala. But first the city received reassurance
from Debbie Prost, head of what is now Prost Marketing Inc., a San
Antonio consulting firm, that the ship would draw far more than the
270,000 visitors a year needed to break even.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, officials also studied the success of six other
cities that had former Navy ships as tourist sites. Since opening
in October 1992, the Lexington has averaged almost 350,000 visitors
a year and has contributed $62 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The ship and the aquarium have also spruced up North Beach, a
section of the city that was badly damaged in a hurricane in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I grew up in this city,'' said Frank Stanford of College
Station, Texas, ``North Beach was infested with drugs and crime.
But as you can see, today it's filled with families.'' Stanford was
showing Corpus Christi's attractions to a friend, Diane Havalda of
Austin. As he spoke, lots of children scampered around the
aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million Greyhound Race Track, opened in 1990 and owned
by a Florida corporation that was able to qualify for certain tax
rebates available under a state enterprise zone, continues to
attract many out-of-staters who spend the winter months in Texas.
But the track has been overshadowed somewhat since the state
lottery began in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The only sizable investment that has not lived up to promise is
the $1.1 million paid to Spain for the right to operate and manage
replicas of the Nina, Pinta and Santa Maria, the fleet that
Columbus sailed to the New World more than 500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fleet has attracted 650,000 paying customers since
opening five years ago, the Pinta and the Santa Maria were damaged
in 1994, when a tow cable snapped and a barge crashed into them.
Repairs by Spanish shipwrights were completed only this summer.
</P>
<P>
   A small zoo and a botanical garden have recently been added to
Corpus Christi's tourism mix, the Asian Cultures Museum moved into
a new building, and the Museum of Science and History was
extensively remodeled and expanded.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As a result of all these efforts, the number of visitors grew to
5.5 million in 1997, from fewer than 2.3 million in 1986 _ a 139
percent increase during a time when total U.S. tourism grew about
89 percent. Hotel room revenues doubled, to $100.4 million.
Tourism-related jobs also doubled, to 10,200, and the
tourism-related payroll almost tripled, to $152 million. The
average visitor's stay, which had never been more than a day, grew
to 2.5 days.
</P>
<P>
   The Convention Center in Bayfront Plaza booked 151,679
convention delegates in 1996, the last year for those figures
available, a 60 percent increase over 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the growth, Corpus Christi doesn't approach the
number of visitors to Orlando, Fla. (35.6 million in 1996), Las
Vegas (30.5 million) or even San Antonio, which recorded 7 million
visitors last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, not all the improvements, including the trendy
restaurants, sleek office buildings and modern hotels along the
two-mile-long white waterfront seawall and walkway, are a result of
tourism. The petrochemical industry, for example, pumps more than
$1 billion into the local economy, while the city's growing health
care services employ about 24,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   It was the collapse of Corpus Christi's decades-long dependence
on gas and oil that sent the city reeling when the price of
domestic oil plummeted from $40 a barrel in 1980 to $10 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1986, unemployment reached a decade-high of 12.2 percent,
and we lost 5,000 jobs in the oil and gas exploration industry,''
said Gary Bushell, president of the Greater Corpus Christi Business
Alliance. Just between 1986 and 1988, hotel revenues fell from
$45.5 million to $38.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pruet, a small business owner, former city councilman and
chairman of the business alliance's tourism committee, said: ``For
almost 100 years oil and gas provided our tax base, funded our
schools and created our jobs. Every big oil company was here. But
when oil went down the chute, they just abandoned those offices and
pulled out. When it was agreed to really go after tourists, we knew
we had to go beyond just T-shirts and kids on the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism indeed remains at the forefront of Corpus Christi's
effort to make a name for itself while adding jobs and earning
money.
</P>
<P>
   While hoping (and lobbying) to attract cruise ships, the city
has formed a partnership with San Antonio whereby cruise passengers
can also fly to that mission city before or after their cruise, to
visit the Alamo or the city's acclaimed River Walk.
</P>
<P>
   It has also established a tourism and trade office in Monterrey,
Mexico, together with its Texas neighbor, Loredo, and the Port of
Corpus Christi, the nation's sixth-largest port.
</P>
<P>
   A big drawing card for Mexican and Mexican-American tourists is
the Selena statue. In the middle of the nine seawall pavilions
along Ocean Drive, the bronze statue continues to attract legions
of fans, young and old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came mostly for the beach,'' said Roberto Leal of
Monterrey, on his first visit here recently with two related
families that together consisted of 10 adults and 12 children.
``But we don't want to go home without seeing the aquarium and the
memorial to Selena.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
