<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-MOVIE-LADN     09-04 1499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBS AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS and GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Another summer movie season comes to a close this
weekend. But it wasn't just another season of summer movies; the
hot-weather months of 1998 were marked by, surprisingly enough, a
few good films.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the usual batch of noisy, overproduced brain-melters,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was enough to make Daily News film critics Bob Strauss
and Glenn Whipp happy to spend much of the past four months inside
darkened theaters (and lots of other folks, too; this year's summer
box office is expected to hit a record $2.5 billion).
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, at least from Bob and Glenn's points of view, there
was something worth talking about for a change when the time came
to assess the summer films of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Whipp: I can't remember a better summer movie slate than
what we had this year, although I don't think it has dawned on most
people just how good the past few months have been.
</P>
<P>
   I was talking to a woman before a screening last week and she
grumbled, ``Another terrible summer.'' And I said, ``What are you
talking about?'' and started ticking off all the good movies. She
considered what I said, paused for a moment and then muttered,
``Yeah. I guess you're right. But there were some bad ones, too.''
It's like people are so programmed to expect junk this time of
year, they haven't realized that the summer of '98 contained some
wonderful exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Strauss: Well, there was ``The Avengers.'' But yeah, in
general _ and I never thought I'd say this _ I don't want summer to
end.
</P>
<P>
   I usually spend this time of year splitting thin hairs over
which soulless, mind-numbing product had the best special effects
or one-liners with a passable resemblance to wit. But this time,
Hollywood released two great films, ``The Truman Show'' and
``Saving Private Ryan,'' which is two more than the decade summer
average.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't all. ``Mulan,'' ``Mask of Zorro'' and ``Out of
Sight'' were unusually smart, well-crafted and distinctive
entertainments. And the studios _ well, one studio, Fox _ actually
released two full-blown assaults on movie complacency, ``Bulworth''
and ``There's Something About Mary.'' Rude, subversive ``Mary''
even turned out to be the most tenacious and profitable hit of the
year, which should encourage others to break some rules.
</P>
<P>
   Whipp: It's just too bad more people didn't turn out for
``Bulworth'' and ``Out of Sight.'' It's hard to blame audiences
though, since there were so many decent movies from which to
choose. Even the second tier of films, movies like ``Ever After,''
``The Horse Whisperer'' and ``The X-Files'' had their pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   And movies you knew were going to stink _ ``Armageddon'' and
``Godzilla'' _ still couldn't hold a candle to the horrific duds we
endured last year. I'd see ``Godzilla'' again before suffering
through a repeat performance of ``Batman &AMP; Robin'' or ``Speed 2.''
``The Avengers'' ... well, at least it had Uma Thurman in leather.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss: So do my dreams, and they're more coherent. Let's not
get too Pollyannish here: This summer, like all summers, was lousy
with listlessly squandered millions.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, things got off to the most dreadful start in memory
last May. ``Deep Impact'' _ which was just as dumb as
``Armageddon,'' but didn't possess the saving grace of knowing it _
was a dishearteningly huge hit, ``Hope Floats'' was pure emotional
pablum, ``Almost Heroes'' put the final nail in Chris Farley's
reputation as a comic, and ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas'' _
perhaps the most unpleasant movie experience of the '90s _ proved
that it isn't enough just to break the rules. You have to know what
you're breaking rules for.
</P>
<P>
   And the bad big movies kept on coming: ``Six Days, Seven
Nights'' (Harrison, give up on the romantic comedies already), ``A
Perfect Murder'' (if this is what Hitchcock remakes look like, I'm
very afraid of the upcoming ``Psycho''), ``Small Soldiers''
(director Joe Dante's lower-tech ``Gremlins'' films were funnier
and more anarchic), and every alleged ``outrageous'' comedy that
didn't involve a dog in a body cast.
</P>
<P>
   Whipp: Geez ... and you left out ``Dirty Work,'' ``Disturbing
Behavior,'' ``Snake Eyes,'' ``54'' and ``Air Bud: Golden
Receiver.'' Maybe it was a god-awful summer after all.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe there are just too many movies. Audiences seem
to think so. Most of the stinkers we've mentioned were roundly
ignored. And the event films, which were shoved down our throats by
fanatical studio marketing departments, typically had one good
weekend and then died. More people remember ``Godzilla's'' ad
slogan _ ``Size Matters'' _ than they do the movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice little trend, this apathy, and one that's been
building for the past few years. Audiences are tired of filmmakers
pandering to them, so they're embracing movies like ``Saving
Private Ryan'' and ``The Truman Show'' almost as an act of
defiance. It's like they're telling Hollywood: We're not as stupid
as you think we are. We can handle challenging topics. And, guess
what? We'd like to see more of them.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss: As long as Hollywood keeps the talking-animal movies
coming, anyway. I wouldn't get too optimistic; pap still sells,
like ``Dr. Dolittle,'' ``The Parent Trap,'' ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and
the space-junk movies proved. And we know that next summer is going
to be all about ``Star Wars'' again.
</P>
<P>
   But yeah, if this summer proved anything, it was that
challenging subjects of all stripes _ graphically realistic war
violence, astute social satire, inspired gross-out lunacy _ can be
as rewarding as they are refreshing. Let's just hope it wasn't a
fluke, like the handful of decent summer movie seasons since the
late '70s have been.
</P>
<P>
   Whipp: And there's a disturbing mind-set going around town right
about now that would seem to indicate that this year could well be
an anomaly. The summer has produced a lot of decent hits for almost
every studio _ hapless Universal being the exception _ but nobody
seems happy. The hits weren't big enough. There were no
``Titanics.'' No ``Lion Kings.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest to find that magical common denominator hasn't
changed, nor will it ever. If anything _ and this is truly
frightening _ the audience erosion for blast-'em-up effects movies
could give us more films that combine explosions and feelings (as
in whoa-oh-oh feelings), a la ``Titanic'' and ``Deep Impact.''
Martial arts heroes will be diagnosed with cancer. Space jockeys
will come down with a fear of flying. That sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss: I'm very afraid. But then, that's why we have indie
films. And at least this summer, they behaved, more or less, like
indies should. They presented truly unique, dangerous visions
rather than masquerading glorified sitcoms _ like ``Shall We
Dance'' and ``The Full Monty'' last summer _ as art films.
</P>
<P>
   Strong stuff like ``High Art,'' ``Buffalo 66,'' ``Pi'' and
``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' certainly wasn't for all tastes, but
the point is that those films weren't trying to be, and they made
summer moviegoing richer and more exciting in the bargain. And
except for maybe ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' the stuff the indies
tried to make more like studio fare _ ``The Governess,'' ``Polish
Wedding,'' ``Cousin Bette'' _ didn't leave much of an impression.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lesson there somewhere. But I doubt it's going to stop
visions of ``Monty''-size profits from dancing through independent
distributors' future summer fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Whipp: That's the thing that really grates on me about some of
these indies. They make these movies about eccentrics _ ``Polish
Wedding,'' ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' being the prime recent
offenders _ and then burnish the edges of the characters and turn
them into these lovable kooks who try so hard to be adorable that
they annoy the hell out of you.
</P>
<P>
   I'd much rather watch amoral types like Jason Patric's
fetus-tossing doctor in ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' and Christina
Ricci's unapologetic Lolita in ``The Opposite of Sex.'' No lessons.
No hugging. And unlike the adorable oddballs, you don't feel like
the characters are going to be marketed as plush teddy bears any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss: Perhaps most encouragingly, merchandisers are going to
think hard before signing on to the next batch of movie monster
toys, too. ``Godzilla's'' disappointing performance may prove to be
as healthy for summer movies as ``Ryan,'' ``Truman'' and ``Mary's''
success. It demolished the conventional wisdom that, as long as a
movie lends itself to cross-marketing fast food and junky kiddie
merchandise, it was everything a summer blockbuster should be.
</P>
<P>
   This summer proved that formula is no longer reliable and that
movies should be designed as movies, not promotional events. And
that making the best film you can is, at least to some degree, a
factor again.
</P>
<P>
   What a shock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
