<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-SOCIETY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITY'S $100,000 STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Put a star on the sidewalk, and they will come.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's always worked for Hollywood, so the Thalians, a
philanthropic group formed by actress/singer/entertainer Debbie
Reynolds to support the Cedars-Sinai Mental Health Center figured
it would work for them. And it did.
</P>
<P>
   They offered a big pink and gold star that looks a lot like the
Hollywood version to anybody donating $100,000 or more, and several
people jumped at the chance. To honor them and unveil the new
star-studded Walk of Stars in front of the Los Angeles medical
building, the Thalians threw a street party.
</P>
<P>
   It was miserably hot, but hundreds of guests turned out in their
Sunday-afternoon best, which ranged from Robert Wagner's natty blue
blazer with a red pocket square, yellow tie and gray slacks, to
Ruta Lee's peach floral tea dress with picture hat. The pair were
the stars of the program but made sure we didn't forget Reynolds by
walking down the stairs with a life-sized cutout of her in a snazzy
red cocktail dress. Wagner told the crowd that he knew Reynolds was
really sorry she couldn't be there in person (she's working in
Alaska), because she's dedicated 43 years of her life to helping
disturbed children. ``The Thalians is her favorite _ and her only _
charity,'' he said, accepting an award on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Other honorees included donors-turned-sidewalk celebrities Donna
and John Crean, Kem Dibbs, John and Gloria Gebbia, Cynthia and Hal
Gershman, Linda Tallen and David Paul Kane, Sandra Krause, Paula
Kent Meehan, Margie and Robert Petersen, and Lee and the late Mitzi
Hughes. The latter bequeathed more than $1 million to the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was the block party hostess, hopes for more stars so
the Walk of Stars will eventually wrap around the block. And
they'll take most anything, she says, including credit cards,
checks, cash, blood, diamonds, Rolex watches and real estate.
Honest.
</P>
<P>
   After the sidewalk ceremony, we danced to the music of Art Deco
and his Society Orchestra and feasted on a sunset supper of
chicken, salmon, Caesar salad and decadent bite-sized pastries
prepared by Sandy Krause and Crustacean restaurant. Then event
chairman Phyllis Friedman handed out souvenir T-shirts and lapel
pins.
</P>
<P>
   Among the celebrity guests were former PlaymateBarbi Benton, who
was there with gal pal attorney Gloria Allred. ``I flew in from
Sacramento just for this event, and it's even hotter there,''
Benton said.
</P>
<P>
   For those wondering how she looks these days, she's still a 10.
At least in her simple but figure-revealing navy blue bodysuit. And
Allred? She went for the sweater-girl look in spite of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The next Thalians event is a black-tie gala on Oct. 17 honoring
actress Sally Field, who's the proud mom of Peter Craig, a newly
published author of ``The Martini Shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Group of Los Angeles threw a soiree Thursday night at
Lola's Martini Lounge and Restaurant in West Hollywood. It's one of
those chichi places with leopard print accents where the
cutting-edge crowd goes to see and be seen while sipping those
trendy pink Cosmopolitan cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, nobody drinks white wine anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But they still eat pizza and saucer-sized cookies at Lola's.
</P>
<P>
   After the feeding frenzy and obligatory schmoozing, Fashion
Group director Kelly Bevan-Spire (she's also the fashion director
for Saks Fifth Avenue) introduced the guests of honor, California
Designer of the Year Janice Levin-Krok and her sister Diane Levin,
who's the CEO of their company called Poleci. They gave us a
preview of their new spring '99 collection and the scoop on their
hot company.
</P>
<P>
   According to Diane, ``We began by working out of our apartment
and wrapping garments in plastic bags from the dry cleaners.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously that was a long time ago, as their designs are now
sold around the world, including Africa and Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
