<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SWISSAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISSAIR STILL WINNING PRAISE FOR SAFETY, EFFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-VICTIMS, CRASH-DITCH and
CRASH-PLANE) 
(jw) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both the airline and the aircraft involved in Wednesday night's
Swissair crash have solid safety records, aviation experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you have heard about the Swiss, you can apply to
Swissair,'' said Stuart Matthews of the Flight Safety Institute, a
nonprofit group based in Arlington, Va., that monitors safety
issues. ``It is known throughout the industry for meticulous care
and the quality of its maintenance and its crews.''
</P>
<P>
   Aviation experts and analysts who follow the industry said
Friday that Swissair is considered one of the world's top airlines,
particularly in the maintenance of its fleet of 62 aircraft. In an
industry that often uses planes for many years _ replacing parts
and overhauling entire aircraft _ Swissair is known for the
relative youth of its airplanes. Its maintenance procedures are so
well regarded that the company makes an unusually large amount of
money by selling its used aircraft to other airlines, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stems from their high standard of maintenance,'' said
Kevin Murphy, an airlines analyst with Morgan Stanley. ``They
maintain the aircraft rigorously. I would be surprised if this
incident is related to a maintenance problem or an engine
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The type of plane that crashed on Wednesday, a McDonnell Douglas
MD-11, is also considered reliable. The only other major accident
involving the craft occurred when a Federal Express jet landing at
Newark International Airport bounced, rolled and caught fire in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   While Swissair received praise from industry experts for its
maintenance record, it has also been credited for its quick
reaction to Wednesday's disaster, both by arranging to fly family
members to the crash scene and by offering immediate financial
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair's last fatal accident was in 1979, when a DC-8 landing
in Athens overshot the runway. The plane caught fire, and 14 people
aboard were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's crash is the company's worst disaster since it was
founded in 1931. The company, born from the merger of two small
regional airlines, has worked to maintain its position in the
increasingly competitive market of European air carriers. Swissair
is much smaller than many of the other established European
airlines, such as British Airways, Air France and Lufthansa. The
Swiss carrier also has had to overcome the fact that Switzerland is
not a member of the European Union, which makes competing in Europe
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Like other European carriers, Swissair has faced an increasingly
competitive business environment as governments decrease
regulations and airlines struggle for passengers in an area packed
with major airports. The company has already taken some steps to
cut costs and increase efficiency, closing nonproductive hubs and
making personnel changes. It has also sought to make alliances with
other airlines to expand its customer base.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company hired an airline executive from the
United States to run its daily operations. Jeffrey Katz, a former
American Airlines executive, was original named chief operating
officer and then promoted to chief executive. While some analysts
said it is not unheard of for airlines, including American
carriers, to hire foreign chief executives, others said the company
was trying to bring in experience from the deregulated U.S. market.
The theory, analysts said, was that an executive who could survive
in the cutthroat world of American airline competition would be
better able to guide the company as Europe became more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are responding to the exigencies of the market,'' Murphy
said. ``You get somebody who can make it in the U.S. deregulated
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In one way, the relatively small size and low profile of
Swissair could prove to be an advantage. Michael Boyd, of the
aviation analysis firm the Boyd Group, said that Swissair is less
likely to be the focus of political violence than some other
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no axes to grind there,'' Boyd said. ``They are not
flashy. They are just a well-run, Swiss-watch type airline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
