<HEADER>
A0364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LIEBERMAN-700     09-04 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LIEBERMAN-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR DESCRIBES ANGER THAT LED HIM TO DENOUNCE CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like many other Americans, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut went on vacation with his family in mid-August. As it
happened, the vacation began just after President Clinton had
admitted on national television to having an inappropriate
relationship with a White House intern and to lying about it.
</P>
<P>
   With four generations of Liebermans sharing a rented beach house
in Madison, Conn., off Long Island Sound, the family found itself
circling back repeatedly over meals to discussions of the
president's behavior. Lieberman's 83-year-old mother was the most
tolerant and protective of Clinton. His children, ages 30, 29, 22
and 10, were more upset.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a Democrat and longtime political ally of Clinton's,
said he was furious with the president _ first for bad behavior,
second for behavior that he said undercut the theme of ``personal
responsibility'' that Clinton and Lieberman had advocated over the
years as they tried to pull the Democratic Party toward the
mainstream values of the political center.
</P>
<P>
   And Lieberman thought that for someone of Clinton's vaunted
ability to communicate, his initial public comments Aug. 17 had
been ``remarkably inadequate'' to the task of articulating how
consequential his wrongdoing had been and how badly he felt about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said in a lengthy interview Friday in his office in
Washington that he was so angry that 10 days ago, while he was
still on vacation, he sat down with his laptop computer and started
composing his thoughts. He had so much to say that he rejected the
idea of issuing a short press release. What he wrote instead was a
stern, 3,000-word rebuke, the eighth draft of which he read
somberly Thursday on the Senate floor, becoming the first member of
his party to assert in a substantive, public way how what he termed
the president's ``immoral'' behavior had damaged the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, Lieberman said in
his 24-minute speech, ``not only contradicted the values he has
publicly embraced over the last six years, it has, I fear,
compromised his moral authority.'' Moreover, he said, it reinforced
``one of the worst messages being delivered by our popular culture,
which is that values are fungible.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Lieberman's speech becomes a turning point in the
already seven-month-long national morality play that has engulfed
Washington remains to be seen, but he said he hoped it would
``start a process.'' Still, for several minutes while he was giving
his speech, Lieberman said, ``I felt lonely out there.''
</P>
<P>
   After he spoke, two of his Democratic colleagues, Sens. Bob
Kerrey of Nebraska and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, took to
the floor to support what he had said. Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle did not speak publicly, but put his arm around Lieberman
and shook his hand. Lieberman's longtime friend Sen. Connie Mack,
R-Fla., crossed the aisle and sat with him while other Republicans
spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he has been bolstered by the generally positive
reaction to his speech, even as some in the Senate have privately
criticized him for what they say is a sanctimoniousness that
infuses his moralizing about society and the degrading effect of
popular culture on mainstream values.
</P>
<P>
   His office phone lines were clogged all day with calls, many of
them supportive of his comments, others saying his speech did not
go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's speech also forced a reaction from Clinton, who was
traveling in Ireland. Prompted by reporters, Clinton said he agreed
with Lieberman that his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky was
``indefensible'' and he was ``very sorry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he ``appreciated'' Clinton's comments but thought
the president still needed to say more. ``As I saw him,'' Lieberman
said of watching Clinton on television on Friday morning, ``I felt
badly that he had to do it, but I knew he had to do it. This is a
process. It's not a one-time thing. It's like having someone in
your family with a problem. It doesn't end with a single statement.
It's a process _ of confrontation, repentance and reconstruction of
the ties within the family.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said the president has called him twice since making his
televised admissions Aug. 17. Lieberman said that in the first
conversation, he told Clinton he was disappointed and angry with
him.
</P>
<P>
   In the second conversation, he told Clinton he planned to make
some public comments that would ``not be comfortable to hear.'' The
senator said, ``He never spoke to me about the content of what I
was going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's chief of staff, Erskine Bowles, called Lieberman
on Monday morning when word spread that the senator was about to
speak. Bowles asked him to hold off until Clinton left Russia.
Lieberman said he had not finished the speech anyway and would give
it later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he had considered calling for Congress to censure
Clinton, but backed off at Daschle's request. He said Daschle was
concerned that calling for a specific action by the Senate now _
before Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr issues a report on his
investigation _ would be premature and might hamper Democrats'
re-election efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And Lieberman worried that a call for censure would distract
attention from his main message about Clinton's corrosive effect on
family values.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he never considered not speaking at all, even as
some senators in the Democrats' weekly lunch Tuesday urged everyone
to ``stay on message'' and talk publicly only about policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an air of unreality to that, because we're not going
to get the public, let alone the media, focused back on those
genuine public problems until we deal more openly and better with
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he did not rule out that he may feel compelled in
the future to call for censure, adding that he hoped further
evidence would not force him to call for Clinton's resignation or
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he said, he hopes Clinton's presidency ``can be
repaired and concluded honorably.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
