<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-SUITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITS, SETTLEMENTS SHADOW SWISSAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite swift announcements of $20,000 payments to relatives of
those killed in the crash of Swissair Flight 111, the specter of
protracted lawsuits and massive settlements loomed over the airline
Friday, as families began grappling with complex legal questions
and seeking advice.
</P>
<P>
   A top aviation lawyer in New York said his ``telephone had been
ringing all day.'' Others said that, based on recent awards in
cases against airlines and manufacturers, the families of the
victims could easily expect a settlement of more than $1 million
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a far more impressive number than even the
Korean airlines case,'' said Aaron J. Broder, referring to the 1983
downing of Flight 007 after it strayed into Soviet airspace,
killing 269 people. Broder recently won a $19 million settlement
for the wife of a victim of Pan Am 103, which exploded over
Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   None of the experts interviewed interpreted the $20,000
compensation _ billed as a ``good-will gesture'' _ as an early ploy
to prevent further legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not done with any strings attached, and it sounds like
it is not, then I think it's really a nice gesture,'' said Jim
Burnett, former chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board. ``It probably has some benefits to Swissair. But I'm not
going to be critical of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims' families can choose the court in which they sue, and
because they prefer courts that will favor their claim, they tend
to end up in the United States, preferably in an urban center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite plainly, we are trying to make a choice based on where
we think we'll get the most favorable results,'' said David
Rapoport, an aviation trial attorney in Chicago. He expects
families in the Swissair crash to file suit in the Southern
District in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Juries have set such precedents for rewarding huge amounts to
victims' families that there is little chance these families will
not proceed in court, attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   Rapoport said the majority of awards are below $5 million. But
they are almost never lower than $200,000, and in some cases have
reached $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Warsaw Convention, airlines are limited to awards of
$75,000 per victim. But two years ago, Swissair, along with all of
the US carriers, waived that limit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, a statement by Swissair acknowledged that the company
was prepared to pay damages. ``In concrete terms, Swissair will
compensate relatives of the victims for losses suffered in the
accident,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   But because the damages are based on individual calculations,
particularly projections of what wages the victim would have
earned, the total cannot yet be determined, it continued.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Boeing, which owns the original MD-11
manufacturing company, McDonnell Douglas, also declined to
speculate about specific damage amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course liability is an unavoidable consequence in
situations like this,'' Russ Young said. ``But particularly this
early on, our concerns are not about legal issues. They're about
technical issues, and understanding what happened, and why.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will not discuss a final settlement until the cause of
the crash has been determined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely the cases will soon be resolved. Lawsuits
resulting from two recent disasters, the crash of ValuJet in 1995
and of TWA Flight 800 in 1996, are still crawling through the
courts. The case of Korean Airline Flight 007 dragged on for more
than a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
