<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0382 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ALTERNATIVES-A     09-04 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ALTERNATIVES-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING HANDCUFFED, MANY STAY PUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Ariz., Fla., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many investors, the choice of whether to sell or hold fast
as stocks swooned in the last two weeks felt like no choice at all:
For better or worse, they said, they were handcuffed to the market
by a need to avoid taking taxable gains or locking in devastating
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Matheson, 51, who does voice-overs for commercials in
Chicago, is one long-term investor whose resolve was severely
tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting on my ledge, thinking about jumping,'' joked
Matheson after last Monday's 512-point dive in the Dow Jones
industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   But once Matheson considered his alternatives, he decided to
leave his stock investments _ about 60 percent of his portfolio _
where they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine locking in these losses,'' he said. ``If I
sold now, I'd be sitting here with a pile of cash and asking, `What
would I do with it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In years gone by, a slide in major market indexes like the one
culminating in Monday's selloff would have sent Matheson and many
small investors like him stampeding for the exits, scrambling to
sell shares and seeking triage for their ailing portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, with a record number of Americans having a
record amount of their net worth in equities, many investors stayed
with their stocks, saying there was nowhere else to go for
double-digit returns. Indeed, there are few investments that will
yield such strong gains, said Dan Seto, senior economist at Nikko
Securities International. ``There aren't too many good
alternatives'' to the stock market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For many investors, today's money and credit markets don't seem
to qualify. A flight to quality, brought on by the stock market's
gyrations and turmoil in foreign financial markets, has pushed
yields on Treasury bonds to their lowest levels in two decades.
Bank certificates of deposit are no better, with one-year CDs
yielding 4.94 percent, on average, in August.
</P>
<P>
   Commodities, too, are seen as unattractive. Commodity markets
are perceived as risky and forbidding for ordinary investors, while
prices of oil, gold and many other commodities are depressed, with
few signs that broad rallies are imminent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some investors point to low interest rates and cheap
oil as positive economic signs that should help stocks rebound
soon, resuscitating their battered stock portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   But by clinging to such thinking, the investors may be whistling
in the wind, while whatever profits are left in their stocks
evaporate or their losses escalate.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, in the last few years, they've been correct: Long-term
investing has proven to be beneficial and profitable,'' said Larry
Rice, chief investment officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co. But history also
teaches that investor complacency about declines can be costly, he
warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not enough fear yet; most of the investing public has
not seen a bear market,'' Rice said, adding that in such strong
downturns, investors usually wind up capitulating and selling very
close to the bottom. Then mutual funds that had been hoarding cash
start buying stocks anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can say is that this time it's going to be
different than every other cycle in history,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   But some investors think it is already too late to sell.
</P>
<P>
   While many analysts say stocks still have further to slide, most
view the remaining downside as fairly limited. If so, selling now
could be a sure way for investors to maximize near-term losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late,'' asserted Duke Jupiter, 34, a stockbroker in
Scottsdale, Ariz. ``If you sold that first day, you could have rode
this out. But the losses would be too steep now and there's not
much more downside. If you get out now and it comes back, you're
going to miss out.''
</P>
<P>
   For many people who have been invested in stocks for a while,
losses are not the issue. Even after the market's fall from July's
record highs through Monday, a slide that erased more than $2
trillion in value from the 30 Dow companies and more than $588
billion from NASDAQ shares _ or nearly all the year's gains _ many
investors continue to have sizable, if smaller, gains in individual
stocks. And they are reluctant to sell now and take a hefty capital
gains tax hit.
</P>
<P>
   Helen G. Bradley, 66, of Jacksonville, Fla., said she was
``trying not to make any actual profits outside of my IRA.'' for
tax reasons. In other words, Ms. Bradley does not want to compound
the damage done by the market's slide by surrendering a big chunk
of her portfolio that is not in an individual retirement account to
the Internal Revenue Service through capital gains taxes on sales
of stock. Although prices have fallen, they are still higher than
the prices she paid for her shares years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some stocks, like Apple Computer and Dell Computer, are still up
more than 100 percent this year, while others, like Gap, Lucent
Technologies, Cisco Systems, Microsoft and Worldcom, are up more
than 50 percent. The short-term capital gains tax could _ at the
maximum rate _ slice a hefty 39.6 percent of that away.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the flat 20 percent long-term capital gains tax rate,
which now kicks in for stocks owned more than 12 months, a sizable
chunk of gains could be taken.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of recent tax law changes, which are retroactive
to Jan. 1, there is less that an investor can do to lock in stock
gains and avoid a big tax bite, said Robert Willens, a tax and
accounting analyst at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   An investor can still buy a put option to hedge against losses,
but buying one for a stock owned less than 12 months will erase all
of the accumulated time the stock has been owned before it can
qualify for the lower long-term capital gains rate, Willens said.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative strategy, called shorting against the box,
which is used to carry a profit into the next tax year, has become
more restrictive, he added.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the investors who are frozen in the market by
nothing more than ticker shock. ``It's been so bad, I don't even
want to know what I've lost,'' said Deborah Bernstein, head of
sales for the colored-stones division of Kimberly Created Emeralds
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I saw it go beyond something I could handle, I stopped
looking,'' Ms. Bernstein said. She made an ill-timed first foray
into the stock market two weeks before last October's decline of
500-plus points, buying individual shares of companies like Oracle,
Staten Island Bancorp and Atmel. Atmel, a specialty computer chip
maker, in particular has been routed since she bought it, falling
more than 60 percent this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it gets better, I think I'm going to sell everything and
start over,'' she said. But not now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
