u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISSAIR-SUITS-BOS &LR;      09-04 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-SUITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITS, SETTLEMENTS SHADOW SWISSAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite swift announcements of $20,000 payments to relatives of
those killed in the crash of Swissair Flight 111, the specter of
protracted lawsuits and massive settlements loomed over the airline
Friday, as families began grappling with complex legal questions
and seeking advice.
</P>
<P>
   A top aviation lawyer in New York said his ``telephone had been
ringing all day.'' Others said that, based on recent awards in
cases against airlines and manufacturers, the families of the
victims could easily expect a settlement of more than $1 million
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a far more impressive number than even the
Korean airlines case,'' said Aaron J. Broder, referring to the 1983
downing of Flight 007 after it strayed into Soviet airspace,
killing 269 people. Broder recently won a $19 million settlement
for the wife of a victim of Pan Am 103, which exploded over
Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   None of the experts interviewed interpreted the $20,000
compensation _ billed as a ``good-will gesture'' _ as an early ploy
to prevent further legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not done with any strings attached, and it sounds like
it is not, then I think it's really a nice gesture,'' said Jim
Burnett, former chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board. ``It probably has some benefits to Swissair. But I'm not
going to be critical of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims' families can choose the court in which they sue, and
because they prefer courts that will favor their claim, they tend
to end up in the United States, preferably in an urban center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite plainly, we are trying to make a choice based on where
we think we'll get the most favorable results,'' said David
Rapoport, an aviation trial attorney in Chicago. He expects
families in the Swissair crash to file suit in the Southern
District in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Juries have set such precedents for rewarding huge amounts to
victims' families that there is little chance these families will
not proceed in court, attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   Rapoport said the majority of awards are below $5 million. But
they are almost never lower than $200,000, and in some cases have
reached $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Warsaw Convention, airlines are limited to awards of
$75,000 per victim. But two years ago, Swissair, along with all of
the US carriers, waived that limit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, a statement by Swissair acknowledged that the company
was prepared to pay damages. ``In concrete terms, Swissair will
compensate relatives of the victims for losses suffered in the
accident,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   But because the damages are based on individual calculations,
particularly projections of what wages the victim would have
earned, the total cannot yet be determined, it continued.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Boeing, which owns the original MD-11
manufacturing company, McDonnell Douglas, also declined to
speculate about specific damage amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course liability is an unavoidable consequence in
situations like this,'' Russ Young said. ``But particularly this
early on, our concerns are not about legal issues. They're about
technical issues, and understanding what happened, and why.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will not discuss a final settlement until the cause of
the crash has been determined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely the cases will soon be resolved. Lawsuits
resulting from two recent disasters, the crash of ValuJet in 1995
and of TWA Flight 800 in 1996, are still crawling through the
courts. The case of Korean Airline Flight 007 dragged on for more
than a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-04 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVAL IN AN ERA OF UNCERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Berger is a contrarian, no doubt about it. A pre-eminent
sociologist of religion, he has been undercutting conventional
assumptions since ``The Noise of Solemn Assemblies,'' his 1961
book, cast a cold eye on the postwar religious revival still in
full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   His latest salvo is in the current issue of The Christian
Century, the journal of liberal Protestantism. Berger, director of
the Institute for the Study of Economic Culture at Boston
University, began by confessing one big error in his early
thinking: that modernity necessarily leads to a decline in
religion.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few locales like Western Europe and few highly
visible groups, like the humanistically educated intelligentsia,
most of the world, he said, is as religious as ever. But he remains
convinced that modern pluralism undermines the ``taken for
grantedness'' that has bolstered traditional religious beliefs and
moral values.
</P>
<P>
   Pluralism, in sum, may not keep people from believing but it
influences how they believe _ namely, with a good deal less
certainty. There are, of course, people who thrive on this lack of
certainty. But most people find it disconcerting, especially when
it touches on life's most basic questions. That is why they are
drawn to various contemporary ``offers of certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   He identifies three of long standing within the Christian orbit.
One can seek certainty in the institution of the church, in an
absolute understanding of the biblical text or in one's own direct
religious experience. Catholicism has tended toward the first,
fundamentalist Protestantism toward the second, revivalism and
Pentecostalism toward the third.
</P>
<P>
   Berger argues that the modern human sciences have weakened all
three possibilities. Historical scholarship creates uncertainties
about the institution's trustworthiness. Biblical criticism raises
doubts about any certain interpretation of the texts. Psychology
and the sociology of knowledge undermine confidence in inner
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   But is the person who rejects these offers of certainty thrown
into the alternative of a relativism that verges on nihilism?
</P>
<P>
   ``If one rejects the stark alternatives of an open-ended
relativism or some variant of absolutist retrenchment,'' Berger
wrote, ``one is faced with a simple but far-reaching question: How
is one to have religious beliefs and to lead a religious life in a
state of uncertainty?''
</P>
<P>
   His answer draws on classical Protestantism and its core
formula: ``By faith alone _ sola fide.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith is capable of providing what direct experience, pure logic
or the ``taken for granted'' knowledge that pluralism undermines
cannot. But Protestantism does not have a monopoly on this
religious posture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a mellow synthesis of skepticism and faith that, in
principle, can be found in any religious tradition,'' Berger wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, words like ``faith,'' ``relativism,'' ``absolutism''
are red meat for voracious theologians and philosophers, and many
will be tempted to have a tasty meal at Berger's expense. But that
may be nothing like the free-for-all his article could provoke
among scholars of American religion.
</P>
<P>
   The new reigning wisdom in those circles has been that only
``strong religion'' is likely to prosper in contemporary America,
only religious groups, in other words, that demand substantial
commitments of time and resources from their adherents and firm
allegiance to beliefs and practices that differentiate the faithful
from the surrounding culture.
</P>
<P>
   This view gains support from the growth of conservative
Christian groups and from the decline or stagnation of ``weak''
liberal denominations that more readily tolerate modern
uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   Berger's article is both a sociological and theological
challenge to that view, and he even supplies a text from Paul's
First Letter to the Corinthians: ``God chose what is weak in the
world to shame the strong.'' He cites some recent evidence that
``weak'' religious institutions can be remarkably vital.
</P>
<P>
   But what gives his article force is less the evidence it cites
than the changed attitude toward mainline Protestantism that it
expresses.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative, Berger has made many biting observations over
the years on the political and economic liberalism marking the
leadership of mainline Protestant bodies (and of American
Catholicism as well), reflective, he said, of a deeper
accommodation to the assumptions of modern culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tended to look on mainline Protestantism as a community very
much gone astray,'' he said in a telephone conversation Friday,
``one terribly vulnerable to fashionable ideas.'' That view is
``still correct,'' he said. ``But it has struck me increasingly
that there is a kind of blessing in this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a pretty demoralized community,'' he added.
``I'm telling them don't be that demoralized.'' The ``era of
uncertainty'' created by modern pluralism has created believers of
a new sort ``who may be a majority of the population,'' he said,
``and need ministering.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus may not be found in ``the self-assured, triumphalist
institutions that merit the appellation of `strong churches,' ''
Berger wrote in his article, but ``in those `weak' places _ where
people are unsure of themselves, groping for a few glimpses of
truth to hold on to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
