<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-ATTACK-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANI GOVERNMENT FORCED STATEMENTS FROM KENYA BOMBING SUSPECT,
LAWYER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BEN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The former lawyer for a defendant charged in the
bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya said Friday that his client
was told, while under interrogation in Pakistan, that the
government of Pakistan wanted his confession in order to improve
relations with the United States, which have been complicated by
Pakistan's test of nuclear weapons earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion by the lawyer, Jack Sachs, came on the day that a
federal judge in Manhattan removed him as the attorney for Mohammed
Saddiq Odeh, one of two defendants charged in the embassy attacks
last month, which killed more than 250 people and wounded
thousands. Sachs said that he believed he was being removed because
he had been appointed to two potential death- penalty cases at the
same time: Odeh's and a second, unrelated case.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said his former client also had told him that Pakistani
authorities coerced him into making statements that are said to
have implicated him in the bombings. ``Three days and three nights
without food and without water, under bright lights, no sleep _
what would anybody say?'' Sachs said.
</P>
<P>
   A Pakistani official in Washington rejected Odeh's contention
that he was coerced into making any statements, saying the
allegation ``is totally baseless and fabricated.''
</P>
<P>
   The official, Malik Zahoor Ahmad, the Pakistani embassy's
minister for information, said that he could not comment
specifically on the assertion that Pakistan sought to elicit Odeh's
confession to improve relations, but he said that ``Pakistan has
always cooperated with the United States in combating terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our track record is visible to the whole world,'' Ahmad said.
``We have always condemned terrorism in all its forms, and we
believe that terrorism is incompatible with civilized behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Odeh's allegations could not be confirmed independently on
Friday. He has been charged with conspiracy to commit murder, use
of a weapon of mass destruction, and 12 counts of murder, one count
for each of the 12 Americans killed in the Nairobi bombing last
month. If convicted, Odeh could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh was said to have admitted a role in the embassy bombings
during his interrogation by Pakistani authorities. But the
documents charging him in the attacks do not cite any statements to
Pakistani interrogators. The documents cited admissions to FBI
agents in Kenya, who questioned him after he was returned to that
country by the Pakistanis, in which Odeh said that he was a member
of al Qaeda, the terrorist organization suspected in the attacks,
and a follower of the group's leader, Osama bin Laden. He denied
any role in the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a religious guy,'' Sachs said after court Friday. ``He
doesn't have what they want. He knows very little about bin
Laden.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sachs said that he had interviewed Odeh extensively in the
Metropolitan Correctional Center in recent days, and his client had
given his account of his interrogation by Pakistani authorities.
One of his interrogators seemed ``to take pity on him,'' Sachs
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy said to him, we're going to use you _ these
confessions _ to help us with the Americans on the nuclear
sanctions,'' Sachs said.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh sat quietly in the brief hearing in U.S. district court in
Manhattan Friday as Magistrate Judge Kevin Nathaniel Fox said that
he would be given a new lawyer. Sachs said both he and his client
were disappointed at the change of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was upset that I was not going to be his attorney because
he had grown to trust me,'' Sachs said.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh's new lawyer, Michael Young, did not return a call seeking
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
