</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARCH' TO UNDERSCORE NEW GENERATION OF BLACK YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a stage set of Manhattan's night sky glittering
behind him, Kweisi Mfume, president of the National Asociation for
the Advancement of Colored People, laid out for a late night TV
audience his organization's agenda for the nation's black youth.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume, a guest last week &UR;  &LR; on HBO's Chris Rock show, spoke about
youth chapters and youth councils and youth protests. He tried to
make a case for bold, new blood in the NAACP _ an organization that
once held the attention and passion of blacks in the millions, and
whose youngest members risked arrest, beatings and even death.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and this was now. Rock, a young, irreverant,
black comedian, wasn't buying Mfume's line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on now, are you guys gonna start hittin' the streets? You
know what I mean?'' Rock said, his gravel voice cracking, his hands
waving in show-me-the-money gestures. ``I mean, you can't leave a
rap concert without the Nation of Islam holding out
stuff...Everybody hits the street. You guys ain't never out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment of subtle truth wrapped in comic banter,
underscoring the growing gulf that many see dividing a generation
of hip-hop-influenced youth from their civil-rights-era elders.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, as some 50,000 young people were expected to converge
on a six-block stretch of Harlem for a rally flamboyantly labelled
the Million Youth March, many blacks here say that gulf will be on
vivid display. They say the crisis surrounding the event is not to
be found in the showdown between the march's controversial
organizer, Khallid Abdul Muhammad, and the city's bulldog of a
mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, who tried to derail the event. Nor is it
in the idea that a man like Muhammad, prone to wildly inflammatory
anti-Semitic remarks, could emerge as a leader of any kind. &UR;  &LR; Nor in
the notion that his march could upstage another youth march
Saturday, in Atlanta, which numbers among its sponsors the NAACP
and Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis, they say, is in the widespread sense among the young
of a lack of black leadership attuned to their concerns. The gap
has grown so wide, and the prospects for future leaders seem so
bleak, some say, that a man like Muhammad can enter the void and
claim to fill it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real searching among African-American youth for
leadership, for some kind of meaning and political direction,''
said Errol T. Louis, a community activist who helped start a credit
union for low-income families in Brooklyn and who cut his political
teeth in Jesse Jackson's presidential campaign. ``And that's the
shame of it, because anyone could have announced this need for a
march and any group could have organized it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Harlem's prominent ministers and political leaders
continued to recruit volunteers to act as peace buffers between
youth and police. An ad hoc group calling itself the Interfaith
Coalition for Peace and Justice made plans to have lawyers standing
by at police precincts, to hand out leaflets with safety tips and
to turn churches along the route of the march into safe sanctuaries
for marchers.
</P>
<P>
   But as some black leaders voice fear of riots and continue to
denounce Muhammad as a spewer of hate, activists and would-be
marchers said they rarely see the same outrage aimed at the daily
wars they wage -- against drugs, unemployment, prison and police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep saying, 'We're afraid of you marching without a
permit. We're afraid for the young people getting hurt at the
march.' Why weren't you afraid for us when the police shot at a
child 16 times for holding a toy gun? Or getting shot by police for
holding a Three Musketeers bar?'' said 27-year-old Monifa Akinwole,
referring to two recent incidents of police gunfire aimed at
unarmed residents in Brooklyn and Queens. ``We're not afraid to
march. We're too busy worrying if our keys will be mistaken for a
gun on our way to work. That's the reality and that's what I think
this march is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the hundreds of young people she works with as an activist at
the Malcolm X Grassroots Movement in Brooklyn, Akinwole said few of
them know about Muhammad or see him as an influence in their lives.
But she says many of them see him as one of the few black public
figures who has reached out to those young blacks who have fallen
and are on the fringe -- drug addicts and dealers, high school
dropouts and gang members. In their eyes, he has met them in their
world, not preached at them to enter his.
</P>
<P>
   And in recent weeks, as Muhammad took the city to court and won
the right to hold the march in Harlem, he has shown them something
they do not see in the black leadership establishment in New York.
He has shown them he is unafraid.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for many, he remains an uncertain influence. Asked if she
knew what Muhammad stood for or wether she understood his platform,
15-year-old Tyshell Cheatham said, ``That's a good question. Not
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheatham said she doesn't tend to identify with activists like
Muhammad; it is her mother and her psychiatrist who serve as role
models as she pursues a career in social work. But Cheatham does
dream of leaders who understand and act against the pitfalls that
could sidetrack her as they have sidetracked some of her friends:
pregnancy, drugs, too little money to pay for school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the anger we feel comes from the police, but it also
comes from just people who are supposed to represent us, adults,
who are not listening to kids. It seems like maybe they've got
better things to do than listen to us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of Muhammad, she said, ``He's been in Harlem, and he's seen
what's been happening to us and he hasn't turned his back.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where incidents of police brutality, cuts in the
city's public college programs and disturbing statistics about
black men in prison often dominate the news, observers say some
leaders who rose up through civil rights activism and Democratic
Party politics fail to grasp the new burdens on young people or the
anger they express in lyrics or in real violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black church, the traditional black leaders from the old
guard have not taken up the charge. They don't have anything to say
to the so-called hip-hoppers and they have alienated them,'' said
Amy Alexander, a Boston author who edited ``The Farrakhan Factor,''
about Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan.
</P>
<P>
   Once one of Farrakhan's most trusted confidantes, Muhammad was
expelled from the Nation of Islam by Farrakhan after anti-Semitic
remarks Muhammad made in a 1993 speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Muhammad (don't) have the answers to the problems,
but at least they recognize that something is wrong. They know the
old guard has dropped the ball and they see that a lot of these
kids are just free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Fela Johannes is one of those free agents. Standing at the
corner of 118th Street and Malcolm X Boulevard Friday, where the
march is supposed to begin, the 16-year-old high school senior from
the Bronx called the march an ``uprising'' that he hoped would make
leaders reckon with the daily struggles of young blacks that never
make the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the real leaders all died,'' Johannes. ``Back in the
day, you knew who they were. But that was like, decades ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
