<HEADLINE>
MANY NEWCOMERS ARE GROUNDED BY TURBULENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of IPO proceeds and issues is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A peek at the Equity New Issue Calendar on a Bloomberg terminal
last week read like a departure monitor at a fogged-in airport.
``Postponed.'' ``Delayed.'' ``Canceled.'' Indeed, as stocks
struggled to climb back after Monday's selloff, not one company
ventured onto the public markets last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I would say the window is closed,'' said Andy
Kessler, a co-founder of Velocity Capital Management in Palo Alto,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   John E. Fitzgibbon Jr., editor of The IPO Reporter, a
newsletter, agreed. ``What's going on in this market?'' he asked.
``Nothing, absolutely nothing. The hurricane shutters are down.''
</P>
<P>
   Four companies that postponed planned stock or units offerings
last week were Datalink, a maker of data storage devices;
Galacticomm Technologies, an on-line communications software maker;
Gary Player Golf, a golf club marketer, and Sunbelt Automotive
Group, a car retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Datalink, Gary Player and Galacticomm said late last week that
they would wait until the second half of September before
considering an initial offering. A spokeswoman for Sunbelt did not
say when it would reapproach the market.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, last week's shutdown follows a month of dismal fortune
for IPOs. The Securities Data Co. said that only 19 came to market
in August, raising a total of $1.33 billion. By contrast, there
were 49 in August 1997, raising $2.86 billion. And even as recently
as July, 46 companies managed to break out of the gate, raising
$3.89 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for recent offerings are grounded, too. According to
Fitzgibbon, as of Aug. 31 only two of the IPOs in the month were
trading over their offering prices: Jenkon International, a
software concern, and Geocities, the Internet company that helps
individuals create their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgibbon said the 19 stocks that went public in August lost
20.4 percent of their value by month's end, on average, with the
worst performance turned in by Pilot Network Services. That
company, which provides secure Internet access services for on-line
businesses, was initially priced at $14 on Aug. 11, opened at $13
and closed on Friday at $6.875.
</P>
<P>
   ``August was a blood bath,'' Fitzgibbon said.
</P>
<P>
   And even those lucky holders of Geocities and Jenkon were put
through the wringer. Geocities jumped to $37.3125 from its offering
price of $17 on Aug. 11, peaked at $51.375 the next day and closed
on Friday at less than half that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkon rose to $5.53125 on Aug. 11 from its offering price of
$5, hit a high of $6.375 on Aug. 26 and closed at $5.75 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest losers in the current selloff are investors
who signed so-called lock-up agreements, agreeing that they will
not sell their holdings for 180 days. Many who did saw their
holdings rise and then were forced to sit on their hands as their
positions collapsed in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``All private-round investors are being asked to sign these
agreements these days,'' Kessler said. But when markets tumble, he
added, the lock-ups can cause newly issued stocks to sink out of
sight once anxious investors flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the current market, anyone who's locked up is going to be
out of luck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what does September hold for prospective IPO investors? The
period after Labor Day has traditionally been popular for initial
offerings, and until recently, the calendar for the fall looked
full. At the end of August, for example, The IPO Reporter had more
than 70 offerings on its September list.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler, however, said he believed half of those prospective
IPOs would be postponed. The current lineup, meanwhile, is weighted
heavily toward very small companies, with scant operating
histories, trying to take their stocks public without the backing
of large, well-known underwriters. Underwriters' support can be
crucial in determining an offering's success.
</P>
<P>
   IPO experts still see a number of high-profile, potentially
well-grounded deals on the horizon. But they say it is unlikely
that any one deal will lift the IPO market out of its doldrums. And
that includes the much-anticipated proposed offering by Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The offering is expected to bring in $2.5 billion or more,
although details are still being worked out. A spokesman for
Goldman said the firm's plans remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgibbon predicted that Goldman, Sachs ``is going to be a
class act onto itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the market picks up significantly this month, the
IPO outlook will likely follow suit, regardless of what Goldman
does, analysts say. Fitzgibbon, for one, thinks a new round of
internet companies will be going public in the coming months.
Indeed, such offerings have fared better than those of other
companies in the market's downturn.
</P>
<P>
   But don't hold your breath. A survey of the top 15 underwriters
by Bloomberg Financial Markets showed that none of them planned
IPOs for this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
