<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARKETS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Rough Ride in Chicago, Too &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It can be difficult to stomach the roller-coaster summer of the
financial markets. Traders and clerks at the Chicago Board of Trade
collapsed on the trading floor on Tuesday after an exhausting
session in which investors tried to protect positions by trading in
Dow Jones stock index futures.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow climbed 288.36 points that day, making up more than half
the 512.61 points it lost on Monday. But over the rest of the week,
it gave most of that gain back, closing down 411.43 points at
7,640.25. With investors looking for a haven from the equity
markets' volatile swings, bond prices rose, pushing yields down to
a three-decade low. The 30-year Treasury bond ended the week at
5.28 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medicine for the Market &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shares of pharmaceutical companies climbed, however, after the
FDA recommended approval of taxmoxifen as a means to reduce the
risk of breast cancer. Zeneca Group PLC, which makes the drug, and
Barr Laboratories, which sells its generic form, rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Zeneca ADRs ended the week down $1.25 at 37.0625. Barr shares
fared better, gaining 44.9375, to close at $33.3125. Barr also
benefited from FDA approval of its ``morning-after'' Preven
Emergency Contraceptive Kit.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech rose, but fell back, ending the week off 25 cents at
$66.75 after the FDA approved its Herceptin drug for metastatic
breast cancer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PILOTS' STRIKE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Rebuffs Plea &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the pilots' strike against Northwest Airlines snarled holiday
travel plans in the Midwest, President Clinton rejected a call on
Thursday by Gov. Arne Carlson of Minnesota to order the pilots back
to work.
</P>
<P>
   The White House called on the two sides to return to the
bargaining table, and they were to have met Saturday in Chicago
with a federal mediator. The pilots, who are demanding increased
job security and higher pay to make up for cuts they took in 1993
to save the airline from bankruptcy, turned down the carrier's
initial offer.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest says it cannot afford to meet the pilots' demands and
has laid off more than half its 51,000 workers, saying that it
could not afford to pay them while it was not operating. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gains for Retailers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American retailers had fairly strong sales for August, with
same-store sales _ those for stores open at least a year _ up 3.5
percent, according to the Goldman Sachs retail composite index.
Wal-Mart's gain was 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, retailers were counting on a strong September, as
tax-free shopping kicked off back-to-school sales. ... General
Motors, still struggling from July strikes, reported that car and
light-truck sales fell 36.4 percent in August, giving the industry
as a whole a decrease of 6.6 percent, despite an increase in
American sales for nearly all other auto companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was up 8.1 percent; Chrysler, 3.5 percent, and Toyota, 10.9
percent. American sales of Daimler-Benz's Mercedes cars surged 75.8
percent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  MORE)
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flashing Mixed Signals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment, as expected, held steady at a low 4.5 percent last
month. .. . The industrial economy continued to show vigor in July,
with new factory orders flowing in at the strongest pace in eight
months, growing 1.2 percent, to a seasonally adjusted $335.2
billion. ... Sales of new homes, however, fell 1.6 percent in July,
to 886,000 units at an annual rate, which was more than expected.
... Growth in workers' productivity posted the smallest gain in
nearly two years in the last quarter _ 0.1 percent, though that was
better than a preliminary estimate of a drop of 0.2 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Economy Unravels &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, meeting with President Boris Yeltsin in
Moscow, delivered a sober lecture to Russian leaders and the
Russian people about the hard realities of capitalism and the price
of international support for relief from Russia's financial mess.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has closed banks, left millions of workers unpaid and
caused the collapse of the government. He signaled, however, that
the West would step up its aid if the Kremlin pressed ahead with
tough economic changes.
</P>
<P>
   Western banks and investment funds, particularly German
institutions, that bet on Russia disclosed losses that totaled in
the billions of dollars. Among the banks reporting sizable losses
were Citicorp, Bankers Trust, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Barclays
and Nomura Securities. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE WORLD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Malaise Spreads &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The finance minister of Mexico, Jose Angel Gurria, who runs a
vigorously growing economy with surging exports and thousands of
new jobs being added daily, lamented how the Asian and Russian
economic crises have battered stock prices in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with Mexico,'' he said of the outside
problems. ``There is a lack of differentiation'' among traders.
Asia's troubles were seen anew in South Korea, where nonperforming
bank loans surged 11.8 percent between March and June to $21.4
billion, and riot policemen were called in to quell strikers. In
Malaysia, the finance minister, Anway Ibrahim, was dismissed after
the government imposed currency controls. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Buyouts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, only weeks after agreeing to a new contract with
its unionized workers, extended a voluntary buyout offer to some of
its management employees. ... Royal Dutch/Shell and Texaco agreed
to combine their European refining and marketing businesses, a step
toward cutting costs and capacity. ... Union Pacific, still
recovering from some of the worst congestion in railway history,
announced a plan to improve and, in some cases, ration its service.
... Delta Air Lines, after failing to reach an agreement with its
pilots, dropped plans to link its routes with United Airlines. The
plan had been the cornerstone of a marketing partnership announced
in April. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Show Goes On &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Livent Inc. named Todd Haimes, the artistic director of the
Roundabout Theater Company, as its artistic director, supplanting
Garth H. Drabinsky, Livent's co-founder and the producer of
``Ragtime'' and several other lavish Broadway musicals.
</P>
<P>
   Livent's new managers, led by Michael Ovitz, suspended Drabinsky
and a vice president last month, citing accounting irregularities.
... After a series of weekend meetings in which Boeing directors,
in the words of Philip M. Condit, the chairman, concluded that
there had to be ``significant changes in the composition of the
management team,'' Ronald B. Woodard, 55, quit as president of the
company's jetliner business. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SEC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Auditing the Auditors? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission, concerned about millions
of dollars of consulting work that branches of Big Five accounting
firms now do for companies that are audited by the same firm, wants
the auditors to meet annually with company directors to explain why
their independence has not been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   After recent disclosures of accounting irregularities at a dozen
public companies like Cendant, Sunbeam and Livent, Lynn Turner, the
SEC's chief accountant, told the 15-month-old Independence
Standards Board that its current requirement _ a letter attesting
to independence _ was not tough enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
