<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0399 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-CLUB-ART-$ADV0     09-04 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CLUB-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANIC? NO, JUST A SEARCH FOR VALUE IN THE LONG RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)  
 (af)  
 By LAURA CASTANEDA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRING HOUSE, Pa. _ The Pennsylvania Caveat Emptor Investment
Club has its routine: Members convene on the first Wednesday of
each month to review the club's stock holdings, analyze new
companies and vote on new stock purchases.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a lot to shake this routine _ more, at least, than a
512-point selloff in the Dow Jones industrial average. Though the
plunge last Monday battered the club's portfolio, members still
waited until Wednesday evening to assess the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we got wiped out,'' Tony Catanzaro, the club's
treasurer, said pleasantly. He explained to other members that
their 1998 gains of 13.5 percent were almost erased by the market's
fall. ``But that just means we've got some buying opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what the club focused on for the next two
hours at the Old York Road Country Club in Spring House, a suburb
of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the club's cool response to the market's
convulsions reflected its enthusiastic embrace of the principles of
the National Association of Investors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The association, a nonprofit group in Madison Heights, Mich.,
that promotes clubs as a way to educate consumers about the
benefits of long-term investing, has built its philosophy on four
core ideas: Investing regularly to take advantage of dollar-cost
averaging, reinvesting earnings to gain the benefits of
compounding, investing in growth companies, and diversifying to
spread risk.
</P>
<P>
   This approach has caught on. The association says the number of
clubs nationwide has jumped to more than 37,500 from 10,000 in
1993. The average club is 8{ years old, has 14 members who each
invest $58 a month and enjoys a 12.4 percent annual return.
</P>
<P>
   Caveat Emptor is somewhat newer _ just three years old;
otherwise, it seems to hew closely to the average. It has 16
members evenly split between men and women who must contribute at
least $50 a month, though they can contribute more. Club members
range in age from 27 to 48 and include a podiatrist, a research
biologist, a sign painter and a carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   The club owns shares in Abbott Laboratories, Aflac, Callaway
Golf, Diebold, Halliburton, Halter Marine, Hannaford Brothers,
Invacare, Lucent Technologies, Paychex, Speedway Motorsports,
Synovus Financial, Trinity Industries, Vishay Intertechnology and
XXSYS Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Catanzaro, a purchasing manager for a pharmaceutical company,
said the club's portfolio outperformed the average for NAIC
investment clubs in 1996 and 1997, posting annual returns of 18
percent and 25 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The club's total assets, which peaked at the end of June at
$32,000, fell almost 19 percent, to $26,000, by Monday, though they
picked up a bit with the partial rebound on Tuesday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the members were investment novices when the group
started in 1995, said Paul Carbone, a medical sales representative
who organized the club. Now, all are comfortable using phrases like
``price-earnings ratio'' and ``combined estimated yield.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we're not nervous is that we're in it for the long
haul,'' Carbone said. ``When we see a stock that may be going south
for a couple of months, we're not going to turn around and sell it
off. As long as the company has good management and growth
potential, and there are no obvious problems, we'll stick with
it.'' Indeed, the club has yet to sell a stock.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of lingering on their losses, members at the Wednesday
meeting focused on future moves. Sticking to the schedule,
individuals reported on stocks in the club's portfolio, leading to
a discussion about whether to buy more shares.
</P>
<P>
   The club also heard a presentation on three water companies
under consideration as new investments. ``Water as a natural
resource is going to be the liquid gold of the future,'' said
Catanzaro, citing several news reports on potential water
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Carbone, who conducted the research, used detailed work sheets
the association provides to help compare and select the stocks by
analyzing each company's historical and projected sales growth,
earnings per share and estimated price-earnings ratios, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   Though none of the three companies seemed worth investing in,
based on their historical performance, Carbone recommended looking
at desalination companies as possible investments.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting's most controversial moment came near the end, when
the 10 members in attendance voted 8 to 2 to spend $300 on more
shares of XXSYS, a former military contractor that repairs bridges
using high-technology polymers.
</P>
<P>
   The club originally bought 100 shares at $4 each in November
1996. Since then, the price has dropped to 32 cents. With
dollar-cost averaging, the stock would have to reach 77 cents for
the club to break even.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get out of this company and not lose any money,''
said Walter Knapp, a research biologist, adding that even with the
$300 purchase, XXSYS would still make up just 1 percent of the
club's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not that big of a risk, and it would be a real
coup if it works,'' agreed Randy Huber, a painter.
</P>
<P>
   But Terry Tobin, a podiatrist, was livid. ``It's throwing good
money after bad,'' she said. ``It really upsets my confidence
level. It's gambling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
