<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELICOPTER-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 DIE AS TWO AIR FORCE HELICOPTERS CRASH IN APPARENT COLLISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add map note; no other changes)  
 (ATTN: Nev., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Air Force helicopters crashed early Friday on a
nighttime training mission over a remote mountainous area in
Nevada, killing all 12 crew members on both crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was the Air Force's most deadly accident since
September 1995, when 24 airmen died in the crash of an Airborne
Warning and Control System surveillance aircraft moments after
taking off from Elmendorf Air Force Base in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The two HH-60 Pave Hawk helicopters, each of which had six
airmen aboard, crashed at roughly 1 a.m. local time while flying
together about 70 miles north of Nellis Air Force Base outside Las
Vegas. It appeared likely that the two craft collided, but
officials at Nellis and in Washington said they would not know for
certain until the Air Force completes an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopters, made by Sikorsky Aircraft of Connecticut at a
cost of more than $10 million each, are designed to carry out
search-and-rescue missions and belonged to the 66th Rescue Squadron
at Nellis. The squadron had recently returned from duty in the
Persian Gulf and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopters were on a routine nighttime exercise inside the
sprawling 5,000-square-mile training range north of Las Vegas, the
Air Force's largest.
</P>
<P>
   They crashed in a mountainous area about 25 miles north of
Indian Springs, Nev., that is so rocky and remote that it took
about four hours for rescue crews from the base, as well as the
Bureau of Land Management and the Energy Department, to discover
the wreckage and recover the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first crash of an Air Force Pave Hawk helicopter
since 1995, when one from Osan Air Base in South Korea crashed,
killing five people. The Pave Hawk has been in operation since
1982.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
