<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSIE-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROSIE OUTLOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first coup was Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Then she switched the set around to capture Barbra Streisand's
good side.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show'' are real stories about
real people.
</P>
<P>
   The third season of the hit daytime talk show starts at 3 p.m.
today on KNBC (Channel 4), and O'Donnell is looking for ways to
ward off celebrity saturation.
</P>
<P>
   With numerous talk shows being added to television, and plenty
of entertainment magazine shows on top of that, there are
practically more openings for star power than there are stars with
interesting stories. The result is more duplication than at Kinko's
on a busy day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people are really, really sick of celebrities,''
O'Donnell said. ``I can point to 14 different outlets for them.
Someone in our office figured out that it would take 230
celebrities a week to fill all the spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosie hasn't totally forgotten how star power got her where she
is. If Tom wants to come back, she'll keep the seat warm. Same goes
for Babs and many others. Rest assured, there is no ban on movie
and TV stars, just a de-emphasis. Now more space will be kept open
for ordinary people who do extraordinary things _ from people who
make awesome chili cheese fries to real-life heroes. She will
expand do-it-yourself segments, such as ``Crafts Corner''; add a
segment for children to speak up, called ``Kids Chat''; and talk to
the experts for advice on child-rearing.
</P>
<P>
   This, incidentally, sounds a lot like the strategy for
Roseanne's new talk show, which will debut next week. Rosie said
she had no idea what her friend had planned, but a high-level
person inside Roseanne's show characterized the shifts in Rosie's
format to be inspired by fear of the new competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of want to make it fresh,'' O'Donnell said. ``The
audience embraced me out of the box because they felt it was
something new. It had a retro feel. It was the Merv Griffin and
Mike Douglas of the '90s. The success has challenged me to do
something that will be exciting and new for the audience as well.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell's success has spawned a gaggle of happy talkers trying
to tap into her audience. The grinning siblings will return with a
new ``Donnie &AMP; Marie'' in the afternoons. Howie Mandel continues
with his silliness. Ricki Lake tried to soften her act, and even
Oprah tinkered with her format after Rosie made it big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the one who thought this up,'' O'Donnell said. ``Merv
and Mike didn't even think it up. They stole it from Steve Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   Those big names in talk-show history were O'Donnell's role
models. She used to watch daytime shows with her grandmother,
munching on a bucket of popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   What struck O'Donnell then was how the hosts seemed to be good
friends with all of their guests. That inspiration has led to a
freewheeling talk show unconstrained by the conventional format.
</P>
<P>
   The rewards have been the top awards in the business.
</P>
<P>
   She has won the Emmy Award for best talk-show host for the past
two years, and her program is the reigning best-show Emmy winner.
She also won this year's Women in Radio and Television's Gracie
Allen Award for outstanding talk show and outstanding talk-show
host.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike all too many talk shows where setups and punch lines are
conceived backstage, O'Donnell only wants directions from the
pre-interviews her producers conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``One celebrity guest told them he liked caviar and eggs, and
they wanted me to pull some out from under the desk,'' O'Donnell
said. ``I was like, `What am I, Kreskin?'''
</P>
<P>
   One of O'Donnell's favorite moments was an interview with Harvey
Keitel, who never does pre-interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no pre-interview set up for the story and it was
like, `Oh my God where are we going?''' she said. ``He ended up
telling a story about shoes, and it was delightful.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've been watching, you have been allowed into some unique
television. Madonna taught yoga, George Clooney competed in a
hamburger-eating contest, Hillary Rodham Clinton worked the Crafts
Corner with three 6-year-olds making a hand-print collage, and you
saw many angles of Tom Cruise's smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some big celebrities I never thought I would get,'' she
said. ``I never assumed Barbra Streisand would do a talk show. I've
interviewed everyone I've ever wanted to get. Now we are going to
look at how we can make it different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
