u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-04 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF BASEBALL INTEGRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Ed Wiley's night was made before the game even
started.
</P>
<P>
   Here he was, in the company of his 3-year-old son, Mitchell,
attending his first Cardinals game ever. It would have been too
much to ask for anything else, and you know very well what I'm
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   But the next thing he knew, Mark McGwire was drilling a vicious
line drive that was clearly going to be a home run. ``I put my hand
up to shield the sun,'' recalled Wiley, who was standing about 10
feet fair and 12 rows up in the left-field upper deck. ``And then
I'm watching it and I'm thinking, `That's coming right at me!'''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Wiley was very happy that some nice person had
pointed out the fact that he had left Mitchell's glove on the
counter at the Cardinals' gift shop a few hours earlier, because
there was absolutely no way he could have fielded this scorcher of
a liner barehanded.
</P>
<P>
   But he did. Now he has a precious souvenir. Was it No. 60? No.
It happened to be No. 7 in a 17-swing batting practice. It was
enough to make the journey from Louisville worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I will treasure forever,'' said Wiley, who had
blown off work in order to plug into the traveling carnival known
as ``The Mark McGwire Show'' as the Cardinal strongman, who entered
last night's game with 59 homers, sought to eclipse Roger Maris's
37-year-old record of 61.
</P>
<P>
   Never has there been so much interest in batting practice. It is
no exaggeration to say that the entire Cincinnati Reds squad
watched every one of those 17 swings. And never has there been such
September interest in a game featuring a team 20 1/2 games out of
first place going up against a team 23 games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   It is an Event within an event, so big that it was deemed
necessary for Major League Baseball to assume control of the media
credentials. In a normal circumstance, there would be somewhere
between 20 and 50 people here covering the game. As long as Mark
McGwire is in pursuit of the record, there will be upward of 700
media people in attendance. It is bigger than big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything like it since I've been around,'' said
Rich Levin, the former UCLA basketball player and longtime
sportswriter who has worked for every baseball commissioner since
1985. ``It is similar to the (Cal) Ripken thing, but there we knew
exactly when it would happen (that Ripken would break Lou Gehrig's
record of 2,130 consecutive games). This is another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The preparations have been in discussion since the All-Star
Game, when Levin contacted the Cardinals to ask if they might want
some help in September and they answered quite emphatically in the
affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   We have now arrived at the point where it is no longer a case of
``if'' for either McGwire or Sammy Sosa (who had banged out No. 57
before the Cardinals even took the field) but ``when'' each will
eclipse the record. If the Big Manager In The Sky has any sense of
history, he will arrange it so that both men are sitting on 60 when
Sosa and the Cubs arrive here for a two-game series Monday. Or
maybe give McGwire 61 and Sosa 60. That would be OK, too.
</P>
<P>
   The overriding pregame issue was propriety. Would the Reds pitch
to McGwire? This was the only team in the National League that had
managed to hold McGwire homerless this season, in part because it
was the team that had thrown him the fewest hittable pitches. In 25
plate appearances against the Reds, McGwire had been walked 11
times, five intentionally and six unintentionally, or at least
semi-intentionally. This spicy data has made crusty Cincinnati
skipper Jack McKeon Public Enemy No. 1 here in McGwireland.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment, Cardinals manager Tony La Russa opted for the
high road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the Reds know if they'll pitch to him,'' La Russa said
before the game. ``I really believe, based on the box scores I saw
from Wrigley Field (in the Reds-Cubs series) _ Sosa had 12 at-bats
in three games _ that they will. I feel they will compete with him.
But let me say this: I don't mind writers second-guessing my
strategies but I don't do that with other teams. I can't profess to
get into their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon, by all accounts, loves being the contrarian. ``He
wouldn't mind being the villain,'' said one Cincinnati observer.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see if McKeon has the chutzpah to
repeat one maneuver he executed this season _ namely, walking
McGwire with the bases empty.
</P>
<P>
   One intrepid scribe brought the issue up to the Reds mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember the circumstance?'' he fired back. ``Twelfth
inning. Tie game. Two out, nobody on. A dangerous man who can beat
you with one swing and who won't be stealing second if you put him
on. That was the situation, and yes, I'd do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was in the middle of the summer. Now it's over. The
Reds have already been mathematically eliminated from playoff
contention. The Cardinals' big goal is to finish over .500. Would
there be any defense for McKeon intentionally walking McGwire in,
say, the ninth inning with the score tied, two out, and nobody on?
Is that necessary to protect the integrity of the game? On such
existential questions does baseball often turn.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to say that no one man is bigger than the game
in the abstract, but in this case, that is simply not true. I
wouldn't be here if Mark McGwire weren't on the verge of breaking
the Maris record, and neither would 650 other scribes. The
Cardinals wouldn't be drawing sellout crowds for the remainder of
the season if not for Mark McGwire. For that matter, Jack McKeon
wouldn't be doing pregame press conferences as the skipper of a
team 23 games out if it weren't for Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   For it to have any meaning, McGwire must break the record in a
proper game played with integrity. We all agree to that. But Ed
Wiley didn't drive his son here from Louisville to watch Mark
McGwire get walked intentionally with no one on base. If anyone is
going to be bigger than the game, let it be Mark McGwire, not Jack
McKeon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
