<SLUG> BC-CRASH-INQUIRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN SUB SEARCHES FOR FLIGHT RECORDERS OF DOOMED JUMBO JET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ An aging Canadian submarine Friday
prowled the ocean crash site of Swissair Flight 111 for flight-data
recorders that may yield clues as to what downed the jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   Government search officials said the 200-foot, black-hulled HMCS
Okanogan initially picked up no sign of the recorder, which if
functioning properly would emit a signal that could be detected by
the submarine's sonar.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. and Canadian officials have expressed doubt that
terrorism played a role in the crash late Wednesday that killed all
229 people aboard, the issue was brought back to investigators'
minds by word that one of the victims was a member of the Saudi
royal family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyebrows went up,'' said a Canadian aviation source.
</P>
<P>
   The search for wreckage moved into its second day as relatives
of some of the 229 victims arrived in Halifax to attempt to
identify remains. Investigators said family members will not be
allowed, at least initially, to visit the temporary morgue set up
at a nearby Canadian military base but will be interviewed about
passengers' clothing and medical records.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for keeping the families away is that most of the
remains are gory fragments. Although Canadian authorities have
approached the issue delicately, Philippe Bruggiser, chief
executive of Swissair's parent company, said tearfully in
Switzerland: ``The condition of the bodies is such that the biggest
body part is (the size of) a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives were allowed to visit near the crash site. Government
workers erected tents on the rocky shore at Peggy's Cove to shield
the families from the mercurial weather and massed news media. The
picturesque point, with its much-photographed lighthouse, is about
seven miles from where the MD-11, bound from New York to Geneva,
went down in the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first family members to arrive was a man whom
officials identified as a relative of victim Prince Bandar ibn Saud
ibn Abdel Rahman. Agence France Presse said the 42-year-old prince
was a Saudi businessman and that his presence on the plane was
confirmed by a Saudi aeronautics source. AFP said the prince was en
route to Geneva because his father was hospitalized in the Swiss
city.
</P>
<P>
   About 175 relatives of victims were flown to Halifax from New
York, and another 80 from Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another air incident, a Royal Airlines charter flight from
Toronto to Glasgow, Scotland, made an unscheduled landing in
Labrador on Friday following the pilot's report that an oil warning
light in the cockpit began to blink after the Boeing 757 began its
trans-Atlantic crossing. The jumbo jet, with 225 people aboard,
made it back safely to the Canadian Forces Base near Goose Bay,
about 600 miles north of Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the submarine Okanogan during the night signaled
that the Canadian government had given up any hope of finding
Swissair survivors, a step the Zurich-based company had taken more
than 12 hours earlier in declaring that all aboard _ 215
passengers, 14 crewmembers _ had perished.
</P>
<P>
   The search for remains and debris continued at sea, where 12
government boats sailed slowly through a circular area with an
increasing perimeter, and on land, where 100 infantrymen combed a
15-mile stretch of shoreline where tides were expected to wash up
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 pieces of luggage, apparently from the plane's cargo
hold, were found Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After run-ins with some small boats in the search area,
investigators warned souvenir-hunters to keep out of the area or
risk being charged with obstruction of justice and having their
vessels seized.
</P>
<P>
   Although leaders of the crash inquiry knew victims' families
would want answers, government aviation specialists said few were
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board must work on the facts,'' said Benoit Bouchard,
chairman of Canada's Transport Safety Board. ``I will admit that so
far there's very scarce information. ... It's a question of time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably not going to be quick,'' said a Canadian
aviation source. ``People are probably not going to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1996 crash of TWA Flight 800 in the Atlantic off Long
Island, N.Y., it took a week to find the recorders that monitor
cockpit conversation and flight-instrument data. The recorders are
housed in waterproof containers, often called ``black boxes, that
are buried in the tail of commercial aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   In the TWA crash, the recorders were found by a remotely
controlled underwater camera in 104-feet of water. The Swissair
flight went down in water that is up to 150 feet with an ocean
floor that varies between rock, shale and gravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenging bottom,'' said Lieutenant Commander D.K.
Agnew of the Canadian navy.
</P>
<P>
   Before being called out on the emergency assignment, the
submarine, only one of three in the Canadian navy, was due to be
decommissioned Friday, after a final sail-past in Halifax Harbor.
One of the nation's subs had already been taken out of service and
the other is being retrofitted as a training vessel for a new class
of submarines that have yet to be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   A navy source said other ``submersibles,'' including a minisub,
could be called in but probably would not be until the Okanogan had
covered the prime search sight.
</P>
<P>
   As the search continued, second-guessing began, with some
aviation specialists questioning why Flight 111 had not been
directed to attempt an emergency landing at Yarmouth, which is on
the southwestern tip of Nova Scotia. The Swissair pilot had wanted
to return to Boston, but air-traffic controllers in Moncton, New
Brunswick, said Halifax was closer, and emergency preparations were
made at the provincial capital's airport.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian aviation specialist said that Yarmouth may not have
been considered because although the runway would have been long
enough, emergency equipment, available at Halifax, was not on hand
at Yarmouth.
</P>
<P>
   On the safety front, Bruggiser said Swissair had made the
cockpit wiring changes requested in MD-11s by the U.S. Federal
Aviation Administration two years ago. Without the changes, the FAA
said, the jumbo jets were subject to fires. The Swissair pilot
reported smoke in the cockpit before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
