<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KIDS-ART-2TAK     09-04 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KIDS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN TALK OF BIRDS, BEES AND THE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Mass., Texas, Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ America's children, some as young as 7, are aware
that President Clinton was unfaithful to his wife, but they seem
less interested in the sexual details of the White House scandal
than the moral shortcomings of a man who would deceive and hurt his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and Monica Lewinsky had a thing even though he
was married to somebody else,'' said Chloe Carrano, who is about to
begin third grade in Hastings-on-Hudson. ``First he stood up and
said it wasn't true. But Monica Lewinsky was always near him, and
his wife saw them hugging and stuff. That was the wrong thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lynch, an 11-year-old in the Bronx, also thought Clinton
had lost moral authority. ``He's lying to people who love him and
trust him,'' the boy said. ``That's no president to me. He should
be ashamed of himself for teaching kids bad things.''
</P>
<P>
   Chloe's and Keith's observations came in the days before Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., stepped forward boldly to declare that
the president's conduct ``sends a message of what is acceptable
behavior'' to the children of America.
</P>
<P>
   The children's comments, and those of many more, from 8 to 18,
in well-to-do suburbs, inner-city neighborhoods, Bible Belt
communities and bastions of liberal thinking, seem to confirm
Lieberman's concern that a president cannot lie to and betray his
family and then claim these are private, not public, acts.
</P>
<P>
   Older children used different vocabulary but made the same
point. ``Why would you go around having fun with other women when
your wife's home cooking?'' asked Tyrone Strother, 15, at a Bronx
community center. Tyrone labeled the president a ``player,'' street
slang for a man who cheats on his wife, and also a ``professional
liar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to lie school, not law school,'' the teen-ager said.
</P>
<P>
   In a simpler time, before sex was a staple on television and
before adultery was acknowledged in family life, children were
sheltered from such matters. ``At these kids' age I couldn't have
defined oral sex,'' said Steve Collums, the principal of Briarcrest
Christian School in Memphis, Tenn. ``Now I think that it is more
likely they can't define chastity, because they are so surrounded
by all of this wherever they turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Such nostalgia is not limited by religion or region. Dr. Michael
Shannon, a pediatrician and father of two in Brookline, Mass.,
echoed the lament. ``Children are bombarded with adult concepts,''
he said. ``It's really bad for kids and very disturbing to
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents, like Shannon and his wife, Elaine, spin the radio
dial to avoid X-rated news broadcasts. Others are like Margie Pena,
who runs a community center in Houston and uses developments in the
scandal to teach her 10 children and grandchildren about morals,
decision-making and forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had like round-table discussions,'' Ms. Pena said,
citing provocative topics like fidelity, humility and machismo.
``We have to try to explain to our children that we are human, that
people make mistakes, that everyone has to take responsibility,
that eventually things can catch up to you. These are hard lessons
that we don't talk about enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Most parents take a middle ground. ``I waver between turning off
the TV and explaining it in a watered-down way,'' said Allan
Harris, a high school math teacher, who was watching his
10-year-old daughter Rollerblade at a rink in Larchmont. ``I've
said to her: What if I kissed another woman? How would Mommy
feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Parents like these, many of them the swing voters who put
Clinton in office, inspired Lieberman's speech by telling him of
their struggle to explain current events to their children.
Lieberman said his constituents, already undermined by the sexual
content of movies and music, did not know how to answer the
youngsters' ``intimate and frequently unseemly'' questions or
whether to let them watch the ``sad and sordid'' spectacle on the
evening news.
</P>
<P>
   For months, parents have been braced for questions about the
specific sexual acts between the president and Ms. Lewinsky. But
children rarely walk this treacherous ground.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the wasted worry was the following scene in a
household in Greenwich, Conn., early in the chain of events, when
pundits were parsing which acts the president considered sex and
which he did not. Drew Colbert, 13, went home one day demanding
clarification from his mother, Catherine Clinton, a Civil War
historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really need to talk to you about this because there's
something I don't understand,'' the boy said. His mother paled and
stammered, she said, sure that euphemisms would no longer satisfy
him. Then came Drew's question. ``What is it when someone suborns
someone?'' the boy wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has produced moments worthy of Art Linkletter's
television show ``Kids Say the Darndest Things.''
</P>
<P>
   One 7-year-old told her father that Clinton should be forced to
``fire all his servants and bring his wife breakfast in bed for a
week.'' One 9-year-old said that he had no idea what DNA was but
was sure, without testing, that Ms. Lewinsky's dress was stained
with Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice cream. One 7-year-old boy guessed that oral
sex was ``when you talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But childish misunderstandings and adolescents' guffawing were
the exception in schools and community centers, which were filled
with words of wisdom, like the quotation by James Madison in a
Memphis social studies classroom: ``If men were angels no
government would be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The children seem to take these moral messages to heart.
</P>
<P>
   The younger ones, more often than not, pointed to the lies the
president told. Cory Hinojosa, a Houston 7-year-old, gets a
time-out if he does not tell the truth, and he thinks a similar
sanction is in order for Clinton. ``They should give a punishment
like not to be president the rest of the year,'' Cory said.
</P>
<P>
   The older ones question Clinton's decision-making. Kenneth
Meltin, a Houston 15-year-old, said it was ``inadvisable'' for the
president to have delivered a television address attacking the
special prosecutor, when he was tired after giving hours of grand
jury testimony. Robyn Beavers, a 17-year-old from the suburbs of
Boston, wondered if stress had led to the ``frantic'' decision to
bomb terrorist sites in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Children of all ages identified with the suffering of Hillary
Rodham Clinton and her daughter, Chelsea, many having experienced
the wound of infidelity in their own families.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Ellis, a Memphis 17-year-old, said her father had had
an affair when she was a toddler and her parents had divorced.
Caroline guessed that Chelsea and her mother were riding ``an
emotional roller coaster.'' The president, in her opinion, was
``emotionally abusive.'' As she spoke, the girl fiddled with a
green macrame bracelet marked with the letters WWJD, which stands
for ``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Prosper, a 14-year-old Bronx boy, said that his father
``played'' his mother many years ago, deserting the family and
sending them cascading into poverty and homelessness. If he were
Clinton's wife, Kenny said, ``I'd slap him silly.'' If he were the
president's daughter, ``I'd tell my mom to leave him, forget about
him. And I'd never think about him as an influence again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny and his mother, Naomi, a home health aide, have discussed
the Clinton family in the context of their own. That opportunity
for personal reflection is the lone benefit of the scandal, several
psychologists said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Tubor, director of the clinical psychology doctoral
program at the City University of New York, cited photographs of
the Clinton family headed for their Martha's Vineyard vacation,
with Chelsea walking between her mother and father.
</P>
<P>
   ``That body language speaks to a lot of kids who think it's up
to them to repair things that go on with their parents,'' Tubor
said. ``It is a good opportunity to point out that Chelsea is
surviving, doing well in school, has her own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Such teaching moments are especially rich with teen-agers, said
Jill Schehr, a school psychologist and the mother of 17-year-old
twins. ``If you try to speak to a kid about an area in their life,
they shut down and say, `OK, Mom, OK,''' she said. ``But you can
talk about Clinton as a symbol. It's in this other zone, like
theater, and that distance lets you bring it into their world.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers are fascinated by a powerful man who is
simultaneously charming, intelligent and crippled by
self-destructive behavior. ``That can have a lot of power in the
adolescent population, because they are in the process of bringing
together the different parts of their identity,'' Ms. Schehr said.
</P>
<P>
   The flaws of this president, so familiar to the young, dominated
conversation one recent afternoon in the courtyard at the Point, a
community development agency in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   First the children spoke of infidelity. ``He dissed his wife by
being a player,'' said Keith Lynch. ``What if he didn't have a
condom on? He could have got AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Ortiz, 12, focused on sorrow rather than disease. His
14-year-old brother betrays his girlfriends by carrying on with
more than one at a time. ``When they find out, they cry so much,''
Nick said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the subject turned to deceit. Keith bet that the president
was not so different from him. ``I lie when I'm trying to get out
of a whooping,'' the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   Nick quickly saw the flaw in that reasoning, for a sixth-grader
or a commander in chief. ``Once they find out you lied,'' the
12-year-old said, ``you just get a worse whooping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
