<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTELLO-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COSTELLO' TAKES ITS SHOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Sue Costello is blond, thin and a ball of energy.
But she's nothing like Jenna Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Costello'' is the new sitcom loosely based on her life, living
and working in South Boston, but any comparisons to ``Good Will
Hunting'' would be like comparing ``Seinfeld'' to ``Serpico''
because they both took place in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   She has her private conversations in the men's room, but can
never be confused with Fonzie of ``Happy Days.''
</P>
<P>
   Her job is at a bar in Beantown. However, ``Cheers'' this is
not.
</P>
<P>
   This is Sue Murphy's (Costello) world and it is unlike any
you've seen on network television. Costello and ``Costello'' are
unique, all right _ maybe too unique for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   The show is often loud and shrill, and the language at times is
coarser than it is funny.
</P>
<P>
   The Southie (that's what they call locals of places like
Dorchester _ pronounced DAWchister _ in Massachusetts) works at a
pub called the Bulldog. She dumps her studly but dim-witted
boyfriend and shocks everyone by going to college.
</P>
<P>
   Sue's mother, Lottie (Jenny O'Hara), is a deeply religious woman
and dutiful wife who can't understand why her offspring would dump
such an eligible bachelor. After all he just got a job as a transit
worker.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Spud (Dan Lauria), is a hard-working man. Her
brother is a lazy malingerer who would fake an injury to get on
worker's comp and have more drinking time.
</P>
<P>
   The executive producer of the project is Cheryl Holliday, who
was a bigwig at ``King of the Hill.'' There is no doubt that she
has the skills to put together a quality show depicting characters
who aren't from New York or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   South Boston is home to hard-hat-wearing, beer-swilling, former
high school hockey fans who are honest and gritty. That being the
reality, ``Costello'' is certainly genuine.
</P>
<P>
   It is the type of show in which people fall off bar stools and
fistfights are not a shocker.
</P>
<P>
   Still this show needs some work. Once Costello calms down, finds
the volume switch on her character, the sitcom may be able to
benefit from the gift of a ``King of the Hill'' lead-in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0434 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRANDPARENTS-SONG-LAD     09-04 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANDPARENTS-SONG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SONG FOR GRANDPARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who sneaked you a cookie when Mom said no? Who
bought that bike that Dad said was too expensive? Who cuddled and
coddled you when you needed it?
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents!
</P>
<P>
   To honor them on National Grandparents Day _ by presidential
proclamation, the first Sunday after Labor Day _ Symphony in the
Glen and a chorus of Los Angeles-area children will perform a
special song at Sunday's concert just for Grandma and Grandpa.
</P>
<P>
   And, since it's an all-Mozart event, ``The Grandparents Song''
is sung to the tune of one of Mozart's most famous arias, !ital!La
ci darem la mano!off! from ``Don Giovanni.''
</P>
<P>
   Orchestra conductor and Emmy-winning composer Arthur B.
Rubinstein, a Hollywood Hills resident who penned the lyrics to the
commemorative tune, said he inherited his musical aptitude from his
grandfather and wanted to honor grandparents everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Orchestra manager) Barbara Ferris and I were sitting and
talking about it and I started singing, `Let's sing a song for
Grandma.' Barbara said, `What is that?' I said, `I'm not sure,' but
I kept working on it. The Mozart melody just seemed perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, he had completed a lyric singing the praises of
grandparents' patience, wisdom and love, all valuable commodities
elders pass along to their grandchildren, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The song dubs Grandma ``the one we turn to when everything goes
wrong ... When she's away, I seem to get in trouble ... She'll kiss
away your tears.'' And Grandpa is ``the one we count on when no one
else will do. He knows all there is to know and teaches it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Grandparents Day Council has proclaimed
Rubinstein's composition its official song.
</P>
<P>
   A group of kids from a Montessori school in Glendale and others
who volunteered to join the chorus after a July 5 concert in the
park have been learning the lyrics from an audiotape Rubinstein
made. The kids rehearsed together for the first time last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The song has a sweet simplicity,'' Rubinstein said. ``And kids
are very smart and they pick up on things like this very quickly.
So I think the concert's going to be wonderful, divine madness.''
</P>
<P>
   A special guest at Sunday's concert will be Jessica McQuade, 10,
the granddaughter of Marian McQuade of West Virginia, who persuaded
President Carter in 1978 to proclaim a special day to honor
grandparents. Jessica will sing with the local chorus of 9- to
13-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour concert _ the third of four conducted this summer
by the nonprofit Symphony in the Glen _ begins at 3 p.m. in
Griffith Park. Admission and parking are free, but concertgoers are
asked to bring a canned food donation for the hungry families of
Los Angeles, to be distributed by the Salvation Army. The concert
area is a short walk up a little hill behind the park's
merry-go-round at 4800 Crystal Springs Drive; shuttle buses also
will be provided.
</P>
<P>
   From 1:30 to 2:30 p.m., before the concert, there'll be free
kids' activities, including music-related coloring books, KUSC
Classical Kids Micester Singers and Rubinstein's junior maestro
class, where kids can learn how to conduct an orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth year for Symphony in the Glen, which is
supported by private and corporate donations and grants. The
group's final concert this year will be an Oct. 25 performance of
``Peter and the Wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (213) 955-6976 or visit the Web site
at www.symphonyintheglen.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
