<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 5
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Thursday, August 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August
14, misstated the involvement of the League of Conservation Voters
in the Idaho Congressional campaign of Dan Williams. While the
league has hired a full-time political consultant to promote Mr.
Williams's candidacy and plans to spend $200,000 to promote his
campaign, those actions are not directly connected to the Williams
campaign. Under Federal law, the league must work independently,
without coordination or contact with the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT (moved on Monday, August 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 17,
about unfounded health scares referred incompletely to Government
action on Alar, a chemical once used to make apples ripen
uniformly. In May 1989, the Environmental Protection Agency
announced steps to prohibit the use of Alar on apples and other
foods, but allowed the chemical to stay on the market for at least
15 months. In the announcement, the agency said the chemical might
pose an unacceptable risk of cancer in humans. Before the ban could
take effect, the chemical's maker, Uniroyal, voluntarily removed it
from the market. It is no longer used on food in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The article also omitted a description of the finances of the
American Council on Science and Health, which has criticized the
furor over Alar. It is a nonprofit organization that receives 60
percent of its financing from private foundations, individual
contributions and sales. The rest of its support comes from
corporations, including food manufacturers. This year Uniroyal
contributed $10,000, which is slightly more than one-half of 1
percent of the council's $1.6 million budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
