<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush, Brown inactive, leaving safety thin
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons must de-activate eight players for Sunday's
game at Carolina, four by the NFL's Friday deadline. The early
inactives are S Devin Bush, who hasn't recovered after spraining
his knee on Aug. 14 at Detroit, rookie S Omar Brown, rookie RB Ken
Oxendine and LB Ben Talley.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Brown and Bush, who will be the primary backup
safety when he returns to health, leaves just three active safeties
_ free safety Eugene Robinson, strong safety William White and
Chris Bayne, who has worked almost exclusively at strong safety in
the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think (Bush) needs another week,'' coach Dan Reeves
said. ``He's close, but I just think it's smart when you count on
someone that much that you don't put him out there until he's
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   CB Randy Fuller or Ronnie Bradford, the nickel safety, could
play back there if needed. Fuller is still a possible inactive
player with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four remaining inactives will be No. 3 quarterback
Tony Graziani. Under NFL rules, the No. 3 quarterback dresses out.
If he plays before the start of the fourth quarter, however, the
first two quarterbacks cannot re-enter the game under any
circumstances. The No. 3 quarterback can play in the fourth
quarter, though, and the first two QBs can be re-inserted if
coaches decide to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Byron's back
</P>
<P>
   Second-year running back Byron Hanspard was at practice Friday
morning, one week after suffering a season-ending knee injury.
Hanspard tore the anterior cruciate ligament and the patella tendon
in his left knee while being tackled on a 22-yard TD run last
Friday against the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard faces a long rehabilitation, with the patella tendon
injury considered very serious. Team doctor Andrew Bishop said
there have been only a handful of instances in NFL history where a
player tore both the ACL and the patella tendon at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard was on crutches, wearing a brace from the top of his
left thigh to his ankle. His right knee was wrapped, too, because
doctors had to take part of the patella tendon in his left knee in
order to repair his shredded ACL in the left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons and Panthers will play on a new playing field at
Ericsson Stadium. ... Carolina tight end Wesley Walls, 32, is the
only offensive starter for the Panthers over 27. ... Former
first-round draft pick Tshimanga Biakabutuka had 104 yards against
the Falcons in the Panthers' victory in Charlotte last year, but he
remains under heavy scrutiny. In the preseason, he rushed 28 times
for 36 yards, 25 of them in the final preseason game. Fred Lane
will start at running back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
