<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McLaughlin makes mark, wins Dura-Lube 200 pole
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darlington, S.C. _ Mike McLaughlin has been coming to Darlington
Raceway for five years without fanfare, but all that changed Friday
when he won the pole for today's Busch Grand National Dura-Lube
200.
</P>
<P>
   In putting his Chevrolet up front with a speed of 164.661 mph,
McLaughlin became only the second Busch driver to start inside the
front row .
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin finished second here a year ago behind Winston Cup
regular Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car felt so good on the first lap that I was able to drive
it even harder on the second lap,'' McLaughlin said. ``We actually
picked up (speed) on the second lap, which a lot of people aren't
able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Sadler was second fastest in 164.562 mph and Buckshot
Jones was just a tick slower in third at 164.551 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably one of the best laps I've had around here,''
said Jones, who is fifth among Busch Grand National series leaders.
``Being able to start that close to the front makes a big
difference. We've been successful testing here and the car has
gotten a lot better in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Series points leader Dale Earnhardt Jr. qualified 34th and will
start on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   Split up
</P>
<P>
   Randy Lajoie will not return in 1999 as driver of the No. 74
BACE Motorsports Monte Carlo. Lajoie joined the team in 1996 after
Johnny Benson moved to the Winston Cup cirucit in 1966. With Lajoie
behind the wheel, the team claimed two series championships, 11
victories, 33 top fives and 51 top 10 finishes. The team is fourth
in the points standings. Lajoie told owner Bill Baumgardner he
wants to explore other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler to the Woods
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Sadler and the Wood Brothers made it official Friday.
Sadler will be in the Winston Cup No. 21 Citgo Ford Taurus in 1999.
The 23-year-old Virginian replaces Michael Waltrip. ``A tremendous
opportunity for me,'' Sadler said. ``And being with the Wood
Brothers can only jump start my transition into Winston Cup
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Minding the boss
</P>
<P>
   Prior to starting his qualifying lap for Sunday's Pepsi Southern
400, rookie Steve Park asked his boss, Dale Earnhardt, if he had
any advice. ``Yeah,'' Earnhardt said. ``Just keep the car out of
the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
