<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-POLE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett out to foil bonus bunch
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darlington, S.C. _ The way Dale Jarrett sees it, you have to run
on the edge somewhat to win the pole at this egg-shaped 1.366-mile
track.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what he did Friday, running a near-perfect lap of
168.879 mph to qualify to start on the inside of the front row in
Sunday's Southern 500.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton threw a scare into the Jarrett camp, however, when
he ran the second-fastest lap, 168.677, to grab the outside pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down here testing a few weeks ago and felt like we had
something that could get the pole,'' said Jarrett, whose last pole
came 21 races ago at Las Vegas. ``But when Ward put up that speed
up there, I wasn't sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace was third fastest, 168.642 mph; John Andretti
fourth, 168.573; and Jeff Gordon rounded out the top five at
168.261 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett will be trying to spoil five drivers' chances for a
million-dollar bonus. Gordon, Mark Martin, Bobby Labonte, Mike
Skinner and Dale Earnhardt could grab the prize by following their
top-five finishes at the Brickyard 400, the most recent race in the
No Bull 5 bonus program, with a win here.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our job here, to keep anybody from winning a million
dollars, and for us to win the Southern 500 trophy ... and give
ourselves a chance to win a million at Talladega (Oct. 11),''
Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin qualified 10th, the first time he's started outside the
top seven in the last seven races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we could run faster,'' he said. ``I don't know for
sure, but I felt like we were having an engine problem. We'll
change it.''
</P>
<P>
   The top 25 qualifiers Friday included 15 Fords, six Chevrolets
and four Pontiacs.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a surprise in the top 10, it had to be Bill Elliott
in seventh. It will be his best start in the last 10 events, and
only his second top 10 in the past 15 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``This track is always a little tough every time I come back
here,'' Elliott said. ``In the spring, we really messed up here and
had a bad run. Today, I just wanted so bad to get a good, decent
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
