<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Progress in talks may avert AirTran walkouts
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AirTran Airlines and its flight attendant union reported
progress in contract talks Friday, boosting hopes that Labor Day
weekend walkouts against the carrier will be averted or at least
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides faced a midnight deadline, after which, if there
was no deal, the union would be free to begin a campaign of spot
walkouts aimed at disrupting the carrier's operations.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said it expects no disruptions even if the union
follows through on the threat, because it has hired replacement
workers and taken other steps to counteract random walkouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making some headway'' toward a contract agreement that
would end the threat of walkouts, union spokesman Jeff Zack said
late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some movement today and we're closer than we were,''
said Thomas Kalil, a senior vice president at AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they didn't reach an agreement, the two sides could
extend negotiations, Zack said.
</P>
<P>
   The union hasn't threatened a mass strike, but rather a campaign
called CHAOS _ Creating Havoc Around Our System _ in which members
would stage walkouts from selected flights. The goal is to cause
uncertainty among travelers, cost AirTran business and prod
management into a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Flight Attendants and AirTran, formerly
ValuJet, have been in on-and-off talks since 1995. Issues include
wages and a union demand that all of the airline's 700 attendants
pay union fees, even if they are not active members.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran is Atlanta's second-largest carrier, with about 120
daily departures.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
