<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest goal for A. Jones: youngest in 30-30 club
 &HT;    ByJack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ He is already the youngest 20-20 player in
major-league history. With 25 home runs and 23 stolen bases and
three weeks left in the regular season, can Andruw Jones join the
30-30 club?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible,'' the Braves center fielder said. ``We've got
22 games left and right now I'm feeling good, hitting the ball
good. Bobby (Cox) has given me opportunities to steal bases. That's
why I'm putting up those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Friday's opener of a four-game series with the Mets,
Jones was batting .462 in his last 11 games, with five homers, 13
RBIs and seven steals. When he homered in the ninth inning
Wednesday against Houston, he became the second-youngest Brave in
franchise history to hit 25 homers in a season, at the age of 21
years, four months. Eddie Mathews remains the youngest, having hit
his 25th homer on Sept. 27, 1952, 16 days shy of his 21st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jones, in his first season as a regular, could go 30-30. ``I
had 18 homers last year and I didn't play every day,'' he said.
``You get a chance to play every day, you got a chance to put up
some numbers. I didn't start well (4-for-40, then a .204 average in
the first month) but I stayed focused and got better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the significance of 30-30, ``It's good to hit 30 homers,
steal 30 bases,'' ``I did those things in the minors,'' said Jones,
who also leads the NL with 17 outfield assists and is tied for
second with eight triples. ``It's a different level now but if you
do it in the minor leagues, some people might say you can do it in
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely, I would be proud (to reach 30-30). My family
would be proud of me. They are already proud of me, the way I'm
playing. They know the way things started at the beginning of the
season, (people saying), `Oh, he has to go to the minors, he has a
bad attitude.' I don't worry about those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I reach both (30-30), I'll be fine. If I don't, I'll be
fine. To come off a bad start and get to 30 homers, or 25 homers,
is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Mending
</P>
<P>
   Danny Bautista, on the disabled list since Aug. 25 with a
partial tear of the medial collateral ligament in his right knee,
is getting healthier but isn't ready to play yet. ``It's still
hurting me a little bit,'' said Bautista, who constantly wears a
knee brace and isn't eligible to come off the DL until Wednesday.
``The doctor told me I've got to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Bautista, who hasn't run yet, said he's two or three days away
from doing so. ``I'm going to try to run, hit a little bit,'' he
said. ``It really bothers me when I turn, twist. I'll wait a couple
of more days and see how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Helms is technically back on the Braves roster. In a paper
shuffle, the backup third baseman, recalled from Richmond Aug. 27
to replace Bautista, was optioned Monday to Class A Eugene to make
room for Curtis Pride on the roster. But Helms never reported
(Eugene's season ended Wednesday) and was recalled Thursday once
rosters were expanded for September. ... Andres Galarraga sat out
the second game of his three-game suspension Friday. ... Bobby Cox
began the weekend with 1,403 career wins, needing four to pass
Jimmy Dykes for 20th place on the all-time managerial list.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
