<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-TECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech, new-look Dogs hit the field
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After an offseason of optimism and an August of anticipation,
Georgia and Georgia Tech will write the first chapters of their
1998 college football seasons today. Both have reasons to be
excited.
</P>
<P>
   In Athens, No. 19 Georgia will unveil a new batch of skilled
players as the Bulldogs host Kent at Sanford Stadium (5 p.m., Media
One pay-per-view). Georgia, which finished the 1997 season with a
10-2 record and a No. 10 national ranking, will be out to prove it
can be a contender in the rugged SEC East despite having to replace
the talented trio of quarterback Mike Bobo, running back Robert
Edwards and receiver Hines Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys were great players, but we feel like we've got some
talented people who have been waiting for a chance,'' said Georgia
coach Jim Donnan, who begins his third season in Athens. ``We're
excited to see how they will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Today marks the debut of freshman quarterback Quincy Carter, who
has returned to college football after two years playing
professional baseball. Carter, a Parade All-American at Southwest
DeKalb in 1995, was chosen Wednesday as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   While Georgia must break in a new quarterback, Georgia Tech will
put one of the ACC's best on the field when the Yellow Jackets host
Boston College today at 3:30 p.m. (WSB). In the last half of the
1997 season, junior Joe Hamilton played as well as any quarterback
in the country, a major reason why the Yellow Jackets went 7-5 and
won their first bowl game since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the maturity and the leadership Joe has shown since
last year. But we know he can get better and more importantly, he
knows he can get better,'' Tech coach George O'Leary said. ``I've
got a lot of confidence about Joe's ability to lead a team.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Georgia Tech is going to make some noise in the ACC this
season, it must improve on a defense that finished last in the
conference, giving up 429 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
