<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Getting harder all the time to get to the quarterback'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons managed 55 sacks last year, second in the
NFL and tops in franchise history. Nine of those sacks came in two
games against Carolina, both Falcons losses. Right end Chuck Smith
is the leader of the Bomb Squad, as he calls it, dropping the
quarterback 12 times last year, sixth in the league.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Falcons are to win at Carolina for the first time
after three losses, they will need a better pass rush than in the
last two preseason games, when they didn't manage one. In fact,
Falcons starters Smith, right tackle Shane Dronett, left tackle
Travis Hall and left end Lester Archambeau were shut out in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal-Constitution asked Smith about rushing the passer.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Can you explain the lack of sacks in the preseason?
</P>
<P>
   Smith: It seems like everybody is changing their style, keeping
(backs) in (to block), running shorter routes, (quarterbacks)
taking shorter drops. It's getting harder all the time to get to
the quarter- back.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What can you do to adapt?
</P>
<P>
   Smith: The days of the pure speed rush are going to be gone
soon. That's why you need to develop inside moves, power moves. The
guy I go against, (Carolina tackle) Blake Brockermeyer, is
aggressive. He's got a pretty good punch (initial blow after the
snap), good balance _ he's good. You got to go hard and mix things
up. Blocking balls (at the line) is going to be huge nowadays.
That's why you see so many guys getting their hands up.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What can the defense do in general to adapt?
</P>
<P>
   Smith: (Defensive backs have) got to hold receivers up, so we
can get some extra time. And it's great to get teams down (on the
scoreboard) so they have to throw downfield and take a deeper
(quarterback) drop. We've got to blitz some, too, because offenses
have gotten more creative.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Any other disadvantages work against you?
</P>
<P>
   Smith: We can't flinch anymore (to draw offensive linemen
offsides). It seems like every little advantage we once had is
gone. Man, it's tough.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Carolina quarterback Kerry Collins seems slow-footed; is he
one of the easier quarterbacks to catch?
</P>
<P>
   Smith: I can't say that Kerry is easy to get to. Over the years,
we've gotten back thereand not gotten him. Last year, Kerry made a
great play to get away from me and run for a first down. I was
running as hard as I could, and I couldn't catch him. I won't say
he's Steve Young, but he does a pretty good job sometimes avoiding
the rush.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
