</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREW APPEARED IN CONTROL UNTIL PLANE DISAPPEARED FROM RADAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-VICTIMS, CRASH-DITCH,
CRASH-SWISSAIR and CRASH-PLANE) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY and MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ As grieving families from several
countries began to converge on this tiny fishing village Friday,
officials looking for the cause of the crash of Swissair Flight 111
on Wednesday said that it appears that the crew was in control of
the jet and making rational decisions about how to land until the
plane abruptly disappeared from radar.
</P>
<P>
   The chief Canadian investigator said that the MD-11 jet changed
course only once, when the pilot was told he was closer to Halifax
than Boston. About 58 nautical miles from the Halifax runway, the
pilot began to make wide circles and dump fuel as he descended, a
procedure essential for the jet to make the extraordinarily rapid
descent from 33,000 feet above sea level to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The very end of the plane's radar track, just before it
disappeared from controllers' screens, shows erratic movement.
Asked if this could indicate that the plane or the cockpit crew was
disabled, Gerden said that ``it is unclear as to accuracy of the
information provided by radar at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerden did not elaborate, but experts said although that the
erratic movement that showed up on the radar might indicated that
the plane had dropped dropped suddenly out of the sky, it is also
possible that a radio on board that responds to radar signals,
called a transponder, might have failed. In normal operation, the
transponder listens for a query from radar and responds with a
short signal that gives the plane's identity and altitude. The
radar system calculates the direction by noting which way the radar
was pointed when it heard the answer, and calculates the distance
from the interval between the question and the answer. But the
transponder could have been disabled by a fire, or it could have
been intentionally shut down by the crew, which may have been
flipping circuit breakers, hoping to eliminate an electrical fire.
</P>
<P>
   Without the transponder, the controllers would have to rely on
``primary radar,'' microwave energy bounced off the plane's
aluminum skin, but this is far less accurate. And aircrafts'
primary radar blips sometimes disappear into clutter, caused by
birds or other interference.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator, Vic Gerden, added that the crew's
communication with air-traffic controllers was ``professional
throughout.'' He said that the crew twice indicated that it had a
serious problem with the plane, but crew members offered no details
except that there was smoke in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   On several fronts Friday, the recovery and investigation
frustrated both officials and grieving families eager for answers.
In choppy waters and thick fog, searchers were able to locate
almost no large parts of the plane, though debris that they did
find from the sea and shoreline showed no signs of fire damage or
other obvious clues.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise and frustration of many investigators, a
submarine equipped with sophisticated sonar and other underwater
listening devices caught no whisper from the ``pingers'' attached
to the jet's black boxes _ the flight data recorder and cockpit
voice recorder. As a result, investigators had little to go on
beyond radar tapes and the tapes of the conversations between the
crew and the ground. Investigators were still pouring over this
information on Friday and said they would release a transcript of
the conversations and a radar map on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But other aspects of the investigation began to move forward. In
New York, the FBI joined the Federal Aviation Administration in
examining cargo manifests for the flight to determine whether any
hazardous materials were on board, either declared or undeclared.
The flight did not carry any materials owned by the airline,
investigators said Friday. That is significant, officials said,
because in the crash of a Valuejet DC9 in Florida two years ago,
the cause of a fire on board turned out to be hazardous oxygen
generators in boxes labeled ``comat,'' meaning company materials.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials also said they were looking closely at six
directives they have issued since 1994 regarding flaws that might
cause smoke or fire on MD-11s. Those are among several orders
issued by the agency for planes under U.S. jurisdiction after
scattered instances of fire or smoke on that type of jet. The
Swissair jet was registered in Switzerland and was not subject to
U.S. orders, but officials said that most European airlines
routinely adopt the FAA directives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a military base several miles to the northeast, medical
examiners also joined the investigation, performing toxicology
tests on the victims' remains that may indicate whether passengers
had inhaled smoke or other fumes before the crash. The medical
examiners, working in a makeshift morgue in an airplane hangar,
began a second painstaking day of identifying the bodies, which are
stored in five refrigerated trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But they said late Friday afternoon that they had not been able
to positively identify a single body yet. The examiners also said
they were working to try to identify the bodies primarily using
dental records and other medical information so that they could
spare the families from having to view the bodies, most of which
are not intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was a simple problem of visually identifying 299
people, it would take at the most three days,'' said Dr. John Butt,
Nova Scotia's chief medical examiner. ``This is not that kind of
task,'' he said and added, ``I have a certain sensitivity and
reluctance to discuss this further.''
</P>
<P>
   As searchers and investigators settled in for what they said
would likely be weeks of work, the families of the victims began to
arrive to be nearer to the place where the jet went down. Officials
said they expected as many as 800 relatives and friends, many of
which arrived in Halifax Friday afternoon on Swissair flights from
New York and Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
