<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMEN-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HOUSE THAT YIELDED BODIES, AN UNEXPECTED ONE IS FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Surprised law enforcement authorities
revealed Friday that they had identified a woman they did not
expect to find among the bodies investigators have unearthed from
the tumbledown green home of an unemployed school aide and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the body of a 34-year-old missing Westchester
County woman, the authorities said, raised new possibilities: that
Kendall Francois, the 27-year-old unemployed school aide, secreted
more corpses than the eight he had he had previously told police
were hidden in the basement and attic, or that one of the eight
women may be buried elsewhere or is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, police arrested Francois, charged him with strangling
a prostitute and said they believed he was responsible for the
murders of seven more women, most of them prostitutes. Some had
been missing for as long as two years.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Dutchess County District Attorney William Grady said
that a total of six bodies had been taken out of the house and the
skeletal remains of two others had been located and would be taken
out of the house once all surrounding evidence is scanned. Of the
six, he said, four have been positively identified. But one of
those four, he said, was someone who police did not expect to find:
Audrey Pugliese, a 34-year-old woman with a record of three minor
arrests, none for prostitution, who moved to Poughkeepsie six
months ago after living most of her life in Westchester County. She
was last seen three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Ms. Pugliese, the three other women positively
identified are Catina Newmaster, 25; Catherine Marsh, 31, and Gina
Barone, 29. The other women who police have said were most likely
buried in the house are Wendy Meyers, 30; Kathleen Hurley, 47;
Michelle Eason, 27; Mary Healey Giaccone, 29, and Sandra Jean
French, 51.
</P>
<P>
   Grady said the possibility that a ninth victim might be hidden
in the house or in the overgrown backyard had spurred the police to
call for special radar-controlled detection equipment that can
pinpoint human remains through earth, wood and construction
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Grady also responded for a second day to criticism that the
county's officials did not respond seriously enough to at least two
earlier attacks on prostitutes. He revealed for the first time that
Francois had been under suspicion for a few months before he was
arrested. But he said the two prostitutes who told police that he
had tried to strangle them did not do so in time or produce enough
``legally sufficient'' evidence to allow the authorities to procure
a search warrant for his house, which is at 99 Fulton Avenue _ a
block from Vassar College.
</P>
<P>
   As police officers continued to search the house Friday, new
details emerged about Francois.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his former teachers at Arlington High School in La
Grange, outside the town of Poughkeepsie, remembered a curious,
diligent and affable young man.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tornatore, a shop teacher, remembered how in metalworking
class Francois worked at a lathe for months and meticulously carved
castles, knights, bishops, pawns and other chess pieces out of
brass and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Grabowski, Francois' freshman social studies teacher,
remembered him as a solid ``B'' student who ``always had his
homework done,'' asked thoughtful questions about topics like
slavery, and took on extra credit assignments in history, a
favorite subject.
</P>
<P>
   He said Francois was also very rational and reasoned matters
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty good at critical thinking,'' he said. ``I never
saw any sign of emotional disturbance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
