<HEADER>
A0463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS &LR;      09-04 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BABE Ruth trained on booze and bawdy behavior. Chances are he never
lifted a weight or swallowed a ``dietary supplement.'' And all
those day games left him with plenty of long nights to partake of
earthly delights.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Babe been in shape, I mean really in shape, he might
have hit 100 home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, had he used creatine and ``andro,'' he might have belted
200.
</P>
<P>
   Moot point. Cripes, Mark McGwire stands on the brink of
surpassing Ruth's total of 60 home runs in 154 games before Labor
Day, an achievement than can only be termed, well, Ruthian. But
that doesn't mean he will eclipse Ruth's legend. No way. The
Bambino dwarfed his would-be peers to such an extent that he belted
more dingers in his greatest seasons than did a goodly number of
teams.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, on the other hand, trails even the pantywaist Twins and
Pirates (94 each) by a significant margin.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, what he _ and, yes, Sammy Sosa, too _ is doing is
phenomenal. And regarding St. Mac, his feats are in no way made
bogus by what he puts in his body. Remember, Ruth and Roger Maris
had nicotine coursing through their veins.
</P>
<P>
   Maris was a multipack-per-day smoker. How juiced was he? His
hair was probably falling out because of all the cigs. The closer
he got to Ruth in '61, the more he lit up. Likewise, all those hot
dogs Ruth reportedly ate were probably full of steroids and God
only knows what else.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line on androstenedione, a ``precursor'' molecule
that's a kissin' cousin of the male sex hormone testosterone, is
that it's as legal as soda pop and highly unlikely to be harmful.
Most doctors I have spoken with consider the more widely used, and
similarly unregulated, creatine to carry bigger baggage because of
how it dehydrates the muscles, causing cramps and stressing
tendons.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, McGwire uses both andro and creatine, as do more of
his buddies than you may realize.
</P>
<P>
   ``To compete at that level,'' says Dr. Walt Lowe, team physician
for the Rockets and the University of Houston, ``pretty much
requires a better-living-through-chemistry approach. You have to do
more than work out. Virtually every professional athlete has some
form of performance-enhancing substance in his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that what McGwire has accomplished is tainted because
of andro is baloney. It's not a steroid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it have any of the negative side effects, the worst of
which can be to cause liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe suggests that smokeless tobacco, which many baseball
players continue to use, is ``a huge performance enhancer,''
noting: ``You take the heavy users off it, and they get sluggish
and lose their edge.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA, the NFL and the International Olympic Committee
have labeled andro a no-no. Why? Because its residue, what Lowe
calls its ``breakdown substances,'' resembles that of steroids,
meaning it can be used as a masking agent for steroids during urine
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Note that baseball does test, with just cause, for steroids, the
observable evidence of which happens to be shockingly apparent. See
a broad-shouldered twentysomething with severe acne on his back,
and you can bet he's on 'roids.
</P>
<P>
   Because andro is a natural substance produced by the body, the
FDA pays it no mind. What little data exist suggest that it helps
to boost testosterone levels by no more than 15 percent, and only
temporarily. If that correlates to McGwire's being 15 percent
stronger, then his home-run count probably isn't being positively
enhanced _ the balls are just traveling farther. Say, 475 feet
instead of 400.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-eye coordination required to jack them into the
hinterlands isn't being impacted by andro or creatine. As McGwire's
defenders are quick to point out, the guy did hit 49 home runs as a
rookie. Apparently, he just knows how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a large side of me that wishes McGwire wouldn't
erase the Babe's 154-game record of 60, one of sport's most sacred
numbers and _ Maris' 61 in 162 games notwithstanding _ most
enduring.
</P>
<P>
   How long ago was 1927? Charles Lindbergh completed the first
nonstop solo trans-Atlantic crossing that May. In September, when
Ruth socked 17 homers, the filming of the first-ever talking motion
picture, The Jazz Singer, was being completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty, count 'em, 60!'' Ruth roared when he returned to the
Yankees' clubhouse on the afternoon of his final shot. ``Let some
other s.o.b. match that!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, oddly, only weeks after the 50th anniversary of the Babe's
death, it's virtually certain to happen. But just as the years
haven't made the big man any less larger than life, McGwire's tear
won't, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
