<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' FIRST OPTION: BIGGER RECEIVERS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Giants are the youngest team in the
National Football League, just as they were last season. They will
also return 20 of 22 starters from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the Giants, who open the season on Sunday against the
Washington Redskins at Giants Stadium, are not the same team that
made a late charge to the division title last season. This year's
Giants have been modified in important ways.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while the Redskins signed defensive tackles Dana
Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson in part to try to stop the Giant
running game, the Giants decided they had to get bigger receivers
if they were going to succeed against the league's top defensive
backs _ two of whom are Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington secondary, led by the All-Pro cornerbacks Darrell
Green and Cris Dishman, held Giants wide receivers to 10 catches
and 113 receiving yards in two games last season. In contrast,
Washington's wide receivers, led by the 6-foot-3-inch Michael
Westbrook, combined for 29 receptions and 371 yards in the two
games against the Giants _ and that was with Jason Sehorn shadowing
Westbrook.
</P>
<P>
   The Giant secondary is smaller with 5-foot-10-inch Conrad
Hamilton replacing the injured Sehorn, and unavoidably, more
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   But offensively, the Giants' receiving corps will benefit
greatly from the presence of rookie Joe Jurevicius, who is
6-foot-5, and from a rejuvenated Amani Toomer, who is 6-foot-3.
Expect both to see considerable time against Green and Dishman,
especially if Ike Hilliard, Chris Calloway and David Patten _ none
taller than 5-foot-11 _ fail to improve their production against
the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Hamilton's debut as a starting cornerback for
Sehorn will draw attention from quarterback Gus Frerotte. Marcus
Buckley also begins his tenure as the team's regular strongside
linebacker _ the position played for most of the last six seasons
by Corey Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley has started 13 games at linebacker in the last five
years, but he has never been able to hold a starting assignment.
Generally considered too small to disrupt an opponent's running
game at the point of attack, the 240-pound Buckley has been
relegated to backup duties. But with Miller in a forced retirement
because of a herniated neck disk, it is Buckley's job to keep now.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Phillips, a second-year player, is Buckley's only true
backup. Phillips, a college defensive end, was not switched to
linebacker until midseason a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few other minor changes Giants fans might notice as
well. The diminutive Patten, who is listed as 5-foot-9 but appears
shorter, is almost 10 pounds heavier because of an off-season
weight program. Running back Tiki Barber is about five pounds
heavier.
</P>
<P>
   Barber may look different to Giant fans, too. He'll be playing
for the first time in the NFL without a black visor across his
eyes. The NFL no longer allows the use of a black shield that
attaches to a player's face mask. Team trainers complained that
when they attended to players who were knocked out or dazed during
a game, they could not see the players' eyes to determine if they
had concussions or other kinds of neurological damage.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers did not want to have to take off players' helmets,
which could be risky, just to examine their eyes, or to shine a
light in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it,'' Barber said of the new rule. ``Now everyone
can see where I'm looking.''
</P>
<P>
   With league permission, some players with special eye problems
will be allowed to use clear visors.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Scott Gragg, who would have become an unrestricted
free agent after this season, agreed to a renegotiated contract
that retains him through the 2001 season. It will reportedly pay
him more than $2 million annually. Gragg, who did not receive an
offer as a restricted free agent last winter, would have been paid
$397,000 this season had he chosen to wait and pursue free agency
after the 1998 season. ... The Redskins will ride a special
seven-car Amtrak train to the New York area on Saturday. For the
last 27 years, the team has flown to play its away games with the
Giants. It won 12 of those 27 games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
