<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CARIBBEAN-PARADE-A     09-04 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARIBBEAN-PARADE-ART-710(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARIBBEAN NEW YORKERS PREPARE LAVISH, AND POPULAR, PAGEANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA and GARRY PIERRE-PIERRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn block lined with auto repair shops becomes
an open-air rehearsal studio for three competing orchestras. As
dusk falls on Parkside Avenue, quick, trained hands strike rows
upon rows of carefully tuned oil barrels; mallets are beat on rusty
tire irons; and the warm August nights fill up with the syncopated
sounds of calypso.
</P>
<P>
   In the one corner of a shop where the roof has not yet collapsed
from rain, a man who makes his living as a security guard
constructs tall, baroque costumes out of cardboard and peacock
feathers. Nearby, teen-agers brought up on basketball and Biggie
Smalls spend the evening mastering the steel-band songs of their
Caribbean parents.
</P>
<P>
   A New World tradition is being remade once more in New York: the
Caribbean heart of Brooklyn is getting ready for its annual
late-summer Carnival, the city's biggest, most extravagant parade.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, in the 31st annual West Indian American Day
Carnival, schoolteachers and nannies will shed their workday
clothes for skimpy thongs and dreamy costumes. The grandchildren of
migrants from the American South will play steel drum with the
children of Trinidadian immigrants. In a distinctly Brooklyn mix,
Haitian ``rara'' bands with their goatskin drums will file among
the tassa drummers, and mammoth trucks will roll down the Parkway,
blasting soca and reggae.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a small, homespun celebration in Harlem in the
1930s has grown into a pageant surpassing older, better-known
processions like the St. Patrick's Day or the Puerto Rican Day
parades. Immigration from the islands has surged, and today, New
York City is home to an estimated 600,000 Caribbean-Americans, the
bulk of them in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But the growth of the parade, and its dozens of attendant
parties, concerts and competitions, is more than a testament to
rising Caribbean immigration. It is also a reflection of how many
Caribbean immigrants who ignored, even snubbed, the rites of
Carnival in Trinidad or Grenada have embraced it here, both as a
way to recall the home they left behind and to keep their children
in the Caribbean fold.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn's West Indian parade draws an estimated 2 million
spectators _ in comparison with the 1 million or so who come out
for the Thanksgiving Day Parade in Manhattan _ and 30 masquerade
bands with as many as 2,000 participants each. The city's
Convention and Visitors Bureau now includes it on its list of Labor
Day weekend attractions, and New Yorkers with no ties to the
islands come to watch and, increasingly, to don costumes in the
masquerade bands, to play ``mas,'' as it is called.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the political power of Caribbean New Yorkers, the
parade has become a mandatory campaign stop. Banners pitching beer
and long-distance telephone services now stretch along the parade
route. And for the last three years, the parade has been broadcast
live on local television.
</P>
<P>
   But even as all of this signals the growing importance of
Caribbean New York in the public culture of the city, the evolution
of the parade also speaks volumes for how old-country rituals are
reinvented, Brooklyn-style.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Barnes, 60, a transplanted Trinidadian whose children and
grandchildren now join her on Eastern Parkway, likened the Brooklyn
parade to a tasty fruit-flavored drink. ``With the grapyness of the
grapyness of the grapyness of it,'' was how she put it, ``but not
the grape.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnival scholars and revelers say the Brooklyn parade is in
many ways a different kind of concoction altogether. For one thing,
it is an American-style march, not a series of free-floating
processions as in Port of Spain, the capital of Trinidad and
Tobago. To accommodate television, the parade must stick to a
schedule, and marshals keep dancers from veering off the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they used to be extremely careless about scheduling,''
recalled Major Owens, the U.S. representative from Crown Heights
who made his first appearance at the parade 18 years ago. ``It was
supposed to start at 11 o'clock, and it wouldn't start till 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, considerable effort has been made to bring the
parade in line, install portable toilets and police barricades, and
garner corporate donations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   But the growth of the parade has also sown dissension between
the organizers and some of the band leaders, particularly over how
to pay for this phenomenally expensive affair. The West Indian Day
Carnival Association, the organizer, says the weekend-long
bacchanal now costs nearly a half-million dollars; for some of the
bigger masquerade bands, like the 1,000-member Hawks International,
a few hours on the Parkway costs $50,000, what with expenses for
costumes and loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   While the city does not estimate the parade's economic impact,
there are a few budding efforts to use it as an engine of economic
development. Una Clarke, the city councilwoman from Crown Heights,
for instance, has proposed a program to generate year-round jobs
for the Carnival costume-makers. Owens is seeking to build a
Caribbean-American cultural museum that would have an office for
the parade organizers.
</P>
<P>
   And corporations with an interest in the Caribbean-American
market have begun to capitalize on the parade, with companies like
Western Union, AT&AMP;T and Mobil sponsoring some of the larger
masquerade bands as well as the parade itself. ``It's relevant to
our target audience, and we want to be part of it,'' said Anthony
Smith, Mobil Corp's manager for diversity marketing and community
relations.
</P>
<P>
   As the parade has gained mainstream notice, it has also fueled
the resurgence of another Trinidadian rite. For the last several
years, Trinidadians hankering for less structure and more steel
bands _ which have all but disappeared from the Parkway, drowned
out by the loud sound-trucks of the mas bands _ have turned to
something called J'ouvert, a free-spirited predawn pageant that
since slavery times has been a venue for drums, dance and social
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, J'ouvert _ a French-derived term pronounced joo-VAY
and loosely translated as ``I open,'' as in the opening of Carnival
_ has grown by leaps and bounds in the last few years. It now draws
about 50,000 people but, so far, no politicians. Amplified music is
barred, leaving only the peals of the steel pan to break the cool
silence of the night.
</P>
<P>
   For J'ouvert this year, Tricia Mayhew and her friends will
slather themselves from head to toe with red paint and dance under
the stars. Ms. Mayhew, a 27-year-old high school science teacher,
has joined the parade on the Parkway ever since she left Trinidad,
11 years ago. But she has not played J'ouvert like this since she
was a child.
</P>
<P>
   `` ``Catching all those faces and listening to the steel bands,
you get that original feeling,'' she said. ``We've gotten so
commercialized now. But to watch these musicians play these notes,
you just marvel. You feel a sense of more freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   If the growth of Carnival is a function of a conventional
immigrant narrative _ doing in this country what one did at home _
the opposite is also true. Many have delved into the rites of
Carnival only after leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   As a Catholic school student in Trinidad, Kathy Clarke was
allowed only a glimpse of the masquerading revelers at Carnival
time. She never covered herself in paint on J'ouvert morning. And
she would never have been caught in the neighborhood pan yard,
whiling away her evenings with the pan men _ and it once was only
men _ who were considered ``hooligans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, both her college-age son and daughter play steel drum. And
Ms. Clarke, a middle school teacher from East Flatbush who moved to
New York in 1979, serves as sort of a den mother for their band,
the Invaders. She joins her children as they play pan on J'ouvert
morning and then rushes home to change into costume for the parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me this _ you're lucky you can keep kids in the
culture,'' she said the other day, as her daughter, Dominique, 20,
practiced on a six-headed bass drum.
</P>
<P>
   Steel band music has also filled a void in neighborhoods where
sports, arts and other recreational programs for young people have
all but dried up.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday evening, the pan yard of the Sesame Flyers
steel band in Flatbush was bustling. Bass drums were spray-painted
gold. The chrome tenor drums were rubbed until they shone. A group
of girls practiced last- minute flourishes on their double-seconds,
the alto of the pan orchestra. Later in the evening, they would
play on Church Avenue, and men and women would pour out of their
hot apartments to stroll and listen.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers now form the core of many bands in Brooklyn.
Roots-seeking may be important to their parents, but the young
people are drawn to the pan yard by other things. They come so they
can stay out with friends long past their curfew. They come because
they feel safe, because the pan yard, they say, is like family.
Mostly, they come for the music.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Browne, 16, has been playing for nearly seven years,
often riding the bus for a half-hour each way to get his hands on a
tenor drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something got stuck on me,'' he said. ``Having something to
play, having fun, hanging out. In the end, it's worth it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
