<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS AGREE WITH SENATOR'S CRITICISM OF CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ill., La., Minn., Calif., Colo., Ga., N.J., Mo.,
N.Y., Pa., Wash., Vt., Ohio, Fla.) (Eds: See also CLINTON-LIEBERMAN, CLINTON-APOLOGY) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Democrats Friday began falling in
line behind an influential Democratic senator who on Thursday
excoriated President Clinton's behavior in the Lewinsky scandal as
``immoral'' and ``disgraceful'' from the floor of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats interviewed across the country stopped short of
calling for Clinton to resign or be impeached, concurring with the
senator, Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, that such steps were
unwise and premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with Sen. Lieberman that what the president did was
wrong and that what the president did hurt the country and the
presidency,'' Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., said through a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La., issued a statement saying, ``I
commend Sen. Lieberman for his appropriate and timely remarks and
the dignified way in which he delivered this difficult but right
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other Democrats echoed similar sentiments in interviews
or statements, including Sens. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, Richard
Durbin of Illinois, Barbara Boxer of California and Max Cleland of
Georgia, and Reps. Robert Andrews of New Jersey and Diana DeGette
of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats stepped up their criticism of Clinton, Speaker Newt
Gingrich of Georgia and Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House
minority leader, agreed Friday to meet on Wednesday to discuss the
procedures for dealing with the report that the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, is expected to file in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has complained that the House Republican leadership is
drafting the framework for the inquiry into possible impeachable
offenses and the handling of the report without consulting
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., who heads the House Rules
Committee, said Friday that if the House approved a procedural
resolution, Starr's report would go to the House Judiciary
Committee with instructions to make an executive summary available
to all House members. If the committee finds that sufficient
evidence exists to proceed with an impeachment proceeding, Solomon
said he would recommend that the full report be made available to
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., started gathering signatures Friday
on a letter to Gingrich asking that lawmakers either give up
campaign time this fall and stay in session ``for as long as it
takes'' or return after the Nov. 3 elections to deal quickly with
any accusations of impeachable offenses by the president.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate are in recess for the Labor Day weekend, so
most lawmakers were out of town Friday. Many Democrats, including
Gephardt and Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority leader,
declined to comment beyond their earlier criticisms of Clinton's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, until Lieberman's scathing 24-minute speech, most
Democrats had confined their comments on the matter. Last month
Rep. Paul McHale, D-Pa., who is retiring, called on Clinton to
resign. And this week Rep. Adam Smith, D-Wash., facing a tough
re-election, said the president's behavior ``repulses'' him.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic incumbents who are women have come under attack
from Republican challengers who accuse them of having a double
standard on sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Linda Smith, R-Wash., the leading Republican challenger to
Sen. Patty Murray, has criticized her Democratic rival's muted
response to the scandal, saying the senator ``seems to have traded
in her tennis shoes for a pair of Hush Puppies.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats Friday chose to associate themselves with
Lieberman's remarks, and not say much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lieberman's comments demonstrate that no one is more
disappointed about what's happened than the president's friends,''
said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeGette said, ``For Democrats, there's just a sense of deep
disappointment, and it just doesn't seem to be going away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But not all Democrats agreed with Lieberman's remarks or their
timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speech was the wrong speech at the wrong time,'' said Rep.
Eliot Engel, D-N.Y. ``Frankly, I think it plays into the hands of
the Republicans who are trying to fan the fires of this whole
Monica Lewinsky situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Engel said Lieberman's speech was putting pressure on other
Democrats to be more critical of Clinton. ``This has a snowball
effect,'' Engel said. ``It becomes a self-fulfilling prophecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Pascrell Jr., D-N.J., said, ``Members of Congress have
a legitimate right to address their concerns and opinions, but I
don't believe this is the time to pile on the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said Lieberman's remarks violated an unwritten rule on
Capitol Hill to refrain from criticizing the president when he was
abroad, in this case Northern Ireland, where he has played in
important role in brokering a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only concern about it was the timing,'' Leahy said. ``Save
the criticism for when the president's plane takes off, or for
Monday or Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Lieberman suggested that there be some sort of
public rebuke of Clinton, a sentiment expressed earlier this week
by many Democrats, including Rep. Marcy Kaptur of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need something else,'' Ms. Kaptur said. ``He doesn't have
to resign, or he could resign and then do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., said, ``On the basis of the
information we now have, we cannot let the impression prevail that
the president's behavior is acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton and other senior Democrats urged restraint until
lawmakers reviewed Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Democrats said they were not swayed by
Clinton's latest effort at contrition Friday. The president told
reporters in Dublin that he was ``very sorry'' for what he did, but
added that ``there's nothing else I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin said, ``The obvious question is whether people believe
that this apology is genuine,'' and added, ``I believe it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats disagreed. Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said through
a spokeswoman that the president's statements were insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. DeGette said: ``At this point, most people feel there
should have been an apology. I still don't hear an apology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
