<HEADER>
A0477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-VICTIMS-1STLD-W     09-04 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-VICTIMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR PASSENGERS WHO LOOKED TOWARD FUTURE ARE NOW PART OF THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add 3 grafs at end)  (bl)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, whenever Janice Wallace closed her eyes, she could
still see her big sister laughing and blowing kisses through the
window of the taxi speeding toward New York's Kennedy International
Airport. For hours, she clung to that memory of Lori Moran, a
34-year-old figure-skating coach who had planned to toast her third
wedding anniversary in the French Alps.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, as Mrs. Wallace watched news flashes of rescue
workers pulling baby bottles, ripped clothing and seat cushions
from the choppy sea off Peggy's Cove, Nova Scotia, she turned her
attention to the business of bringing her sister's body back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like reality now,'' said Ms. Wallace, 33, as she and her
family made plans to fly to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The dark waters swallowed 229 lives when Swissair Flight 111
plunged into the Atlantic on Wednesday night, and Friday many
grieving families began the painful process of trying to recover
their dead.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for information about the newlyweds, refugee workers,
retirees and others lost in the crash, dozens of families flew to
Nova Scotia from Kennedy Airport on a Swissair charter flight.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like the relatives of Joseph La Motta, 49, the son of
boxer Jake La Motta, drove to the Ramada Plaza Hotel at Kennedy
Airport hoping for news from Swissair executives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many sought to give information that would help with
the identification process. John Dedes hunted for the medical
records of his cousin, Dr. Eugenia Spanopoulou, a cancer
researcher, who was killed flying her 18-month-old son to meet her
father in Greece for the very first time.
</P>
<P>
   Elayne Shuster searched for the dental records of her sister,
Stephanie, a 32-year-old Manhattan corporate executive, who had
been on her way to business meetings in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest concern now is to find her,'' said Ms. Shuster,
35. ``That's the only thing that's going to give us, as a family, a
sense of closure.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was little news to comfort the families. Rescue
workers, who reported recovering about 60 bodies Thursday, stopped
estimating the body count Friday. And as relatives stayed glued to
their television screens, investigators reported only the recovery
of about 100 suitcases, saying they believed many bodies were
trapped in the wreckage below the waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this was just God's will,'' said Lynn Ross, the
fiancee of Joe La Motta, her voice choked with tears. She said she
could not bear to fly to Canada until his body is found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine standing there looking at that body of water
and being reminded all over again how Joe died,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night, the passengers stepped on the jetliner
looking forward to the future. Joe La Motta was thrilled about
traveling to Geneva to promote his company, LaMotta Foods Inc., and
its LaMotta Tomotta sauce, a family marinara recipe handed down
from his father.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hausman, 33, an Illinois farm boy whose love of agriculture
catapulted him to the top of the grain buying industry, was
preparing for a business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   And Norman and Caroline DePledge of Concord, Mass., were
settling into their seats along with their grown children, Jane and
Michael, bound for a 10-day walking tour though Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were so excited about Switzerland,'' said Alma Healy, a
neighbor who met the family 20 years ago. ``They were really each
others best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight included many passengers like the DePledeges, who
were fulfilling tightly-clasped dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Tahmoush, 77, the retired chief executive officer of
Frank B. Hill, an insurance brokerage house, was planning a
long-awaited reunion. During World War II, Mr. Tahmoush, then an
officer in the U.S. Army, was injured and cared for by a Belgian
couple. And he was on his way to visit that couple's 63-year-old
son for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Spanopoulou, a scientist at Mount Sinai Hospital's Derald H.
Ruttenberg Cancer Center, and her husband, Andrew Hodtsev, an
immunologist, were taking their little boy, Platon, to be
christened in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a rising star in her field of molecular immunology
and cancer, Dr. Spanopolou was recently named an investigator for
the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, a prestigious competitive
award that goes to top young scientists conducting cutting-edge
work.
</P>
<P>
   But this trip was for pleasure. And she was looking forward to
presenting her new baby to her family when the plane fell from the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the crash traveled quickly. Mrs. Wallace, the sister of
Ms. Moran, the figure skating coach, was sleeping when her father
called with the news. She shook herself awake, insisting the news
could not be true.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moran and her husband, Michael Dichkus, an architect, had
been planning the trip for months. And Ms. Moran, who spent four
years coaching at Chelsea Piers in Manhattan before moving to the
Ice House in Hackensack, N.J., about a year ago, had spent long
evenings flipping through travel guides, dreaming about the Eifel
Tower, long walks in Paris and sightseeing in Grenoble, France.
</P>
<P>
   It was their third anniversary and the couple looked forward to
celebrating their happy lives. They had a new house, which Dichkus
fixed and fussed over until his hands got sore. They had a blooming
garden with red dahlias, sunny marigolds and ripe tomatoes. And
this year, after the trip, they planned to finally start a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a lot of renovations in the house, and she loved that
garden,'' Mrs. Wallace said. ``Every moment she wasn't at the rink,
she was outside taking care of the garden, out there at six o'clock
in the morning, pulling weeds.''
</P>
<P>
   But reality set in as divers pulled wreckage and bodies from the
ocean and Swissair executives announced that no one had survived.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, overwhelmed by the grim sight of the broken plane and
the debris, Mrs. Wallace turned off the television set and started
making arrangements for the trip to Canada with her family. She
planned to take flowers from the garden and to hold tight to those
last images of her sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember saying `Bon voyage' and she was blowing kisses out
the window,'' said Mrs. Wallace, weeping. ``She had her arm out the
window waving as she went down the street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
