<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSPAN HINTS AT EASED STANCE ON RATE INCREASE
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, said that the
central bankers were growing more concerned about the effect of the
global financial crisis on the U.S. economy, and he seemed to open
the door to consideration of a rate cut if the global situation
continues to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring and early summer, Federal Reserve policy-makers
were more concerned about the threat of renewed inflation,
Greenspan said, and they adopted a policy stance signaling they
stood ready to raise rates at the first sign of any significant
inflation. But he said policy-makers decided last month that the
global turmoil posed a growing threat to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   CHERNOMYRDIN DETAILS FINANCIAL PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Russia's acting prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, detailed a
series of economic remedies that would shore up the nation's
banking system and ease the country into an ``economic
dictatorship'' where the money supply would be rigidly controlled
and failing factories could face bankruptcy for the first time. The
Parliament put off a vote on the new government until Monday,
buying more time for political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   GM AND UNION REACH SATURN PACT
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and the United Automobile Workers reached an
accord at the automaker's Saturn assembly plant in Spring Hill,
Tenn., averting another strike. Details of the agreement were not
disclosed, but both sides said it affirmed the plant's partnership
between management and labor.
</P>
<P>
   TWO CARRIERS ORDERED BACK IN AIR
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of transportation, Rodney Slater, ordered Mesaba
Aviation and Express Airlines I, commuter carriers that suspended
service last week because of the pilots' strike at Northwest
Airlines, to resume flights to 17 small cities no later than
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   DOW RALLIES LATE BUT LOSES GROUND
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 186 points
before it and other market measures recovered, cutting their losses
by two-thirds and more. The Dow closed down 41.97 points, or
five-tenths of 1 percent, at 7,640,25. It is now down 3.4 percent
for the year. The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
8.37 points, or nine-tenths of 1 percent, to 973.89, and the Nasdaq
composite index dropped 5.34 points, or three-tenths of 1 percent,
to 1,566.52.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury securities traded mostly higher. The yield of the
30-year bond dropped to 5.28 percent from 5.30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURES EXCHANGE WINS APPROVAL
</P>
<P>
   Cantor Fitzgerald won approval from the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission for the first computerized futures exchange in
the United States, the latest in a global shift to electronic
networks. The system will compete with the Chicago Board of Trade,
the nation's largest futures market.
</P>
<P>
   MOODY'S MAY LOWER RATINGS IN ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service said it might lower its debt ratings
for China and Hong Kong. Moody's pointed to slowing exports and
investment in China and Hong Kong's deteriorating economy and
decision to spend currency reserves to buy stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's said it might lower its rating on Nomura Securities,
Japan's largest brokerage firm, because of concerns about its
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICES OF NEC RAIDED IN TOKYO
</P>
<P>
   Japan's military contract-padding scandal spread to NEC as Tokyo
prosecutors raided the giant multinational electronics company. The
search came after raids on Thursday at the Japanese Defense Agency
and Toyo Communication Equipment Co., an NEC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   COOPER IN DEAL FOR BRITISH COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Cooper Industries of Houston said that it had acquired the
British company TLG, formerly known as Thorn Lighting Group, for
$535 million in cash. Thorn is a major European maker of lighting
equipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
