<HEADER>
A0484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PRIMARIES-NYT &LR;      09-04 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COMING SOON: THE BICOASTAL PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   The California state Legislature voted this week to move its
presidential primary from June to the first Tuesday in March. If
Gov. Pete Wilson signs the bill into law, it will virtually
guarantee that the national presidential primary system becomes a
compressed melee in which nominations are awarded to the candidates
with the most money and highest profile.
</P>
<P>
   New York has already scheduled its year 2000 primary for the
week of March 7, as have most of the New England states. California
hopes to persuade Washington and Oregon to create a West Coast
regional primary on the same day. That means candidates coming out
of the New Hampshire race in February will immediately be forced
into a massive, bicoastal campaign. Huge advertising budgets will
be essential, and any candidate without a private jet might as well
call it a day.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to blame the Californians for wanting to hold their
primary early. The days when candidates were tested over a long
primary season and the final decision was not made until June are
gone. Given the way other states have been leapfrogging to the head
of the line, the next presidential nominees may be set in concrete
even before the Super Tuesday primaries in mid-March. In 1996,
California tried moving its presidential primary to the end of
March as an experiment and found that even then it was little more
than an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Like most lawmakers who are now scheduling their primaries too
soon and too close together, Californians say they would happily
join in any system that made things more rational. ``If we just
make the parties realize the system's broken, that will be great,''
said one of the early-primary backers. But the parties have so far
shown little interest beyond protecting New Hampshire's status as
the only February primary.
</P>
<P>
   A long, deliberative primary season is in the interest of
everyone, except perhaps well-financed names like Vice President Al
Gore, who might benefit from a race decided too fast for people to
become familiar with his competition. The National Association of
Secretaries of State has been working on a plan that would create
five regional primaries, each to be held a month apart.
California's vote makes it clear that the secretaries of state
should act quickly if the next primary season is to be saved. Party
activists interested in opening up the 2000 presidential race to as
many candidates as possible should press their leaders to get
involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
