<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HOMETOWN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE HAS ALWAYS HAD POWER 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCONNELL  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ Long home runs have always been Mark
McGwire's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has natural power,'' says former USC coach Rod Dedeaux.
``It isn't anything that comes out of bottle or from a pill you can
take. It's a gift from the good Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was known for his long home runs, even while playing in
the American Little League in Claremont, Calif. That reputation
grew in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest home run I saw Mark hit at Damien, and maybe the
longest home run I ever saw period, was one he hit at Ganesha High
in Pomona,'' said Tom Carroll, McGwire's varsity coach at Damien
High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit one over the fence in left field, which is only about
300 feet away, but is about 30 feet high. It then cleared the
backyard of a house, landed in the middle of the roof, bounced off
the roof and out into the street beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably the highlight of Mark's baseball career at Damien was
the 1981 Pomona Elks Baseball Tournament. Damien made it all the
way to the finals, in which it played Covina on a chilly spring
night at Ralph Welch Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember we had a huge crowd for the game,'' Carroll said.
``And I remember Mark pitched very well, but we made a couple
errors and Covina finally beat us, 6-5, in nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what most folks remember about that game is that Mark hit
two long, long drives. Both were caught by Covina outfielders who
were playing him about as deep as you could play and still be in
the same zip code. At any other park, those two drives would have
been home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   While playing for Jack Helber's Claremont American Legion team,
the legend continued to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, he hit one into the next county,'' Helber said.
``Really.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field we played on at Claremont-McKenna College is in Los
Angeles County, but there is a service road out behind the left
field fence and a ways beyond that is the L.A.-San Bernardino
County line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark hit one that cleared the left field fence, cleared the
service road and landed in the next county. I don't know how far
that is, but I do know I never saw anyone else come close to doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit several tape-measure home runs at USC, but his
longest may have been hit in Memphis when he was a member of the
U.S. Olympic team in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit one that must have gone 600 feet,'' said former Cal
Poly Pomona coach John Scolinos, who was an assistant coach on that
U.S. team. ``It left the ballpark and landed on a highway out
beyond left field. I've been around baseball a long time, but I
have never seen a longer home run. I was just amazed. I turned to
Rod Dedeaux and said I couldn't believe what I just saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rod just said, `Oh, that's Mark. He does that all the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
