<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW PLANS TO SPEND, THEN SAVE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Viktor Chernomyrdin has battled to become prime
minister, critics have wondered how he could placate the Communists
and still take tough steps to rescue Russia from its deepening
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin gave his answer Friday: by turns.
</P>
<P>
   In a major address to Russia's upper house of Parliament,
Chernomyrdin outlined a two-stage plan that would begin with the
easiest and most popular step: turning on the money-printing
presses so the government could pay workers back wages and prop up
ailing banks.
</P>
<P>
   Only later would the government impose an iron discipline on its
tumbling currency by rigidly linking it to gold and hard-currency
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agreed that Chernomyrdin's decision to put off the day
of reckoning just might get him through the Communist-dominated
lower house of Parliament, which has balked at his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It may also help the Kremlin defuse the strikes and mass
demonstrations that the Communists have planned for early October.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the strategy would also escalate Russia's
roaring inflation and further depress its collapsing currency
before corrective action is finally taken. As Chernomyrdin
acknowledged Friday, ``We will get a growth of prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A growth of prices'' was a rather pallid euphemism for what is
happening in Russia now. Inflation shot up 15 percent for the last
two weeks of August _ an annual rate of more than 2,000 percent.
The ruble has tumbled over that period from 6.2 rubles to the
dollar to about 17 rubles.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the wreckage that once was the Russian economy,
Domingo Cavallo, Argentina's former economics minister who emerged
this week as one of the Kremlin's most influential advisers, made a
plea for fast action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk of going to hyperinflation is very high if they do
not act quickly,'' he said in an interview. ``There are no economic
grounds to say that it is premature. When you have to prevent
hyperinflation, the quicker you act, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo helped conquer sky-high inflation in Argentina by
establishing a currency board _ a system that establishes a fixed
exchange rate linked to a hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Fyodorov, the pro-free-market Kremlin aide, who was
reappointed first deputy prime minister this week, has embraced the
concept and made it a central feature of Chernomyrdin's economic
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Chernomyrdin nor Fyodorov, however, spelled out when
their new currency policy would take effect. And only the broad
strokes of the strategy were clear.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how it would work. Heeding the Parliament's call for a
looser monetary policy, the government would print more money.
</P>
<P>
   That would enable the government to pay back wages to the Army,
civil servants and defense workers, soothing popular discontent.
Pensions would also be paid, and the new infusion of rubles would
also help prop up teetering banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to settle accounts with the past,'' Fyodorov told
Russian television. ``Because otherwise everybody will tell us,
`Look, you owe us this and that.'''
</P>
<P>
   But sometime after that populist splurge, Fyodorov explained,
the purse strings would be drawn tight.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in January, the government would get tough by
bankrupting unprofitable companies, trying to balance the budget,
beefing up tax collection and imposing a flat tax of 20 percent on
personal income.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to convey the sternness of the future measures,
Chernomyrdin dubbed it an ``economic dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The country will have to live according to strict, absolutely
clear rules,'' he said. ``All these measures will need new
legislative support, and new legislation should come into force
starting in January of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Russia would be like a chronic drinker who would go
out for a final binge before swearing off alcohol once and for all.
Thus the plan has raised some troubling questions.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia lacks the political consensus to undertake painful
reforms and currency stabilization measures now, will there be
sufficient support in the depths of winter, when inflation is
raging, shortages plague the nation and the 2000 presidential vote
is even nearer? Or will Russia again put off taking the tough
medicine?
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's approach also poses difficult choices for
Russia's friends in the West.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the managing director of the International
Monetary Fund, Michel Camdessus, said Russia has a ``very urgent''
agenda of economic and financial improvements that have to be made.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton indicated during his summit meeting here this
week that he was prepared to lead a new effort to expand Western
assistance if Russia kept on the reform path.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a senior Clinton administration official expressed
frustration with the outlines of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Some important details of the plan remained to be spelled out,
such as how much money would be printed. Until the Parliament
approves a new prime minister and his team is fully in place there
is no government to make those decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate question is whether the plan signaled that the
shock waves of the economic crisis had finally impelled Russian
leaders to act.
</P>
<P>
   Some were skeptical. ``It is not a program,'' said Mikhail
Berger, the economic specialist and editor of the newspaper
Segodnya. ``It is a statement of intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the specter of empty store shelves, hungry soldiers and
a worthless currency, Chernomyrdin insisted he would press ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time has run out,'' Chernomyrdin said. ``Each lost day takes
months, years to make up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
