<HEADER>
A0491 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-ADVANCE-CO     09-04 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eagles strong test of Jackets' progress
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Georgia Tech opens its season today against Boston College,
the Yellow Jackets will learn exactly how much has changed for
Boston College and how much has stayed the same for Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Yellow Jackets are back from their 42-14 blowout of
Boston College last October, a game in which they rolled up 303
yards rushing and looked bad for about the length of time it took
Quinton Lee to rush 76 yards for a touchdown on the second play of
the game. After that, it was all Yellow Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Wiley, the senior member of Tech's running-back
unit, says the Yellow Jackets have washed those memories from their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting a great game out of Boston College,'' Wiley
said. ``We're not underestimating them. I know they're a better
team. ... When we saw them, they didn't play their best game. We're
not using last year as any kind of indicator.''
</P>
<P>
   When the two met last season, the Eagles were playing without
starting quarterback Matt Hasselbeck and Mike McCloud, their best
running back, because of injuries. Hasselbeck is gone, but Cloud is
back and healthy and the focal point of Boston College's offense.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mutryn, who got his only start of the season against Tech,
has won the starting quarterback job and is secure in his progress
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Brian Maye, who missed last season with a neck
injury, has returned, and coach Tom O'Brien, a former George Welsh
assistant at Virginia, has established his program in his second
year.
</P>
<P>
   He knows Boston College has to be a different team against the
run this year than the one that gave up 200 yards rushing per game
last season and had a free safety, Pedro Cirino, leading the team
in tackles (130).
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a good challenge for our defenders to play
(quarterback) Joe Hamilton, (fullback Ed) Wilder and Wiley,''
O'Brien said. ``They ran all over us last year. ... We didn't stop
the run last year against anybody. George (O'Leary) was kind and
took his quarterback out midway through the third quarter. That's
something we have to concentrate on and are concerned about at
BC.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets expect Boston College to crowd the line of
scrimmage and will counter by testing their new group of receivers.
Gone is Harvey Middleton, who had two catches against the Eagles,
including a 28-yard touchdown, and Mike Sheridan, who had two
catches for 26 yards, is out with a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   One area Tech wants to look different this season is on defense,
where new coordinator Randy Edsall will test his aggressive scheme.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Tech would enjoy another 42-14 win and another bowl
trip, Wiley said this team is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a feeling now, (that) we know we can (win) if we do
the things we need to do, go out and play to the best of our
ability,'' he said. ``Last year we thought maybe if we play 100
percent we'll get a win. This year it's a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
