A0492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-ADVANCE-COX     09-04 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs inquisitive about QB Quincy
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athens _ Perhaps no place has its finger on the pulse of Athens
sports as much as Loco's Deli &AMP; Pub on Harris Street. For months,
bartenders and patrons alike have projected that freshman
quarterback Quincy Carter would bring magic to the Bulldogs this
season.
</P>
<P>
   After Carter's almost three-year layoff from football, Georgia
fans will finally get a look at the former Parade All-American from
Southwest DeKalb High when he starts against Kent in today's opener
at Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for months,'' Loco's manager Dave Bruno
said. ``All you've been hearing about is how great this guy is.
Now, we finally get to see if it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   When Georgia opened preseason camp more than a month ago, the
team's biggest question was whether Carter, who spent the past two
years playing baseball in the Chicago Cubs' minor-league system,
could learn the Bulldogs' thick playbook fast enough to earn the
starting job.
</P>
<P>
   He did, enough to satisfy Georgia coach Jim Donnan, who picked
the 20-year-old rookie to start over veterans Jon England and Mike
Usry and freshman Nate Hybl. Now, Carter continues his on-the-job
training against the Golden Flashes _ and in front of Georgia's
first sellout crowd for a non-SEC home opener since the Bulldogs
opened against UCLA in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just got to go out and do your job,'' Carter said.
``We've got some great fans. Fortunately, they've been behind me
since I stepped on campus. They want me to do this and that, but
I'm not trying to go overboard and be Superman. I'm just trying to
do the job and not make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter assumes the position of Mike Bobo, the SEC's top-rated
passer a year ago, and he's charged with continuing the momentum of
last season's turnaround: a 10-2 record, No. 10 national ranking
and a 33-6 demolition of Wisconsin in the Outback Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can keep that roller-coaster thing from going up
and down, so we're consistent every year,'' Donnan said. ``We've
got the capabilities of being very good. But if things don't go
right early, we've got to be careful we don't hit the panic button
and just hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent, which has a 13-74-1 record this decade, probably won't be
much of a measuring stick for Carter. Georgia opens its SEC slate
at South Carolina next week, so don't expect Donnan to reveal much
of his offense. Donnan says he's installed some option offense, but
``you probably won't see much of it (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Donnan undoubtedly will want to test Carter, who gives
the Bulldogs perhaps their most mobile quarterback since James
Jackson started from 1985-87. Carter rushed for 1,489 yards and 32
touchdowns during his three years as a starter at Southwest Dekalb.
He also threw for 4,450 yards and 37 scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that he'll succeed,'' Southwest
DeKalb coach Buck Godfrey said. ``You're talking about someone that
was mature enough to start when he left here (in 1996). And then
you add those two years spent playing baseball and you've got a
prototypical quarterback. ... The only thing that Georgia has to
worry about is that the NFL will come calling in a couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
