<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-POMONA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMETOWN FEELING MCGWIRE MANIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCONNELL  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ McGwire-mania is sweeping the nation, and those
feeling the brunt of the media storm are here in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many phone calls are we getting? Only about 20 million,''
said a harried receptionist at Dr. John McGwire's dental office in
Pomona. ``It's unbelievable. It's hard to get any work done around
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. McGwire has been gone most of the summer, and he isn't
giving any interviews anyway. And don't try to tell me you're one
of his patients ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mentioned in a USA Today article about Mark, and then
went away for a few days,'' said Jack Helber, who coached McGwire's
American Legion team. ``When I came back, my phone message tape was
completely filled up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have just about flat run out of things to say about Mark.
And while I'm at it, no, I can't get anyone tickets to Cardinals
games, or Mark's autograph. If it's that bad for me, you can
imagine what's it like for the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Former USC coach Rod Dedeaux knows the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're calling for Rod Dedeaux, I'm sure you want to talk
about Mark McGwire,'' said Heidi, a receptionist at Dedeaux's
company, Dart Transportation in Los Angeles. ``I don't even have to
ask anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the McGwires, the unusual spelling of their
last name makes their listings stand out in the Pomona phone book.
Fans and the media have been relentless, especially in the past
month. Anyone with a connection to Mark McGwire is fair game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh gosh yes, I've gotten calls from all over the country,''
said Tom Carroll, the athletic director at Damien High. ``New York
Times, USA Today, Associated Press, you name 'em, I've talked to
'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have had a bunch of photographers at the school. Most
of them aren't too happy, when they find we don't have a shrine to
Mark in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to talk about Mark, but classes are in session here now
and, at some point, we need to get things back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
