</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PREDICT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opening day means there's nowhere to go but up
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing more humbling _ and perhaps sillier _ than
predicting the stock market is picking college football games. So
given the events of the past week on Wall Street, this seems like
the perfect time to start this weekly effort. Like our portfolio,
there's no way to go but up _ we hope.
</P>
<P>
   We'll predict final scores because it's fun. We'll keep a record
of wins and losses each week in order to chart the true lack of
knowledge of your humble scribe. But be advised: we will never,
ever discuss point spreads. If you're dumb enough to bet on college
football, a game played by overdeveloped 19- and 20-year olds, you
deserve your misery.
</P>
<P>
   This first week will be particularly intriguing, as there are
more games matching nationally-ranked teams than any opening
Saturday we can remember. With that cautionary note, let us begin.
</P>
<P>
   Kent at No. 19 Georgia, 5 p.m.: Bulldog coach Jim Donnan
actually has been holding freshman quarterback Quincy Carter back
in practice because he didn't want folks to know how good this kid
really is. Today he turns him loose against the Golden Flashes, who
will be but a 25-watt bulb Between the Hedges. Georgia 52, Kent 14.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College at Georgia Tech, 3:30 p.m. (ABC): The Yellow
Jackets can be a Top 25 team if they can figure out a way to stop
somebody. Randy Edsall was hired as defensive coordinator to do
just that. The Eagles are a second-division team in a bad
conference (Big East). Georgia Tech 28, Boston College 14
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Ohio State at No. 11 West Virginia, 8 p.m. (CBS): Buckeye
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer is eligible after passing Golf and Aids
Awareness. He should be the perfect antidote for Mountaineer
running back Amos Zereoue, who hopes to use this game as a
springboard to a serious Heisman Trophy candidacy. Sorry, Amos. You
won't be famous today. Ohio State 24, West Virginia 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Citadel at No. 3 Florida, 6 p.m.: Jesse Palmer starts at
quarterback for the Gators, who can pick their number in the Swamp.
Florida 82, Citadel 0.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Birmingham at No. 4 Nebraska. 1:30: Ditto. Nebraska 62,
UAB 6.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Michigan at No. 22 Notre Dame, 2:30 p.m. (NBC): Michigan,
the defending AP national champions, returns nine starters from the
nation's No. 2 defense. The Irish have improved, but not enough.
Still, it will be closer than most people think. Michigan 17, Notre
Dame 10.
</P>
<P>
   No. 10 Tennessee at No. 17 Syracuse, Noon (ESPN): Tee Martin
gets his first start at quarterback in what will be a loud, hot
Carrier Dome. The Vols can move the ball, but so can Syracuse with
quarterback Donovan McNabb. Better bring lunch and dinner to this
one. It will be a shootout. Tennessee 38, Syracuse 31.
</P>
<P>
   No. 21 Southern Miss at No. 13 Penn State, 2:30 p.m.: Southern
Miss has a history of going into hostile stadiums and scaring the
home team. The Golden Eagles will do it again on Saturday but come
up short. Penn State 17, Southern Miss 13.
</P>
<P>
   No. 15 Colorado State vs. Colorado at Denver, 10 p.m. (ESPN):
The Rams, which opened the season by winning at Michigan State last
Saturday, have been looking forward to this game for more than over
a year. Colorado is the underdog after struggling last season, and
with good reason. Colorado State 24, Colorado 20.
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida at Louisiana Tech, 7 p.m.: This game would have
been on television, but the network brass was afraid it would last
too long. La. Tech's Tim Rattay threw for 590 yards against
Nebraska last week. Central Florida's Daunte Culpepper may be the
best quarterback in the country. La. Tech 45, Central Florida 42.
</P>
<P>
   The rest: Ole MIss 24, Memphis 10; Kentucky 34, Louisville 17.;
Miss. State 17, Vanderbilt 7; BYU 28, Alabama 21; South Carolina
17, Ball State 7; Clemson 31, Furman 14; North Carolina 45, Miami
(Ohio) 17.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
