<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 9/4/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- NY-CARIBBEAN-PARADE, 9-4 --
One of the biggest draws, and biggest expenses, of the annual West
Indian American Day Carnival are the elaborate costumes like this
one being assembled by Mitch Phillips. Masquerade bands will spend
as much as $50,000 to march on Monday, the parade's 31st
anniversary. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) GRACE, Md. -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- UNUSUAL-MUSEUMS , 9-3 --
At the Decoy Museum in Havre de Grace, duck decoys surround a
likeness of R. Madison Mitchell, a well-known local carver. This
area was duck hunter's nirvana until a series of laws during the
1930s and '40s curtailed hunting. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- CLINTON-KIDS-2, 9-4 --
Kenny Prosper, a 14-year-old Bronx boy, says that his father
``played'' his mother many years ago, deserting the family and
sending them cascading into poverty and homelessness. If he were
Clinton's wife, Kenny says, ``I'd slap him silly.'' If he were the
president's daughter, ``I'd tell my mom to leave him, forget about
him. And I'd never think about him as an influence again.'' (Vic
DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HASTINGS-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. -- Sept. 4, 1998 --
CLINTON-KIDS-1, 9-4 -- ``The president and Monica Lewinsky had a
thing even though he was married to somebody else,'' says Chloe
Carrano, who is about to begin third grade in Hastings-on-Hudson.
America's children are aware that President Clinton was unfaithful
to his wife, but they seem less interested in the sexual details of
the White House scandal than the moral shortcomings of a man who
would deceive and hurt his family. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-DAY, 9-4 --
Third-seeded Jana Novotna during her 6-2, 6-3, defeat of France's
Sandrine Testud in the third round at the U.S. Open on Friday. The
Wimbledon champion needed only 56 minutes to triumph over her
second consecutive French foe, having ousted Amelie Cocheteux in
the second round. (Vic Delucia/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- CLINTON-LIEBERMAN, 9-4 --
``I felt lonely out there,'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman says of
delivering his recent speech critical of President Clinton.
Lieberman, a Democrat and longtime political ally of Clinton's,
says he was furious with the president - first for bad behavior,
second for behavior that he says undercut the theme of ``personal
responsibility'' that Clinton and Lieberman had advocated over the
years. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia -- Sept. 3, 1998 --
CRASH-RDP-2, 9-3 -- Two mourners stand by the Peggy's Cove
lighthouse and look out to sea toward the area of the crash of
Swissair Flight 111. 175 friends and relatives of the 229 crash
victims were flown here from New York and Europe. They will be
asked to indentify their loved ones from among the bodies found
thus far. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia -- Sept. 3, 1998 --
CRASH-RDP-1, 9-3 -- Escorted by Red Cross volunteers, some of the
friends and relatives of the 229 victims of Swissair Flight 111
survey the crash site and mourn their losses Friday. 175 friends
and relatives of the 229 crash victims were flown here from New
York and Europe. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- LURIE-NOVELS, 9-4 -- Alison
Lurie's latest novel is set in Key West, Fla., where she has a
home. Lurie is a transoceanic novelist, equally at home on both
sides of the Atlantic, but with an even greater following in
England than in the United States. Although she lives most of the
year in Ithaca, N.Y., where she teaches children's literature at
Cornell University, she keeps an apartment in London. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
PERFIN-GUIDES-2, 9-4 -- New York Stock Exchange traders handled
record volume Tuesday as some investors saw Monday's selloff as a
buying opportunity. Whatever your personal circumstances and the
condition of your portfolio, financial experts say there are a
number of steps that every smart household should at least consider
in today's highly unsettled - and sobering - environment. (Steve
Hart/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
PERFIN-GUIDES-1, 9-4 -- Gregory Kourmoulis, a New York Stock
Exchange messenger, takes a break last Tuesday in the Trinity
Church graveyard near Wall Street. In reaching stomach-churning,
sleep-depriving levels last week, the gyrations of the stock market
seemed to restore meaning to an old Wall Street maxim: to invest is
to choose between eating well or sleeping well. (James Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CHICAGO -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
INVEST-ALTERNATIVES, 9-4 -- Michael Matheson, 51, an investor in
Chicago, says he will keep his money in stocks. ``I was sitting on
my ledge, thinking about jumping,'' jokes Matheson after last
Monday's 512-point dive in the Dow Jones industrial average. But he
decided to leave his stock investments - about 60 percent of his
portfolio - where they were. ``If I sold now, I'd be sitting here
with a pile of cash and asking, 'What would I do with it?' `` (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WESTPORT, Conn. -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
6 -- INVEST-PSYCHOLOGY, 9-4 -- Jeffrey Mitchell, 38, of Westport,
can track his investments over the Internet, even while watching
his sons, Eli, left, and Zachary. Most investors who track the
movements of their stocks on the Internet - about three million now
have on-line brokerage accounts - are enthusiastic about the
virtues of expanded access to information. (Janet Durrans/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SPRINGHOUSE, Pa. -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
6 -- INVEST-CLUB, 9-4 -- Paul Carbone, who organized the
Pennsylvania Caveat Emptor Investment Club, giving a report on a
prospect. The club gets together on the first Wednesday of every
month to review its holdings, analyze new companies, check the
status of its ``fantasy stock game,'' and vote on new stock
purchases. This month was no different, even though the club's
portfolio got clobbered by the recent stock market swing. (Tim
Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 -- INVEST-LYNCH, 9-4 -- Peter Lynch, the
star manager who built the Fidelity Magellan fund, says investors
waste a lot of time analyzing the big picture at the expense of
weighing business fundamentals. He and entertainer Lily Tomlin are
starring in a new series of Fidelity commercials. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
CANCER-FUND-RAISERS, 9-4 -- Elizabeth Tilberis, editor in chief of
Harper's Bazaar. Because of the advocacy of the socially prominent
and well-connected Ms. Tilberis and a handful of grass-roots
organizations, along with recent developments in diagnosis and
treatment, ovarian cancer has finally begun to make inroads into
the charitable arena dominated by more easily marketed diseases
like breast cancer and AIDS. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- GRILLED-PIZZA-AZR, 9-2 --
Here's a dish you won't find at your local pizzeria, unless you
live in Tijuana. At left, ingredients are assembled to make up
grilled Mexican pizza. The finished product, right. (Michael
Ging/Arizona Republic photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
WALLPAPER-MAGAZINE-3, 9-4 -- A1956 George Nelson chaise at Form and
Function in SoHo. A wave of downtowners who once embodied the
``Rent'' life style, partial to thrift-store fashions and long
hours at coffee houses, has been transformed into an upwardly
mobile crowd. They can be described as the Wallpaper Generation,
after the two-year-old design and life-style magazine that has
given an ultra-hip spin to the retro-future look of the postwar
decades. (David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
WALLPAPER-MAGAZINE-2, 9-4 -- Frankie Inglese, a downtown deejay, at
home with his collection of vintage electronics. He traces his love
of space age design to mid-'60s album covers. ``It's nearly the
year 2000,'' he says. ``We have great technology, like cell phones,
the Internet and digital cameras. But we're still sitting on
eyesores by Ikea. This is not what the future was supposed to look
like.'' (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
WALLPAPER-MAGAZINE-1, 9-4 -- Ed Briggs and Kelly Galligan, in their
Chelsea apartment, are among the grunge slackers cleaning up their
acts and turning to mid-century modern furnishings like those
featured in Wallpaper magazine. ``We call it the Change,'' Briggs,
46, says. ``A lot of our friends have gone through it, too.'' Their
collection includes a shag rug, an amoeba-shaped table and space
age lamps. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
