<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0501 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASSO-CELTICS-$ADV7-2     09-04 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASSO-CELTICS-$ADV7-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER SUSPECT'S LIFE PACKED WITH ECCENTRICITIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  For release Monday, Sept.7) 
(Attn.: N.C., N.J., N.Y.) 
 
By RONNIE CROCKER 
and RUTH RENDON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Every day was St. Patrick's Day at Sue Basso's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was green,'' recalled Richard Charlesworth, who
lived with Basso's family after losing his job in 1996. He
remembered green streamers and Irish-theme decorations that were
never taken down. There were fine Irish whiskeys and an ample
collection of Irish music on compact disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``She even had a shamrock-shaped telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   This Celtic obsession had started long before. In 1990, she
convinced her family to legally adopt an Irish surname, despite a
lack of evidence that any of them were Irish. In a holiday picture
from around that time, Sue and her husband beam as they show off a
shamrock-applique photo album.
</P>
<P>
   But if Basso could be charmingly eccentric, she also struggled
her whole life with a dark side that alienated her family and
spooked the people she befriended. She told lies for no apparent
reason, they said, and had a violent temper. Once, she was accused
of sexually abusing her son.
</P>
<P>
   Today she, that same son and four family friends are in the
Harris County Jail, held without bond on charges of capital murder
in the savage beating death of Louis ``Buddy'' Musso, a 59-year-old
mentally impaired man Basso had taken in.
</P>
<P>
   Houston police are looking into whether Basso, 44, had a hand in
the May 1997 demise of Carmine Joseph Basso, whose name Sue had
adopted a couple of years earlier when she started telling people
they were married. Carmine was 47 when he died, and the cause of
his death was listed at the time as natural.
</P>
<P>
   And authorities in the Houston area and New Jersey, where
Carmine was from, are investigating whether there are other
mentally impaired people who accepted the woman's kindness and
became victims.
</P>
<P>
   The truth will be difficult to determine.
</P>
<P>
   With Suzanne Burns Peek O'Malley Basso, it always is.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Basso was a pack rat.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her arrest, her tiny rent house in Jacinto City,
a community of 10,000 just west of Houston, was stuffed with
plastic storage boxes, clothes, records and CDs, stereos and
television equipment. A bedroom had been converted into a cramped
office. There were a dog, a cat and two ferrets.
</P>
<P>
   But Basso collected people as well, usually folks she could keep
under her thumb. Homeless people, mentally ill and retarded, the
outcast. Her daughter, Christi Hardy of Houston, recalls that her
parents always had somebody living with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would pick almost anyone up off the street,'' Hardy said.
``They were weird like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, said Hardy's husband, the couple would then brag on
themselves for their good-heartedness.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, after he lost his job at Home Depot,
Charlesworth gladly accepted this generosity. Basso, who worked as
a security guard at an apartment complex in southwest Houston,
offered to let him stay in their two-story apartment rather than
see him homeless.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, noticed many strange things.
</P>
<P>
   The grown son _ James David O'Malley Jr., whom he knew as
``J.D.'' _ was forced to eat on the floor, for instance, and
Charlesworth was quietly assigned the role of baby sitter. The
young man frightened him somewhat, he said, because of his quick
temper.
</P>
<P>
   Sue sometimes would lock the two in the house before going out.
</P>
<P>
   But the oddest thing was the mystery over whom Sue was married
to.
</P>
<P>
   She lived with James O'Malley Sr., but introduced Carmine Basso
as her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Carmine, a wiry man with a thick mop of hair who liked to
chain-smoke Kools cigarettes, and Sue got into some terrible
fights.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1995, Sue had taken out an elaborate wedding
announcement in the Houston Chronicle. Most of the claims in the ad
_ that Sue was heir to a Nova Scotian oil dynasty and that Carmine
had won the Medal of Honor, that they had a young ``very
exceptional'' daughter together, for instance _ were shown to be
fabricated. And the $1,372.50 bill was never paid.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Harris County Clerk's Office has no marriage license
on record for them. Court records show that while Suzanne O'Malley
filed for divorce from James O'Malle Sr. on April 12, 1996, the
proceedings were dropped the following Jan. 7 because no one
pursued it.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy thinks the wedding story was yet another product of her
mother's hyperactive imagination. She noted that her parents were
never apart and that Sue kept O'Malley on a tight leash, ordering
him to work overtime in his security guard job against his will and
refusing to let him get a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   (The elder O'Malley, now serving time in the Harris County Jail
for assaulting his wife, declined to be interviewed for this
article. So, too, did Basso, her son and each of their
co-defendants.)
</P>
<P>
   Charlesworth, now 44 and living in an apartment in northwest
Houston, said he also was puzzled when Sue introduced him to
Carmine as her ``long-lost brother,'' a psychologist. The only time
she ever got really angry with him, he said, was when she found out
he had admitted to Carmine that he was actually a hardware store
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, Charlesworth declined an offer to accompany Sue,
O'Malley Sr., J.D. and Carmine to New Jersey. When he saw J.D. a
few months later, after the group had returned to Houston, the
young man had news: Carmine was dead.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only reason he turned down their offer to move
back in, opting to remain on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like living with the Addams Family,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A HISTORY OF TROUBLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sue Basso's troubles began early, in Schenectady, N.Y., when she
was the youngest and cutest of three daughters in a family of eight
children. An older sister described an abusive childhood that
seemed to take its heaviest emotional toll on Sue. She skipped
school, sneaked out of the house late at night and, after being
sent to a school for troubled girls, got caught stealing a car.
</P>
<P>
   Sue's now-grown daughter, who has cut all ties with her, said
Sue's life as a married woman was equally erratic, marked by a
series of affairs. She also remembered her mother throwing her out
of the house after walking in to find O'Malley Sr. molesting her.
</P>
<P>
   Always an attractive woman, Sue began putting on weight in the
late 1970s and, as her daughter said, ``letting herself go.''
</P>
<P>
   People who have known her over the years don't seem surprised
that Sue Basso is in trouble, but they are shocked to learn she is
charged with murder. Her most serious charge to date was for
forging a check in 1989, and she received deferred adjudication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suzanne has always had a troubled life, but I never, ever
thought she would do anything like this,'' said Carol LeRoy, her
oldest sister, who still lives in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lives in a fantasy world. It's not like she's disconnected
from reality or anything. She just has a different way of looking
at things.''
</P>
<P>
   LeRoy has not seen her sister in more than a decade and is
hesitant to talk in detail about their childhood, describing it
generally as ``dysfunctional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was physical abuse. There was sexual abuse,'' she said.
``Suzanne was a victim of both.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the other children in the family grew up with no major
problems, Sue suffered through more than the typical teen-age
rebelliousness. At 14, she was sent by the courts to St. Anne's
Institute, a Catholic school for troubled girls in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   (Years later, in the bogus wedding announcement in the
Chronicle, Sue Basso described herself as a ``valedictorian
graduate of Saint Anne's Institute of Yorkshire, England.'' Friends
and family say it was a typical twisting of the truth.)
</P>
<P>
   After school, she married a Marine named James David Peek. Said
her sister, ``They seemed like they were going to lead a pretty
normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the marriage was far from normal. Hardy, the older of the
Peeks' two children, said that when she was a child, her mother
brought home a procession of lovers. Sometimes she would send her
children to their rooms or her husband out onto the porch while she
had sex with the men.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to think,'' said Hardy, 25, who today
attends classes for medical transcription and lives in a
working-class neighborhood with a husband and children of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that age, when you're brought up around that, it's just
part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The family moved from New York to North Carolina when Christi _
known then by her birth name, Mary Anne Margaret Peek _ was 5. They
then moved briefly to Houston, then returned to a trailer park in
North Carolina in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Her paternal grandparents, Hardy recalled, bought the kids most
of their Christmas presents. Of her parents, she remembers chaos.
Her mom was temperamental, she said, ``never the pleasant mother.''
There were drunken rages, wild accusations, visits by the police.
</P>
<P>
   And sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy said she and her brother were sent to foster homes after
their father was convicted in August 1982 in Onslow County, N.C.,
of taking indecent liberties with a child and sentenced to three
years in prison. According to the North Carolina Department of
Corrections, Peek served less than a year before being paroled.
</P>
<P>
   LeRoy took the children for a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got involved and probably shouldn't have,'' she said. ``It
got Suzanne a little more involved in my life than I was able to
deal with at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time she saw her sister, she said, was in 1987 when Sue
returned to New York ``because she had problems psychologically and
she thought she could come into New York state and could take the
children back to Texas with her.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents didn't regain custody, however, and young Mary Anne
(Christi) went to live with her maternal grandmother elsewhere in
New York. The boy, Harold John Peek _ now 23 and known as James
O'Malley Jr. _ was sent to live with an aunt in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The pair gravitated back to their mother when they were young
adults.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, James and Sue Peek had their names legally changed to
O'Malley and began referring to their son as James David O'Malley
Jr. _ ``J.D.'' for short. The reason Sue gave was that some
ancestor had declared in a will that he wanted the family to take
the O'Malley name. But as with many of her mother's stories, Hardy
could find no truth in this one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, shortly before she married Scott Hardy in 1992, Mary Anne
Margaret Peek moved to Houston and changed her name to Christianna
Dianna O'Malley. She goes by Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two children, they were so bonded to her it was a
foregone conclusion they were going to end up with her,'' LeRoy
said of Sue's pull on her son and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But again, it was a turbulent relationship. Hardy's husband, who
worked as a security guard with James Peek/O'Malley and knew the
family before he met Christi, said he once had to step in when Sue
cuffed J.D. repeatedly for breaking an Irish figurine.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hardy also recalled that Sue nailed windows shut to keep
her son from leaving the apartment while she was away. He said she
ordered her son to a local mall to shoplift and to beg for leftover
rolls from Cinnabon. He said J.D. repeatedly complained that his
mother was forcing him to have sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hay, spokeswoman for Harris County Children's Protective
Services, said her agency and Houston police investigated
allegations made by James O'Malley Jr. when he was 17 that he was
being sexually abused. Neither found the allegations to be valid,
Hay said.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed that Sue Basso was manipulative and domineering.
Scott Hardy said the O'Malleys would serve guests on the few pieces
of fine china they owned, then warn them not to break it because of
how much it cost. They subscribed to magazines like the New Yorker
simply to impress visitors.
</P>
<P>
   For many who knew her, the strain of a relationship with Sue
Basso ultimately proved too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have a close relationship with her because, quite
frankly, I couldn't trust her,'' said LeRoy, recounting the lost
years with her sister. ``I just realized I had to put distance
between her and I if I was going to be able to function. It's very
painful to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   They feel guilty, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy repeatedly expressed a desire to apologize to the family
of the victim in the slaying case, Buddy Musso. A jogger discovered
Musso's body on the morning of Aug. 26 near a ditch in Galena Park,
a community of 11,000 just west of Houston. He had been savagely
beaten _ for breaking a Mickey Mouse ornament, police were told.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators think Musso was killed the night before in the
home of the four other defendants, an apartment in southwest
Houston. They say the attackers stripped him after the beating and
threw him into a bathtub filled with bleach and pine-scented
kitchen cleaner, possibly while he was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still dealing with this,'' said LeRoy. ``Part of my
problem is being the oldest child. It's like a second mother. I've
always had this sense of responsibility. It feels for me, just
thinking about this, that maybe if I had had more influence or time
trying to get through to her it wouldn't have been this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Also charged, along with Sue Basso and her son, are Bernice
Ahrens, 54; her son, Craig Ahrens, 25; her daughter, Hope Ahrens,
22; and the daughter's fiance, Terence Singleton, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Bernice Ahrens, a file clerk for a health-care business, had
moved into the apartment with her two children in late 1996.
Singleton moved in later.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment manager Donna Higgins said the family paid their rent
on time and never caused problems, but little more information
about them has emerged. Ahrens' employer called her a dedicated
worker who had never missed a day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A TYPE OF SERVITUDE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Musso, a widower described by a niece as having the mind
of a child, was the last person to live with Sue and her family. By
all accounts, it was not a pleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   Musso had been in an assisted-living home in Cliffside Park,
N.J., before boarding a Greyhound bus for Texas in June. He
received monthly Social Security checks and bagged groceries at a
local store. His son, Antonio, told The (Bergen County, N.J.)
Record that Musso had told him he had purchased an engagement ring
for Sue Basso, whom he had met at a church bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he had been led to believe they were going to marry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Musso was forced into a type of servitude, ordered to
sleep on a mattress in the living room of Basso's cluttered home.
Their landlord saw Basso order Musso around, having him carry in
groceries and take out the trash. A neighbor recalled seeing Musso
a few days before his death, beaten and bloody but afraid to call
police.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Chief Robert Pruett of the Galena Park police said the
man had been deprived of food as well.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of Aug. 26, Sue Basso was asking people who lived
nearby if they had seen Buddy. ``He's missing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett said she reported the same to police before a jogger
found the body along Main Street. It didn't take long, he said, to
find inconsistencies in Basso's story.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has since found a ``so-called last will and
testament'' of questionable legality for Musso. He said it
specifies that Sue Basso receive all insurance benefits, but that
police have been unable to find any life insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the death of Carmine Basso is being investigated as
well. He was found dead in his Latin Security office, but an
autopsy listed the manner of death as natural and the cause to be
erosive esophagitis, complicated by malnourishment. (Esophagitis,
sometimes referred to as gastroesophagal reflux disease, is marked
by severe heartburn caused by the backflow of stomach acid into the
esophagus.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely going to look at it,'' said Houston police
Sgt. Tom Ladd. ``I've got to get with the medical examiner and go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett said Sue Basso claimed at the time to be in New Jersey
when she called Houston police last year to report she had not
heard from her ``husband,'' Carmine. But he said he now has a
witness who claims she actually was in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   So Pruett is learning what many others already know: With Sue,
the truth is often hard to figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
