automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- NY-CARIBBEAN-PARADE, 9-4 --
One of the biggest draws, and biggest expenses, of the annual West
Indian American Day Carnival are the elaborate costumes like this
one being assembled by Mitch Phillips. Masquerade bands will spend
as much as $50,000 to march on Monday, the parade's 31st
anniversary. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) GRACE, Md. -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- UNUSUAL-MUSEUMS , 9-3 --
At the Decoy Museum in Havre de Grace, duck decoys surround a
likeness of R. Madison Mitchell, a well-known local carver. This
area was duck hunter's nirvana until a series of laws during the
1930s and '40s curtailed hunting. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- CLINTON-KIDS-2, 9-4 --
Kenny Prosper, a 14-year-old Bronx boy, says that his father
``played'' his mother many years ago, deserting the family and
sending them cascading into poverty and homelessness. If he were
Clinton's wife, Kenny says, ``I'd slap him silly.'' If he were the
president's daughter, ``I'd tell my mom to leave him, forget about
him. And I'd never think about him as an influence again.'' (Vic
DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HASTINGS-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. -- Sept. 4, 1998 --
CLINTON-KIDS-1, 9-4 -- ``The president and Monica Lewinsky had a
thing even though he was married to somebody else,'' says Chloe
Carrano, who is about to begin third grade in Hastings-on-Hudson.
America's children are aware that President Clinton was unfaithful
to his wife, but they seem less interested in the sexual details of
the White House scandal than the moral shortcomings of a man who
would deceive and hurt his family. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-DAY, 9-4 --
Third-seeded Jana Novotna during her 6-2, 6-3, defeat of France's
Sandrine Testud in the third round at the U.S. Open on Friday. The
Wimbledon champion needed only 56 minutes to triumph over her
second consecutive French foe, having ousted Amelie Cocheteux in
the second round. (Vic Delucia/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- CLINTON-LIEBERMAN, 9-4 --
``I felt lonely out there,'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman says of
delivering his recent speech critical of President Clinton.
Lieberman, a Democrat and longtime political ally of Clinton's,
says he was furious with the president - first for bad behavior,
second for behavior that he says undercut the theme of ``personal
responsibility'' that Clinton and Lieberman had advocated over the
years. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia -- Sept. 3, 1998 --
CRASH-RDP-2, 9-3 -- Two mourners stand by the Peggy's Cove
lighthouse and look out to sea toward the area of the crash of
Swissair Flight 111. 175 friends and relatives of the 229 crash
victims were flown here from New York and Europe. They will be
asked to indentify their loved ones from among the bodies found
thus far. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia -- Sept. 3, 1998 --
CRASH-RDP-1, 9-3 -- Escorted by Red Cross volunteers, some of the
friends and relatives of the 229 victims of Swissair Flight 111
survey the crash site and mourn their losses Friday. 175 friends
and relatives of the 229 crash victims were flown here from New
York and Europe. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1998 -- LURIE-NOVELS, 9-4 -- Alison
Lurie's latest novel is set in Key West, Fla., where she has a
home. Lurie is a transoceanic novelist, equally at home on both
sides of the Atlantic, but with an even greater following in
England than in the United States. Although she lives most of the
year in Ithaca, N.Y., where she teaches children's literature at
Cornell University, she keeps an apartment in London. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
