<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-TRAFFIC-2ndTak     09-04 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-TRAFFIC-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: xxx pride there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The market for heroin in Dallas-Fort Worth began to heat up two
years ago as young people began using it not just in the suburbs
but in inner-city Fort Worth and Dallas, where young addicts left
crack to the ``old people,'' according to dealers and law
enforcement experts.
</P>
<P>
   Lemarcus Tyrone ``T-Dog'' Williams, 25, said he sold more heroin
than crack in the years he was dealing out of a house in the Stop
Six neighborhood of Fort Worth. Only four of his 20 friends did not
use heroin, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   He increasingly sold to white youths from the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These white kids come and buy double and triple what people in
my neighborhood buy,'' Williams said. ``They're scared to come to
my neighborhood, so they buy more.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was arrested last year on heroin and cocaine
charges, is serving nine years in prison for possession with intent
to distribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heroin has been in my neighborhood ever since I can
remember,'' he said. ``Where were the feds before? As long as you
stay in your own neighborhood, they leave you alone. They just came
after us because a bunch of white people started coming to my
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade of law enforcement crackdowns in South Florida and in
California helped push heroin traffickers to develop routes into
Texas, drug agents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the Pillsbury Dough Boy effect. You punch them in
the tummy and it sticks out somewhere else,'' said U.S. Senior
District Judge John Kane in Denver, a critic of the national drug
strategy on interdiction.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, traffickers began flooding North Texas
neighborhoods with highly potent forms of black tar heroin that can
be snorted, and major dealers began moving into the area, the DEA's
Lunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first was Juan Nieves Mendoza-Villanueva of Fort
Worth, who operated a cocaine distribution ring dating to the
mid-1980s, then began selling heroin, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When Mendoza-Villanueva was arrested in 1997, his organization
was smuggling 2 pounds of black tar heroin _ almost $1 million
worth _ each month, Lunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza-Villanueva, 44, a distant relative of jailed Mexican
drug kingpin Juan Garcia Abrego, is serving a 191/2-year federal
sentence in Fort Worth. After Mendoza-Villanueva's arrest, DEA
officials say another Fort Worth dealer moved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Nieves Mendoza was down, Jose Vega right after that gets
arrested in just a matter of months with 3 pounds of Mexican black
tar heroin,'' Lunt said. ``There are organizations out there ready
to take another organization's place.''
</P>
<P>
   Vega, 36, has been indicted on heroin charges and is scheduled
to go on trial Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican heroin traffickers control 90 percent of the Texas
market, but smugglers from Colombia, Nigeria, Russia and Turkey
have also set up shop here and throughout the United States,
looking for a piece of the lucrative action, federal officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's all kinds of entrepreneurs out there who have targeted
the U.S. market,'' said Don Ferrarone, a retired DEA special agent
who was in charge of the Houston office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a Turkish drug ring wrapped 163 pounds of heroin in
wax, placed it in water softener containers and shipped it on a
commercial flight from Istanbul to D/FW Airport, said Paul Coggins,
U.S. attorney for the Northern District of Texas. The heroin, worth
an estimated $46 million on the street, was then trucked to Lubbock
in West Texas, where the drug ring wanted to test the North
American market by pushing heroin in Dallas-Fort Worth as well as
in large Northern cities, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The ring was discovered after a tip from European authorities,
Coggins said. Investigators found an estimated 50 pounds of heroin
in a shed at the importer's residence. He led authorities to the
rest of the stash, the largest seizure of Southwest Asian heroin in
the United States and the sixth-largest of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, the last of five men was convicted of setting
up the organization. The convictions put a dent in the ring,
Coggins said.
</P>
<P>
   A temporary dent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be naive to think that we shut that organization down
completely,'' he said. ``It's more accurate to say that we've stung
them, but they may move to another town like Wichita Falls or San
Angelo.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug traffickers are armed with all the high-tech gadgetry that
enormous drug profits can buy. They use night-vision goggles,
automatic weapons, cellular telephones that have been ``cloned''
with stolen phone numbers that are impossible to trace, encrypted
phones that scramble conversations, and portable radios that are
readily available in Army surplus stores or on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   Area distributors sometimes use computers to organize their
highly profitable enterprises and remote video cameras to track the
movements of law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Traffickers also rely on years of accumulated information about
law enforcement strategies to stay a step ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Nestoroff, the DPS airplane smuggling expert, distributed
brochures listing the ``signs of a smuggler'' to small Texas
airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they posted the brochures up on the board at the airport
and they (the traffickers) were right there, writing down what it
said and learning what to be careful about,'' Nestoroff said.
</P>
<P>
   To elude authorities who rely on such profiles, traffickers
became equal opportunity employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that you would see a lone man headed to San
Antonio and you would say, `Ah ha, there's our heroin smuggler,' ''
said Robert Gonzalez, a U.S. customs inspector at the Hidalgo
international bridge, about seven miles from McAllen in far South
Texas. ``Now we catch all types _ men and women, old and young, one
man or a whole family.''
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 3RD TAKE FOLLOWS) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
