<HEADER>
A0509 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-TRAFFIC-3rdTak     09-04 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-TRAFFIC-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: xxx whole family.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffickers also use a multitude of smuggling methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffickers become smarter in time,'' the DEA's
Villaescusa said. ``You have three seizures at the airport and,
boom, they will adjust and won't use the airport for a while and
use another way to get it here.''
</P>
<P>
   When smugglers saw that U.S. officials were getting more
sophisticated at stopping small airplanes hauling drugs, they
started using trucks, which are virtually camouflaged among the
thousands of trucks crossing the border each day _ traffic that
continues to grow as the North American Free Trade Agreement
eliminates trade barriers at U.S. borders.
</P>
<P>
   To elude Texas highway patrol officers who monitor the area's
drug pipeline roads _ Interstates 35, 30 and 20 and U.S. 59 and 75
_ smugglers divide large shipments of heroin into multiple
vehicles, making it more difficult to detect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see what these guys doing interdiction stops are
facing,'' the DPS' Caley said. ``They are looking for the mother
lode, but the mother's babies are getting by. There are smaller
loads that are going by in pickups and cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffickers exploit the increased air routes to Central and
South America from D/FW Airport. They ship drugs in the cargo holds
of airliners and hide their stashes behind walls in toilets.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines intensified its anti-drug efforts, including
use of drug-sniffing dogs, when it added flights to Latin America
in 1990, spokesman Tim Smith said. But there are no machines that
can screen for drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traffickers, on the other hand, have their own drug dogs to
``sniff-proof'' drug cargo. They also buy into established
companies to help disguise their illicit trade, federal officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of new money-laundering laws requiring banks to
report deposits larger than $10,000, drug organizations changed
their tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we got more sophisticated, they got even better at money
laundering,'' the Customs Service's Figueroa said.
</P>
<P>
   With huge profits at stake, heroin traffickers have become more
violent.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation can be swift and deadly for dealers and couriers who
break rank. ``There's cases up and down Texas of someone losing a
load and turning up in a car, gagged, with their hands tied and
shot execution-style,'' said Roberto Medina, U.S. Customs Service
associate agent in charge in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those on the front lines of the drug war say that law
enforcement efforts against the heroin flow can be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrarone recommends persistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this takes a total commitment that doesn't go away
every time we have a new administration,'' he said. ``You get a
bunch of smart people together, devise a plan and turn up the heat
and cause the organizations to basically run out of fuel. But it
doesn't happen overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Well-coordinated, hardball efforts such as the investigation in
Plano can reinforce the message that a community won't stand for
drug trafficking, said Mike Bradford, U.S. attorney for the Eastern
District of Texas. The indictments were the result of cooperation
among local, state and federal law enforcement agencies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the drugs go elsewhere, then we'll worry about that another
time, because we need help right now here,'' U.S. Attorney Coggins
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
