<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSTON-STOX-HNS &LR;      09-04 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-STOX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S STOCKS HIT EARLY, HARD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Area investors lamenting this week's stock market
carnage would have felt a lot more pain if they heavily invested in
local companies.
</P>
<P>
   This year's market swoon pummeled Houston stocks earlier and
harder than stocks elsewhere. Once again, the city's dependence on
energy businesses and other commodities is the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil-service stocks, in particular, have suffered severely
in this market and I think it's somewhat overdone,'' said money
manager Richard J. Fruth of Richard J. Fruth &AMP; Associates in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A look at 50 of Houston's biggest publicly traded companies
showed the average stock was down 18.8 percent for the year through
last Friday. &UR;  &LR; That compares to a 0.36 percent rise in Standard &AMP;
Poor's benchmark of 500 large companies through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 losers, all of which lost more than 50 percent, were
all businesses in oil and gas, and oil-field services, according to
the list.
</P>
<P>
   The list was compiled by Chase Bank of Texas, with updated
calculations by the Houston Chronicle using information from
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston companies were definitely hit harder than the overall
stock market because of the concentration of energy companies in
the population,'' said Henry Lartigue, Chase's chief investment
officer. ``It's the energy stocks that are pulling this average
down.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some notable winners on the list. The top 10 companies
were in a variety of industries and included American General Corp.
(financial services), Compaq Computer Corp., NL Industries
(pigments and specialty chemicals), BMC Software and Waste
Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer stocks in general this year have done pretty well,''
Lartigue said.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of Houston stocks makes a strong case that while
it's good for an investor who knows local companies well to invest
in some hometown favorites, it's also important to diversify by
looking outside this area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have such a concentration of energy companies that in
the boom times, we tend to overperform and in the lean times, we
tend to take it on the chin more than others,'' said David Lapin,
president of Lapin &AMP; Wigginton Asset Management in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Falling prices for commodities, ranging from grains to gas, also
has hit mining companies.
</P>
<P>
   In precious metals, gold prices have been dismal, and that's
stung the stock of Battle Mountain Gold Co., a Houston gold-mining
company.
</P>
<P>
   Battle Mountain stock, which was down 16 percent last year, has
slid even further, falling 19.6 percent for the year through
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold has lost its status over about the past decade as an
inflation hedge, primarily because if you're scared of inflation or
some sort of political problem in your country, it's a lot easier
to move into another country's currency,'' said Lynn Bernard Jr.,
executive vice president of global investment strategies at
Pinnacle Management &AMP; Trust in Houston, a money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of gold by central banks around the world also have
depressed gold prices, said portfolio manager B.J. Willingham,
president of Willingham Asset Management in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The problems locally are not just related to falling commodity
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the companies in the consolidation business _ buying
smaller operators and building national operations _ have also been
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the consolidators have been hit pretty hard
recently,'' said Mel Cody, an analyst at Sanders Morris Mundy in
Houston, an investment bank that has advised many consolidators.
</P>
<P>
   Falling share prices are particularly bad news for these
companies because they use their shares for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   So when stock prices fall, ``that means the currency you use for
acquisitions is being devalued,'' Cody said.
</P>
<P>
   While Houston's economy is more diversified than it was before
the Oil Bust, commodity prices still matter most.
</P>
<P>
   While the value of oil company stocks moved up late this week _
reacting to oil prices moving above $14 a barrel and moves by
companies to buy back shares _ they still are depressed for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the commodity price comes down, the market will start to
mark down the value of companies that have reserves in the ground
because it makes proven reserves worth less,'' Lartigue said.
``Since the price has come down so hard, a lot of the exploration
companies will simply delay doing further exploration, and that is
even worse on the companies in the service business that provide
the drilling pipe, the rig.''
</P>
<P>
   The drop in oil and gas prices is part of a general decline that
had pushed commodity prices to 21-year lows. This is explained by
an oversupply of some commodities, according to Goldman Sachs, a
New York investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Houston energy stocks started feeling the pain earlier than the
rest of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because oil prices started to come under pressure earlier in
the year, the energy stocks have been weak since the beginning of
the year,'' Lartigue said. ``Most of these energy stocks peaked
last year and started down.''
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas prices haven't fallen as much as crude oil prices,
but they have suffered because of a glut that had its roots in last
year's warm winter and a seasonal downturn that always hits between
the hot summer months and the winter heating season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drop in energy stocks, Lartigue argues they're still
a good investment long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hiccup that we've gone through is simply a pullback in
the price of oil,'' he said. ``Overall, the demand for energy
should rise over the next five years because developing countries
are growing and they will have greater demand for energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asian troubles also figure into the declines here in several
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many commodities, including oil, are priced in U.S.
dollars, the dollar's strength against Asian currencies has made
them more expensive for overseas customers, Goldman Sachs said.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's financial crisis has shut down the region's construction
projects, cutting demand for such industrial metals as aluminum,
copper, nickel and zinc, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Coach USA, a company that operates bus lines, saw its stock
plummet from a high of 52 in July to 27 3/4 Friday. Investors are
worried that a reduction in Asian tourists will hurt Coach's West
Coast operations, Cody said.
</P>
<P>
   Falling stock prices have made companies skittish about going
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of capital raised in Houston over the last
several years in energy and it's pretty tough to do that now,''
Willingham said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
