<HEADLINE>
MD-11 HAS GOOD SAFETY RECORD, BUT SOME FLAWS THAT COULD POSE FIRE
HAZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs `hours' for `miles' in description of jet's history; adds
details on Swissair's performance and reputation; polishing and
rewriting throughout.) (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-VICTIMS, CRASH-DITCH and
CRASH-SWISSAIR) 
(js) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The widebodied MD-11 jet designed by McDonnell
Douglas has been in service since 1990 and is widely regarded as
safe and reliable, but Federal Aviation Administration records show
that the plane has had a number of mechanical problems _including
some that posed fire hazards _ and several accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation experts and analysts also say that Swissair has had a
solid safety record and is considered one of the world's top
airlines, particularly in the maintenance of its fleet of 62
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Swissair plane that crashed Wednesday night near Halifax,
Nova Scotia, was 7 years old _ fairly young by aviation standards _
and had flown 35,000 hours in 6,400 flights. The pilot reported
smoke _ but not fire _ in the cockpit before the MD-11 was lost
from radar.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-11 is a longer, wider and more efficient version of the
DC-10, which is still flown by many airlines throughout the world.
As with other models, there have been several instances in the past
of flaws in the MD-11 leading the manufacturer and the FAA to call
for inspections, repairs or alterations to prevent electrical
short-circuits, fuel spills, overheating or other potential fire
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those actions were taken after reports of smoke or fire
in a plane while it was in service, or by the discovery during
maintenance of electrical wires that were chafed or charred or of
some other tell-tale sign of damage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, FAA records show a potential fire hazard from
arcing in electrical contacts between a cable and a generator;
smoke in a cargo compartment during loading, caused by damaged
cables feeding power into the plane; damage to fuel conduits in the
fuselage; a malfunction in a vacuum waste exhaust heater that could
ignite insulation in the cargo hold, and several instances of
chafing of various wire bundles that posed the threat of electrical
fires.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Transportation Safety Board, there
have been several accidents involving MD-11s. But the plane's
safety record is on a par with other airplanes in widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   The only other major accident involving an MD-11 occurred in
1997 when a Federal Express jet landing at Newark International
Airport bounced, rolled and caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   The main wing slats on an Eastern Airlines plane en route to
China deployed improperly in 1993, causing the plane to buck
violently in the air over Alaska. Two people died and several dozen
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   A fire on an American Airlines MD-11 at New York's Kennedy
Airport in 1995 forced the plane's evacuation, in which two people
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA issues airworthiness directives mandating that U.S.
airlines fix flaws as they are discovered, but the directives are
not binding on foreign airlines unless the aviation agencies in
those countries issue similar orders. Most developed countries and
large airlines, however, especially those flying into the United
States, comply with the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also generally comply with safety and mechanical
recommendations from airplane manufacturers, known as alert service
bulletins, which normally form the basis for any FAA directives.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Breitler, a Swissair spokesman, said Friday that the
airline routinely complies with all directives, mandatory or not.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair's last fatal accident was in 1979, when a DC-8 landing
in Athens overshot the runway. The plane caught fire, and 14 people
aboard were killed. The crash of Swissair Flight 111 was the
company's worst disaster since its founding in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you have heard about the Swiss, you can apply to
Swissair,'' said Stuart Matthews of the Flight Safety Institute, a
nonprofit group based in Arlington, Va., that monitors safety
issues. ``It is known throughout the industry for meticulous care
and the quality of its maintenance and its crews.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other European carriers, Swissair has faced an increasingly
competitive business environment as governments increasingly allow
deregulation and airlines struggle for passengers in an area
densely packed with major airports. The company has already taken
some steps to cut costs and increase efficiency, closing
nonproductive hubs and making personnel changes. It has also sought
links with other airlines to expand its customer base.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company hired Jeffrey Katz, a former American
Airlines executive, to run its daily operations. While some
analysts said it was not unheard of for airlines, including
American carriers, to hire foreign chief executives, others said
the company was trying to bring in experience from the deregulated
U.S. market. The theory, analysts said, was that an executive who
could survive in the cutthroat world of U.S. airline competition
would be better able to guide the company as Europe became more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign airlines flying to and from airports in the United
States are required to meet international safety standards set by
the International Civil Aviation Organization, a U.N. agency,
although in some cases these rules are not identical to regulations
issued by the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The international rules are meant to provide a common level of
protection while preserving each nation's right to regulate and
inspect its own airlines. The FAA, in turn, reviews each foreign
nation's enforcement practices before allowing airlines from that
country to operate here.
</P>
<P>
   But many important safety regulations issued by the FAA apply to
all airlines operating in this country, agency officials said.
Among these are rules governing hazardous cargo, including
materials that might cause fires.
</P>
<P>
   After oxygen generators carried in the cargo hold of a Valujet
Airlines DC-9 in Florida in 1996 started a fire that caused the
plane to crash, killing all 110 people on board, the FAA issued a
regulation prohibiting both foreign and domestic airlines from
transporting them on passenger flights with at least one stop in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the FAA disclosed that both domestic and foreign
airlines may have unwittingly violated the rules.
</P>
<P>
   After Boeing acquired the manufacturer in 1990, it announced
that it would stop making the three-engined MD-11, which is a
larger and more efficient variant of the DC-10, in the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
