<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ACCREDITATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UT RESIDENCY PROGRAM MAY LOSE ITS ACCREDITATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The University of Texas-Houston Health Science
Center's 5-year-old program in emergency medicine _ the only such
program in the region _ faces losing its accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still an accredited residency program,'' said Dr.
Maximillian Buja, dean of the UT Medical School at Houston. ``But
we have received a notice of the intent to withdraw accreditation,
which would be effective July 1, 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the accrediting body is most concerned about the
leadership of the program, which is now under its fourth chairman
in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The notice came from the Accreditation Council for Graduate
Medical Education, which oversees the qualifications of medical
residency programs nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Residency programs train medical school graduates in various
medical specialties, such as pediatrics, obstetrics-gynecology,
surgery and emergency medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Such training programs in emergency medicine are reviewed
regularly by a special committee of the accreditation council to
ensure that they meet the agency's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The notice does not mean that the training program definitely
will lose its accreditation, Buja said. The UT Medical School now
is trying to determine whether it should appeal the accrediting
body's decision or simply try to start a new program after the
accreditation is withdrawn, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If UT decides to appeal, it must file its rationale as to why
the accreditation should not be withdrawn by November, Buja said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that because this emergency medicine program is the
only one in the Houston-Galveston area, it is a critical community
need,'' he said. ``We have every intention of successfully
appealing this or resurrecting a program after that. We intend to
have an emergency medicine residency program.''
</P>
<P>
   The program started as a new department about five years ago,
under its first chairman, Dr. David Olson. But Olson resigned and
was replaced by Dr. Michael McCallum.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum, however, became ill shortly after he was named and he
later died, Buja said. Then Dr. Norberto Adame was named acting
chief, and the department was made a division of the surgery
department to give it more administrative stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Adame stepped down as chairman, though remaining on the
staff, and is now director of emergency medicine at Hermann
Hospital in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Adame was replaced by the present acting chief, Dr. John Harris,
a radiologist. Buja said, ``Dr. Harris is one of our senior
faculty, and he has a lot of administrative experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Buja said a nationwide search is under way for a new person to
head the emergency medicine division.
</P>
<P>
   Eight new emergency medicine residents enter the program every
year. There are now 24 residents in the three-year program, Buja
said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, who are physicians undergoing additional training in
the specifics of emergency medicine, practice in the Hermann
Hospital emergency room, Buja said.
</P>
<P>
   Accreditation is important because most residents must train in
an accredited program before they are qualified to take exams that
would certify them as emergency medicine doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the existing students could finish before the
accreditation is taken away _ if it is _ but the others would have
to transfer or risk graduating from a non-accredited program.
</P>
<P>
   The American Board of Emergency Medicine is an official
certifying body for emergency medicine physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a shortage of emergency medicine physicians in Texas
and nationwide,'' Buja said.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions that managed care would reduce emergency department
visits and thus the need for emergency physicians have proved
false, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Memorial-Hermann system will have 200,000 emergency room
visits this year, Buja said.
</P>
<P>
   In the May issue of the Annals of Emergency Medicine, John
Moorhead, the next president of the American College of Emergency
Physicians &UR; , &LR;  and some colleagues documented the need for emergency
medicine physicians by pointing out that many of those now staffing
emergency rooms are not board-certified.
</P>
<P>
   In his study, he found that 58 percent of physicians practicing
the nation's nearly 5,000 emergency departments were emergency
medicine-residency trained and 53 percent were board-certified in
emergency medicine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
