<HEADER>
A0522 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-MALONE-CELLUCCI-BO     09-04 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MALONE-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MALONE AND CELLUCCI, RHETORIC TURNS PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One candidate says the other is a hypocrite without a
vision for leading the state. His opponent has responded in kind,
calling his rival disingenuous and, in what he considers the
ultimate insult, a liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Do you get the feeling that Paul Cellucci and Joe Malone don't
like each other very much?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be damned if I'm going to let him attack my character
without responding,'' Malone said forcefully this week after
watching a new Cellucci attack ad. ``Everything is on the table in
next week's debate.'' That, said Malone, includes Cellucci's
reported $700,000 personal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci fired back: ``He's been pounding me for eight months,
and I decide to give him a little taste of his own medicine, and he
melts down. It's stunning. Stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, the acting governor, and Malone, the state treasurer _
candidates for the Republican nomination for governor _ have had an
increasingly strained relationship since they took office in the
executive branch in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have only worsened in recent days, and the hostility
is sure to be loud and noticeable Wednesday night when the two men
meet again in Worcester for their last televised debate before the
Sept. 15 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Their two camps have split the GOP in Massachusetts. On one side
are Malone's supporters, who believe they are the heirs of Ronald
Reagan's legacy, true antigovernment conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side &UR;  &LR; are the Cellucci people, disciples of former
Governor William F. Weld and the torch-bearers for a balanced
budget, lower taxes, and social liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci people say Malone is destroying the Republican party by
waging a negative campaign against the acting governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem with Joe Malone is he just rolls around in the mud
all the time and never seems able to say anything good about anyone
other than himself,'' said Senator Brian P. Lees, an East
Longmeadow Republican who is close to Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   The Malone people imply that Cellucci is intimidated by Malone's
political skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul has never been comfortable with Joe,'' said Tom Trimarco,
Malone's first deputy treasurer. ``He has always seen Joe as a
looming presence.''
</P>
<P>
   History is full of political rivalries. George Bush accused
Ronald Reagan of practicing voodoo economics. Bob Dole snarled at
Bush to ``stop lying about my record.'' In the 1990 Massachusetts
GOP primary campaign, Bill Weld portrayed Steven Pierce as an
out-of-touch ``right-wing ideologue.''
</P>
<P>
   The interesting twist to the Cellucci-Malone fight is that the
two men may have more similarities than differences. Both are
Italian, both are Republicans. Cellucci, 50, attended his local
high school, Hudson Catholic; his family ran a car sales business.
Malone, 44, went to his local high school, Waltham High; his family
ran a trucking business.
</P>
<P>
   Both entered politics at a relatively young age. Cellucci was 29
when he was elected a state representative; Malone ran against US
Senator Edward M. Kennedy in 1990 at age 33.
</P>
<P>
   But there are differences. Cellucci reached the executive branch
by first serving in the Legislature for 14 years; Malone has no
legislative experience. Cellucci studied accounting at Boston
College; Malone played football at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cellucci nor Malone will admit to feelings of enmity.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person, I like him,'' Malone said. ``I think he's a nice
fellow. I plan on winning this race, but if it turns out I don't,
I'll say, `Let's go to work electing some Republicans, including
Paul Cellucci.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said the two used to go out for lunch twice a year in
the Italian North End, and they've been to New Orleans to watch the
Super Bowl with Weld.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always gotten along great with Joe Malone,'' said
Cellucci, who had once suggested through intermediaries that Malone
become his running mate. Malone declined.
</P>
<P>
   But the Malone camp says that during the Weld years, Cellucci
jealously guarded access to the popular governor, shutting Malone
out. And the only time the pair went to lunch was in 1995, after
they had both won reelection and a showdown in the race for
governor looked to be inevitable. Over pasta at Filippo's, the two
tried to reach detente.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci says he is surprised that Malone felt locked out of the
corner office. ``I was the one, quite often, saying we ought to
invite Joe Malone to this or to that,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   If Cellucci is angry, it's at the tenor of the campaign. ``My
complaint is that since January, he has run a very negative
campaign,'' he said. ``I think the Republican party has done a good
job of bringing Massachusetts back. I think we've got a remarkable
story to tell, and he seems to be trying to tear that down.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, on the other hand, says their differences are deep and
philosophical, not personal. ``We come from two different
approaches. He comes up from inside (the State House), and I come
from outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure began building at last week's Republican debate in
Springfield, as Malone nearly called Cellucci a liar, using the
words ``disingenuous'' and ``unfair and misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, on the other hand, called Malone a hypocrite, in a
slightly nicer manner. ``The campaign of Joe Malone is do as I say,
not as I do,'' Cellucci said, asserting improper patronage in the
Treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, Cellucci unveiled ``Chocolate or Glazed,'' also
known as the donut ad. The ad refers to a ``secret slush fund _
paid for with your tax dollars'' for Christmas parties, rock
concerts, golf fees, and donuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Joe Malone wants his hands on the $19.5 billion state
budget,'' the ad says. ``No wonder. At $3.50 a dozen, that's over
65 billion donuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone responded sharply, promising to dredge up Cellucci's very
large, and largely unexplained, debts.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he was incredulous at Malone's reaction. The
intent of the ad, he said, is not to impugn Malone's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the reformer he says he is,'' Cellucci said. ``He's
not the fiscal conservative he says he is. That's the intent of the
ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as history is filled with political rivalries, so, too, is
it replete with stories of mended fences. Bush forgot about voodoo
economics long enough to become Reagan's vice president. The
snarling Dole carried Bush's legislative agenda through Congress.
And Weld put the out-of-touch Steve Pierce in charge of human
services.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and Malone say their enmity will end the day after the
primary. Malone says the two men will share a bowl of pasta and
move on; Cellucci said the specter of a big-spending Democrat in
the corner office will bring the campaigns together.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, after all the name-calling and venom, the pasta
get-together will be one closely watched political meal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
