<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV06-B     09-04 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disparity between elite and popular opinion of Bill Clinton
has never been greater. Congressional Democrats have begun taking
potshots at the president; it's hard to find a pundit who hasn't
called for his head. Meanwhile, the public puts its approval of
Clinton's conduct of the presidency in the vicinity of 70 percent.
They cannot both be right.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be the prestige press which has lost its way? A
suggestive piece of evidence that it &UR;  &LR; has is to be found in the
treatment that television, magazines and newspapers have accorded
Clinton's second speech about the Lewinsky matter _ the one he made
in a little church on Martha's Vinyard at Oak Bluffs. It has been
all but ignored.
</P>
<P>
   I obviously cannot prove it, but my conviction has only grown
that the heart of it was among the most remarkable political
speeches in self-defense of the last half century _ comparable to
John F. Kennedy's address on the subject of his catholicism
delivered to protestant ministers in Houston, or Martin Luther
King's ``I've been to the mountaintop'' speech in Memphis, on a par
certainly with Nixon's ``Checkers'' speech _ and light years apart
from it in tone.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the press has treated it as if it had little or no
significance. Nor have the newspapers supplied the background
necessary to understand the difference between the two speeches,
and the distance that the president travelled between them. They
have not yet been able to pin down what transpired in the course of
Clinton's testimony that fateful Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's second take on Monica Lewinsky comprised only three
paragraphs at the end of a lengthy speech to a small congrgation in
Union Chapel on the 35th anniversary of Martin Luther King's ``I
have a dream'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   The president apparently wrote the speech longhand that morning,
without the aid of lawyers or speechwriters. He delivered it with
an umistakable transparency. There was no biting of the lower lip,
though his blink-rate escalated sharply at one point, and his eyes
bulged with emotion at another. I quote the end of the speech here
in full, though a transcript is a poor substitute for seeing and
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you know that I'm having to become quite an expert in
this business of asking forgiveness. And I ... It gets a little
easier the more you do it. &UR;  &LR; And if you have a family, an
Administration, a Congress and a whole country to ask, you're going
to get a lot of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to tell you in these last days it's come home to me
again, something I first learned as President, but it wasn't burned
in my bones _ and that is, in order to get it you've got to be
willing to give it. And all of us _ the anger, the resentment, the
bitterness, the desire for recrimination against people you believe
have wronged you _ they harden the heart and deaden the spirit and
lead to self-inflicted wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so it is important that we are able to forgive those we
believe have wronged us, even as we ask for forgiveness from those
we have wronged. And I heard that first _ first _ in the civil
rights movement. `Love thy neighbor as thyself.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is here that a little exegesis will help.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton muffed the speech he made Monday night, August 17,
after testifying before a grand jury for four hours, it apparently
was because he was so furious he could barely contain himself.
</P>
<P>
   Why furious? Starr's prosecutors are reported to have pressed
the president for extremely intimate details of the
relationship. &UR;  &LR; According to one account, Clinton is said to have
interrupted his testimony for an hour in rage over graphic
questions. (There were five interruptions in all, according to
Newsweek.) By all accounts, he is said to have left the questioning
in high dudgeon _ and immediately reinstated in his address the
attack on Starr that so many persons found inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of some details of the testimony purporting to be
dependable story emerged slowly. First Newsweek reported that a
``knowledgeable source'' close to Starr had said, ``When people
read his report, they'll want to throw up.'' Then, citing
``multiple sources close to the case,'' web reporter Matt Drudge
ventured some salacious details. Next the New York Post and several
British papers followed. And soon it all boiled over on talk radio
_ from whence it moved into the nation's high schools and junior
highs and onto late-night television including Jay Leno. Then the
web-zine Slate undertook an inventory of the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't made it into the prestige press. Renewed court
strictures against leaks of grand jury testimony have prevented
mainstream news reporters from obtaining the kind of multiple
source corroboration required to ascribe the rumor to genuinely
knowledgable sources.
</P>
<P>
   (Clinton's problems began on the business pages with the saga of
Whitewater; perhaps it is only fitting they should return there
when they become so excessively personal that there is no appetite
for them on the front page.)
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the alleged practice was undignified. The
grossly unequal relationship between the chief executive and the
intern was inappropriate, even Clinton has admitted. But to many
persons, including the president, it was the line of questioning
about the detail of the relationship that was truly disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Clinton had already admitted a sexual affair to the
grand jury; it was the first thing he did when he sat down that
day. And his sexual conduct has little or no bearing on the conduct
of his other duties in the minds of most Americans. In pressing for
the details _ if that is what they did _ the prosecutors may have
revealed an interest so prurient, a self-righteousness so great and
a malice so keen as to deeply violate the trust that had been
placed in them. No wonder Clinton walked out. No wonder he made the
angry speech he did that night.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of roasting from friends and foes alike for having
lashed out at his foe that Monday evening, Clinton returned to the
subject on Friday, August 28 with his meditation on his
``self-inflicted wounds'' at Oak Bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   Granted that the speech was not teed up for networks'
convenience in prime-time. Granted also that the president is such
a virtuoso talker that it is difficult to tell whether you are
getting the real thing. Still, the speech seemed to do several
much-needed things at once, deftly and economically.
</P>
<P>
   It repeated the apology _ at least as much apology as Clinton
apparently intends to make. It laid out the situation as he sees
it, juxtaposing his sexual misconduct with his enemies' political
vendetta. And it underscored the fundamental truth of forgiveness _
that it must be mutual _ which makes it so unlikely that it will be
forthcoming in this situation. More likely the Hatfields should
forgive the McCoys. The nation eventually will change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that the true test of a chief executive's ability is
the willingness to endlessly repeat himself, and generally speaking
that is true. But this was a rare moment of genuine political
theater _ a man attempting to serve as the chief defender of
civility in public life _ even while admitting his contemptible
behavior that permitted the assault on it to commence in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   If there were another Democrat of any stature on the scene, this
responsibility might be divided. He or she might tackle Starr and
his supporters: for their attempt to infuse the civil realm with
religiosity, the legal realm with political purpose. As it is,
Clinton must defend himself _ and the Republic as well.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr's report will be presented to the Congress. We
will have access to the details of his investigation. Then it will
be reasonable to make up our minds as to whose conduct has been
more offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it makes sense to remember that we have been
listening to a one-sided conversation. ``There is a tidal feeling
of betrayal and embarrassment running across the country today,''
thundered the New York Times on the day after Starr apparently
pressed Clinton about the details of his sex life. By the time
Starr's report gets to Congress, that tide may well be running the
other way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
