<HEADER>
A0535 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-LADN     09-04 1743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-LADN </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE'S ROOTS REACH TO CLAREMONT, CALIF. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCONNELL  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of a disastrous work stoppage in 1994-95, major
league baseball was in dire need of a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it has one. His name is Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The man you see every night on TV is the real McGwire, a modest
young man enjoying the wave of fame.
</P>
<P>
   But what the public doesn't see is a man with whom family comes
first, and to whom nothing came easy. His path to baseball
greatness was the path less traveled, a steep road littered with
the rocks of misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is about failure,'' McGwire said earlier this year.
``Even the best hitters make out seven out of every 10 at-bats.
Anyone can handle success. To play in the major leagues, you have
to be able to handle failure.''
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in omens, here's one for you: McGwire, at age 10,
hit a home run in his first at-bat in Little League.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in reality, here's a big dose: McGwire has
suffered seven career-threatening injuries, a couple of serious
illnesses and a host of bumps and bruises. He's learned to accept
failure and to play in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Long before he closed in on Roger Maris's single-season home run
record, back when he was a youngster growing up in Claremont,
McGwire learned to persevere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised more has not been written about all that Mark
has overcome,'' said Jack Helber, one of several local coaches who
influenced the slugger.
</P>
<P>
   Helber, a teacher at Claremont High in Claremont, Calif.,
coached McGwire in 1980 and '81 with the Claremont Cardinals
American Legion team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was ever given to him,'' Helber said. ``He's worked so
hard for success that you have to admire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's suffered a string of injuries, ever since he was a
freshman in high school. But he's battled back, every time. He
changed positions -- from pitcher to first base -- very late in his
baseball life, but still made the majors. Through it all, he hasn't
changed a bit. He's a genuine person, a super nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's taking some sort of supplement, it's not to get
stronger. It's to stay healthy. I'm sure, right now, his worst
nightmare is suffering a season-ending injury.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire transferred from Claremont High to Damien in 1977, in
the middle of his freshman year. At Damien, he played basketball
and baseball. His athletic accomplishments in both sports were
limited by a series of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most serious injury Mark had, while he was at Damien, was
a back injury,'' said Tom Carroll, the school's athletic director
and Mark's baseball coach. ``That was when he was a freshman, and
it really set him back. In fact, for a time there was some question
as to whether he would be able to play any sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, he was able to return to basketball and baseball.
Then, he hurt a knee as a junior and that was another setback for
him. People tend to forget that Mark was a very good basketball
player. If he had stayed healthy, who knows? He might have gotten
some scholarship offers in basketball and chosen that over
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire chose not to play football -- a decision that labeled
him as ``soft'' in some minds. Coming out of high school, one major
league scouting report on McGwire carried the notation: ``Injury
prone. Lacks toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are two labels McGwire has spent the past 20 years trying
to shed.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was a good player for Damien, but not a great one. He
was the Spartans' co-Most Valuable Player as a senior, sharing the
award with another pitcher, Mike Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good ballclub in Mark's senior season,'' Carroll
said. ``Mark and Alexander were our top two pitchers. We had a good
catcher in Mike Dorning, who went to Notre Dame, and a good center
fielder in David Turney, who played at Mt. San Antonio College and
then at the University of Nebraska. So, I can't really say Mark was
the best player on that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt Mark was a pro prospect. But he was a long way from
being a polished player.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire played well enough, however, to impress Marcel
Lachemann, then the pitching coach at USC. Lachemann convinced USC
head coach Rod Dedeaux to take a look at the young pitcher, and
McGwire was offered a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two games I saw him (at Damien), he hit two homers in each
game,'' Lachemann said. ``I thought he was definitely a pitching
prospect. And, obviously, he could swing the bat, too. He was big
then for a high school senior, but obviously, not as big as
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos drafted McGwire in June 1981, in the ninth
round. Ninth-round picks don't attract big money, and the Expos had
precious little to throw around anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran scout Jack Papke took the less-thanoverwhelming Expos'
contract offer to the McGwire residence in Claremont, but later
admitted, ``I kept the car motor running.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, it was a short visit. The McGwires said thanks, but
no thanks. Mark was officially a Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if his time at Damien made him a better baseball
player,'' Carroll said. ``I like to think we did make him a better
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, Mark really developed after he left Damien. I
think it helped that he was able to concentrate just on baseball at
USC. And I know it helped him to play on the Claremont American
Legion team. When he was successful there, it really seemed to lift
his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire played for his hometown Claremont Cardinals in 1980 and
'81. He hit .318 in 1980 and .426 in 1981, with a team-record 13
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like at Damien, Mark started out with us as a pitcher,''
Helber said. ``But I liked his power and liked the idea of getting
his bat in the lineup on an every-day basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Mark worked out at first base. I remember telling my
infielders that if they threw the ball in the dirt when Mark was at
first, I would fine them. High throws were fine because Big Mark
would go up and get 'em. Eventually, Mark became a very good first
baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire almost missed the 1981 season with Helber's Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came down with mononucleosis,'' Helber said. ``For a while,
it looked like he would have to sit out the entire summer.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire returned, however, and hit 13 home runs in 39 games.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was 6-4 as a pitcher in 1980, but only 3-3 in 1981. With
Randy Robertson and Scott Campbell carrying the load for the
Cardinals in 1981, McGwire was able to concentrate more on playing
first base, and his hitting improved dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   That '81 team went 39-19 and reached the state American Legion
tournament at Yountville. McGwire showed his tenacity one night
during the tournament, during which the team stayed in an old Army
barracks at the Veterans Administration hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys settled in about 10 p.m., but these Fullerton guys
had the radio blaring and were having a party,'' Helber said. ``It
was keeping our guys awake. Finally, about 1 a.m., Mark had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He marched to the next room, turned the radio off, and
announced to the Fullerton team, `Good night, gentlemen!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now everybody knows Mark's game face. At 6-foot-5, when he's
unhappy, it's a pretty scary sight. And that's the Mark McGwire
that Fullerton bunch saw that night. After Mark went over there, we
never heard another peep out of 'em the rest of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has always said his two seasons spent with the Legion
team were happy times, and that he and Helber have stayed in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably going to be mad at me for telling you this, but
a couple times now, he's purchased new uniforms for the team,''
Helber said. ``But I guess the nicest thing he ever did for the
Claremont Cardinals was in 1988, when he was playing for the
Oakland A's. We had once again made the state playoffs, and had an
off-day at Yountville. So Mark arranged for tickets to an A's game
for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, it turned out that he brought us all down on the field
before the game, had his photo taken with the team, shook
everybody's hand, wished us luck and was just a super neat guy. Our
kids never forgot the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was a pitcher at USC in 1982 and '83, and a very
promising one. But Dedeaux thought there might be more to McGwire
than just a big kid who threw hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, first of all, I think you need to know that big guys
usually are late bloomers,'' Dedeaux said. ``It takes a while for
them to get the mechanics of baseball down. A guy on those same USC
teams as McGwire, Randy Johnson, is a classic example.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mark, I knew he was a very good athlete and a
hard-working kid, who had a great work ethic. I was also thinking
back to a guy we had at USC, named Dave Kingman. Kingman came to us
as a pitcher, but we gradually worked him into the every-day lineup
and he went on to a very successful major league career. So I
started to experiment with Mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mark, the more he played at first base, the more I liked
him. And, of course, even then he had great power. Awesome power.
But the interesting thing is, he really worked at becoming a good
hitter, not just a power hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also at USC that McGwire met his future wife. It's common
knowledge now that the marriage didn't work out. But for McGwire,
raised on family values, the subject of the broken relationship is
extremely painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally, he and his ex-wife have handled the split very
well,'' Helber said. ``There's no fighting over money, or the kid.
Mentally, well, it was a very difficult thing for Mark, something
he'll never get over. For him, it's a lot easier to accept failure
as a baseball player than failure as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is, by nature, a quiet, introspective person. So, all this
attention is tough on him. But I think he's handled himself just
great. That is a tribute to his upbringing, and the fact he's
overcome a lot of adversity to get where he's at. For a young man,
he has a very mature perspective on things. And fame isn't going to
change him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Mark, family will always come first. When he was a rookie
with the A's, he had a chance to hit 50 home runs, but instead went
home to witness the birth of his son, Matthew. And he would do the
same thing today -- even if it meant missing out on 62 home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
