<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SAYS RATES MAY FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sharp reversal from previous upbeat assessments
of the US economy, Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan said
Friday that America is in danger of being drawn into the maelstrom
of the global financial crisis, an event that could damage or end
its long economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not credible that the United States can remain an
oasis of prosperity unaffected by a world that is experiencing
greatly increased stress,'' he said in a speech at the University
of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   As he always does, Greenspan avoided saying what the central
bank might do about the problem, especially whether it might lower
interest rates to try to keep US growth going in the face of
overseas trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprising departure from the Fed's taciturn ways, he
revealed that the central bank policymakers meeting behind closed
doors last month concluded that global turmoil already posed such a
threat to US prosperity that they needed to alter bank policy. They
shifted the Fed's policy stance from one of being ready to raise
interest rates at the first serious sign of inflation to one of
being as likely as not to cut them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Greenspan's remarks were widely interpreted as signalling
that the Fed is preparing to make a growth-spurring rate cut,
perhaps as early as its late September meeting. The remarks were
also seen as a critical gauge of how quickly and how far the
nation's and world's economic outlook has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a dramatic change from where we were only eight weeks
ago when the chairman was waxing poetic that this was the best
economy he had seen in 50 years,'' said Mark M. Zandi, chief
economist with Regional Financial Associates in West Chester, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deepening global economic crisis and selloff in the
financial markets significantly increases the chances of an
interest rate cut,'' Zandi said.
</P>
<P>
   In his last public comments in late July, Greenspan hinted that
the Fed was more worried about the economy overheating than
slipping into recessions and was therefore more likely to raise
rates. With consumer spending strong and unemployment low, ``the
potential for accelerating inflation is probably greater than the
risk of protracted, excessive weakness in the economy,'' he said in
congressional testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's benchmark federal funds rate, the interest that banks
charge each other for loans, has been at 5.5 percent since March,
1997. For much of last year and the early part of this year, many
economists had expected the central bank to raise the rate to
perhaps 6 percent to dampen overly fast economic growth and choke
off renewed inflation. But the Fed did not act largely because it
believed that the collapse of Asian economies that began last year
would do the dampening for it.
</P>
<P>
   Now however, the central bank appears to have concluded that the
Asian crisis has gone too far, spreading from the Far East to
Russia, Latin America and elsewhere, and could pose a serious
threat to the US.
</P>
<P>
   The spread showed up with a vengence in the stock market where
the Dow Jone industrial average and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index
have lost almost 20 percent of their value since their mid-July
peaks. But analysts were uncertain before Greenspan's remarks
whether the Fed believed the stock selloff was a signal of
impending economic trouble or simply the bursting of a troubling
fincnancial bubble.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Greenspan counseled investors to be cautious,
saying ``we have relearned in recent weeks that just as a bull
stock market feels unending and secure... so it can feel when
markets contract that recovery is inconceivable... Both, of course,
are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Periods of euphoria or distress tend to feed on themselves,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said Greenspan's remarks indicate the Fed has
concluded that more is at work in the markets and the economy than
a case of nerves and is prepared to act to ensure that it does not
slip into a downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was scheduled to meet late Friday with US Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin and senior Japanese officials to discuss
Tokyo's so far unsuccessful efforts to pull itself out of a severe
recession. US officials believe that Japan must start growing again
in order for the rest of Asia to pull itself out of crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
