<DOCNO> NYT19980904.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-USOPEN-DAY-ART-41     09-04 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-DAY-ART-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSER-KNOWN FIGURES GET THEIR MOMENT ON STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steffi Graf and Jana Novotna won with surprising
ease; Martina Hingis and Patty Schnyder triumphed, but with
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   But on the first Friday of this eerily calm U.S. Open, two women
who made the strongest impressions were not stars or even rising
stars. They were Americans Kimberly Po and Annie Miller, who can
roam the stalls and halls of the National Tennis Center with little
fear of getting swarmed for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Po, a 26-year-old Californian, recorded the only upset of the
day session, defeating 14th-seeded Dominique Van Roost of Belgium,
6-4, 6-2. Miller, a 21-year-old from Michigan, lost to Monica
Seles, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   But if Po's and Miller's fortunes differed on the hardcourts
Friday, their futures may take them in similar directions: away
from their sport and toward lifestyles where the scenery and the
computer rankings are not updated at such dizzying and disorienting
paces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been struggling a bit, wavering with what I want to
do,'' Po said, after reaching the fourth round at the Open for the
first time in eight tries. ``But it hasn't been hard here to be
motivated and to know what I want to do these two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   After joining forces with her coach Donnie Young in early 1996,
Po went from a journeyman baseliner to a legitimate threat,
reaching the quarterfinals of the Australian Open in 1997 and a
career-high ranking of 14. But last November she had surgery to
remove some cartilage in her right shoulder. ``I didn't hit a ball
from November until April,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Po resumed roaming the globe with Young in May. After struggling
throughout the summer, she has won three matches in a row at
Flushing Meadows in straight sets. The discouraging news for Po is
that she must now face Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Miller reached the third round in a Grand Slam event for the
first time, but despite her ability to sustain baseline exchanges
with Seles, Miller is no longer prepared to make the same
commitment to tennis as Seles. Barring a last-minute change of
heart, she will begin the fall semester as a student in Michigan,
studying Spanish, statistics and geography instead of opponents'
groundstrokes and serving tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my three-year career so far, I've been known to be so tough
on myself that I go on the court and kind of suffer because I'm so
negative,'' she said. ``I really think going to school this fall
will help me gain some perspective into my life and what I want out
of it a little more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Graf, who has had her own travails in recent years, both
physical and psychological, is clearly on the upswing. But her
lopsided 6-1, 6-1 victory over the 16-year-old Croatian Mirjana
Lucic was bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Lucic made her Grand Slam debut at the Open and
pushed Novotna to three sets on Arthur Ashe Stadium in the third
round, demonstrating precocious poise, power and potential. But a
year later, in the same round and on the same court, she showed
little more than stage fright, shanking groundstrokes,
double-faulting eight times, and at one point late in the second
set, swinging at a Graf serve with her forehand and missing the
ball entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had nothing inside me,'' said Lucic, who has
often cited Graf as her role model and who has sought advice and
support from Graf this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lucic needs that support because in July, after accusing her
father, Marinko, of beating her, she left Croatia for Nick
Bollettieri's Academy in Florida with her mother and siblings. Her
father has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steffi was great from the beginning, helping me, telling me
what to do,'' Lucic said.
</P>
<P>
   For a set, it appeared that Hingis, the seeded No. 1, might not
make it through to the fourth round, but she eventually righted her
listing game and solved the riddle of Amelie Mauresmo's big serve
and backhand, winning by 4-6, 6-2, 6-2. In July, Mauresmo, an
athletic 19-year-old and former world junior champion, won the
first set against Hingis and led by 4-1 in the second in a Fed Cup
match on clay in Switzerland. Hingis managed to prevail then, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I lost the first set, I was like, hey girl, kind of wake
up,'' Hingis said of Friday's match. ``You don't want to go back
home after this match.''
</P>
<P>
   Other women struggled less to remain on the road. Schnyder,
seeded 11th, defeated Mary Joe Fernandez in straight sets and will
face Graf. Novotna beat the normally daunting Sandrine Testud of
France, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, second-seeded Marcelo Rios dropped a set but
not the match, 6-2, 6-7 (4-7), 6-2, 6-2, against the Italian
qualifier Giorgio Galimberti to reach the third round. No. 7 Alex
Corretja defeated the French qualifier Jean-Baptiste Perlant, 6-4,
5-7, 6-7 (8-10), 6-1, 6-0. And No. 11 Yevgeny Kafelnikov topped
Tommy Haas of Germany, 7-5, 6-2, 1-6, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   The American Jan-Michael Gambill defeated Magnus Norman of
Sweden, 6-4, 6-2, 6-7 (8-10), 6-3, and then confirmed that he
expects to make his Davis Cup debut against Italy in the semifinals
later this month. With Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi and Michael Chang
abstaining and Jim Courier injured, Gambill expects to play singles
along with Todd Martin.
</P>
</TEXT>
