<HEADLINE>
SOSA STAYS LOOSE ... AND BLASTS NO. 57 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The third pitch he saw of the night was really a
ball. Well, it would have been a ball if he hadn't swung at it. But
Sammy Sosa swings bats very well. So well that last night he was
able to send a baseball 401 feet at Three Rivers Stadium and wipe
out a 68-year-old Cubs record in one motion.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to know the Cubs right fielder to understand the
items that go into his daily diary. You are living his diary with
him. He now has 57 home runs, one more than Chicago's Hack Wilson
had in 1930 _ which was both the club and National League record
until Sosa and Mark McGwire started playing home run derby this
summer. The only person who wasn't happy about that was a young man
named Jason Schmidt, the Pirate who gave up the homer during the
Cubs' 5-2 win. Everyone else? Happy. Especially Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   He moved within two home runs of season leader McGwire and is
now only five away from breaking the record set by Roger Maris in
1961. With each homer, Sosa knows the crowds will grow. He knows
some of the fans will boo, as many among the 36,000 (the Pirates
drew just over 8,000 Thursday) did last night in the fourth inning,
when he did something silly _ hitting a single. He doesn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he is giddy about his daily routine. It usually begins
with a glance at the highlight shows, a prayer, a chat with the
media, a home run or two during the game, and, by nigtfall, a
summary of his previous 20 hours or so. We hope you're having fun
during this season. Sosa is. You said something about pressure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure?'' he said. ``This isn't pressure. Pressure for me
was when I was back home, a shoeshine boy. Yeah, I was a shoeshine
boy. Trying to make money for my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in the Dominican Republic, where Sosa's bats were tree
branches or slabs of wood. Baseballs were actually socks with
rubber taped in the middle of them. Word is that the stroke was
good even then. He said he dreamed of coming to the United States
back then, and since coming here, he hasn't stopped saying, ``I
love this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The serious baseball portion of Sosa's Friday began at about
4:30 p.m. He walked through the stadium's quiet corridors, talking
with public relations officials, teammates, and stadium personnel.
He was told that a crowd of anxious media awaited on the field,
already forming a semicircle that had only a glimmer of light at
the center. That was the space the crowd was reserving for Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes later, the player emerged from the dugout and
slipped into the crowd. Behind him, two stadium workers smiled and
snapped photograph after photograph. Sosa couldn't stop smiling.
And joking.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked him if he would be disappointed if, say, he
finished the season with 64 home runs and McGwire had 66 or 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' he said. ``I love this country. Whatever happens
now, I'll take anything I can get.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked why he keeps referring to McGwire as ``The Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has 59 home runs,'' Sosa replied.
</P>
<P>
   More laughs. Sosa was told that he sounds like boxing promoter
Don King with his constant reverie about America.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Sosa said, smiling again. ``I say, `God bless America.'
He says, `Only in America.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that he enjoys the publicity. He knows no one
expected him to be in this race. Know how many home runs he had on
May 24? Nine. By that time, McGwire had 24. But the next day, Sosa
hit two home runs and hasn't stopped swatting balls into the skies
of Pittsburgh, Chicago, St. Louis, Los Angeles, New York ...
</P>
<P>
   Since May 25, Sosa has hit 48 home runs. So when someone
brazenly mentioned that McGwire has hit all his homers with ``no
one behind him'' in St. Louis, Sosa quickly replied, ``I don't have
anyone behind me.'' Maybe he shouldn't have said it. But ask
yourself: Would you disagree with him?
</P>
<P>
   On and on, the questions came at Sosa. He connected with many of
them as if they were waist-high pitches such as the one Schmidt
threw him that he sent over the right-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   How many home runs will McGwire hit?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said 70 before,'' he said. ``Probably 69 or 70.''
</P>
<P>
   Whom have you talked to about maintaining your focus?
</P>
<P>
   ``God,'' he said. ``I pray before the game. I believe in God.
I'll pray for you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed again. He said he told McGwire to do the same thing,
to not let the attention become a negative. Now, he promises, when
he goes to St. Louis Monday, he is definitely going to get an
autographed bat from McGwire. And in case you were wondering, no,
he doesn't mind that the country he loves so much _ the United
States _ seems to be rooting a little harder for McGwire. Big deal.
Leonel Fernandez, the president of the Dominican Republic, called
him after he hit his 56th home run to tie Wilson's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire is the man here, but I'm the man over there,''
Sosa said. ``If he goes there, I'll pass my uh, my crown to him for
the day he's going to be there. And after he leaves, I'll take it
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
