<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KATZENMOYER PLAYS; OHIO STATE TAKES A HIT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Katzenmoyer is eligible to play; all's well in the world.
All is certainly well in Columbus, Ohio, where Ohio State football
is stronger than ever, now that Katzenmoyer and two teammates have
been declared academically eligible to play in Saturday night's
game at West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   And so a new college football season begins on a fitting and
familiar tone of skepticism and doubt, with borderline academic
fraud and the age-old question of what a semiprofessional,
on-campus entertainment is doing on a campus in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just good to be playing a football game,'' Andy Geiger,
the Ohio State athletic director, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The last few weeks have certainly been an orgy of punishment for
the Ohio State family ever since Katzenmoyer, a junior linebacker,
revealed what summer school courses he was taking in an effort to
pull up his grade-point average: Music, AIDS Awareness and Golf.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger, entering his fifth year as the athletic director, is in
the middle of the maelstrom surrounding the Buckeyes' middle
linebacker. He has had tours of duty at Brown, Penn and Maryland,
but this is the nastiest swirl he has been involved with. ``This
has been very strong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer, the 1997 Butkus award winner, needed to lift his
grade-point average after last year and needed six credit hours in
the summer. ``It was a situation where he got into his major, then
struggled in terms of the g.p.a. and needed to take electives to
boost it,'' Geiger said. ``He needed to take courses he could be
successful in.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of academic counselors, the linebacker maneuvered
around the academic minefield. They scoured the university catalog
and came up with three classes that would work. Then one day,
Katzenmoyer told a reporter what courses he was taking.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger is planning to have a meeting soon with the advisers and
the players. ``We will talk about the mistakes _ the perceived
mistakes _ the grown-ups have made,'' Geiger said, ``and we'll talk
to the athletes about keeping quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's not the ideal solution. The major problem is
that Katzenmoyer is an academic square peg in a round hole. Like a
large number athletes, he is forced to go to a school he might not
otherwise bother attending simply because the road to the pro ranks
dictates he do so.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger was candid in what was essentially a defense and
explanation of his all-America linebacker. ``He is not the most
articulate guy, he's shy,'' Geiger said. ``He's never been
especially intellectually curious. He's a football player, not a
bad kid, and he's been hammered.''
</P>
<P>
   But this business of shortcuts and entitlement didn't begin with
summer school. Katzenmoyer had an inkling he owned a piece of the
campus three summers ago as a freshman when he boldly requested No.
45, which was last worn by Archie Griffin, the two-time Heisman
Trophy winner and a Columbus icon.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger was in his second year at Ohio State and admits being
intimidated by the school's sports machinery, which wanted to sign
the high school defensive player of the year. ``Intimidated might
be the right word,'' he said. ``I was trying to help the coaches
and the school; we said yes. I think he would have been better
served had we said no. I was trying to help as many people as
possible and wound up not helping anyone. That may not have been
the smartest thing we ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ohio State is in a mess it hopes will be forgotten
after a few easy victories. Geiger says the long-term problem is
that until the liberal arts curriculum expands to embrace the
sports culture, there will always be a Katzenmoyer variation:
athletes whose primary purpose is to play basketball, baseball,
tennis or football.
</P>
<P>
   ``A musician who plays the tenor sax and wanted to be a jazz
player had to learn in clubs and bars,'' Geiger said. ``Now they
can go to a school of music and get a degree in jazz, jazz theory.
We've never accepted sports that same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher education has a long-standing, long-range problem, but
Ohio State has an immediate one: Every time Katzenmoyer makes a
tackle or gives an interview, every time the Ohio State president
surveys his packed stadium, he'll be reminded of this dirty little
problem in higher education's closet.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the university, the Buckeyes won't be reminded
for too much longer. Geiger doubts that Katzenmoyer will be around
after this year. Columbus is a tough place to play. The full weight
of the state sits on the athletic department, in particular the
football program. When it's great, it's great. When it's bad, it's
horrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a double-edged sword,'' Geiger said. And when it
cuts, a lot of folks bleed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2244EDT &QL; 
