<SLUG> BC-BELL-LONGDISTANCE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BARS BELLS FROM OFFERING LONG-DISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Texas)  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dashing the main hope of the Bell local telephone giants for
quick entry into the $80 billion long-distance business, a federal
appeals court in New Orleans on Friday reversed a lower court's
decision that would have removed the main barrier between the Bells
and the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   In a split decision, a panel of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals restored the cornerstone of the Telecommunications Act of
1996. That provision requires the Bells to convince federal
regulators that they have opened their local networks to potential
competitors before they are allowed into the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   No Bell has yet passed that test.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ruling, issued after major financial markets closed,
handed an important victory to the big long-distance carriers in
their regulatory struggle against the Bells. The Bells, which
dominate the $100 billion local telephone business, are trying to
get into the long-distance market while the existing long-distance
carriers, including AT&AMP;T Corp., are trying to keep the Bells out.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, Judge Joe Kendall of U.S. District Court in
Wichita Falls, Texas, ruled that the act's main provision
unconstitutionally singled out the Bells for punishment. The
Constitution bars Congress from passing what are known as ``bills
of attainder'' _ laws that impose punishment without a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall's decision stunned almost everyone involved with the
telecommunications industry except the Bells themselves. In the
ensuing months, many experts predicted that the ruling would be
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit against the government was originally filed by SBC
Communications Inc., the parent company of Pacific Bell and
Southwestern Bell, and was joined by Bell Atlantic Corp. and U S
West Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells contend that the act treats them unfairly because
non-Bell local phone companies, such as GTE Corp., have been
allowed into the long-distance market without having to pass the
rigorous regulatory review imposed on the Bells.
</P>
<P>
   The court in New Orleans did not agree. Referring to the Bells,
the court said that ``the Act does not declare them monsters or
otherwise seek to punish them on the basis of past conduct, and
thus does not run afoul of the Bill of Attainder Clause.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Grady Jolly wrote the majority opinion, which was joined
by Judge Rhesa Barksdale. Judge Jerry Smith dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Had it held up, Kendall's decision would have allowed the Bells
into the long-distance market immediately. The ruling never went
into effect, however, because Kendall stayed its implementation
pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   SBC said Friday that it had not decided whether to appeal
Friday's decision to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Friday night, William Kennard, chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, said: ``The real winners in today's
decision are America's consumers. This means more choice and lower
rates for telephone service.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard was joined in praising the decision by Jamie DePeau, a
spokeswoman for MCI Communications Corp., the No. 2 long-distance
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is a clear victory for competition,'' she said.
``Maybe now the Bell monopolies will put their efforts toward
opening local markets to competition rather than obstructing
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC contended that consumers were hurt by the ruling because it
would keep them from using the Bell companies for both local and
long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the benefits of full and effective
competition are being delayed,'' the company said in a statement.
``As long as the `Special Provisions' of the act prohibit SBC and
other Bell companies from entering legitimate lines of business,
including long-distance, consumers will continue to be handicapped
in their choice of providers and services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
