<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX HELP KEEP TORONTO ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ If the Red Sox want to inspire hope where there is
none, this is how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   With Nomar Garciaparra's 23d error of the season and seventh in
the last 14 games setting the tone in the first inning, the Sox
went down to their worst loss of the season, a 12-1 beating at the
hands of the Toronto Blue Jays under a full moon and open SkyDome
roof.
</P>
<P>
   The win was the second in a row over the Red Sox and eighth
straight overall for the Blue Jays, who broke the game open with a
seven-run seventh inning fueled by Jose Canseco's three-run home
run off Tim Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays, who have Roger Clemens on deck this afternoon,
are a season-high nine games over .500 and within seven games of
the Red Sox in the American League wild-card chase.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who have lost six of their last nine and haven't won
consecutive games since Aug. 26, managed just six hits off Pat
Hentgen and 40-year-old relic Dave Stieb.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green had four hits, including his 30th home run off
reliever Carlos Reyes, making him the first Blue Jay player to have
30 home runs and 30 stolen bases in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Only White Sox rookie Mike Caruso has a lower fielding
percentage among AL regulars at shortstop than Garciaparra, who has
made more errors than any big league shortstop except Caruso (33)
and Colorado's Mark Grudzielanek (28) in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Garciaparra staggered fill-in first baseman
Mike Benjamin with a hard sinker that Benjamin barely held on to.
Friday night, with plenty of time to throw out Canseco, who is not
known for overexerting himself down the line, Garciaparra bounced
one past Mo Vaughn at first, an error that directly led to the Blue
Jays' first two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who had singled and taken third on the error, scored on a
passed ball, Canseco advancing to third, and Canseco scored on
Carlos Delgado's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley halved that lead with a two-out home run in the
second, the 28th of the season for the onetime Blue Jay, but Darrin
Fletcher answered with an opposite-field homer in the bottom of the
inning to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays went ahead, 4-1, in the third when Green's drive
hit the base of the left-field wall and caromed past Troy O'Leary.
By the time O'Leary ran the ball down, Shannon Stewart, who had
been hit by a pitch, scored, and Green took third when O'Leary
overthrew two cutoff men.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco took a pathetic half-swing at a knuckler to strike out
and Green was out in a rundown on Delgado's comebacker to the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hatteberg dropped Green's foul popup with two out in the
fifth, and Green hit the next pitch for a double, but the Blue Jays
didn't make the Sox pay for that error as Canseco grounded out to
short.
</P>
<P>
   There was no getting off the hook the next time, however, when
the Blue Jays broke the game open in the seventh. Craig Grebeck
doubled and scored on Stewart's single to make it 5-1. The Sox
pitched out on the next play, correctly guessing that Stewart would
be stealing, but Jason Varitek was unable to get a good grip on the
ball and never made a throw.
</P>
<P>
   A clearly annoyed Wakefield snatched Hatteberg's toss back to
the mound, then intentionally walked Green. He then hung a
knuckleball over the middle of the plate that Canseco promptly
turned into an hors d'ouevre for someone dining in the Windows
Restaurant, his blast crashing off the glassed-in restaurant
located in the second deck of SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was the 38th of the season and 389th of his career
for Canseco, tying him with Hall of Famer Johnny Bench for 32d on
the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   That was all for Wakefield, whose yield of eight runs was one
run more than his previous high this season. There was still more
agony for the Red Sox to endure, however. Lefthanded reliever David
West, proving to be no more effective for the Sox this time than he
had on his previous go-around, gave up a single to Delgado and
walked Jose Cruz. When he went ball one on Tony Fernandez, Jimy
Williams yanked him for Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez hit Reyes's first pitch over the head of center
fielder Darren Lewis for a two-run double, and Fletcher singled
home Fernandez to make it 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, 2 for 12 with runners in scoring position in
Thursday night's loss, came up empty in their only four chances
through eight innings Friday night. Garciaparra flied to right with
the bases loaded in the third off Hentgen, whose streak of 183
consecutive starts ended Aug. 29 because of shoulder tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Hentgen showed no signs of soreness Friday night, holding the
Sox to four hits in 6 1/3 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
