<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Replacement medals return pride
 &HT;    By Teresa Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ His original war medals may be at the
bottom of a canal somewhere, but Dan Roy says the replacement
medals he received Friday remind him why he served his country in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Roy, whose Purple Heart, Bronze Star and five other Vietnam War
medals were stolen from his home Aug. 2, was ambivalent when he
first learned police were trying to find new medals to replace the
priceless ones stolen.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling gave way to exuberance on Friday when a Lake Worth
collector of military antiques presented the Port St. Lucie veteran
with seven original-issue medals mounted on black velvet and
encased in glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they would mean as much as my originals, but
they do,'' said Roy, flanked by his 16-year-old son Brent and
12-year-old daughter Whitney. ``I really wanted them back so I
could give them to my children one day.''
</P>
<P>
   John Fravel, a veteran and collector of military antiques in
Lake Worth, read about the police department's efforts to replace
Roy's medals in a newspaper and scoured his collection to see if he
had original-issue medals of the same kind. He estimates the seven
medals are worth about $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to have the original medals, not replacements
that were issued years later,'' Fravel said. ``The replacements
have a lacquer finish and you can't see as much detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy, who served in the Marine Corps from 1967 to 1969, received
the medals during a short ceremony at the police department Friday.
When asked about his most vivid memories of Vietnam, Roy said
``getting wounded kind of stuck out.'' He earned the Purple Heart
after an enemy grenade exploded beneath his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked out shrapnel for the next 10 years,'' the 51-year-old
machinist said.
</P>
<P>
   Roy thanked police for catching the teenagers who broke into his
home and said he hopes they turn away from crime after the episode.
Police recovered Roy's pellet gun, compact disc player and
hand-held TV from the youths, but they told officers they couldn't
remember where they had discarded the medals.
</P>
<P>
   Police Cmdr. Chuck Johnson said the three suspects still are
awaiting trial in juvenile court.
</P>
<P>
   As for Roy, he promises to keep his new medals locked up in a
safe and make sure he quickly repairs any faulty windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel very good that the community cared enough to
do this for me,'' said Roy, who moved to Port St. Lucie from
Okeechobee a year ago. ``We were shunned when we came home from
Vietnam and even though we shouldn't have been there, we were and I
have to remember the 50,000 men who lost their lives there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
