<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH VICTIM ROGER WILLIAMS, 54, FOUND WAY TO SPOT HEART RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, N.C.)  By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Williams, a physician who pioneered the use of genetic
data to identify people at risk for cholesterol-related heart
disease, was among the 229 people who died in the crash of Swissair
Flight 111 on Wednesday. He was 54.
</P>
<P>
   Williams lived in Salt Lake City and conducted his research
there, at the University of Utah School of Medicine. He was on his
way to Geneva to lead an international meeting of scientists
engaged in finding genetic diseases through extensive genealogical
research.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman Starke, the executive vice president of the American
Heart Association, said Williams' death was ``a huge loss to the
preventative cardiovascular effort in the United States.'' He said
Williams had done much to shape the preventive approach to heart
disease by ``finding ways to identify the people who are most
likely to get in trouble before they actually do get into any
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' work in this field concentrated on genetic familial
hypercholesterolemia, an inherited form of high cholesterol that
contributes to heart attack and stroke among people under the age
of 55. Some young and seemingly healthy athletes have actually had
the condition and have suddenly collapsed and died of heart
attacks. In fact, about 100,000 deaths a year are attributed to
this genetically triggered sudden rise in cholesterol, with about 5
percent of American families carrying the genetic variations that
can lead to premature heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The genetic marker associated with this condition was identified
in the late 1970s by Michael Brown and Joseph Goldstein, who in
1985 won the Nobel Prize in physiology for their work.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was quick to realize that, aside from advancing
molecular biology, the discovery provided a powerful diagnostic
tool. Moreover, he realized that his home state of Utah offered an
ideal social environment for tracing the genetic predisposition for
heart disease. Not only did Utah have large families, but because
of the Mormons' collection of genealogical data, an abundance of
family trees existed. Williams was able to use this information,
involving 1.3 million people, to seek out those who had the trait
and to analyze the ways the risk was distributed within the
population. Once identified, those whose family histories indicated
vulnerability could be notified and treated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Williams observed that although scientists had
succeeded in pinpointing the genetic factors that put many people
at high risk, ``we're still having great difficulty in alerting
both the public and the health care profession to the need for
screening and treatment for people with a family history of early
cardiovascular disease.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that about one-third of those with genetic
hypercholesterolemia had been diagnosed, while the ``other
two-thirds are unaware of their potentially lethal condition.''
</P>
<P>
   At his death, Williams was a professor of internal medicine at
the University of Utah School of Medicine and the director of the
university's Cardiovascular Genetics Research Clinic, which he
founded. After graduating from Weber State University in Ogden,
Utah, in 1971, he completed medical school at the University of
Utah and served his residency at Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Linda, and seven children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
