A0665 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SWITZER-TEX     09-04 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SWITZER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITZER SEES NO TUNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the eve of his first fall without a football job since 1993,
Barry Switzer isn't backing down from his belief that there aren't
enough differences between last year's 6-10 Cowboys and this year's
edition to leave room for great optimism.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eve of the Cowboys' 1998 season opener tomorrow
against the Arizona Cardinals, Switzer does not offer any
second-guessing of owner Jerry Jones, coach Chan Gailey, the
Cowboys and their winless, action-packed preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer said he remains best-buddy close with Jones, possesses a
rather guileless affection for even the Cowboys players who never
respected him, and feels comfortable enough with successor Gailey
to be host of a dinner honoring him.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThursday night\S I invited Chan and all the Cowboys coaches
to join me over at my restaurant \RYvette in Addison\S,'' Switzer
says. ``There's nothing but good feelings there. I'd never do
anything to hurt the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   But, that doesn't mean Switzer thinks the Cowboys are much
better than the 6-10 team of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, they haven't helped themselves at the skill
positions on offense, and that defensive line is going to really
have to improve quickly, or the same things that happened last year
_ a defense that got worn down _ is going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Switzer see happening for some of the key Cowboys
season?
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman: ``I made mistakes with Troy. I didn't handle it
right. They were innocent, but I regret them. I could have handled
things differently, but understand something: I didn't make the
mistakes on purpose. I hear people accuse me of that, and it's the
dumbest thing I ever heard of! Why would I sabotage one of the keys
to my team's success? Ridiculous!
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy will need a supporting cast. Brett Favre might not need
one. He might improvise his way to a touchdown. You give Troy a
supporting cast though, and he's as good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin: ``We went back and looked at
films of '92, four films. Saw Emmitt and Michael, with a burst that
neither of them have anymore. But they can still win. It's not
about want-to with those guys, I'll promise you.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Johnston: ``D.J., the punishment he takes, the nature of
that neck injury, I'm surprised he came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Nate Newton: ``I said all along, big Nate gets himself in shape,
if he wants to make that last hurrah, he's got such good feet, he
can be as good as any guard they run out there. With all the talk
of the Cowboys needing to go get a free-agent guard, I said, when
Nate's in shape, he's as good as any guard that was in free
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Switzer, who by reputation is the reason the Cowboys eroded
in both on- and off-field performance, feel vindicated by the
continued turmoil after his departure?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I don't care about vindication,'' he said. ``I worked
at my job, just as much as \RJimmy Johnson\S did. And that's
according to guys who were assistants to both of us. But I don't
take any satisfaction is seeing people do the wrong thing. People
have sometimes done the wrong thing since the beginning of time.
That's predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   For Switzer, the right thing now has little to do with sports.
Oh, he'll go to the Oklahoma-North Texas game today. He's
fascinated by Mark McGwire's pursuit of Roger Maris' home-run
record. He's saddened by news of Charles Haley's comeback attempt.
And one of these days he'll probably accept one of many invitations
to watch a Cowboys game from a Texas Stadium suite.
</P>
<P>
   But immediately, Switzer keeps getting calls from Hollywood.
Director Oliver Stone has seen Switzer's cameo performances in
three sports-related projects _ (''Arliss'' on HBO, ``Possums''
starring Mac Davis and ``Varsity Blues'' starring Jon Voight) _ and
is finding on-camera time for him in a major release, ``On Any
Given Sunday'', a Stone project that stars Al Pacino and Dennis
Quaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've decided there isn't going to be a movie based on my
``Bootlegger's Boy'' book,'' says Switzer, co-author of the
best-selling autobiography. ``There's probably some money to be
made, and it'd be a good movie. But I'm turning \RHollywood\S down
there. It'd just be a vanity project. What do I need that for?''
</P>
<P>
   Seems to be his feeling about a few things these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
