<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA GIVES LEITER ALL THE HELP HE NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK Before the start of Friday night's game at Shea
Stadium, fans flocked behind the New York Mets' dugout, waving
signs wishing Mike Piazza a happy birthday. The well-wishers were
not totally selfless because many of the signs also bore messages
begging the slugging catcher to stay in New York after this
season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the game, a banner in the bleachers skipped the birthday
greetings and simply said, ``N.Y. Mike.'' The fans raised it, and
Piazza nearly put a hole through it in the fourth inning, ripping a
two-run home run, estimated at 485 feet, just to the left and
beyond it to put the Mets in front for good in a 2-1 victory over
the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone got a great souvenir if they were out there on the
highway with the window open,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Mets one game behind the Chicago Cubs, who
beat the Pittsburgh Pirates 5-2 Friday night, in the National
League's wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   While Piazza celebrated with a line single to center in his
first at-bat, a walk on four pitches after the home run, and
another bullet to right for a single in the eighth inning, what the
Mets got on his 30th birthday was a masterful five-hit, complete
game performance by Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   The only blemish for Leiter came in the top of the seventh
inning when he retired the first two batters but allowed the
Braves' only run. Greg Colbrunn reached on an infield single and
Ryan Klesko ripped a line drive to center. Brian McRae started in,
but the ball sailed over his left shoulder and rolled to the wall,
scoring Colbrunn from first.
</P>
<P>
   While Leiter was sharp, Piazza was overpowering. He homered for
the third consecutive game and has eight home runs and 20 runs
batted in over his last 10 games, with 18 hits in 31 at-bats. It
was the red-hot Piazza who carried the Mets to a 5-4 mark on their
West Coast trip, hitting .536 during the nine games. No wonder the
home fans greeted him with a standing ovation in his first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   After the home run, Piazza, who has been booed soundly at home,
was treated to another ovation by most of the 36,617 fans. And
after his single in the eighth, the fans sang ``Happy Birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was honored, not only by the cheers, but by the nice calls
and gifts,'' Piazza said later. ``I was honored at the response.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The fans had much to cheer about as the Mets defeated the Braves
for the first time in six games this season. While the Mets may
harbor no hopes of catching the division-leading Braves, who still
hold a 13-game lead on the Mets, they did need to put a dent in
Atlanta's dominance, since this was the first of seven games the
Mets have with the Braves in their final 22 games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's home run provided the margin that Leiter needed in a
duel of left-handers with Tom Glavine, who entered the game with an
18-5 record, including an 11-1 mark and a 1.81 earned run average
on the road. Glavine was equally sharp, allowing just five hits in
seven innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter, who improved to 14-5, won for the fourth time in his
last five outings. He retired the first six batters, and when he
walked Klesko leading off the third, he promptly erased him with a
double play. Leiter allowed a pair of singles in the fourth inning,
but again got out of trouble by getting Andruw Jones to ground to
second. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leiter survived a scare in the ninth when Chipper Jones, leading
off, drilled a shot into the third deck in left field that curved
foul. Jones then reached on a walk. But Javy Lopez grounded to
third baseman Edgardo Alfonso, who rifled a throw to second baseman
Luis Lopez, who turned the double play, the Mets' third of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter threw only 112 pitches, a low number for him. But because
he had to bear down on every pitch in a game of such importance, he
said, the ``mental pain'' made the outing seem more strenuous.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey started the game in right field for the Mets, his
first appearance since Aug. 2 when he strained his left hamstring.
But after playing four innings and grounding out to the mound in
the fourth, he was removed and replaced by Brian McRAE. ``I don't
want to baby it,'' Huskey said before the game. ``I have to find
out if it's good or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Payton made his first major-league start, in left field.
Payton, who underwent two major surgeries on his right elbow in the
last three years, entered the game on Tuesday in San Diego on a
double-switch and was 2-for-2. Friday night he went 0-for-3 and had
an uneventful game in the field, catching the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley caught his first game Friday night since last
September, working behind the plate at Norfolk for the first five
innings of the first game of a doubleheader. No runners tried to
steal on him, and he was 1-for-2 at the plate with a walk. He
played left field in the second game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
