<SLUG> BC-NY-ANTISEMITIC-VANDAL-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED IN DRAWING OF SWASTIKAS IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a week he was a busy man, the police said: He
roamed through the predominantly Jewish neighborhood of
Williamsburg, Brooklyn, leaving symbols of Nazi Germany in his
wake.
</P>
<P>
   But the string of hits with a felt-tip marker ended Friday
morning, when two transit bureau police officers took notice of a
man rendering a swastika on an elevated subway platform and slapped
the cuffs on him, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest came with a twist: The man, identified by the police
as Christopher Maldonado, 31, was dressed in Hasidic clothing,
complete with a skull cap on his head and a prayer shawl under his
black suit. He wore a full beard, the police said, but he had gone
on his spree without the distinctive side curls worn by the
Hasidim.
</P>
<P>
   Maldonado professed to being a practicing Hasidic Jew, and to
prove it he opened his bag; along with the markers and a German
tour book, he was lugging around 15 Hebrew books, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was Puerto Rican but converted to Judaism in
1985,'' said Capt. John Ward, the executive officer at the 90th
Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   Maldonado faces charges of possession of graffiti tools and at
least eight counts of aggravated harassment, Ward said. Each
harassment charge carries up to a year in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Ward said: ``We spoke in Yiddish, and he admitted it.'' When I
asked him why, he just said that the people who usually bothered
him were other Jewish people and he wanted to get back at them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The police said Maldonado had been busy with retribution Friday.
Shortly after 1 a.m., a man told the police that he had yelled at
Maldonado while the suspect was drawing swastikas on aluminum light
poles on the street. Just before 9 a.m., a member of the
neighborhood's safety patrol reported seeing Maldonado drawing
swastikas on a telephone booth. Maldonado later said he had been
angered by a nearby candy store owner who had kicked him out of the
store, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Maldonado was caught drawing a final swastika, 6
inches by 6 inches, on the wall of the subway platform at 9:10 a.m.
Then he told the authorities about the weeklong spree, giving them
precise locations, Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps remembering more, and so far, he's been right about
every location,'' Ward said. ``It's not like he's the Green River
Killer, but he keeps unearthing swastikas for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Maldonado, who was also wanted on a 1993 menacing charge,
appears to have otherwise kept a low profile over the last five
years. The police said he had no convictions on record and seemed
to live on welfare payments. When not living on the street, he kept
a room at a $9-a-night hotel on Broadway in Williamsburg, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working in the Hasidic community for 13 years and
I've never seen anything like this guy,'' Ward said. ``At this
point, I really haven't been able to figure him out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-98 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
