</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-RALLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: YOUTHS' VOICES AREN'T SILENT, JUST IGNORED
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The crossfire is an appropriate starting point for a
discussion with the Rev. Anthony Nathaniel Lucas. Break the word
down to its components and you have symbols of faith, suffering and
redemption. Taken as one word, it is something that has touched
Lucas' life when he has had to pray over the bodies of young people
who died violently.
</P>
<P>
   He saw an added meaning to the metaphor of the middle as he
talked about Saturday's youth rally in Harlem. The volleys of
denunciations and fears of violence that have accompanied the
so-called Million Youth March since it was announced have almost
obliterated the rally's stated goal of reaching out to urban youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a power problem with Khallid Muhammad and Mayor
Giuliani battling,'' Lucas said. ``They're not focused on the youth
because they're focused on their own agendas, whatever that may be.
But the youth are always caught in the crossfire. They are
forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas seems youthful himself, even though at 32 he has a newly
minted doctorate in theology. He credits whatever trace of youth he
possesses to a career spent working with young people, especially
in southeast Queens. For seven years he ran a youth ministry at
Allen African Methodist Episcopal Church, before deciding this
summer to broaden his scope and ambition and strike out on his own
with the Joel Deliverance Church, a congregation that he hopes will
unite children and adults as they confront problems in their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas favors strategies, not slogans, which can seem to be in
short supply in the arguments of those who have eagerly stepped
into the rally's spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone asked me what's the purpose of this march, other
than to raise self-esteem, I wouldn't know what it was,'' he said.
``I'd like to see people march to the schools in southeast Queens
or the Bronx and protest for the kids who are in school. March to
the stock market or wherever the jobs are and get them jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lost opportunity here, he said, one that has informed
his work with young people around the country, where he has
listened to their concerns about sex, drugs, violence and peer
pressure. The most important thing he has learned is that young
people want to be heard. Sounds simple, but he said it has eluded
even preachers with good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn to listen to youth,'' he said. ``They are
the real thermostat for what's happening in the community. They
know what others feel. They may even have some answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The young people he works with do have questions. David
Latimore, a lanky 14-year-old, wonders why he sees so many
teen-agers cutting classes. He is also puzzled about why schools
are crumbling and overcrowded while the public is in the grip of
Lotto mania. Weren't those dollars supposed to support education?
He feels as if he is part of an invisible generation, especially
when he sees what has dominated the public debate lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never see what young people think,'' David said. ``The
news is about what's going on in the president's life. Who wants to
know about his sex life? There are more important things. Young
people have problems, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' 14-year-old brother, Hurron, raised another issue. He was
curious about summer jobs, since he couldn't get one this year.
Instead, he saw day camp jobs filled by ``old people'' in their
20s. Fortunately, he kept himself busy at home and church. He has
good morals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It also vexed him that despite his upbringing, he still gets
followed by store clerks when he goes shopping. It happened last on
Tuesday at a sneaker store.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stare at you,'' he said. ``A lot. And they don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers hate the idea of being judged by skin color or
clothing. They insist that adults could learn from them, even from
those written off as hoodlums. Lucas recounted how in his previous
ministry he was able to reach troubled youths through several new
strategies, like letting them preach in church, and one very old
one: listening to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be heard,'' he said. ``When you talk of black and
Latino kids, they're a forgotten generation. It's a fear that has
to do with ignorance and negative hype. We're taught to fear them
without giving them the chance to tell us what they're thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is evident. ``If we don't deal with them now and
let them become monsters, once they're through with each other,
who's next?'' he said. ``We are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
