<SLUG> BC-FBO-DEL-RIO-SPIRIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEL RIO, TEXAS, TRIES TO RECAPTURE NORMALCY THROUGH FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Stacy Feducia 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ They played football at Ram Stadium here last
night.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the portable toilets dotting the corners of the
historic San Felipe neighborhood. In spite of the search-and-rescue
spray-painted Xs on the three-walled houses scheduled for
bulldozers. In spite of the flood waters that swallowed part of
their town.
</P>
<P>
   This was, after all, the first Friday night of football, and
this was their archrival Eagle Pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the eyes of Del Rio are on you tonight _ they want to come
here and have fun and watch their football team play,'' Rams head
coach Joe George said in the locker room before kickoff. ``They
have seen a lot of tragedy. They have seen a lot of heroes. We can
be heroes tonight. We can be 60 men who give them everything we
have. This can be our finest hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be our finest hour.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many. Though Eagle Pass won, 28-21, the Del Rio
Rams were heroes long before they walked through the Ram Stadium
gate.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Aug. 23, rain began to fall from the leftovers of
Tropical Storm Charley. Twenty-four hours later, more than 600
homes had been destroyed, nine people were dead, and an estimated
1,500 people were sleeping on aluminum camping cots at the Red
Cross shelter in the Del Rio Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   That Tuesday, they had football practice.
</P>
<P>
   Del Rio is the only high school in town. It is 54 miles from the
nearest Class 5A school in Eagle Pass and three hours in a school
bus from its District 26-5A opponents in southwest San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can buy a Del Rio coffee mug 140 miles from nowhere and
three feet from hell,'' Rams trainer Brad Dixon joked. ``Not many
of these folks are here by choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many of them return after going away to college either,
school board member Lewis Nunley said. The town has about 34,000
people; the high school, about 2,100. The varsity has won one game
in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody thinks we're going to win this game,''
junior free safety Chris Villarreal said. ``But we're gonna prove
them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Rio had beaten Eagle Pass for 13 consecutive years before
losing in 1996, and they were beating them again last season until
the Eagles scored in the last minute of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All summer we worked so hard,'' senior team captain Justin
Henegar said. ``Everyone was in the weight room. This was the most
important game. We were completely focused on Eagle Pass, and then
this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   That first football practice began with hopeful phone calls and
tentative drives to the homes of some 80 players. It began with
helmets and shorts and only half a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what had happened to the others,'' said senior
John Alexaitis, who volunteered to serve meals at the civic center.
``Maybe a day or two later, they started coming back, but a lot of
people were sick from the water and a lot of people still had to
help clean up.''
</P>
<P>
   The second day of practice, Brackett High School, 24 miles away,
offered its showers and practice field for a morning. One parent
laughed at the irony of 78 football players getting cleaned up and
showered, while the rest of the town smelled bad because the water
wasn't running.
</P>
<P>
   The failed water system has kept school closed for two weeks,
and Tuesday is the earliest it could reopen.
</P>
<P>
   Only one player on the team lost everything. Others sustained
varying degrees of water damage, none too severe. A spaghetti
dinner benefit is planned for a freshman volleyball player whose
house was washed away, coach Val Warrior said.
</P>
<P>
   No school-aged children were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In the spaces between two-a-days, the players found their finest
hours, sharing in the camaraderie of trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Villarreal removed branches from the living room of his elderly
neighbor's home. A few nights before, he and his father had carried
her four grandchildren from the overwhelmed house to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Henegar and eight other players helped the National Guard unload
a semi-trailer sent from Dickinson High School last week and filled
a funeral tent with canned goods, bottled water and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward, they gave us these pins that said `I Love DHS' and
told us to wear them the next day at school,'' said Herman Flores,
a junior quick guard. ``We haven't had school yet, but I've got
that pin in my Jeep. I'm gonna wear it when we get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong side guard Baldemar Briones lives on a ranch adjacent to
the creek and missed the first week of practice as he helped his
father recover their damaged property.
</P>
<P>
   Briones found two of his goats hanging dead from their horns in
mesquite trees. A round bale of hay clung to a fence post four feet
off the ground. Railroad cross ties poked from pecan branches like
windmill blades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to come back to practice,'' Briones said. ``I
don't think we should have had it. We needed some time to get over
the main stuff, and get things back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Normalcy will wean the 73 remaining refugees from the civic
center and give it back to BINGO night and Chamber of Commerce
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Normalcy came yesterday with the arrival of the first mobile
homes for displaced families at the American Campground. Normalcy
will be permanent when American Red Cross volunteers, FEMA workers
and supply trucks recede like the journalists and camera vans and
rains before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal is what we want,'' said Red Cross volunteer Patricia
Zawlocki of Indiana. ``The numbers of people in the shelter drop
every night. For their mental health, we want them to get back to
their normal lifestyle, like watching movies, cooking dinner,
attending church.''
</P>
<P>
   And playing football.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight players formed a matrix across the practice field
Thursday morning at 9 o'clock. His hands clasped behind his back,
George gave an order for push-ups and shouted ``Down! _ Down! _
Down!'' as their bodies rose and fell to his command, just as they
had in every practice for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   In the parking lot next to Ram Stadium, the 230-member Ram Band
_ the pride of Del Rio _ marched with empty spaces in formation for
the 20 or so flood-stricken students who haven't yet returned
because ``they are still a part of this band,'' director Juan Nanez
said.
</P>
<P>
   And last night, they returned to normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   They played football because they wanted to keep score on
something less significant than persons missing, bodies recovered,
families displaced.
</P>
<P>
   They played football because it was the first game of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   It was, indeed, their finest hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
